<HEADLINE>
UNARMED RED SOX PUNCHED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BLUE JAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Long after Sunday's 5-1 loss to the Toronto Blue Jays,
the door to manager Jimy Williams's office remained closed. Team
medical director Arthur Pappas, trainer Jim Rowe, pitching coach
Joe Kerrigan, and vice president of baseball operations Mike Port
were all inside. Meanwhile, the pitcher whose immediate future they
were discussing lingered just outside.
</P>
<P>
   Was Jeff Fassero awaiting word about whether he was being placed
on the disabled list?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm just waiting for (a clubhouse attendant) to get the
umbrella from my golf bag,'' Fassero said. ``It's spitting pretty
good out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was obviously more going on than just pillow talk
regarding Fassero. He said he hurt his neck sleeping badly because
of an oversized pillow in his Atlanta hotel room last weekend,
flip-flopped turns with Pete Schourek, then complained of no
strength in his arm while lasting just two innings Sunday against
the Blue Jays, his shortest start of the season. Fassero had no
explanation for what he called a ``dead arm,'' but the word in the
Toronto clubhouse was that Fassero's back was bothering him.
</P>
<P>
   While Fassero said he would be surprised to go on the DL, he
conceded that he might have to miss a start. ``It's a wait-and- see
thing,'' he said. ``For sure, I don't want to, but I don't want
what happened today to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do the Red Sox, who didn't score until they were down to
their last out in the rubber match of this three-game set with the
Blue Jays and who remain in first place only by default, as the
Yankees are matching them loss for loss. The Yankees, who come in
Monday night after being swept in a four-game series at home by the
White Sox, remain a half-game back in the AL East. The Blue Jays,
four games over .500 for the first time this season, closed to
within a game of the top and can look forward to playing the Sox
again next weekend in SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Eight pitches into the game, the Sox were down, 3-0, as the Blue
Jays went bloop single, bunt single, and Raul Mondesi's 14th home
run into the left-field screen to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third straight game in which a Blue Jay had homered
in the first inning. Mondesi, who later homered off Rheal Cormier
in the eighth for the final Toronto run, hit a two-run home run off
Schourek Friday night, and Tony Batista took Ramon Martinez deep
for a three-run home run Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When Brad Fullmer, a lefthanded hitter, pounded a fastball into
the right-field stands leading off the second, it was 4-0 and
Hipolito Pichardo was taking off his jacket in the bullpen. When
the Sox came out for the third, Fassero remained in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't right,'' Williams said. ``I thought it better to
take him out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has been placing early calls to the bullpen with
alarming frequency. In the last 11 games, nine have been started by
pitchers other than Pedro Martinez. In all but one, Sox starters
have failed to make it into the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Blue Jays, who have now homered in a club-record 17
straight games, starters Schourek, Ramon Martinez, and Fassero
stuck around for a total of only 8 2/3 innings. But that was
sufficient time for the Blue Jays to inflict some serious damage:
20 hits, 15 earned runs, 6 walks, 4 home runs. That comes out to an
earned run average of 15.58.
</P>
<P>
   Can Sammy Sosa pitch?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't pitch,'' said Williams when asked if he might consider
some alterations in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids put us in the particular position we're in. Hang
with 'em. Believe in 'em. They can pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have physical ailments, that's a different story. But
as long as they are healthy and feel good about themselves, I'm
putting them out there every fifth day.''
</P>
<P>
   Another superb job by the Sox' pen _ Mondesi's home run off
Cormier was one of just three hits allowed in seven innings by
Pichardo, Rich Garces, Cormier, and Rod Beck _ gave a sellout crowd
of 32,925 a reason to endure the raindrops that came with greater
insistence in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox were held to just three hits in seven scoreless
innings by journeyman Frank Castillo, who in three previous starts
against the Sox had been cuffed around for 13 runs in 13 innings.
They didn't advance a runner to third until they loaded the bases
against reliever Paul Quantrill in the ninth, and didn't score
until Scott Hatteberg delivered a pinch single off closer Billy
Koch.
</P>
<P>
   But Koch induced Jose Offerman to tap into a force play to end
the game, and the Sox were left to ponder the meaning of losing
their fourth straight series at home, not counting Pedro's mastery
of Cleveland in that rain-made, one-night stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to keep playing,'' Williams said. ``You fight through
this, keep going. You don't drop your head. Nobody's going to feel
sorry for you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
