<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL TIGER EVER BE SATISFIED? 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ What's really frightening is that you
know he's not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Do me a favor. Spread your hands about 6 inches apart. That's
the approximate cumulative distance of six shots that constituted
the difference between Tiger Woods's bogey-free 67 in the final
round of the US Open Sunday and a round of 64 or so. If he had made
only half of those shots, there's your 7 under. And it wasn't too
far back in his mind, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible, but not too realistic, to go out there and
shoot 10 under par,'' he said, wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   Book this, here and now. Tiger Woods will shoot that 61 in a
major. Nothing that has ever been said about the limitations that
apply to every other golfer who has ever lived applies to Tiger
Woods. He is a relentless, single-minded, magnificently talented
workaholic who will simply not be stopped. He was raised to be the
greatest golfer of all-time and he will fulfill his promise.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred to me as he walked up the fabled 18th at Pebble
Beach Sunday that even Tiger Woods might take pains to savor a
moment such as this, because even Tiger Woods is unlikely to stride
up the fairway on the 72d hole of a US Open with a 15-stroke lead
more than once in his career. Then I thought about the putt that
stopped about an eighth of an inch in front of the hole on No. 3,
the bunker shot that came verrry close to holing out on 17, and the
very makable birdie putts that just slid tantalizingly to the left
on 1, 2, 8, or maybe one or two others that could just as easily
have gone in as not and I realized that it is foolish to make any
such assumptions when the person in question is the most supremely
gifted human being ever to participate in this particular form of
human endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   He won this Open by 15, yeah. Oh, I understand the millimeter
nature of this game well enough, but it doesn't change the fact
that under only slightly different circumstances he could easily
have won it by 20, and that's without even factoring in the
aberrational triple bogey he took at No. 3 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Tiger allowed himself a moment of satisfaction
on No. 18. It was, he said, after he deposited his 4-iron on the
fairway that he allowed the fact that he really was going to win
this tournament to sink in. Incidentally, Tiger's club selection
did not meet with the overwhelming approval of gallery members
assembled along the right side of the hole, right in front of
Padres owner John Moores's new ostentatious mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting three hours,'' wailed one fellow. ``I want
to see a wood come out of that bag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' advised his companion. ``He didn't go to Stanford for
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The memory of the driver he hit into the rocks Saturday was all
Tiger needed to go into a play-it-safe mode on 18. He wasn't going
to stain what had been, by his own admission, a fairly wonderful
afternoon of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Had he gone out and shot a reasonably efficient 72 or 73, his
image would not have been tarnished in the slightest. But that's
not the Tiger way. Tiger had a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted a day of golf with no bogeys,'' he confessed.
</P>
<P>
   In order to accomplish that goal, he only needed three
par-saving putts, the best of which was a 15-footer on No. 16.
``That was one of the biggest highlights of the day,'' he beamed.
``I had worked so hard all day to avoid bogeys, and to make that
felt great.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the record, or records, that motivated him. To this
moment, he probably doesn't have a full grasp of everything he
accomplished during this blissful week of golf. He went out Sunday
to play golf properly for golf's sake, to build on his first three
days with yet another demonstration of total golf. He did exactly
that.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else in the 156-man field either flat-out stunk or
fluctuated severely in an attempt to tame Pebble Beach. The other
nine men in the top 10 had a cumulative total of nine subpar
rounds. Tiger was under par three times and even par once. John
Huston was the only other man to submit two subpar rounds and in
between he spit out a 75 and a 76.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone else, Pebble Beach was a classic US Open course,
intimidating and downright unneighborly. For Tiger Woods, Pebble
Beach was a moderate challenge, but little more. Narrow fairways,
firm greens, menacing rough, wind, fog, famine, pestilence,
locusts, photographers, the moneyed scent of all those RRWPs (Rich
Retired White People) walking around. All these had an effect on
155 of the 156 competitors. Some very legitimate people had trouble
breaking 80. Tiger was 12 under.
</P>
<P>
   This is what can, and will, happen when Tiger Woods puts it all
together, and it is not good news for the rest of the golfing
world, not when he's only 24 years old. He drives better than
everyone most of the time. He can do things with his irons no one
else can. His short game is jaw-dropping. And when he putts the way
he did this week, it's like Shaq making his free throws. It's just
plain unfair, is what it is.
</P>
<P>
   What he did by winning this tournament by 15 strokes leaves us
with very few remotely comparable analogies. Help me out. Winning a
Wimbledon final by love, love, and love? A Super Bowl, 100-0? Who
knows? What we do know is that they've been swatting at the little
ball with sticks for a few centuries now and during that time only
one man has won two majors by double figures and that man is Tiger
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   It's beyond even talking about ``Tiger has raised the bar,'' and
these other pros know it, even if they don't want to admit it. The
problem is he is the only golfer in the world who can actually
humiliate people, and there is no doubt that he will continue to
improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always try to get better,'' he said. ``Whether it's new
techniques or new equipment, there are always things you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't upset he failed to birdie the 18th as a
fitting dramatic flourish, but I don't believe him. That would have
been a perfect ending, but if you're Tiger Woods, the good news is
now you have unfinished business. Now you have yet another goal.
And he'll do it, too. He'll win that major with a birdie on 18, and
we all know what he'll want then.
</P>
<P>
   Eagling the 18th to win his record-breaking 19th major would be
a nice touch, don't you think?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
