<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE READY TO PASS ON OLYMPICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Kobe Bryant has his mind on a championship ring and
an engagement ring but sounds ready to skip any involvement with
Olympic rings this summer.
</P>
<P>
   USA Basketball has made overtures toward him as a possible
replacement for the injured Grant Hill on the Olympic team. But the
Lakers' star swingman is leery of the schedule - which runs from
practices in late August through the Games in late September.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is getting married this summer and also plans to spend
time in Italy, where he grew up and now is part-owner of a pro
basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm kind of leaning towards not going,'' he said
Sunday, as the Lakers prepared for Game 6 of the NBA Finals, ``but
to be honest with you I haven't given it that much thought. I'm
just concentrating on this, and focusing on the game (Monday) and
just take it from there. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things I'd like to do this summer,'' he said.
``Spend time with my family, get married, and relax, just take some
time off.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant also cited the awkward timing of the event - the team
returns to the U.S. just before NBA training camps open, the first
week of October.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson supported Bryant's decision. Asked whether
Bryant should play, Jackson said: ``Absolutely not. Kobe's getting
married this summer, it's his personal time, this is something that
should be special for him. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, they had an opportunity to get to Kobe long before
this and before guys backed out of it, relatively speaking. If they
wanted him as an alternate, they probably should have asked him
last summer to be an alternate, if they have such things. But he's
made plans in his own personal life, and he's got to honor that.''
</P>
<P>
   Attitudes: Earlier in the playoffs, veteran Ron Harper bemoaned
the Lakers' lack of killer instinct and said they weren't ``hard
enough'' as a team. But he believes the rough road they've
traveled, losing eight times in 22 playoff games, has had a
positive effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has hardened us up real well, I think,'' he said. ``Believe
me, we saw this four times (in playoff series) now, I think, so it
comes I guess. It comes and goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said: ``It's a physical matter. It's not just a mental
matter. What happened to us (the Pacers) just physically came at
us. ... There were sequences where we just had to stop penetration
through making a charge an obvious call, that you can't overrun us
here, we're just going to get in your way and play basketball in a
defensive posture. And in the process, we were playing a little bit
slip-hardy, kind of what we call a French style of basketball which
is grab-ass ball and as a consequence cost us.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy explanation: Robert Horry has heard enough about the
Lakers' playoff miscues and said the losses are not just about
failing to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen us slip yet,'' he said. ``People expect since
we're up, we're just supposed to come out and step on people, that
the teams we're playing are just the Clippers. But it's not that
way. These teams got a lot of star players on their team, and they
come through when it's pressure time. It's not the fact that we
slipped, the other team just steps up and performs a little bit
better than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Bryant continues to play on a sprained left ankle
but said it's not affecting his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said. ``I can't stop on a dime like I want
to, but for the most part it's fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
