<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA TALKS RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 LA HOYA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was supposed to be a coronation Saturday night
at Staples Center, but it may have turned into a violent retirement
party for Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   What boxers say 90 minutes after losing a world title fight by
the thinnest of margins has to be taken not with a grain of salt
but with a salt lick. Yet, an obviously troubled and downcast De La
Hoya made clear losing the WBC welterweight title by split decision
to ``Sugar'' Shane Mosley had convinced him of what so many people
outside the sport already believe.
</P>
<P>
   It convinced him boxing is a place where business decisions can
influence ringside decisions. Can, and too often do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to live with what goes on around boxing,'' De La
Hoya said after judges Lou Filippo (116-112) and Pat Russell
(115-113) scored what had been a marvelous clash of skills and
wills for Mosley, while judge Marty Sammon had it 115-113 for De La
Hoya. The Globe card made Mosley a 115-113 victor by virtue of his
winning the final five rounds both tactically and physically. Yet
De La Hoya saw it another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things go through your mind after a fight like
this,'' De La Hoya said. ``You start to think, `What happens if
they do give me the decision?' Then there's no rematch. No third
fight. For a lot of people, this is a business. People wanted a
rematch to make more money, but I'm not looking at it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed with that. I just don't feel I can
continue on like this.''
</P>
<P>
   As De La Hoya spoke, his trademark smile was gone. So, too, was
his habit of translating every answer he made from English to
Spanish or the reverse, a courtesy to his bilingual fan base. But
this was not a time for courtesies. It was a time for curt answers
and barely controlled anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a (expletive) business,'' muttered Joel De La Hoya,
the fighter's brother, as the now former champion repeated his
reservations about what had just happened to him.
</P>
<P>
   Although De La Hoya was careful to take nothing away from
Mosley, he also conceded him nothing. When he finally arrived at
the postfight podium nearly two hours after the decision had been
announced, De La Hoya wore a bruised right eye and a broken heart.
One had been caused by Mosley. The other had been caused by his
profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to rethink my career over the next few days,'' De La
Hoya said. ``Think about a lot of things, including retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to rethink my whole game plan in life. It takes a lot
of courage to take on all comers the way I have. Fighters have to
be careful. They can be very stubborn and take on more and more and
more until they cross the line (and pay dearly for it). I have to
decide where I cross that line. There's life after boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   At 27, De La Hoya would seem to have years of life left in
boxing as well as a fruitful life without it, but he has carried
the disappointment of his controversial defeat to Felix Trinidad
inside him for nearly a year, and now it seems to have eaten away
at his soul.
</P>
<P>
   When, only two fights later, he felt he had fought another close
fight and been denied victory not by his opponent but by the
judges, his emotions poured out like a summer thunderstorm, anger
and accusation barely hidden in the shower of words.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, at one point, he did say he ``had no problem'' with
Mosley being handed the decision because ``he deserved it.'' But
five minutes later, he said he thought he had won by one point.
Then he said the judges should have declared a draw. ``To take it
from me like that, I just don't feel it's justice.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya piled up an early lead against Mosley, as he had
against Trinidad, but then began to tire. As he waned, Mosley's
purported speed advantage finally surfaced, and he began to wax De
La Hoya with lead right hands and a stinging jab, switching to
southpaw several times to confuse his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya never backed down and seldom backed up, but the jab
he'd used to bother and even daunt Mosley was less and less in
evidence as the fight wore on. That allowed the challenger to do
just a little bit more in most of the final five rounds, which De
La Hoya lost on two of the three judges' cards.
</P>
<P>
   Against Trinidad, De La Hoya had seemed to build an
insurmountable lead through the first eight rounds before he began
to tire. That night, he chose to box (some would say run) the final
four rounds, and it cost him a heavily disputed decision. This
time, he stalked Mosley throughout the night until the two came
together in the final three minutes and went toe to toe as the
crowd leapt to its feet and let loose a primordial roar of
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Both men fought furiously for what they wanted. Not the WBC's
plastic belt, but simple mastery of the other. Neither got it
fully, but twice Mosley nailed De La Hoya solidly _ solidly enough
to drop a less-focused and fierce opponent. When the final bell
tolled, the two embraced, great warriors who had earned the other's
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a close fight,'' conceded Mosley (35-0), whose face was
bruised and knotted on the right side from the repeated pounding of
De La Hoya's jab and left hook. ``We went toe to toe for 12 rounds.
We showed we're both great warriors. Two great warriors. Oscar is a
great champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really sharp. There were a lot of sharp punches. I had
to make sure I had enough energy left to close the show in that
12th round. I felt I outpointed him. I was just the better man
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the consensus at Staples Center, as was the belief that
viewers had witnessed one of the best fights in years between two
equals. Yet De La Hoya was still lingering on the Trinidad fight,
which he has always believed he won handily.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days leading up to Saturday night's clash with
Mosley, De La Hoya talked incessantly of Trinidad, and after the
defeat, his promoter, Bob Arum, claimed there had been two secret
meetings between members of the Nevada Athletic Commission without
any De La Hoya representative present, meetings he said paved the
way for De La Hoya's first defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Whether true or not, Arum insisted it was that experience, not
the loss to Mosley, that had his franchise fighter talking of
moving into a business in which he could make his own decisions
without relying on others at ringside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may very well be that the last time anyone sees Oscar De La
Hoya is tonight,'' Arum said. ``But you would not have seen him
take this position if the Trinidad thing hadn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar is a good sport. If he heard the same decision without
the Trinidad decision before it, he wouldn't be talking the way he
was talking.''
</P>
<P>
   He may not be talking that way a week from now, either, but for
one more night, Oscar De La Hoya held the boxing world enthralled.
He had lost, but he was still the headline maker. He had lost, but
now he was threatening his sport with a bigger loss.
</P>
<P>
   Himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
