<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER WOODS SHATTERS STORIED RECORDS IN OPEN ROMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Break out the industrial-size eraser.
Tiger Woods has rewritten golf's history book.
</P>
<P>
   Not just at the U.S. Open, where he lapped the field by 15
strokes in Sunday's final round at Pebble Beach Golf Links and
shattered more records than frenzied fans at a disco-demolition
night promotion.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about a rout of all-encompassing, global
proportions. We're talking about eclipsing any whipping
administered by anyone who has ever teed up in one of golf's major
championships.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods drained his final putt at the 18th hole, he did more
than finish further under par (12 under) than any player in Open
history. He did more than match the tournament's lowest scoring
total (272) by closing with a bogey-free 67. He did more than tie
or break seven Open scoring records.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 24, pushed aside the 138-year-old mark of Tom Morris Sr.,
winner of the 1862 British Open, for the most lopsided winning
margin at one of golf's major championships. Morris pounded Willie
Park by 13 strokes. Woods subdued his closest Open pursuers, Ernie
Els and Miguel Angel Jimenez, by 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play as solidly as I did all week, it's hard to describe
the satisfaction. I never had a low point,'' said Woods, who
finished 72 holes without three-putting a green and struck the ball
more crisply _ in his estimation _ than during his 12-stroke
victory at the 1997 Masters. ``It was neat walking up 18 knowing
that, if you just stay alive, you'll win the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods finished as a living, breathing testament to flawless
golf, in the estimation of Els, his final-round playing partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome to watch, just a dominating performance. He was
never in any kind of trouble,'' Els said of Woods' closing round,
when he stretched a 10-stroke lead to a 15-stroke romp and grabbed
a slice of history. ``Whatever I say is an understatement. Just the
perfect display of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   If Morris, who reigned for 138 years as the most dominant
performer in a major championship, had been in the 2000 Open field,
Els said Woods ``would have beat him by 80 shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, however, was more pleased by becoming the first player in
Open history to finish double-digit deep in red numbers at the
Open. Before Woods posted Sunday's 12-under total, the best
previous mark had been 8 under, by Jack Nicklaus and Lee Janzen. To
Woods, that stands as a greater accomplishment than bumping aside
Morris in the domination department.
</P>
<P>
   ``To finish a U.S. Open this many under par, you know you've
played well,'' Woods said. ``You know it's something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Peers were quick to second that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all felt for the longest time that someone was going to
come along who could drive the ball 300 yards and putt like (Ben)
Crenshaw,'' Nick Price said. ``Well, this guy drives the ball
better than anyone I've seen and putts better than Crenshaw. He's a
phenomenon, no doubt about it. When he's on his game, I don't see
anyone challenging him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, who played three practice rounds with Woods before
the tournament, said he saw this coming before Woods struck his
first shot _ or broke his first tournament record _ during
Thursday's round of 65.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him miss one shot in three days,'' O'Meara said. ``At
that point, I thought, `If there's not much wind, he'll set the
record.' Jack Nicklaus has the greatest record in golf. But Tiger
Woods is the greatest player I've seen. He has all the shots. He
has mental toughness. If you built the perfect golfer, you'd build
Tiger Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kite said he was struck by the surgical precision with which
Woods removed all drama from the event during the weekend rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the most sedate crowd I've ever seen for the final
day at the Open,'' Kite said. ``There was so little excitement, it
was almost disappointing. It was like the tournament was already
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, it was. Woods began the day with a 10-stroke lead.
He ended it with 14 pars, four birdies, a slice of history, a U.S.
Open trophy and extreme satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come out here this week and perform the way I did, on one
of the greatest venues there is in golf, it doesn't get much better
than that,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, no one else who has ever played major
championship golf can comprehend the feeling. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
