<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALS TREADING LIGHTLY 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On a dreary afternoon on Yawkey Way, it was the only
measure of comfort for the still-in-first-place-but-oh-so-shaky Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jeff Fassero, Sunday's losing pitcher who may be headed to
the disabled list, noticed when the man inside the Green Monster
hung a 9 beside CHI in the first inning, before NY had taken its
first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it and said, `You've got to be kidding me,''' Fassero
said of the first sign that the Yankees would also be in for a long
day, one that wouldn't end until the Chicago White Sox finished a
17-4 demolition and sweep of the defending champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me feel good,'' Fassero said of the Bronx bombing, one
in which the Yankees were outscored, 42-17, in the four-game set on
their own turf.
</P>
<P>
   Sox designated hitter Brian Daubach was paying attention, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing, especially since it was El Duque,'' Daubach said,
noting that it was the Yankees' Cuban ace, Orlando Hernandez, who
absorbed the first-inning beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure when they come here tomorrow they're not going to be
real happy, either. It's going to be a tough series.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in a span of 25 days, the Sox and Yankees
come together with first place on the line. The Sox already have
traveled twice to New York; this will be the Yankees' first visit
this season to Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   But for what is supposed to be a showdown between the best teams
in the division, both the Sox and Yanks are playing like teams that
won't be occupied come October.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 19, when the Sox beat the Tigers in Fenway Park to
move 12 games above .500, their high-water mark, they have a record
of 10-16. They've lost six of eight series, including their last
four series at home, while splitting a rain-shortened two-game set
in the Bronx last week.
</P>
<P>
   But remarkably, the Yankees, who have won three of the last four
World Series, have matched the Sox nearly loss for loss, going
10-15 in that same time.
</P>
<P>
   You think the Sox have problems? Last week, the Yankees placed
Roger Clemens on the DL with a strained groin and hoped he isn't
out a month. Their second baseman, Chuck Knoblauch, took himself
out of a game last week after making three throwing errors and
followed that up by conking the mother of FOX resident wise guy
Keith Olbermann behind the Yankees' dugout on Saturday. He's a
basket case (Knoblauch, not Olbermann).
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, after being lit up for nine runs, including Jose
Valentin's grand slam, while recording just two outs, El Duque was
taken to the hospital for X-rays after complaining of elbow pain.
He was diagnosed with a right elbow sprain and is day to day.
Yankee starting pitchers are 21-25 with a 5.08 ERA. Since May 19,
the staff ERA is 5.26. So far this month, the ERA has soared to
6.31, due in no small part to a White Sox offense that scored in
double figures in three of the four games.
</P>
<P>
   A long-time baseball man from Toronto took one look at the
scoreboard Sunday and imagined the reaction of Yankee owner George
Steinbrenner. ``You know the smoke signals are traveling back and
forth from New York to Tampa right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Given Steinbrenner's track record, who would be surprised if the
Yankees show up Monday night with Sammy Sosa or Juan Gonzalez in
tow, with pitchers Brad Radke and Scott Erickson not far behind?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not feeling too good about ourselves,'' Yankees manager
Joe Torre told New York reporters Sunday, ``but we keep checking
the standings and we're only a half-game behind. It's amazing to be
in this position with what has happened to us this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a strange four weeks for the four teams that made the
playoffs in the AL last season. It's not just the Sox and Yankees.
The injury-battered Indians, the five-time defending AL Central
champs, are a game above .500 (14-13) in that time but a startling
7 1/2 games back of the surprising White Sox, who are 21-7 since
May 19 and have the majors' best record. The Rangers, who won the
West, are 10-16 since May 19, including a nine-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays, who have taken two out of three from the Sox on
both trips into the Fens, are three games over .500 (15-12) in that
span but have closed to within a game of the Sox in the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew they'd be good,'' Daubach said. ``They got off
to a slow start, but they've been scoring runs all year. They
probably have the best offense in the league. We've got to score
more than five to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Daubach said it's become tougher to play most everybody. ``There
are no pushovers this year,'' he said. ``You've got to play every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox closer Derek Lowe agreed. ``There's not a dominant team like
there was before,'' he said. ``There are so many good teams this
year, it's hard to pull away from anybody. Everyone is so used to
seeing the Yankees win 100 games a year, so when they're not ahead
by five or 10 games, you want to say they're going to go on a run.
But that's not easy with so many good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   What it really says, of course, is that the Yankees, while
retaining much of their former splendor, are finally revealing some
of the same flaws that bedevil good teams that in the past have
fallen short of the Bombers. Like the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what you do before the All-Star break,'' Lowe said,
``what really matters is what you do in the last two months. You
just want to be in it at the All-Star break. That's our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees treading water right alongside them, staying
within striking distance may not be quite as hard as it's been in
the past. That's assuming, of course, someone can cool off those
go-go White Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 0016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7968 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-BLUEJAYS-CASTILLO     06-19 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BLUE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTILLO KEEPS RED SOX IN PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
 JAYS-CASTILLO-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Things are starting to fall into place for Frank
Castillo and the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo, despite a host of quality starts, was saddled with a
2-5 record and 4.71 earned run average entering Sunday's game. But
he is now pitching as the Jays hoped he would when they signed him
as a free agent last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at Fenway Park, he had his best outing of the season,
pitching seven strong innings of three-hit shutout ball as the Jays
thumped the Red Sox, 5-1, and thrust themselves into the AL East
race.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Castillo superb back-to-back starts. Last week in
Detroit, he went seven innings and held the Tigers to five hits and
two runs in Toronto's 4-2 win.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo, who before landing in Toronto pitched for the Cubs,
Rockies, and Tigers, had the Sox eating out of his hand. The
veteran righthander was touched for a leadoff single by Manny
Alexander in the third, a one-out double by Carl Everett in the
fourth, and a leadoff single by Jeff Frye in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed no runner beyond second base before turning his 4-0
lead over to Paul Quantrill and Billy Koch. Quantrill had a 1-2-3
eighth inning but got into trouble in the ninth and was bailed out
by Koch, who notched his second straight save over the Sox and 15th
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Castillo's) pitched very well for us of late, and to shut the
Sox down in this ballpark was quite an effort,'' said Blue Jays
manager Jim Fregosi. ``He threw 120-plus pitches in seven innings
and I just thought he did a heck of a job to get us as far as he
got us.''
</P>
<P>
   Castillo hasn't pitched badly of late and his record coming in
was deceiving. In six of his previous eight starts, he pitched six
or more innings, and his last two efforts _ both on the road _ had
been gems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a good trip,'' said Castillo. ``It started in
Detroit on Monday and ended today. It was a fun week for me.
Location was the key, that and keeping the guys off balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gonzo (Alex Gonzalez) made a great play in the first and Mondy
(Raul Mondesi) a great play in the second and they went out and
scored runs for me. That made it a little bit easier for me to just
go out there, keep the ball down, and throw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Castillo issued just two walks, both with two outs in the second
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking for trouble when you do that in this park,'' he
said, ``but fortunately, I got (Darren) Lewis on a ground ball and
that was the end of that. Things are coming around. I've been
throwing well and the team has been scoring some runs for me and
we've been winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning so much lately, that the Jays are now just a game out of
first place with a six-game homestand on tap. Toronto (37) actually
has won more games than both the Sox (35) and Yankees (34), and
with those two teams about to begin a four-game series Monday
night, the Blue Jays could reach the top before too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good ball right now,'' said Koch. ``You've got
us, Boston, and New York. Three quality teams atop the AL East
battling it out. It's going to be a close race all year. Hopefully
we can piece something together, play like we've been playing, and
take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Fregosi hasn't lost sight of the closeness of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every club in our division has had problems this year,'' he
said. ``At one time or another every club has lost some key
players. No team in the division has really put a streak together
and that's why we're as close as we are. I think it's going to stay
that way all season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
