<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION LOOKING VULNERABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Though the Revolution appear to be on
the verge of adding striker Jorge Cadete, other weaknesses are
becoming obvious despite the team's first-place standing.
</P>
<P>
   A proven goal scorer should be a priority for the Revolution,
who completed the first half of the MLS season with one of the
least-productive forward lines in the league. Wolde Harris
converted his sixth goal of the season in a 4-2 loss to the
MetroStars Saturday, but his strike partners have been ineffective
and/or inefficient except for a brief stint by Jamar Beasley.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolution's 7-5-4 mark is on a pace to set a team
record for points. And the Revolution appear to be far better
prepared to progress than in past seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But potential vulnerabilities persist.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic, experienced strikers have been able to take advantage
of the Revolution's inexperience in central defense. Mauricio
Wright derailed Adolfo ``El Tren'' Valencia in the second half
Saturday, but Valencia had already done his damage, outmaneuvering
Brian Dunseth for the tying goal late in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Fernando Clavijo might also have to reconsider his options
off the bench. Some of the young players have made important
contributions, the most recent being Beasley's two-goal performance
in a 3-0 win over San Jose June 10. But Carlos Parra and William
Sunsing both remained in reserve for the MetroStars game,
reinforcing the sense of diminished confidence in them after a 1-0
loss to the Mid-Michigan Bucks in a US Open Cup match last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Imad Baba and Ted Chronopoulos have injected effectiveness into
the offense from their wing midfield positions, but Baba appeared
to be slowed by a leg injury and Chronopoulos was out with a
strained back against the MetroStars. Now the Revolution must
prepare to meet San Jose without suspended midfielders Leonel
Alvarez and Ivan McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   Mauricio Ramos returned from Japan to provide a midfield point
of reference. But if the Earthquakes concentrate on marking Ramos
out of the game in San Jose, the Revolution will struggle to find
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   These are problems Cadete will not be in a position to resolve,
even if he arrives next week. The earliest he could be expected to
play for the Revolution would be July 4.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to the MetroStars began a five-game road trip the
Revolution seem ill-prepared to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough loss to take (against the MetroStars) because
it was a 6-point turnaround,'' Chronopoulos said. ``If we had won,
we would be 10 points ahead of them and feeling very confident
going into San Jose. But it's not the end of the world. We are
still in first place, and we will go on from here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad I wasn't out there, but it was better to rest. I'll
be ready by Wednesday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
