<SLUG> BC-RAC-LOUDON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ARBOR DAY AT LOUDON 
</HEADLINE>
 CLASSIC-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Although rain postponed the featured Chevy Trucks
Superbike race of the 77th American Motorcyclist Association's
Loudon Classic _ it is rescheduled for 11 a.m. Monday at New
Hampshire International Speedway _ it hardly put a damper on Chris
Arbor's day.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old native of Salem, N.H., who works as a service
manager at Riverside Motorsports in Somerville, Mass., successfully
negotiated a wet and slippery racing surface at NHIS to score his
first career victory in Sunday's Buell Pro Thunder race.
</P>
<P>
   Arbor used his knowledge of the 12-turn road circuit and his
supreme confidence in wet race conditions to wrest the lead away
from runner-up Shawn Conrad of Sheboygan Falls, Wis., with one lap
remaining in the 24-lap race. Arbor captured a $5,000 winner's
purse, which had been doubled by NHIS track owner Bob Bahre as a
means of enticing 22 out of 40 Pro Thunder riders to brave the foul
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it ranked as his biggest payday, Arbor did a double
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean, biggest?'' he asked incredulously. ``It's
like my only payday.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbor's only mistake of the day came when he fell out of the
lead on Lap 16 as he skidded off course and into a tire wall near
Turn 3. He was able, however, to remain in the saddle and keep his
Ducati ride from hitting the ground, allowing him to jump back into
the fray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stay loose and not get overtired,'' he explained.
``I had a knee injury last year and it's not quite right yet, so I
had my leg off (the bike) going into 3 and tried to stretch my
knee. I locked the front wheels, went into the tire barriers, and
barely saved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got back on the track and took two laps to calm myself
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he did, Arbor was able to chase down Conrad. On Lap 23,
Arbor ripped off his fastest lap of the race (1 minute 31.547
seconds) and passed Conrad at the same spot in Turn 3 where he had
gone off the course earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know I had the lead,'' Conrad said. ``I was just
riding around comfortably and giving lap traffic plenty of room. I
made the mistake of looking at the scoring tower to see what lap we
were on, but I didn't see what position I was in. It's my mistake
that I didn't do that. I think I could've gone faster there at the
end if I knew I had the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   That might have posed a problem for Conrad, especially since ``I
haven't had any wet laps here ever,'' he said. But that wasn't the
case with Arbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee I had more confidence out there in the wet than
anybody racing today,'' said Arbor, who had four years of racing
experience in the Loudon Road Racing Series at NHIS but only two
weekends as an AMA-licensed professional. ``I was in no rush to get
the lead. I just tried to stay smooth and stay under control.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Filice of Modesto, Calif., took the checkered flag in the
MBNA 250cc Grand Prix over runner-up Charles Sorensen, who extended
his lead in the standings, and third-place finisher Jeff Wood of
Mansfield, Mass. The 37-year-old Filice, who came out of a
five-year retirement this season, recorded his fourth 250 GP
victory at NHIS and 23d overall in the series. ``I always wanted to
come back to racing,'' said Filice. ``When I did this year, I
wanted to do it right. I didn't want to be a backmarker because
that wouldn't be racing to me.'' . . . Jocelin, the 29-year-old
female Yamaha rider from Winslow, Maine, finished 23d in the 250cc
race, her best effort of the season. She crashed in the season
opener at Daytona March 12 and recorded a DNF after a mechanical
failure in her first race back at Road Atlanta this month . . .
Aaron Yates won the Pro Hondo Oils 600 Supersport Race, the first
event, over runner-up Jamie Hacking and third-place finisher Eric
Bostrom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
