<SLUG> BC-LABIZ-EXODUS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. ISN'T TAKING CARE OF BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Upon taking the city's helm seven years ago,
millionaire businessman Richard Riordan pledged to make Los Angeles
a business-friendly place.
</P>
<P>
   But as he enters his final stretch as mayor of the nation's
second largest city, economists and community leaders think the
city has woefully failed to reach its potential as a pivotal
business center.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the city has watched large corporations move their
headquarters to other cities; business tax receipts have declined
in the past decade when adjusted for inflation; nine major
corporations are suing the city alleging double taxation; and
experts brand the city among the most expensive places to do
business in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one of the most potentially powerful economic bases in
the United States, but getting it to function on all cylinders is
very difficult,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist at the Los
Angeles Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders and economists don't blame the mayor. Rather, they
applaud his effort to resuscitate the city's standing as an
international business and industry hub but note he has been unable
to move many needed reforms through the political processes at City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But they say the city has struggled to recover from the 1992
L.A. Riots and the 1994 Northridge Earthquake while witnessing a
decade of unprecedented U.S. economic growth sail by with little to
show for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I think the Riordan administration, working with the
council, has done a masterful job in attempting to rebuild, we've
had a long way to come,'' said City Controller Rick Tuttle. ``When
you look at it in terms of real dollars, we still have a ways to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles took in $260 million in business tax receipts in
1990. This year, the city is expected to collect $310 million,
which Tuttle's office said translates to a decline when adjusted
for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles metropolitan area, anchored by the city of Los
Angeles, ranked 120th in a Forbes magazine list of the best areas
in the nation to do business. And the entire county still has
117,000 fewer jobs than at its peak in 1989, despite a diving
unemployment rate nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The number of businesses paying taxes in the city has increased
since Riordan's election in 1993. But that total includes many
small businesses and, according to some observers, could include an
unknown number of established enterprises that only began paying
city taxes as the city announced it intended to step up collection
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the city is defending itself against the very types
of powerhouses it aims to woo. Nine major corporations, including
Eastman Kodak and the owners of five department stores, have sued
the city, alleging that its business tax system unfairly benefits
locally based businesses while discriminating against companies
based elsewhere that do business in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could get a better report card,'' said Carol Schatz,
president of the Central City Organization, which advocates for
downtown business interests. ``As you move through business circles
... you still hear from too many business people that L.A. is a
difficult city to do business in.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's economic development staff members said they are
confident that the city's ability to keep and attract businesses
will surge after his initiative to improve the city's business-tax
system is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, the mayor has proven that he has some real vision,
and when he proposed tax reform more than a year ago, it was the
right thing to do,'' said Deputy Mayor Rocky Delgadillo.
</P>
<P>
   A key component to reform is simplifying the convoluted business
tax system, Delgadillo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can solve the business tax situation, I think we will be
a real powerhouse in the region and people won't be making
decisions to move across the street,'' Delgadillo said in a
reference to companies relocating to adjacent cities with lower
business taxes and fees.
</P>
<P>
   The city's business tax advisory committee, which has been in
place for five years, plans to make its recommendations in October
to simplify the business tax code.
</P>
<P>
   Also crucial, officials say, is targeting tens of thousands of
businesses that are believed to be operating without paying city
business tax. The city - which estimates some 60,000 businesses
aren't paying the levy - is supporting state legislation to help
municipalities identify the scofflaws.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser pointed to other reasons for the city's difficulty in
attracting business. Some business owners are dismayed, he said, by
strife in the Los Angeles Unified School District, the relative
shortage of city land available for building, and political
infighting between council members representing different areas of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers will frequently make the comment that they get
caught between two sort-of-competing groups,'' Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Councilman Mike Hernandez, who chairs the council's
Community and Economic Development Committee, thinks the city is on
the verge of a renaissance. Its ability to bounce back from the
riots and earthquake will only make it stronger, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to survive some major catastrophes that have
shown the willpower,'' he said. ``I don't think there's any other
city like ours.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
