<HEADLINE>
CORA MAKES MOST OF SECOND CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Alex Cora couldn't earn the Dodgers starting
shortstop job in spring training, but he's taking advantage of his
second chance.
</P>
<P>
   Since being recalled from Albuquerque on May 31, Cora has
received significant playing time and prompted manager Davey
Johnson to go with a platoon of the left-handed hitting Cora and
original starter Kevin Elster, a right-hander whose hitting has
cooled off after a fast start. Cora started again Sunday against
St. Louis right-hander Darryl Kile.
</P>
<P>
   Cora, 24, entered Sunday's game batting .272 and had hit in
seven consecutive games earlier in the month. Elster's average has
dropped to .222. He batted just .176 during the 10-game homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Elster, and I told him I'd be doing a little
platooning,'' Johnson said. ``Not necessarily straight platooning,
he could still be in there against some right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna use this time to get Alex comfortable. I think
we've accomplished that.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting better After a shaky beginning, second baseman Mark
Grudzielanek is settling in at his new position and providing solid
defense. His error-free game Sunday was his 13th in a row. The
converted shortstop has just one error in his last 31 games and six
in 64 games played this season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers remain near the bottom of the National League in
fielding. Only Florida and San Diego had more errors than the
Dodgers' 57 entering Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Raising awareness: Players wore temporary blue ribbon tattoos
Sunday as a sign of solidarity in support of finding a cure for
prostate cancer. All major-league players were to have worn the
tattoos while umpires, coaches and some players wore blue
wristbands.
</P>
<P>
   The accessories were part of CaP Cure's annual Home Run
Challenge in which fans pledge donations based on the number of
home runs hit in games during Father's Day week.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Shawn Green's single in the third inning Sunday
marked the 49th consecutive game he reached base safely. He has
reached base in 64 of the Dodgers' 67 games, 45 of which he got on
at least twice.... After an off day today, the Dodgers start a
six-game trip to Houston and St. Louis on Tuesday. In the National
League, only the Cardinals have more wins on the road than the
Dodgers, who are 19-14 away from home this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
