<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7978 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-19 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS NOT READY TO CONCEDE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Lakers are scheduled to win the NBA title late
Monday night or early Tuesday morning. Almost anyone here without
Indiana ties will tell you that. Angelenos talk about the title as
if it were a flight in perpetual holding pattern, circling LAX
before being cleared for a runway.
</P>
<P>
   When the title arrives, there will be a party on Figueroa
Street. Commentators will regale you with Six Degrees of Michael
Jordan (``Well, if you do a word scramble on `Michael Jordan,' you
can find either `O'Neal' or `LA,' so this is destiny . . . `Bryant'
has six letters and Michael won six titles, so Kobe must be the
next Michael . . . A young Michael signed with Phil Knight of Nike,
Nike is in Oregon, Ahmad Rashad went to college in Oregon, Rashad
is one of Michael's best friends, and, right now, Ahmad is
interviewing Phil Jackson, who coaches Shaq and coached
Michael!''). ``Dynasty'' will be used about 325 times.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it won't.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of parties sometimes forget a few details, and this
is no exception. Has anyone considered what will happen if guys
named Jalen, Reggie, and Mark crash the party? Has anyone factored
in the obvious? That, you know, the Pacers can still win this
thing?
</P>
<P>
   I know I didn't before coming here. Part of the reason is that
the NBA hasn't had a true Super Bowl III-type upset in the 1980s or
'90s. The closest you can get is the Celtics' win over the Lakers
in '84. But do you really want to say a team that had both Larry
Bird and an '81 title on the shelf upset someone? There were no
gasps when the Rockets, Bulls, Spurs, Lakers, Pistons, and 76ers
won titles, either.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that history, it's easy to become absorbed in the
current LA hype. Check that: It's easy to become absorbed from
afar. At close range, these Lakers scare me. I saw them Sunday, and
they had a monks-in-meditation aura about them, which would be fine
if they were monks in meditation. They had such a flower-child calm
that I had a vision of them huddling before Game 7. That's a real
problem since, according to the itinerary, they're supposed to win
the title in Game 6. These Lakers don't exude the kind of calm of a
parent in a crisis; peel away the top layer of their calm, and
you'll find arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. They expect to win it. But they also lost their last game
by 33 points. There are three explanations for a performance like
that in a championship series. One is that you had a bad day, which
everyone has. Two is that you gave up. Three is that the other team
did something for which you have no answer.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers know they can always get 30 or 40 points from O'Neal.
Bird knows the Pacers don't have anyone who can guard the league's
MVP, so the coach prays Shaq won't go for 50. Next year, Bryant
will be a consistently dominant player. He is the one player in the
league who is capable of winning the MVP and Defensive Player of
the Year trophies in the same season, something that hasn't been
done since 1988 (a guy named MJ pulled it off). I like Bryant a
lot. He is smart, charismatic, and beautiful to watch. He is also _
unlike Shaq _ guardable.
</P>
<P>
   If I were a Laker fan, I would be buoyed by a couple of
historical endorsements. I would know my team didn't lose three
games in a row all year and, as the memorable refrain of the
most-recited June stat tells us, I would know no team has ever come
back from a 3-1 deficit to win a title. I would also know this is
not a great Laker team, and I would realize the Pacers knew it,
too. Shaq and Kobe are the best guard-center combination in the
league. Glen Rice's game, though, is an echo of what it was. Robert
Horry, Ron Harper, Rick Fox, and Brian Shaw are all inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   This team is beatable. Its difficulty in closing games has been
traced to a lack of focus, although that's not the real weakness.
LA is a classic first-impression team. Glance at it, and you are
blown away. Study it for five or six games, and you can decode it.
</P>
<P>
   Really, why have we already given the title to the Lakers? They
lead this series, 3-2, and it could easily be reversed. That point
was made to Bird Sunday, and the coach responded with a dry, ``But
it's not.'' The Pacers certainly have their flaws. Their best
post-up player is a slow, 6-foot-2-inch point guard (Mark Jackson).
They have a point guard playing small forward (Jalen Rose) and a
7-4 center (Rik Smits) who has the soul of a shooting guard. They
have an old, 3-point shooting center (Sam Perkins) who was drafted
after retiree Jordan and before retiree Charles Barkley. Chris
Mullin, who is on the bench, was drafted in the same year as
bygones such as Keith Lee and Ennis Whatley.
</P>
<P>
   They are aged and also wise. They are much better shooters than
the Lakers. And, trust me, they are hungrier than the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a completely different team than we were at the
beginning of the series,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that his team knows what to expect now. No one is
shocked when scenes such as Sunday's develop: A quiet media pack
suddenly begins to sprint to a corner, as if it is being chased
through Jurassic Park. You soon learn that Phil Jackson will be
speaking in that corner, and the rush is for prime camera and
microphone position.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is exaggerated during the Finals. The games are
longer, the commentary is more intense, and the premature
dismissals of a team come much more, well, prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   But step back for a moment. Remember the Trail Blazers had the
Lakers down by 15 points in Game 7 at home. They lost. They didn't
lose because Jackson found a way to merge pop culture with
mysticism. He didn't combine the triangle offense with Zen and
``Shaft'' to vault past the Blazers. His team won because its
opponents became tense and missed easy shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers won't do that. They all recite the mantra that is
tattooed onto Jalen Rose's left arm: Nothing to Lose. The words
have been on Rose's arm since his senior year in high school, but
the message seemed more visible Sunday. The Lakers had better end
the series Monday night. If they don't, the Pacers will win it,
giving the NBA its first ``upset'' champion in two decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
