<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATSON STRUGGLES IN FINAL ROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH - Tom Watson took a ride in the time machine Sunday
afternoon and it helped ease a disappointing final round in which
he failed to qualify for an automatic return for his 29th U.S.
Open.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's trip down memory lane came when his tee shot landed in
the rough left of the flagstick on No. 17 at Pebble Beach Golf
Links. It was almost the same spot from where he launched his
miraculous birdie chip-in to defeat Jack Nicklaus in the 1982 Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball ended up left of the green, Bruce (Edwards), my
caddie (who also caddied for Watson in '82), said, 'No! I can't
believe that - not again!'
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a little different situation, obviously,'' Watson
said.
</P>
<P>
   A different result, too.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Watson did as Edwards suggested 18 years ago - he
merely got it close but not close enough to avoid bogey. And
although Watson birdied 18 - as he also did in '82 to lock up the
two-stroke win over Nicklaus - the final-round 73 left him 296 and
three strokes shy of automatic qualifying for next year's Open.
</P>
<P>
   The top 15 finishers and ties in each Open get to return the
following year. Watson finished in a tie for 27th Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there with the idea of trying to shoot 3-under par
to try to get exempt next year,'' said Watson. He added that,
health permitting, he would try to qualify for the 2001
championship at Southern Hills if the U.S. Golf Association did not
extend him another exemption as it did this year - ``for which I'm
grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his first birdie try from that spot on No. 17 since he
sank one of the most-memorable shots in Open history, Watson said,
``I was thinking about holing it - that would have been a birdie to
talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   More Watson: In talking about that tournament-clinching shot
earlier this week, Watson remembered that ``probably in the stands,
there were probably close to 1,500 people. But I've had, over the
course of 18 years, probably 6,000 to 10,000 people saying they
were there.''
</P>
<P>
   Open schedule: Next year's U.S. Open will be played at Southern
Hills in Tulsa, Okla., followed by trips to Bethpage Black in New
York (2002), Olympia Fields near Chicago (2003), New York's
Shinnecock Hills (2004) and North Carolina's Pinehurst No. 2 in
2005.
</P>
<P>
   Woods a wonder: Winner Tiger Woods, only the fifth player to win
three different USGA championships, moves into a tie for fourth in
all-time USGA titles with seven. He previously won three U.S.
Junior Amateur titles and three U.S. Amateur titles - all
consecutively.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, the only player to win those three USGA titles, joins
Johnny Miller as the only player to win the Open and Junior
Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   With this win, Woods becomes only the 13th player to lead the
Open start to finish and the fifth to do so without being tied at
the end of any round.
</P>
<P>
   He exits Pebble Beach Golf Links with Open records for low
36-hole score (tied at 134), largest lead after 54-hole (10
strokes, to break a 79-year-old standard) and lowest Open
tournament score (72, to tie Jack Nicklaus and Lee Janzen).
</P>
<P>
   He also has the record for largest 54-hole lead in any major
(tied with Henry Cotton in 1934 British Open). His 15-stroke
winning margin breaks a 138-year-old record for any major, set by
Old Tom Morris, who won the British Open by 13 strokes over Willie
Park in 1862. In the modern era, Woods held the winning margin
record with his 12-stroke victory Tom Kite in the 1997 Masters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
