<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER'S TALE 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Yellowed, frayed, and covered with a
century's dust, the pages of golf's history books were scattered to
the Pacific winds Sunday, rendered senseless by a young man whose
genius brought the game as close to the edge of perfection as ever
witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods did more than shoot 4-under-par 67 and win the 100th
playing of the US Open on the fabled holes of Pebble Beach Golf
Links with records for score (12-under 272) and margin of victory
(15 shots); he dominated a major championship in a manner the sport
has not seen since the days of Old Tom Morris. And we are talking
138 years ago, folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My words probably can't describe it, so I'm not even going to
try,'' said Ernie Els, whose willingness to help the United States
Golf Association fill out a field that Woods could knock silly,
earned him a reward of $390,150 for sharing second place with
Spain's Miguel Angel Jimenez (71_287).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, second place in the 2000 US Open means you were as
close to Woods as the folks strolling the beach hundreds of feet
down the cliffs from where he was creating his masterpiece. Woods
had won this US Open, for all intents and purposes, with an opening
65 as foundation for ensuing trips of 69 and 71, but since 72 holes
is dictated, the 24-year-old maestro decided to close it out with a
clinic to earn his $800,000 and become just the eighth wire-to-wire
winner of this championship.
</P>
<P>
   Woods found 10 of Pebble Beach's 14 narrow fairways, navigated
his way to impossible greens 15 of 18 times, and wore the look that
his beleaguered group of challengers dread. ``He meant business,''
said Els, Woods's playing partner who felt more rundown than
runner-up. ``I'm kind of embarrassed. Finishing second is good, but
15 shots behind?''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how those 20, 30, even 40 behind felt, for during a
tournament in which the field averaged 75.355 and no one else was
able to get under par, Woods was able to put up a performance that
reminded of his 1997 Masters triumph by 12 shots. (Indeed, he's the
only player in history to win two major championships by
double-digit margins.)
</P>
<P>
   Augusta was nice, but ``to win our national championship, being
American,'' said Woods. ``It's a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   So utterly dominating was Woods that you need a time tunnel for
perspective. Only three previous times had a major championship
winner prevailed by double digits _ Old Tom Morris at the 1862
British Open (13 shots), Young Tom Morris in that event eight years
later (12), Willie Smith (11) in the 1899 US open _ a reality so
chilling that even today's players of great skill were praying for
miracles.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to shoot 85,'' said Lee Westwood (71_289, T-5th), when
asked how someone could overtake Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with a 10-shot lead, Woods could have afforded an 81,
but that's the type of negative thought that has no chance of
penetrating his mind. ``I knew if I went out there and made no
bogeys, if I was patient, I knew I'd make a putt here and there and
maybe increase the lead,'' said Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a plan carried out to perfection, for Woods missed
just one green in going out with nine straight pars. He was stuck
at 8 over and his cushion had been trimmed to nine shots, but Woods
had very little reason to panic because every PGA Tour's worst
nightmare was on display _ Tiger Woods putting well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back at each and every round,'' said Woods, ``I
made important par putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Like at the par-5 sixth hole, which he played sloppily after a
fairway-splitting drive. His second shot, as it had done in Round
3, ended up in hay next to a bunker and Woods didn't have much of a
shot. He punched out through the green and into more thick stuff,
and his fourth shot left him a 6-foot putt for par, which he
drained.
</P>
<P>
   A birdie at the 10th broke his string of pars, then he became
just the second player in US Open history to reach double digits
under par when he poured in an 18-footer at the par-3 12th. Heading
in that direction felt good, so Woods knocked a sand wedge to 1
foot on the par-4 13th and made that birdie. At the par-5 15th he
lofted another sand wedge to 8 feet and made that to get into an
area of red numbers that has never been negotiated in 100 rich
years of this event.
</P>
<P>
   Nice, said Woods, but what really got him pumped was the 16th, a
15-foot putt that saved par. ``I had worked so hard not to make a
bogey, if I had missed that putt, I would have been ticked at
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   No fear of that, because he drained that putt just as he had
drained every other big putt that got in his way. His march to his
first US Open and third major championship, said Woods, was won
with his putting and a short game that always gave him chances to
make par.
</P>
<P>
   And the best thing, it was suggested, was that next month's
British Open is at St. Andrews, a course that sets up nicely for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Woods paused, but didn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The records are great, but you don't really pay attention to
that. You pay attention to the fact that I got my green coat
(Masters win) and here this week, I got the trophy. Now I get to go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is where most of the world's best players wish he would
stay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
