<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS CONFIDENT ENTERING GAME 6
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Glen Rice did not order the Dom Perignon.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson didn't ponder the parade route.
</P>
<P>
   And Ron Harper certainly did not study the backs of his hands to
determine which of his seven ringless fingers should get the next
diamond-encrusted beaut.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Lakers were mostly business Sunday, as they prepared for
tonight's Game 6 of the Finals, and a possible date with official,
NBA-licensed championship confetti. But there was no mistaking
their confidence that the celebration is near.
</P>
<P>
   Now and again, they flashed signs of humility over the 33-point
pounding they took Friday from the Indiana Pacers. But dismissing
the pain of Game 5 proved as easy as saying goodbye to sleepy
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, back in their comfort zone, the Lakers sounded ready
to finish this series tonight at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the city is going to be pumped up, I think the fans
will be pumped up and the team is going to be pumped up. I look
forward to the game,'' Shaquille O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here,'' Jackson said, ``to win a basketball game, and
we're going to do it on Monday night, and that's what we want to
do. That's the only game there is right now for us is Monday's
game.''
</P>
<P>
   No mention of a Game 7 on Wednesday. No hint that the Lakers are
taking the win-one-of-two approach. And no lack of motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember, the last game we got our butts kicked,
so we're definitely going to come out and play hard,'' Rice said.
``Once we win the ring, (things) will be more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   An out-of-town reporter wanted a clarification on that last
sentiment. ``Like I said, once we win the ring,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the Lakers spent Sunday morning reviewing film from
their 120-87 Game 5 loss, digesting how the the Pacers could shoot
57 percent and take 36 free throws, how Kobe Bryant could miss 16
of 20 field goals and how they could be outrebounded by 12.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis was brief. All the Lakers figure they need is a
return to the aggressiveness that got them a 3-2 lead in this
series. That trait was clearly lacking as the Pacers freely drove
the lane Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to see how you perform sometimes to understand what
happens to you,'' Jackson said. ``There's a lot of things that
happen in the course of aggressiveness. When you take the ball, or
you take the game towards somebody, everything seems to fall in
place. And that happened with the Pacers just coming harder at us
than we went at them. As a consequence, all the things fell in
their direction, and we had to see that to remedy it, so to
speak.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the only Lakers showing an obvious edge were O'Neal
(35 points) and Rick Fox (one flagrant foul, one technical foul,
several scrums and a lot of elbows).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't put your foot down,'' Fox said, ``then guys are
going to walk over you, teams are going to have less respect for
you. And in the past, that's been the case with us. No one has
respected us as a team that's willing to go out and take a game.
And until you show a team that you're willing to do whatever it
takes and you're not going to be walked over, as we have been in
the past, being swept 4-0 each year, they're going to continue to
do it. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about winning the game,'' he said. ``And my whole
attitude is simply do whatever it takes to win, that's what Game 6
will have to be about. There is no, 'Oh, I wish I could have done
this,' 'I wish I would have stepped up to Jalen Rose,' or 'I wish I
would have been more aggressive with Rik Smits or boxed this one
out' or 'I wish my energy would have been a lot higher than Austin
Croshere's.' There is none of that. So you don't meet it, you bring
an energy that's greater than theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, the Lakers often misplace that energy when
they leave town. They have failed in all five elimination games on
the road, often badly.
</P>
<P>
   But then they come home and produce routs and miracles: A
27-point rout of Sacramento to win the first round, a 22-point
demolition of Phoenix to win the second round, a fourth-quarter
comeback from 15 points down to defeat Portland in the conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when we take a whuppin' like that, we respond well,''
O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, give the Lakers a few minutes of embarrassment,
and they'll respond with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like talking about stuff like that because I'm a
little superstitious,'' Robert Horry said, ``but hopefully,
everything will stay true to form. Every time we play bad, really
bad, we usually come out and play well. Hopefully, we can keep it
the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
