<HEADER>
A7984 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     06-19 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER LEAVES PEERS IN WOODS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There goes the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Jack's old neighborhood. And Watson's. And Hogan's.
</P>
<P>
   Golf, not to mention its storied links at Pebble Beach, will
never seem the same anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, golf's fresh prince, gave the grand game a four-day
makeover this past weekend. Par, the official language, never
sounded so plain.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers are not supposed to win the U.S. Open by 15 strokes.
Golfers are supposed to hack their way around a U.S. Open course,
lose a dozen Titleists and pray the rosary for pars.
</P>
<P>
   But there it was Sunday for all to see. It was Secretariat
again, charging alone down the home stretch at the Belmont. It was
Joe Montana, lapping the Broncos. It was Bush, steamrolling
Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Even for those who refuse to sit still for televised golf, it
became riveting TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mind-boggling how he could lap the field like that,'' Dr.
Trey Holland, president of the U.S. Golf Association, said at
Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Years from now, perhaps, dads will tell their sons how on
Father's Day, 2000, they sat in front of the family Sony and
watched the great Tiger Woods run rings around the best golfers in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, Tiger does it again. Which he well might.
</P>
<P>
   There goes the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods began the final round Sunday with a 10-stroke lead,
it broke a record that had been on the U.S. Open books for 79
years. Had Tiger simply toured the Pebble Beach, Calif., course in
par, his closest pursuer, Ernie Els, would have had to shoot a 60
to overtake him.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. Nor did young Woods, who closed with a 4-under 67
and, in the process, made a mockery of everyone else's 72-hole
score.
</P>
<P>
   The Nick Faldos, the Vijay Singhs, the Colin Montgomeries. While
Woods was making 21 birdies, the best score that any of the mere
mortals in the field could shoot for the four days was 3 over par.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Woods talked about the ``sense of calmness'' that he felt
all week.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe he did. But his fellow pros looked like fawns caught
in the headlights.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was golf, not a Don King weigh-in. What you saw, though,
was a psych job, an intimidation the likes of which golf has never
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III said it back at the Bay Hill tournament in March
and was promptly shussed by his fellow pros. The best players in
the world don't get intimidated by anyone, they tsk-tsked.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. And why did they all seem to wet their Dockers this
week when they saw Tiger begin to pull away at Pebble Beach?
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, many seem to remain gracious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's magical,'' pro Bobby Clampett said. ``But nothing he does
surprises me.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Tom Watson: ``He has set a standard only he can reach. And
it's a great thing for the popularity of golf. He brings to the
game youth, diversity and commitment _ and it's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some pros might even share Watson's sentiments. But I
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Does golf need the weekly competition to be successful? History
suggests that golf, indeed, thrives when it boasts a dominant
player _ a Ben Hogan, an Arnold Palmer or a Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   But it also thrived, in part, because Palmer was challenged by
Nicklaus, who in turn had to vie each week with the likes of Lee
Trevino, Gary Player and eventually Watson.
</P>
<P>
   After last week, who is Tiger Woods' Trevino?
</P>
<P>
   David Duval? Get serious.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia? Check back in two years.
</P>
<P>
   When he played at Colonial in 1997, Woods was 21 and
temperamental. With a chance to win on the tournament's final day,
he swan-dived to a 72, making double bogey twice. All day long, he
muttered. He cussed. On the ninth fairway, he got admonished by a
playing partner for rudely walking ahead while the player was still
shooting. Woods left Colonial that day in a huff.
</P>
<P>
   But the Woods we see now is three years older and three years
wiser. His well-chronicled outburst Saturday morning was quelled
quickly with an apology and an afternoon of birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Replaced, he said, by the ``sense of calmness.''
</P>
<P>
   Calmness? Easy for Tiger Woods to say.
</P>
<P>
   There goes the neighborhood. Wow. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
