<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT CARDINALS AT OWN GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fans with tickets for the outfield seats knew
better than to follow the Los Angeles tradition of arriving late.
</P>
<P>
   More than an hour before Sunday's game against the St. Louis
Cardinals, both the left- and right-field bleachers at Dodger
Stadium were filled with more fans than usual through the first few
innings of a game. The chance to see Mark McGwire take batting
practice prompted the early arrivals, but there was no shortage of
power hitting early in the game either - and it wasn't all from
McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, McGwire hit a two-run home run to right
field that went an estimated 425 feet, but home runs by Eric Karros
and Adrian Beltre helped the Dodgers to a 6-3 victory in front of
50,713 and prevented the Cardinals from sweeping the three-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   Karros' leadoff home run to left field in the second inning was
his 20th of the season. It marks the quickest Karros has reached
the mark and makes him the fourth player in Dodgers history to have
at least six consecutive 20-home run seasons, tying him with Ron
Cey and trailing only Gil Hodges (11) and Duke Snider (nine).
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's home run was his 25th of the season and second in as
many days, giving him 546 for his career, one shy of Mike Schmidt
for seventh on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' Shawon Dunston came close to adding another home run
when he led off the third inning with a drive that bounced back
into fair territory after hitting the top of the fence in left
field. Dunston was thrown out trying to advance to third on the
play.
</P>
<P>
   No extra-base hits were required to give the Dodgers the lead an
inning after Karros brought them within one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When E.K. hit it, hit that home run, it made them come down,''
Dodgers starter Chan Ho Park said of the shift in momentum he felt.
</P>
<P>
   Park started the four-run third inning with a single and Todd
Hollandsworth reached on a fielder's-choice grounder. Mark
Grudzielanek followed with a single to right field that drew a
throwing error, which brought in the tying run and advanced
Grudzielanek to third. Grudzielanek scored the go-ahead run by
beating Ray Lankford's throw to the plate on a sacrifice fly by
Gary Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre extended the lead to 6-2 with a two-out, two-run home run
to left center, after which only one player from either side
advanced past second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's encouraging, but we're still not swinging up and down the
lineup like I'd like us to,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Park (9-4) faced the minimum three batters in the third, fourth
and sixth innings. He earned his fifth consecutive win and finished
with nine strikeouts and no walks in seven innings. The
right-hander was removed after the seventh inning because of
cramping in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any other time, I'd let him keep going,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis starter Darryl Kile (10-4) did not allow a hit in his
final three innings before being replaced by Heathcliff Slocumb in
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Shaw retired the side in order for the Dodgers in the ninth
to earn his first save since May 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7986 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-DEVILRAYS     06-19 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DEVIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FINISH WORST ROAD TRIP SINCE '86 WITH A THUD
</HEADLINE>
 RAYS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The lineup squandered scoring
opportunities and failed to produce an extra-base hit for only the
second time this season.
</P>
<P>
   A seventh-inning error allowed four unearned runs to cross the
plate, and, of course, the offense grounded into two more double
plays.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Texas Rangers put the finishing touches on their worst
road trip in 14 seasons with Sunday's 6-1 loss to the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing good ball right now,'' right-hander Rick
Helling said, ``and I don't think you can single out any one
aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the Rangers' nine-game swing through Colorado,
Baltimore and Tampa Bay produced one victory. That leaves the
Rangers' 0-for-7 run through Detroit and New York in July 1986 as
the franchise's undisputed champion of unproductive travel.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the defending division champions returned to Texas
last night trailing the American League West-leading Oakland
Athletics by 71/2 games after their 10th loss in 11 contests.
</P>
<P>
   The events of Sunday's seventh inning condemned Helling (7-6) to
his fifth consecutive loss in as many starts despite surrendering
only two earned runs and few well-hit balls through 6 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   A double-play ground ball off the bat of center fielder Gabe
Kapler ridded Devil Rays right-hander Rick White (2-4) of the
potential tying run on base in the seventh inning after Mike Lamb's
leadoff single.
</P>
<P>
   Matters only worsened during the bottom half of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' Luis Alicea owned the league's third-best fielding
percentage (.979) among second baseman entering Sunday's game, but
his one-out throwing error opened the floodgates.
</P>
<P>
   Devil Rays shortstop Ozzie Guillen hit a ground ball toward the
middle of the infield with Bobby Smith running on the pitch.
Smith's presence near second base forced Alicea to rush his feed to
shortstop Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea's back-handed toss sailed over Clayton's head and into
left field, and Smith scored the Devil Rays' third run all the way
from first.
</P>
<P>
   The out not recorded also granted the Devil Rays an extra at-bat
during the inning, and it proved even more costly. Helling pitched
around switch-hitting outfielder Quinton McCracken after falling
behind in the count. The walk loaded the bases for left fielder
Bubba Trammell, who had struck out swinging on a curveball in his
previous at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Two curveballs from Helling put Trammell at an 0-2 hole, and
fastballs on the next two pitches set up another curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was down and away,'' Helling said. ``It might not even have
been a strike. It was the first one he touched all day. He just got
enough of the bat on it to put it in play. It was a good pitch. It
was right where I wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trammell hit the pitch off the end of the bat and dumped it into
shallow left-center field. Left fielder Rusty Greer sprinted and
dived in vain, and Trammell strolled into second base with a
three-run double.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time before he really got me on a curveball,'' Trammell
said. ``I knew I was going to get it again. Fortunately, I got it
out of the infield, and it fell in. Rusty made a great try.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, though, out of Greer's reach, much like victories for
Helling of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like everything that can go wrong is going wrong for
me right now,'' Helling said. ``It gets frustrating. You get tired
of going out there and feeling like you're doing the job and have
nothing to show for it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the Rangers returned home with little to show for this road
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make it,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
``We go through streaks like this every year. We'll get the
starting pitching straightened out, and we'll get home, regroup and
it will be fine.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
