<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, June 19.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-U.S. (Prague, Czech Republic) _ The Clinton
administration is exploring with some of its NATO allies and Russia
the possibility that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia be
allowed to leave office with guarantees for his safety and his
savings, senior U.S. and NATO officials say. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ Much has changed in Mexico to
make the current race for the presidency the fairest and most
competitive in the country's history. What has not changed,
opposition and election officials say, is the ruling party's
long-entrenched system of vote-buying and coercion. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Washington) _ By relaxing rules and applying only a
spotty enforcement of travel restrictions, the Clinton
administration is opening Cuba to American travelers at a rate not
seen in more than 40 years. While administration officials deny
that the increased travel is intended to undermine the 38-year-old
embargo against Cuba, the new flow has given rise to a flurry of
business, personal and political contacts and there is a renewed
push in some circles _ both Democratic and Republican _ to relax
the commercial boycott, one of the last relics of the increasingly
distant Cold War. By Christopher Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-COAL (Datong, China) _ The harsh face of coal mining in
China _ a country that, its own alarmed officials admit, has the
world's worst record of mine safety. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-VIOLENCE (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ Zimbabweans have been
looking hopefully toward neighboring South Africa as the waves of
political violence and lawlessness wash across this beleaguered
country. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-SECURITY (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ The government was
already facing hurdles in its efforts to prosecute a scientist
accused of mishandling nuclear secrets at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory, but last week's disclosures that two hard drives filled
with highly sensitive weapons data had inexplicably vanished have
potentially made it far more difficult for prosecutors in what had
once been described as a major national security case. The
scientist, Wen Ho Lee, has insisted from the time he was indicted
last year that security breaches at the laboratory are common, and
that the kind of downloading he did -- moving classified data, in
the open, from a secure to unsecured computer, then downloading it
to tapes -- was done frequently by other experts protecting data
from an unreliable computer system. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   VT-HEALTH-BENEFITS (Cowtown, Vt.) _ With health insurance for
nearly all children and prescription drug coverage for many people
on Medicare, Vermont is in the vanguard in terms of providing
medical benefits. The array of health benefits Vermont affords its
citizens _ not just the elderly but also children and low-income
adults _ is unmatched by any other state. And while many of
Vermont's programs would not work in larger, more urban, more
racially and ethnically diverse states, other aspects could serve
as a pattern elsewhere. Today, 93.5 percent of all Vermonters have
health insurance, including essentially all children. By contrast,
only 63 percent of low-income children in Texas and 60 percent in
Arizona are insured. What it all means, based on interviews with
the governor, doctors and ordinary folks who depend on the
benefits. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-TAKESHITA (Undated) _ Former Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita, who reigned as one of Japan's top kingmakers long after
he was driven from office by scandal in 1989, died on Monday after
an extended illness, a hospital official confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   CULT-KIDS (Island Pond, Vt.) _ In June 1984, state police raided
a cult called the Northeast Kingdom Community Church and rounded up
all the children to examine them for evidence of child abuse.
Stories about the alleged abuse were rampant at the time. A judge
disallowed the raid and the examinations, but the case made a big
splash nationally. The children who were rounded up in the raid
will hold a `teach-in' on Sunday in the town beach in Island Pond.
The list of invited speakers includes both the children, some of
the key law-enforcement officials who conducted the raid, the man
who was commissioner of child-protective services at the time, and
presumably some of the church members. By Sally Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore plans in a speech on
Tuesday to propose a $200 billion program to help low- and
middle-income taxpayers build retirement accounts separate from
what they will receive from Social Security, his aides said. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-III (New Haven, Conn.) _ Born at the earliest fringe of
the baby boom, Bush was pressed during his years at Yale to take
sides in the great battles then unfolding over politics, civil
rights, drugs and music. Mostly he was a noncombatant in those
upheavals, but when forced to choose he ultimately retreated to the
values and ideals established by his parents' generation. Unlike
others of his generation, like Clinton or Gore, Bush never wore his
hair long, agonized over Vietnam, wrestled with existentialism or
cranked up Rolling Stones songs to annoy his parents (instead of
hard rock music, he listened to soul). Even today, Bush thunders in
his stump speeches against boomer-style self-indulgence and appeals
for a ``responsibility era'' that in some respects sounds like the
1950s; he likes values as clean-cut as his hair. By Nicholas D.
Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-VP (Austin, Texas) _ With little more than a month to go
before Gov. George W. Bush, the de facto Republican presidential
nominee, settles on the person with whom he wants to share the
ticket, the list of possibilities seems to be getting shorter. But
that does not mean it is getting a whole lot clearer, because Bush
is holding his cards so close to the vest that even his most
trusted advisers insist they have not been able to sneak a peek. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-MEDIA (Scranton, Pa.) _ A series of incidents last week
illustrates what is, in the view of some Democrats and Republicans
alike, Al Gore's surprisingly tough struggle to get out a message
that clicks with voters. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   COVERDALE-PROFILE (Washington) _ Ask just about anyone in the
U.S. Senate and they will say this about Paul Coverdell, the
Republican senator from Georgia: If you want something done, and
done well, and you don't want the person hogging all the glory,
call Coverdell. It is one reason he ascended into the Senate
Republican leadership so quickly, as a mere freshman. By Lizette
Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVIOR-RATINGS _ ``Survivor,'' a breakout hit in every
way, has stunned the television industry by generating for CBS the
kind of ratings with young viewers that normally are associated
with shows on the Fox network or ABC. Last week, ``Survivor''
pulled in the most viewers under the age of 50 of any series CBS
has played on a Wednesday night at 8 p.m. in the entire 13-year
history of the Nielsen people-meter system. By Bill Carter and
Allison Fass.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   TALENT-AGENT (Los Angeles) _ Since taking the president's job at
the Beverly Hills headquarters of William Morris last August, the
talent agent Jim Wiatt has not just sought to fix William Morris
but has shaken up the talent agency business with a relentless
effort to lure stars from his old employer, only two miles away.
Even by the brass-knuckle standards of two former William Morris
agents, Michael Ovitz and Ron Meyer, who used similar tactics 20
years ago to turn Creative Artists into the town's dominant agency,
Wiatt's efforts have been surprising, dramatic and fast-moving. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MESSAGES (San Francisco) _ Despite the explosive
popularity of instant-messaging programs on the Internet, it became
apparent last week that one facet of the service may not be instant
at all: It may be a year or more before users of competing
instant-message services can send missives to one another. By Matt
Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   NORTEL-CANADA (Undated) _ Nortel, the Canadian
telecommunications equipment giant, has become a company for the
Americas. It is growing so rapidly outside Canada that doubts are
being expressed at home about its corporate citizenship. Its
headquarters remains in Brampton, Ontario, but more of its 75,000
employees live and work south of the Canada-U.S. border than north
of it. And these days, just 9 percent of its $18 billion in
revenues comes from Canada. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
