<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST RACE FOR SECOND IS TIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH - The other Open, now (begin ital)that(end ital)
was a thriller.
</P>
<P>
   While Tiger Woods was playing one-on-one with history in his
runaway victory at the U.S. Open, the best competition in the
centennial national championship was the race for second place at
Pebble Beach Golf Links.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els of South Africa and Spain's Miguel Angel Jimenez
prevailed in that 62-man shootout, tying at 3-over-par 287 for a
score that matched other notable winning efforts at other notably
difficult Open courses.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Hale Irwin shot in 1974 at Winged Foot, when he won
his first of three Open championships. It's what Jack Fleck shot
when he upset four-time Open winner Ben Hogan in 1955 at The
Olympic Club. And it's what's Hogan hammered out at Merion and
Oakland Hills, when he won his back-to-back titles in 1950 and '51.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' record-setting victory might have flattened the field,
but many of his closest pursuers were playing solid golf. They were
undone not just by Woods' brilliant play but by the way already
difficult Pebble Beach was set up by the U.S. Golf Association -
which doesn't like to see its championships won at under par.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA accomplished its goal with everyone but Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played different tournament after two rounds, you know?''
said Jimenez, who was 3-under-par before going bogey-bogey on his
final two holes to finish ever-par 71 ``And I feel very - I feel
like I had to play a different tournament. It was a great
performance. It was great to finish second.''
</P>
<P>
   Els liked much of his own effort, as well, after he and Jimenez
topped the tournament within the tournament by a stroke over John
Huston. Seven others were within four strokes of Els and Jimenez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I played good enough to get myself in great figures,''
Els said after a closing 70. ``It was a bit disappointing when I
saw there was no chance of catching Tiger,... I wanted to play a
solid, good round of golf, which I did from tee to green, but just
missed a lot of putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Huston, who finished fourth alone at 288.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I feel like I played pretty well,'' he said. ``It
doesn't look very well compared to what Tiger is doing, but neither
does anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Huston, 39, was optimistic after his best Open finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I'm getting better as I'm getting older,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's Padraig Harrington, who wound up tied for seventh with
England's Lee Westwood at 289, two strokes off the second
tournament lead, called it ``a great week up until the seventh hole
today.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Harrington was 3-under par for his round but went
bogey-bogey on Nos. 7 and 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that,'' he said, ``I seemed to lose it, lost the
adrenaline and lost focus.... But I certainly learned a few things
today that will help me in my future.''
</P>
<P>
   England's Nick Faldo was a stroke back at 290, followed by Vijay
Singh of Fiji, Stewart Cink, David Duval and Loren Roberts - all at
291.
</P>
<P>
   Singh, the reigning Masters champion, was the sharpest of Woods'
pursuers on Sunday, shooting a closing 68 for second-best score of
the final round. But he wound up disappointed for his overall
effort after shooting 80 in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play well,'' he said. ``Obviously, my goal was to
win. I guess that didn't materialize.... I'm very, very
disappointed. I'm a little a lot more disappointed than I ever was.
So that's the way it goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
