<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7992 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-GLF-WOODS-OPEN-SPI &LR;      06-19 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-OPEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS WINS U.S. OPEN BY (GASP) 15 SHOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ At the 100th U.S. Open, golfer after
golfer raised a white flag and surrendered. In the end, all that
was left flapping in the stiff ocean breeze was stars and stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at attention were 32,000 golf fans at Pebble Beach,
plus millions more in front of their TV screens, all in awe of a
record-breaking, history-making and Open-defying four days by Tiger
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I guess I won,'' he said coyly. ``It was a great week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Open is meant to punish, leave lasting scars. Woods, more
than the elements, had the world's best players sobbing and
cowering, scoring a 15-stroke victory _ the largest winning margin
in a major championship; the second-largest, by a stroke, in a PGA
Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   He stumbled on just seven of 72 holes. He didn't three-putt all
week.
</P>
<P>
   He simply treated some of golf's oldest records as if they were
flagsticks, and hit it stiff every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully he'll tell us he used his `A' game this week,''
Irish golfer Padraig Harrington said. ``We'd believe him.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods shot 12-under-par 272, tying an Open record previously set
by Jack Nicklaus in 1980 at Baltusrol and Lee Janzen in 1993 at
Baltusrol.
</P>
<P>
   He became the first wire-to-wire Open winner since Tony Jacklin
in 1970 at Hazeltine.
</P>
<P>
   His 15-stroke victory in a major tournament surpassed by two a
century-old record set by Tom Morris in the 1862 British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Woods shot 4-under 67 Sunday, leaving him bogey-free in his
first and fourth rounds at Pebble. The victory was the 20th of his
career, his third major and worth $800,000, giving him season
earnings of $4,949,731 and career earnings of $16,264,860.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all felt for the longest time that someone was going to
come along who could drive the ball 300 yards and putt like (Ben)
Crenshaw,'' Nick Price said. ``Well, this guy drives the ball
better than anyone I've seen and putts better than Crenshaw.''
</P>
<P>
   Players joked that the Open was hosting two tournaments this
time: one for Woods and one for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Spaniard Miguel Angel Jimenez and South African Ernie Els shot
287 to split runner-up money, each receiving $390,150. At the top,
it was two foreigners and a player from another planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finishing second is good,'' Els said. ``But I'm kind of
embarrassed finishing 15 strokes behind the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if the USGA implements 8-foot rough, 10-foot
wide fairways and greens shaved to the sand level for the 2001
Open. If nothing else, golf's governing body should consider a
separate set of Tiger tees.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, hold those changes. The Open might have
trouble finding someone for Woods to play with.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they try taking him out of his game, they'll make it
impossible for the rest of us,'' Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead by 10 strokes over Els entering the final round, Woods was
greeted by a rock concert roar when he stepped on the first tee.
Yet he wasn't about to do anything foolish.
</P>
<P>
   He parred his first nine holes, keeping the ball in play and
hitting every green. The plan was simple.
</P>
<P>
   Patience brought rewards. Woods birdied the 10th, 12th, 13th and
14th holes, dropping putts from a foot to 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   He flirted with bogey only at the par-4 16th, when he overshot
the green and ran a chip out of the deep grass 15 feet past the
pin. But he calmly curled the ball into the cup to save par and let
go with one of his trademark fist pumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to have a day where I made no bogeys,'' he said. ``I
went up and buried that putt and it felt so good to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As Woods easily strode up the 18th fairway, boats sounded their
horns in the bay and the boisterous crowd leaned hard on the ropes,
threatening to overrun deputies and security guards. A few unruly
people were even chased down in the stands and escorted out.
</P>
<P>
   When he putted out for par on the final hole, Woods wearily
plucked his ball from the cup, hugged his caddy, Steve Williams,
and Els, removed his hat and smiled and waved to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made important par putts,'' Woods said at the media center.
``I kept telling you guys every time I came in here that I made
those big par putts. You have to make them in the U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, winner of the 1997 Masters and 1999 PGA Championship,
needs only a British Open to complete a personal grand slam. Only
four other golfers have accomplished this feat: Ben Hogan, Jack
Nicklaus, Gary Player and Gene Sarazen.
</P>
<P>
   Woods will get his chance in a month. A Union Jack would hang
nicely with the checkered flag he got for lapping the field.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
