<HEADLINE>
WEARY SPARKS HOLD ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KERRY MURRAY  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Under the circumstances, Coach Michael
Cooper said he was pleased with the way his Sparks played.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pretty, but what do you expect after back-to-back
games and having to board a plane at 4 a.m. on Sunday to make the
trek back from Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have liked to perform at a maximum level, but a win
is a win and we saw some good things tonight,'' Cooper said of his
team's 70-62 win over the Charlotte Sting on Sunday evening before
a crowd of 4,847 at the Forum. ``We had just played a tough game up
in Portland where we could have lost, but we came back with another
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve turnovers and .397 shooting percentage clearly revealed
that the Sparks (6-2) were tired, but their efforts were good
enough for the win over bottom-of-the-barrel Charlotte (1-8).
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the Sparks played to the level of their competition.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with the Sparks' slow start and subpar numbers, both
halves were clearly dominated by Mwadi Mabika and Co.
</P>
<P>
   For the second game in a row, Mabika led the Sparks in scoring,
this time with 21 points and five rebounds. Against Portland the
night before, the starting forward sizzled with a career-high 26
points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's definitely raised it up a notch,'' Cooper said. ``We're
looking to do some things to get her more shot opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Mabika has turned things around after a five-point performance
against Seattle on June 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've just been trying to be more aggressive, trying to
penetrate more,'' Mabika said.
</P>
<P>
   And Lisa Leslie, of course, added the rest of the offense needed
to get the job done, tallying 20 points, six blocked shots and five
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte, on the other hand, struggled. The Sting turned the
ball over 22 times, which Los Angeles in turn cashed in for 17
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the one area we did not do so good in,'' Coach T.R.
Dunn said. ``We turned the ball over way too much and a lot of
those turnovers were unforced.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, nine of those turnovers resulted in an eight-
point Sparks run, and in the second half, similar sloppy play
enabled Los Angeles to keep its comfortable lead.
</P>
<P>
   Down the stretch, the Stings' Summer Erb, a first-year WNBA
player, scored 16 of her 21 points. But that wouldn't be enough to
come close to the Sparks even on an apparent off night.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles faces a much bigger task on Tuesday night, when the
Sparks play host to the three-time defending WNBA champion Houston
Comets at the Forum at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, however, believes his team will be ready for that test
against the Western Conference leaders after a good day and a half
of rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
