<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL DESERVING AS STORM'S FOCAL POINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ From all different sections of KeyArena Sunday night,
you could hear a few enlightened refrains from Storm fans eager for
the home team to build itself a lead:
</P>
<P>
   ``Set a screen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the ball to Edna.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, Edna.''
</P>
<P>
   And out on the floor, where the Storm could not seize an
opportunity against a Utah team missing star players Jennifer Azzi
and Natalie Williams, the calls seemed just about right.
</P>
<P>
   The ball in Edna Campbell's hands is a reassuring thing.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, with that cool and control and the funky little
hitch-step at the start of her dribble, is a sight that can inspire
hope that something good might happen.
</P>
<P>
   If the Storm is going to make any noise this inaugural season,
it's because Campbell is the focal point of this expansion team
that coach Lin Dunn correctly calls a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Natalie Williams special? Hell yes. Is Edna Campbell
special? Absolutely,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edna Campbells don't come along in a lifetime. People like her
having something they're just born with. She has tremendous heart.
She can't stand to lose. She's a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Storm roster turnover has been furious since the first game
of the season. Dunn has used the waiver wire like it was a jump
rope, sending players skipping back and forth across the country in
an effort to bring in new blood, fresher legs, quicker hands and,
most importantly, more offensive firepower.
</P>
<P>
   But while Dunn two-stepped to get unsigned free agent Stacy
Lovelace into a Storm uniform, and while Dunn cajoled the Cleveland
franchise to deal starting guard Michelle Edwards to Seattle, it is
Campbell who is holding up the torch for where and how the Storm
must play to win.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, in a 56-53 loss to the Starzz, it was Campbell
alone who could uncork any sort of offense, especially in the first
half, where the Storm's reliance on Campbell was both correct and
yet alarming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we relied on Edna in the first half,'' Dunn said. ``We
rely on Edna always. Before the game. During the game. After the
game. All the time. Edna's definitely our go-to player. We're
starting to help her share the load, but we've got to start getting
some productivity from our inside people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a lot of natural talent. We've got Edna. We've
got Michelle, but our post players are a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   When Campbell was lifted for a substitution with 8:13 left in
the half, the Storm was leading 10-8 in an abysmal shooting game.
Campbell, who scored a game-high 21 points, was 4-for-4 for eight
points at that point while the rest of the Storm was 0-for-12.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Dunn made an attempt to get better ball
movement. But when it came down to crunch time, after the Starzz
had pulled away from a tie at 47 and something needed to be done,
the ball was back in Campbell's hands.
</P>
<P>
   She is the lone shooter on a team aching for some more offensive
talent.
</P>
<P>
   With 14 seconds left, Campbell hit a 6-foot jumper to pull the
Storm within three, 54-51. She hit a 5-foot running jumper with 7.8
seconds left to close the gap to 55-53.
</P>
<P>
   After Kate Starbird went to the line to make it 56-53, it was
Campbell who hoisted a 25-footer with about 1 second left to end
the game _ another game that told Campbell something about her
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to ice the cake,'' Campbell said. ``We're not
finishing the job. We need to dig down deep and believe we can
win.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an impossible wish, certainly. But what the Storm needs is
one more Edna Campbell. Maybe even two, but let's not get piggish.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Storm is lucky enough to have the original Edna
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   At 31, a nine-year pro who has played in Brazil and Poland and
the ABL and one year with the Phoenix Mercury of the WNBA, Campbell
is everything Dunn promised: Edna the Engine. Edna the scorer. Edna
the heart and soul of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Although Campbell is entirely too humble to make much ado about
her contributions, it is impossible to say where the team would be
right now without her.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Storm's atrocious shooting Sunday night, Campbell
has been a treasure to watch so far this season. And during the
three-game homestand that the Storm completed Sunday night against
Utah, the one thing that consistently shined for the Storm was
Campbell, whose game-high 22-points Tuesday night led to a Storm
upset of the L.A. Sparks in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``She lights up the room with her smile. She lights up the arena
with her intensity and her effort. She lights up the community when
she goes into a school to talk about breast health awareness or
drug abuse or whatever. She's just a tremendous person,'' Dunn
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is her third system she's had to learn in three years.
She was in the ABL. She was in the Phoenix system. Now she's thrust
in the Seattle Storm system. And we knew it would take a little
time for her to adapt to what we wanted her to do and she needed
some help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Storm is lucky to have Campbell in the house. But Dunn is
right. Campbell needs help. Someone to set her some good screens. A
post player inside she can feed or pick and roll with.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Storm fans have identified Edna Campbell as the go-to
woman. Now she just needs some more players to go with her.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
