<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NEAR-MISS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CONTROLLER FAILED TO REPORT NEAR-COLLISION AT LaGUARDIA AIRPORT  
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A US Airways Airbus and a smaller turboprop plane
came within 100 feet of colliding at La Guardia Airport last week,
but the air traffic controller responsible for the incident never
reported it to the Federal Aviation Administration as required, the
FAA said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time that the controller, whose name was not
released, committed an operational error and then compounded it by
failing to report it, an FAA official said. The controller has been
decertified and may be fired, said the FAA official, who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The near-collision early last Monday, just after midnight,
between an Airbus A-320, which had just landed, and a Beech King
Air turboprop that was taking off, came as air safety regulators
are focusing increased attention on near-collisions and on
conditions at La Guardia in particular.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the National Transportation Safety Board released a
study that found that the risk of collisions on the ground between
airplanes had been growing lately because of increasing air
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   And on Saturday, the National Transportation Safety Board told
the FAA that La Guardia's rules for spacing between planes landing
and taking off on intersecting runways, which allow a plane to
depart as long as no large plane is within two miles of landing, do
not allow enough space. The board's recommendation was prompted by
a near-collision at La Guardia in April 1998 in which a landing
DC-9 missed a departing Airbus A-320 by as little as 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   That incident, too, was never reported by La Guardia
controllers.
</P>
<P>
   In last Monday's incident, which was first reported in Monday's
Washington Post, the controller cleared the Airbus to land on La
Guardia's Runway 4 at 12:18 a.m., the FAA official said.
</P>
<P>
   As the Airbus touched down, the controller cleared the turboprop
to take off on Runway 31, which intersects Runway 4 at a right
angle. The turboprop passed less than 100 feet above the Airbus,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was reported by the Airbus's pilot on Thursday, the
FAA official said, although the controller was required to report
the incident to supervisors and to the FAA immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The controller failed to report another near-collision that
occurred on Dec. 2, 1998, the FAA official said. After that
incident, which was found to be the controller's fault, the
controller was decertified, retrained and put back on the job, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the controller may be dealt with more harshly, the
FAA official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real crime is not reporting it,'' the official said. ``If
you make a mistake, that's fine, we're all human, and it can be
corrected. But when you fail to tell your supervisor, that's a
no-no.''
</P>
<P>
   The controller, the official said, ``could be canned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
