<SLUG> BC-FBO-AVENGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINOVICH LEADS AVENGERS TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's not logical for a team with a 2-8 record to
talk about making the playoffs, but the Avengers might have a
reason to start thinking big.
</P>
<P>
   The team is beginning to take shape after a month full of roster
moves, and the Avengers earned their second victory in three games
by beating the Florida Bobcats 63-49 in front of 8,578 at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers won for the first time in front of the home fans,
set a new franchise high for points in a game and completed their
longest play from scrimmage, a 45-yard touchdown pass from Todd
Marinovich to Anthony Rice in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The recent success is thanks in large part to the continued
improvement of quarterback Marinovich, who completed 13 of 22
passes for 200 yards and six touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to definitely get the hang of it,'' Marinovich
said. ``A lot of it is that I'm getting the time to throw back
there, which I didn't have much of before. ... We're talking about
the playoffs, definitely. Right now, we feel like we can beat
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Playoff talk is a little premature, even though 12 of the
league's 17 teams will advance to the postseason and the Avengers
continue to improve on both sides of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter was the best indicator of that improvement.
The Bobcats (3-6) tied the game 42-42 on a 40-yard field goal by
Joe O'Donnell as the buzzer sounded to end the third quarter, but
the Avengers responded with perhaps their most impressive drive of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking from arena football decorum, the Avengers gave the ball
to fullback Andy Chilcote four times in a nine-play, 43-yard drive
that took six minutes, eight seconds off the clock. Marinovich
found Chris Jackson in the corner of the end zone for a 49-42 lead
and the Avengers led the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can run the ball, it makes it harder for the
secondary to cover the receivers, because they never know where the
ball is going to go,'' Chilcote said. ``When you have a six-minute
drive ... the guys look at each other in the huddle, and no matter
how tired we are, we just keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida quarterback Jim Arellanes misfired on three consecutive
pass attempts, and the Avengers had the ball back less than two
minutes after their long drive against an obviously winded Bobcats
defense. The Avengers pushed the lead to 56-42 three plays later
when Marinovich found former USC teammate Travis Hannah for a
23-yard touchdown pass with 4:48 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Florida got to within seven points with 47 seconds remaining on
a 2-yard scoring run by Steve Gorrie, but Victor Hall recovered the
onside kick at the Florida 6. Chilcote capped the scoring with a
4-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Brock said he believes the Avengers have a realistic chance to
make the playoffs if they win their four remaining games, three of
which are against teams with sub-.500 records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing right now,'' said Rice, who caught two touchdown
passes, ``is to keep going forward, and not go backward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
