u e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     06-19 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ANGLOMANIA: A European Love Affair &LR;  By Ian Buruma. Vintage,
$14. The author, whose Jewish great-grandparents left Bismarck's
Germany to settle in England, examines an idea that has taken many
forms in the European imagination over the centuries: the idea of
Britain. ``His own and his family's story is artfully woven''
through the book, ``making this both a memoir and a work of
intellectual history,'' Alexander Stille wrote in The New York
Times Book Review in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLLECTED POEMS: 1920-1954 &LR;  By Eugenio Montale. Translated by
Jonathan Galassi. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $18. This bilingual
version of the three major books of one of Italy's greatest poets
(1896-1981) is filled with verse ``of an unignorable kind'' and
features ``Galassi's superb translation ... and commentary,''
Nicholas Jenkins wrote last year. Montale was ``an unequaled
chronicler of the seedy but meaningful edges of modern life.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; REPAIR &LR; , by C.K. Williams
($12), a Pulitzer Prize-winning collection by an American poet
known for his ``exact, bewildering, slant rendering of raw emotion
and careful thought,'' as one critic put it in 1999. ``Williams
spares neither himself nor the reader anything. This is his
singular genius and passion.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELEANOR ROOSEVELT. The Defining Years: Volume 2, 1933-1938 &LR;  By
Blanche Wiesen Cook. Penguin, $17.95. In her continuing account of
the iconoclastic, take-no-prisoners first lady, the author
``continues her diligent pentimento, getting at the tender,
sprightly creature behind the starchy, strident image, chronicling
how the timid housewife ... shed her chrysalis and turned into the
New Deal's relentless `Eleanor Everywhere,''' Maureen Dowd wrote
last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HANNIBAL &LR;  By Thomas Harris. Dell, $7.99. The third part of the
author's horror trilogy about the far reaches of abnormal
psychiatry involves a rematch between the intrepid FBI agent
Clarice Starling and her nemesis, Dr. Hannibal Lecter, aka Hannibal
the Cannibal. Last year the reviewer Stephen King called this ``one
of the two most frightening popular novels of our time, the other
being `The Exorcist.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LETTERS FROM YELLOWSTONE &LR;  By Diane Smith. Penguin, $12.95. In
1898, a young medical student and avid botanist becomes the sole
woman on a Smithsonian-backed expedition to Yellowstone National
Park. Last year one critic called this ``a thoroughly enjoyable,
intriguingly offbeat epistolary novel'' with ``a host of memorable
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ART OF THE MOVING PICTURE &LR;  By Vachel Lindsay. Modern
Library, $14.95. In one of the earliest books of serious film
criticism, the poet champions the silent films of D.W. Griffith and
others. ``He is eloquent in his repudiation of whatever slur there
be in the term `canned drama,''' The New York Times Book Review
said in 1916. Lindsay ``has a vision of the nation remade by this
new art form which cuts deeper than the newspaper or the public
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Modern Library, as part of a series on the movies, has also
reissued  &UR; AGEE ON FILM: Criticism and Comment on the Movies &LR; , by
James Agee ($14.95), a collection of reviews that originally
appeared in Time magazine and The Nation in the 1940s, and several
other essays, including ones on John Huston and silent comedy
written for Life magazine. ``Each of his reviews brings the movie
before you, alive and whole,'' Richard Griffith wrote here in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; MEMO FROM DAVID O. SELZNICK &LR; , selected and edited by Rudy
Behlmer ($15.95), the legendary producer of ``Gone With the Wind''
and ``Rebecca'' is given flesh though his voluminous
correspondence, primarily his private letters, telegrams and
memorandums. ``Selznick was at once a brilliant man and an
unmitigated interfering nuisance,'' Charles Higham wrote in 1972,
and his memos ``make harrowing reading.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PREEMPTING THE HOLOCAUST &LR;  By Lawrence L. Langer. Yale
University, $12.95. In these essays, a scholar argues that the
Holocaust was an act of pure evil ``beyond guilt and atonement,''
with no redeeming lessons and without heroes or martyrs, only
victims. ``Always thoughtful and provocative, he writes about
complex moral issues in a lucid and forceful style,'' Lore
Dickstein wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE BREAD OR I'LL APPEAR &LR;  By Emer Martin. Anchor, $12. In this
novel about an Irish family struggling to stay connected, a young
woman journeys to Japan and Central America in search of her older
sister, who fled home 14 years earlier. Her ``odyssey movingly
reveals the harm of clinging to the past, even in the name of
family,'' Megan Harlan wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE METAPHYSICAL TOUCH &LR;  By Sylvia Brownrigg. Picador USA, $15.
This first novel uses a weird online romance between a lonely
graduate student in philosophy and a suicidal, possibly
nonexistent, author to explore the nature of being and the
intersection of the physical and metaphysical worlds. The result is
``a serious and intelligently wrought piece of fiction,'' Geoff
Nicholson said in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
