<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8182 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-INDIANS-VIEW-HILLARY-     06-19 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIANS-VIEW-HILLARY-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY, FORGET CAMPAIGN REFORM AND GUN CONTROL LAWS! 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By TIM GIAGO (NANWICA KCIJI) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Way out here in the hinterlands I believe we have a much better
perspective on America than those living right next to the
powers-that-be on the banks of the Potomac or in the city
considered to be the center of the universe _ New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the Indian reservations we often are puzzled at problems
that should have simple solutions and yet become unsolvable because
of the nature of politics. For instance, there appears to be a real
problem among the voters in New York State about the senate
candidacy of Hillary Clinton. There is also a question of why she
is still with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   I always believed that the way politicians solve the problems of
their home states in the house or the senate is by the political
connections they have established among their peers in Washington.
It doesn't take a rocket scientist to seek out the problems and
needs of any state. So why are New Yorkers so concerned that
Hillary is not a native New Yorker? They didn't raise such a ruckus
when another outsider, Robert F. Kennedy ran for the senate seat in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that many New Yorkers are attaching all the baggage
of Bill Clinton to the apron strings of Hillary? How many voters
really cared if Franklin D. Roosevelt loved Eleanor and if he did,
why?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton proved to be a very poor husband to Hillary in one
respect: he cheated on her. Hillary forgave him his transgressions
and continues to love him. Hasn't that ever happened in the
families of those who would chastise her for this? I would think
she should be admired and respected for holding her marriage
together in the face of such public ridicule. At one time in my
life I wish I had had her courage.
</P>
<P>
   I have observed Hillary to be a caring, compassionate and honest
person. Isn't that what leadership is all about? The wolves of
Washington did everything in their power, honestly and dishonestly,
to discredit her and she survived. And in my mind, she came out of
it a much better person. If I was a New Yorker I know I would vote
for her.
</P>
<P>
   Who has the power in America: the people or the special
interests? Of course the answer should be the people, but that
answer is much too simple. We sit out here in Indian country and
see the power and money brokers control the government. Politicians
cannot survive without money. They get the bulk of their money from
the special interest groups. The National Rifle Association and big
oil for instance, have some politicians in their hip pockets. What
does that tell us about the land of the free and the home of the
brave?
</P>
<P>
   It's like a Catch-22. Politicians will not install campaign
reform because they need this glitch to get re-elected. And yet the
people who vote want campaign reform but they keep electing people
to office who have the power to bring about reform and will not. It
is a national disgrace to see a George W. Bush raise millions to
get elected or a Bill Clinton raise millions for his party even
though he can never run for president again. What it tells the
young people out here is that money makes the world go around.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with gun control laws. States with the toughest
gun laws, Massachusetts for example, have reduced the death by gun
shot wounds among children by 50 percent. Coincident or reality? I
own a hunting rifle and I would not mind at all having to register
it or get a license for it or get a trigger guard installed. If I
wanted to buy another rifle I wouldn't mind having to go through a
background check to get it whether it took one week or two months.
What's the big deal?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we have never had an American Indian boy or girl walk
into a school and gun down teachers and fellow students. This seems
to be the dominion of teenage white boys.
</P>
<P>
   Changing the subject, I polled a few of my friends and relatives
on the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation and asked them who they
believed Al Gore would pick as a running mate. The person most
mentioned out here in Indian country is Sen. Tom Daschle, (D-S.D.)
Just thought I'd throw that in just in case it becomes a reality.
You can then say you read it here first and it could prove how
astute us country folks can be.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if it doesn't, one can always say that the hicks out
here in the hinterlands really don't know a darned thing about the
real world.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Giago (Nanwica Kciji _ ``Stands up for Them'') is an Oglala
Lakota. He is editor and publisher of the weekly newspaper, The
Lakota Nation Journal. He can be reached at: P.O. Box 3080, Rapid
City, S.D. 57709-3080 or e-mailed at: editor at
lakotanationjournal.com)
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; c.2000 (c) 2000 The Lakota Nation Journal &QL; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on NEW
AMERICA NEWS SERVICE and other features. &QL;
</P>
