<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8183 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-LATINO-VOTE-NEW-AMERI     06-19 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-VOTE-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATINO VOTER TURNOUT CRITICAL IN NOVEMBER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JAMES E. GARCIA  
 &HT;    It would be the largest number of Latino votes ever cast in a
U.S. presidential election: 6 million.
 &HT;    And the number could go even higher still.
 &HT;    Led by the efforts of the Southwest Voter Registration Project
and the U.S. Hispanic Leadership Institute, Latino groups and
activists across the country are mounting ``Latino Vote 2000,'' an
aggressive campaign to register hundreds of thousands of Hispanic
voters in the coming weeks and months.
 &HT;    Latino voter-drive efforts are not new. What is new is that
election-day turnout this fall by Latinos might well decide
countless local, state and federal races _ including the
presidency.
 &HT;    Raising the stakes even higher are predictions that an
unprecedented number of Latinos may shift their support from
Democratic to Republican candidates.
 &HT;    Vice President Al Gore and the Democrats still have strong
support among Latinos, but Texas Gov. George W. Bush is making real
headway. If he plays his cards right, I think he could match _ or
even exceed _ the nearly 40 percent support that Reagan received
from Latinos in his 1984 landslide re-election.
 &HT;    With Republicans holding just a six-seat majority in the House,
lawmakers on both sides of the aisle know just how critical a
Latino swing vote could be. And a strong victory by Bush can only
help down-ticket candidates, namely those in voting districts where
Latinos abound.
 &HT;    Consider the results of a recent survey by the Tomas Rivera
Policy Institute, a national think-tank that studies Latino
political trends. The non-partisan group found that in three Los
Angeles-area congressional districts each candidate's margin of
victory in 1998 was smaller than the number of registered Latino
voters who did not cast a ballot.
 &HT;    Put another way, a higher turnout by Latino voters could very
well have meant victory for the losing candidate.
 &HT;    For instance, Republican Congressman James Rogan, a member of
the House team that fought for President Clinton's impeachment, was
re-elected in California's 27th District by 6,800 votes in 1998.
Yet 21,000 registered Latino voters did not cast a ballot,
according to Matt Barreto, a Tomas Rivera researcher.
 &HT;    This tells us that getting Latinos registered to vote is only
half the battle. Along with voter registration drives, Latino
leaders of every political ilk should be mounting get-to-the-polls
drives.
 &HT;    Incidentally, it isn't that Latinos don't care about elections.
It's just that for most of our nation's history, our vote hasn't
really mattered to the cast of mostly non-Latino politicians
running for office.
 &HT;    Things could be different this year. The trends are all tilted
in the right direction. Latinos today are better educated. More
Latinos are starting new businesses, moving into management jobs
and even taking roles in the upper ranks of corporate America. And,
most significantly, there are simply more Latinos _ about 31
million by the latest estimates.
 &HT;    As a result, the growth in the number of Latinos who have
registered to vote has been striking. Juan Andrade, head of the
U.S. Hispanic Leadership Institute, says the number of registered
Latino voters nationwide jumped by 164 percent from 1976 to 1996,
compared to 31 percent in the general population.
 &HT;    Latino voter-registration efforts received an unexpected boost
in the 1990s in the wake of ``anti-Latino'' initiatives, according
to Russell Jauregui, an attorney in Pasadena, Calif., and a former
volunteer organizer for Southwest Voter.
 &HT;    Most Latino voters angrily rejected the sharp conservative shift
in Congress on the issues of welfare and immigration legislation
during the Gingrich years. And several California ballot
initiatives managed to wound the GOP image in the Latino community.
 &HT;    As a result, hundreds of thousands of Latino voters had little
trouble deciding to pick Democrats over Republicans in 1996 and
1998. Clinton, for instance, won more than 70 percent of the Latino
vote in 1996.
 &HT;    But there isn't a similar ``negative force'' pushing Latinos to
the polls this campaign season, Andrade said. Ironically, that has
some Latino leaders worried. While they appreciate the GOP's
kinder, gentler attitude toward our community, many Latinos may
feel that because the ``threat'' has subsided they can stay home on
election day.
 &HT;    ``We need another Pete Wilson,'' jokes Andrade, referring to the
former California governor who still draws the wrath of many
Latinos for his support of a ballot initiative barring illegal
immigrant children from public schools.
 &HT;    Hopefully, Latinos won't need another Pete Wilson to get us to
the polls in November. Latinos should know that with 6 million-plus
votes to wield in the general election, politicians across the
country and the political spectrum will think twice before
repeating Wilson's mistakes. All we have to do now is cast our
ballots.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (James E. Garcia is editor-in-chief of Politico magazine, a
monthly publication covering U.S. Latino politics. E-mail
Politico1(at)aol.com or visit www.politicomagazine.com.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 James E. Garcia 
