<HEADER>
A8192 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-BACKGROUND-CHECKS-GUN     06-19 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKGROUND-CHECKS-GUNS-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYING ALIVE MEANS KEEPING BACKGROUND CHECKS ON GUNS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By DERRICK K. BAKER  
 &HT;    Solely because I have been robbed at gunpoint, an interminable
episode years ago that scared me nearly to death, my opinions about
the absolute necessity of background checks for people who want to
buy guns are not up for debate.
 &HT;    A certain firmness to your convictions results when the cold
barrel of a Saturday-night-special has been pressed to your sweaty
temple and you've been admonished by some weasel about how easy it
would be to scatter your teen-age brains over the storage room of a
variety store.
 &HT;    That searing flashback aside, while the U.S. Justice
Department's success in blocking 204,000 of the more than 8.6
million prospective gun sales last year won't in any way ultimately
stop guns from falling into the hands of criminals, it's reasonable
to guess that within that number of blocked sales lay more than a
few sub-moronic dolts who had no business having access to guns.
 &HT;    To paint a more detailed picture about the positive and
immediate effects of the Brady Act, which was instituted in
February 1994 and required the background checks, last year the
number of purchase rejections numbered 536,000 out of nearly 22.3
million applications. That's a lot of law-abiding citizens and
certified nut jobs alike who might have had his or her former
co-workers squarely sighted in the crosshairs that are the mind's
eye.
 &HT;    Moreover, numbers from the Department of Justice reveal that
state and local police rejected an even higher percentage of
would-be gun buyers than the FBI: The rejection rate among state
and local agencies was 3 percent compared with 1.8 percent for the
FBI.
 &HT;    Is this to imply that the Barney Fifes of the country are more
efficient in keeping guns out of the hands of evildoers than the
highly trained bunch at the FBI?
 &HT;    As a matter of fact, President Clinton and his minions long have
contended that the states are better equipped than the FBI to
conduct background checks, but some states don't want to pay the
costs.
 &HT;    According to the Justice Department, all state agencies had
access to computer databases that record past felony convictions,
and many accessed databases with other disqualifying information
such as fugitive status, court restraining orders, mental illness
and domestic-violence misdemeanor convictions.
 &HT;    The counter contention is true _ that all too often, criminals
don't walk into Billy Bob's Gun Shop to purchase a gun to rob a
7-Eleven or the 80-year-old church deacon. But far too many guns
purchased by law-abiding citizens end up without serial numbers and
in the hands of Pookie Jenkins, who gets a cheap thrill sticking up
people who look and live like him.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, here's a memo to the reluctant decision makers in
those states reluctant to pay for background checks: Take a second
_ and close _ look at your moral compass, before too many
legislators like yourself wind up the victims of violent crimes
committed with guns possessed by some of the very same people who
would have been blocked.
 &HT;    Joining those legislators is the National Rife Association, that
conglomeration of mostly self-righteous ostriches who can't see the
forest for the trees, who want more enforcement of existing gun
laws.
 &HT;    Who better than them to have a problem with accepting the rather
direct correlation between application rejections and the decrease
in firearm-related crimes since 1992?
 &HT;    Granted, the use of firearms has fallen from 31 percent in all
violent crimes eight years ago to 25 percent just two years ago.
But a crime is a crime, and we can reduce the frequency of those
crimes, particularly if we enjoy life.
 &HT;    So if I sound a bit angry at those who would fight the
productivity and constitutionality of background checks for
prospective gun owners, please bear with me. My anger and cynicism
and incredulity have something to do with being among the millions
of Americans who've had the experience of staring life _ and death
_ squarely in the face, courtesy of a firearm.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Derrick K. Baker is a columnist for N'Digo, an African-American
weekly newspaper published in Chicago. Baker can be reached by
e-mail at Dbaker1004(AT)aol.com.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Derrick K. Baker 
<TEXT>
