<HEADER>
A8219 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN21-CO     06-19 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Another ``read my lips'' from a Bush?
 &HT;    For release June 21, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'd think George W would have learned from daddy's mistake.
But when the presidential candidate, seeking to participate in the
GOP's newest anti-administration, politically motivated maelstrom,
told a Florida audience last weekend that our nuclear secrets will
be secret again in his administration, he was mirroring his
father's ``read my lips, no new taxes'' boast that came to bury his
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely: ``I'll bring this sorry chapter to a close. In my
administration, our national labs will be secure again, our vital
information will be sealed again, our nuclear secrets will be
secret again.''
</P>
<P>
   Some campaign promises just can't be kept and George W ought to
know better than to vouch that no similar problem will haunt his
presidency _ if he's elected. Say you'll do everything possible to
ensure that it doesn't happen but don't guarantee it; it's
foolhardy to do so, as the senior Bush found out.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the Super Bowl and George W isn't Joe Namath.
</P>
<P>
   The furor over the misplaced computer hard-drives at the Los
Alamos National Laboratory has brought drool to the lips of the
political savages of Capitol Hill. They are calling for the head of
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, I presume in the context of ``the
buck stops here'' guideline set down by Harry Truman.
</P>
<P>
   But if that be the case, then how come Caspar Weinberger
remained secretary of defense for Ronald Reagan when 247 U.S.
Marines were blown to bits in a horrific breach of security in
Lebanon? And that's not the only one the GOP guard dogs ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when it became public that security had been breached
in the theft of nuclear secrets being passed to China, the GOP
mercenaries targeted the Clinton administration as being jelly when
it came to nuclear secrets. What was odd about it was that the
secrets were stolen during the Reagan and Bush presidencies as
well.
</P>
<P>
   As GOP senators and representatives harangued the Clinton
administration for not cracking down on something that had been
investigated for almost three years, someone reminded Sen. Trent
Lott that it was on Reagan's and Bush's watch that most of the
thefts took place. He responded, incredulously, that he was not
going to dwell on the past, but wanted to know what's being done
now about correcting the problem.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how serious is the Los Alamos crisis, and neither
did all those Republicans who spent last weekend bellowing on
network TV, including Sen. Richard Shelby (R-Ala.) who called for
Richardson's resignation. There is much more to be learned,
including whether the secrets were compromised at all.
</P>
<P>
   But we are in an era of intense political fury. In a capital
where no secret is ever safe, where leaks are more like waterfalls,
partisan politics will turn on the slightest opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   As if money-raising and slush funds were not enough to sicken
the general public, the political combat is getting more disgusting
by the moment. There is no working bi-partisan government anymore,
just partisan acrimony.
</P>
<P>
   There is little the Democratic administration has done, or has
not done, that has not resulted in some call by the GOP for an
investigation or a resignation.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush does get elected, can we expect a similar reaction from
the Democratic partisans during his administration? I'm afraid so.
They likely will watch his every step -- and misstep -- and clamor
for investigations in an act of political revenge; a vicious chain
that may have its eye-for-an-eye roots in the partisan-driven 1987
Democratic rejection of Ronald Reagan's nomination of Robert Bork
to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   And should Gore reach the presidency, then Lott and his folks
will continue to behave as they do today.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the real examination of breaches such as happened
at Los Alamos (if it happened) is driven not by professional
inquiry but more by political penchant, by public opinion based on
poisoned positions _ and by obtuse statements by presidential
candidates who should know better.
</P>
<P>
   We know where the buck stops _ Harry told us so _ but how many
are passing it around maliciously on the way up?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
