<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-WEATHER (San Francisco) _ Fragile technologies in orbit
and on Earth can be affected by powerful solar storms that can fry
satellites, disrupt power grids and snarl long-distance
communications. This vulnerability has spawned a new career that is
increasingly vital to power companies, the telecommunications
industry and the military: space weather forecaster. By KEAY
DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   MIRANDA-WARNING (San Francisco) _ The prosecution of a Aug. 13,
1998, murder on the campus of the University of California at Davis
fell apart after disclosures that detectives conducted illegal or
coercive interrogation tactics. The case demonstrates that improper
interrogation tactics can undermine the criminal justice process.
It suggests that such police methods are especially dangerous when
used on suspects who are illiterate and uneducated. By SETH
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Last year, U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio voted
to enact dramatic education reforms to give states and local school
districts wide discretion in spending federal aid. But last week,
the four-term Republican congressman broke with his party and
quietly reversed his vote, siding this time with the Democratic
White House _ and Hillary Rodham Clinton _ to retain federal
control over education spending. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   401(k)-LAWSUITS (Undated) _ Three recent lawsuits highlight the
potential conflicts between workers and employers who are entrusted
to manage their retirement savings accounts through 401(k) plans.
By VANESSA HUA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SAN-JUAN-ISLANDS (Friday Harbor, Wash.) _ A decade ago,
virtually everyone aboard my ferry would have been a Washington
state resident. But on this day I count a healthy smattering of
out-of-state license plates - evidence that the enchanting San Juan
Islands, once Seattle's private dominion, are starting to make it
onto the map for the rest of us. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   HILL-COUNTRY-RESORT (San Antonio) _ Looking for an antidote to
the early summer heat? Sink into an antique rocking chair on Aunt
Mary's Porch. Float along the 950-foot Ramblin' River. Saunter down
a three-quarter-mile nature trail, spying for native plants beneath
stately live oak trees. It's all part of the family fun at the
Hyatt Regency Hill Country Resort, a favorite San Antonio retreat.
By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   With: HILL-COUNTRY-INFO
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Probably the most useful piece of travel
advice I was ever given was: ``Never pack anything you have to plug
</P>
<P>
   in, iron or worry about losing.'' Probably the second-best was:
``Every glass of `free' mint tea you drink in a Moroccan carpet
shop will end up costing you $600.'' Here is some advice from other
travelers. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-TIGER (Pebble Beach, Calif.) _ The old hands who have
watched Tiger Woods make his first fortune en route to the PGA
Tour, make another while on it, and now back up his advance notice
with deeds as monumental as Sunday's 15-stroke victory at the U.S.
Open . . . they're the ones who know best. ``What he's done is
raise the bar to a standard only he can reach,'' said Tom Watson,
one of the few golfers of the last half-century who knows the
triple burdens of trying to be lead dog, being lead dog, and losing
the job. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-OPEN-TV (Pebble Beach, Calif.) _ The formula for NBC's
success here at the U.S. Open was really quite easy. Put Tiger
Woods on the air and keep him coming. By The San Francisco
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-OAKLAND-MOVE (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Giants managing
general partner Peter Magowan says his team will oppose any attempt
by the Oakland Athletics to move to Santa Clara County. The A's
confirmed Saturday that they have submitted a rough outline to
Major League Baseball considering such a move. By RYAN KIM and JOHN
SHEA.
</P>
