<SLUG> BC-DINOSAUR-TREX-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DINO FORMERLY KNOWN AS T. REX? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN McTAVISH  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would a Tyrannosaurus rex by any other name be as fearsome?
</P>
<P>
   It's no idle primordial question.
</P>
<P>
   T. rex, the world's most famous dinosaur, whose toothy visage
has adorned everything from blockbuster movies to children's
bedspreads, could be in for a name change to Manospondylus gigas.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't have quite the same imposing ring, does it?
</P>
<P>
   Even the translation from Latin doesn't compare: Manospondylus
gigas means ``giant, thin vertebrae,'' while Tyrannosaurus rex
means ``tyrant lizard king.''
</P>
<P>
   Put yourself in the place of prehistory's preeminent land-based
killing machine. Would you rather be remembered as a piece of bone
or the baddest reptile on the planet?
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not T. rex fans like it, the ancient predator's tag
has been in question since earlier this month, when about 10
percent of a dinosaur skeleton was unearthed at a South Dakota
ranch by the Black Hills Institute of Geological Research, the same
company that in 1990 dug up Sue, the most complete T. rex fossil
ever found.
</P>
<P>
   The South Dakota bones could be part of an earlier fossil dug up
in the same general area in 1892 by paleontologist Edward Drinker
Cope, who dubbed his find Manospondylus gigas. But Cope didn't
extract enough of the fossil for his name to stick in the
scientific community.
</P>
<P>
   In 1902 a more complete specimen was discovered in Montana by
Barnum Brown and later named Tyrannosaurus rex by paleontologist
Henry Osborn.
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Larson, president of the Black Hills Institute of
Geological Research, suspects that his company's South Dakota find
_ including ribs, vertebrae, the jaw and parts of the skull _
belongs to the same colossal carnivore Cope found more than a
century ago. If so, according to the rules of paleontology, the
first name would take priority.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Larson recently told the Associated Press: ``That puts the
name Tyrannosaurus rex in peril.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe, said Christopher Brochu, a paleontologist at the
Field Museum of Natural History in Chicago, where the T. rex called
Sue was unveiled May 17. It would take overwhelming evidence to
unseat the name Tyrannosaurus rex from the zoological nomenclature,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do not think that the name Tyrannosaurus rex is in
any danger,'' Brochu said. ``Larson would have to demonstrate that
he's got the original animal. I doubt that this can be done. If it
can, I'll eat my words. But I'm skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the worst comes to pass and we have to sink
Tyrannosaurus rex, I'm sure the public would still call it that
because that's what everybody knows it as.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Evans, educator and curator of natural science at the
Children's Museum of Indianapolis, where T. rex is an unofficial
mascot, believes that kids would be especially confused by a name
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about the validity of the find, but I'm sure the
rules of paleontology will have to bend with this one,'' Evans
said. ``T. rex is ingrained in our culture. It's a definite icon.
You get kids to mention any dinosaur and the first thing they say
is T. rex. Any 4-year-old would pretend to be the `tyrant lizard
king' but none would want to be the `giant, thin vertebrae.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Evans said, Larson probably wouldn't be unhappy if the
name just stayed Tyrannosaurus rex.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dug more T. rexes than anybody on the planet,'' Evans
said. ``So I'm sure he's the last one who would feel good about
calling it something else. He's pretty attached to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
