r e BC-MOVIE-HI-LINE-KANSAS-     06-19 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HI-LINE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HI-LINE DIRECTOR HAS SOUND FOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Actors become directors. Screenwriters become directors. Film
editors and directors of photography become directors.
</P>
<P>
   But sound guys?
</P>
<P>
   After more than a decade as a production sound mixer for Steven
Spielberg, Ron Judkins decided it was time to make his mark. He put
his flourishing career on hold, coughed up his life savings (it
helped that the 40-something-year-old isn't married), scrounged
additional dollars from investors and shot ``The Hi-Line,'' a moody
coming-of-age film and love story.
</P>
<P>
   Starring Rachael Lee Cook (``She's All That'') and newcomer Ryan
Alosino, it's the story of a bored young woman in small-town
Montana. Her life is turned around with the arrival of a young
Chicago man who claims to be recruiting employees for a proposed
department store. But the stranger has another agenda, and the
young woman discovers she was adopted; she demands that the
Chicagoan take her on a search for her birth mother.
</P>
<P>
   The film also stars Margot Kidder, Stuart Margolin and Tantoo
Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Direction is something I always wanted to do,'' Judkins said
in a phone interview from Austin, Texas, where ``The Hi-Line'' was
receiving a commercial run. ``I only got into sound because I
needed money to survive, and I was seduced by success. After all, I
worked with Spielberg on every film he's made since `Hook.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But after 20 years in the business, I realized I was getting
older and needed to return to my original dream to make my own
movie. I'd been writing scripts the whole time, and a couple even
went into development, which meant several rewrites and lots of
meetings, and in the end I wasted two years and the movies never
got made. So I decided to get whatever resources I could and put
together my own film.''
</P>
<P>
   The plot of ``The Hi-Line,'' Judkins said, is in no way
autobiographical. ``But growing up I'd think, `Hey, these can't be
my real parents.' I was waiting for the real ones to show up and
take me away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then on Thanksgiving five years ago, I was in my garage going
through some old photos, and here was a shot of the girl I had a
crush on in third grade. And I entertained this fantasy of tracking
her down but without her knowing I'm looking for her. So I started
playing with that idea, inventing a situation where someone comes
from your past with information about you that even you didn't
know, information that could change your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The premise also raised questions about what makes us who we
are. Is it how we were brought up? Or is it genetics, who are
parents really are?''
</P>
<P>
   As a production sound mixer, Judkins is familiar with movie
sets; his primary job is to record the dialogue spoken by actors.
But being a director was a big leap.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 14, I'd watch my mother drive the car, and I'd
figure it couldn't be that difficult. But it's terrifying your
first day behind the wheel. It's like that the first day on the
set. I'm waiting for someone to tell us what to do, and then I
realize, `Oh, yeah, I'm supposed to do that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I realized I had learned something from watching other
directors work, things about taking control. I'm glad I came to
directing after being on the set. I've worked with several
first-time directors who were editors or writers, and they're
really bewildered because they don't know the protocol, they don't
know all the individual jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   For a first-time effort, ``The Hi-Line'' has a real sense of
style, much of it stemming from Judkins' insistence that his actors
take time with the delivery of their lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first days of rehearsal, they would race through the
dialogue; they'd been taught that in acting school. But that's very
unrealistic to me. In real conversation, you hear somebody say
something, and it takes a second to think about it and formulate a
response. I told them not to speak until they had really heard what
the other person said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted there to be space. Having been a sound person, people
expected me to create a film heavy on sound design, with a lot of
noise. But it's just as important not to have sound, to have those
pauses. I think the film's sound parallels what the characters are
going through, this bleak emotional landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hi-Line'' has found a distributor and continues to make
the rounds of festivals. Meanwhile, Judkins has three projects on
the back burner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that it's an uphill battle for indy films.
Everyone thinks you go to Sundance and sell your movie. But there
are hundreds that don't get shown or picked up by a distributor.
Lots of really good little films don't get sold, and it's
heartbreaking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
