A8244 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     06-19 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA SUFFERS FROM KUDZU DEFICIENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have always felt that there was something missing from this
part of Florida and now I think I know what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Kudzu.
</P>
<P>
   Other states in the south are positively wallowing in kudzu and
their citizens seem happier and more prosperous as a result.
Residents of kudzu-intensive states like Georgia and Alabama make
baskets out of kudzu as well as jams, jellies, tofu and a kind of
wine that not only goes well with seafood but also doubles as a
particularly high-octane stock-car fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the kudzu-deficient plains of west-central Florida,
on the other hand, spend their free time complaining about the
drought.
</P>
<P>
   Kudzu is so scarce in these parts that some people may not even
know what it is. This is unfortunate because kudzu is not only
beautiful to look at, it is extremely easy to cultivate.
</P>
<P>
   In her essay ``How to Grow Kudzu,'' Thelma Mable Cooper points
out that kudzu grows equally well on concrete as it does in dirt.
She does suggest, however, that you plant you kudzu at night
because if you plant it by day, ``angry neighbors might see you and
throw rocks at you.''
</P>
<P>
   (I suspect that this is just the natural jealousy that people
who can't grow nice gardens have for people who can.)
</P>
<P>
   For fertilizer, Cooper recommends using 40-weight non-detergent
motor oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kudzu actually doesn't need anything to help it grow,'' Cooper
writes, ``but the motor oil helps to prevent scraping the underside
of the tender leaves when the kudzu starts its rapid growth. It
also cuts down on the friction and lessens the danger of fire when
the kudzu really starts to move. Change oil once every thousand
feet or every two weeks, whichever comes first.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other plants, kudzu can profit from a good mulch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found that a heavy mulch for the young plants produces a
hardier crop,'' Cooper writes. ``For best results, as soon as the
young shoots begin to appear, cover the kudzu with concrete blocks.
Although this causes a temporary setback, your kudzu will accept
this mulch as a challenge and will reward you with redoubled
determination in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Tree-huggers will be happy to know that kudzu is the perfect
plant for organic gardening. Advocates of the scorched-earth
approach to gardening will also find kudzu to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kudzu is oblivious to both chemicals and pests. Therefore, you
can grow organically and let the pests get out of the way of the
kudzu as best they can, or you can spray any commercial poison
directly on your crop. Your decision depends on how much you enjoy
killing bugs. The kudzu will not mind either way.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper also recommends growing kudzu close to your house,
especially if your house is not in very good condition and you want
to sell it. In a short time (five minutes), the kudzu will cover
your house completely, concealing minor flaws like broken windows,
cracked shingles, missing roof, etc. that might ``turn off''
prospective buyers.
</P>
<P>
   This quality of kudzu might be especially useful in Sarasota
where architecture nags complain about the lack of a unifying theme
in our public buildings. An impenetrable, green, leafy verdure
covering all buildings, including those that haven't even been
built yet, would not only provide such a theme, it would also
provide our many local artists with a free and abundant supply of
basket-weaving material.
</P>
<P>
   As if this were not enough, kudzu is extremely drought-resistant
to the point that blasting it with a flame-thrower only makes it
sprout more vines.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, those of us who live in this part of Florida have spent
too much time arguing about bridges and too little time touting the
joys of kudzu.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, if it's good enough for Georgia, it's good enough
for us.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
