<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERSQ&AMP;A0620-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q &AMP; A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for ``The Perfect Smile'' tooth whitening
system, distributed by Guthy-Renker Corp. Also, how can I get Lance
Armstrong's autograph?
</P>
<P>
   _ Linsey J.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Perfect Smile is no longer distributed by Guthy-Renker.
The system is available from ProHealth Laboratories ($24.58) at
(800) 520-1906. Unfortunately, Lance Armstrong does not mail
autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If Monday's child is fair of face, and Tuesday child is full
of grace, what are Wednesday, Thursday, Friday and Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   _ L. Smith A: Wednesday's child is full of woe, Thursday's child
has far to go, Friday's child is loving and giving, Saturday's
child works hard for a living, and the child born on the Sabbath
day is blithe and bonny and good and gay.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm moving into a smaller home and am interested in a Murphy
bed. Do you know where I can buy one?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bev D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Contact the Murphy Bed Co. at (800) 845-2337 or visit
www.murphybedcompany.com to purchase a system. Prices begin at $550
(mattress not included). The brainchild of San Franciscan William
L. Murphy this wall bed was invented out of desperation for more
space in a tiny apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Friends flew us to Matagorda Island, and while beachcombing,
my husband found a wine bottle with a note inside, plus a $1 bill
dated 1995. The note is mostly faded and printed in German. Do you
know of anyone who could bring out the printing?
</P>
<P>
   _ Flo Nix
</P>
<P>
   A: Not an old note, but a curious one. Try this recommendation
from the specialists at the University of Texas' Preservation and
Conservation Studies program. Attempt to raise the writing with a
high contrast copier or a black light.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The water dripping from my air conditioner looks like good,
clean water. Is it drinkable? Is it distilled?
</P>
<P>
   _ Tommy H.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I wouldn't do it,'' admits Jay Fox, natural resource
specialist, who added, ``It is no more safe than drinking the water
off a metal roof.'' Think about it. The metal surface of the unit
could be full of dust, dirt and algae. The water could contain
leached metal (not a healthy additive). At the very least (if
forced by catastrophe _ natural or otherwise), treat the water. Add
one teaspoon of bleach per gallon of water before consuming it.
Maybe using it on the lawn is a better idea.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Back in the mid- to late 1970s, there was a tabloid called
the Austin Sun. The sportswriter was Big Boy Medlin. His columns
were hilarious. Is he still writing somewhere?
</P>
<P>
   _ H.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: James ``Big Boy'' Medlin is special projects director for E!
Entertainment Network. His last special project was 1999's ``Search
Party,'' in which celebrities and viewers traveled to beach resorts
for ``crazy athletic events and off-the-wall scavenger hunts.'' A
far cry from his writing credit for ``Roadie.'' Write to him in
care of the network, 5750 Wilshire Blvd., Los Angeles, Calif.
90036.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At the airport, during a U.S. Customs check-in, my daughter
playfully snapped a picture of her friend's suitcase being
searched. To her surprise, the customs officer confiscated her
film. Is it really illegal to take a picture of a customs officer?
</P>
<P>
   _ Debbie Mullins
</P>
<P>
   A: It is not allowed. Customs inspectors have about as much
humor about photographs as they do about bomb threats. ``For
security and safety purposes, photographs are not allowed in this
non public area,'' says U.S. Customs spokeswoman Layne Lathram.
Criminal elements may take more than a passing interest in the
identities of these officers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a recipe that calls for 2 cups of Milnot. What is it,
and where can I find it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Nia Meissler
</P>
<P>
   A: Milnot is a canned evaporated milk product in which the fat
has been removed and replaced by soybean oil. Milnot is cholesterol
free. You can purchase the milk from the Milnot Co. by calling
(800) 877-6455. Of course, you will have to buy a case (24 12-ounce
cans).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a pair of fiddler crabs. The female is carrying a
sponge containing several thousand eggs. The sponge appeared nine
days ago. How long before the eggs are laid? Can they survive in
fresh water? How many can I expect to survive? What should I feed
them?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: The eggs have been laid, says Don Harper of the Texas A&AMP;M
Marine Lab. Female crabs generally carry their eggs attached to the
abdominal appendages until they hatch. If the crabs were collected
from a marine environment, they need a marine environment. Harper
warns that a very small percentage will survive. And the preferred
menu? Fiddlers scrape the surface layer of the mud where they live
and ``extract detritus and small living organisms with their
mouthparts,'' so the rich mud will provide the food.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the best oil to use after sanding a kitchen butcher
block table.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Mineral oil is the best to recondition the wood and help
prevent it from absorbing other juices (e.g. raw meat). Some
experts recommend heating the oil slightly before application (20
seconds in the microwave). Slather. Let the oil sit 5-10 minutes.
Wipe. Reapply if necessary. Q: Is there any place to order the
``Muggles for Harry Potter'' shirts that were sold at the Chicago
BookExpo?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but you will have to wait _ these popular T-shirts ($15
children's sizes, $18 adult, plus shipping) are back-ordered. A
``muggle,'' for those of you who are Harry Potter-challenged, is a
non magical person.
</P>
<P>
   Muggles shirt sales raise money for the American Booksellers
Foundation for Free Expression. The group is concerned that the
J.K. Rowling books have been challenged in 13 states. Want to help
spread the word that First Amendment challenges will be fought?
Pick up 100 Muggles for Harry Potter buttons for $40 ($30 for
members).
</P>
<P>
   Call ABFFE at (212) 587-4025 to put your name on the waiting
list for a shirt or to purchase the buttons now. Q: I have a friend
in California who has an 1840 Republic of Texas $3 bill, with a
serial number 10. Does it have any monetary value?
</P>
<P>
   _ William J. Robinson
</P>
<P>
   A: The Republic produced $3 bills along with $1, $2 and $5
bills. According to Calvin Burgin at Larry Spence Rare Coins, this
bill, depending on condition and authenticity, could be worth $25
to $150. The most valuable Republic of Texas currency? The $500
bill
</P>
<P>
   Q: I sent off for tickets to the David Letterman show in
December 1998. To ensure I would get tickets, I also sent a request
for my mother and my sister. It's been a year and a half and no
tickets. I'm ready for another trip to the Big Apple. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.W.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your previous requests could have been construed as multiples
and therefore discarded. The Letterman ticket team does not take
kindly to multiple ticket requests. Try again. Send a postcard to
Late Show Tickets, Ed Sullivan Theater, 1697 Broadway, New York
10019. Two tickets per postcard. The wait could be nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Standby tickets are issued by phone (no more waiting in line) on
the day of taping. Call (212) 247-6497 at 11 a.m. To try for
tickets due to cancellations, visit
www.cbs.com/network/tvshows/mini/lateshow/pantsnews/tickets.shtml.
Audience members must be 18 or older. Q: Can you please tell me who
the attorney was for Ruiz in Ruiz v. Estelle and how to get in
touch with him/her?
</P>
<P>
   _ L. P.
</P>
<P>
   A: You are looking for William Bennett Turner of Rogers, Joseph,
O'Donnell &AMP; Quinn, 311 California St., San Francisco, Calif. 94104.
A graduate of Harvard Law School and Northwestern University, civil
rights attorney Turner was born in Fort Worth. Turner represented
the prisoners in a number of suits consolidated by Federal Judge
William Wayne Justice into Ruiz v. Estelle, which resulted in
radical improvements in the Texas prison system.
</P>
<P>
   David Ruiz wrote his petition for improved prisoner's rights on
toilet paper. W.J. Estelle was the director of the department of
corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar: Etymologists have several theories about
the derivation of the popular American phrase ``OK.'' Some
attribute it to that well-intentioned phonetic speller Andrew
Jackson, who marked texts with ``Oll Korrect''; others to the
Democratic O.K. Club supporting the candidacy of Martin Van Buren.
O.K. stood for Old Kinderhook, a Van Buren title referring to the
Hudson Valley village of his birth. Mino by Guthy-Renker. The
system is available from ProHealth Laboratories ($24.58) at (800)
520-1906. Unfortunately, Lance Armstrong does not mail autographs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If Monday's child is fair of face, and Tuesday child is full
of grace, what are Wednesday, Thursday, Friday and Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   _ L. Smith A: Wednesday's child is full of woe, Thursday's child
has far to go, Friday's child is loving and giving, Saturday's
child works hard for a living, and the child born on the Sabbath
day is blithe and bonny and good and gay.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm moving into a smaller home and am interested in a Murphy
bed. Do you know where I can buy one?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bev D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Contact the Murphy Bed Co. at (800) 845-2337 or visit
www.murphybedcompany.com to purchase a syste.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the best oil to use after sanding a kitchen butcher
block table.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charles S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Mineral oil is the best to recondition the wood and help
prevent it from absorbing other juices (e.g. raw meat). Some
experts recommend heating the oil slightly before application (20
seconds in the microwave). Slather. Let the oil sit 5-10 minutes.
Wipe. Reapply if necessary. Q: Is there any place to order the
``Muggles for Harry Potter'' shirts that were sold at the Chicago
BookExpo?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but you will have to wait _ these popular T-shirts ($15
children's sizes, $18 adult, plus shipping) are back-ordered. A
``muggle,'' for those of you who are Harry Potter-challenged, is a
non magical person.
</P>
<P>
   Muggles shirt sales raise money for the American Booksellers
Foundation for Free Expression. The group is concerned that the
J.K. Rowling books have been challenged in 13 states. Want to help
spread the word that First Amendment challenges will be fought?
Pick up 100 Muggles for Harry Potter buttons for $40 ($30 for
members).
</P>
<P>
   Call ABFFE at (212) 587-4025 to put your name on the waiting
list for a shirt or to purchase the buttons now. Q: I have a friend
in California who has an 1840 Republic of Texas $3 bill, with a
serial number 10. Does it have any monetary value?
</P>
<P>
   _ William J. Robinson
</P>
<P>
   A: The Republic produced $3 bills along with $1, $2 and $5
bills. According to Calvin Burgin at Larry Spence Rare Coins, this
bill, depending on condition and authenticity, could be worth $25
to $150. The most valuable Republic of Texas currency? The $500
bill
</P>
<P>
   Q: I sent off for tickets to the David Letterman show in
December 1998. To ensure I would get tickets, I also sent a request
for my mother and my sister. It's been a year and a half and no
tickets. I'm ready for another trip to the Big Apple. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.W.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your previous requests could have been construed as multiples
and therefore discarded. The Letterman ticket team does not take
kindly to multiple ticket requests. Try again. Send a postcard to
Late Show Tickets, Ed Sullivan Theater, 1697 Broadway, New York
10019. Two tickets per postcard. The wait could be nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Standby tickets are issued by phone (no more waiting in line) on
the day of taping. Call (212) 247-6497 at 11 a.m. To try for
tickets due to cancellations, visit
www.cbs.com/network/tvshows/mini/lateshow/pantsnews/tickets.shtml.
Audience members must be 18 or older. Q: Can you please tell me who
the attorney was for Ruiz in Ruiz v. Estelle and how to get in
touch with him/her?
</P>
<P>
   _ L. P.
</P>
<P>
   A: You are looking for William Bennett Turner of Rogers, Joseph,
O'Donnell &AMP; Quinn, 311 California St., San Francisco, Calif. 94104.
A graduate of Harvard Law School and Northwestern University, civil
rights attorney Turner was born in Fort Worth. Turner represented
the prisoners in a number of suits consolidated by Federal Judge
William Wayne Justice into Ruiz v. Estelle, which resulted in
radical improvements in the Texas prison system.
</P>
<P>
   David Ruiz wrote his petition for improved prisoner's rights on
toilet paper. W.J. Estelle was the director of the department of
corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar: Etymologists have several theories about
the derivation of the popular American phrase ``OK.'' Some
attribute it to that well-intentioned phonetic speller Andrew
Jackson, who marked texts with ``Oll Korrect''; others to the
Democratic O.K. Club supporting the candidacy of Martin Van Buren.
O.K. stood for Old Kinderhook, a Van Buren title referring to the
Hudson Valley village of his birth. Minority opinions include ``aux
quais,'' French for ``at the docks'' (where le action is) or an
Indian term, ``okeh,'' meaning ``it's so.'' Wonder how Oklahomans
feel about all this?
</P>
