<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News fast? Why not try dieting?
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ A few weeks ago, the mellow, accentless
voice of Dr. Andrew Weil came out of my car radio, courtesy of
National Public Radio, and told me to turn off the news.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Weil is a holistic, New Age, alt-medicine practitioner with
an auralike ring of white hair and beard around his face and a book
in the stores, ``Eight Weeks to Optimum Health.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is filled with health tips. Like drinking filtered
water, trying breathing exercises, drinking ginseng teas and eating
your broccoli. He also prescribes a ``news fast.'' No newspapers,
no radio, no TV.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on this would be a fairly transparent conflict of
interest. If too many people fast figuratively, I would fast
literally.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the idea that I might not be good for your optimum health
gets me down. It suggests that in the feast of knowledge, I'm a
mere glazed jelly donut.
</P>
<P>
   But Weil has a point. A lot of news taken indiscriminately and
without a sense of humor could make someone view the world as a
loud, stupid and dangerous place.
</P>
<P>
   People who expect horrible things because they think real life
is like the crime-o-rama of local TV news probably would be
cynical, unhappy, unlikely to feel optimum.
</P>
<P>
   I have been on extended news fasts. I did this when I was on
vacation or at a university. In other words, at times when little
was expected from me.
</P>
<P>
   But a news fast is an extreme measure. What's called for instead
is a better news diet. And it's not hard to read healthy, get your
daily minimum dose of irony, and still feel as good as realist
would dare.
</P>
<P>
   Here, then, are the strata of the news-intake pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   AVOID LIST:
</P>
<P>
   Child actors, celebrities with causes, people who interpret Alan
Greenspan, Donald Trump, gun nuts, anyone associated with any
prosecution that vied for the title ``trial of the century.'' In
particular avoid: People who have unsuccessfully run for president
twice or more, people who have run for any office more than three
times, rock musicians on a comeback after drug-abuse and personal
scandal, second-tier shock jocks, profess
</P>
<P>
   ional doomsayers, sound-bite moralists and anyone not in uniform
carrying any kind of flag. And car wrecks. You would know they
happen whether they were in the paper or not. Anything additional
is mere variation on the theme.
</P>
<P>
   READ SPARINGLY
</P>
<P>
   You should count to three before reading: A crime story more
than 50 miles from your home. A story that announces a hot trend
based on a television show and what two guys from the office say. A
story with more than one unnamed source that take more than six
words to describe _ sources close to people familiar with those
involved in the case. A story about anyone's divorce or
child-custody fight (whether or not they are from Cuba). A story
using the phrase ``tech-heavy Nasdaq.'' Any political media event
that involves use of props. Political polls.
</P>
<P>
   READ AS MUCH AS YOU LIKE:
</P>
<P>
   Comics. You are not too old to read the comics. Columnists, of
course columnists. They are sterling but misunderstood and
underpaid people who bring humor and perspective to a confusing
world. Stories about the stupidity of criminals. They will enhance
your sense of personal safety. State Legislature stories. They can
be dull, but legislatures have more direct effect on folks than our
over-covered White House. Letters to the editor that don't involve
guns, abortion or the Social Security benefit notch. Anything about
someone actually accomplishing something.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of junk-news out there. I don't blame Dr. Weil for
wanting to chuck it all.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is some danger that, in our ignorance of the world,
bad people with less-than-optimum designs on our health and welfare
would be left to do what they want.
</P>
<P>
   There probably were self-actualized people in optimum health who
were on news fasts in Germany when Adolf Hitler came to power.
</P>
<P>
   Optimum health will only take you so far.
</P>
<P>
   Being engaged in the outside world is stressful and trying. But
taking that on is part of what we laughingly call ``being an
adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, I just report the news.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
