<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0620-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Common sense and government don't always mix
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ A few columns ago I was complaining about the
new postmaster who came to town after our Mr. Reed retired, and as
good as accused me of trying to steal a mailing envelope when he
could see that all I was doing
</P>
<P>
   was stuffing my old blue dress into it to mail to a friend for
her yard sale.
</P>
<P>
   The new postmaster and I were the only folks in the place, so it
wasn't like I was going to make off with his envelope and get lost
in the crowd. Besides he knows my name, my face, and where I live.
And my picture isn't even on his ``WANTED'' wall.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, he got a little pushy, and I got a little huffy _ for
all the good it did me, because he still made me pay for the
envelope separately before I finished stuffing it.
</P>
<P>
   Did he really think I was intending to knock over his post
office for a lousy red, white, and blue mailer? Apparently he did.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, I wrote about it and as it turns out, a lot of folks
had something to add.
</P>
<P>
   An 80-year-old M.D. in California wrote: ``Your comments were on
target. Born and raised in Ballard/Clinton, Mo. After WW2 service
and finishing school, I moved to Rialto, Calif. (population 2800
and citrus groves). Now Rialto is 80,000-plus and one orange grove.
If I call the P.O., I get Denver, Colo. P.O. exchange. My mail
service is mostly borderline poor. Progress sometimes isn't all it
is cracked up to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of reminds me of the conversation I overheard once in the
teacher's lounge at school. ``I need a repairman _ my washer won't
spin,'' my colleague wailed into the phone. There was a pause, then
she said: ``In Pemberville'' ... `` near Bowling Green'' ...
``Ohio! Where are you?'' She slapped a palm to her forehead and
repeated in absolute disbelief. ``You're telling me I have to talk
to somebody in Utah to have a washing machine repaired in northwest
Ohio?''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what they were telling her.
</P>
<P>
   In the small town of Woodville, Ohio, an insurance agency owner
has been having a little fun of her own. ``The IRS,'' she explains,
``sent us a letter stating they couldn't mail our return check to
us at a post office box and that every time they had mailed it to
our street address, the post office had sent it back to them. They
couldn't get the check to us anywhere _ but they could get the
letter to us at the street address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the post office where we've been doing business for
generations, and said, ``We have a problem here. One federal agency
(the IRS) is saying we can't use a post office box for taxes. The
other (post office) is saying if I have a post office box, I have
to use that box number. What do I do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We went round and round on this for weeks. Then one day the
post office said the carrier could deliver mail to my street
address on Monday through Friday, but if it has the box number on
it, it stays at the post office until we pick
</P>
<P>
   it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's no problem, I explained, since the post office is less
than a block away. But I asked if it wouldn't be easier on the
carrier if they just put all our mail in the box and let us pick it
up. Nope, they couldn't do that. ``I asked what they were going to
do with mail for the agency's street address on Saturday when we're
closed. The clerk said, ``Oh, we'll just throw that in your box.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dumbfounded. It makes no sense that they can't put
street-addressed mail in my box Monday through Friday, but it's
okay on Saturday. I asked why, and the clerk said it was
``regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   From the looks of my mail, a lot of folks are confused by and
annoyed with the postal service. So am I. And I resent paying the
salary of some guy who sits in Washington cranking out silly
directives warning the Gibsonburg postmaster to be on the lookout
for grand theft _ envelope.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to common sense?
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
