<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An online grocery trip proves less than perfect
 &HT;    By Jennifer Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I got a call on the weekend from a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got it,'' she said. ``You've got to try it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' is a new Internet grocery delivery service. ``It'' had
dominated a good portion of the conversation at a local coffee
house where three of us were attempting to knit together wits that
had been thoroughly unraveled by the Pandora's box that is the end
of school.
</P>
<P>
   We were swapping notes on summer plans when the conversation
took a sharp right. Commiserating on the upcoming need for more
food to feed children suddenly home all day led to tales of
``why-I-hate-going-to-the-supermarket.'' (The group consensus was
that food shopping is like housework, a necessary evil doomed to be
repeated and repeated and repeated.)
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' said my friend, ''maybe not if you do it on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   We were skeptical. Would it really save time? Could you find
everything you need? What about preferred brands? (Morris the cat
could take lessons from my son in finicky eating.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As we talked I realized a sea change had occurred. As little as
a month ago, my friend had little to no interest in the Internet
beyond its ability to help her son with his homework. When I asked
for her e-mail address so I could send her some sites to look at
for summer camps, she couldn't remember it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she was raving about the joy of online grocery shopping.
The difference, of course, was that this use of the Internet had
function and meaning, immediate meaning, in her life. One
time-consuming weekly chore _ a physical trip to the grocery store
nutes.
</P>
<P>
   I settled in to do my shopping. I confess I didn't read the all
instructions. (I'd blocked out time but not that much.) It was
still a little cumbersome, but much less so than the earlier sites
I'd shopped on. About sixty-five percent of the time I found my
preferred brand, and I wasn't certain what the ``store brand'' was.
It did appear that using the site would become easier with
increased use.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from my friend, I saved pertinent items on a weekly
list as I did my shopping. A little over an hour later, I was
nearly done. ``Not bad,'' I was thinking. ``I could get used to
this. Call up my weekly list, add, subtract. ... I'm outta here.''
</P>
<P>
   And I was, just not as I had planned. The server died and my
carefully almost completed virtual shopping list was gone.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, that's technology.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
