<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WordPerfect vs. Word brouhaha keeps churning
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The uproar created by my discovery and disclosure of a
sinister underground network of DOS users has now evolved into a
frontal attack upon my choice of word processors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a management consultant for a wide variety of large and
small firms and I have to be equally proficient in Word and
WordPerfect,'' writes Mike Atchison.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my favorite things to do with Word-centric writers _
such as you appear to be _ is to challenge them to reproduce a page
out of any publication, and I'll do the same page in WordPerfect.
I'll beat them by almost 20 percent every time.''
</P>
<P>
   As I said last week in regard to a similar offer from the
redoubtable Miz Becker of Denver, I'm not accepting challenges
these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find WordPerfect 9 to be just as easy to use and much faster
with complicated layouts. By the way, it still has the great
`reveal codes' feature that Word users never get a chance to
appreciate.''
</P>
<P>
   Here Atchison makes the same assumption as Becker did in last
week's column. It has obviously not occurred to either of them that
there may be some of us who don't want to be confronted with codes.
</P>
<P>
   Having a word processor that will reveal its codes implies that
the user wants to fiddle with them. This in turn inevitably implies
that the user knows what the codes mean. I don't know what they
mean. I don't want to know what they mean. I don't want to be one
of those men Who Knew Too Much.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to another, potentially more serious, issue with the
whole idea of a word processor that reveals its codes. It smacks of
Bring Your Child to Work Day at the National Security Agency.
</P>
<P>
   What is a code for, if not to keep secrets? A word processor
that will blab its secrets to any Tom, Dick or Geeky who happens to
click his mouse in the right place is a low, treacherous thing.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, obviously, is an outfit that knows how to keep a
secret, and it has instilled this sterling trait into its word
processor. I applaud that.
</P>
<P>
   Next comes J.B. McKoy, to compare Word unfavorably with
WordStar:
</P>
<P>
   ``With all of Word's bloatedness, I have yet to find the simple
but very useful block copy function in it that was present in
WordStar 18 years ago,'' he writes. ``This function allowed you to
mark the upper left and lower right corners of any block of text in
the body of a document, and copy it. There have been many times
I've wanted to just take a chunk of a page in Word, but it requires
you to take entire rows instead. This means a lot of manual work to
get the piece you wanted in the first place. Do you know why such a
simple but useful function would still be missing from Word?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Mr. McKoy, imagination fails me. If I understand you
right, you want to be able to copy, let's say, only the right half
of a paragraph. The concept works with a spreadsheet, but I can't
see its use when dealing with text. Applying that idea to this
paragraph, you might have:
</P>
<P>
   ``me. Why would anyone want
</P>
<P>
   to copy, let's say,
</P>
<P>
   The concept works with a
</P>
<P>
   spreadsheet, but I
</P>
<P>
   Applying that idea to this para-
</P>
<P>
   graph, you''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt I'm missing something here. Perhaps that the right
techniques, probably involving a pair of pliers and a hypodermic
full of sodium pentothal, would persuade Word to reveal its codes
on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
