<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0620-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yahoo's treasures prove it's not just a search engine
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Well, here's a surprise from our friends at Yahoo
Internet Life magazine (www.yil.com). In its July issue listing 10
Internet essentials, Web portal Yahoo is the number one pick for
searching the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it's become much more than just a directory, Yahoo
remains the first place to look for Web sites on a particular
topic,'' the blurb for Yahoo says, along with the disclaimer
``(Yahoo) is our licensing partner but we're editorially
independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   But affiliation or no affiliation, Yahoo (www.yahoo.com) still
topped a list of essential Web sites that included a lot of sites
that actually are pretty useful, such as weather.com, tickets.com,
Excite's newstracker (nt.excite.com) and Careerbuilder's mega job
search (www.careerbuilder.com).
</P>
<P>
   So there is an off chance that maybe Yahoo Internet Life isn't
taking the easy way out by picking its licensing partner as the
best place to search the Web. It might be time to take a second
look at Yahoo and see how much service and utility it provides for
its legions of users.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo is the oldest, the biggest and without a shadow of a doubt
the most jam-packed Web portal online. It's also one of the most
popular.
</P>
<P>
   Since Tom Filo and Jerry Yang founded Yahoo in the mid '90s, a
crop of really good Web portals such as Lycos, Snap and Excite have
cropped up offering a wide variety of features and services in
addition to just plain old Web searching.
</P>
<P>
   There are also great sites like Google that simply let you
search, no shopping, no stock quotes, just searching. So even
though Yahoo is no longer the only game in town, it's still one of
the most popular sites on the Web. After America Online, it's the
second most popular site on the Web, with approximately 49 million
unique visitors in April, according to Web measurement firm Media
Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   When people talked about Yahoo, they used to call it a search
engine, but Yahoo's very testy spokespeople always insisted that
Yahoo was much more than that, and, upon close inspection, it is.
Like it or not, Yahoo is a category killer when it comes to wading
through and ultimately finding the needle in the enormous Internet
haystack.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to Yahoo's success is in the way it tries to organize
the Web, not just by category and subject but by country and
special interest areas for news hounds, sports fans, and financial
wizards. Name y section (finance.yahoo.com) is a search/information
engine that is strictly devoted to financial news and information.
Links to almost every financial site imaginable, a partnership with
Reuters, and the ability for users to track their own stock
portfolios make YahooFinance one of the best financial portals on
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo is a global concern, as anyone who scrolls down to the
bottom of the start page will see. There are many other Yahoos in
many other countries and languages. This is one feature of Yahoo
that more Web searchers should take advantage of.
</P>
<P>
   A search for ``Gladiators'' star Russell Crowe doesn't turn up
much on the American site, but a visit to Yahoo Australia and New
Zealand has reams of information about the Australian Oscar
nominee, including information and digital downloads of his very
obscure, very alternative rock band.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Web users have already discovered Yahoo mail, a free
Web-based e-mail service, while many more use Yahoo to keep up on
current events with its news sections that attack national and
international news with the sort of depth of coverage you could
search for on your own if you had at least half a day and a
complete knowledge of the Web. Yahoo also has auctions and shopping
areas, but they're not the real reason people go to Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   But that said, users who visit Yahoo Travel shopping for
airfares will find that its online partner, Travelocity
(www.travelocity.com) may suggest a substantially cheaper fare to a
nearby city. It's the value-added bonus of alliances like this one
that keep users coming back to Yahoo to do a lot more than search.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Yahoo is all about searching the Web and organizing
a seemingly endless stream of information into easy-to-find,
easy-to-digest bites. Yahoo organizes the Web in such a way that no
matter what obscure bit of information you want to find, it will
find a way to bring it to you.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
