 &HT;    A DVD for the dollar-conscious
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Still leery about this new-fangled DVD technology? Leer no more.
Konka has sidled into the home entertainment market with the
KD1800U DVD deck ($199; www.konkausa.com), an ``affordably'' priced
unit that, nevertheless, still offers picture and sound quality
notably superior to a high-end VHS player. Respectably functional
with standard DVD features _ remote, multiple language options, CD
and S-Video compatibility, various screen sizes and ratios _ the
KD1800U has a fresh and stylish appearance, sleek and silver, which
belies the fact it's a low-end component. By the time this sexy
thing gives up the ghost, high-end DVD players will be similarly
priced, which makes the KD1800U the perfect starter DVD machine.
Still leery? You're still playing 8-track tapes, too, aren't you?
</P>
<P>
   'FIGHT CLUB' DVD A REAL PUNCH IN THE NOSE
</P>
<P>
   Disenfranchised, disgruntled and ultimately disassociated guys
from the IKEA Generation start a bare-fisted brawl society in order
to vent all that world-weary angst. Then things get interesting.
Then, when things start to get a little weird, they get extremely
weird. Targeted directly at the 30-year old male-without-an-outlet
demographic, Fight Club Special Edition DVD ($35; www.foxdvd.com)
is hemorrhaging with extras: optional feature length running
commentary _ thoughts and anecdotes from actors Brad Pitt, Edward
Norton, Helena Bonham Carter and director David Fincher, for
example, as well as craft secrets elucidated by the production
crew. This edition also includes a second DVD gushing with extra
footage, behind-the-scenes clips, beguiling stills and concept art
gallery, and much more. Also featured for the first time is the new
``THX Optimode'' that allows for individual calibration of audio
and video to optimize one's home theatre performance.
</P>
