<HEADER>
A8271 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-FEATURE-GWTW0620-     06-19 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-GWTW0620-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Margaret Mitchell's childhood writings have reappeared _ and now
you can see them
 &HT;    By Julie Bookman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Have you ever written poetry, a short story or even a
book _ or at least started one? What do you do with stuff you
write? Do you toss it, hide it, show it to anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Mitchell, who was born Nov. 8, 1900, in Atlanta, wrote
all the time as a young girl. As a young adult, she worked as a
reporter for this newspaper (earning $25 a week).
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1926, in a tiny apartment she called ``The Dump,'' she
started writing ``Gone With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   It was published in 1936 and caused a worldwide sensation. The
book is a sweeping saga (a big, epic story) set in and around
Atlanta before, during and after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   While ``GWTW'' is loved by millions, it isn't loved by everyone.
African-Americans have long objected to the way Mitchell depicted
slaves and slave owners in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Several books have been written about Mitchell and how she came
to write the famous book. But after she died in 1949, family
members followed her wishes and destroyed most of her letters and
other writings.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell probably never dreamed that an old box of her childhood
writings would be unearthed in the 1990s, giving fans and scholars
greater insight into the natural talent she displayed as young as
age 8 and 9.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happened. Seven years ago, two people were
cleaning out an old Atlanta house. In one crushed and filthy
cardboard box, they were amazed to discover Mitchell's childhood
writings. They found letters, diaries, plays and stories, all
written by Mitchell between 1907 and 1918, from age 7 through her
high school years.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those writings have been collected into a new book
called ``Before Scarlett: Girlhood Writings of Margaret Mitchell,''
edited by Jane Eskridge (Hill Street Press, $21.95).
</P>
<P>
   You can also see many of these newly discovered childhood items
at the Margaret Mitchell House &AMP; Museum in Midtown. The exhibit is
included when you take a tour of ``The Dump,'' which has been
restored to look much like it did when Mitchell lived there.
</P>
<P>
   DID YOU KNOW?
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Mitchell was considered a tomboy and even had the
nickname ``Jimmy.'' She liked animals and loved riding ponies. She
also loved to play baseball, fly kites, go skating and get into
mudball fights.
</P>
<P>
   The 1939 movie version of ``Gone With the Wind'' _ one of the
first movies in color _ won eight Academy Awards, including best
picture. (It beat ``The Wizard of Oz.'')
</P>
<P>
   The best-selling book of all time is the Bible, with an
estimated 3.8 billion copies sold from 1815 to 1999. Next in line
are ``Gone With the Wind'' and ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' by Harper
Lee. Each has sold more than 30 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
