<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8276 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TV-COLUMN062     06-19 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TV-COLUMN0620-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The `doctor' is in, dispensing bitter pills
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Laura Schlessinger, the radio talker who equates
anti-gay bigotry with family values, is coming to television this
fall, and the sparks are already starting to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Should ``Dr. Laura,'' as she bills herself, be allowed to call
gays and lesbians ``biological errors'' on a nationally syndicated
TV show? The First Amendment tells us she has the right to say it,
but we don't have to listen. Or agree with her.
</P>
<P>
   But the power of TV adds another dimension to the free speech
debate. It's not like Schlessinger is espousing her views on a
street corner, where anyone who wants to can step up and disagree.
When ``Dr. Laura'' arrives Sept. 11, the only option offended
viewers will have is to hit the remote or write letters to the
station.
</P>
<P>
   As the debut nears, debate is springing up around the country.
Why are stations carrying a show that some people believe is
nothing more than hate-mongering? On the other hand, people who
believe Schlessinger is simply spouting old-fashioned
Judeo-Christian values don't understand what the fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   First a bit of background. Schlessinger, who has a doctorate in
physiology, is the most popular radio talk show host in the
country. The TV version of ``Dr. Laura'' is being produced by
Paramount, which is owned by Viacom, which also owns CBS. Thus, all
CBS-owned and -operated stations were strongly encouraged to buy
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an opportunity to decline and did not,'' said Ross
Newsome, Austin's KEYE's general manager. ``She's a dynamic
personality. She can be very condescending and rude, but 20 million
people tune in to her radio show. Whether you agree with her or
not, it makes you stop and think, and thought-provoking
entertainment is what we want.''
</P>
<P>
   No pilot for the new series was made, so nobody except
Schlessinger and company knows what to expect. We do know she will
address myriad topics, not just homosexuality, and she will have
guests and a studio audience. If it's similar to her radio show,
topics will include child rearing, marriage and social issues. If
her style is the same, she'll be strident, loud and preachy. Even
people who agree with her are sometimes put off by her know-it-all
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a genius to figure out why ``Dr. Laura'' is
coming to television. She's popular on radio, and she could make a
lot of money for a lot of people on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially the sampling will be big because it does well here
on radio,'' Newsome said. ``She has a core audience, and we think
this could be a franchise program for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't take a genius to figure out why gays and lesbians
are upset by the prospect. Nationally, the Gay and Lesbian Alliance
Against Defamation, or GLAAD, has launched a campaign to ``Stop Dr.
Laura.'' Locally, the Austin Gay and Lesbian Political Caucus is
considering its options. Representatives of the group have met with
KEYE executives and expressed their concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them what we found offensive _ that her remarks are
defamatory and often outright misrepresentative,'' said Allan
Baker, co-chairman of the caucus. ``This kind of speech, given such
a potentially large audience, contributes to an atmosphere of hate
and intolerance. And it can lead to hate crimes and discrimination,
especially against gay and lesbian youth.''
</P>
<P>
   KEYE's general manager was impressed with the caucus and says he
takes their concerns seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand their sense of caution and how damaging some of
her views have been to the gay and lesbian community,'' Newsome
says. ``But in this wonderful democracy we live in, she has a right
to be heard and judged.''
</P>
<P>
   So, are GLAAD and the Austin caucus advocating censorship? Isn't
this a free speech issue?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a free speech issue, because no one has the right to
a TV show,'' Baker says. ``She can express herself any time she
wants, but when she does it on TV, I don't get a chance for
rebuttal in the same forum.''
</P>
<P>
   t she thinks. But speaking on television does have more of an
impact than yammering in a civic auditorium. The show's producers
and distributor must be mindful of that and open up the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   But this argument wouldn't even rear its head if someone came
along with a talk show that lambasted African Americans, Hispanics,
Asians or Jews. Would a pilot called ``The KKK Koffee Klatch'' or
``Nazi Nattering'' be considered? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   And yet a host who blasts gays and lesbians has a show in mid
afternoon, a time when children, especially impressionable teens,
are home watching. It's pathetic and potentially dangerous, but it
probably won't last. Hearing her for three hours a day is bound to
be enough, even for her ardent fans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
