<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, June 20, 2000 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN20 _ A fire alarm sends luxury apartment
residents fleeing from their building at 4 a.m. with barely clothes
on their backs and into the middle of a street party where young
men and women are dressed in their finest party duds. (Joe Murray,
Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ A few columns ago I was
complaining about the new postmaster who came to town after our Mr.
Reed retired, and as good as accused me of trying to steal a
mailing envelope when he could see that all I was doing was
stuffing my old blue dress into it to mail to a friend for her yard
sale. Naturally, I wrote about it and as it turns out, a lot of
folks had something to add. (Schuett, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ A few weeks ago, the mellow,
accentless voice of Dr. Andrew Weil came out of my car radio,
courtesy of National Public Radio, and told me to turn off the
news. Dr. Weil is a holistic, New Age, alt-medicine practitioner
with an auralike ring of white hair and beard around his face and a
book in the stores, ``Eight Weeks to Optimum Health.'' (Lane,
Daytona Beach News-Journal). MOVED.
</P>
