<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: MY WASHINGTON PAJAMA PARTY
 &HT;    By JOE MURRAY
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It wasn't until I had clumped down seven flights of
stairs, my shoes hastily affixed to the wrong feet, and had burst
through the fire exit onto the street at 4 a.m. did I realize, by
golly, maybe the building really was on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the chaos that greeted me.
</P>
<P>
   A police unit with emergency lights exploding like disco strobes
had traffic sealed off at the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Cars and people were everywhere. You would have thought it was
New Year's Eve, instead of nearly dawn on a Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Was that screaming I heard, people trapped in the burning
building from which I had narrowly escaped?
</P>
<P>
   But, as my grogginess began to clear, I realized that it was a
happy noise _ people laughing and talking up and down the crowded
sidewalks and side streets, young men and women dressed in their
finest, fanciest party duds.
</P>
<P>
   And if I had to guess, I'd say they were likely laughing at me
and my fellow residents of the luxury apartment building where a
fire alarm had sent us fleeing into the streets.
</P>
<P>
   There we were, barely with clothes on our backs and huddled
along the edge of the sidewalk, while all around us there was a
party going on.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought _ at 4 a.m. _ that people could be having
such a good time?
</P>
<P>
   Music was everywhere, blaring from shiny, sleek automobiles
lined bumper to bumper both ways on the street, like a parade
coming from both directions.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the cop was doing there, trying to control the
traffic. I doubt the police even knew about the fire alarm.
</P>
<P>
   But it had certainly gotten my attention.
</P>
<P>
   WEE-WAAW, WEE-WAAW, the siren sounded over the room speaker. And
then this recorded voice:
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fire reported in the building. Please leave the
building by the nearest exit. Do not use the elevators.''
</P>
<P>
   Didn't have to tell me twice, though it kept repeating and
repeating and repeating ...
</P>
<P>
   WEE-WAAW, WEE-WAAW!
</P>
<P>
   I was out of there, barely taking time to pull on a shirt and
pair of pants, grab my wallet and jump into my shoes wrong feet
first, and then go galloping down the stairs and out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Only to find myself in the midst of a street party.
</P>
<P>
   By all appearances, the bunch of us was gathered together like a
gaggle of street people, a backwash of pinched, white faces,
alternatively flushed and pale, middle-aged fossils gasping and
wheezing, forced from our apartment fortress and into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the onlyreason we were up this time of the early
morning was to go the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   I managed to hitch up my britches, tuck in my shirt tail and
swap my shoes to the proper feet. The others were tidying
themselves similarly, as best they could in what they were wearing.
</P>
<P>
   As a group we shuffled to the front of the building, where the
arched canopy at the entrance offered refuge. Indeed, assembled
refugees were what we resembled.
</P>
<P>
   And all around us ... it's party time!
</P>
<P>
   Some time later, maybe half an hour, we were informed that it
was OK to return to our rooms, that the fire alarm had been a false
alarm. I don't know about everybody else, but I would have been
just as happy hanging around on the street a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. I piled onto an elevator with the rest of them.
Outside we had stood stone silent. Now everyone was speaking at the
same time. But not one word about the fire alarm. What we were
talking about was the 4 a.m. celebration we had witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   One white-haired couple, explaining that they lived on the
street side of the building, said it was like that every weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes on and on,'' the man said. ``Finally, the police will
use bullhorns to tell everybody to get off the streets, go to their
cars and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that we went home as well, to luxury apartments where
you pay upwards of $2,000 a month, to sleep safely and securely in
the knowledge that a security force was on duty at every locked
entrance to our building.
</P>
<P>
   But you had to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Were we the privileged ones?
</P>
<P>
   Were we the ones most enjoying life?
</P>
<P>
   Or were we the ones locked out?
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net;
</P>
<P>
   mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; website,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
