<SLUG> BC-HEATH-LEDGER-IN-THE-PATRIOT-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SON OF THE AMERICAN REVOLUTION: HEATH LEDGER ON `THE PATRIOT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Heath Ledger in a scene from ``The
Patriot.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    You say you want a revolution? Heath Ledger is happy to oblige.
 &HT;    The young Australian actor, who first caught Hollywood's eye
with his swinging, singing Shakespearean turn in ``10 Things I Hate
About You,'' finds himself in Colonial America in ``The Patriot,''
opening nationwide on June 28.
 &HT;    One of this summer's event pictures, ``The Patriot'' casts
Ledger as the son of Mel Gibson, another brooding and handsome
Aussie _ though, oddly enough, both are cast as Americans this time
around. It's the story of Gabriel Martin (Ledger), a staunch
Colonialist who defies the orders of his father, retired war hero
Benjamin Martin (Gibson) and enlists in the Revolutionary War. One
thing leads to another, and soon father is drawn into battle
alongside son.
 &HT;    ``The thing that was really interesting to me was that Gabriel
had an unusual arc to his life,'' the affable Ledger says by
telephone from Columbia Pictures' New York offices. ``He makes the
transition from young boy to young man.
 &HT;    ``I could relate to that,'' Ledger says. ``I could understand
that time of life, when you step out from your father's opinions
and have your own ideas for the first time in your life. When you
discover that in yourself, it's rather exciting. The energy in you
is exaggerated, and you make exaggerated stands.
 &HT;    ``I think Martin sees himself in Gabriel,'' the actor says
thoughtfully. ``He was quite a savage, and I guess he could see
that bloodlust and enthusiasm coming out of me. He's afraid for me
to discover those qualities in myself _ but, of course, I'm not
going to listen to him, not going to hear any of that until I
discover it for myself.''
 &HT;    The 21-year-old Australian, who hails from Perth, admits that he
knew ``only the basics'' about the Revolutionary War when he signed
on for ``The Patriot.'' He did some studying to prepare, but says
that he was more interested in a sense of the era than in
historical details as such.
 &HT;    ``Obviously I couldn't begin to read enough books to discover a
real insight into what happened, to discover an insight into
Gabriel,'' he says. ``The Revolutionary War is pretty much just a
setting for the story, and the story is about a family. It's a love
story between a father and son that's set during the Revolutionary
War.''
 &HT;    Bonding with Gibson proved easy, Ledger says, mercifully going
easy on the hyperbole.
 &HT;    ``Mel and I had a mutual understanding that we just found in
each other's eyes when we first met,'' he says. ``We didn't go
fishing or anything. Most importantly, we developed a mateship as
friends, instantly, and that translates through to a relationship
as father and son.
 &HT;    ``We pretty much knew how it was going to play, and we took it
from there.''
 &HT;    Ledger's favorite scene in the movie is one in which Gabriel
confronts his father about his war experience. Ledger, Gibson,
director Roland Emmerich and his crew gathered on location at
Cypress Gardens, a manmade marsh, on a blustery winter's night to
capture the moment.
 &HT;    ``It was the last scene we shot for the movie,'' Ledger says.
``We shot it on Jan. 21, all night, until about 8 a.m. It was just
Mel and I sitting around a campfire, and it felt good. I felt
connected to Mel.
 &HT;    ``It was the end of the movie,'' he says. ``We'd been through so
much, and it was a turning point in the story, where Gabriel pulls
something out of his father, from the depths.
 &HT;    ``There was also a lunar eclipse that night, so there was a
blood-red moon in the sky that made the moment even more
beautiful.''
 &HT;    As ``The Patriot'' prepares to storm theaters, Ledger _ whose
credits include ``Black Rock'' (1997) and the Australian television
series ``Roar'' (1997) _ stands at the intersection of anonymity
and stardom. Though some are touting him as the next Mel Gibson,
Ledger simply wants to be Heath Ledger.
 &HT;    ``I haven't felt it yet,'' he says of his next-big-thing status.
``The only time I think about it is when people ask me about it. I
don't let it bother me.
 &HT;    ``It's there,'' he admits after a moment. ``Everything around me
is suddenly changing. But that little spark inside of me is still
the same. I really don't spend that much time thinking about fame,
and I don't care to.''
 &HT;    Instead, Ledger thinks about acting, a craft to which he's
devoted more than half his life, but one that still stirs his real
passion.
 &HT;    ``Acting is a medium of expression for me,'' he says. ``I get to
pass something from me to someone else, and I love to do that. It's
a medium of art, too.
 &HT;    ``I guess I was 12 when I started in amateur theater,'' he says.
``It was just a hobby. I never said I wanted to go to Hollywood, I
never thought I'd be making movies.
 &HT;    ``But doors kept opening and I kept following paths,'' Ledger
says. ``And it's been fun. Along the way I discovered myself. I had
to discover myself in order to portray people _ I had to fully
understand myself, inside and out.
 &HT;    ``So that's been a journey for me.''
 &HT;    Ledger's journey is only beginning, of course. He's halfway
through filming ``A Knight's Tale,'' which he calls ``a comedy
about the jousting life that's set in 15th-century London.'' Once a
``Tale'' is told, Ledger will move on to ``Four Feathers,'' a
remake of the classic 1939 British drama about a 19th-century war
deserter who attempts to reclaim the respect of his family and
friends.
 &HT;    As serious as he may be about his work, Ledger _ who considers
Los Angeles his current base, though right now he says he's
``living out of bags wherever I'm shooting'' _ stresses that he
doesn't live his roles. He's not his characters, and they aren't
him.
 &HT;    ``I tend to try to use the method of just acting,'' he says.
``That's what I feel my job is ... I'm pretty relaxed when it comes
to being on a set. I don't like to walk around and stress out too
much. It keeps things fresh for me, keeps things spontaneous.
 &HT;    ``I love acting, love it with a passion,'' he says. ``But it's
also just something that fills up a bit of time and space between A
and C in my life. Ultimately, on the grand scale of things, acting
is quite insignificant to life in general.
 &HT;    ``But I do love it, and that's why I'm still doing it.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Patriot,'' consult the
official Web site at www.thepatriot.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
