<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TAKES-OVER-TELEVISION-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME CANADA!: CANADIANS ARE TAKING OVER AMERICAN TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Hayden Christensen in a scene from
``Higher Ground.'') 
 By KEVIN DICKSON  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before July 7, 2000. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The far North is heading south.
</P>
<P>
   In years past there were always one or two Canadian-born
celebrities who would break out of that country's frigid climes and
into the American show-biz spotlight. Remember the heydays of Lorne
Greene, Anne Murray and Robert Goulet?
</P>
<P>
   But the Canadian invasion has shifted into hyperdrive in recent
years. Spearheaded by Celine Dion, Shania Twain, Bryan Adams and
other musical types, the list has expanded exponentially to include
a brave new crop of feisty Canucks, all eager to take over
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Television, in particular, has proved a potent breeding-ground
for northern lights. Here are 10 of the brightest. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   + Hayden Christensen.
</P>
<P>
   You may not know him yet, but just wait.
</P>
<P>
   Christensen, born in Vancouver and raised in Toronto, was until
recently best known for his role as hunky Scott Barringer on the
Fox Family Channel series ``Higher Ground.'' Nowadays, however,
he's best known as the future Anakin Skywalker.
</P>
<P>
   After his recent selection to follow Jake Lloyd as Anakin in the
next two episodes of George Lucas' ``Star Wars'' saga, the
19-year-old's acting career has done the same thing that Mark
Hamill's did when he jumped ship on ``Eight Is Enough'' in favor of
the original ``Star Wars'' in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire time I've been involved in the casting process _
for eight months _ actually being in the new `Star Wars' movie just
seemed so farfetched,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for an actor who, seven years ago, got his start on the
smarmy daytime soap ``Family Passions.''
</P>
<P>
   + Pamela Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's astute business sense, coupled with her memorable physique
and her questionable taste in men, has seen her skyrocket from
Playmate to ``Home Improvement's'' Tool Time girl to ``Baywatch''
babe and then into a hellacious sex-tape scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The story has a happy ending, however, as she's returned to the
small screen as star and executive producer of ``V.I.P.,'' one of
the world's most successful syndicated shows.
</P>
<P>
   + David James Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   After first coming to fame as Alison's sex-addicted rehab
boyfriend on ``Melrose Place,'' the Toronto-born Elliott nabbed the
starring role in ``JAG'' as Lt. Commander Harmon Rabb Jr. _
``Harm'' for short.
</P>
<P>
   After poor ratings got the show cancelled by NBC, ``JAG'' was
picked up by CBS, where it slowly but steadily built an audience,
becoming a genuine hit in its fourth year. Audiences warmed to its
combination of legal drama and military thrills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that about the show,'' Elliott says. ``It keeps it
interesting. But I think it hindered the show a little in the
beginning, because it was tough for people to put a finger on what
it was. That and getting over the prejudice of it being a military
show. People going, `Aaah, I don't like military shows,' when in
fact it's more than just that.''
</P>
<P>
   + Joshua Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   After Pamela Lee, Josh Jackson is probably the best-known
Canadian working in television at the moment. His portrayal of
Pacey, ``Dawson Creek's'' perpetual underdog, has cemented the
popularity that Jackson earned in the beloved ``Mighty Ducks'' film
series.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Jackson doesn't get too excited either by the
popularity of the show or by his own celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing it for three years,'' the Vancouver-born
Jackson says, ``and the initial blush of the show has worn off for
all of us. The crazy glow and the madness it had when it first came
out has died down, and now what makes the show most interesting, at
least for myself, is coming to work every day with actors I
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find it a challenge, to bring your best work to the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   + Carly Pope.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expected much when Carly Pope's series, ``Popular,''
debuted on WB last fall.
</P>
<P>
   My, how things change. What at first looked like merely another
generic WB teen-angst festival blossomed into the most demented,
yet also most morally adept, comic series on teen television.
</P>
<P>
   As Sam, the unpopular, politically aware half of the stepsister
duo that powers the series, the Vancouver-born Pope has seen her
popularity soar.
</P>
<P>
   Pope compares her character to ``a builder or a contractor. She
has all the right tools, but she doesn't know how to use them
properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite unlike Pope, who doesn't have that problem at all.
</P>
<P>
   + Ryan Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Reynolds' breakthrough series has survived so-so ratings
and the loss of half of its title. His genial sitcom, ``Two Guys
and a Girl'' _ nee ``Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza Place'' _ will
return to the ABC Friday-night lineup this fall, where fans of the
Vancouver native hope the show will find a new audience and
flourish in the friendlier time slot.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds had already had a measure of success in Canada when he
literally decided, on the spur of the moment, to drive south and
try his hand in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove down to Los Angeles,'' he says. ``Took several
attempts to get across the border, because I was just this ignorant
young Canadian thinking I could just cross and go to work!''
</P>
<P>
   + Scott Speedman.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ``Felicity'' scraped into a third season by the skin
of its teeth, look out for big things from Scott Speedman, the
Vancouver boy who plays Ben. He was handpicked to replace Brad Pitt
in the upcoming Gwyneth Paltrow vehicle ``Duets.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't look for him to move back to Vancouver anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a love/hate thing with Vancouver,'' Speedman says. ``I
was born in London, England, and I was just over there and it's
just rank and gets me down. Vancouver is a little slow for me, but
British Columbia is one of the most amazing places.''
</P>
<P>
   + Tonya Lee Williams.
</P>
<P>
   She may be young, but it's her background that suggests she's
restless: Born in England, Tonya Lee Williams lived in Jamaica,
then returned to England before making Oshawa her home.
</P>
<P>
   Since she took on the role of Dr. Olivia Hastings on ``The Young
and the Restless,'' Williams has entered the pantheon of soap-opera
stars ... and, again, relocated _ this time to Los Angeles with her
dog, Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   + Caroline Rhea.
</P>
<P>
   As Hilda Spellman on ``Sabrina, the Teenage Witch'' and as a
virtual fixture on ``Hollywood Squares,'' Caroline Rhea has come a
long way from the New York comedy clubs where she slaved for seven
years. This irresistibly ebullient Montreal girl, who still tours
her bawdy comedy routine in her spare time, jokes about her role as
the good witch's aunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she says, ``I hope I am more mature than her. She's
like 512 years old, and is always looking for something to do
because she's been there, done that.''
</P>
<P>
   + Eric McCormack.
</P>
<P>
   The irony that Eric McCormack's character is gay, yet plays the
``straight'' man to the series' trio of neurotic, high-maintenance
characters is not lost on him. In fact, the Torontonian sees it as
a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Will is gay and Grace is straight, this show is free
to explore their relationship without building toward a sexual
payoff at the end,'' he says. ``Our series has the spirit of a
classic romantic comedy, except there's no possibility that these
two people will end up as a romantic couple.''
</P>
<P>
   In real life McCormack is married, and he and his wife maintain
homes in Los Angeles and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kevin Dickson is a Los Angeles-based correspondent for TV
Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
