<SLUG> BC-MARK-WAHLBERG-IN-THE-PERFECT-STORM-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING WAVES: MARK WAHLBERG TACKLES `THE PERFECT STORM' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Mark Wahlberg with George Clooney in a
scene from ``The Perfect Storm.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Marky Mark doesn't live here any more.
 &HT;    Mark Wahlberg is an actor, not a rapper or an underwear model.
But his past won't stay buried.
 &HT;    On the set of his upcoming film ``The Yards,'' he was thrilled
to have Faye Dunaway say to him, ``Mark, my son is going to do what
you do.''
 &HT;    Wahlberg was all ready with acting tips when Dunaway continued:
``So, Mark, what goes on in that modeling world, anyway? Are there
a lot of drugs at the photo shoots?''
 &HT;    The young actor, who has garnered critical acclaim for ``Boogie
Nights'' (1997), ``Three Kings'' (1999) and ``The Perfect Storm,''
which will open June 30, sighed.
 &HT;    ``I said, `Hey, Faye, I did one underwear ad. I'm not a
model,''' he recalls. ``She said, `Yes, OK, Mark. But he wants to
be a model just like you, and I hope he doesn't get caught up in
the debauchery!'''
 &HT;    Wahlberg grimaces, then laughs. Clad in jeans and a T-shirt as
he reclines on a couch at New York's Essex House and devours a
bagel, he swears that his Calvin Klein days are behind him.
 &HT;    ``As far as going out, pulling down my pants and running around
in my underwear, I don't think I could do that anymore,'' he says
cheerfully. ``Maybe a 20-year anniversary _ I'll come out with my
beer belly and pull down my pants.''
 &HT;    He can joke now, of course, because he's earned solid Hollywood
credibility lately, most recently as a young fisherman pitted
against a killer North Atlantic gale in Wolfgang Petersen's ``The
Perfect Storm,'' based on the best-selling real-life saga by
Sebastian Junger.
 &HT;    Co-starring is George Clooney, who plays the fishing-boat
captain. Clooney and Wahlberg are becoming quite the screen duo _
they co-starred in ``Three Kings,'' and Clooney is producing
Wahlberg's next film, the rock-band saga ``Metal God,'' due later
this year.
 &HT;    ``For `The Perfect Storm,' George personally went to Wolfgang
Petersen and suggested that he give me an audition. He campaigned
for me,'' Wahlberg says. ``I just want to be the one to say that
George is much more than just good-looking _ he is one hell of a
guy.''
 &HT;    Don't expect them to be the new Redford and Newman, however.
 &HT;    ``No,'' Wahlberg jokes, ``it's kind of like he's Eddie Murphy
and I'm Judge Reinhold.''
 &HT;    To prepare for his role, Wahlberg _ who grew up in the Boston
suburbs _ went back East to hang out on fishing boats. He even took
a room above the Crow's Nest Bar in Gloucester, Mass., where the
fisherman he's playing actually hung out.
 &HT;    ``I also got to know my character's family,'' he adds, ``which
just provided invaluable insight, although it was tough for them to
talk about what happened.''
 &HT;    Many of the calmer water shots were done in real boats outside
Gloucester, where Wahlberg grumbles that the only real hazard was
the swarm of fans who trail Clooney everywhere.
 &HT;    ``Even the sea gulls were screaming, `George, we love you!'''
Wahlberg says sarcastically.
 &HT;    The storm scenes, on the other hand, were filmed on the Warner
Brothers lot, in a special hurricane tank which measured 95 feet by
100 feet by 22 feet deep.
 &HT;    It wasn't as dangerous as a real hurricane, the actor says, but
it was hardly less uncomfortable.
 &HT;    ``You get in the water, and they turn on the wind. The waves are
crashing,'' Wahlberg says. ``You really do feel like you're going
to die. It was just so tough getting through a day.''
 &HT;    Spending day after day soaked to the skin wasn't what he'd
expected after his performance as porn actor Dirk Diggler in
``Boogie Nights'' won him rave reviews and a reputation as a rising
star.
 &HT;    ``The good thing is that I have just been very busy,'' he says,
laughing. ``The bad thing is that people ask me about the size of
my private parts.''
 &HT;    He insists that his acting career is the real thing, however,
not merely the latest stop in a highly varied life.
 &HT;    ``I always wanted to act,'' he says. ``You know, I had been
bulls--ting and acting most of my life. It only made sense.''
 &HT;    In retrospect, he adds, the turning point came in 1985, when at
15 he was sentenced to 45 days in jail for assault after an
argument over a bottle of beer.
 &HT;    ``That experience was definitely a wake-up call,'' he says. ``It
sounds strange, but I also got very into Bruce Lee in prison. I was
into working out, because I had to stay in shape to protect myself.
When I got out, I'd go to the gym instead of hanging out on the
corner with my friends.
 &HT;    ``It saved my life,'' he says. ``I feel like I'm blessed. I
found myself on a path where so many had gone before me _ a lot of
my friends watched their lives go down the chute. I just decided I
wanted something better for myself. I wanted to live the good life,
I wanted to do the right thing for my family.''
 &HT;    Sibling rivalry gave him his first break. His brother Donnie had
become a teen-music sensation with New Kids on the Block, and
Wahlberg followed suit, achieving a 1991 platinum album with his
rap group, Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch. That led to his Calvin
Klein contract _ and, between the underwear and the rapping, to
frequent problems in launching the acting career he really wanted.
 &HT;    ``At first, acting was so tough,'' he says. ``I got offers like,
`Hey, Mark, why don't you be a rapping, skateboarding dude? Or play
the punk a--hole for us?' I didn't want to be identified as that
type of guy, so I turned down a lot of offers.''
 &HT;    He finally got his acting break in ``Renaissance Man'' (1994),
which led to ``The Basketball Diaries'' (1995), ``Fear'' (1996) and
then ``Boogie Nights'' (1997). Then came stardom, and a whole new
set of issues.
 &HT;    ``It still kills me when I read stuff about myself,'' Wahlberg
admits. ``For instance, I heard someone say me talking about having
a troubled past was just something I did to boost my bio and give
me credibility.
 &HT;    ``Believe it, I was not trying to brag about it,'' he says.
``I'm not proud of my past. I don't think I need it to be
credible.''
 &HT;    The actor sighs.
 &HT;    ``I think I've been misunderstood all the way around,'' he says.
``I thought acting was the one thing that would make it difficult
for people to figure out who I was, because I could slip into
character.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, he has had to deal with persistent rumors of an
affair with Jennifer Aniston, his co-star in ``Metal God.'' He and
Aniston have both firmly denied the rumors, but that doesn't matter
once the tabloids are in gear.
 &HT;    ``My mom believes everything she reads,'' he says, wincing.
``She calls me up and says, `Jennifer is dating that nice Brad
Pitt, and you leave that boy's girl alone, Mark!'''
 &HT;    Wahlberg throws his hands up in the air, then laughs.
 &HT;    ``Maybe my life was easier when I was just dropping trou!''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
