<HEADLINE>
A REBEL STILL RUNNING: PATTI SMITH ISN'T GIVING UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer/songwriter Patti Smith.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    She's been called a punk priestess, a rock-'n'-roll poet
laureate and one of many voices of a generation.
 &HT;    She rejects the most fawning of those titles, but Patti Smith is
happy to be called an artist _ and no word fits her better. Whether
through poetry, visual works or, most frequently, music _ including
her latest album, ``Gung Ho'' _ Smith has spoken with a
particularly strong conscience and sensibility.
 &HT;    During the 1970s she declared that ``Outside of society/is where
I want to be,'' but Smith actually revels in community and
champions the power of the collective spirit. The singer/songwriter
takes seriously the message conveyed by her 1988 hit, ``People Have
the Power,'' and never more than this year, when America is in the
midst of a presidential campaign.
 &HT;    ``I was listening to the State of the Union address,'' Smith
recalls. ``Clinton was saying `Everything's fine, it's fine, we're
fine,' and I was thinking, `No, we're not fine.'
 &HT;    ``Our children are shooting each other,'' she says passionately.
``We're becoming a totally materialistic society, our environment
is compromised. There's so many reasons why we're not fine.
 &HT;    ``Maybe economically things are good,'' she concedes, ``but that
doesn't make good people. That doesn't make a good country, that
doesn't make the moral fabric of the country good. There're too
many things happening that point to a spiritual lack and a lack of
unity and a lack of clarity in our country.''
 &HT;    The 53-year-old Smith, a Chicago native who was raised in New
Jersey and now resides in New York with Jackson and Jesse, her son
and daughter, has been spurred by her sense of the country's drift
to launch her most extensive American tour since the 1970s.
 &HT;    Back then, her Patti Smith Group _ blending classic-rock
conventions with the irreverent spirit of the punk and new wave
movements _ played some of the era's most visceral and challenging
music. She hopes to provoke people again this year, using the songs
from ``Gung Ho'' as a catalyst for thought and ideas.
 &HT;    ``I think that is very American,'' says Smith, a longtime
Democrat who supported Bill Bradley but also sings on the album
about the need for a ``New Party.'' ``It addresses global issues,
but I feel like it's got specifically the things that I'm concerned
with, especially in an election year, that our country has to
address _ things like gun control, some kind of education reform
and political-money reform ... and, most important, the
environment.
 &HT;    ``There're a lot of things I'm concerned about,'' she concludes,
``and I want to stick around America and use my voice as much as I
can and support the Democratic Party.''
 &HT;    Smith's return to the political arena follows a period of
introspection brought on by the death of her husband, former MC5
guitarist Fred ``Sonic'' Smith, of heart failure during 1993. Her
brother, Todd, died of a heart attack the following year, and
Smith's next two releases _ ``Gone Again'' (1996), only her second
album in 17 years, and ``Peace and Noise'' (1997) _ were dark
affairs, ruminating on her sense of personal loss.
 &HT;    ``Gung Ho,'' on the other hand, returns to the bold, punchy
energy of her earlier work.
 &HT;    ``I just had a few difficult, really difficult years, and I had
to rebuild my energy, rebuild my confidence and reacquaint myself
with performing and recording and collaborating with others,''
Smith explains. ``I had help _ Alan Ginsberg, Bob Dylan, Michael
Stipe, the members of my band and friends. It was rewarding, but it
was difficult. And it did take awhile.''
 &HT;    ``Gung Ho'' features a variety of guests, including R.E.M.
singer Stipe, Tom Verlaine of the group Television, former Husker
Du member Grant Hart and harmonica player Skaila Kanga. Smith's son
Jackson also plays guitar on the track ``Persuasion,'' which was
co-written by his parents.
 &HT;    But at the core of ``Gung Ho'' is Smith's group, which includes
longtime associates Lenny Kaye on guitar and Jay Dee Daugherty on
drums, with bassist Tony Shanahan and guitarist Oliver Ray, who's
also Smith's current boyfriend.
 &HT;    ``I think that we fortify each other,'' Smith says of the group.
``I did `Peace and Noise' with the same people, and we did that
record ourselves, with no producer _ we just forged through that
one. This one is really a result of all our efforts through the
last record, and touring and collaborating.
 &HT;    ``I think we've found our place,'' she says. ``The musicians
bring in music, and I respond to some of it and they become the
songs. It was just, I guess, the collective spirit of the band. I
think we all stay in step.''
 &HT;    ``Gung Ho'' is a Chinese term that means ``working together,''
which Smith felt made it an appropriate title for the album. But
the title song itself _ a nearly 12-minute epic that closes the
album _ was inspired by her research into Ho Chi Minh, which she
began after seeing a documentary about the Vietnamese leader.
 &HT;    ``I spent two years studying his work, studying his life,
studying how he mapped out independence for the Vietnamese
people,'' Smith says. ``And in doing so, I found out he used our
Declaration of Independence as a guide and our Revolutionary War as
a guide, and I found that very interesting. It also moved me to
study the Declaration of Independence.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to write a song about his life,'' she adds, ``because
I have always opposed the Vietnam War, but I never understood it. I
suppose it was an opportunity for me to comprehend what the whole
thing was about, and so I did.
 &HT;    ``I was impressed with his knowledge of the history of our
country and the history of our freedom,'' the musician says. ``And
now, more than ever, I know that war was wrong.''
 &HT;    Since ``Gung Ho's'' release, Smith has also declared her own
independence. She bolted from Arista Records, her home since 1975,
to protest the ouster of Arista founder Clive Davis, whom she
inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame earlier this year.
 &HT;    ``He gave me the freedom to record as I see fit and artistic
control of what I do,'' Smith says. ``That means a lot to me.''
 &HT;    She may for the moment be one of rock 'n' roll's homeless, but
Smith says that she looks forward to a lot more music to come.
 &HT;    ``I really feel like I'm coming from a position of strength, of
health, of energy,'' says Smith, who's also working on a book about
her relationship with the late artist Robert Mapplethorpe. ``After
`Gone Again,' I really thought that would be my last record. But so
many people really encouraged me to go on. And people, when I would
perform, they seemed happy to see me.
 &HT;    ``So as long as I can do something of worth, as long as I can
contribute things that I think are of good quality, I'll continue
performing and I'll continue making records,'' she concludes. ``And
when I think I can't contribute anymore, I'll move on to something
else.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Gung Ho,'' consult the
