<HEADLINE>
ALMOST SKY DIVING _ WITHOUT JUMPING FROM A PLANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos of the X-Treme wind machine and of a
``sky-diving'' Blair Green _ one of the professionals who help
amateurs use it _ are available by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.)
 By CLIFF GROMER 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sky diving is not an extreme sport except for folks too timid to
try it. Compared to the current wave of recreational mayhem that
pushes the envelope of sanity, and mental and physical endurance _
stuff you could experience a decade or so ago only in the circus _
sky diving is downright tame. Nondivers love to repeat the tired
excuse about how it doesn't make sense to jump out of a perfectly
good airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Sky divers make up a private club. They're the only ones who
know the incomparable sensation of truly flying _ swooshing through
the air without the benefit of any mechanical device save a
descent-slowing parachute. Thermals and arm-flapping
notwithstanding, a sky diver's route of flight is irreversibly in
one direction: down.
</P>
<P>
   But during free fall, before the chute is pulled, a diver's body
acts as an airfoil of sorts, through the subtle movements of hands,
feet and posture. Sure, plummeting humans might be a source of
amusement to passing birds, but it's flying nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Sky diving, however, requires substantial training and equipment
_ and a perfectly good airplane to jump out of. An alternative that
closely duplicates the sensation of flying is the sky-diving
simulator, a mobile vertical wind tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be confused with those ``Honey, I Cut The Elevator
Cables'' amusement rides, the sky-diving simulator supports your
body on a cushion of air. You can rise, descend, turn and _ for the
advanced _ perform somersaults, headstands, dives and other
assorted aerobatics.
</P>
<P>
   The simulator consists of a 1200-horsepower Detroit Diesel
engine hooked to a DC-3 propeller facing upward that generates wind
speeds up to 150 mph needed for the supportive air cushion. Air
speed is variable depending on the weight of the flyer. The whole
shebang is mounted on a huge trailer that's hauled by a commercial
truck.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one such device in the world at this time, the
3-year-old X-Treme Air owned and operated by Paradigm Entertainment
Group in Grand Rapids, Mich. X-Treme Air travels from coast to
coast and is booked by colleges that want to shake up their
students. Corporations also hire the flying machine to wake up
three-martini-lunched executives and to experience something that
blows even more air than their PR department (if such a thing could
be possible).
</P>
<P>
   X-Treme Air was recently at Teikyo Post College in Waterbury,
Conn., about a 90-minute drive from Manhattan, but surprisingly,
the line of students waiting to sign up for the ride was short. The
flyers, myself included, were divided into groups of six for a
10-minute orientation with one of the three pro flyers who
accompany the X-Treme Air machine on its cross-country trek.
</P>
<P>
   Students, including males, were told to remove jewelry and
piercings (boy, things have changed since I went to school). One
girl neglected to remove her tongue ring and the wind pressure
caused pain. Any loose stuff could drop into the spinning prop
where it would then shoot up and through you like shrapnel.
Participants donned helmets, goggles and special flying suits that
had handles for the pros to grab and control them.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside the machine we sat around the perimeter of the wind
tunnel on a giant air-filled doughnut. Then the pros put on an
impressive demonstration of trick flying, shooting up 25 feet in
the wind stream, somersaulting and diving headfirst. Now there's an
idea for an extreme sport _ diving into a spinning DC-3 prop.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to fly, each of us rose into a kneeling
position and leaned toward the center. ``Don't push yourself off,''
we were warned, ``or you'll shoot across and torpedo the student on
the opposite side.''
</P>
<P>
   We were also told to keep our hands out and not wave to friends
or we would flip. ``Keep your feet straight out behind you and
don't flail them or you'll spin, and arch your back slightly, sort
of like a human banana.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of us leaned out and the two pros standing on opposite ends
of the doughnut grabbed us by the suit's handles. They are really
experts at what they do, having flown some 50,000 people with no
fatalities or injuries. They guided us up and down and, when the
prop rpm increased, jumped into the wind stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would happen if you didn't hold us?'' asked one student.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd fly out over the top and land on the pavement about 50
feet away,'' came the answer.
</P>
<P>
   The experience itself was exhilarating and a real adrenaline
rush. The wind pressure turns your face to rubber. Your lips
vibrate in the breeze. But you actually do feel like you're flying
and don't even notice the handlers who are controlling you.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-minute ride seems a lot longer, but it's still over too
soon. And you want more. Much more. It's enough to make you look
around for a perfectly good airplane to jump out of.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact Paradigm Entertainment Group at
616-365-1074.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
