<SLUG> BC-MP3-NAPSTER-COLUMN-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAPSTER'S DESTRUCTIVE MUSIC DOWNLOADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A graphic illustration of a pirate Web surfer opening a
treasure chest labeled Napster is available by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 By TOBEY GRUMET 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am not an old lady. Honestly I'm not.
</P>
<P>
   But sadly, with Gen Y being raised on computers and the
Internet, I tend to feel left out of the loop when I consider
what's going on behind the average college kid's door.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to believe what's going on out there,'' a
friend recently said to me. He'd just returned from a college
reunion at Cornell, and while there he was startled by the rampant
use of something called Napster at college parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't one CD player in use at the party,'' he said.
``All the music was being run off computers, playlists and an
amplifier. In fact, during a meeting at my fraternity, they decided
to scrap getting a new stereo. They were just going to keep the
amp, and buy a new computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever hear of Napster? If not, let me clue you in. Napster is a
computer software _ now a startup dot.com company _ invented by a
19-year-old who just wanted to share some of his guitar samplings
with his online buddies.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds innocent enough, but that teen-ager's bright idea has led
to a heap of legal questions. Napster also allows you to find,
share and download hundreds of thousands of MP3 music files to your
computer, MP3 player or CD Recordable-for free. This music is
digital and, unlike the old days of waiting for your favorite song
to come on the radio so you could tape it, downloading music files
is practically instantaneous. Once you've downloaded the software,
you do a quick search for the music you want, and start pirating.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Napster turns your computer into a server. So let's
say you want to find Bruce Springsteen's ``Born In The USA.'' You
press Search, type in the title and/or artist and hit Return.
Within nanoseconds you're given a list of all the people who have
Napster software, are on their computers at that moment, and have
``Born In The USA'' on their playlist.
</P>
<P>
   You can choose which person you'd like to take the song from,
depending on how fast their modem is or whether they have a cable
or T1 line. The software downloads the song to your own playlist _
and voila!, you're set to rock on.
</P>
<P>
   I'll admit, it's hard to hate this program. The thought of
downloading almost any song I want in minutes is certainly
tempting. And it brings back all kinds of ``down with the system''
feelings I had at one time. But, the adult in me knows this isn't
great for the people who wrote the song, sell the song and perform
the song.
</P>
<P>
   I realize this makes it harder for struggling bands to retain
contracts, and I know it makes the creative contingent wonder what
they're working for. If I ever get around to writing that great
American novel (that is, when I get around to it), I'm not going to
want people enjoying my work for free. I'd feel cheated, and since
I'm already a poor writer, not getting royalties would be a drag.
Oh no _ am I becoming the establishment I once rejected?
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America is not amused. In
December, the organization sued Napster for contributory copyright
infringement. That means Napster may not literally hand over
pirated material to computer users _ but the makers of the program
aren't doing anything to prevent this.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, performers and musicians aren't happy either. Heavy
metal group Metallica has filed a suit against Napster and,
according to Industry Standard magazine, rapper Dr. Dre has said he
wants all his copyrighted songs off the software.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that is helping slow down the Napster rage is its
incessant gobbling of bandwidth on college campuses. Basically,
when you download Napster software, your computer becomes a server,
and servers consume a ton of bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, schools including Yale, the University of Southern
California and Indiana University have banned students from using
Napster _ though if you think that's going to stop people from
getting free music on the Internet, I've got a great bridge to sell
you here in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, there will have to be some regulations put into
place. As the online generation matures, how people access music
will continue to change, and lawmakers will have to do something
about it.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
