<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8317 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPM     06-19 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHWATCH-BRIEFS-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: A graphic illustration of space vehicle, a photo of a
star field in the Orion nebula, a photo of an underwater electronic
``nose'' and photo of wood bridge are available by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKET INHALES ITS WAY INTO ORBIT
</P>
<P>
   NASA believes a new type of propulsion system will make it
cheaper to fly to the international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Known as a combined-cycle rocket engine, it inhales oxygen from
the atmosphere for about half of its flight. Conventional rockets
use oxygen stored on board. In both cases the gas supports fuel
combustion. Using an external oxygen supply will lower a vehicle's
launch weight. At $10,000 a pound to reach orbit, this
substantially reduces launch costs.
</P>
<P>
   The latest tests at the Marshall Space Flight Center in
Huntsville, Ala., demonstrated what engine performance would be
like during low-speed flight, when high thrust levels are needed to
push the rocket through Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-FLOATING PLANETS
</P>
<P>
   Images captured by UKIRT, the United Kingdom Infrared Telescope
in Hawaii, contradict the prevailing wisdom that planets must orbit
stars. The most sensitive survey ever undertaken of the region in
the Orion nebula where new stars are forming has revealed 13
``free-floating planets,'' says Philip Lucas, the University of
Hertfordshire astronomer who analyzed the images.
</P>
<P>
   About the size of Jupiter in our own solar system, each
free-floater has too little mass to ignite and become a star, or
even a so-called ``brown dwarf.'' Rather than orbit a star, they
drift through space alone.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, only two similar objects had been discovered, both in
the southern Chamaeleon nebula. The discovery of 13 in one cluster
suggests to astronomers that free-floating planets might be common.
</P>
<P>
   AQUATIC NOSE CAN SNIFF SCENT OF LIFE
</P>
<P>
   An electronic nose that can work at the intense pressures found
more than a mile beneath the sea is helping biologists locate
exotic forms of deep sea life.
</P>
<P>
   Created at the University of Delaware and Analytical Instrument
Systems in Flemington, N.J., the sensor can detect the sulfur-rich
compounds found in gases that spew from underwater vents. These
vents have drawn the attention of marine biologists because the
vents attract many exotic species of life.
</P>
<P>
   These species, because of their distance from the surface, can
obtain their energy only from locally available chemicals, instead
of sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time a system like this has been built to
operate at such great depths and pressures,'' chemist George Luther
told a meeting of the American Chemical Society. Some of these vent
dwellers may possess enzymes useful in processing food and drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   21ST CENTURY WOOD BRIDGE
</P>
<P>
   Call it a step backward for progress. A steel span over the
Maronne River in France has been torn down to make way for a wood
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem a bit backward, but the new 189-foot bridge is
actually wider and stronger than the older steel structure.
</P>
<P>
   Wood was not the engineers' first choice. Local residents
insisted upon it to match the scenery, which includes the remains
of a 13th-century castle. ``We hose Douglas fir because of its good
mechanical properties and its performance in terms of natural
durability,'' says engineer Jean-Louis Michotey. The wood was
laminated and arranged into three spans joined by hinges. In a
concession to modern times, the deck is reinforced concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Although France may have the newest wood bridge, the longest, at
328 feet, is in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   CANCER KILLERS FROM THE DEEP
</P>
<P>
   Sponges, marine worms and other creatures of the deep may
provide a new arsenal in the war on cancer, say Stanford University
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm follows studies that show that bryostatin, a
chemical compound produced by Bugula neritina, a tiny, plantlike
animal found off the California coast, has powerful cancer-fighting
abilities. It appears to prevent the growth of tumors in a variety
of human cancers, including melanoma, non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and
renal cancer, Paul A. Wender of Stanford told a recent meeting of
the American Chemical Society.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 clinical trials aimed at evaluating bryostatin are
currently under way in the United States. Preliminary findings show
cancer patients improve while suffering only minor side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it takes 14 tons of B. neritina to produce less
than 1 ounce of bryostatin. Not surprisingly, bryozoan farms have
begun to sprout up in California.
</P>
<P>
   Wender predicted that the ocean, and coral reefs that support a
broad array of marine life, will be a rich source of other
disease-fighting agents.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
