<HEADER>
A8320 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-19 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM'S CLOCK HAS RUN OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If all goes well this week, Gary Graham will finally get what he
deserves: a lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   This coldblooded killer's worthless life is scheduled to end on
Thursday _ he's had eight execution dates, according to one news
report _ despite much protest, not to mention weeping and gnashing,
by the Gary Graham fan club. Led by bleeding-heart actor Danny
Glover and like-minded death penalty foes from Hollywood and
elsewhere, the save-Graham forces are trying to exploit recent
controversy about capital punishment in a desperate attempt to
rescue Graham from the death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for society and the cause of justice, Graham may
have dodged the executioner for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's case provides a textbook example of the virtually
endless appellate process that keeps convicted killers on Death Row
for 10, 15 and 20 years. These misguided death penalty opponents
are constantly screaming that lowlifes like Graham are shortchanged
by the justice system _ but Graham's case has been reviewed dozens
of times since he was convicted of the 1981 murder of 53-year-old
Bobby Lambert in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Graham has pursued every goofy appeal that his lawyers could
devise; all have been rejected by the courts. After nearly two
decades of stalling, Graham and his partisans are reduced to
arguing that it is unreasonable to execute a killer whose
conviction was based on the testimony of an eyewitness to the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   The implications here are mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   If the testimony of a sure and certain eyewitness _ the witness
in Graham's case was, and is, as sure and certain as you will find
_ is useless in a murder trial, how many past and future killers
must go unpunished?
</P>
<P>
   Graham gunned down an innocent bystander in a supermarket
parking lot. He left behind none of that precious DNA, the new
be-all and end-all of the criminal justice system. But a
schoolteacher named Bernadine Skillern saw Graham shoot Lambert.
She identified him for police. She never wavered while testifying
in Graham's murder trial, and she has never wavered since.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Skillern has been ostracized, harassed and
threatened _ but she has not yielded to the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Mr. Graham shoot and kill Mr. Lambert on that parking
lot in 1981,'' Skillern said at a news conference last week. ``That
has not changed. It's not going to change. I saw him shoot and kill
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Skillern said she met with the media ``because the public was
being misinformed regarding the Graham execution.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press quoted her:
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw his face three or four different times from angles, then
full-face ... I saw him full-face as he was crossing the drive. My
lights were on him in the car ... I'm very sure. There has never
been a doubt in my mind. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are those who question the accuracy of eyewitness
testimony, and there have been verified examples of
misidentification by such witnesses. But credible eyewitness
testimony has always been _ and will continue to be _ a cornerstone
of the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   The jury believed Bernadine Skillern. The jury believed beyond a
reasonable doubt that Gary Graham killed Bobby Lambert. That's how
the system works.
</P>
<P>
   Graham has had practically 20 years to prove that Skillern and
the jury were wrong. He hasn't even come close. The clock has run
out.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General John Cornyn pointed out last week that
Lambert's murder was part of a weeklong crime spree that involved
at least 13 victims.
</P>
<P>
   The AP quoted Cornyn:
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Graham is not the innocent victim in this case; he is the
convicted murderer. For 19 years, Graham's victims and their
families have had to live with the consequences of his crimes. It
is now time for them to have the closure and the justice our system
provides.''
</P>
<P>
   This case has dragged on too long. Justice has been delayed too
long.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, finally, needs to keep his appointment with the
executioner. Danny Glover needs to shut up and make a movie.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
