<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8326 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     06-19 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GENTLEMEN,' START YOUR ANTICS ON COMEDY CENTRAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fact that absolutely nothing in the Comedy Central series
``The League of Gentlemen'' is familiar _ not the stars, not the
jokes, and certainly not the peculiar town in which it is set _
actually helps to make the show fresh and fascinating, if not
exactly rip-roaring funny.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning a 14-episode run on Monday, it features the British
comedy team of Steve Pemberton, Mark Gatiss and Reece Shearsmith,
an obviously talented trio of performers who pull off the
remarkable feat of portraying more than 60 men and women
characters, young and old, fat and thin, living in a bizarre small
town in northern England. They include, among other oddballs, a
psychotic couple running the local store (who murder people), a
blind photographer, a vet who kills more animals than he saves, and
a man who raises, and constantly talks about, toads.
</P>
<P>
   The humor _ often dark, sexually crude and strikingly unusual _
recalls such famous British comedies as ``Kind Hearts and
Coronets'' and ``Lady Killers,'' although, on second thought,
American viewers who find PBS a bore probably wouldn't know much
about those.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say, then, that ``The League of Gentlemen'' features the
kind of bizarre scenarios and rampant absurdity rarely seen on
American television unless ``Monty Python'' is your cup of tea or
the other Comedy Central import, ``Absolutely Fabulous,'' about a
pair of boozing, carefree women, made you chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that ``The League of Gentlemen'' made it outside
northern Britain, let alone onto American television, has come as
something of a shock to the show's creators, who wonder,
rightfully, whether its humor is too geographically and culturally
specific.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bit jolting for anywhere outside some public TV markets
and certainly for Comedy Central, which, beginning with Benny Hill
during the channel's early years, has over time schooled its
audience in the British sensibility of eliciting laughs. The Brits
live well in the context of Comedy Central, which continues to
solidify its identity as a cable channel unafraid to take risks,
even when it attracts bad (which often means good) press in the
form of shows like ``South Park'' and its seemingly endless scenes
involving bodily functions, and personalities along the lines of
Craig Kilborn, whose sarcastic, smirky nature was a good fit.
</P>
<P>
   How much its risk-taking has paid off probably depends on how
one looks at cable success at a time when luring a half a million
viewers to an episode is something of an achievement.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, ``South Park'' drew the channel's best ratings,
about 500,000 viewers, but even that was minuscule compared to
network programming shows like the canceled ``Safe Harbor,'' a
lifeless drama that had more than triple the number of viewers. In
general, Comedy Central programming draws less than half as many
viewers as leading cable channels like TNT and USA. Another problem
has been, of course, holding onto talent once they become stars.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Maher took his nightly ``Politically Incorrect'' series to
ABC, and Kilborn, who chaired ``The Daily Show,'' followed a
similar path to CBS. And the comedy channel's talent drain doesn't
include its behind-the-scenes losses, like its prized writers who
are steadily beating paths to sitcomland on the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Just when one of its programming chiefs, Doug Herzog, was touted
as a future savior, he bolted for greener pastures at Fox, although
the greenery turned out to include hidden land mines. (He has since
been replaced.)
</P>
<P>
   This is a big week for Comedy Central, which begins to sprinkle
original programming over five nights with series that are much
like ``The League of Gentlemen'' _ hit-or-miss propositions that
may or may not be around this time next season.
</P>
<P>
   Also being introduced is ``Strip Mall,'' which stars Julie Brown
as a former child star who lives in the San Fernando Valley and is
married to a nerdy owner of a dry-cleaning facility at the Rancho
del Toro. The joke is that it's a strip mall full of sex, greed and
sin.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is simultaneously cornball and silly. The dialogue
is lame, and even Brown's exaggerated mannerisms do little to
salvage what's in the script. That began Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't Forget Your Toothbrush,'' beginning Tuesday, is a goofy
game show that originated in England but has been revamped for
American audiences. It's said to be a game show, but it's more of a
series of sketch comedy routines, in which people from the audience
are picked to be involved in the sketches and can win items.
</P>
<P>
   The people in the studio audience show up with their luggage in
anticipation of winning vacations said to be either nice or trashy.
(Scotland was the prize in the preview I saw.) Comedian Mark Curry,
last seen in the sitcom ``Hangin' With Mr. Cooper,'' is the host,
and it's clear that he's been out of work for some time.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot, he persuades a woman to destroy her beloved
stuffed animal for $1,000. In another, much funnier sketch, a woman
is blindfolded and asked to guess what four men have under their
kilts.
</P>
<P>
   The series joins second-season shows ``The Man Show,'' which has
the distinction of being on more critics' worst lists than any
other show, and ``Turn Ben Stein On,'' as well as new episodes of
``South Park'' and the British version of ``Whose Line Is It
Anyway?'' (The American series is a ratings success on ABC.)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike UPN, Comedy Central has sidestepped the scolding that
comes with offering humor that's considered juvenile and
frat-boyish, unless you count the outcry a few seasons back over
``South Park'' and its conspiracy to corrupt minors. Comedy Central
remains the channel of choice for college-aged men, and I'd be
surprised if ``The League of Gentlemen'' didn't rally guys around
the tube much the way ``Sex and the City'' lures women.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the programming remains mean-spirited, although Comedy
Central prefers the terms ``smart'' and ``innovative.'' Or, better
yet, ``edgy.''
</P>
<P>
   The channel has certainly come a ways since being formed in 1991
as a result of the merging of HBO's Comedy Central and MTV's Ha!
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   It initially relied heavily on television stand-up routines, but
by the early '90s most viewers had grown weary of watching mediocre
comics in front of brick walls. The channel lacked resources to
produce high-quality sitcoms, so it merely bought them from
somewhere else, airing reruns of ``Saturday Night Live,''
``McHale's Navy'' and ``The Benny Hill Show,'' among others.
</P>
<P>
   Its back against the wall, this forced Comedy Central to be
inventive and daring, although I'd call it desperate.
</P>
<P>
   One of the early successes was ``Mystery Science Theater 3000,''
an amusing program in which characters sat in front of a film
screen and ridiculed bad movies.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Comedy Central saw a glimpse of its audience and has
since zeroed in on a far more narrow view of comedy than its name
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   As befits a channel that prizes absurdity as comedy, Comedy
Central is lucky to have ``The Daily Show,'' which remains one of
the more witty _ and even in Comedy Central tradition, cynical _
contributions to TV's comedic landscape.
</P>
<P>
   At least there, your brain doesn't have to collapse in order to
enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
