<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-WEATHER-PERSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR WOMEN, THE FORECAST ISN'T SO HOT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EILEEN MITCHELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN RAMON, Calif. _ What's your beef?
</P>
<P>
   You have one, don't you? Everyone else does. Like the writer of
a recent letter to the editor.
</P>
<P>
   He griped about meteorologists who often preface weather reports
with, ``Here's good news: It will be cooler tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me and many other Hispanics, good news is warm, even hot
weather,'' the writer complained. ``Yet so far as I know, there has
never been a Hispanic weather analyst in the Bay Area.''
</P>
<P>
   I know what he means. I have similar thoughts whenever I watch
Spencer Christian, the weatherman on Channel 7 in San Francisco. Oh
sure, he talks intelligently about pressure highs and lows, and
advises whether I should wear a sweater if I visit San Francisco
that weekend, but what does he know, really? He's a black male. I'm
a white female. HELLO? What about MY people?
</P>
<P>
   The weather report would mean so much more to me if it were
delivered by a woman who was 50 percent Irish, 25 percent Colombian
and 25 percent French. She would also be around my age, early 40s,
since hormonal fluctuations could drastically impact what
temperature is deemed as ``too cool'' or ``too warm.'' One good
estrogen power surge could easily transform ``too warm'' into
anything over 58 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   I would prefer a female meteorologist with curly hair because
she would understand the effect that weather has on curly-haired
women.
</P>
<P>
   How many times has NBC weatherman Willard Scott flippantly
predicted ``mild precipitation''? Mild? To a bald guy, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle to a curly-haired woman is the beauty equivalent of the
Exxon Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask any middle-aged, European/South American, curly haired,
pre-menopausal female. If there were a meteorologist who understood
our needs and recognized the concerns of my people, we would be
better emotionally equipped to face a damp day in which we all
resemble Carrot Top.
</P>
<P>
   I want a SAD meteorologist. I suffer from Seasonal Affective
Disorder, and a meteorologist who also gets depressed when the days
are short and it's gray and overcast would sympathize with the
gloomy effect that bad weather has on people like me.
</P>
<P>
   She wouldn't cheerily predict howling winds and icy rain as ``a
cozy day to stay indoors and snuggle near a fireplace with a good
book.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that supposed to sound appealing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hide the knives,'' she would warn instead. ``Refill that
Prozac prescription and stock up on tissues. Go out and get
yourself a couple of men. Ben &AMP; Jerry come to mind, because
sisters, hear me when I tell you, we are in for one dreary spell.''
Amen.
</P>
<P>
   I need a middle-aged, European/South American, curly-haired,
pre-menopausal weather analyst who understands the chafing of heat
rash, the sorrow of sweat stains and the anguish of the frizzy
blues. Someone who sleeps with an electric blanket in the summer,
complains about the heat in the winter and on more than one
occasion has mistaken her sun block for hair conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   Move over, weatherman. I don't mean to rain on your parade, but
a gale force is blowing into town and she's going to call the
weather the way it really is _ frizzy and depressing. So tell me:
</P>
<P>
   Where do I apply?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
