r k BC-INDONESIA-HNS &LR;      06-19 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TREAT INDONESIA WITH RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AL HIRSHEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Indonesia offers a kaleidoscope of cultures
and landscapes. It is an anthropologist's heaven. It is a dream for
any naturalist.
</P>
<P>
   This is true on any of 13,000-plus islands that make up the
archipelago that stretches almost 3,100 miles from the Asian
mainland into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But I've been intrigued by something else during the almost two
years I have lived in Jakarta and worked in Indonesia (in corporate
debt restructuring, investment and corporate governance).
</P>
<P>
   What fascinates me are glaring contradictions, either apparent
or real, of the Indonesian psyche (or at least the people on the
island of Java, which has 60 percent of the population and most of
the powerful politicians).
</P>
<P>
   For many foreigners living here, these contradictions try or
even break their patience. They can't get past Indonesia's negative
ways. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ The society is permeated by the long history and tolerance of
corruption at every level.
</P>
<P>
   _ Business and government are conducted on a very hierarchical
base. The wish of the boss determines all. No action is taken
without his or her direction. He or she is waited on as if a great
potentate. This system stifles initiative and breeds fear.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many Javanese tend to lack directness in dealing with others
and rarely show emotion. And yet, and I generalize, many are quick
to feel insulted, to act on rumors and, in some cases, to run amok
(an Indonesian word).
</P>
<P>
   Let me give an example:
</P>
<P>
   My driver and I came upon a street fight between students at
different schools, a common occurrence here. The kids appeared to
be no older than 13 or 15. In a matter of minutes, rocks as big as
grapefruits were being thrown. One hit our car.
</P>
<P>
   As we hastily left, people were running toward the fight with
sword-like metal bars. When I asked what the fight was about, I was
told: ``It just is what the school kids have always done.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are episodes like this one:
</P>
<P>
   When four local university professors were approached to write
questions for a proposed quiz show, they thanked the producer for
the opportunity, and for the chance to sell the answers.
</P>
<P>
   I do not profess to love the pollution of Jakarta, the
corruption, the mistreatment of the ethnic Chinese minority or the
violence that erupts among religious or ethnic factions. But there
are many positive sides to Indonesian society. These are things we
can only hope will reappear in America:
</P>
<P>
   _ Simple good manners and civility.
</P>
<P>
   _ Respect for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   _ An awareness of the importance of and respect for family and
community.
</P>
<P>
   _ Religious and ethnic tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   _ The importance of character and personality, not competence or
status.
</P>
<P>
   _ The avoidance of saying no. (In order to be civil and polite,
Indonesians often soften their responses to ``not yet'' or ``maybe
later.'')
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurraham Wahid's first act after his election was to
go to the grave of his parents to show respect and give thanks for
what they had done for him. It is a Javanese duty to drop
everything and visit the hospital or attend the funeral of, not
only family and friends, but colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cursing or road rage on the streets and highways.
</P>
<P>
   Once you are accepted as part of their ``family,'' the sweet and
hospitable character of the Indonesian is evident. The poker face
gives way to a great sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Age is considered a plus in this society. Indonesians value the
opinion and wisdom of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   In Yogyakarta, a 28-year-old man who worked for me and was a
former anti-Suharto student leader asked me to visit his
father-in-law (a former head of the university the young man
attended and an ardent Suharto supporter at that time).
</P>
<P>
   His father-in-law had suffered a stroke. The young man felt that
because of my age (61) and perceived status as a Western
businessman, my visit to the hospital would give the man
encouragement and his wife support. The thoughtfulness of the young
man and the experience moved me deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again I have attended functions that reaffirm the
importance and support of family and community. And it's
interesting that to my hosts, the care and feeding of my driver is
of equal importance to my own.
</P>
<P>
   I think my experience can be helpful to U.S. policymakers in
their approach to Indonesia. It is the most populous Muslim
country, a fledgling democracy with great promise.
</P>
<P>
   The government is attacking the problems of corruption,
including its court system. Rule of law is an important goal of
this new democracy. Indonesia's geographical location gives it
great strategic importance, and its wealth in oil, gas, minerals is
vital to the West.
</P>
<P>
   We should always keep in mind the psychological effect on its
people of the country's colonial past, treat its government and
people with patience and respect _ and keep a touch of humility.
</P>
<P>
   Arrogance, perceived or real, will undermine our goals to
support a democratic country friendly to America.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Al Hirshen is a director of Ernst &AMP; Young in Jakarta and an
international consultant.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 1251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
