r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-19 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE LAST ANNIVERSARY IN A CAREER MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In June of 1975, when I took a job as a sports
writer at the San Francisco Examiner, I would have been amazed (and
appalled) had anyone told me I'd still be here when the 24th
anniversary of my hire date rolled around.
</P>
<P>
   Never a woman with a personal or professional grand plan, I
didn't think about how long I might stay at the Examiner. I was 26,
only nine months separated from New York City and a national
magazine job, and I was sick of the financial insecurity that
hounds most free-lance writers.
</P>
<P>
   All I knew was that I wanted steady work for awhile; the
Examiner offered it.
</P>
<P>
   Like all new employees, my first few months were officially
probationary. But, by early August, my boss confided that I was a
shoo-in for permanent status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I worry about becoming a hack,'' I wrote in my journal.
``So easy it is to fall into phrases that normally make my stomach
contract. Daily newspaper writing: Blessing or burden?''
</P>
<P>
   Hooo boy. Besides being immature and arrogant, I did not yet
understand the virtues and rewards of daily journalism. I had not
yet fallen in love with newspapering.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I never did FALL in love with it. Rather, like a
mail-order bride, I discovered that an agreement born of necessity
could grow into a deep and lasting passion _ one that somehow
satisfies and arouses at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   But it took years. And God knows how many stories. Stories I got
high doing and stories I hated myself (and some assistant city
editor) for having to do.
</P>
<P>
   Never though, even as the hire-date anniversaries piled up, did
I think of myself as committed to this newspaper. I believed I was
a free person who could leave any day I wanted. Able to gather
information and disseminate it in solid, easy-to-read English
sentences, I knew I was eminently employable.
</P>
<P>
   Probably even by somebody who'd pay me a whole lot more money.
</P>
<P>
   And so the years passed. The '70s, '80s and '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential administrations came and went. The economy fell and
rose. The earth above the San Andreas and Hayward faults
occasionally moved. And, somewhere along the way, I traded in
Scotch whisky and late nights for a couple of glasses of red wine
and ``Law and Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the office, friends and lovers took turns starring on
center stage in my heart. All but a few drifted onto the periphery
or into the wings. Some got thrown out of the theater completely.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, five publishers and a couple of football teams worth of
editors took charge, then took a powder. A large handful of
colleagues died _ of cancer, AIDS, heart disease and homicide.
Scores more left in droves, often to work for somebody who found
them eminently employable and paid them a whole lot more money.
</P>
<P>
   New colleagues, usually young, ambitious and 10 times smarter
than I'll ever be, joined up in highly welcomed ones and twos.
</P>
<P>
   Sentenced by corporate bottom-liners to a lean diet, the
Examiner ``family'' shrank in size, but somehow never in quality.
Those of us who'd been around awhile (us ``geezers''), joked
sardonically about the family's dysfunctional nature. But we knew
that we could find no better sisters and brothers in anybody's
newsroom anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the people,'' I said about a million times. ``The people
I work with still make it all worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to June 21 and the 24th anniversary of my
hiring.
</P>
<P>
   Everything I've learned from 30 years in journalism tells me
there will be no 25th, that _ this time next year _ the San
Francisco Examiner, as I have known it for half my life, will not
exist.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's to me and the mail-order husband I have grown to
love. Happy Anniversary to us. It's been one hell of a great run.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
