<HEADER>
A8340 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SPACE-WEATHER-HNS &LR;      06-19 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-WEATHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR THESE FORECASTERS, WEATHER IS ALL IN THE STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Powerful solar storms can fry satellites,
disrupt power grids and snarl long-distance communications. This
vulnerability has spawned a new career that is increasingly vital
to power companies, the telecommunications industry and the
military: space weather forecaster.
</P>
<P>
   So new is this job that not everybody believes Craig Sechrest
when he says that is how he earns his pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can imagine some of my family dinners, where my relatives
start talking about their jobs _ say, they're talking about fixing
car motors _ and they ask me, `What do you do?''' said Sechrest,
who works at the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's
(NOAA) Space Environment Center in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them I look at sunspots and geomagnetic activity in the
near-Earth environment. They look at me and say, `Yeah, right!'''
</P>
<P>
   Space weather-casting is increasingly vital in an age when
humanity relies on technologies that are vulnerable to cosmic
hurricanes of radiation and high-speed particles. Satellites, cell
phones, pagers and continent-spanning power grids can be harmed by
the intense energy spawned by these storms.
</P>
<P>
   NOAA, NASA and power companies rely more and more on space
weather forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department guards its satellites, communication
networks and other functions against space storms by operating the
55th Space Weather Squadron at Schriever Air Force Base in Colorado
Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most folks think of space as a vacuum _ you get taught that in
grade school, but in our briefings with our customers, we're
constantly reminding them that space is a hostile environment,''
said Lt. Col. Jeff Carson, the squadron commander whose clients are
the Air Force, Army, Navy, Marine Corps and Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   During a bad solar storm, military officials ``who use the high
frequency portion of the spectrum, anywhere from 3 to 30 megahertz,
oftentimes will literally be knocked off the air by the X-ray
energy hitting Earth's atmosphere. Those impacts can last anywhere
from several minutes to two hours,'' said Carson, who received his
master's degree in meteorology at the Naval Postgraduate School in
Monterey, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   On June 6, a million miles from Earth, the Solar and
Heliospheric Observatory (SOHO) satellite detected two eruptions on
the sun that experts refer to as ``X-Class flares,'' one of which
was associated with a monstrous event called a coronal mass
ejection, when the sun spews out a massive amount of matter at
once. Usually the matter dissipates in space, but occasionally it
heads toward Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what the public affairs people like to call `a billion
tons of matter moving at a million miles an hour,''' said Joe
Gurman, U.S. project scientist for SOHO, a joint project of the
European Space Agency and the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration. Gurman works at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center
in Greenbelt, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The June 6 storm wasn't that unusual, as major storms go:
Similar events happen an average of about once a month during
periods of maximum solar activity. Periods of ``solar maximum,''
like now, occur once every 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   The June 6 storm could have been worse. Space weather
forecasters have not forgotten the ``Titanics'' of their young
profession, like the massive power failure in Quebec that was
triggered by a solar storm in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   An even bigger electrical collapse might occur nowadays because
utilities increasingly rely on electricity shared over power grids
thousands of miles long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regularly monitor solar activity,'' said Staci Homrig of
Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric in San Francisco. The utility compares
NOAA's reports of solar activities with the performance of PG&AMP;E
lines: ``We know the symptoms. We're watching for them and we
believe it's not impacting our system.''
</P>
<P>
   Space scientists constantly monitor solar activity through
deep-space satellites such as ACE, the Advanced Composition
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the University of California at Berkeley are
helping NASA develop another sun-watching satellite, called HESSI
for High Energy Solar Spectroscopic Imager. It is scheduled for
launch in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Both ACE and HESSI are primarily scientific missions that aim to
better understand the sun and how it works.
</P>
<P>
   But their observations augment alerts of solar storms from other
sources, including military satellites and the Air Force's global
network of ground-based solar observatories.
</P>
<P>
   Space forecasting is a sign of the times. ``As we become a more
technologically dependent culture, we have more and more
technological systems that are affected by space weather,'' Gurman
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added wryly: ``The people who develop space
satellites for pager communications will never admit that space
weather is to blame (for failures), because that's an `act of God'
and you don't get insurance for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
