<P>
   RACE-POLITICS (Bainbridge Island, Wash.) _ When he was sworn in
three years ago as the leader of a county with a population greater
than that of a half-dozen states, Ron Sims became one of three
nonwhites holding the top political jobs in Washington state. The
others are Gary Locke, the nation's first and only Chinese-American
governor, and Norm Rice, Seattle's mayor, who is black. Sims is a
natural storyteller with a compelling one to offer, a bootstrap
tale about a journey from anger to open arms. Yet his friends and
advisers have long urged him to keep a large part of that story _
race _ bottled up. What people want to hear are his views on
property taxes, traffic growth and salmon. On this day, however,
Sims has been asked to say something in honor of the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr., and he is tempted, he says, to let them see the
whole man. But do they really want to hear what it is like for a
black politician to live in two worlds? By Timothy Egan.
