<HEADER>
A8355 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUM     06-19 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUMN-ADV25-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV25 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS 
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 25, AND THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's EVERYDAY ETHICS column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the EVERYDAY ETHICS column _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHECKED OUT
</P>
<P>
   Q: I met a man who does research for large organizations at a
library that allows you to request 12 periodicals a day. To
circumvent this rule, he pays Russian immigrants a few dollars to
submit his requests in their names, violating the spirit of the
regulations and the minimum-wage laws. What is my ethical
obligation to the immigrants, who must need the money?
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Hoke, Washington
</P>
<P>
   A: To cheat a library, that noble institution of democracy, and
to exploit poor immigrants are indeed unethical acts, but are you
certain this is happening? If those Russians are his research
assistants, their requests are as legitimate as anyone's. And do
you really know their pay scale?
</P>
<P>
   If your suspicions can be confirmed, you should tell the
immigrants about the minimum-wage laws and the librarian about the
request-slip laundering. The library can decide if the Russians are
inconveniencing other patrons; the immigrants can think about
pushing for a raise.
</P>
<P>
   I'd hold off on calling the cops. Some researchers have had it
worse. In George Gissing's 1891 novel, ``New Grub Street,'' Marian
Yule describes her job: ``The readers who sat here at the radiating
desks, what were they but hapless flies caught in a huge web, its
nucleus the great circle of the Catalogue. Darker, darker. From the
tower wall of volumes seemed to emanate visible motes, intensifying
the obscurity; in a moment the book-lined circumference of the room
would be but a featureless prison-limit.'' If you spot anything
like that, then call 911.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Out to dinner, my wife and I became helplessly distracted by
blaring radio commercials. I had noticed the tuner in the back on
my way to the restroom, so I took the liberty of changing the
station to a commercial-free channel. My wife thinks I should have
asked someone who worked at the restaurant to change the station
rather than take matters into my own hands, but I think it was
simpler and faster just to do it myself. What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   _ Matthew Johnson, Andice, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Your dispute seems more about etiquette than ethics, and it
is one in which I side with your wife. You're certainly free to ask
the restaurant manager to turn the radio down, or off, or to be
switched to another station, but you have no right to impose your
own taste on your fellow diners. Similarly, if the color of the
walls offends you, you may complain, but you may not pull out a
roller and a dropcloth and start redecorating. Someone else's
restaurant; someone else's call.
</P>
<P>
   While it may indeed be simpler and faster to take matters _ and
the radio dial _ into your own hands, that's not much of a defense.
If an action is inapt, performing it more swiftly does not augment
its benevolence. I'm just as reluctant to be robbed by a fast thief
as by a dawdler.
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant's running commercial radio (or even those ``Car
Talk'' guys) may be annoying, but it is not unethical. Short of
cranking up the volume high enough to make your ears bleed, the
restaurant is free to pollute the audio environment any way it
likes. Because something is unpleasant needn't mean it is
unethical.
</P>
<P>
   That said, while your pre-emptive strike on the radio dial is
impolite, it is not particularly unethical. You harmed no one, and
should they desire it, the restaurateurs can easily switch back to
all-commercials, all-the-time radio. However, you may want to
reconsider the wisdom of offending the people who are about to
prepare your food.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist &LR; nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on EVERYDAY
ETHICS and other features. &QL;
</P>
