<HEADER>
A8364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-DRUGS-480&AMP;     06-19 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-DRUGS-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND CHINA WILL COOPERATE IN FIGHT AGAINST DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The United States and China agreed Monday to step up
their cooperation against the production and smuggling of illegal
drugs, especially heroin and methamphetamine, which have emerged as
scourges in both countries and throughout much of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, U.S. and Chinese law enforcement
agencies have sometimes cooperated to stop contraband drug
shipments. But on Monday the two governments signed their first
legal agreement to share information and evidence related to drug
smuggling, and officials from both sides predicted more
wide-ranging collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was announced here by Barry R. McCaffrey, the
retired army general who directs the White House office of national
drug control policy. McCaffrey is visiting China with counter-drug
officials from several U.S. agencies as part of an eight-day tour
that will also take them to Hong Kong, Hanoi and Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important moment,'' McCaffrey said after two days
of talks with Chinese officials. He said such collaboration was
vital to combatting global heroin trafficking and the fast-rising
abuse of methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   Since China began to open its borders in the late 1970s, it has
become a major transit route for heroin produced in southeast Asia,
especially Myanmar, the former Burma. Some of that heroin is
shipped by ethnic-Chinese gangs to the United States, although the
bulk of the heroin sold in the United States now comes from Latin
America, primarily Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The smuggling has engendered rising heroin addiction inside
China, especially in the southern province of Yunnan and in the
western region of Xinjiang, which receives heroin smuggled from
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   According to McCaffrey's office, factories in southeast China
are important producers of methamphetamine, which is sold
throughout East Asia, and of ephedrine, the ingredient used to
produce methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey listed several areas in which the United States hopes
to gain China's cooperation, including the sharing of strategic
intelligence about drug operations, money laundering, control of
precursor chemicals like ephedrine and of the weapons that make
their way to drug gangs, and on the analysis of seized drugs to
identify their sources.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which last year stationed a Drug Enforcement
Administration agent in Beijing, had also proposed opening a
Federal Bureau of Investigation office in China, but it has not
received an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Yang Fengrui, director of drugs at China's Ministry of Public
Security, who appeared with McCaffrey Monday, said he believed
Sino-American cooperation ``is going to enter a new stage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A hundred years ago in the Opium Wars, China was victimized,
and we can never forget that pain,'' Yang said, recalling an era
when Britain and other colonial European powers forced a defeated
China to accept opium.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yang said China was ready to work with the United States to
solve drug cases and control precursor chemicals and to exchange
samples from seized drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has repeatedly praised China's government for
making serious anti-drug efforts. McCaffrey said Monday that he did
not question the determination of Chinese officials to fight drug
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   He also praised China, which has been embarrassed by drug
scandals in international athletic competitions, for participating
in a new global agency to combat the use of performance-enhancing
drugs in sports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
