<HEADER>
A8375 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-EUROPE-WIRELESS-     06-19 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-EUROPE-WIRELESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN REFERRING TO WIRELESS IN EUROPE, USE THE FUTURE TENSE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BARCELONA, Spain _ It was a grand experiment, if maybe not the
clever promotional idea it must have seemed: At a technology
conference here attended by a bevy of companies and hundreds of
investors, every attendee received a free Internet-equipped
Ericsson cellular telephone.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be a chance for investors to experiment with
the new technology, to measure its potency hands on _ not to
mention spurring the investors to plow money into some of the
companies building applications and hardware for the latest
generation of handsets.
</P>
<P>
   But it became clear quite quickly to the people who received the
free phones that for all the hype about wireless application
protocol, or WAP, ``m-commerce'' and even the buzzword mouthful,
B-to-B m-commerce, the technology is still far from ready to
attract a mass market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to call my secretary and ask her what happened
to the market today,'' said a French banker after fitfully pounding
the phone's buttons for 10 minutes to check the latest stock
figures. ``I can do it in half the time, and it will be
significantly less painful.''
</P>
<P>
   The phones were not a complete bomb, though. Many investors
seemed to enjoy the ``gee whiz'' nature of the devices, considering
them a precursor of what is to come. And there is a lot on tap,
even if it will not become a mass-market reality for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's ready for prime time in a long way,''
acknowledged Gareth Hughes, managing director of Psion, the British
maker of hand-held devices, which is beginning to develop products
based on the wireless protocol. ``As much as I hate to say it, much
of what's out there is likely to disappoint the market with the
hype that's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Hughes described a science-fiction-like future that
he argued is only a year or two away from reality in Europe, where
the percentage of people who use mobile phones is much higher than
it is in the United States. His company is developing devices for
both white-collar and blue-collar work forces that will allow for a
variety of transactions and data exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   He waxed on about hand-held devices for doctors that will allow
them to pull up patients' records in real time with zoomable views
of X-rays and other diagrams. He demonstrated a hand-held device
that will allow corporate users to log on to a corporate network
and make a major stock trade on behalf of institutional clients.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he said, BMW sales representatives in Germany use a
wireless Psion device that allows them to call up car
specifications and other data. The service may be slow now, but as
wireless broadband, or high-speed Internet connections over the
phone, rolls out _ still at least five years away in Europe,
according to most estimates _ car shoppers will be able to look at
a BMW catalog on a hand-held device and then design their own cars
while driving inside test models. And they will pay by beaming bank
details to the salesman, if Hughes has his way.
</P>
<P>
   That will just be the beginning. According to Motorola, one of
the largest manufacturers of mobile phones, making phone calls on a
hand-held device will be only one tiny function. The devices will
be used as credit cards, to pay for a meal at a restaurant or
groceries at the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   The devices will also have a business-to-business angle: Workers
will be able to buy things with the device using the digital
equivalent of a corporate credit card and be able to receive a
reimbursement approval almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Michael R. Lynch, the chairman and chief executive of the
Autonomy Corp., an Internet software company, said that mobile
devices would go even one step further than the supermarket
example. He is working with clients who are developing devices and
software that will allow shoppers to scan a product's bar code in a
store and immediately display a list of other vendors selling the
same product and at what price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will change the whole experience,'' he said. ``It will be
even more competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   By tracking the location of customers' phones, stores and
restaurants will be able to alert customers who are in the
neighborhood to sales and specials they are running. Several
companies are even developing systems that would effectively alert
people if friends were nearby.
</P>
<P>
   A variation on that theme is another product in development that
would play matchmaker of sorts by issuing an alert when a possible
suitor with similar interests is nearby based on a questionnaire
both people would fill out beforehand. The company says that it is
aware of the potential perils and that the system will be
anonymous, with built-in mechanisms to avoid stalkers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides making payments for movie or airline tickets, mobile
devices will also act as a key to get into homes and offices, a
garage-door opener and identification device for all sorts of
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   It may all sound fanciful, but it is coming, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next 24 months will be the test,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Robin Saxby, chairman and chief executive of ARM Holdings,
one of the leading designers of microprocessors for hand-held
devices, still thinks m-commerce _ B-to-B or not _ is still a bit
of a pipe dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take at least 10 years to get it right,'' he said,
making reference to the free phone he received at the conference.
``Come on. These things just don't work.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
