<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8376 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-VIDEOS-ONLINE-NY     06-19 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-VIDEOS-ONLINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF IT'S ON VIDEO, YOU CAN FIND IT SOMEPLACE IN YOUR COMPUTER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    
 (ART ADV: Two color photos showing the box covers of the videos
``Stuart Little'' and ``Boys Don't Cry'' are available in JPEG
format by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    
 By PETER M. NICHOLS  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Pick a movie, any movie _ not one with Julia Roberts, but
something out of the mainstream that you know you would have one
chance in 1,000 of finding in the average video store. Something
like ``The Cranes Are Flying,'' Mikhail Kalatozov's acclaimed 1957
film about tangled love in wartime Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Or choose anything old, foreign, obscure or rare _ D.W.
Griffith's ``Female of the Species'' with Mary Pickford and Lillian
Gish, ``The Communist Weapon of Allure'' or the western ``Rio
Rattler.''
</P>
<P>
   On foot or horseback, it would take hours to scour video stores
to buy such items. On the Web, the hunt could be over in minutes.
</P>
<P>
   You will usually need a half-dozen places to look. Take
``Cranes'' as an example.
</P>
<P>
   Many buyers would go straight to Amazon.com, the 800-pound
gorilla of online video sales. Amazon carries 100,000 video titles
and, according to a report by Alexander &AMP; Associates, a Manhattan
consulting firm that follows the industry, accounted for almost 50
percent of online video sales in the last quarter of 1999. The site
also includes an auction of rare and hard-to-find videos.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon is linked to the immense Internet Movie Data Base,
www.imdb.com, which does not sell videos directly but is an
annotated index of 230,000 films from around the world, a total
that rises by the hour. On that database is a complete description
of ``The Cranes Are Flying.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the interactive nature of many video sites on
the Web, the database lets movie fans write reviews. Robert De
Saint-Loup of Balbec, France, writes, ``In its subsuming of vast
social, national and world events to a love affair, it is
essentially no different from a conventional Hollywood movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to the ``Cranes'' entry is a box that links the user to
Amazon.com, but a balloon states that the movie is not available
from Amazon. So the search continues.
</P>
<P>
   The second-largest site in terms of revenue, Familywonder.com _
with 11.3 percent of the Web video market _ is basically for
children and their parents. Not the likeliest source for
``Cranes,'' though it does offer foreign films, in addition to
animated, live-action and horror productions, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The third-largest site, Reel.com, a general, all-service source
that is owned by Hollywood Video, the nation's second-largest chain
after Blockbuster, doesn't have the movie. Nor does
Blockbuster.com.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-largest site, the online auction house eBay _ 5.5
percent of the market _ had 1,874 foreign films up for bids
recently, but ``Cranes'' wasn't among them. You could have bid on a
``rare'' edition of Pedro Almodovar's ``Matador,'' however, which
stood at $25 with nine days and 12 hours left on the block.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-largest site, Bigstar.com, whose home page says it has
80,000 titles, listed ``Cranes'' and gave some particulars _ but
it, too, did not have the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cranes'' was available from two well-known sites, however. The
site for Movies Unlimited, www.moviesunlimited.com, had the tape
for $47.49, down from $49.99. At Facets International,
www.facets.org, ``Cranes'' was listed at $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   Of the sites checked, only these two had the film. Several
others noted for deep collections, including www.kimsvideo.com, an
arm of the famous New York video store, and Tlavideo.com, which
belongs to the Philadelphia-based chain and mail-order company, did
not.
</P>
<P>
   Movies Unlimited, also in Philadelphia, and Facets
International, in Chicago, publish catalogs of 40,000 to 45,000
titles, sprinkled with tapes even seasoned videophiles probably
haven't heard of. They have huge inventories of foreign and
art-house movies, along with large and eclectic collections in
every genre, from cult and horror to silent film, American
independents, all kinds of retro television and the performing and
fine arts. Facets has an extensive collection of foreign cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Both sites look for the unusual, often title by title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make an effort to track down the stuff,'' says Irv Slifkin
of Movies Unlimited. ``We deal with hundreds of independents and
small companies. Often we deal with one person who owns the
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment he was pleased to be able to list ``Incubus,''
the 1965 horror film directed by Leslie Stevens and featuring
William Shatner speaking Esperanto.
</P>
<P>
   Even Facets didn't have that one. But Amazon did. ``Our price:
$34.95,'' the entry read.
</P>
<P>
   As the largest site, Amazon attracts videos from all quarters,
including hundreds of tapes from fledgling independent movie makers
offered in Amazon Advantage, a special section on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Like Facets, Movies Unlimited and most other sites, Amazon
quickly leads clients to related titles. Customers who bought
``Incubus'' at Amazon, the site says, also bought ``Blood Feast''
(1963), ``Macbeth'' (1978) and ``Black Sunday'' (1960) on DVD. Four
similar titles were suggested by Facets.org, including ``The
Devil's Nightmare'' (1971), Jean Brismee's ``slice of demented
Belgian-Italian sleaze.''
</P>
<P>
   DVD buyers may need an extra push to start browsing.
</P>
<P>
   ``DVD households tend to be more tech-savvy, so it's more of a
planned purchase,'' says Greg Durkin, Alexander &AMP; Associates' video
research director. ``People go to Reel or Amazon and type in the
title. It's the same with books and music.''
</P>
<P>
   From that, retailers hope, something else catches the eye of
customers, leading to the impulse purchase. Studios spend a lot on
banner ads, ever flashing and changing. Buyers looking up one title
spot others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `Why don't I just go ahead and buy it, if it's
discounted that much?''' Durkin says.
</P>
<P>
   And how much is that? Prices vary widely and often deceptively
online. At the end of 1999, Amazon had an average price of $24.97.
Familywonder.com's was $12.83, Reel &QC; .com's $15.23, eBay's $20.32
and Bigstar.com's $12.25.
</P>
<P>
   Sites regularly trumpet savings of ``30 to 40 percent.'' A young
market, video e-commerce accounted for only 2.2 percent of overall
cassette sales and 9.6 percent of DVD sales in the fourth quarter
of 1999, and players jockeying for market share often lower prices
drastically.
</P>
<P>
   But for new mainstream titles, shoppers are often better off
buying at the video store. If price is the main consideration, shop
around various sites but remember: The average price paid for a
video on the Web, according to Alexander &AMP; Associates, was $19.25
at the end of last year, compared with $14.25 in stores. Thank
shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say that cutting prices below cost will thin
out video e-commerce, and that many sites will fail or be
consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Video and DVD are low-margin commodity products,'' says Carrie
Johnson, an analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon will only get bigger, Johnson says. So, too, in all
likelihood, will sites related to the big store chains and solidly
established mail-order operations such as Facets, Movies Unlimited
and TLA.
</P>
<P>
   And don't worry about the movies _ there will always be plenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine Shatner in Esperanto,'' Slifkin says.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
