<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8387 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECHNOBUDDY0620-COX     06-19 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0620-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cell phone insanity is spreading, so here are some rules
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The man was obviously insane, maybe dangerously so,
waving his arms, speaking loudly as he walked alone along the
street on a dusky evening near the newspaper where I work.
</P>
<P>
   As near as I could tell he was either excited about a baseball
game or explaining to no one in particular that he intended to buy
bread on the way home.
</P>
<P>
   Then I saw the tiny wire leading from the cell phone and the
microphone and earpiece. He was having a cellular phone
conversation as he walked. To avoid scaring folks such as myself,
maybe he should get a sign: ``Not crazy, just talking on the cell
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   There are very few times that I need to have long conversations
while walking down the street, now that they have the medication
right. But seemingly normal people who have homes and families are
walking the streets, talking about the darnedest things. It's
because of those danged low cell phone rates and free airtime
offers.
</P>
<P>
   I yearn for the days when the only people having monologues were
wearing three jackets and mismatched shoes.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not the only danger from cell phone addicts. If they
don't kill you on the road, they'll drive you crazy in the
elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Just this morning on the elevator at work, a fellow standing 8
inches away from me was explaining to his wife why his golf round
lasted 18 hours on Saturday. It was obvious, from listening to his
end of the conversation, that she wasn't buying. He would have been
better off spending enough time getting a better story together.
From what I could hear, he was finding out in a personal way that
cell phones can be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   There are other dangers, too.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine at work got a strange call the other day. Her
phone rang and _ instead of hearing someone say hello _ she was
listening to a heated discussion at a business meeting. Turns out
that her boyfriend had his phone in his hip pocket and _ by
squirming just right _ hit the button that re-dialed her work
number.
</P>
<P>
   No harm was done, it was just funny, but you don't have to be a
genius to see how an accidental call like that could be downright
awful under the wrong circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Most people seem to have more cellular airtime than they have
something to say. Now I get calls from friends, driving in their
cars, who want to ask me if I've seen the latest model of the Ford
Explorer, or to muse about what they plan to have for dinner. Now
that free long-distance calling is part of most plans, I keep
hearing from folks all over the country who want to tell me about
the traffic jam that they've encountered in Cincinnati or about
their dog's medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is a wonderful thing, but it's just about to bore me
to death.
</P>
<P>
   So today, at the risk of hurting your feelings, let's talk about
how to act right. Think of it as Husted's Rules for Cellular
Etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 1. If you are so busy that you have to make and take calls
on the golf course, in the movies and other places where decent
folk are trying to get away from it all, then you are too busy to
have fun. Stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 2. Turn the danged thing off when you go to church, the
movies or a play. That weird nee-nah, nee-nah sound frightens
children and annoys adults.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 3. Unless you are having a really interesting conversation
_ something that could be turned into a soap opera _ don't have it
within my earshot.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 4. If you really don't have anything to say and simply
enjoy making calls, get a job as a motel switchboard operator.
</P>
<P>
   And please, if you disagree, send an e-mail. Don't call me using
your cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
