 COUPLE COMPLAINS OF A BULL IN A CHINA SHOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1997 wedding of Steven and Emily Shalansky is now a fond
photo-album memory, but as of last week the Massachusetts couple
was still waiting for much of the china their wedding guests
purchased for them three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they prepare for the arrival of their first baby in
November, the Shalanskys are battling with Bloomingdale's over the
retailer's failure to deliver the fancy French china.
</P>
<P>
   What particularly irked the Shalanskys was the lack of urgency
they sensed from Bloomingdale's officials. ``They've just been
passing us off with overt indifference,'' said Emily.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration reached the breaking point last week when the
Shalanskys called me. They voiced a common complaint of many
consumers, that retailers take their money and then fail to deliver
what was promised. Rather than leveling with the consumer about the
problem and rectifying it, the Shalanskys say Bloomingdale's strung
them along and in the end failed to compensate them properly for
lousy customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomingdale's last week agreed to take back the china the
Shalanskys had received and issue a refund equal to the current
retail price of the china, a total of approximately $3,500. The
Shalanskys had wanted an additional $3,100 to purchase a new set of
china, but Bloomingdale's refused to compensate them further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disappointed and we still want additional
remuneration,'' said Steven Shalansky.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomingdale's officials, while acknowledging poor customer
service, nevertheless say they were caught in the middle between an
angry customer and a manufacturer, Christofle of Paris, that
couldn't deliver the product. ``It's beyond our control,'' said
senior vice president Anne Keating.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Marc Gallot, president of Christofle's US operations, said
he heard about the Shalanskys' situation just last week and felt
terrible about it. He said he planned to personally intervene to
rectify the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Gallot said delays of several months with china deliveries are
not uncommon because of the uncertainty of the manufacturing
process, but he said a three-year delay was totally unacceptable.
``The service has been very poor, terrible, awful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong is still not entirely clear. The Shalanskys
registered with Bloomingdale's in December 1996, well in advance of
their August 1997 wedding. Among the items they listed was an
expensive china pattern made by Christofle, a respected company
that started out as the silversmith to the emperor Napoleon III.
Christofle is known worldwide, with stores called pavillons in
cities ranging from Buenos Aires to Athens, Paris to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Guests to the Shalansky wedding paid for nine table settings,
plus eight rimmed soup bowls and seven accent plates. These items
cost nearly $2,200 in all.
</P>
<P>
   The Shalanskys didn't think much about the china as they dashed
off to Bermuda for their honeymoon, but after the thank-you notes
had been written and the wedding gown stored away, they began
calling the Bloomingdale's store in Chestnut Hill, Mass. to seek
progress reports. They said they were typically told about vague
problems with the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   A few pieces would arrive in the mail periodically, but as of
last September, two years after their wedding, only three place
settings and three soup bowls had been delivered. Frustrated,
Brookline, Mass. couple wrote a letter to the chief executive of
Bloomingdale's in New York. Laurie Thornton, the general manager of
the Chestnut Hill store, responded with a letter in which she said
she was ``appalled at the lack of customer service you
experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton said some items from the original registry had been
purged from the Bloomingdale's system and were being reordered. She
said Christofle had promised delivery by December and as a token of
apology she offered a Christofle teapot worth $240.
</P>
<P>
   The Shalanskys were so encouraged by the tone of Thornton's
letter that they decided to pool the $240 from the teapot with more
of their own money to buy a full 12 place settings.
</P>
<P>
   But December passed and the full order had still not arrived. In
April, the Shalanskys wrote another letter to the chief executive
of Bloomingdale's demanding their china and additional
renumeration.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton again responded, this time blaming a warehouse
relocation and operational difficulties at Christofle for the
delay. She promised to seek alternative sources for the missing
china. ``This process will take a few weeks, but my hope is that we
can successfully fulfill your order,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after calls from the Globe, Bloomingdale's officials
said they could not obtain assurances from Christofle of a
guaranteed delivery date. So they told the Shalanskys to return the
china that had been delivered and get a full refund.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Bloomingdale's store at Chestnut Hill is
carrying the same Christofle pattern the Shalanskys purchased. And
when I called the Christofle store in New York, I was told I could
take delivery of 12 place settings of the same pattern in four
months.
</P>
<P>
   Gallot said the four-month delivery pledge is what his factory
in France is promising, but he said he could not guarantee it. He
also noted the pattern the Shalanskys purchased is partly made by a
supplier to Christofle, which makes delivery even more problematic.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Shalansky said he is convinced only the Globe's
intervention forced the issue to come to a head last week. Asked
what he and his wife plan to do now, he said: ``We're going to shop
somewhere else and never shop at Bloomingdale's again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline discounts
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With gasoline prices going through the roof, drivers with gas
guzzlers might want to check out Carclub.com as a way to save some
money this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Carclub costs $5.99 a month, or about $72 a year, which is
steep. But it offers a 10 percent discount for the rest of this
year on gasoline purchased at any of the 110,000 gas stations
nationwide that accept MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Club membership has other benefits as well, including
reimbursement of auto insurance deductibles of up to $500 in the
case of an accident, a mechanic hotline for second opinions on
repair estimates, and even directions when you get lost.
</P>
<P>
   The gas discount, however, is the real value. Here's how it
works. You sign up at carclub.com or 1-800-227-2582 for what, in
effect, is a prepaid gas card. You prepay up to $200 a month. You
can then go to any gas station that accepts MasterCard and buy gas
there. Carclub will pay the gas station owner the price on the pump
but deduct only 90 percent of that price from your card's account.
</P>
<P>
   If you spend $80 a month on gasoline, for example, the card will
save you $16, nearly three times the monthly cost of the
membership. With prices at many stations hitting $1.60 a gallon and
expected to go higher this summer, the savings is at least 16 cents
a gallon. A Carclub spokeswoman said the discount will continue
next year, but probably at the reduced level of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Carclub's chief advantage over other gas discount programs is
that it allows you to shop for the lowest-priced gas and then get
10 percent off that price. By contrast, several oil companies offer
gasoline rebate programs with their credit cards but require you to
buy gas at their stations. Priceline.com is also planning to unveil
a gas card soon, allowing users to place bids on what they want to
pay for gas. But that will take more effort and also restrict where
you can fill up your tank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bruce Mohl is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached at
617-474-2510, by e-mail at mohl(at)globe.com, or at The Boston
Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
