<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CHICKEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAY ANIMATORS FEATHER THEIR NEST WITH `CHICKEN RUN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think spending 18 months shooting an animated prison
breakout film starring chickens would make codirectors Peter Lord
and Nick Park empathetic to the plight of poultry, think again.
Both had just eaten fowl for lunch and were feeling none the worse
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no one we knew, so it was all right,'' says Lord, 46.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Lord and Park's goal with their new film, ``Chicken
Run'' (opening Friday), was to make heroes out of hens, not destroy
the breast, wing, and drumstick market. They achieved that goal by
making ``The Great Escape'' with fowl, a ``Hogan's Heroes'' for
hens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken Run'' is about an imprisoned group of birds who have
two choices in life: Lay eggs regularly or become the next
evening's meal for their captors, the Tweedys. Their plucky young
leader, Ginger (played by Julia Sawalha, veteran of the British
comedy series ``Absolutely Fabulous'') tries to liberate her fellow
hens innumerable times before the film's beginning credits crawl to
an end. But it's Mel Gibson's character, Rocky the rooster, who may
finally give the birds the skills they need to break free.
</P>
<P>
   Packed with comedy, drama, and a dash of action thanks to visual
references to ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' and ``Aliens,'' ``Chicken
Run'' is the first big-screen outing for Aardman, a clay animation
studio in Bristol, England, founded by Lord and David Sproxton.
Aardman has achieved cultlike status (not to mention snagging three
Academy Awards for best animation short films) with the help of
their popular hand-molded creations Wallace, an inventor, and his
faithful pooch, Gromit.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a world where animation hits, whether ``The Rugrats
Movie'' or ``Tarzan,'' tend to come from literature or television
series that audiences are already familiar with. Will viewers
respond to a film filled with strange fowl?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wallace and Gromit did a lot of groundwork for us,'' says
Park, 41, with a laid-back delivery that makes him sound like a
British hippie. ``I think we'll have quite a devoted following on
this movie.''
</P>
<P>
   And the film does offer the fans something familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the California raisins?'' asks John Canemaker,
director of the animation program at New York University's Tisch
School of the Arts, of the 1980s commercials that featured plump
singing raisins. ``It's the same sort of clay animation technique
that `Chicken Run' is doing.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laying the egg &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To develop the film, Park and Lord followed their instincts
rather than the money-generating Disney musical formula. So you
won't hear the poultry break into Negro spirituals over their
enslaved plight. Instead you get chickens with wings that work like
arms and beaks that contain a dazzling set of teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Many viewers may wonder about the birds' extensive dental work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean they don't have teeth?,'' says Lord who was in Los
Angeles with Park doing media interviews. ``We were hoping no one
would notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Park, ``We went to a chicken farm actually and discovered
that they don't have teeth. It was a bit of a shock. But we were
too far down the line of production at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   They're joking, of course. Lord and Park added teeth and armlike
musculature to their feathered characters for specific reasons. One
gave their stars the ability to enunciate their lines. The other
allowed the chickens to dig ditches, build airplanes, and _ knit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These chickens of ours have to hold the screen compellingly
for 83 minutes,'' says Lord. ``They have to be able to act really
well. And, you know, it's very difficult if you have beaks stuck in
front of your face and just wings.''
</P>
<P>
   But the animal kingdom is filled with a variety of creatures.
Why choose chickens in the first place? Park and Lord mull over the
matter for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that chickens had had bad press for too long,'' Lord
finally explains. ``Something should be done to address the
balance.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The fertilization &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The concept for the film developed after Park drew a picture of
a hen digging under a wire fence with a spoon. Park had had an
affinity for the birds since he was a child; his sister had owned a
pet chicken. ``Chicken Run'' gave Park a chance to try to end fowl
stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never really been used in movies except to play
extras,'' says Park. ``Usually they go flying out of a barn when a
car goes racing through. People think they're just dumb animals and
are only good for that kind of role. Whereas when you get close to
a chicken and live with it, then you get to see they do have
character and a lot of comic potential.''
</P>
<P>
   That potential becomes apparent when you see Ginger and Rocky
staring soulfully at each other in one scene and kissing in
another.
</P>
<P>
   The kiss was a particular challenge. Park and Lord first
experimented with having the beaks meet together like suction
tubes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which was totally bizarre,'' says Lord. ``It was totally
ridiculous. It was hard to take the moment seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   They solved the problem by allowing this moment of intimacy to
remain private. After several false starts, Rocky and Ginger lock
lips turned away from the camera.
</P>
<P>
   As for the hysterically blank stare that passes between Rocky
and Ginger as they fall for each other: ``That's one thing we love
to play with, really, the dead kind of look,'' says Park. ``I think
people read things into the characters. That gives them depth, you
know.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
An animated history &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lord and Park have worked in animation most of their lives. Lord
and his Aardman cocreator Sproxton experimented with animation on
their kitchen tables as teenagers before founding Aardman in 1972.
Park was already making his own animation movies in his parents'
attic when, at 12, he was introduced via television to Aardman's
work in the form of their shape-shifting Morph character.
</P>
<P>
   Lord and Sproxton dabbled with traditional animation ``for about
a week,'' jokes Lord, in the beginning of their career. But the
pleasure of shaping plastic into living creatures quickly won out.
</P>
<P>
   It's an arduous task. An eye, leg, hand, or arm of just one
character can be adjusted 24 times to create a second of film seen
on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's slow, it's weird, it takes you all day,'' says Lord,
``But then when your film comes back from the laboratory and you
get to see it, you find that you've created this moment of life _
or so it seems. That's what it's about, animation, meaning giving
life.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to clay animation ``no one else does it
better, I don't think,'' says Lord, than Aardman. Remember the
animated images in Peter Gabriel's ``Sledgehammer'' video? That's
Aardman's work. The studio's preeminence in the field was further
cemented in the 1990s when Park won Oscars for directing the
Wallace and Gromit shorts ``A Grand Day Out,'' ``The Wrong
Trousers,'' and ``A Close Shave.''
</P>
<P>
   If that award record isn't enough to lure people into theaters,
having superstar Gibson voice one of the film's lead characters
might do the trick. Park and Lord started working with Gibson while
he was filming ``Lethal Weapon 4.'' Gibson spent mornings filming
``The Patriot'' and afternoons voicing Rocky to complete his
``Chicken Run'' chores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often wondered why he agreed to do it,'' says Lord,
laughing. ``Playing as a chicken, I'm sure, wasn't his best offer
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Park, ``He probably hadn't done enough poultry roles
recently.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the truth is Gibson's a fan, so you could say Wallace and
Gromit made him do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
