<HEADER>
A8405 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      06-19 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THIS COUPLE, FULL PENSION IS THE WAY TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I work in education and would like to retire in
June 2002, when I will be 59 1/2. Our projected pensions have a 2
percent annual cost-of-living increase. In addition to my pension,
I will receive a monthly stipend of $500 from age 59 1/2 to 62, due
to my longevity with the school district. At 62, I will qualify for
$500 a month in Social Security. Counting an anticipated withdrawal
of $2,000 a month from our mutual fund accounts, we would have a
maximum gross monthly income of $8,900. Should we leave all our
money in the pensions and take the guaranteed lifetime payout, or
withdraw some and invest it? Both pensions would continue to make
full lifetime payments to the surviving spouse when the first of us
dies. We are not concerned about leaving an inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   G.W., Boring, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I hope you're not a math teacher. In calculating that $8,900
maximum monthly income, you counted both the Social Security
benefit that begins at age 62, plus the longevity stipend, which
ends at 62. So your income upon retirement would range from a low
of $8,100 to a high of $8,400.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether to take the full pension or the smaller
pension plus cash shouldn't take much analysis. You would have to
find an investment with a return in excess of 19 percent to supply
a cash flow to match what the pension offers, and in addition you
would sacrifice half of the cost-of-living adjustment if you went
for the lower pension. Clearly, this pension plan is designed with
heavy incentives to take the lifetime pension rather than the cash.
I think you would be foolish to take anything but the full
pensions.
</P>
<P>
   To express the situation another way, if you took the $122,500
in cash and invested it in a portfolio that produced average 10
percent gains _ and then withdrew $1,950 a month _ the pool would
run dry in less than 7.5 years. The full-pension option is so
attractive it's a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, my main suggestion is that you take a different
approach to budgeting your retirement, beginning with the low end
of the range for the pensions, and then considering the possibility
that you might not want to take as much as $2,000 a month from your
mutual fund accounts at the outset. I have never been a big fan of
budgeting an income stream with a stock-dominated portfolio being a
major source of the income; what you are basically planning on is
spending anticipated capital gains, which may or may not be in the
offing.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term, it doesn't appear you are being particularly
aggressive in terms of your expectations. A sequence of withdrawals
of $2,000 a month from a $350,000 portfolio would require a return
of only 6.87 percent to avoid depletion of your capital.
</P>
<P>
   But while several of your funds feature the word income, they
are all, in fact, dominated by stock holdings. Only United
Continental Income fund, with 30 percent bonds, and United
Retirement Shares, with 13 percent bonds, have fixed-income
positions. The highest current yield of any of your funds is the
2.05 percent of United Continental Income fund.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you take one of two approaches to getting income from
the fund portfolio. One is to move about half of the money to pure
bond funds, from which you would withdraw the actual yield, a move
that might net you about $1,000 a month. As for the other half, I
suggest you draw a line in the sand at $175,000; if the fund
balance exceeds $175,000, you could take your $1,000 additional
withdrawal, provided it did not bring the balance below that
$175,000. If the stock markets deliver you a bad season, you could
then rebudget for a thin month and squeak through.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the assumption of a 6.87 percent return is indeed
reasonable, you might have a few tough months at the outset, but
before a great deal of time elapses your balance should be so
comfortably in excess of that $175,000 you won't have to worry. The
advantage here is that while you would indeed be spending capital
gains from your stock funds, at least you would be spending only
capital gains that have actually occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The second approach would involve more flexibility in your
budgeting, since it would entail leaving all of the money in the
stock-dominated funds, but being prepared to take no withdrawals at
all in the event the portfolio slipped below that $350,000 level.
In the long run, this approach would be more attractive, but it
would also expose you to larger potential shocks in the early
years.
</P>
<P>
   I am leery of plans that anticipate fairly steady stock market
gains. But I also think you should retain a significant part of
your savings in stocks or stock funds. The 2 percent annual COLA
that applies to both of your pensions will help you deal with the
inflation that's likely during the years of your retirement, but
it's probably not going to do the entire job. About 10 years into
your retirement, you will doubtless find you'll want to make
heavier withdrawals from the fund accounts. If a significant part
of the money had been in stocks during that decade, the odds are
very strong the balance would be sufficient to support those higher
withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I seem to have substantial savings, but no direction. I'm not
sure where to put my savings to maximize growth. I am saving for
the long term, but within a year I plan to get married and buy a
home. Homes here average about $300,000. In the future, I'd also
like to own a small condo in Florida, which would probably cost
about $100,000. I plan to work at my current job for another 27
years and retire with an 80 percent pension. Also, new funds are
being offered in my deferred compensation plan, and I would like to
add more funds to diversify. I feel I have no direction, and with a
stock market that is very unpredictable, I could lose all. I
believe I'm diversified, but I'm not sure.
</P>
<P>
   R.J., Scituate, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you have no direction, you've certainly gone a long way
for a fellow of 32. In addition to earning the pension you are
looking forward to, if you continue contributions to the deferred
compensation plan at current levels and achieve 10 percent average
annual returns, you would amass $1,723,860 in that account. If your
Roth IRAs were fully funded for the same period, that would add
another $347,142.
</P>
<P>
   In short, with those accumulations in addition to your pension,
it seems to me your long-term planning is pretty well taken care
of. Certainly with a 27-year time frame in those accounts, you
don't need to worry about the stock market's health. In a period
that long, you will go through many markets good and bad. The trick
is simply to stick to the program.
</P>
<P>
   Because the IRA and deferred compensation plans should deal with
your retirement so well, I suggest you deal with the uncertainties
of the current stock market by making a whopping down payment on
your home. You can determine for yourself how large a mortgage
payment you want to face, and how much in the way of emergency
savings you require. You might fund as much as half _ and perhaps
even more _ of your home purchase from your various taxable savings
accounts, still leaving you with about nine months' income in
emergency savings. If you do that, I'd suggest thatonce you decide
on the amount of your taxable mutual fund positions you want to
sell, do it immediately. Since you plan to buy within a year,
whatever amount will go for the down payment would have become
short-term savings, and thus would be more appropriately invested
in a money market fund than in the various stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   (But if you decide to retain some of the taxable stock positions
as long-term investments, I'd put Putnam Health and Sciences fund
at the head of the list of keepers.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the new investments available within your deferred
compensation plan, you can stick with both of the Fidelity funds
you are now using and diversify by building small positions _ in
the 10 to 15 percent range _ in the small-cap and international
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
