<HEADER>
A8410 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE-MASS     06-19 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE-MASSAGE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE INSURANCE COMPANIES RECOGNIZE HEALTH BENEFITS OF MASSAGE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    (ART ADV: Photos of people receiving massage and of some of
those mentioned in story available in JPEG format by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    
 By JULIANNE REMINGTON 
 c.2000 InterNetwork News
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   Her muscles sore and tight from fibromyalgia, Cheryln
Christoffels used to feel like she'd been run over by a truck when
she woke up in the morning. No more. Now that she's visited a
massage therapist, she says that she feels like she's ``improved 90
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that kneading muscles relieves stress and aids
circulation. ``It's invaluable in helping an individual have less
pain, and it improves their range of motion,'' says physiatrist
Jerry Blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, massage allows a person to sleep better too.
Insurance companies are realizing that massage can be an integral
part of a rehabilitation program.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health defines therapeutic massage as
the manipulation of soft tissue to prevent and alleviate pain,
muscle spasms and stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the muscle is tight and short, there's less blood supply
and less circulation,'' says Blow. ``What massage does is break
that cycle. You get in and soften up the muscles and break up the
hardened area.''
</P>
<P>
   Massage not only increases circulation but also boosts the
body's pain-relieving endorphins, according to the American Massage
Therapy Association. Still some say it's not medical therapy, and
research must prove its benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The AMTA cites numerous studies showing that massage lowers
heart rate and blood pressure while increasing circulation.
``Therapeutic massage enhances medical treatment and helps people
feel less anxious and stressed, yet more alert,'' states the AMTA.
</P>
<P>
   The National Certification Board for Therapeutic Massage and
Bodywork certifies therapists, and 29 states and the District of
Columbia regulate the field. As insurance companies recognize the
expertise of the therapists, they're providing more coverage for
prescribed treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Not all proponents of massage feel convinced that increasing
insurance coverage, however, is a good thing. Some say it will make
for a lot of paperwork and may ``medicalize'' the practice in a way
that makes some therapists uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Whether insurance offers coverage for massage or not, doctors
warn that not all patients benefit from muscle kneading and soft
tissue manipulation. This includes those with inflammation of the
veins or phlebitis, infectious diseases, certain cancers, some skin
conditions or specific cardiac problems.
</P>
<P>
   Whether through insurance or their own pockets, consumers now
spend $2 billion to $4 billion annually for massages. Since many
can't afford the average $45 per hour fee, insurance policies often
determine who gets the therapy and who doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Some states are even considering legislation that would require
insurance companies to cover treatments by licensed massage
therapists. According to ATMA, several health and managed-care
plans already cover it including Oxford Health Plans Inc., PREMERA
(formerly Blue Cross of Washington and Alaska, and Medical Services
Corp.,) Prudential Insurance Company of America, Great-West Life
and Annuity, Group Health Cooperative of Puget Sound and
Alternative Health Insurance Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish my insurance covered it,'' says Christoffels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once massage therapy is prescribed,'' says Blow, ``you or your
doctor may need to seek authorization from the insurer if coverage
is not clearly spelled out in your policy or plan.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written survey of physicians, nurses, dentists and other
health professionals at the University of Florida, 52 percent said
they had tried an alternative treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this survey, we've learned that the health science
faculty are pretty much like anyone else when it comes to their own
health,'' said Dr. Allen Neims, a professor of pharmacology and
former dean of the University of Florida's College of Medicine.
``This is significant, because they are the role models and
teachers of the next generation of health-care professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   About half of U.S. medical schools offer elective courses on
alternative therapies, Neims said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous amount of individuality in how
integrative treatments are presented to students by the faculty,''
Neims said. ``Some include quite a bit of information and others
are quite resistant to it, seeing it as a step backwards
scientifically. While there is room for both views within the
college, I hope this study gives people a little more sense of
permission to teach these things. Teaching about them does not have
to be an endorsement.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health opened an Office of
Alternative Medicine in 1992 to study therapies like massage. NIH
reported the following results:
</P>
<P>
   _ Office workers massaged regularly were more alert.
</P>
<P>
   _ Massage therapy decreased the effects of anxiety and pain in
burn patients.
</P>
<P>
   _ Abdominal surgery patients recovered more quickly after
massage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Premature infants who were massaged fared better than those
who weren't.
</P>
<P>
   _ Autistic children showed less erratic behavior after massage
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really want to feel better, and doctors are finding
that massage is a great way to get people back to a functioning
level,'' says Blow. ``We can all use massage at one time or
another, but in acute medical conditions, it's extremely
beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   (Julianne Remington writes for Healthsurfing.com.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
