<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8411 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-GOLDIE-HAWN-LIFEBEAT-     06-19 2010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDIE-HAWN-LIFEBEAT-ART-1700-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE GOLDIE, HAPPY ALL THE TIME
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    (ART ADV: A photo of Goldie Hawn is available in JPEG format by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By JULIANN GAREY 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
<P>
   Goldie Hawn was practically giddy with excitement as she and her
date, her 13-year-old son, Wyatt _ made their way into last
spring's all-star tribute to legendary singer Joni Mitchell.
``She's just one of the greatest poets of our time,'' said Hawn,
glowing with admiration. ``She's given us so much joy and so much
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon the music was vibrating up through the floor, and Bryan
Adams and Wynonna were bringing down the house with their cover of
Mitchell's ``Raised on Robbery.'' Sitting in the audience, Hawn
tried hard to stay in her seat, but her shoulders shook, her hips
wriggled, her hands clapped, and her blond mane swung back and
forth over her bare shoulders. If she weren't afraid it would
mortify her son, she would have been on her feet, dancing. But as
the mother of a teen-ager, she knew better. So Hawn kept her butt
in her seat.
</P>
<P>
   But the smile on her face was pure joy.
</P>
<P>
   Goldie Hawn is about nothing if not the thoughtful and
considered exploration, cultivation, renewal and expression of joy.
It is not a subject she takes lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a light personality and a deep-thinking brain,'' she
said. ``Those are two very different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in suburban Takoma Park, Md., by her mother, Laura, a
dance teacher, and her father, Edward, a musician, Hawn always
loved to perform and planned a career on the stage as a singer and
dancer. But then a talent agent spotted the 22-year-old Hawn
dancing in a chorus line, signed her up, and landed her a small
role on a CBS television series. One day, George Schiatter, the
creator of Rowan and Martin's ``Laugh-In,'' happened to walk by the
set. And that was that.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Laugh-In,'' Hawn's trademark giggle was born when she
flubbed her lines on camera and broke into a fit of laughter. She
discovered, along with the rest of the country, that she was a
comedic natural. ``Directing Goldie was more a question of getting
out of the way,'' says Schlatter, ``because whatever was going to
happen was better than what I would have directed her to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawn hardly fits the stereotype of the neurotic comedian. It's a
safe bet that 99.9 percent of her colleagues aren't as happy as she
is. Offstage, good comedians are supposed to be at least a little
angst ridden, right? Filled with just a touch of self-loathing?
</P>
<P>
   Not Goldie. ``She is an amazing positive energy force,'' her
friend and Pacific Palisades, Calif., neighbor Martin Short has
said, ``that just emits sunshine and joy wherever she goes.'' Her
``Everyone Says I Love You'' co-star Alan Alda feels there's
something almost therapeutic about hanging around Hawn. ``We need
people like her to lift our spirits,'' he's said. ``There's always
a lot of laughing and fun with Goldie.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, too much unadulterated perkiness probably wouldn't be
tolerated for long among some of Hawn's friends _ Woody Allen,
Steve Martin, Bette Midler. Yet somehow Hawn's radiant happiness is
far from relentless or irritating.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's unique about Goldie,'' said Diane Keaton, who worked
with Hawn on ``The First Wives Club,'' ``is that she has a huge
capacity to enjoy life. Every morning she would get a cappuccino,
and every day it was 'the best cappuccino!' It's fun to be around,
because I'm not that way at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In next month's ``Town and Country,'' a romantic comedy about
two couples facing mid-life marital crises, Hawn stars opposite
Garry Shandling, the actor/comedian who has to be _ at least
temperamentally speaking _ her polar opposite. ``They are such an
unusual combination that the chemistry was just explosively
funny,'' says ``Town and Country'''s producer, Simon Fields.
``Garry's very understated and self-deprecating, and Goldie's very
big and very funny. You don't often get to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Hawn's happiness so unique in Hollywood is that it
wasn't born yesterday. She is not the celebrity
ex-junkie/sexaholic/overeater who just last week found the
kaballah/community service/low-carb diet that changed her life.
This is the way she has always been _ though it continues to
surprise even her. ``It's kind of amazing, really,'' she has said.
``My kids look at me and say, 'Mom, you're so happy!' And I do feel
happy. I feel joyful inside. I can't explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what makes Hawn's joy so integral to her is that it's
based on a lifetime of self-examination and re-examination _ of
learning from her mistakes, of relying on her strong sense of
family. Perhaps it's even biological. ``I came in this way, but
now, as I get older, I'm trying to figure out where it really comes
from,'' she said. ``What is this tickle of joy that I have? Are you
born with it?''
</P>
<P>
   It's such a big subject for her that Hawn is planning to make a
film about it _ Joy: The Documentary. Here's how she pitches her
project: ``I want to know where joy lives. I'd interview
scientists, religious leaders and heads of state. I want to find
out exactly what it is that makes people happy. I want to look into
the biology, the chemistry of the human brain and find new ways to
access a level of happiness within us. A baby smiles something like
72 times a day. Where does that smile go? That's what I really want
to know.''
</P>
<P>
   So, ask what makes and keeps Goldie Hawn happy, and you don't
have to worry that she's going to give you a ``buying a new pair of
mules'' answer. The foundations of her contentment are far more
substantial. Her philosophy: ``There are ways to sustain joy inside
of you.'' And here they are.
</P>
<P>
   1. LIVE IN REALITY
</P>
<P>
   Probably the toughest thing about being famous is fame. It tends
to screw up everything _ especially relationships with friends,
family, lovers. Somehow, Hawn has managed to avoid that trap. ``She
has handled her fame better than any actress I know,'' said Nancy
Meyers, who produced ``Private Benjamin'' with Hawn. ``I've seen a
lot of people go wacky. She doesn't hide from it, and it doesn't
distort her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawn credits her father with teaching her to stay grounded. ``He
told me that the minute you lose reality, you lose everything,''
she said. ``I'm a very practical person, and as I got older, I
stayed realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Being realistic keeps her sane _ in business, in love, in life.
``I've learned,'' she's said, ``that if you are giving all you can
and it still doesn't make a difference, you must give up control
over others. The only person you can control in the whole universe
is yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawn is probably questioned more about the longevity of her
happily unmarried relationship with actor Kurt Russell (17 years
this past Valentine's Day) than about the longevity of her career.
Yet she is always quite frank about the fact that she prefers to
wake up each day and make the choice to be in that relationship and
understand that it only has a certain life span, whatever that may
be.
</P>
<P>
   That said, she also thinks we tend to give up on relationships
too quickly. ``Really be clear that the grass is not always
greener,'' she said. ``We have a tendency to think, Oh, if I could
just be over there, wouldn't it be fun. But the truth is you're
just ... grasping for some answers, and the answers are in your
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   2. GET YOUR PRIORITIES STRAIGHT
</P>
<P>
   When Hawn made ``The First Wives Club'' in 1996, she was facing
the big 5-0. The film gave her a chance to poke fun at her own
ingenue image before Hollywood did it for her. And when she made
``The Out-of-Towners'' three years later, she was facing the same
empty-nest syndrome issues as her character.
</P>
<P>
   Three of her four children (Oliver Hudson, 24, Kate Hudson, 20,
and Russell's son, Boston, 19) had, by that time, all moved away
from home.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her career, Hawn's work has reflected the issues
she's facing in her personal life. But her personal life has always
been her priority.
</P>
<P>
   Twice during her career, Hawn chose not to work at all for more
than two years at a stretch _ when Wyatt was born in 1986 and when
her mother became terminally ill in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was a big part of my life,'' she said, ``and it was
a joy to be able to take care of her till the end. I've made
choices not to work, choices not to go out of town, choices in
terms of my priorities ... but there's nothing I would call a
sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   3. PAY ATTENTION TO WHAT YOU LOVE
</P>
<P>
   Among Hawn's top priorities these days is spending more time
alone with Russell just ``playing.'' ``When we find we're not
playing together,'' she's said, ``we drop everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawn is mindful about taking care of the important people in her
life. ``Like not losing the wish to make love. I think that's very
important .... And sometimes you just don't feel like it. But when
you do, afterward you feel great I think it's important that we
honor each other with tenderness and attention. We have a tendency
not to see each other after a while. But you have pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawn is convinced that the world-weary look see in some people's
eyes comes from the fact that they've stopped paying attention to
the world. They're forgetting to notice things because they're
jaded _ they've been there, done that. Hawn's solution: ``We can
train ourselves to look with wonder at that tree. I know it's a
cliche, but it works.''
</P>
<P>
   4. SEEK OUT QUIET
</P>
<P>
   Hawn, who was raised Jewish (``All I ever wanted was to marry a
Jewish dentist''), is now a practicing Buddhist who's been
meditating for years. ``I try to meditate 20 minutes a day.''
</P>
<P>
   For women, whom she believes often get stuck with the lion's
share of caretaking responsibilities, this completely private time
is crucial. ``I think mothers have to work on nurturing themselves
first,'' she said. ``When a woman feels happy inside, she can give
her children a more optimistic feeling about life.''
</P>
<P>
   5. KEEP CHALLENGING YOURSELF
</P>
<P>
   So what's next? Hawn is working on the script for ``Ashes to
Ashes,'' a movie about a woman who goes to India to carry out her
late husband's dying wish. Then of course there's her search for
joy _ the documentary. But that's all very short-term. Where does
she see her life going? What path will she follow?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the focus is ... who I want to be at 60, at 70, at 80,''
she said. ``I want to move in a fashion that helps me through the
transition of letting go of motherhood and moving into my
womanhood. Using my feminine power, my feminine energy to continue
to express myself. To teach and learn and accomplish things.''
</P>
<P>
   The message is that you can't be happy if you're bored. ``Ask
those questions,'' she said. ``Challenge yourself, face your fears,
all the things we think we can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hawn isn't happy all the time. Let's just say that
she's a student of happiness _ with a wall full of diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   (Juliann Garey is a contributing editor to ``Redbook''
magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
