<HEADER>
A8415 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      06-19 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSS-BORDER POLLUTION HITS MEXICAN TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ ``Man by Day, Woman by Night.'' ``Size Does
Matter.'' ``I Don't Want My Son to Marry the Housekeeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Topics from the best of Jerry Springer? How about ``Cosas de la
Vida (Things of Life)''?
</P>
<P>
   Trash TV has come south of the border, and it's causing a stir
in this conservative, class-conscious society.
</P>
<P>
   Three new talk shows, all produced by Mexico's two major
television networks and broadcast nationally, have debuted over the
last few months to a mix of criticism and through-the-roof ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absurd what they show on those programs,'' said Esteban
Castillo, 30, a mechanic who admits to having clicked on a few
episodes. ``The people are always yelling and fighting. But it's
fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk shows are an extraordinary leap in a country bound by
religious and cultural traditions; where people prefer to keep
their dirty laundry home rather than hang it out before millions of
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why the shows' producers often have to troll
the streets to find participants, luring them with the promise of
appearing on national television, a chance to see a real TV studio,
a free makeover, and a gratuity of up to 300 pesos, about 10 times
the average daily wage.
</P>
<P>
   Once on stage, the panelists engage in an hour of constant
bickering, insults, reprimands, and even brief fistfights that are
quickly ended by broad-shouldered bodyguards in tight T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   But even in their brief, scandalous existence, these shows have
broached subjects questioning seldom-discussed issues here:
extramarital affairs, domestic violence, interclass relationships,
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is a closed and conservative society like so much of
Latin America, but this show helps give people a chance to express
themselves,'' said Roberto Romagnoli, the 25-year-old producer of
``Cosas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We deal with the same daily issues that people face in their
lives, and that's what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   These are not the first shows of this genre to be broadcast in
Mexico, but ``Cosas,'' ``Hastaen las Mejores Familias (Even in the
Best Families)?'' and ``Martha Susana'' are the first to be made in
Mexico, featuring nationally known hosts and guests who might as
well be neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some warn that these new US-influenced shows are just
another bad influence from the north that could have a corrosive
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a culture lacking in ethics that damages
people's integrity,'' said Xavier Esteinou, a communications
professor at Mexico's National Autonomous University, in the
newspaper Reforma. ``The issues are presented in a coarse way,
lacking creativity, with an end to generate high ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   The shows' producers agree _ at least about the ratings part.
</P>
<P>
   All three new programs have been gold mines for their networks.
``Cosas'' has broken ratings records for TV Azteca, second only to
``Hasta,'' which airs on Televisa.
</P>
<P>
   Both programs are on at 4 p.m. in Mexico City, during the
traditional lunch hour when children and parents are usually at
home.
</P>
<P>
   On one recent Thursday, both shows drew higher ratings than a
championship soccer match.
</P>
<P>
   Romagnoli has only two concerns about his show's future: that he
continue to find interesting panelists and that the authorities
don't get too upset over what he airs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had other shows at this network stopped because of
pressure from the government or because they were too aggressive,''
he added with a chuckle. ``I hope they don't do that to us. Maybe
they'll see that we're also doing something good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Chacon is chief of the Globe's Latin America bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
