<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8421 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RADCLIFFE-FAUST-ART-B     06-19 1635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADCLIFFE-FAUST-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 DREW GILPIN FAUST: A WOMAN FOR THE CIVIL WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the steakhouse and the locker room, the Civil War remains
one of the great male redoubts in our culture.
</P>
<P>
   For an incoherent tangle of reasons, American men continue to
read and write about it, reenact and imagine it, in ways that
sanctify and separate it from all other conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   It is a rare woman who is drawn to the patriotic gore of the
Civil War. But then Drew Gilpin Faust was not your average girl
growing up in Clarke County, Va., home to the state's clarion
segregationist, Harry Byrd. As children, Drew played Grant to her
older brother's Lee. As an adult, she plumbed the shadow between
the moral rectitude of the adults there and the bite of their
racism.
</P>
<P>
   Conflict seduced her early. While at Bryn Mawr, she raised hell
from Selma to Washington, D.C., in the civil rights and antiwar
movements. Still with her is Michael Herr's line from his book
``Dispatches'': ``I think Vietnam was what we had instead of happy
childhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the incoming dean of the Radcliffe Institute For Advanced
Study is in the vanguard of a small band of women who are Civil War
scholars of standing. Rarer still, Faust is fascinated by war's
violent death.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can be more interesting than trying to figure out what
made people kill each other?'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   For her next book, Faust, 52, departs from an impressive oeuvre
of Southern social history and heads into the very maw of war as
she examines the effects of massive death on the North and South.
The Civil War scholar from the University of Pennsylvania considers
the carnage that left more than 600,000 dead to have been the most
significant aspect of the great moral and geopolitical fight. And
while that point may appear obvious, she says it has been never
been addressed frontally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a struggle to digest that death,'' Faust says.
``Americans in the North and South were faced with the possibility
of death's meaninglessness. They got the notion for the first time
that God was more distant, more inscrutable. This death laid the
foundations of modern sensibilities like irony and doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Men and women on both sides struggled as never before with the
haunting questions of theodicy _ the tension between a just, loving
God and the presence of evil. As the war wore on, they increasingly
asked how such a power could countenance such a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were battles where you could walk for a mile on bodies
without touching the ground,'' Faust says. ``This raises the
question of how the Civil War generation responded to that level of
slaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Irony is noticeably absent in huge chunks of popular Civil War
culture today. Men eagerly reenact the killing in anodyne
pageantry. During a break in the filming of ``Gettysburg,'' a bunch
of Confederate extras actually stood up and cheered as the actor
Martin Sheen, dressed as Robert E. Lee, rode by.
</P>
<P>
   The death project grew from Faust's 1996 award-winning book
examining how white Southern women fared during the Civil War in
the absence of the men who both idolized and subjugated them in the
antebellum South. She chose for a title what Frank Zappa had named
his band: ``Mothers of Invention'' (subtitled ``Women of the
Slaveholding South in the American Civil War'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I got interested listening to the voices of the women in
`Mothers of Invention' and wondered why hasn't anyone written about
death,'' Faust says. ``I saw it as a gender issue. Women think
about death as the first outcome of war. They are so often the
designated mourners.''
</P>
<P>
   The women in her book also rekindled the unsettling feelings
Faust felt in her youth as she pondered what it meant to be a white
Southerner. ``I was torn between empathy, sympathy, and horror,''
she says of these women, whose letters to their husbands were
marbled with poignancy and jarring racism.
</P>
<P>
   Faust's intellectual curiosity spread like an oil slick from
Southern social history to the carnage itself. As a professional
historian, her path toward the meaning of death in the Civil War
appears inevitable. It raises the question of why there aren't more
women like her, populating the male world of Civil War history.
</P>
<P>
   Some specialists argue that over the years male Civil War
historians have simply denied women entrance to the ranks.
Elizabeth Leonard, a Civil War historian who teaches at Colby
College, recalls the dyspeptic reaction by a male historian to an
address she gave about women nurses during the Civil War at a
history conference in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stood up and dressed me down,'' Leonard recalls. ``He was
saying, `This is not your place.' To be fair, this was the only
case like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Others maintain that women have never been interested in the
battlefield because they have never had to fight. So what happened
at Antietam is foreign to them. Still others wonder if women are
emotionally less comfortable confronting violent death than men.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear: Until recently, there were hardly any women
Civil War historians. ``There were very, very few in 1980,'' Faust
says. But since then, she has seen a dramatic increase. Adds
William McFeely, the Pulitzer Prize-winning biographer of Grant,
``I was astonished teaching at the University of Georgia at the
number of women interested in the Civil War.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything is relative. While the volume of entrants into the
field has grown by scores, Faust puts the number of top women at
about a dozen. In this elite cadre, she mentions Catherine Clinton,
Nina Silber, Carol Reardon, LeeAnn Whites, and Leonard. Of this
group, only Reardon is a military historian.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the women studying the Civil War still steer clear of
the bloodshed, notes James McPherson, the Civil War historian at
Princeton whose history ``The Battle Cry of Freedom'' won the
Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armies and tactics for the most part don't attract women
scholars at all,'' McPherson says. ``Most of them write around the
edges. They are interested in social history or slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Reardon, who teaches at Penn State, is the obvious exception.
She has just finished a year at West Point teaching, among other
things, the art of war. She recalls being chastised by feminist
colleagues merely for choosing to pursue military history.
</P>
<P>
   ``One told me that I'd sold out to the patriarchy,'' Reardon
recalls. ``I laughed. Then she wanted me to focus on women in
military history. I told her I'm not going to write about Joan of
Arc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is not why there are so few women military
historians, but why there are so few military historians in
general,'' she continues. ``This is not a gender thing. It's the
whole field. A lot of it has to do with Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Older military historians who rose to prominence in the 1950s
and '60s have retired, says Reardon, while younger ones who came of
age in the '60s pursued other branches of history because of their
antiwar sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard finds another reason for the absence of women in the
military field: an overtly contrarian strain to skirt the
traditional. ``So much of what feminist history is about is
rejecting the standard notion of history and trying very explicitly
not to look at what everyone else has always looked at,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Civil War history as we know it is changing.
If the wall between military and social history is falling, however
slowly, in favor of a more coherent look at both aspects of the
conflict, women like Faust deserve credit. ``Her work has never
been gendered in the narrow sense,'' says McFeely. ``She is a
historian's historian with a no-nonsense, acute mind.''
</P>
<P>
   This shift will challenge both male militarists and orthodox
feminists to think wider. ``Keeping them separate diminishes the
power of both,'' says Faust of the two disciplines. ``We'll have
more women looking at all of these questions, breaking down the
boundaries between `I do military history' and `I do social
history.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Weber is a case in point. Weber, 37, a former reporter
for the Sacramento (Calif.) Bee, is McPherson's lone female
doctoral candidate in Civil War history. She exemplifies the new
generation of female Civil War historian bent on understanding all
facets of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Within the military sphere, Weber focuses on Fredericksburg, the
Virginia battle in late 1862 where Lee's forces slaughtered
poorly-led Union troops. Her dissertation examines the civilian
will of both sides to continue the war in the face of such horrific
losses. To address this subject competently, she notes, ``You have
to know the battles.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber is hesitant even to talk openly about why women eschew
military history, in part out of fear that some of her thoughts
will ignite feminists. Still, she wonders out loud, ``Is life more
precious to women? Are women less comfortable with these losses
than men? They're the mothers, after all. I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Faust, who will assume her duties at the Radcliffe Institute on
Jan. 1, dismisses emotional differences of gender and cites instead
the male clubbiness among Civil War historians that women have long
found hostile. More important, she adds, women scholars have
avoided military history because, ironically, it has been held in
lower regard within the academic community and considered a tougher
route to a successful career.
</P>
<P>
   Weber is unfazed. ``I know hardly any women interested in
military history,'' she says. ``But I am interested in good
stories, and this is the best story in American history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
