<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8422 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FUHRMAN-SKAKEL-BOS &LR;      06-19 1838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUHRMAN-SKAKEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUHRMAN TAKES THE GLOVES OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDPOINT, Idaho _ Nestled in a pine-filled valley between the
rugged Bitterroot Mountains and a snow-capped column of smaller
peaks, Mark Fuhrman can nearly see Ruby Ridge from his isolated
ranch.
</P>
<P>
   If this is Elba for the former cop whose racist invective helped
free O. J. Simpson, many believe it's a fitting exile among the
scattered network of white supremacists and neo-Nazis drawn to the
wilds of northern Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   For Fuhrman, the past is always present in a pilloried American
life that is a fascinating example of uncommon resilience, rather
than redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman bristles at the suggestion that he feels a kinship with
the Aryan Nations, located in nearby Hayden Lake, or to Ruby Ridge,
where separatist Randy Weaver's wife and son were killed in a
standoff with federal marshals in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But he also concedes that he is nearly powerless to alter his
image as a national symbol of bigotry and rogue police work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the carcass that the ravens come down and pick on,''
Fuhrman said recently, in his first extensive interview in years.
``Most people bury their dead, don't they?''
</P>
<P>
   If not, most try to keep the corpses out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, when Michael Skakel, a Kennedy cousin, appears at a
probable-cause hearing in the 1975 murder of Martha Moxley, the man
who is widely credited with reinvigorating that long-dormant case
is not expected within 2,000 miles of the Stamford, Conn.,
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   After protests by ABC News staff, Fuhrman was dropped by ``Good
Morning America'' as a paid consultant during the case. So, as the
national media revisit the slaying, the author of ``Murder in
Greenwich,'' a best-selling book that named Skakel the likely
killer, will be watching instead from his 20-acre mountain ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman says he enjoys the seclusion, but in a three-hour
interview he also spoke about the drawbacks of a life consigned to
the fringes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer to just be the Mark Fuhrman before June 13, 1994,''
he said, referring to the day when Simpson was arrested for murder.
``But that's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Impossible because, although Fuhrman is praised by the Moxley
family as a person and detective, millions of people share the view
of Alan Dershowitz, one of the Dream Team attorneys who represented
Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a man who harbors the most primitive racist views,''
Dershowitz says. ``He has returned to the guise of a smiling,
gentle, misunderstood man. But he's a virulent racist, sexist, and
anti-Semite who is the most dangerous kind because people like
him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moxley's impressions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dorthy Moxley, the mother of Martha Moxley, counts herself among
those who like Fuhrman. ``I was impressed with him,'' she says.
``He was very articulate and very smart. I think the world and all
of Mark Fuhrman. He just couldn't be nicer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Moxley says that Fuhrman's book, while helpful, was not the
pivotal element that led to murder charges against Skakel. The case
has been a group effort, she says, and much of the credit should go
to Fairfield County State's Attorney Jonathan C. Benedict, who she
says scrupulously reexamined the evidence and requested an
investigative grand jury in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman, however, said in the interview that staff from
Benedict's office told him they planned to use ``Murder in
Greenwich'' as an outline for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   To his critics, such a statement is one more suspected example
of the embellishments, and worse, that have been linked to the
Fuhrman persona.
</P>
<P>
   The most notorious statements, the racist rantings that he
committed to tape and replayed years later during the Simpson
trial, continue to shadow Fuhrman. But now, removed to the
mountains, Fuhrman has found a life that is lonelier but more
lucrative than the adrenaline-pumping career he pursued on the
streets of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old is at work on ``Murder in Spokane,'' a book
about a serial killer. The book follows the success of ``Murder in
Brentwood'' and ``Murder in Greenwich.'' Fuhrman also is the host
of a weekly radio call-in show in Spokane, Wash., about 80 miles
from his Idaho ranch. The show allows him to air his unambiguous
opinions on American crime, morals, race, and _ inevitably _ O. J.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman _ tall, relaxed, lean, and muscular _ says he is content
with the domestic routines he has fashioned with his third wife and
two children. ``Living in Idaho is very peaceful. Hunting, fishing,
raising horses,'' he said, looking out a hotel window in Spokane
before heading to the radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman projects an image of the Marlboro Man at peace, but a
lingering anger appears to smolder just below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   To Fuhrman's thinking, the culture that made him a pariah _ a
society once honorable, self-sacrificing, and admirable _ has been
polluted by political correctness and ethnic pandering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On racial profiling, quotas
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Racial profiling is a myth, he says. Affirmative action can lead
to dangerously low professional standards. And perhaps sports
stars, who in increasing numbers commit crimes, have a gene that
predisposes them to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you right now, there's no such thing as racial
profiling. . . . I'm really sorry, guys, but the very people who
are committing the crimes are creating the racial profile,''
Fuhrman says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tell a policeman that he can't even react to a certain
crime because someone is a certain color, all you'll have is a
policeman who rolls up his window and puts on his Walkman.''
</P>
<P>
   On affirmative action, Fuhrman says that more recruiting should
be done in minority neighborhoods. But he scoffs at the notion of
quotas, and links efforts to increase racial and gender diversity
at the Los Angeles Police Department to relaxed physical
requirements at the academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should get qualified people of all races to be great cops
and detectives, but maybe they don't want to,'' Fuhrman said.
</P>
<P>
   Such outspokenness has attracted a loyal and growing audience on
his radio call-in show. Called ``All About Crime,'' the Thursday
program is the station's highest-rated show in the 2 to 4 p.m.
slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like in the NFL, we have some really terrible,
terrible behavior _ like murder,'' Fuhrman said on a recent show.
Later, he asked his listeners whether the American sports culture
might be breeding criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The brass at KXLY-AM in Spokane like the Fuhrman phenomenon so
much that they are considering adding a second show during the
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to talking about crime on radio, Mark is one of
the most qualified anywhere,'' said Mike Fitzsimmons, the regular
talk-show host who plays second fiddle to Fuhrman on Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman's notoriety, far from being a disadvantage, has become a
reason for tuning in, says Jim Bickel, the station's program
director. Bickel even jokes about the Simpson defense allegation
that Fuhrman manufactured physical evidence. ``Do you know how
Mark's neighbors know it's spring? Because he's out in the garden
planting gloves,'' Bickel said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Joking aside, Fuhrman's life changed irrevocably after he lied
under oath about whether he had used racial epithets or bragged
about beating minorities. And although Fuhrman notes that he
retired from the force in 1995 on the 20th anniversary of his hire
_ a common practice that allows him to collect an estimated $25,000
annual pension _ it is widely believed that he was pressured to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman then moved to Sandpoint, a small-town mecca for artists
where city leaders tout a focus more akin to Greenwich Village than
the interests of a small group of vocal hatemongers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have militia walking down the street. We wouldn't
tolerate them,'' Fuhrman said.
</P>
<P>
   But a racial separatist ran for mayor last year, prompting a
tough counter-campaign by human rights groups and financial
resources from Coldwater Creek, a mail-order clothing business that
is the largest private employer in north Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `There's no vindication'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The supremacist, who lost, had flooded mailboxes in the past
with what a Coldwater Creek spokesman, David Gunter, called a
``convoluted'' and ``hate-based'' message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly is not very focused, and it is anything but
representative of the Sandpoint area and north Idaho as a whole,''
Gunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Like misperceptions of Sandpoint, Fuhrman says, he also
considers himself unfairly demonized. Fuhrman lays much of the
blame on a news media he calls more interested in political
correctness than whether the tapes that unveiled him as a perjurer
reveal his true character.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman insists his work on the Moxley murder was not an attempt
at rehabilitation. ``I can never do anything that would vindicate
anything I did in the Simpson case. There's no vindication to take
away the words I used,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if people are going to call me a racist solely because of
the Simpson case, it's absurd. If that's all they think and they've
done no reading either way, they got the opinion that Johnnie
Cochran wanted them to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Cochran, Simpson's lead defense lawyer, once branded Fuhrman a
``lying, perjuring, genocidal racist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I am,'' Fuhrman said. ``I'd say to Mr. Cochran:
`What have you done for your race? I spent 20 years protecting
them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fuhrman acknowledges he made a colossal mistake when he
told a Simpson lawyer, F. Lee Bailey, that he had not used racial
slurs. ``I was dancing as fast as I could,'' Fuhrman said. ``I had
32 million people watching me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman insists that his taped racist remarks were role-playing,
prompted by an aspiring screenwriter who also asked him to imitate
a ``good'' cop, ``dumb'' cop, and other variations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was absolutely absent of relevance,'' Fuhrman said of the
tape, although he concedes that it was ``irresponsible'' for him to
have made the comments. ``My life changed, and it changed for all
the wrong reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz disagrees with Fuhrman's assessment. Far from being
mere role-playing, Dershowitz says, the tape corroborated the
racist sentiments that others had heard from Fuhrman.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fuhrman denied knowing her, a real estate agent
testified in the Simpson trial that Fuhrman told her all blacks
should be incinerated, and that he would pull over interracial
couples and fabricate evidence against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a horrible man,'' Dershowitz says, ``and no one should
give him any credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Fuhrman concludes, he has managed to insulate his 7- and
9-year-old children, a girl and a boy, from these kinds of
comments.
</P>
<P>
   But the time will come when they will ask what he did to be so
hated. Then, Fuhrman says, he will reply: ``Dad made some mistakes.
Don't make them.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, and adds, ``But Dad was a good detective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
