<SLUG> BC-ROOTBEER-COMEBACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOT BEER REGAINING ITS FIZZ AFTER YEARS OF FLAT SALES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON DICKSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE, Texas _ Rich, frothy, sweet, spicy and creamy.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply rooted in American history. A favorite beverage of
nostalgia buffs.
</P>
<P>
   Root beer appears to be making a big comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurateurs, retailers and soda jerks in Dallas-Fort Worth are
reporting renewed interest in the carbonated concoction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lady in here who saw our sign from an airplane window
and drove straight here from D/FW Airport,'' said Keith Chauhan,
manager of an A&AMP;W All American Food restaurant that opened this
year in Grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   An A&AMP;W restaurant has opened in Dallas, and one is being built
at Harwood Road and Grapevine Highway in North Richland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Root beer aficionados prefer it from the tap and in a frosty
mug, Chauhan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people bring their kids in here,'' he said. ``They
want their root beer in a frosty mug. You don't mix ice with it
because that spoils the taste.''
</P>
<P>
   At Plano-based Dr Pepper/Seven-Up, which makes three of the
nation's top-selling root beers _ A&AMP;W, Hires and IBC _ year-to-date
sales of root beer have increased 6 percent, spokeswoman Emily
Livingston said.
</P>
<P>
   That is remarkable considering that overall sales of carbonated
beverages have increased less than 1 percent during the same time,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just available in more places now,'' Livingston said.
``The increased availability is reminding people how much they like
it. These brands have a lot of history.''
</P>
<P>
   The modern beverage can be traced to the 1870s. Early root beer
makers experimented with various ingredients, including herbs,
wintergreen, juniper and sassafras extract.
</P>
<P>
   Root beer has been popular for much of the 20th century.
Teetotalers touted it as a temperance alternative to alcoholic
beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Because most root beer has little or no caffeine, some consider
it a healthier alternative to other soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   But through the years, mega-colas such as Coca-Cola and Pepsi
seized much of the soft drink market. Despite figures that show
growth in root beer sales, it has less than 3 percent of the soft
drink market share.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those who love the foamy drink are fiercely loyal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just tastes a lot better than the others,'' said Saginaw
resident Martin Cantu, an airplane mechanic at Kitty Hawk in
Grapevine who tipped back a frosty mug during a recent lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I like it a lot. It's just a lot different taste.
It doesn't have the carbonation that Coke does. It's a different
taste that is almost addicting. Once you've had it, you've got to
have it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Stanford of Colleyville treated his nieces and nephews _
Elizabeth Hammon, 7, Rebecca Hammon, 5, and Jacob Pruett, 10 _ to
cold mugs of root beer on a recent afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's making a comeback. It never left us,''
Stanford said. ``We drink it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   At Main Street Barber Shop in Grapevine, which sells sodas made
with sugar (no corn syrup allowed) in 1950s-style bottles,
customers drink almost as much Frostie Root Beer as they do Dr
Pepper, co-owner Al Gonzales said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Grapevine's newest restaurants, Big Buck Brewery and
Steakhouse, plans to sell homemade root beer on tap and in bottles,
an official said. The restaurant is expected to open about Labor
Day.
</P>
<P>
   At the company's three Michigan restaurants, root beer is second
to Coca-Cola in sales, Big Buck President William Rolinski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got hit this weekend at our store in Gaylord, Mich. One
gentleman bought 32 cases of it,'' he said. ``Ours is very sweet,
and it's got a light froth. We use beet sugar in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Young people often are reluctant to order root beer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people have an aversion to root beer, but the parents
say, `Son, you've got to taste this.' Then their eyes light up,''
he said. ``We're trying to find those old flavors that people
remember when they were kids.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
