<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PRAYER (Washington) _ Strengthening the wall between
church and state, the Supreme Court rules that a Texas school
district violated the Constitution when it allowed students to hold
prayers before high school football games. In a 6-3 decision, the
court says that by granting students the right to use the school's
public address system at a school-sponsored event, the local board
of education gave preferential treatment to a particular religious
viewpoint. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-MYANMAR (Washington) _ The Supreme Court makes it harder
for states to refuse to buy from companies that do business with
nations known for human rights abuses. Saying states have no right
to make foreign policy, the justices unanimously invalidate a
Massachusetts law that limits state purchases from companies doing
business with Myanmar, also known as Burma. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-SAFETY (Washington) _ With the start of summer, a group of
lawmakers and safety advocates are warning that the highways could
become more hazardous if a new federal proposal goes into effect
allowing truckers to drive 12 straight hours before taking a break.
Currently, U.S. Department of Transportation rules limit truck
drivers to 10 consecutive hours behind the wheel. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Scrub Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson as a potential running mate for Vice President Al Gore.
The Republican call for his resignation over the Los Alamos nuclear
lab security flap goes too far. But since another security lapse
has happened on his watch he is now tarnished and the Republicans
will gnaw at this like a dog with a bone. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
