<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-KRANZ-BOS &LR;      06-19 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-KRANZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VIEW FROM THE CONSOLES AT MISSION CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
FAILURE IS NOT AN OPTION 
Mission Control from Mercury to Apollo 13 and Beyond 
By Gene Kranz. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 320 pp. Illustrated. $26. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a pep talk for the ages. Gene Kranz, flight director for
the stricken Apollo 13 spacecraft, gathered NASA controllers around
him and told them:
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, listen up. When you leave this room, you must leave
believing that this crew is coming home. I don't give a damn about
the odds, and I don't give a damn that we've never done anything
like this before. Flight control will never lose an American in
space. You've got to believe, your people have got to believe, that
this crew is coming home. Now let's get going.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the ultimate space-age crisis of the years before the
Challenger disaster, the moment when Houston really had a problem.
But the crew of Apollo 13 persevered and prevailed, and Kranz and
his controllers brought the men home. It is the story of America: a
can-do attitude, an ideology of daring, a challenge met with
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Now Kranz, who joined the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration in 1960, and was assistant flight director for
Project Mercury and flight director for the first lunar landing,
has written a memoir of an era and an idea that are fast receding
into the mists but that, in many ways, represented the best of us _
and the best use of our idealism and our instinctive fascination
with machines.
</P>
<P>
   In these pages are none of the racy revelations that Tom Wolfe
brought to his story of the men who had the right stuff. Nor are
there particularly searching or revealing portraits of the
astronauts we met in the pages of Life magazine and on
black-and-white television sets. No matter. Kranz has provided a
workmanlike chronicle of America's reach into space _ and a flight
controller's view of the drama inherent in sitting behind a console
trying to figure out whether a launch should occur, whether a
mission would continue, whether lives could be saved. Besides the
D-Day crossing from Britain to Omaha Beach, this might have been
the most important American journey of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Also the most exciting. Recently the return into space of John
H. Glenn Jr., the stoic commander of Friendship 7, transported a
riveted nation back to 1962, when Cold War tensions prevailed and
when a fragile Atlas booster _ ``a pressurized metal balloon,'' as
Kranz calls it _ was America's ladder out of earth's atmosphere.
Kranz reminds us of the improbability of it all, and of the
innocence that accompanied that improbability. ``It was difficult
at such times to maintain my focus,'' he writes. ``I felt a strong
urge to yell out, `We've got an American in orbit!' '' We all felt
that way.
</P>
<P>
   Through these pages stroll _ streak would be a better word _
such figures as Alan B. Shepard, Gus Grissom, M. Scott Carpenter,
Wally Schirra, L. Gordon Cooper, Donald Slayton. They were the
flyboys of space. They travelled into space alone, but _ and this
may have been their most enduring, endearing attribute _ they never
forgot that they were not really alone. We were all behind them,
watching, hoping, praying. But Kranz and his colleagues were behind
them, doing back-of-the-envelope calculations to figure out, for
example, whether to leave Glenn's retrorockets on his capsule to
keep a pesky heat shield in space, or how to bring Carpenter back
to earth after he fell behind in his flight plan. ``Once again,''
Kranz writes of the Carpenter episode, ``we were lucky _ but luck
has no place in space flight.''
</P>
<P>
   No place, maybe, but it sure did play a role. There was luck
coursing through the entire enterprise, and some of the luck was
having controllers like Kranz at the other end of a communications
link that was so precarious that it looks positively primitive to
our eyes here in the first breath of the 21st century. For all the
emphasis on astronaut training in the cult of space, so much of it
was, literally, flying by the seat of the astronauts' and
controllers' pants. The plan for the first American spacewalk,
performed by Gemini 4 astronaut Ed White, was stitched together by
Kranz in what can only be called a rush job.
</P>
<P>
   This was, to be sure, experimental science, and no one involved
in it ever thought otherwise. There was care, there was attention
to detail, but mostly space flight, especially in the early days,
involved risk. Most of the time the risks paid off. Sometimes they
did not, and the results were tragic. Kranz doesn't say that
explicitly, but his words to his fellow controllers in the wake of
the accident that killed three Apollo astronauts on the launchpad
in January 1967 are vivid enough:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the cause! We were not ready! We did not do our job! We
were rolling the dice, hoping that things would come together by
launch day, when in our hearts we knew it would take a miracle. We
were pushing the schedule. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   There was risk every day, every mission, from Shepard's brief
brush with space in his Mercury capsule to Apollo 13's terrifying
brush with death in its aborted mission to the moon. The hard
thing, about the missions and about the challenge of managing risk,
was the distances involved _ the distance between Cape Canaveral
and the moon, for example, and the distance between earthbound
mission controllers and the poor souls risking their lives in
spacecraft built by the lowest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   So when an explosion imperiled the astronauts aboard Apollo 13,
Kranz and his controllers battled the limits of their knowledge,
experience, and expectations. ``The frustration of the crew and
controllers was starting to creep into their voices,'' he writes.
``Everything we knew about our spacecraft, all that we had learned
about the design, precluded the kind of massive failures we were
seeing.'' Even so, it was indisputable that an oxygen tank had
exploded aboard the spacecraft 200,000 miles from the earth (and
45,000 miles from the surface of the moon) and that more than the
success of the mission was in danger.
</P>
<P>
   The controllers came up with a plan: Use the lunar module, which
was designed to land on the moon, as a lifeboat. Use the force of
lunar gravity to sling the crippled spacecraft around the back side
of the moon and back toward earth. Use duct tape where necessary
(yes, the astronauts were equipped with supplies of duct tape). Use
as little electrical power, water, and oxygen as possible. ``Crew
comfort was our last priority; they would have to tough it out,''
Kranz writes.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Kranz brought the men home, ending a mission in many
ways more dramatic than the first lunar landing itself. The success
in ending NASA's failure was a story of heroism and brains, but
mostly of the human spirit. ``We _ crew, contractors, controllers _
had done the impossible,'' Kranz writes. ``The human factor had
carried the day.'' His chronicle is the story of Mercury, Gemini,
and Apollo, and of the human factor that made them possible and
made them work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David M. Shribman is the Globe's Washington bureau chief. He
covered John Glenn's presidential campaign and his shuttle flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
