<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
 !!!  1/2 ``Boys and Girls'' A smart, witty college romance about a
cautious guy (Freddie Prinze Jr.) and a commitment-phobe (Claire
Forlani) edging from friendship into something more. Part of its
charm lies in its keen awareness of everything that can go wrong in
a relationship, part in its seductive settings (the Berkeley
campus, San Francisco, the Marin foothills), part in its ability to
convince us that these two could actually handle the academic load
at a good college. (PG-13) 
 
 !!!  ``Fantasia 2000'' Disney's new edition isn't going to retire
the studio's classic 1940 blend of animation and classical music.
It does reprise Mickey Mouse's ``Sorcerer's Apprentice'' sequence,
but the seven new segments mostly seem unremarkable. Two are
brilliant: Whales glide through a cool blue and green universe of
sea and sky to Respighi's ``Pines of Rome'' are hypnotizing, and
Hans Christian Anderson's ``Steadfast Tin Soldier'' is set to
Shostakovich at his liveliest. (G) 
 
 !!!  ``Love's Labour's Lost'' Kenneth Branagh takes a lesser
Shakespearean comedy and turns it into a '30s musical, with help
form Gershwin, Porter, Berlin, and Kern, and a diverse slate of
elegantly costumed actors more than willing to face the music and
dance. Although far from effortless, it's one of the more stylish
and winning pieces of time travel to which the Bard has been
subjected. (PG) 
 
(FL)  !!!  1/2 ``Shaft'' John Singleton's rejiggering of the
blaxploitation classic is cooler and grittier than the original,
and more explosive. Half the job is done simply by the casting of
Samuel L. Jackson _ the undisputed king of cool, and believably
dangerous _ as the new Shaft, a cop with a short fuse running a
vicious racist killer to ground. Richard Roundtree, the original
Shaft, climbs aboard as Shaft's uncle. (R) 
 
(FL)  !!  1/2 ``Titan A.E.'' This full-length animated sci-fi
ranges from ordinary to derivative (``Star Wars'') in its story of
a young hero charged with saving humankind from annihilating
aliens. But the computer-generated visuals from Don Bluth's studio
are terrific. The environments are fresh and imaginative; the
voicings by Matt Damon, Drew Barrymore, and Bill Pullman are
pluses, too. (PG)
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
