<HEADER>
A8435 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GROOVE-BOS &LR;      06-19 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GROOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKER HARRISON PUTS A HUMAN FACE ON THE TECHNO PARTY SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At its essence, it's all about the music.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you hear plenty about the kids who've blown their
wool-capped tops on Ecstasy, and get trippy from Vicks VapoRub
slathered inside surgical masks. But what gets lost in most
discussions of raves _ those massive dance gatherings _ is the
music, the thriving, driving lifeblood of the scene.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who has ever attended a rave, it ain't just a party.
It's a religious revival where the church is a warehouse, the
spirit blesses the crowd at 135 beats per minute, the DJ is a god,
and the altar is made up of two turntables, a mixer, and a milk
crate full of vinyl.
</P>
<P>
   It's a scene in which Greg Harrison immersed himself in San
Francisco in the mid '90s, which probably explains why his film
``Groove'' arrives in theaters Friday as the first movie to
convincingly capture the pulse of the rave, as well as the people
who find themselves while looking for the perfect beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in the scene are looking for a film to portray
their culture,'' said Harrison, who wrote and directed the film,
during a recent stopover in Boston with the film's producer
Danielle Renfrew, and one of its stars, Lola Glaudini.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want a film that takes them seriously,'' he said, ``and
there's a lot of subtlety and humanity in the scene which just gets
whitewashed by the mainstream media.''
</P>
<P>
   The film also stars Hamish Linklater, Denny Kirkwood, Mackenzie
Firgens, Jeff Witzke, Angelo Spizziri, Steve Van Wormer, Rachel
True, and some of the best DJs ever to lay hands on a turntable. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The moments of one night &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unfolding over a single night, ``Groove'' is less a linear story
than a series of moments. There's the ``break-in'' to secure an
abandoned warehouse as a rave site; the single e-mail message that
spreads the word among devotees; the difficulty in finding reliable
directions to the rave; and the various relationships among the
participants, especially David (Linklater), who is attending his
first rave, and Glaudini's character, the worldly-wise Leyla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was by no means a raver. I've been to raves, and been to
parties and DJ events,'' said Glaudini, who also has formal dance
training. ``I was probably investigating that scene in the early
1990s. I'm a total electronic-music head, and not a closet one. I
have a prolific collection of various DJs, and I follow their
careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those DJs, who receive title-card introductions, are the
true stars of ``Groove.'' Securing the skills of such beatmasters
as WishFM, Polywog, Forest Green, and Britain's legendary John
Digweed was a big part of Harrison's effort to make his film as
authentic as possible, but it wasn't his only bow to keepin' it
real. One of the most striking things about ``Groove'' is that its
dancers can actually dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everyone was plucked from the clubs,'' said
Renfrew, who first met Harrision through a mutual friend in the
rave scene. ``They're all ravers,'' Harrison said. ``The
underground scene came out in force to make the film.''
</P>
<P>
   With his background as a film editor, Harrison, 30, was eager to
make a film, and began toying with the idea of a movie about the
rave scene. Not only would such a film be possible financially, but
``dramatically and creatively, I felt the rave scene worked as a
film, only if I could capture the essential joy of the dance floor,
the music, and the scene,'' he said. ``I wanted to put a human face
on the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, Harrison argued, has been something the mainstream media
have neglected to do. They ignore that raves are often peaceful
events, without the violence that can mar other gatherings of
youth. They overlook that ravers are black, white, Latino, Asian,
straight, gay, lesbian. They neglect to mention that raves are less
about people's differences and more about what they share _ an
unbridled love of the music that moves them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What most people think of when they think of raves is a very
simplified view,'' Harrison said. ``There's never an exploration of
what the music means to people, or what the experience of the music
is on the dance floor, what their emotional experience is, or even
why people are drawn to take drugs in that environment.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The spin on drugs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While some aspects of the culture have seeped into the
mainstream through the music of such artists as Fatboy Slim, Moby,
Chemical Brothers, Air, and Groove Armada, what most folks know
about raves they learned from TV newsmagazines. Those stories
mostly concern drugs, whether it's law enforcement seizures of
Ecstasy or kids who OD'd on GHB, a synthetic hormone. Are drugs a
part of the scene? Absolutely, and in ``Groove,'' there is drug use
_ unapologetic, perhaps, but hardly glorified. This, however, did
not endear Harrison and Renfrew to potential investors when they
were shopping their film.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said the conversation was usually along the lines of,
`We're very interested in this youth-culture movie, we've been
looking for a rave script, but before you send it, we have to know
if anyone dies in it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, nobody dies in ``Groove.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted someone to die because then it would make it OK
that there's drug use,'' Renfrew said. ``They wanted more
consequences.'' Several other companies, she said, ``wanted to add
a gun'' or gang violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted simplified fake drama, superimposed onto a culture
they didn't understand,'' Harrison said. ``Translating the scene to
a film is very difficult because essentially the experience of a
rave is nonverbal, nonintellectual, visceral, emotional, and
internal to a certain degree. It's very hard to resist the
temptation to tack a false drama onto it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the music _ what ``Groove'' and the rave
scene are all about. It's not Vicks VapoRub, glow sticks,
pacifiers, or baggy clothes; the drama and the drug are in the
music, bathing everyone in a cocktail of light and sound, and
spinning them into a divine rapture as if it's the end of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a magnetic quality to it, almost like a
primal thing,'' Glaudini said. ``It's the bass line, the
repetition, the sequencing, the build. It's very seductive.''
</P>
<P>
   Without vocals or lyrics, the music ``avoids intellectual
interpretation,'' Harrison said. It's universal, allowing ``lots of
people from all walks of life, whether it's a banker or a kid from
the inner city, to access the same piece of music. It's rhythm, and
rhythm is outside linear thought, rational thinking, and structured
society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what creates the community around the music,'' Harrison
said. ``It's a scene based on openness, acceptance, creativity,
experimentation, and those are things people can relate to. It's
about being alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
