<HEADER>
A8437 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS &LR;      06-19 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Running Mate'' by Joe Klein (Dell, $26.95). Forget the
notoriety of Klein's first ``Anonymous'' political novel _ this one
proves once and for all that he knows Washington and knows how to
write. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Plowing the Dark'' by Richard Powers (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$25). Perhaps his best-executed story yet, crammed with erudition
and cutting-edge science but unmistakably human. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``From Dawn to Decadence'' by Jacques Barzun (HarperCollins,
$36). A magisterial survey of the West's past 500 years, as
readable as it is learned. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Papal Sin'' by Garry Wills (Doubleday, $25). Concentrating
mostly on the past century and a half, a Roman Catholic indicts the
``structure of deceit'' he sees in his church's confrontation with
modernity. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``MotherKind'' by Jayne Anne Phillips (Knopf, $24). This
thoughtful novel is a crash course in the essential mysteries of a
child's birth, a mother's death, and a woman's plight as she
negotiates between the two. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Mafiya'' by Robert I. Friedman (Little Brown, $25.95). An
investigative reporter doggedly documents how the Russian mob
landed on America's shores and is expanding its influence at a
rapid clip. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pastoralia'' by George Saunders (Riverhead, $22.95). A second
striking collection finds personal stories, and occasional grace,
in the schlocky sprawl of the American dream. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Human Stain'' by Philip Roth (Houghton Mifflin, $26). An
eloquently imagined American tragedy, with a good man undone by his
desire to be ``just on his own and free.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At End of Day'' by George V. Higgins (Harcourt, $24). Artful
and uncompromising, this final novel by the vernacular master tells
a story right out of the crime-news headlines. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anil's Ghost'' by Michael Ondaatje (Knopf, $25). The author of
``The English Patient'' sets up another collision of history and
imagination, in his native Sri Lanka. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``White Teeth'' by Zadie Smith (Random House, $24.95).
Incandescently inventive, insouciantly multicultural, this debut
novel shows off the new English and the new London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
