<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8438 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-FARRELL-BOS &LR;      06-19 1668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FARRELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EILEEN FARRELL STEPS INTO THE SPOTLIGHT ONCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eileen Farrell sang for the last time in 1995, closing an
unusual and glorious all-American career that had lasted since
1941, when she had her own weekly show on CBS Radio.
</P>
<P>
   The soprano was only 20 when network radio made her a national
figure _ at 24 her name appeared in the lyric of a Cole Porter
song, ``Big Town.''
</P>
<P>
   This year Farrell celebrated her 80th birthday, and despite some
health problems, she retains her spirit; she still talks about her
life in a spirit of celebration. Eight years ago, she told the
Globe she had ``no plans'' to write an autobiography. ``I've had a
lot of publicity in my life,'' she said, ``and what the public
doesn't know, I don't want them to know. I was married for 40 years
and had two kids, and what else is there to say?''
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, that summary omitted her half-century on
radio, television, the operatic stage, and the concert platform,
not to mention the long series of recordings documenting her art
and achievement as one of America's best pop singers.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, a longtime admirer, Brian Kellow, executive
editor of Opera News, convinced Farrell to work with him on
producing her autobiography, ``Can't Help Singing,'' which
Northeastern University Press published last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Now Farrell returns to an old stomping ground, Symphony Hall.
She was a great favorite of Arthur Fiedler's and made one of her
first recordings with the Boston Pops (``Solveig's Song'' from
Grieg's ``Peer Gynt''); later she was the star of one of the
all-time best ``Evening at Pops'' shows singing opera arias in one
part and pop songs in the other _ Harold Arlen's ``When the Sun
Comes Out'' really cut loose. In her book she admits that she loved
Arthur Fiedler dearly but ``I purposely avoided looking at him . .
. because if I had looked, I would have been lost around the first
bend.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell also recorded Wagner scenes with Charles Munch and the
Boston Symphony and sang a superb Act II of ``Tristan und Isolde''
with William Steinberg and the BSO. This week she will be there for
a special fund-raising dinner/-concert for the Longy School of
Music, which will present one of its first three lifetime
achievement awards to her, along with Pops associate conductor
laureate Harry Ellis Dickson and Rosebud C. Holland, for more than
three decades a beloved music teacher in the Boston public schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Upbeat despire illnes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farrell spoke over the phone from her home in New Jersey last
week sounding remarkably upbeat, considering what she's been
through lately. ``Just a year ago I had a quadruple bypass
operation, and then I got an infection in my leg, where they took
the veins out to put into my heart. So now I have to get around
with a walker and a wheelchair. Steps and I don't agree anymore, so
I try to stay home and take it easy. But I am going to come to
Boston and do a book signing as well as attend the Longy School
event! I was amazed at how many people showed up to see me when I
did a book signing at the Met.''
</P>
<P>
   `Well, I know I said I wouldn't ever write an autobiography. I
figured I'd been around so long that people would either know my
story or not be interested. And I didn't want to write the usual
kind of opera autobiography _ you know, the kind that's about how
great I was. I'll never forget trying to read the autobiography of
that tenor with the white hair, you know the one I mean, James
McCracken, and about the fourth or the fifth page he was telling
you how he realized he was the greatest living tenor. `Good for
you, buddy,' I thought. But who wants to read stuff like that?''
</P>
<P>
   As Farrell talks, her voice clears up and rings across state
lines; she probably doesn't really need the telephone. And she
hasn't gotten over her old habit of speaking her mind. In her book,
she remarks that when she met Thomas Schippers when he was 19 _ he
became America's golden boy of music in the 1950s and 1960s _ she
realized ``he'd never been five feet from (bunk) in his life.''
Confessing that she ``would have made a lousy diva,'' she admits a
sneaking admiration for people who could get away with it, like the
soprano Eleanor Steber, ``who carried it off like a one-egg cake
before breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An ordinary life
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farrell's book is unusual because she worked hard to keep her
life as ordinary as possible under the circumstances of her unusual
talent _ the one drawback of her book is that there's virtually
nothing in it about how hard she must have worked to learn all that
music, master all those styles, in so many languages. Born into an
Irish-Catholic family in Willimantic, Conn., she went to New York
straight out of high school, and it didn't take long before she had
won her place on the radio. She spent some of the prime years of
her career raising her family on Staten Island; her husband, Robert
Reagan, was a New York policeman, who posed in casual family photos
carrying his heater. She took the ferry to work _ in Carnegie Hall,
at the Met, and Avery Fisher Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Farrell could sing just about everything, and did. She toured
the hinterlands with the Bach Aria Group _ and sang Marie in
historic performances of Berg's ``Wozzeck'' with the New York
Philharmonic. She appeared with every important American orchestra
and became a favorite soloist of the two greatest American
conductors of her era, Thomas Schippers and Leonard Bernstein; she
sang at the opening night of Philharmonic Hall. She was not a
favorite of Rudolf Bing, the general manager of the Met, and her
book makes it abundantly clear he was not a favorite of hers. But
she did sing five of her operatic roles in 46 performances with the
company, and she did win one prestigious opening night.
</P>
<P>
   On the radio she had sung light classics and her first
recordings were mostly of operettas and Broadway shows. (``When
they couldn't get the original cast,'' she jokes, ``they called
me.'') The microphone loved her voice, although she found the
process of recording uncomfortable. ``The hardest thing,'' she
says, ``is that you had to be so quiet because every bit of noise
came through the microphone. It was very difficult making records,
but once they were done, I thought they were fine.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, she dubbed the soundtrack for a popular Hollywood
film, ``Interrupted Melody,'' the biography of the Australian
soprano Marjorie Lawrence who was struck down by polio at the
height of her career. Farrell wasn't given credit on screen, but
people demanded to know who it was; the soundtrack album was
finally reissued as ``The Art of Eileen Farrell.'' The album
contains the most gorgeous performance of ``Over the Rainbow'' ever
recorded. Farrell was happy to hear that her interviewer thinks so.
``Harold Arlen, who wrote that song, was a very close friend, and
later on I made a whole album of his songs with a trio. You have to
sing things the way you sing them, with your own voice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new career
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farrell began a whole new career in 1959 when Louis Armstrong
came down with pneumonia before a television performance from the
Spoleto Festival. Farrell, who was at the festival to sing the
Verdi Requiem, stepped in and sang ``The Sunny Side of the Street''
with Armstrong's band and became a pop star (``It had to be a song
I knew the words to,'' she recalls). Her first pop album, ``I've
Got a Right to Sing the Blues,'' made the charts, and she continued
to make beautiful albums from the Great American Songbook for the
next 35 years, moving easily into a new register, a new style, a
new vocal placement, while maintaining the same standards of
musicianship, phrasing, and diction she brought to her classical
singing. She spent her career singing what she wanted to sing, not
what others wanted her to, and the result was there never was
anyone like her.
</P>
<P>
   A robust sense of humor carried her through some great trials _
an unhappy teaching career at Indiana University; the agony of of
having a son fighting in Vietnam; the death of her husband. One of
her Indiana students told Farrell she was scared to death of her
because ``she used to be a star'' _ Farrell later wore a T-shirt
with those words emblazoned on it.
</P>
<P>
   The soprano enjoyed her first trips to the ``new'' Met in
Lincoln Center this season _ for 35 years she never saw the point
of going there. ``I must say that orchestra has improved so much I
can't believe it. And the intermission during the broadcast of
`Tristan und Isolde' was really wonderful. I had never met Birgit
Nilsson before. They asked her when she had first heard Miss
Farrell and she said she had heard me on the movie soundtrack. I
had to say that I was sorry that I had never heard her sing, and it
was so embarrassing, I thought I would die!'' (Nilsson, who is
about as tactful as Farrell, quipped, ``You really missed
something!'')
</P>
<P>
   Farrell still keeps in touch with some her musical friends, such
as Beverly Sills, and she still enjoys going out to hear cabarets.
``I love Wesla Whitfield, she is such a lovely girl, and her
diction is so good. We correspond.'' In her book Farrell laments
that there was no official tape of the joint concert she gave with
her friend, the legendary queen of cabaret, Mabel Mercer. ``But
after the book came out, two people sent tapes to me. That was such
a wonderful concert. I would sing and she would sing and then we
would sing together, and we had the words in a huge loose-leaf
notebook because she couldn't always remember what was coming next
_ and neither could I! Her words were in red and mine were in
blue.''
</P>
<P>
   And the soprano says she's looking forward to being driven up to
Boston. ``Other people are going to take care of all the details
and wheel me down the aisle. The only thing I have to remember is
to put my teeth in before I smile!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
