<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8439 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-PLOUGH-BOS &LR;      06-19 1884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-PLOUGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLOUGH AND THE MOVIE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ Leave it to Stephen Rea to take something long thought
of as being confined to a narrow slice of Dublin history and make
it relevant to Belfast, all of Ireland, and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   To the consternation of traditionalists, Rea, the actor best
known for his Oscar-nominated role as the reluctant IRA executioner
in Neil Jordan's ``The Crying Game,'' has revised Sean O'Casey's
great play ``The Plough and the Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   The play, written in 1926, is still set in Dublin during the
1916 Easter Rising, when a group of idealistic Irish men and women
staged a quixotic rebellion that was a failure until the British
began executing its leaders and public opinion swung firmly behind
the rebels. A cast of loquacious working-class Dubliners still
debate the honor of rebellion and the futility of war. But Rea has
added some modern references to his native Northern Ireland and the
most recent incarnation of the Troubles, the term the Irish use to
describe their ancient fight with the British and among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This is, no pun intended, revolutionary. In Ireland, you tinker
with O'Casey at your peril. The country has changed rapidly over
the last decade, its booming economy transforming it from one of
Europe's poorest countries to one of the richest. The peace process
in Northern Ireland, meanwhile, has over the same period changed
the future of that tortured corner of the island from a mostly
violent debate to a mostly political one.
</P>
<P>
   But while most Irish people are more than willing to accept the
new way business and politics are conducted on their island,
reinterpreting O'Casey is seen by some as going, as the playwright
might have put it, beyond the beyonds. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Taking stock &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as the play ended a monthlong run here at the Gaeity
Theater, Rea _ who not only directs but stars as Fluther, the
play's ambivalent central character _ sat down and assessed its
impact, his critics, and whether his version of the O'Casey classic
will travel beyond Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was prepared for the criticism, he replied,
``Yeah,'' speaking with the same laconic tone and displaying the
same mournful expression that has made him a popular film actor and
a staple in Jordan's movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think it's irresponsible of theater to go at people with
the same production, over and over, as if nothing else has happened
in the world since it was written,'' he says, sitting on a couch in
the bowels of the Gaeity, near St. Stephen's Green, where the
rebels of 1916 made a stand.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Belfast, Rea, 50, always has been something of a
rebel himself. But while many of his contemporaries picked up a
gun, Rea picked up something far more dangerous, far more
subversive: his culture.
</P>
<P>
   There has never been anything more threatening to Britain's
imperial hold on any part of Ireland than Irish culture. For most
of the last eight centuries, the British tried their best to stamp
it out. They made it illegal to teach the Irish language, which was
essential to passing down what was almost entirely an oral
tradition. The English language had more success undermining the
indigenous culture than English soldiers, a situation captured
poignantly in ``Translations,'' written in 1980 by Brian Friel, the
Tyrone-born playwright who with Rea, Seamus Heaney, and Seamus
Deane founded the Field Day Theatre Company in Derry that same
year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite centuries of repression, the Irish never stopped
asserting their identity through their language, music, poetry,
prose, and drama. Rea enthusiastically joined that cultural
revolution, arming himself with an abiding interest in Irish drama,
in particular. &QL; 
 &QL; 
At home onstage &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While primarily known for his film work, Rea is at heart a stage
actor. At 18, he began his professional career in 1968 with the
Abbey, Ireland's national theater, but soon headed over to London,
where his first big role was in O'Casey's ``The Shadow of a
Gunman.''
</P>
<P>
   He has played several roles in the ``Plough,'' appearing
opposite the late Siobhan McKenna, who was also a Belfast native.
But Rea had never played Fluther, the role that the late Donal
McCann made his own, until he got a call last year from Noel
Pearson, the prolific Irish film and theater producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noel asked me if I wanted to play Fluther. There was no talk
of directing. I said, sure, great. One thing led to another and
before I knew it I was the director, too, mostly by default,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Rea added props and references in an attempt to link the Easter
Rising with the post-1969 Troubles. In 1969, Northern Ireland spun
out of control when the Protestant-run government cracked down on
the Catholic civil rights movement, which was demanding equal
rights in housing and employment. Loyalist extremists burned down
Catholic neighborhoods, Catholics retaliated by forcing Protestants
out, and as virtual civil war broke out, the British army arrived
in August 1969. The unrest breathed life back into a dormant Irish
Republican Army, which went on the offensive, shooting British
soldiers and the overwhelmingly Protestant police force.
</P>
<P>
   Rea puts onstage some of the scenes he watched as a young man in
Belfast. A looter scoots across the stage carrying an electric
guitar, which hardly would have been available in any of the
storefronts whose windows were broken by the shelling of the
General Post Office by a British gunboat in the Liffey some 84
years ago. A television, not yet invented in 1916, shows images of
burning buildings. Fluther rides onto the stage on a bicycle,
singing a bit of ``My Way,'' long before Paul Anka wrote it and
Frank Sinatra, not to mention Sid Vicious, made it famous.
</P>
<P>
   The British soldiers who appear toward the end of the play,
after Bessie Burgess has been shot at the window, mistaken for a
rebel sniper, are dressed in uniforms worn in the 1970s. Over the
loudspeaker comes an English accent shouting, ``Shoot the sniper!
Shoot him dead!''
</P>
<P>
   The tape, Rea explains, is authentic, a recording of a British
soldier exhorting his comrades to shoot demonstrators in Derry on
Bloody Sunday, on Jan. 30, 1972. The killing of 14 unarmed
Catholics that day, and especially the British government's
foolhardy attempt to portray the dead as somehow being culpable in
their own deaths, poured fuel on what had been a relatively small
fire. Moderates became extremists, on all sides. About half of the
3,600 people who died in the Troubles since 1969 were killed in the
five years that followed Bloody Sunday, as the IRA was flooded with
recruits and the British cracked down hard.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the play, the white noise of helicopters, part of
the aural landscape in Belfast for nearly 30 years, fills the
stage. For anyone who has heard that noise in Belfast, it is
haunting.
</P>
<P>
   Some theater critics, not to mention some audiences, found the
insertion of modern references off-putting, and some accused Rea of
letting his politics unduly influence his art. Rea disagrees.
``Most of my choices were theatrical, not political,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   While Rea changed none of the dialogue as O'Casey wrote it, he
did change the emphasis given to some scenes, especially by
emphasizing the conflict within the relationship of Jack and Nora
Clitheroe, rather than Fluther's observations on the madness all
around him. Jack sees his duty first to Mother Ireland and runs off
with the rebels. Nora demands that her husband put her first,
considering family more important than country, and falls apart
when Jack is killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to humanize them both, especially Nora,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He also tried to humanize the British soldiers, who in some
productions are portrayed as one-dimensional bullies. He insisted
on casting Englishmen in the roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the soldiers I saw in Belfast were nervous,'' he
says. ``They were just kids, a lot of them.''
</P>
<P>
   While traditionalists sniffed, Mary Holland, The Irish Times
columnist who is one of the most perceptive commentators on
Northern Ireland, found the play ``almost unbearably moving.''
Holland said it was a stroke of brilliance to link O'Casey's
meditation on the futility of war that brought Ireland partial
independence with what seems to be the end of the war in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful moment in Rea's production comes not with
Burgess's death, or Nora Clitheroe's slow descent into despair, but
when two British tommies level their guns at Fluther.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lay them down and I could beat the two of ye without
sweating,'' Fluther tells the tommies, contempt dripping from each
word.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken by Rea, the words have a resonance lacking from previous
productions of ``Plough.'' And with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen that happen in real life,'' says Rea. ``I've seen
people held back from going after British soldiers. And I know what
that moment is like, when someone could do something stupid, and
someone could get killed.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catching Rea's act?
</P>
<P>
   That Rea's revision of O'Casey is considered so unusual, and
controversial, underscores the reluctance of many Irish artists to
tackle the subject of the Troubles, and especially to take risks
the way Rea has. While audiences for the monthlong run at the
1,110-seat Gaeity ran at about 70 percent capacity, you would think
a production directed by and starring someone of Rea's stature
would have been a nightly sellout.
</P>
<P>
   But the aversion of some theatergoers, and some of the criticism
directed at Rea, has nothing to do with art or with his
reinterpretation of O'Casey. There is a sizable element in southern
Irish society that dislikes anything and everything about Northern
Ireland. They were embarrassed by the Troubles. They don't like
Northerners, Catholic or Protestant. And they especially don't like
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   After I interviewed Rea, I walked across town to meet an old
friend at Mulligan's, a traditional pub on Poolbeg Street near the
Liffey. As I waited at the bar, a well-dressed man standing next to
me noticed my theater program, and as we talked, he learned of my
interview with Rea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd better be careful of that one,'' the man said, suddenly
turning hostile. ``You know who he's married to.''
</P>
<P>
   Rea is married to Dolours Price, who in the 1970s was convicted
of being part of an IRA team that planted car bombs in London, then
went on a hunger strike and forced the British authorities to allow
her to serve her prison time in Ireland. After her release, she and
Rea were married in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   For many Irish people like the well-dressed man at Mulligan's,
there is no redemption for people like Price, or Rea.
</P>
<P>
   There are no concrete plans to take this version of O'Casey on
the road, though Rea confesses to being intrigued by the prospect
of taking it to Belfast, to Boston, even to New York, where he was
nominated for a Tony award in 1992 for his role as a hostage held
by Islamic terrorists in Frank McGuinness's ``Someone to Watch Over
Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like this to be seen in other places,'' Rea says,
betraying for the first time something that others would see as
ambition.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know me,'' he says, smiling. ``I'm game for anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
