<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8440 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-NASAW-BOS &LR;      06-19 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NASAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RICH BIOGRAPHY OF HEARST UNMASKS A SHADOWY LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE CHIEF 
The Life of William Randolph Hearst 
By David Nasaw. Houghton Mifflin. 
687 pp. Illustrated. $35. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orson Welles saw through a lens darkly. His ``Citizen Kane'' was
a gloomy portrait of William Randolph Hearst, a man of Falstaffian
flamboyance who seldom felt gloomy himself. Hearst ruled American
journalism for half a century, ran a multimedia empire, kept a wife
on one coast and a mistress on the other, made millions, lost
millions, and collected art the way one of his underpaid newsboys
might collect baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   The most apt lines in Welles's movie echo in the booming
narration about ``the greatest newspaper tycoon of this or any
other generation'' who was ``more newsworthy than the names in his
own headlines!'' But teary-eyed over a sled, busted up about
Rosebud? Not Will, as his doting parents called him. He was a sunny
Californian, born in 1863, the only child of George Hearst, who
mined a Gold Rush fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Every chapter of David Nasaw's biography is as rich in human
insight as its subject was rich in material possessions. This book
is for those who want their biographical protein straight, seasoned
with gracefully straightforward writing and no psychobabble. The
saga is as suspenseful as the serial Hearst ordered for the movies
``The Perils of Pauline.''
</P>
<P>
   Why now, 49 years after the death of ``The Chief''? W. A.
Swanberg's ``Citizen Hearst'' is 40 years old and lacked access to
the Hearst family papers. Nasaw, a City University of New York
historian, plunged into the archives and uncovered a warts-and-all
wealth of anecdotes. The Chief was an original thinker, a savvy
businessman, and an indulgent father. He was also a wastrel, a
bully, and an accomplished mama's boy, manipulating Phoebe Apperson
Hearst, who had inherited her husband's millions.
</P>
<P>
   Welles was right in one regard. He did not make of Hearst's life
a serious documentary, but chose lurid melodrama, the same stuff
Hearst and other publishers served up daily. They employed stunts
and sensationalism to disguise a thin diet of real news, as some
still do. Absent his baroque habits, Hearst was a bottom-line baron
like Frank Munsey, or Munsey's modern avatar, Rupert Murdoch. But
the Hearst personality was festooned with as many gargoyles as the
loot he shipped from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Nasaw documents these traits with almost painful candor. Hearst
was a compulsive collector, as his mother reported from Paris to
George in San Francisco. ``He wants all sorts of things,'' Phoebe
wrote, and had developed ``a mania for antiquities.'' Will was 10
years old at the time.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, as business manager of the Lampoon, he ``engaged in
a full-scale advertising and marketing campaign to make the journal
self-sufficient.'' Studying, however, was not on his dance card,
and he became the most notable dropout in Harvard history until
another multimedia magnate, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   At 23, Hearst became ``editor and proprietor'' of the San
Francisco Examiner, a gift from his father. His self-sufficiency at
the Lampoon was not replicated when he bought newspapers,
magazines, and movie studios, not to mention paintings,
bric-a-brac, sculpture, and mansions to put them in. He begged and
borrowed from his mother, then from banks, because, Nasaw writes,
``He didn't believe in the Protestant ethic or Poor Richard's
aphorisms. A penny saved might be a penny earned, but a penny
borrowed was worth even more.''
</P>
<P>
   He hired celebrity journalists, including eventually Benito
Mussolini and Adolf Hitler. At the Examiner in the 1880s, then at
the New York Journal in the 1890s, he ran populist, antibusiness
crusades in preparation for his entry into politics. He served two
terms in Congress, ran for governor of New York, and ran for
president. In 1929, Winston Churchill described him as ``a grave,
simple child, with no doubt a nasty temper, playing with the most
costly toys. A vast income always overspent; ceaseless building and
collecting; two magnificent establishments, two charming wives,
complete indifference to public opinion, . . . a 15 million daily
circulation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizen Kane'' is the 35th of 36th chapters in ``The Chief,''
as if the author wished to portray his subject in Technicolor
before discussing the film's famously noirish portrait. Charles
Foster Kane was ``a mystery'' concocted by Welles, but was William
Randolph Hearst a mystery? Lincoln Steffens wrote so in 1906, two
years after Hearst ran for president.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's politics seemed a mystery when blended with
circulation-boosting populism before he evolved into a plutocrat.
He urged regulation on business when he was a young entrepreneur in
the 19th century, but as he grew richer, he changed. He declared
for Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1932 only because he believed FDR was
``a conservative.'' Hearst soured on the New Deal quickly,
predicting Alf Landon's victory in 1936 before the Kansas governor
carried only two states. ``The result of the Chief's
anti-Communist, anti-Roosevelt crusade had been a loss of
circulation and advertising,'' Nasaw writes. ``Readers forced to
choose sides between the president and the publisher had voted
twice: at the ballot box for Roosevelt, at their newsstands against
Hearst.''
</P>
<P>
   As bankruptcy loomed, threatening his possessions, Hearst showed
another side: He so loved his stuff that, at 74, he was again,
Nasaw writes, ``a spoiled child.'' When his mistress, Marion
Davies, hocked her jewels to help him, Hearst was both gallant and
shrewd. He insisted on treating her aid as a loan, for which he put
up his Boston papers as collateral. (Readers of the Boston Record,
American, and Sunday Advertiser would have been surprised by the
amount: $1 million.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1927, H. L. Mencken wrote that Hearst ``debauched
journalism,'' but also ``shook up old bones, and gave the blush of
life to pale cheeks. . . . There was scarcely a newspaper in
America, in 1900, that did not show his influence.'' Nasaw's
epilogue gives a brief account of the current state of the Hearst
Corporation and Hearst-Argyle Television that makes it clear that
that influence is not a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   The Chief himself led a tribe of sycophants, hangers-on,
loafers, and freeloaders. Some newspaper dynasties started later
and lasted longer. None of his five sons finished college and
``while Hearst had demanded that they work for a living and
threatened to cut them off if they did not, he had never followed
through on any of his threats.'' But his sons, by making family
letters fully available to Nasaw, have served both Hearst and
history well. American history resonates on each page. After 600 or
so, when I knew there weren't many more, I felt a little
Rosebud-ish myself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
