<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-NY-SENATE-HNS &LR;      06-19 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAZIO'S FLUCTUATION ON EDUCATION BECOMES CAMPAIGN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Last year, Rep. Rick Lazio voted to enact
dramatic education reforms to give states and local school
districts wide discretion in spending federal aid. And last month,
Lazio stood by those reforms, saying they would ``provide our local
schools the flexibility they need to use their resources to produce
real results.''
</P>
<P>
   But last week, the four-term Republican congressman broke with
his party and quietly reversed his vote, siding this time with the
Clinton administration to retain federal control over education
spending.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, which surprised Lazio allies and opponents alike,
marks the latest political change of heart for the congressman in
his U.S. Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Education ranks among the top three areas of concern _ above
crime, the upstate economy and taxes _ for New Yorkers who will
choose between Clinton and Lazio for the seat being vacated by Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton never has had to be held directly accountable
for her positions on education because she never has held elected
office. But in speeches as first lady and the Democratic candidate
for Senate, she at least appears consistent in her plans for public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Lazio's congressional voting record shows a shift
on education matters since the start of his Senate campaign. He
also has modified his position on vouchers and voted in 1995 for
legislation that, among other things, would have eliminated the
U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no more important issue than education for our future
and the choice in this election is very clear as to who will stand
for the children, the teachers, the families of New York,'' Clinton
said Wednesday in a speech attacking Lazio's then-opposition to the
Democratic plan that earmarked federal aid to hire new teachers and
build new schools.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio embraced the White House plan a few hours later. He was
one of only seven Republicans to vote against his party's education
reforms, which squeaked by in the House, 217-214.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican's campaign staff said Lazio was concerned about
the lack of funding for education in the GOP plan, which would
allow states and local school boards wide discretion in spending
federal dollars. But the vote came the same day Clinton launched
her sharpest criticism of Lazio so far, accusing the lawmaker of
portraying himself as a mainstream politician while siding with
conservative House leaders on key congressional votes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's vote marked a sea change in Lazio's position on how
federal funding should be allocated for education.
</P>
<P>
   In two votes last fall, Lazio supported bills embraced by the
House GOP leadership to give states and local school districts
spending discretion. As recently as last month's state Republican
Party convention in Buffalo, Lazio reinforced the
power-to-the-states plan as one of his main education campaign
platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will push for federal policies that provide our local
schools the flexibility they need to use their resources to produce
real results,'' he said then. ``Let the other side push its
`Washington-knows-best' programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton proposes earmarking $2.9 billion specifically
for new teachers and classrooms. She also has adopted a Democratic
proposal to reduce federal interest on construction bonds to pay
for new school buildings, a plan she says would save New Yorkers
$2.7 billion in local tax hikes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other Lazio education votes appear to be inconsistent with his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although he calls himself a strong proponent of public
education, Lazio voted in 1995 on legislation to balance the
federal budget _ a bill that included eliminating the U.S.
Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Lazio also has wavered on his support of
vouchers _ publicly funded scholarships to send students to private
and parochial schools. While he consistently voted in favor of
vouchers in Congress, Lazio said earlier this month that he now
supports vouchers only for ``schools that are failing, and there's
no opportunity for children to learn, or if they're not safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton opposes vouchers outright.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lazio and Clinton share ground on other school
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Both aim to recruit mid-career professionals into teaching
ranks. Clinton, borrowing an idea from Sen. Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y., and Republican Gov. George Pataki, proposes granting up to
60,000 scholarships annually for college students who commit to
teaching in high-need schools for at least four years. In addition,
she has proposed financial bonuses for 15,000 professionals in
other careers to become teachers. It is unclear how she plans to
pay for those plans.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio successfully lobbied for an amendment to be added to the
1999 Teacher Empowerment Act allowing career professionals to
bypass standard certification processes to become elementary and
secondary school teachers. But he missed voting on the bill because
he was chatting with a colleague on the House floor, said a Lazio
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   On the matter of teachers' merit pay, Clinton opposes enacting a
system of salary raises based on students' classroom performance.
Lazio has expressed reservations about merit pay but has not ruled
it out.
</P>
<P>
   Both support public charter schools, although Clinton has
criticized New York's two-pronged system of approving them _ by
both the State University of New York and the Board of Regents _ as
confusing inconsistent with other states. Both also support
affirmative action in college admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton already has seized on Lazio's apparent
inconsistencies and is likely to continue haranguing the
congressman on his most recent turnabout on education. ``You're
going to have a great time trying to figure out where he stands on
issues,'' Clinton said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Responded Lazio: ``My campaign will stress my strong record of
standing up for New York, a mainstream record I am proud of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
