<HEADLINE>
CALL OF THE WILD: WHAT TO DO WHEN BABY ANIMALS DROP BY
UNEXPECTEDLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Often, in late spring, wild baby animals, often injured or
abandoned, will show up unexpectedly in the yard. What do you do?
The Humane Society of the United States has some guidelines to help
the well-intentioned decide which is intervention or interference.
</P>
<P>
   Administering first aid or giving food to an injured animal can
harm or even kill the animal. Your first action should be to
contact a local animal shelter, animal control agency or
veterinarian who specializes in wildlife or exotic pets. Their
assistance will be the animal's best hope of surviving.
</P>
<P>
   Determining whether a juvenile animal needs help isn't always
easy. Signs of illness or injury are vomiting, diarrhea, bleeding
and an apparent broken wing or limb. An animal that is cool to the
touch is in shock or hypothermic and needs immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife that appears orphaned may not be. Some animals like
deer and rabbits may leave their offspring alone for long periods
of time.
</P>
<P>
   The following guidelines suggest steps to take when you see a
juvenile animal that seems to be in need:
</P>
<P>
   _ A nestling, a young bird with just the beginnings of feathers,
which has fallen out of the nest should be put back in the original
nest or a makeshift one hung from a nearby tree branch. A plastic
berry basket lined with paper towels works well. If no parent
returns by nightfall, call a rehabilitator or animal shelter for
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Fledglings, young birds with full feathers, and occasional downy
tufts on their heads, spend a great deal of time hopping around on
the ground. They are capable of short-distance flights, and the
parent birds are often heard or seen nearby. They should be left
alone unless obviously sick or injured.
</P>
<P>
   _ Squirrel babies, found on the ground, need help if their eyes
haven't opened yet or they are incompletely furred. Place a fallen
squirrel in a partially covered box at the bottom of a tree and
stay completely out of sight. If the mother doesn't retrieve her
young within a few hours or by nightfall, call the rehabilitator or
animal shelter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Baby rabbits usually require no assistance if the nest area is
intact and the parent is in the area. They are fed by the mother at
dawn and dusk, so you are unlikely to actually see her. If you find
furless young with closed eyes, put them back in the nest and cover
the nest with loose grass and mark the top with an X made of
sticks. If the marker is undisturbed the next day, that usually
indicates the mother hasn't returned to feed them, a professional
should be called for further advice before removing the young.
</P>
<P>
   If rabbits are active and furred with open eyes and erect ears,
they are probably old enough to fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fawns are often left alone by their mothers for long periods
of time during the day. So unless a fawn is bleeding or looks
physically injured, it is best to vacate the area so the mother
will feel safe returning.
</P>
<P>
   _ Opossum young will occasionally fall off the mother. If the
juvenile is longer than 7 inches (not counting the tail), it is
best to leave it alone. Many young opossums have been saved from
certain death by bystanders who have retrieved them from their
mother's pouch or from the surrounding area after she has been hit
by a car.
</P>
<P>
   If you determine that a wild animal really does need help, the
first thing to do is call an animal shelter, which can direct you
to a wildlife rehabilitator. You will be advised how to keep the
animal safe, warm and protected until you can get the appropriate
help.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
