 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, June 20.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL  &LR;  (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-NKOREA (Seoul, South Korea) _ South Koreans are suddenly
enthralled with all things North Korean. They are flocking to buy
books on North Korea, communism and the North Korean leader, Kim
Jong Il. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-KOREA-SANCTIONS (Undated) _ The Clinton administration on
Monday dropped many economic sanctions against North Korea put in
place a half century ago after the country's communist forces
invaded the South. By Julian E. Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-IMMIG-DEATHS (Dover, England) _ British customs officers
checking a consignment of imported tomatoes aboard a Dutch truck in
this Channel port early Monday instead found the bodies of 58 Asian
men and women who were presumed to be economic migrants being
smuggled into Britain. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-ABACHA (Geneva) _ In the Swiss investigation of former
Nigerian leader Gen. Sani Abacha, $100 million has been turned up
in bank accounts held at the bank controlled by the Liechtenstein
royal family. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-DRUGS (Beijing) _ The United States and China agreed
Monday to step up their cooperation against the production and
smuggling of illegal drugs, especially heroin and methamphetamine,
which have emerged as scourges in both countries and throughout
much of Asia. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story will move by 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ President Ernesto Zedillo said
that critics who charged that the July 2 election may be marred by
fraud were antidemocratic. His comments marked his first public
entry into the election. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL  &LR;  (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   RACE-POLITICS (Bainbridge Island, Wash.) _ In the state of
Washington, a black public official and an Asian-American governor
confront the question of how an open discussion of race could
affect their political prospects. A continuing series. By Timothy
Egan.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DEATH-PENALTY (Austin, Texas) _ A portrait of the Texas
Board of Pardons and Parole, which is unlike any other body in the
country and has a major voice about executions in Texas. All the
members are appointed by Gov. George W. Bush. And they never meet
in person but talk only on the phone. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WOMEN-COURTS (New York) _ They fill the courtrooms and
hallways of New York City courthouses each day: parents, siblings
and friends who show their support for a loved one. In most cases
they are lone women, a solitary mother, wife or girlfriend
determined to support a scorned defendant or bring to life a murder
victim. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-AUTHORS (New York) _ The reading public just can't
seem to get enough of New York City police stories. Lucas Miller, a
New York City police detective and former narcotics undercover
officer, writes a column for the online magazine Slate. Another
member of the force, Edward W. Conlon, writes about his work life
under the pseudonym Marcus Laffey for The New Yorker. It may be
hard for Police Commissioner Howard Safir to put a stop to this
while he is trying to sell his own book. By Daniel J. Wakin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-PRAYER (Washington) _ The Supreme Court ruled 6-3 that
student-led prayer at high school football games is
unconstitutional, saying such prayer is similar to student-led
prayer at commencement, which had already been banned. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TRADE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court on Monday
unanimously struck down a Massachusetts law that would have banned
the state from doing business with companies that trade with
Myanmar. The court said the legislation would have pre-empted
federal authority to set foreign policy. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-HEALTH-CARE (Washington) _ Nearly 1 million low-income
parents have lost their Medicaid coverage and are probably
uninsured as a consequence of welfare overhaul, says a study by an
advocacy group that lobbies for universal health coverage. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE  &LR;  (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GALAPAGOS (Undated) _ Great treasures are not always
instantly recognizable as such. Even Charles Darwin, one of
history's celebrated geniuses, did not recognize the importance of
the Galapagos Islands _ the archipelago that would become forever
enshrined in history as the inspiration for his world-changing
revelation on evolution _ when he first set foot on their shores
165 years ago. By Warren Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PHYSICS-RENAISSANCE (Undated) _ After years of impasse, the
study of subatomic particles has been undergoing something of a
renaissance. A new generation of physicists is stretching its
collective mind and coming up with radical ideas about how the
universe may be constructed. Some are proposing the existence of
extra dimensions. Others are building bridges between islands of
thought that once seemed hopelessly remote, rekindling hopes of a
unified ``theory of everything'' that would explain all the
particles and forces of nature. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL  &LR;  (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   SEAGRAM-VIVENDI (Undated) _ Talks involving Vivendi, Canal Plus
and Seagram appeared to be heading toward a close, and observers
expected Vivendi to pay about $75 a share in stock. For Vivendi, a
utility, telephone and TV company, the main prizes in the deal
would be Seagram's Universal Studios and its music business, and
Vivendi was expected to sell some of its own water-company assets
along with Seagram's liquor business. But many investors remember
past alliances of these sort that floundered. By Geraldine
Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   SAATCHI-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, the British
advertising giant, whose clients include Procter &AMP; Gamble and
Hewlett-Packard, said it was in talks that could lead to its being
taken over. Its stock jumped more than 20 percent. Early
speculation centered on the U.S. companies Grey Advertising and
Interpublic Group. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT (Washington) _ Developments in the government's
request to certify the Microsoft case for direct Supreme Court
review. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS  &LR;  (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary by Gail Collins.
</P>
