   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-GUERIN (Dublin) _ Four years after the assassination of
crusading reporter Veronica Guerin, organized crime is flourishing
in Ireland. By Kevin Cullen. 1126 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-JOURNAL (Mexico City) _ Mexicans go Jerry Springer to
air dirty family laundry long considered extremely private. The
phenomenon triggers a heated debate. By Richard Chacon. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WEB-PRIVACY (Washington) _ Congress is finally getting serious
on the issue of Internet privacy. With 300 bills pending, nothing
substantial will pass this year, but legislation is taking shape.
By Anne E. Kornblut. 1650 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CHOOSING (Undated) _ Gore-Bush _ how do people go about
deciding who's the one? When you examine five key determinants of a
presidential vote it becomes clear not only how the voter's mind
works, but just how much Bush has succeeded in seizing the
general-election advantage. By Scot Lehigh. 1750 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-HISTORY (Washington) _ Political scientists,
psychologists and sociologists spend endless hours unlocking the
mystery of how, and why, voters change their minds. As they are
doing so, historians are changing their minds about the choices
voters already have made. By David M. Shribman. 1460 words.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-MAVERICKS (New York) _ Independent GOP group is blitzing the
airwaves with anti-Gore ads ahead of the primary. Jill Zuckman.
1270 words.
</P>
