<HEADER>
A8502 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-GLF-TIGER-HNS &LR;      06-19 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CAN ANYONE TOPPLE TIGER WOODS? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAY RATTO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ It's hard to be philosophical when you're
young. Too many trees, not enough forest, and all that.
</P>
<P>
   But the old hands who have watched Tiger Woods make his first
fortune en route to the PGA Tour, make another while on it, and now
back up his advance notice with deeds as monumental as Sunday's
15-stroke victory at the U.S. Open . . . they're the ones who know
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's done is raise the bar to a standard only he can
reach,'' said Tom Watson, one of the few golfers of the last
half-century who knows the triple burdens of trying to be lead dog,
being lead dog, and losing the job. ``People are starting to
realize that. The players are saying, `Is there any other player
but Tiger Woods?' and the answer is, `No.'''
</P>
<P>
   This coming from a man who was the answer to the question, ``Is
there any other player but Jack Nicklaus?'' in the late '70s. This,
coming from a man who could not be the answer to the question, ``Is
there any other player but Tom Watson?'' until the early '80s.
Watson got it coming and going, as Nicklaus did before him.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods didn't have that as he ascended what has been mostly
a remote throne, nor does he seem to have it now. His victory in
the Open puts him alone, with no challenger even in sight, no
matter how many straw golfers are propped up before him.
</P>
<P>
   He now owns two of the 12 most lopsided victories in
professional golf history. He missed by a single stroke tying the
record for widest margin ever, in the hardest tournament there is.
A potential rival? Save your candidate the embarrassment and hold
your tongue with rivet tongs.
</P>
<P>
   There is but one, and there is no visible second, or even a
third. Welcome again to one-man golf.
</P>
<P>
   The last fellow in this position was Nicklaus, and the older
hands still cling to him as the shield for the greatness of an
earlier time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I can think of someone who was far ahead of the rest of
the field like this. Jack,'' said Tom Kite. ``The late '60s, early
'70s . . . he was by far No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when you consider Gary Player or Lee Trevino?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was by far No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see Woods as the Nicklaus in training.
</P>
<P>
   ``These young guys, I feel for them,'' Nick Price said.
``They're taking a pounding from this guy. I always thought some
day there would be someone who can hit the ball 300 yards
consistently and could putt like (Ben) Crenshaw. Well, (Woods) hits
the ball as far as anyone I've ever seen, and he putts better than
Crenshaw. He's a phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that isn't clear enough for you, consider this, also from
Price:
</P>
<P>
   ``When he plays his best, it's almost impossible to beat him.
Maybe he can be beaten on a certain course here or there but not
everywhere. There are a lot of great young players out there right
now who won't get any credit because Tiger gets it all. I think
there are a lot of young guys who are going to start scheduling
around Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds disheartening to some.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need competition,'' Kite said. ``Otherwise, it gets to be
boring. I think Tiger wants that. He wants to be pushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in a few years. Maybe by that college guy Price says is
out there. It doesn't seem likely, but the elders agree that the
line of succession cannot die out with Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, this is healthy,'' Watson said. ``Someone's going to reach
that standard a few times and touch it. Some time in the future,
someone will do it. Remember when you guys used to ask me if there
would ever be someone to dominate the sport like that ever again,
and I always said, `Of course there will,' and here he is. And I
think that's a good thing. He brings youth, length, diversity,
commitment, and I think it's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Price, too, advances the rising-tide-raises-all-boats theory
that most golfers believe to their economically conservative souls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guys in college now who will come out, and they're
all gauging their game to his game,'' Price said. ``Just the way
people came out and aimed their game at Nicklaus'.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a long time to wait, and a lot more one-sided slogs like
last weekend's. It also assumes that Woods intends to stand quietly
while the next heir-presumptive, whomever he might be, perfects his
chops.
</P>
<P>
   Watson spoke admiringly of the way Woods changed his backswing
to improve his ball-striking. Mark O'Meara gushed about his mental
control. The scoreboard screamed out the arm-bar he has across the
collective throat of the rest of the membership.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only questions left between Woods and Nicklaus in
the debate to see who is the best golfer ever are ones that have
nothing to do with anyone but Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Will he have the creativity to discover fresh new ways to
compete with himself when the rest of the field is as prone and
inert the way it was last week? Can he find the self-control not to
drop F-bombs into the ears of small television viewers, as Nicklaus
had the self-control to lose all that weight and stop smoking while
he played? Will he resist the impulse to become so swamped by his
own fortune that he gets into golf course design, media
conglomerates and other forms of planetary domination?
</P>
<P>
   Will he see Michael Jordan, one of the men to whom he is now
compared, in his present incarnation and think, ``Hey, I think I'll
wear a suit every day and run the Warriors''?
</P>
<P>
   Well, let's not get stupid here. By comparison, winning the
United States Open by 15 shots is something any old cheese could
do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 1538EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8504 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-GLF-OPEN-TV-HNS &LR;      06-19 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-TV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NBC COMES OUT ROARING, THANKS TO A TIGER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHELLE SMITH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ NBC faced down one of sports
broadcasting's toughest mandates Sunday afternoon while telecasting
the final round of the U.S. Open, milking the drama out of a
foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   But the network had two factors working in its favor. First, it
has plenty of experience, having done this routine with Super
Bowls, NBA Finals involving the Chicago Bulls and Olympic telecasts
where the events were, well, actually concluded. Second, the star
of this exercise in inevitability was Tiger Woods, who gave the day
a Super Bowl-like feel with the two-touchdown margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   The formula for success here was really quite easy. Put Tiger on
the air and keep him coming.
</P>
<P>
   Run out of things to say about him? Show him playing. He isn't
playing at that particular moment? Show tape of what he did at the
previous hole, the one before that and if necessary, the one before
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was probably on the air about 50 percent of the time,''
estimated NBC executive producer Tom Roy.
</P>
<P>
   If watching Tiger Woods do a number on a field of the world's
top players isn't going to prove entertaining then watching him do
a number on history would have to suffice.
</P>
<P>
   Woods had barely gotten to the 11th tee when NBC host Dan Hicks
announced that ``it's not too premature to start the coronation''
and the graphics department started pumping out statistics of
historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   The only suspense left by the time he made his victory lap down
the fairway at 18 was whether he would finish with a four-round
total of 271 and break the U.S. Open record held by Jack Nicklaus
and Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the day, with this golf course playing so
difficult, there was a chance that Tiger could have come back to
the field. But obviously that didn't happen,'' Roy said. ``At that
point it became a march to history and we started dealing with the
record and the appreciation of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   As the round wound down, Hicks _ strong in his debut as the Open
host _ called it ``a remarkable week by a remarkable player.''
Analyst Johnny Miller called it ``the greatest performance in golf
history.'' And while sports television and hyperbole go hand and
hand, it was tough to work up a rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   From a visual perspective it was a near-perfect day. In other
words, NBC couldn't have done much to screw it up. In fact, the
only bad grade for the day came at the end of the telecast when NBC
resorted to that pseudo-acoustic national anthem to accompany its
historical montage.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's best investment of the week turned out to be the boat-cam.
After it was fogged out of commission the first day and a half, it
turned out to be an impressive and effective angle. No more so than
on Sunday when Woods made his way up 18 with the cliffs in front of
him and the crowd behind him. It made the moment seem as big in
scope as it actually was, a feat that's often difficult for
television.
</P>
<P>
   All of this will pay off with huge ratings. Woods has proven to
be a viewer magnet no matter how competitive the rest of the field
and there was little else on to offer competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
