<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-IMMIG-DEATHS-     06-19 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-IMMIG-DEATHS-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
58 CORPSES FOUND ON TRUCK IN ENGLISH PORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, England _ British customs officers searching a
consignment of imported tomatoes aboard a Dutch truck in this
Channel port early Monday found the bodies of 58 Asian men and
women inside the dark, airless space.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how the people in the truck _ presumed to be
poor migrants being smuggled into Britain _ had died. But
suffocation was suspected after it was discovered that the
refrigeration equipment had been switched off, the doors had been
locked from the outside and there was scant ventilation. With
temperatures reaching 91 degrees, Sunday was the hottest day in
Britain so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Two male survivors were taken to a Kent County hospital, and the
driver, identified only as a citizen of the Netherlands, was
arrested. The victims _ all adults and all but four of them men _
were described as ``orientals'' until a more accurate national
identity could be established. The majority of Asians who try to
enter Britain surreptitiously are Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pugash, spokesman for the Kent police, said the two
survivors were expected to recover, though he added, ``It's hard to
say `non-life-threatening' when you consider the trauma they went
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Their security, he said, was a top priority, and they were being
closely guarded. ``This kind of thing doesn't happen spontaneously
on this scale,'' he said. `` It takes a lot of planning and finance
and coordination, and if you were one of those responsible for it,
you wouldn't want to have any survivors around afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair, speaking in Portugal where he was
attending a European Union summit meeting, said the discovery of
the bodies demonstrated the importance of stamping out the ``evil
trade in people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Nationality Directorate's Intelligence
Section believes that at least 20 criminal groups are actively
involved in bringing illegal immigrants into Britain and forcing
them into prostitution and jobs at slave wages. Groups of
bewildered, frightened and sickly foreigners emerging from the
backs of overloaded vehicles have become a common sight at Dover
and other Channel ports.
</P>
<P>
   In London, the home secretary, Jack Straw, told the House of
Commons: ``This particular incident is now subject to a major
police investigation. The government is determined to continue to
crack down on the evil trade in such trafficking, whose
perpetrators have no regard for human life.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pugash said he had spoken to the police and customs officers who
first came upon the grisly sight. ``Nothing had prepared them for
what they found in that lorry,'' he said. ``They were absolutely
appalled, absolutely traumatized.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Knott, a Customs spokesman, said the truck, one of the
4,000 that pass through Dover's Eastern Docks terminal daily, had
been singled out just after midnight for inspection because it fit
a profile developed by officials to identify vehicles suspected of
transporting contraband. The Dutch-registered truck had just made
the four-and-a-half hour crossing from Zeebrugge on a freight-only
P &AMP; O Stena Line ship that left the Belgian port at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Knott declined to say what had aroused suspicions, but a
spokeswoman for the P &AMP; O shipping line said the driver paid cash
for the trip and the company to which the vehicle was registered,
Van Der Spek, was unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Using a fork lift, the customs inspectors unloaded stacked
crates of tomatoes from the 58-foot truck that had in effect formed
a wall blocking what was behind. ``It is common for us to find
veneers, if you will, or false bulkheads like this put up to hide
things,'' Knott said.
</P>
<P>
   A single customs officer climbed into the exposed space, where
he made the horrifying discovery, Knott said. Emergency services
were summoned, and police took over the case. Two pathologists from
the Home Office arrived from London Monday morning to conduct
autopsies and determine how the victims had died.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, tomatoes still lay on the concrete loading
dock where customs officers, working in the dim amber light of the
unloading shed, had hurled them when they discovered the gruesome
human cargo. Forensic specialists dressed in white full-body suits
picked over the wilted vegetables and broken wood slats Monday
while the doctors worked inside a refrigeration hangar next door
that had been converted into an emergency morgue.
</P>
<P>
   A rolling flotilla of large ferries kept landing at the piers,
which lie at the base of Dover's famous white cliffs. Trucks rolled
down the gangplanks and then lumbered out the exits toward
northbound highways. In mid-afternoon, one of them was stopped,
and, as reporters watched, six young men were escorted out a back
door and marched into an interrogation office.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The surge in the number of people seeking asylum is a big
political issue in Britain, an insular nation that has always felt
the added security of having no overland borders with other
countries, aside from the frontier between Northern Ireland and
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   A record 75,000 people claimed asylum for the year that ended in
February, compared with just over 49,000 the year before. The war
in Kosovo, which prompted many Kosovar Albanians to seek refuge in
the West, accounted for only some of the rise. There were large
influxes of people from Eastern Europe, Central Asia and, as
Monday's episode seemed to illustrate, China.
</P>
<P>
   Although the requests of most asylum-seekers to Britain are
denied, two-thirds of those who are refused vanish in an effort to
stay here. The government says it intends to get tougher and is
introducing plans to imprison and deport larger numbers of new
arrivals. Immigration has been at the center of political debate in
recent weeks, with Conservative party leader William Hague making
inroads on Blair's popularity by using deliberately emotive
language to warn of the dangers of a ``flood of bogus asylum
seekers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Blair's government and the Conservative opposition joined Monday
in denouncing the lucrative and exploitative business of smuggling
human beings into Britain. Both Labor and Tory politicians stressed
the need for closer examination of cargoes on the continental
European side of the Channel. ``I accept entirely that there is a
need greatly for other countries to improve the checking of
vehicles coming in here,'' said Straw.
</P>
<P>
   The British government introduced tougher new measures this
spring, including fining drivers $3,000 for each illegal foreign
stowaway found in their trucks. Some $1.8 million has been levied
thus far, and a spokesman for Blair said Monday that ``As a result
of that, there's been a 49 percent reduction in the number of
clandestine entrants discovered in vehicles in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   When Straw visited Dover in April to publicize the new
regulations, he arrived at a moment when eight illegal immigrants
were being flushed from the back of a Czech truck.
</P>
<P>
   The government may boast of the effectiveness of the fines, but
drivers and trucking companies claim that the government is
penalizing them for the failures of border control authorities.
Drivers say people clamber onto the trucks without their knowledge
while they are parked on side roads or in gas station or restaurant
parking lots while waiting to cross the Channel. One company
official told The Evening Standard, ``It's like a householder being
fined for reporting a burglary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
