<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8519 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MIRANDA-WARNING-HNS &LR;      06-19 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRANDA-WARNING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROSECUTORS LOSE CASE AFTER POLICE VIOLATE SUSPECTS RIGHT TO
REMAIN SILENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A gardener discovered the dead man face up in
the dry creek bed at the edge of the University of California at
Davis campus, amidst crushed beer cans and cigarette butts. He was
missing one sandal.
</P>
<P>
   Forty feet above him on Low Water Bridge, police found his other
sandal, along with a receipt for beer and a cashed unemployment
check. Those clues led them to arrest three men who allegedly
confessed to robbing Jose Garcia Reyes and pitching him to his
death on Aug. 13, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecution of the case fell apart after disclosures
that detectives conducted illegal or coercive interrogation
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate resulting in no justice for Mr. Reyes,'' said
Deputy District Attorney Valerie McGuire, the Solano County
prosecutor. ``It's unfortunate . . . anytime police officers engage
in conduct that's prohibited.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reyes case demonstrates that improper interrogation tactics
can undermine the criminal justice process. It suggests that such
police methods are especially dangerous when used on suspects who
are illiterate and uneducated.
</P>
<P>
   The case confirms that video- and audio-taping entire
interrogation sessions can be crucial to establishing what goes on
inside the interrogation room. Only two states, Alaska and
Minnesota, require recording interrogations, and the practice
elsewhere in the United States and in California varies widely.
</P>
<P>
   And it illustrates what experts say is a police tendency to rely
on purported confessions at the expense of other evidence that may
corroborate _ or contradict - suspects' statements.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives in the Reyes case had no evidence against the three
defendants other than their statements, McGuire acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming they had the case sewn up, the officers failed to
adequately pursue evidence implicating a fourth man, a convict who
police say was the last known person seen with Reyes, defense
lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the case collapsed when a judge suppressed
statements from the first suspect because a detective failed to
fully advise him of his Miranda rights to remain silent and to have
legal help before questioning. The judge threw out statements from
a second suspect because another detective kept questioning him
after he invoked his right to remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   The Miranda procedure is meant to protect the constitutional
right against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   And the judge disregarded statements from the third suspect
because, while the detective advised him of his Miranda rights, he
then used promises and threats to illegally extract a statement
ruled involuntary and unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was, in fact, coercion,'' said Solano County Superior
Court Judge Eric R. Uldall.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the prosecution team said in interviews that no one
had meant to violate the suspects' rights. ``Nobody tried to
coerce, intentionally, any statements out of these guys,'' said Lt.
Joyce A. Souza of the UC-Davis Police Department. ``There was no
conspiracy to try and violate anyone's constitutional rights.
Everybody thought they were doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the San Francisco Examiner found a pattern in which police
across the state violated the Miranda rights of suspects _
sometimes deliberately _ in efforts to obtain incriminating
information.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Justice has told police they may
lawfully question suspects even after they have invoked their
rights to remain silent or to have legal counsel, although state
and federal courts have criticized the practice as illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court is now considering whether to overturn
the Miranda rule in a case called U.S. vs. Dickerson. Some
prosecutors say Miranda lets criminals escape punishment, but the
U.S. Department of Justice says that the rule helps win convictions
and that reversing it would bring more claims that police violated
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how police handled the Reyes case emerged from
court records, police reports and interrogation transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes, 57, was an unemployed tomato picker known as an amiable
drunk around his neighborhood in Dixon, a city of 15,110 just south
of Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The receipt on the bridge led Solano County Sheriff's Detective
Jose Cuevas to the Home Town Market in Dixon, where a clerk
confirmed that Reyes, joined by a younger man, had cashed his $264
unemployment check the day before. The detective learned the pair
had gone to buy more beer at a nearby 7-Eleven, where a
surveillance camera filmed Reyes and the other man, whom he
recognized as Ruben Campos.
</P>
<P>
   Campos was an illiterate migrant laborer who spoke little
English. He worked in the UC-Davis grape fields, his attorney said,
and was in the country illegally.
</P>
<P>
   Campos lived in a child's play house in the yard behind some
friends' rented home, court records show. He was about 24 years
old, but didn't know his birth date.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Cuevas found Campos sitting in front of his friends'
house, and Campos voluntarily went to Dixon police headquarters,
where detectives interrogated him.
</P>
<P>
   Cuevas' subsequent report made the case look tidy: Campos
initially denied being with Reyes the day of his death but then
admitted to murder.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, Campos confessed that he, Guadalupe
Franklin and Juan Palomino had spent much of the day drinking with
Reyes. Around midnight, the four men drove to Low Water Bridge and
drank more. When Reyes refused to lend Franklin $20, Franklin hit
him. Campos added that he and the other men had then thrown Reyes
from the bridge, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Campos' statement, police focused on Franklin and
Palomino.
</P>
<P>
   Like Campos, they were uneducated immigrants and manual
laborers. ``Most of their day appears to be spent wandering from
one bar or store to another to obtain alcohol,'' said John Coffer,
Franklin's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   And like Campos, reported Cuevas, both men denied and then
admitted beating Reyes at the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   But in court, the prosecution began to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Campos' attorney, Deputy Public Defender Donald Sawyer,
contended that UC-Davis police detective Javier Barragan, who
initially interrogated Campos, had failed to give him complete
Miranda warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Campos was confused but apparently tried to invoke his rights to
remain silent and to have a lawyer, the interrogation transcript
shows. Yet the detective continued to question him. At the end of
the interrogation, Campos was arrested for murder.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, he allegedly confessed his role in the murder to
Cuevas.
</P>
<P>
   But in court, Deputy District Attorney McGuire revealed that
UC-Davis police had told her they had deliberately interfered with
Campos' right to counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detective Barragan indicated he intentionally failed to give
Mr. Campos his complete advisement,'' McGuire told the judge,
according to a court transcript. ``He told me he did this to
intentionally elicit a statement from Mr. Campos.''
</P>
<P>
   McGuire agreed that by law Campos' statements could not be used
to prove his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people don't have any other evidence against Mr. Campos,''
McGuire told the court. ``Therefore, the people move to dismiss.''
</P>
<P>
   The case of Guadalupe Franklin, 42, who lived with Campos in the
play house and who spoke English poorly, was also thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Uldall found the interrogation was not coercive but he
ruled that kSolano County Sheriff's Detective Jose Cuevas had
violated Franklin's Miranda rights by questioning him after he'd
invoked his right to remain silent. At McGuire's request, the court
dismissed the case on May 10, 1999 for insufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Juan Palomino, 21, who spoke no English, was thrown
out after it was shown that Cuevas in effect force-fed a confession
to Palomino and coerced him into regurgitating it.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ofshe, a UC-Berkeley sociologist and court-recognized
expert on interrogations, testified for the defense that Cuevas'
interrogation of Palomino was among the most coercive he had seen.
</P>
<P>
   Ofshe said the case underscored the importance of recording
interrogations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this hadn't been tape recorded, there's a good likelihood
Palomino would have been convicted,'' Ofshe said.
</P>
<P>
   The case also shows that police may put too much weight on
uncorroborated confessions, Ofshe said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the confessions crumbled in court, police failed to
adequately pursue evidence pointing to another potential suspect,
sources said. So far the suspect has not been arrested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
