<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8523 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LABOR-NYT &LR;      06-19 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR SEEKS NEW YORK MINIMUM WAGE OF $6.75 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A push by labor unions to lift New York state's minimum wage to
$6.75 an hour, from $5.15, has turned into one of the last major
battles in this year's legislative session in Albany, N.Y., as
small businesses lobby fiercely to block an increase.
</P>
<P>
   Business lobbyists are pressing the Republican-controlled state
Senate to vote against the increase before the end of the session,
scheduled Thursday. The Assembly, which is dominated by Democrats,
overwhelmingly approved the $6.75 wage two weeks ago by a vote of
120 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials argue that the minimum wage needs to be lifted
well above the $5.15-an-hour authorized by the federal government
because living expenses are so high in New York. But corporate
leaders assert that raising the minimum wage would hurt small
businesses, especially upstate, where pay levels are generally
lower than in New York City and its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of issue that excites fierce support and
opposition from such diametrically opposed groups that there would
never be a legislative resolution until the very last minute,''
said Edwin Donnelly, the chief lobbyist for the New York State
AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   The wage issue is heavy with political consequences this year,
since all 211 seats in the Legislature are up for grabs in
November. Many Republicans fear that if they oppose a higher
minimum wage, the Democrats and labor unions will flog them over
the issue in the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican lawmakers consider an increase to $6.75 in
January to be preposterously steep and say the Assembly Democrats
proposed so large a jump not with the expectation that it will
become law, but in the hope that it will become a winning campaign
issue. Many Senate Republicans are also unhappy with a provision in
the Assembly bill that would raise the minimum wage each year at
the same rate that the statewide average wage rises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immediate raise to $6.75 and the escalator are poison
pills to make sure this doesn't pass,'' said Assemblyman John Faso,
the Republican minority leader. ``I think this is a political
gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, New York has not raised its minimum wage above the
federal level, but some Assembly Democrats said it was time to do
so because the $10,000 a year paid to full-time workers making the
minimum wage was too low to support a family. They also noted that
Connecticut and Massachusetts had raised their minimum wage above
federal levels. Connecticut's is $6.15 an hour and will rise to
$6.70 on Jan. 1, 2002. The Massachusetts minimum of $5.25 will go
to $6 in January, and $6.75 a year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1960s you could support a family on the minimum wage,
but you can't do that in any guise, way or form now,'' said
Catherine Nolan of Queens, chairwoman of the Assembly's labor
committee and the bill's sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking for $12 an hour, we're asking for $6.75,
which is achievable. The more money you put into people's pockets,
the more money they spend. So this would help the economy by
generating more goods and services.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan said that the business groups were shocked that the higher
minimum wage sailed through the Assembly, and have responded with a
huge lobbying campaign in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Alesse, state director of the National Federation of
Independent Business, an association of small businesses, said he
was confident that a higher minimum wage would not be approved this
year, but Donnelly of the AFL-CIO expressed confidence that labor
would prevail on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Alesse called a raise to $6.75 ``a hideously bad idea.'' ``The
small-business community is completely unanimous against this,'' he
said. ``It will hurt the business climate and in particular the
small-business community.''
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that most minimum wage workers in New York were
teen-agers, he said raising the minimum wage would do little to
lift families out of poverty. Instead, raising the minimum wage
would cause many small businesses to lay off low-wage workers, he
said, because it could squeeze their profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   One of business' biggest fears is that if the minimum wage does
go to $6.75, it would put pressure on employers to give raises to
workers earning $6.75 to $9 an hour. Many union leaders also say
that is how a higher minimum wage could help lift many low-wage
families out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Several lawmakers said Joseph Bruno, the Senate majority leader,
was caught between business lobbyists who want him to stop any
minimum wage increase and Republican pragmatists who are urging him
to negotiate with Assembly leaders for a smaller increase.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno was consulting with labor, business, the Assembly and Gov.
George Pataki, said Bruno's a spokesman, John McArdle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to do something in such a way that's not going to
put smaller business at a disadvantage, while also recognizing
labor markets out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has said he was open to increasing the minimum wage,
although he said he feared it could hurt the tourism industry in
the Catskills and Adirondacks, where many workers at hotels,
restaurants and ski resorts are paid the minimum.
</P>
<P>
   As for the increase to $6.75 approved by the Assembly, Charles
Deister, a spokesman for the governor, said, ``It's certainly
something he'll take a look at.'' He added that the governor
thought the minimum wage was an issue that should be handled at the
federal level, not the state level.
</P>
<P>
   The Working Families Party, a new political party set up with
the support of several labor unions, is one of the main forces
behind the push for a higher minimum wage. Some Senate Republicans,
worried that their seats might be vulnerable, are hoping to gain
the endorsement of the Working Families Party, which would give
them an extra ballot line. But the party has said it will look to
whether a candidate has backed the higher minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Some lobbyists said that if the Senate took no action on the
minimum wage bill, it might seek to placate organized labor by
approving another labor-backed bill, one that would require a day
off each week for farm workers and would extend overtime coverage
to them. Under current law, farm workers can be required to work
365 days in a row and do not qualify for time-and-a-half pay when
they work more than 40 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
