<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: PORTUGAL'S POUSADAS _ HISTORY WITH A
DISCOUNT  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    For nearly six months out of the year, Portugal's
government-sponsored hotels, known as ``pousadas,'' offer a 40
percent discount for travelers ages 60 and older.
 &HT;    This was just the sort of deal that Ted and Fran Lewis of
Severna Park, Md., were hoping to find. Not long ago, the couple
planned to celebrate the completion of Fran's chemo and radiation
treatments for cancer by traveling to Portugal to take advantage of
the discount program at the pousadas. The discount applies to stays
Sundays through Thursdays from Nov. 2 to March 31. The Lewises'
accommodations ranged in cost from $60 to $130 (U.S.) per night,
which included a breakfast buffet.
 &HT;    After arriving at the Lisbon International Airport, the Lewises
got in their rental car, headed southeast across the long Vasco de
Gama bridge which spans the Tagus River and, after an hour on the
road, arrived in Alcacer de Sa. There, a resident directed them to
the Pousada de Alfonso II, which sits on the highest part of town
overlooking the River Sado.
 &HT;    The castle dates back thousands of years and has withstood the
occupations of the Phoenicians, Arabs and Romans. From their room,
they could see a number of stork nests on high poles, complete with
occupants.
 &HT;    On their first full day in Portugal, the Lewises took a
three-hour drive to Sagres and spent the night in the Pousada do
Infante. From there they took time to drive to Cabo St. Vincente
and explore the lighthouse where Prince Henry the Navigator is said
to have established his Navigation School.
 &HT;    ``The chefs all tried to outdo themselves by offering a
selection of local foods and desserts,'' says Ted, describing the
evening meals he and his wife enjoyed at the pousadas. Although
roast kid with herbs, giblet rice and rich fish soups would have
pleased any palate, Ted most enjoyed the small clams with fried
pork chunks. Each meal ended with coffee and a glass of port,
enjoyed by a crackling fireplace in the sitting room.
 &HT;    In the town of Evora, the couple checked into the Pousada dos
Loios, a former convent and now a UNESCO-designated Heritage Site,
in the historic center of town. Right outside the entrance is a
Roman temple that dates back to the second century and contains 14
of its original 18 columns.
 &HT;    The next day it was off to Beja and the Pousada de Sao
Francisco, a former Franciscan convent from the 18th century. The
Lewises say, ``the impressive building combines the mystic monument
of the past with today's standard of comfort.''
 &HT;    That evening, they were one of only three couples to eat in the
large dining hall. ``All through dinner, a talented pianist played
Gershwin and Cole Porter,'' Ted Lewis reports. ``After the meal, a
complimentary after-dinner drink from the region was presented by
the maitre d'.''
 &HT;    According to the Lewises, the meal prices in the pousadas were
on a par with those in good, local restaurants. For example, a
dinner for two, including bread, cheese, olives, a main course, a
bottle of wine and coffee, cost about $50 (U.S.) with tip.
Sometimes, after a heavy lunch, they simply shopped at the local
supermarkets for light dinner snacks.
 &HT;    Next up was the town of Obidos, which is completely encircled by
walls, all intact. There, the Pousada do Castelo was the first to
be adapted and restored from a historical monument.
 &HT;    From the castle ramparts, one can look down on the village of
typical white houses with blue trim, flower pots filled with
geraniums marching across the windowsills and narrow streets paved
with cobblestones.
 &HT;    During a brief stop in Batalha, the Lewises wandered through an
impressive monastery that stands as a fine example of Gothic
stonework. Nearby in the village of Fatima is the internationally
famous shrine of the same name, where, according to the Catholic
Church, three peasant children witnessed the appearance of the
Virgin Mary in 1917. A neo-Baroque basilica with a 215-foot-high
central tower dominates a 37-acre esplanade where the faithful
pray. On the esplanade there is a glass-enclosed building where
Mass is celebrated several times a day.
 &HT;    After heading north to Oporto to visit the port-wine caves along
the Douro River, the Lewises spent the night in the seaside town of
Villa do Conde in a 500-year-old inn similar to the pousadas. Then
they drove south the picturesque fishing village of Nazare. What
they had hoped to see _ colorful boats pulled up on the beach and
fisherwomen in their costumes of many petticoats handling the cargo
of fresh fish _ was far from the reality.
 &HT;    ``Well, we were several decades too late,'' Ted Lewis says. ``We
saw only one elderly lady drying her sardines and a wreck of an old
boat on the beach as a memento of the past.''
 &HT;    Lewis equates the comfort of the pousadas to that of four- and
five-star hotels. A bellhop was always on call, ready to lug their
luggage up to their room. ``Of the six pousadas we tried, only the
Pousada do Castelo in Obidos was missing an elevator,'' he says.
 &HT;    Before heading home, the Lewises stopped in Sintra to see the
Royal Palace. They also had a look at both Cascais and Estoril up
the coast from Lisbon before checking into the Pousada de Dona
Maria I in Queluz, where they spent their last night. Both agreed
that the trip ``was a special treat for both of us, as it was meant
to be.''
 &HT;    To learn more about Portugal's pousadas, contact Enatur at
www.Pousadas.pt for booklets and maps or to make reservations.
 &HT;    The Portugese Tourist office Web site is www.portugal.org, or
you can call (212) 354-4403. 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Adele
Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th
Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send Adele a postcard from your trip
with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you find for
seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to Adele by electronic mail. The
address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on your
keyboard.)
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
