<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SHOPPING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: CHOOSING PARADISE IN THE CARIBBEAN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Paradise is a relative term, and that's especially true when it
comes to choosing an island in the Caribbean. Some couples might
find a sleepy island such as Grenada to be Eden, one where
nightlife consists of quiet beachfront bars and the wake-up call
comes with the breaking surf.
 &HT;    But an active family of four might imagine paradise to be a
different place altogether, an island like Puerto Rico, where large
beachside hotels come with multiple pools and water slides,
kid-friendly restaurants and even a casino.
 &HT;    If price is an issue, choose an affordable island. For the most
bang for the buck, look to Aruba, the Dominican Republic, Jamaica,
Puerto Rico and St. Thomas. They are all blessed with a large
number of resort hotels and condominiums. All of those rooms
translate to cheaper prices overall.
 &HT;    Secondly, all these islands are served by non-stop flights from
the United States. Flights are plentiful and relatively affordable,
since there's not a second or third flight in a puddle-jumper. And
the budget-minded will find that the most affordable air/hotel
package deals are available on these islands.
 &HT;    For those who can spare only three or four days, the flight
should be as painless as possible. So the Dominican Republic,
Jamaica, Puerto Rico and St. Thomas are also good picks _ islands
that are relatively close by and served by non-stop flights from
the United States.
 &HT;    Many people choose an island by default because they really want
to stay at a particular resort. It might be an upscale resort like
Guanahani on St. Bart's or a simpler place like Lambert Beach
Resort on Tortola.
 &HT;    For many travelers, that's just fine because in the end it's the
resort, not the island, that's the real destination for them. They
intend to spend the lion's share of their time there.
 &HT;    Even on bigger islands known for big resorts, such as Jamaica,
resorts like Strawberry Hill offer privacy and seclusion. For those
traveling with kids, choosing a kid-friendly resort is usually the
way to go, with the island taking second place.
 &HT;    But for travelers who like to explore, to get a little history,
find a little Caribbean culture or need a dash of city life,
choosing an island because of a certain resort may not be ideal if
the resort is isolated or seems like a compound.
 &HT;    Some islands are better than others, depending upon the season.
September and October mean prime hurricane season in the Caribbean,
so many resorts have low rates that reflect not just rain and
humidity but the real possibility of a storm visiting their island.
Try to head below the hurricane belt, to islands such as Aruba,
Bonaire, Curacao, Grenada, Tobago or Trinidad. These destinations
are almost always well out of harm's way and provide a safe haven
during these months.
 &HT;    Travelers looking for islands where formal dress means Teva
sandals and shorts should consider St. Croix, the perennial sleeper
of the three USVI. A little more bustling is the boater's haven of
Bequia; a little quieter still is Culebra, off the coast of Puerto
Rico.
 &HT;    Or go farther off the beaten path. The little island of
Carriacou is the desert-like yin to the jungle-like yang of
Grenada. The island of St. Eustatius is a quiet sibling of St.
Maarten, a 20-minute flight away.
 &HT;    The rule of thumb with all of these islands is that they take
longer to get to but they also take one farther away.
 &HT;    Serious bird-watchers and hikers might want to go to Dominica to
see one of the great natural paradises in the Caribbean. On an
island like St. Lucia, there's terrific hiking among the Pitons.
 &HT;    On Curacao, Christoffel Park, the 4,500 acres that encompass the
ruins of several 18th-century plantations as well as 1,239-foot Mt.
Christoffel are worth exploring. Grenada also has terrific hiking,
with waterfalls, and a rain forest.
 &HT;    If snorkeling or diving really matter, choose a place that's
known for providing a tantalizing glimpse into how the lower half
lives. In Grand Cayman, there's stingrays aplenty at Stingray City,
which lies just off the northwest tip of Grand Cayman Island.
 &HT;    On St. John, where locals say the best half of the island lies
underwater, there's a well-marked underwater trail. Bonaire has
elkhorn coral up to 10 feet across, coral terraces and trumpet fish
swimming through the aquatic equivalent of the Louvre.
 &HT;    The Turks &AMP; Caicos are surrounded by reefs some 65 miles wide
and 250 miles long. And Anguilla boasts six marine parks. For
dedicated windsurfers, Aruba and Bonaire are tops.
 &HT;    Maybe the driving force is golf. Maybe it's gambling. Maybe it's
the perfect honeymoon island. For more information, start with the
Caribbean Tourism Organization _ 80 Broad St., New York, N.Y.
10004; 212-635-9530; www.caribtourism.com _ which distributes a
free Caribbean Vacation Planner. 
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
<TEXT>
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on WAY TO GO!
and other features. &QL;
