<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8535 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      06-19 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bad News for Pests
</P>
<P>
   A water droplet hitting the waxy top of a leaf is like a
basketball hitting a backboard _ it rebounds off the surface. This
can be a problem if, for example, the water is a pesticide solution
being applied to crops. Studies have shown that in much pesticide
spraying, less than half of the spray is retained by the plants.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists in France, researching how droplets rebound from
such a hydrophobic surface, have discovered a way to help make them
stick. The key, they report in the journal Nature, is to add small
amounts of a polymer to the solution.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists studied droplet impact using a video system that
recorded 1,000 frames per second. A plain water droplet hits,
spreads out to a maximum diameter and then contracts so much and so
quickly that it leaves the surface. A droplet containing
polyethyleneoxide or another polymer, on the other hand, contracts
very little and stays where it hits. The researchers found that the
elongational viscosity of the polymer _ that is, how it resists
stretching _ dampens the contraction of the droplet.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers say their findings could be useful not only in
agricultural spraying but in industrial and consumer applications
where cutting waste or preventing the spread of contaminants is
desired. They note that so little polymer is needed that other
characteristics of the solution are essentially unchanged, meaning
that other processes that it has to go through _ pumping, for
example _ would not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Ice Age Survivor
</P>
<P>
   The Irish elk was a spectacular animal, the largest deer that
ever lived, with antlers that spanned up to 12 feet. Like some
other large mammals, it was thought to have become extinct at the
end of the last ice age, about 10,600 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of its demise, however, have been found to be a bit
premature. Radiocarbon dating by British researchers of a specimen
unearthed two centuries ago on the Isle of Man shows that it is
only about 9,225 years old. Thus the Irish elk joins some other
large mammals, including the woolly mammoth, as an unexpected
survivor into the Holocene, the modern post-ice age epoch.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, reporting in Nature, found that the body size
of the specimen was well below the mean for the species, indicating
that the same factors thought to have killed off the animal during
the Ice Age _ notably a lack of food _ probably contributed to
decreasing body size.
</P>
<P>
   The Isle of Man became separated from mainland Britain about
10,000 years ago. So the finding shows that some large mammals were
able to survive the ice in isolated spots, only to die off later,
unable to cope with changes in vegetation, perhaps, or the victims
of human or other predators.
</P>
<P>
   A Modern Survivor
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists who had been concerned that California sea
otters might be going the way of the Irish elk got some good news
this month with the release of spring survey numbers that show that
the otter population increased by almost 11 percent from the year
before, to more than 2,300.
</P>
<P>
   The population has been on a roller-coaster ride in recent
decades, declining in the mid-1970s, picking up again after
restrictions on some fishing nets were instituted and then
declining again. While otter experts said the current increase, the
first since 1995, was an encouraging sign, they added that the
increases would have to continue for several years before they
would declare that the declines have stopped. Particularly
encouraging in the current survey was the fact that the number of
otter pups increased by almost 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys are done twice a year, in May and November. Spotters
cover about 375 miles of the central California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Disease, pollution, loss of food sources and entanglement in
fishing gear are all considered causes of the decline of the
animals, which were listed as a threatened species in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
