<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PRAYER (Washington) _ Maintaining the wall between church
and state, the Supreme Court rules that a Texas school district
violated the Constitution when it allowed a student to lead prayers
before high school football games. In a 6-3 decision, the court
says that by granting students the right to use the school's public
address system at a school-sponsored event, the local board of
education gave preferential treatment to a particular religious
viewpoint. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-MYANMAR (Washington) _ The Supreme Court makes it harder
for states to refuse to buy from companies that do business with
nations known for human rights abuses. Saying states have no right
to make foreign policy, the justices unanimously invalidate a
Massachusetts law that limits state purchases from companies doing
business with Myanmar, also known as Burma. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-RDP (Washington) _ A roundup of other cases handled by the
Supreme Court. By LETITA STEIN.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-HATE-CRIMES (Washington) _ The Senate is debating
amendments on hate crimes that were included in a defense
authorization. By JOHN HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-SAFETY (Washington) _ With the start of summer, some
lawmakers and safety advocates are warning that the highways could
become more hazardous if a new federal proposal goes into effect
allowing truckers to drive 12 straight hours before taking a break.
Currently, U.S. Department of Transportation rules limit truck
drivers to 10 consecutive hours behind the wheel. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXECUTION (Houston) _ Four people who say they were robbed
and terrorized in 1981 by Gary Graham criticize the convicted
killer's supporters and call for an end to the efforts to block his
death sentence. By SALATHEIA BRYANT and KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   TUITION-BACKLASH (Houston) _ Houston Community College board
members thought they were doing a good deed by offering in-state
tuition to undocumented immigrants. But the move has generated a
backlash, with international students who hold visas saying they
are being punished with the higher rates charged foreign students.
But they say that if they let their visas lapse, they will become
illegal immigrants and qualify for lower tuition. By ED HEGSTROM.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TEXAS (Houston) _ President Clinton speaks before the
Southwest Voter Registration Project and Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee, then goes to Austin to attend a pair of
fund-raisers. By GREG McDONALD and JULIE MASON.
