<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8556 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-SAN-JUAN-ISLANDS-3TAK     06-19 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAN-JUAN-ISLANDS-3TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WASHINGTON ISLANDS OFFER ESCAPE TO ANOTHER WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN FLINN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRIDAY HARBOR, Wash. _ Escorted by a pair of frisky killer
whales, watched by glinty-eyed bald eagles, we're aboard the
Washington State Ferry Yakima, gliding past prettily timbered
islets and misty, fiord-like inlets.
</P>
<P>
   As we round Shaw Island on our approach to Friday Harbor, we're
lined up in the ferry's gaping mouth like impatient settlers
awaiting the start of a land rush.
</P>
<P>
   In front are the bicycle tourers, their mountain bikes loaded
with saddlebag-like panniers. Next come the sea kayakers, with
Crayola-bright boats affixed to the roofs of their SUVs. Behind
them are cars full of whale watchers clutching binoculars and
Dramamine, and bed-and-breakfasters with their wicker picnic
hampers.
</P>
<P>
   With a shuddering reverse of its engines the Yakima eases to a
stop at the pier, the mesh barrier across the ferry's mouth comes
down, and we all spill forth in pursuit of our own private island
pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, virtually everyone aboard the ferry would have
been a Washington resident. But on this day I count a healthy
smattering of out-of-state license plates _ evidence that the
enchanting San Juan Islands, once Seattle's private dominion, are
starting to make it onto the map for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   A forested archipelago of anywhere from 172 to 786 islands _
depending on who's counting and whether the tide is out _ the San
Juans occupy the strait between the northwest corner of the
continental United States and Vancouver Island, British Columbia _
a strategic position that, as we shall see, once led to the
silliest military engagement in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Lying in the rain shadow of the snow-capped Olympic Mountains,
the islands get only half the annual precipitation of soggy
Seattle, 70 miles to the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   They're home to potters and poets, winemakers and llama
breeders, Internet entrepreneurs and New Age shamans. Each island
has its own personality: Thirtysomething Microsoft millionaires
erect waterfront trophy homes on San Juan Island, while Franciscan
nuns in habits and Polarfleece sweaters operate the ferry dock on
Shaw Island.
</P>
<P>
   On the ferry ride over, I'd wondered how long it would be before
I heard The Question. It didn't take long. A 50ish couple was
studying the route map, and the woman turned to her husband and
said, ``Where's the island from that book - you know, San Pietro?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer: In an author's imagination. The setting for David
Guterson's critically acclaimed novel and film, ``Snow Falling on
Cedars,'' San Pietro Island doesn't exist, although the puzzled
couple can be forgiven: There's an otherwise-accurate map in the
book showing it to the south of San Juan Island.
</P>
<P>
   Although the novel was largely based on events on Bainbridge
Island, 65 miles to the south in Puget Sound, longtime residents
say it accurately captures life in the San Juans half a century
ago. That life, though, has all but vanished. The strawberry farms
and the Japanese immigrants who worked them are long gone, and the
fishing trawlers have mostly disappeared from the harbor, replaced
by pleasure yachts and whale-watching boats. Taciturn Scandinavian
fishermen have given way to cell-phone-toting real estate agents.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Jeri, and I visited the San Juans twice in the past two
years, investigating three of the four islands served by ferry _
San Juan, Orcas and Lopez. What follows is a sampler of scenes from
those trips.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop in Friday Harbor was the Whale Museum, dedicated
to the islands' most celebrated inhabitants _ orcas, or killer
whales. About 90 orcas forming three resident pods _ named J, K and
L _ ply the salmon-rich Haro Strait between San Juan and Vancouver
islands, and museum visitors are invited, for a modest fee, to
adopt one. While a young male with the evocative name of K-27
looked particularly toothsome, I decided to pass for the time
being.
</P>
<P>
   The museum had photos of every resident orca, an exhibit of
orcas in American-Indian art, orca skeletons and a pickled orca
brain. Playing in the background was the song of the orcas, a
series of atonal, vaguely New Age-ish screeches and shrieks.
They're the undersea world's Yoko Onos.
</P>
<P>
   The resident pods can often be seen from Lime Kiln State Park,
but for a closer look we boarded a whale-watching boat at Roche
Harbor, on the island's northern tip.
</P>
<P>
   As we wended through a labyrinth of tiny islets, we glimpsed
nesting bald eagles, a swimming otter and dozens of harbor seals
lolling on rocks _ but no orcas. We sailed into Canadian waters and
reached Saturna Island; time was running out. Then the call came in
on the radio: J pod had been spotted off Lime Kiln Point. At full
throttle, we motored south for 20 minutes and then cut the engine
so that we drifted on a path to intercept the northbound whales.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly there was a 5-foot-high dorsal fin knifing through the
water, coming straight toward our boat. We let out a collective
gasp as it disappeared beneath the surface and popped up again on
the other side of us.
</P>
<P>
   Another orca thrust its head out of the water for a look around
_ a move known as a ``spy hop.'' Others, perhaps half a dozen in
all, rasped and exhaled an oily spray that turned
kaleidoscope-colorful as it caught the light. A minute later J pod
dove and vanished as one, and we motored home.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH CAMP
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes from Roche Harbor, we turned into a dirt parking
lot, walked down a forest path and emerged at British Camp _
hallowed ground of what has come to be known as the Pig War.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon Treaty of 1846 ceded Vancouver Island to the British
and everything else south of the 49th parallel to the United
States, but neglected to mention the islands in between. Both
nations coveted them, and for years their settlers coexisted
uneasily.
</P>
<P>
   In 1859, an American farmer, Lyman Cutlar, discovered a
Berkshire boar belonging to the Hudson's Bay Company uprooting his
potato patch. Cutlar shot and killed the pig, the British
threatened to haul him off in irons, and an international incident
was off and running.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Navy dispatched five warships full of Royal Marines,
and the U.S. Army sent an infantry company led by Capt. George E.
Pickett, who later, as a Confederate general, would lend his name
to an ill-considered charge at Gettysburg.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers glared at one another across San Juan Island, but
before the shooting could start, both sides received orders to put
down their rifles. The United States was heading toward civil war,
and Britain was preoccupied by events on the Continent; neither
wanted a war over a tiny archipelago in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The two armies decamped to opposite ends of the island and
eventually became friends, hosting each other to dinner parties and
Christmas celebrations, until the matter was adjudicated by _ of
all people _ Kaiser Wilhelm I of Germany, who awarded the San Juans
to the United States. It was the last armed conflict between the
United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of the Pig War inevitably end with the line, ``and the
only casualty was the pig.'' This isn't quite true. Six Royal
Marines and 16 U.S. soldiers died during the 13-year occupation,
victims of drownings, disease and what a sign at the U.S. cemetery
calls ``a surprising number of suicides.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, British Camp is quiet and serene, with the surprisingly
intact blockade and barracks overlooking pretty Garrison Bay. If
nothing else, it's evidence that the British had a better eye for
real estate than the Americans, who set up camp at the south end of
the island on an exposed, wind-lashed peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FRIDAY HARBOR, Wash.: x x x wind-lashed peninsula. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   LOPEZ ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Lopez Island is known as the most bucolic and flat of the San
Juans, the best venue for a bicycle tour. With that reputation in
mind, we scrimped by renting cheap seven-speed bikes _ a big
mistake, it turned out. ``Most flat,'' we discovered, is not the
same as ``flat.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time we'd pedaled, huffing, up the seemingly endless hill
from the ferry landing into Lopez Village, we were exhausted. To
revive ourselves, we stopped at Holly B's Bakery for some
sensational cinnamon rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Country lanes lined with wild raspberry and blackberry bushes
took us through rolling farmland, past grazing cows, hay bales and
weathered red barns. Almost every residence, we noticed, sported a
whimsical mailbox in the shape of an orca or ferry or some other
island icon.
</P>
<P>
   And just about every motorist we passed _ bearded farmers in
Studebaker pickups; soccer moms in Dodge minivans; aging flower
children in aging rustmobiles _ saluted us with the Lopez Wave, a
subtle lifting of the right index finger off the steering wheel. In
response, I raised my own finger off my handlebar. I felt like a
local.
</P>
<P>
   Bald eagles and Canada geese swooped overhead, and blue herons
and oystercatchers worked the tidal flats. Dark, leaden clouds
gathered, and it began to drizzle. Giving thanks, we cut short our
circuit of the island and, pushing our clunky bikes up the steeper
hills, retreated to Holly B's Bakery.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ORCAS ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   Orcas Island, it turns out, is not named for the local killer
whales, but for the erstwhile viceroy of Mexico, Don Juan Vicente
de Guemes Pancheco y Padilla Orcasitees y Aquayo Conde de Revila
Gigedo. If you go back and look carefully, you'll find an ``Orcas''
in there somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Shaped like an ineptly forged horseshoe, Orcas is the largest of
the San Juans, at 57 square miles, and also the highest, at the
2,407 feet (the summit of Mount Constitution.) It's home to
Eastsound, a pretty little New England-style village of white
clapboard homes and shops; to some of the archipelagos' finest
artisans and craftsmen; to the historic Rosario Resort; and to an
eclectic collection of bed-and-breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   For years, we'd had our eyes on one B&AMP;B in particular: the
Spring Bay Inn. We'd been unable to get reservations on our first
visit, but we got lucky on our second.
</P>
<P>
   Down a long, potholed dirt road on the island's southeast tip,
we were just beginning to give up hope when we arrived at the
elegantly gabled inn. In the common room, with its high, vaulted
ceiling, a fire crackled in the large Rumsford fireplace. Big
picture windows looked out over the inn's private cove _ Spring
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, Carl Burger and Sandy Playa, are former California
park rangers who made a career switch a decade ago. The
half-finished inn they took over and completed has five bedrooms,
each with its own fireplace, four-poster bed and assorted antiques;
one room has its own hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning, we awoke to a tray filled with
croissants, fresh fruit, homemade granola and coffee. Then it was
time for the inn's signature event: A two-hour guided sea kayaking
tour.
</P>
<P>
   On the gravel beach steps from the back door, we donned life
jackets, slid into fiberglass kayaks and paddled out of the cove
into East Sound, with the snowy ridges of the distant Olympic
Mountains rising before us. Playa led the way, while Burger stayed
behind to assemble brunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to lead all the kayak trips and Carl always did the
cooking,'' Playa said. ``But he finally had enough of that
arrangement, and now we switch off every other day.''
</P>
<P>
   We paddled through glassy-still water past a raft of odd-looking
birds with pronounced bumps on their beaks, rhinoceros auklets,
Playa told us. She pointed out a bald eagles' nest, and while I
examined it through my binoculars, two golf ball-like heads popped
up.
</P>
<P>
   In the distance, a wedding-cake ferry pulled out of Lopez Island
and glided silently toward Shaw. On our way back to the inn, we
paddled around the point at Obstruction Pass for a view of snowy
Mount Baker, only to find it cloaked in thick clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the inn, brunch was waiting for us: cornmeal pancakes,
marionberry smoothies, homemade carrot juice, fruit salad and
vegetarian sausage patties.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, I was idly scanning the inn's guest book when I came
across an entry far more literate than the scribblings you usually
find in these things.
</P>
<P>
   The prose style seemed vaguely familiar. In a clear, precise
hand, the author had described his morning paddle: ``. . . the
whistling wings of goldeneye, a few mergansers, eagles like
sentinels in the trees. The cove flat &AMP; green, the madrone-covered
slopes falling fast toward the water. The drone of a float plane,
the passing of a ferry, a surf-scooter traveling low.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's David Guterson, the guy who wrote `Snow Falling on
Cedars,''' explained Burger. ``He stayed with us a couple of years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Guterson had perfectly described my own morning paddle through
the emerald waters of Orcas Island. And, unlike San Pietro, I am
happy to say, this island is quite real.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FRIDAY HARBOR, Wash: x x x is quite real. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Car ferries to the islands leave from Anacortes,
60 miles north of downtown Seattle. The fare from Anacortes to
Friday Harbor for a car with two passengers in summer is about $28.
Note that fares are collected only on westbound ferries. If you
start in Friday Harbor and continue around the islands in a
clockwise direction _ a reasonable thing to do _ you pay only for
the Anacortes-Friday Harbor leg. For more information, phone
800-843-3779 or go to the Web site (www.wsdot.wa.gov/ferries).
</P>
<P>
   An alternative that saves half a day of travel and delivers
breathtaking views is to take a float plane from Seattle's Lake
Union or Lake Washington to Friday Harbor on San Juan Island or
Rosario Resort on Orcas Island. Round-trip fare on Kenmore Air is
$150, weekdays; $160-$175, weekends. Check for Internet specials on
its Web site (www.kenmoreair.com) or phone 800-543-9595.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around: Inter-island ferries are free or under $10,
depending on direction. Car rentals are available from the Inns at
Friday Harbor on San Juan Island and Rosario Resort on Orcas Island
(see below).
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay: On San Juan Island, the Inns at Friday Harbor
offer simple but spacious and clean rooms in downtown Friday
Harbor. Doubles, $79; suites, $89; large two-bedroom suites with
kitchen, $149. 680 Spring St., Friday Harbor, WA 98250; phone:
800-752-5752; fax: 360-378-3725; Web: www.theinns.com.
</P>
<P>
   Venerable Roche Harbor Resort, at the other end of the island,
has its own marina and turn-of-the-century charm. Rooms with shared
bath, $79-$89; private bath, $94-$150. MacMillan Suites, with
fireplaces, $235-$295. P.O. Box 4001, Roche Harbor, WA 98250;
phone: 800-451-8910; fax: 360-378-6809; e-mail:
roche &LR; rocheharbor.com; Web: www.rocheharbor.com.
</P>
<P>
   On Orcas Island, Spring Bay Inn offers rooms with fireplaces,
evening wine tasting, complimentary kayak tours, breakfast and
brunch. Rooms are $195-$235, with a two-night minimum. P.O. Box 97,
Olga, WA 98279; phone: 360-376-5531; fax: 360-376-2193; e-mail:
kayakinn &LR; rockisland.com. At the historic, full-service Rosario
Resort on Orcas Island, rooms start at $188, suites at $252. 1400
Rosario Road, Eastsound, WA 98245; phone: 800-562-8820; fax:
360-376-3680; Web: www.rosario-resort.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat: In Friday Harbor, the Friday Harbor House serves
meals with fresh local ingredients and a great view of the harbor.
Entrees, $15-$24. 130 West St.; phone: 360-378-8455.
</P>
<P>
   On Orcas Island, Cafe Olga's country kitchen turns out salads,
quiches, omelets and Mediterranean-style fare. Lunch only; entrees,
$6-11. If there's a wait _ and there probably will be _ you can
browse the cooperative crafts gallery that shares the building.
East of Morgan State Park at Olga Junction; phone: 360-376-5098.
Roche Harbor Resort on San Juan Island and Rosario Resort on Orcas
Island offer fine dining with sensational views.
</P>
<P>
   What to do: Whale Museum, 62 First St. North, Friday Harbor, WA
98250; phone: 360-378-4710; Web: www.whalemuseum.com. Adults, $5;
children, $2, children.
</P>
<P>
   Whale watching: San Juan Safaris runs three-hour trips out of
Roche Harbor. Adults, $45; children, $35. P.O. Box 2749, Friday
Harbor, WA 98250; 800-450-6858; Web: www.sanjaunsafaris.com. The
outfitter also runs three-hour guided sea kayaking trips for the
same price.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: Washington State Tourism, P.O. Box 42500,
Olympia, WA 98504-2500; phone: 800-544-1800 or 360-586-2088; fax:
360-753-4470; Web: www.experiencewashington.com. For an on-line
