<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REJECTS ATTEMPTS BY STATES TO INTRUDE ON FOREIGN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday unanimously struck down
a Massachusetts law aimed at boycotting companies that do business
in Myanmar, ruling that crucial differences between the state law
and existing federal sanctions against the former Burma
``compromise the very capacity of the president to speak for the
nation with one voice in dealing with other governments.''
</P>
<P>
   Making a rare excursion into the realm of foreign policy, the
court said that under the Constitution's Supremacy Clause, which
gives Congress the power to pre-empt state laws, the Massachusetts
law had to fall because it ``stands in the way of Congress'
diplomatic objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   The court stopped well short of declaring that states have no
constitutionally valid means of taking positions with foreign
policy implications, as many did during years of protest against
the apartheid regime in South Africa. Rather, Justice David H.
Souter's majority opinion focused tightly on the ways in which
Massachusetts' Burma law, adopted in early 1996, was irreconcilable
with a federal law passed by Congress three months later and
carried out by a presidential executive order in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Souter said that while Congress adopted a ``calibration of
force'' policy, giving the president great flexibility to impose or
lift sanctions as a form of diplomatic leverage, the Massachusetts
law was much more categorical in barring state agencies from doing
business in most circumstances with any domestic or foreign company
that conducted business in Myanmar. ``We see the state Burma law as
an obstacle to the accomplishment of Congress' full objectives
under the federal act,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling left proponents of cutting off trade with the Asian
country's repressive military regime with several other possible
approaches, including divestment by public pension funds of the
stock of companies that do business there.
</P>
<P>
   When arguments were heard on March 22 in the case, Natsios vs.
National Foreign Trade Council, 99-474, a comment by Justice
Anthony M. Kennedy foretold the court's ruling. A situation in
which 50 states might conduct 50 different foreign policies would
be ``inconsistent with what the Federalist papers say was the
purpose of forming the union,'' Kennedy remarked.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts law had limited, with strict exceptions,
companies that did business in Myanmar from doing business with the
state. But the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Boston declared
the law invalid, and the high court on Monday said the appeals
court was correct.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration had asked the Supreme Court to rule
as it did. Members of Congress were split on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling may not be the last the court will be asked to
address in the area of ``foreign policy,'' or at least foreign
trade policy, as addressed by states and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen states and dozens of local governments at one time
imposed various sanctions against South Africa. Several were
challenged in court, but they never reached the Supreme Court, and
it might be that that those dormant lawsuits (or others to be
crafted in the future) articulate issues that the justices would
have to consider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
