A8564 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CANCER-ESSAY-NYT &LR;      06-19 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-ESSAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL SHAKEN BY BEING NEAR DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By MICHAEL C. DOHAN, M.D.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adapted from the Annals of Internal Medicine (April 4, 2000)
</P>
<P>
   I am 63 years old and have been living with a form of chronic
leukemia for more than seven years. Two years ago, progression of
my disease forced me to make an important personal decision:
whether to receive a bone marrow transplant, a risky and difficult
procedure. I chose to go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 months of chemotherapy, I qualified for an autologous
bone marrow transplant, one in which my own marrow cells would be
extracted, ``cleaned up'' and re-infused. At first I rejoiced, but
I also soon felt anxiety and doubt.
</P>
<P>
   My hospital room was small and had a special air lock to prevent
infections. Doctors, nurses, my wife and other visitors had to wash
and put on a mask and gloves to enter the room.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the staff addressed me as ``doctor,'' which made me feel
special, but I quickly realized that playing doctor-patient was a
struggle. As much as my professional life in medicine had been
about control, as a patient I needed to let go and trust someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Following intense chemotherapy, I was taken to a small room
where I would receive a lethal dose of radiation. The sessions were
lonely, and as I lay on a trampoline with an X-ray machine above
and below me the clicking of the machines seemed like the ticking
of a bomb. Lethality was always on my mind during my time in
therapy. I thought about the survivors of Hiroshima and Nagasaki,
who had no one waiting in the wings to give them healthy marrow. I
wondered what might happen if something went wrong with my own
marrow and there was none to give back. The progressive and extreme
physical and mental weakness accompanied by constant nausea made me
want to withdraw from the world. I wished at times I could just
say, ``STOP! No more therapy!'' But I never said a word to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   On reflection I am struck by my inability to share my terror.
Perhaps admitting my terror would have made it impossible for me as
a physician to retain my belief in the science of the procedure.
During the radiation therapy, I just wanted to lie in bed and
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the last radiation treatment, my wife was in
the room as my team of doctors and several nurses gathered around
and returned my treated bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   As I recovered, I hung onto every day, hoping it might be the
day I'd go home. But as I approached discharge after three and a
half weeks in the hospital, I became nauseous and prone to dry
heaves. My nurse correctly attributed this to anxiety. That tiny
room, which at times seemed like a cell, was, along with the
support staff, a more important crutch for me than I realized.
</P>
<P>
   Once home, I did not talk to anyone about my experience in the
hospital. When I tried to talk about it, I cried. I was totally
surprised at my own reaction. I suspected that I was suffering from
post-traumatic stress disorder. My wife and I set up an appointment
with a psychiatric social worker. The first meeting was difficult;
I cried more than I talked. But that night, I had the first decent
sleep since coming home.
</P>
<P>
   It is still hard to understand why my experience was so
difficult. Was it because I had never been so sick before? Was it
the experience of being brought so close to death? Was it the
mental and physical helplessness? Was it something about the
therapy? Did a physician's perspective make it more difficult? It
was probably all these, and more.
</P>
<P>
   What I remember now, months later, was my sense of extreme
helplessness, and my inability to muster the strength to fight it.
Visitors helped just being there, but conversation was difficult
and there was little I wanted to do except occasionally listen to
music. Everything was out of my hands. I just had to wait, and
hope. As a doctor, I had always taken pride in caring for others,
and I was the one in charge. I was accustomed to feeling in charge
of my own health, too _ pursuing athletics and embracing a healthy
and vigorous lifestyle. My time in the hospital disrupted that
sense of control so completely that even now, more than a year
later, some emotional fragility remains.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been written about the impersonalization of modern
medical care. The trust we place in our caregivers remains an
essential component in recovering from illness. My own physician
and other providers were with me every step of the way and their
support has been enormously important _ important enough that I
trusted them to kill me, and then bring me back to life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
