<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ELEPHANTS-REPEL-A     06-19 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ELEPHANTS-REPEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT IDEA REPELS CROP-MUNCHING, CRUNCHING ELEPHANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Pa., Mich.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYP1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(Editors: a recipe for dung-pepper appears at end of story.) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Ferrel Loki Osborn loves elephants. But he also
loves the villagers of the Zambezi River Valley in northern
Zimbabwe, whose fields of carefully tended corn, cotton and banana
crops have long tempted elephants looking for a convenient midnight
snack.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the root of Osborn's years-long quest for the
ultimate elephant repellent _ and a potential career shift from
zoologist toward pepper-extract eco-entrepreneur. He has devised a
multipronged array of repellents, some of which rural farmers can
concoct themselves, all using capsaicin, the chemical that puts the
heat in hot peppers.
</P>
<P>
   This 33-year-old elephant expert, reared in Connecticut and
educated at Cambridge, began seeking a solution after he found
himself occasionally helping to shoot ``particularly cheeky'' young
bulls that were repeat offenders, sometimes despoiling fields in an
almost playful cat-and-mouse game with outraged, fearful farmers.
</P>
<P>
   To those who recoil at the thought of an elephant biologist
killing an elephant, he points out that the clash between
pachyderms and people has deadly consequences on both sides: close
to 200 people are crushed or gored by elephants in Zimbabwe each
year, leaving a strong impression in the minds of rural folk whose
hatred for elephants grows, as does the tendency to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Crop-raiding elephants have even become issues in elections in
several African countries, with rural communities demanding an
armed response by the government. The conflict also increases
peoples' resentment toward the parks and preserves that are the
elephants' haven.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Osborn said, a park official visited a
village that had seen the fruits of five months of tilling,
planting and weeding trampled to dust one night. He was tied to a
tree and beaten.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Osborn began studying why some elephants _ even at the height of
the rainy season when there is plenty to eat _ leave forests and
grasslands on moonless nights and pad silently into farms.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to New York City last week, he described his findings
to staff members at the Wildlife Conservation Society in the Bronx,
which has supported his recent work with several grants.
</P>
<P>
   He said crop raids by wildlife had happened ever since humans
first began practicing agriculture, with elephants being part of
the problem both in Africa and Asia at least for centuries. ``There
are Sanskrit records of this in India going back thousands of
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem has intensified in recent years, particularly in
places like northern Zimbabwe, as farmers have pushed farther into
forests seeking fertile soil to grow cotton and corn for cash and
food crops.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Zambezi River, there is an annual rhythm to the raids,
he said, which begin quite abruptly halfway through the wet growing
season, which runs from October to May. ``The trouble usually
starts in February,'' he said. ``They start coming out like
someone's flipped a switch.''
</P>
<P>
   The raiders are usually young bull elephants that roam in small
packs seeking females.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, at least, it appears to be an indulgence, taking
advantage of an easy snack, he said. ``Not to be anthropomorphic,''
Osborn said, ``but their behavior is often like that of young human
males.''
</P>
<P>
   With the aid of professional hunters, Osborn tested whether
shooting a few elephants in a pack of crop-raiding bulls deterred
the survivors from returning. When the presence of an elephant
carcass did not dissuade the others from coming back, he used the
findings to make a case to farming communities that shooting was
not the solution.
</P>
<P>
   But what was?
</P>
<P>
   In some places, costly electric fences have been built, often
with aid from conservation or international development groups, but
Osborn has watched savvy elephants snap the upper wires with their
tusks, then gingerly step over the lower ones. At more than $2,500
for a mile of fence, not counting repairs, this strategy is costly
and impractical, at best, he said.
</P>
<P>
   From days spent hiking in the American West, he said, he
recalled how hot pepper extracts were used in bear repellents. In
the East, they have been used to deter deer, skunks, and squirrels.
They are used in some ant repellents _ and capsaicin is an
ingredient in some self-defense sprays to deter human attackers, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Given elephants' reliance on smell and taste, he said, the
theory was ``it must hurt them 10 times more.''
</P>
<P>
   In Africa, over the last seven years Osborn began experimenting
with ways to use a spray against invading elephants.
</P>
<P>
   The first efforts involved homemade contraptions resembling fire
extinguishers that produced a peppery fog. But these required the
operator to get dangerously close to elephants, and a change in
wind direction meant trouble for the person as well as the animal.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Birochak, a designer of defensive spray devices in Wayne,
Pa., devised a low-tech launcher using pressurized air _ pumped up
with a bicycle pump _ to lob a small pepper-spray grenade 60 or 70
yards.
</P>
<P>
   But that fairly complicated device has since been reserved for
the most recalcitrant elephants, Osborn said.
</P>
<P>
   For the main effort, he has gone several steps further down the
technology ladder, devising a layered pepper defense that starts
with the design of the farm itself.
</P>
<P>
   Many farms in the river valley are laid out rather haphazardly,
with no clearly defined ``edge'' that elephants can recognize. So
he worked with some farmers to help them create a cleared path
between forest and fields. He said elephants' behavior changes when
they venture into fields, showing that they are cognizant that they
are on hostile terrain.
</P>
<P>
   To make a raid more difficult, the farmers then plant hot
peppers and dense, thorny thickets of sisal _ a source of poles and
cord fiber _ around the field perimeter. Elephants tend to avoid
unpalatable or thorny plants, Osborn said.
</P>
<P>
   Next comes the cash crop, generally cotton, which elephants eat
grudgingly. Deepest in the field, the farmers plant the most
desirable food crops, like corn.
</P>
<P>
   Around the edge, he helped villagers at six sites erect a flimsy
pepper-coated fence, consisting only of lengths of rough twine
strung between hand-hewn poles. The strings were smeared with a
mixture of grease and an extremely concentrated extract of
capsaicin from habanero peppers, the hottest of the hot.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper intensity is measured in Scoville units, a system devised
in 1912 by Wilbur Scoville, a Detroit pharmacologist. Jalapeno
peppers rate 2,500 to 5,000 units. The habanero extract used by
Osborn registers 1,000,000 Scoville units.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Osborn imported the substance from American hot-sauce
suppliers, but he is planning to set up a small factory in Zimbabwe
to begin producing the extract from locally grown peppers,
hopefully creating a new market for the country's farmers and
providing a local source of anti-elephant essence.
</P>
<P>
   A research assistant, Kinos Mariba, came up with another weapon:
adobe-like briquettes of elephant dung and ground hot chilies.
</P>
<P>
   On the moonless nights that elephants prefer, farmers set small
fires around their fields. When they hear intruding elephants, they
poke the embers into a blaze, creating a haze of acrid,
trunk-stinging smoke. (The dung does not seem to contribute to the
repellent effect but is simply an abundant burnable medium, he
said.)
</P>
<P>
   The operation, at least for the first year, was a success, he
said. ``You'd see elephants looking with confusion at the tip of
their trunk,'' he said. ``If they pushed through the fence, they
got it on their sides and try to wipe it off with their trunk.''
</P>
<P>
   The response, almost invariably, was that the elephants would
shuffle off in search of easier fare.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   This year, the goal is to see if the farmers at the test sites
pursue the strategy on their own as the growing season approaches.
``This will only work if they want it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While in the United States, he has bought a large supply of
habanero and tabasco pepper seed to bring back to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   A secondary goal, he said, is to create a line of gourmet hot
sauces that could be produced in northern Zimbabwe and sold
internationally to raise money for the elephant research.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the frustrations of being a zoologist is that you don't
really produce anything,'' he said. This way, he said, he may be
able to create jobs, a market for a new crop, and perhaps save a
few elephants _ and a few farmers.
</P>
<P>
   DUNG-PEPPER  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-ELEPHANT BRIQUETTES
</P>
<P>
   (Courtesy Kinos Mariba)
</P>
<P>
   1 pound hot chilies, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds fresh elephant dung.
</P>
<P>
   1. Blend the dung and pounded peppers and form into a brick
shape.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place in the sun for a day or two to harden and dry out.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: Makes one briquette.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
