<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8572 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-PRESIDIO-LADN &LR;      06-19 2575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDIO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDNIGHT AT THE OASIS?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by clients of NYTimes news service) 
(Eds: Fact box included. ART AVAILABLE.) 
By ERIC NOLAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IF YOU GO &QL; 
GETTING THERE: The next time you plan to fly to San Francisco,
consider Oakland Airport _ for two reasons. First, San Francisco
Airport is chronically congested, and prone to heavy fog. If it's
doubtful a flight from Southern California will be able to land on
schedule, the pilot is routinely required to cool his jets on the
ground here before being permitted to take off. Oakland, much
farther inland, is rarely subjected to fog. Second, United Airlines
has a stranglehold on San Francisco and seems to price its flights
accordingly. You can often get a much better fare from Southwest
into Oakland. The drive across the Bay Bridge to the city center
usually takes about 20 minutes. If you drive from the L.A. area,
San Francisco is about 355 miles via Interstates 5 and 580, 440
miles via Highway 101.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDIO PARTICULARS: The easiest approach is probably from
Lombard Street (Highway 101) just south of the Golden Gate Bridge.
In the Marina district, Highway 101 veers sharply right from
Lombard onto Richardson Avenue on its approach to the bridge. To
enter the Presidio, continue on Lombard _ which actually requires
you to get into a left-turn lane to avoid Richardson and the stream
toward the bridge. Once in the park, follow the signs to the Main
Post, where the visitor center is housed. It is open from 9 a.m. to
5 p.m. daily (closed Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Year's Day).
The Presidio is the rare national park that requires no fee to
enter.
</P>
<P>
   LODGING: Hotels in the low $100s are rare in San Francisco, but
you'll find one such option at the no-frills Marina Motel, at 2576
Lombard St. _ just two blocks from the Lombard Gate entrance to the
Presidio. Many rooms open onto an inner courtyard, which blunts the
din of traffic on Lombard. Rooms are almost claustrophobically
small, but who spends any time in a hotel room in San Francisco?
The grounds are lovingly tended, with flower pots and planter boxes
overflowing with geraniums, roses and bougainvillea. Murals are
painted on a couple of the courtyard walls. And this might be the
property's strongest asset: Parking is free and plentiful _ in
garages, no less. Don't judge this place by its exterior. The neon
sign, left over from the 1950s (``Drive In,'' it implores) was
retained for kitsch. Look for it while driving westbound on
Lombard. If you get to Linoleum Larry's, you've gone too far.
Information and reservations: (415) 921-9406 or (800) 346-6118.
</P>
<P>
   DINING: There are some outstanding trattorias in this area,
where seating is confined to a handful of tables and service is so
attentive you feel as if you've dropped in at somebody's house.
Curbside Too, serving country French, is probably the best. Try the
warm goat-cheese salad ($7). Entrees (most in $20s and $30s) are
served with a startling variety of vegetables. The wine prices are
so low, you at first wonder if they are misprints (only $28 for a
1997 Chateau de Bellevue Burgundy Morgan, for example). The chef,
wearing his apron over jeans, twice stopped by our table to make
certain everything was satisfactory. The restaurant is at 2769
Lombard St.; phone (415) 921-4442. Other options: Bistro Aix, 3340
Steiner St., phone (415) 202-0100; and Ristorante Bonta, 2223 Union
St. (in the Pacific Heights district), phone (415) 929-0407.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: The Presidio Visitor Center can be reached at (415)
561-4323. Web: www.nps.govrsf. At Fort Point, efforts are made to
conduct two tours daily, but that hinges on the availability of
volunteers to lead them. It's best to call the morning of the day
you intend to visit: (415) 556-1693. For general tourist
information on San Francisco, call (415) 391-2000. Web:
www.sfvisitor.org &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
An oasis by the Bay &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Once a fortified military base, San Francisco's Presidio is now at
the center of a battle over its future &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Story by Eric Noland/Travel Editor &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ The city presses up against its borders like a
fungus. Walk along Lake, Filbert or Jackson streets and you observe
San Francisco in its quintessence: residences and buildings jammed
together, stacked on top of one another, oozing over every vacant
square foot, conferring priceless value on an unobstructed view of
water or a sliver of parking space.
</P>
<P>
   Cross the boundary, however _ over Lyon Street or West Pacific
Avenue _ and it's as if you've stepped into a different world, a
world in which time literally seems to have stood still.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Presidio, which was a military post for 218 years
and has been a national park for the past six. As San Francisco
real estate boomed over the past century, this 1,480-acre parcel at
the northern tip of the city operated in a federal vacuum,
blissfully oblivious to the burgeoning growth that besieged its
edges. And visitors today are the richer for it.
</P>
<P>
   Here is open space lushly overgrown, winding roads and trails
that follow spectacular coastal bluffs, gullies choked with
forests, and charming buildings that date to the Civil War, with
discreet expanses of undeveloped land around them. This is what
makes the Presidio so unique: It is a sprawling urban oasis on the
edge of the most densely settled city in the West.
</P>
<P>
   It came into being in 1994 as part of the wave of military-base
closures that followed the conclusion of the Cold War. It had been
prime defensive turf since 1776, when Juan Bautista de Anza III
stood on a bluff overlooking the mouth of San Francisco Bay and
determined that this would be the ideal site for an adobe fort to
guard one of New Spain's most important harbors.
</P>
<P>
   Over the ensuing years, it would be home to Union Army garrisons
during the Civil War, a biplane airfield in the early 1900s, a
defense-intelligence training ground for Japanese-American soldiers
during World War II ... and home to more varieties of menacing
cannons than you can count.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all of this, the post has long been a fairly open
environment. San Franciscans could wander in for a walk or a picnic
or a romantic moment, knowing that they might encounter nothing
more disconcerting than an armed patrol tramping by. In the few
years since the National Park Service replaced the Sixth Army as
the Presidio's steward, visitors to the city have begun to discover
it _ and embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the park is very much in a state of flux. While the
Presidio was a pretty peaceful place during its military days (even
during the Bear Flag Revolt of 1846, U.S. Commodore Robert F.
Stockton referred to his ``quiet and undisturbed possession of the
defenseless port''), it is now a battleground involving the park
service, the Presidio Trust, and San Francisco's active
environmental and no-change-now-that-I'm-here groups.
</P>
<P>
   Congress decreed four years ago that the Presidio would have to
be a self-sufficient enterprise by 2013, and the Presidio Trust was
commissioned with the task of generating the park's $35 million
annual operating budget. That is to be done by leasing former
military buildings for commercial and residential uses. A plan to
let filmmaker George Lucas raze a fabulously ugly hospital to build
a movie production center has drawn particular fire.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the remainder of the park is a hive of activity.
Renovations are planned for some of the Presidio's 510 historic
buildings, many of which are great to look at but are barely
habitable. A new visitor center and museum is due to open next
month. And Crissy Field, an area of bay frontage that was used for
landfill in the less environmentally sensitive time of 1915, is
being restored to its original state as a tidal marsh.
</P>
<P>
   Even as these projects proceed _ and the various factions
wrestle over whether the existing buildings are destined to become
a bustling business park _ the Presidio remains a delightful place
to visit. There are remote paths that afford stunning views of the
Golden Gate Bridge and the craggy coastline below the bluffs. There
are narrow, squiggly lanes ideal for bicycle riding and other forms
of exertion. There are fascinating buildings that provide a kind of
architectural timeline of the post. There is rich history of
military vigilance at the entrance to the bay, even though,
thankfully, it was never tested.
</P>
<P>
   Any visit to the Presidio should begin with a stop at the
visitor center, which occupies a corner of the centrally located
Main Post (near the corner of Montgomery Street and Lincoln
Boulevard, just west of the Lombard Gate entrance to the park).
This stop is essential for one reason only: to acquire a map.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike San Francisco itself, which is laid out in a reassuring
grid of streets, the Presidio's roads date to horse-and-buggy days,
and they twist and turn along the natural contours of the land.
Thus, plunking down $2.71 for the Official Map &AMP; Guide to the
Presidio of San Francisco, published by the Golden Gate National
Parks Association, is sure to spare you a good deal of aggravation.
</P>
<P>
   During my visit in May, a tourist pulled her car to a sudden
halt within a few feet of me and, in obvious exasperation, asked
for directions to ``the road back to the city.'' She had been
driving in circles _ less than half a mile from one of the exits.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to explore the Presidio's hidden delights
is to take a walk on some portion of the Coastal Trail, which
meanders 1.5 miles from near the southern promontory of San
Francisco Bay to the broad expanse of Baker Beach along the Pacific
Ocean. (The map is helpful here, too, because the path isn't
particularly well-marked.)
</P>
<P>
   Over its course, the trail passes beneath the Golden Gate
Bridge, picks its way along coastal bluffs and skirts seven
different gun-battery sites from different eras, including some
earthen-work defenses that date to 1876.
</P>
<P>
   Take your camera. The trail affords some stunning views of the
Golden Gate Bridge, sometimes through breaks in the verdant forest.
For one of the best views of the bridge, locate the concrete shell
that is Battery Boutelle (it's on the map), climb its staircase and
iron ladder, and venture out to the edge of the bluff.
</P>
<P>
   Early one weekday morning, the trail was all but deserted. The
hum of inbound commuters approaching the bridge toll booth on
Highway 101 competed with the deep, plaintive blasts of foghorns.
The morning fog was so thick that it collected on tree boughs and
dripped like rain. Wildflowers along the trail were shoulder-high
in some stretches. The air was rich with the scent of cypress
needles. Waves assaulted the rocks far below. And the city felt
far, far away.
</P>
<P>
   Another popular walk is the Ecology Trail, which describes a
two-mile loop at the center of the Presidio grounds, beginning and
ending at the Main Post. Along this route, you'll get a sense of
the Army's prodigious tree-planting efforts in the final few years
of the 19th century. The Army stuck 100,000 trees in the ground
over an 11-year period, mostly eucalyptus, Monterey cypress and
Monterey pine. Today, the park service and the trust lament the
fact that the soldiers didn't choose trees native to California,
but why quibble? The forests are nonetheless lush and beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   At many points along the path, flowers grow in thick patches,
brightening the landscape with clusters of nasturtium and San
Francisco lessingia.
</P>
<P>
   Near its conclusion, the walk follows a ramrod-straight stretch
lined with street lamps. This is Lovers' Lane, so named because in
the 1860s it was the primary route for soldiers headed for town.
</P>
<P>
   On its final leg toward the Main Post, the walk crosses an 1885
footbridge over El Polin Creek. Alas, this quaint, 115-year-old
structure has been despoiled with spray-paint graffiti _ one of the
unfortunate byproducts of increased public access to a former
military reservation. It makes you wish the area was still
patrolled by sticklers for order with fixed bayonets.
</P>
<P>
   The Main Post itself is laid out in precise, military fashion, a
tidy rectangle configured around a former parade ground. Typical _
although the beauty of San Francisco Bay lies about a quarter-mile
away _ not one building has a bay-view aspect.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of historic architecture on this post, and some
of the most intriguing buildings are right here, along Funston
Avenue. They are former officers' quarters, dating to 1862, built
in Queen Anne/Stick style. Stroll among these structures and you
might feel as if you're in a small town in Pennsylvania,
contemplating the latest act of President Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   The Presidio grounds feature some hidden quirks _ including a
cemetery where the pets of some post residents were buried _ as
well as several locales that have been well-trodden by visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Baker Beach stretches along the Pacific coast in the southwest
corner of the park. Once again, the views of the Golden Gate Bridge
to the north are terrific, especially if you're lucky enough to
find it partly shrouded in fog. However, parents with young
children and those of modest sensibilities should be forewarned:
Baker Beach appears to be exceedingly popular with San Francisco's
aging, overweight male nudists.
</P>
<P>
   For history buffs, Fort Point is a favorite. Docents dress up in
Civil War uniforms and conduct free, hour-long tours of the
prison-like fortress that stands in the shadow of the Golden Gate
Bridge's southern footings. Our guide, Chris Burgin, was
exceptionally knowledgeable, holding interest even as most of us
shivered in the drafty, depressing edifice of granite, brick and
concrete that was commissioned in 1850 to protect the newest state
in the union.
</P>
<P>
   On a walk through the former powder magazine, we were told that
soldiers commonly put their socks on over the shoes before
entering, because a shoe nail striking a floorboard nail could
generate a disastrous spark.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the sun was shining on the Golden Gate Promenade, a
broad, three-mile path that hugs the edge of the bay from Fort
Point nearly to Fisherman's Wharf. It seemed a welcomed antidote to
the bowels of the fort, but it passes alongside the massive
construction project that is the Crissy Field restoration, so it
figures to have considerably more appeal when the work is completed
next spring. Even so, it was crawling with walkers, joggers,
cyclists and skaters.
</P>
<P>
   In its six years as a national park, the Presidio has proven to
be quite a curiosity, and its positioning on the edge of a major
city has undoubtedly contributed to a crush of visitation. Some 14
million people wander through here annually, according to park
spokesman Roger Scott. Thus, it ranks behind only Great Smoky
Mountains National Park (in North Carolina and Tennessee) in
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the equivalent of Central Park,'' said Scott, who came
to the Presidio from the nation's only other urban national park,
New York's Gateway. ``With the environmental concern that
Californians have, and certainly the awareness that San Franciscans
have, they want to hold on to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifics of the Presidio's future use might be uncertain as it
strives for self-sufficiency, but there is probably little cause to
fret that its unique ambience will be significantly altered. There
are precious few urban treasures such as this.
</P>
<P>
   Sentries have been posted to make sure it remains so. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
