<HEADER>
A8574 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-CHESTNUT-STREET-LADN &LR;      06-19 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHESTNUT-STREET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SIMPLE CHARM OF CHESTNUT STREET
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by clients of NYTimes news service) 
Eds: ART AVAILABLE 
 
 
By ERIC NOLAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The appeal of San Francisco lies in the fact
that its many parts produce such a delightful sum. More than a
city, it is confederation of neighborhoods, each with a distinct
sense and soul.
</P>
<P>
   One such region is Chestnut Street, a five-block stretch of
simplicity, charm and funk in the Marina district, tucked neatly
between the Presidio and Fisherman's Wharf. Chances are, you've
passed very near to it without being aware of its existence. It
lies parallel to Lombard Street, which serves northbound Highway
101 traffic on what for many is a hell-bent dash toward the Golden
Gate Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Next time, slow down, turn off and explore a tiny San Francisco
neighborhood that is as comfortable as an old bedroom slipper. No
tourist promenade this. It is a working street, with an independent
grocery store, two ancient movie theaters, several Chinese-run
laundries and dry cleaners, even a shoe-repair shop that appears to
be stubbornly resisting the digital revolution (its shelves are
stacked with old cardboard boxes holding laces, heels, soles).
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, there are small eateries and coffee houses _ most
with sidewalk tables _ that have no affiliation with any national
chains.
</P>
<P>
   As you stroll along Chestnut between Divisadero and Fillmore,
you might notice that the crowd seems primarily composed of
neighborhood residents, and there is almost a European feel to the
place. Planter boxes brim with flowers on the sidewalk and
second-story window ledges. An elegantly dressed lady was seen
guiding two yappy dogs on leashes into the Pottery Barn (OK, there
are a few chain outlets), and nobody so much as blinked. In a
convenience store early one morning, not only was the TV off, but
the shop was filled with the gentle strains of Mozart's Piano
Concerto No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   This is a great place to browse through shops or catch a bite to
eat. Or both. A few of the highlights (Chestnut Street addresses in
parentheses):
</P>
<P>
   Earthsake (2076) is a narrow, deep, airy shop with an impressive
selection of untreated fabrics in linens, clothing and bedding
items. It also stocks an eclectic supply of greeting cards, candles
and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of enormous, impersonal Staples and Office Depot
outlets, it's encouraging to find an independent stationery store,
Kimmel's (2144), with about 10 feet of street frontage _ but,
somehow, carrying just about everything you'd require.
</P>
<P>
   The Marina Super grocery store (2323) displays its produce in
bins on the sidewalk. It also has a butcher shop. And when was the
last time you encountered a market that promised free delivery?
</P>
<P>
   Mathray's Flowers (2395) also makes maximal use of the sidewalk,
exhibiting many of its colorful and pleasantly scented wares there.
</P>
<P>
   Books Inc. (2251) is part of a small Bay Area chain of a
half-dozen stores. The rear quarter of this store is devoted
entirely to children's books, its walls colorfully painted in
cartoon characters. The shop also carries a selection of
international newspapers and features a great number of books on
cooking, gardening and travel.
</P>
<P>
   You might wonder how Frank's Shoe Service (2412) can subsist
entirely on replacing worn heels or securing loose luggage straps,
but a sign in the window offers a clue: The proprietor bills
himself as an expert on Birkenstock sandals. In this corner of the
Bay Area, that probably means he'll be able to retire early.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut Street also features several inviting cafes, delis and
coffee houses. Don't be surprised, however, if cash is the only
form of payment accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The Grove (2250), a popular locals hangout, is a friendly place
to stop for morning coffee or breakfast _ and it will keep you out
of a cookie-cutter Starbucks down the street. The Grove offers six
different gourmet coffee drinks daily. Be advised that the
breakfast menu leans heavily toward vegetarian items.
</P>
<P>
   For heartier fare at breakfast or lunch, it's hard to beat
Judy's Cafe (2268). The portions are substantial and diverse,
including a breakfast scramble featuring smoked salmon, Bermuda
onions and cream cheese. Andale Taqueria (2150) can also attack a
robust appetite with its mesquite-grill Mexican items.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for sandwiches for a picnic on the grounds of
the Presidio, the best option is probably Lucca Delicatessen
(2120), an Old World deli that is worth a stop just for the rich
smells within. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
