<HEADLINE>
L.A. BECOMES ECLECTIC
</HEADLINE>
  Hollywood Bowl expands program 
to accommodate more world music 
(For use after Tues., June 20, 2000 by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On that fateful day in 1963 when he first heard John Coltrane's
``India,'' Tom Schnabel suddenly realized there was more to popular
music than do-wop and surfer ditties.
</P>
<P>
   Coltrane's music ``was putting me into a trance state,''
Schnabel writes in ``Rhythm Planet,'' his highly readable 1998
collection of essays on world music makers.
</P>
<P>
   Henceforward, the Palisades High School student was ``on a
journey, a search for something deeper than what my life as a
middle-class adolescent in a Southern California suburb had to
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven years later, Schnabel's polyglot musical tastes
have helped refashion those of his once-provincial hometown. As the
former host of KCRW-FM's groundbreaking ``Morning Becomes
Eclectic'' from 1979 to 1989, and now host of the station's popular
weekend program ``Cafe L.A.,'' Schnabel has introduced many
Angelenos to such globally far-flung performers as Youssou N'Dour,
Caetano Veloso and Angelique Kidjo. He has also produced several
world music CD compilations, taught world music at UCLA and
consulted on several motion picture soundtracks.
</P>
<P>
   Now Schnabel has another bully pulpit for proselytizing the
polyrhythmic gospel.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday evening, the Hollywood Bowl will launch its 79th
season with the first of six ``World Music'' concerts programmed by
Schnabel and sponsored by KCRW. Dubbed ``Fiery Flamenco,'' the
concert will explore various global permutations of Spain's
propulsive dance music.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the Bowl's inaugural ``World Festival 1999'' drew
50,000 listeners to hear acts like Tex-Mex accordion master Flaco
Jimenez, superstar Celtic fiddler Natalie MacMaster (who returns
here July 30) and Rahat Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan, heir apparent to the
late Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan, king of Pakistan's Sufi devotional
singers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two seasons, the addition of ``World Festival,''
and an eight-concert jazz series headlined by L.A.'s
Clayton-Hamilton Jazz Orchestra, have substantially altered the
Bowl's cultural topography.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly but steadily, the venue's longtime diet of classical and
pops, served by white-coated musicians to the wicker-hamper crowd,
has given way to a funkier, more wide-ranging musical smorgasbord.
Just as the Beach Boys' wistful harmonies no longer exclusively
define the Southern California sound, the Bowl has come to reflect
the rapidly mutating tastes of the diverse city that encircles it.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. is not the same place I grew up in the '50s and the
1960s, and I think it's better,'' says Schnabel, who's been
appointed program manager of world music for the Los Angeles
Philharmonic Association. ``I think a more multicultural society is
(more stimulating) than one where everybody is sort of like someone
in a Henrik Ibsen play.''
</P>
<P>
   For world music aficionados, this summer is shaping up as one of
L.A.'s richest ever. The Bowl's six subscription concerts offer
intriguing pairings of established and lesser-known artists. Many
trace their overlapping musical bloodlines to the mass exodus of
native Africans to the New World.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``Global Divas,'' a July 16 concert hosted by
current ``Morning Becomes Eclectic'' frontman Nic Harcourt, links
South African song empress Miriam Makeba with Albita, the
androgynous platinum-blond avatar of classic Cuban !ital!guajiras
</P>
<P>
   and !italsons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiery Flamenco'' combines French gypsy guitarist Thierry
``Titi'' Robin-Gitans with Del Monte Flamenco/Anjani's Kathak, a
troupe that melds Moorish-influenced Spanish dance and kathak, the
classical dance form favored by the Rajastan court of India. A
separate, non-subscription Bowl concert on July 1, ``Tropical
Serenades,'' showcases Grammy-winning, falsetto-voiced Brazilian
Milton Nascimento alongside Juan-Carlos Formell's supple guitar
evocations of his Cuban homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Other world music attractions playing L.A. this summer include
the great South African jazz-pop horn player Hugh Masekela, June 29
at the California Plaza Watercourt downtown; the Jewish-fusion
ensemble the Klezmatics, July 9 at the John Anson Ford Amphitheatre
in Hollywood; and a free Aug. 24 zydeco double bill at the Santa
Monica Pier.
</P>
<P>
   Want more ululating vocalists and swinging reggae-sambaists? You
may want to book ahead for the Bowl's Aug. 2 jazz series concert
profiling Cuban pianist Chucho Valdes and his quartet. Even this
past weekend's Playboy Jazz Festival had a distinctly Latin flavor.
</P>
<P>
   David Prather, an actor who's in his fourth year of hosting the
annual kid-oriented ``Open House at the Hollywood Bowl,'' thinks
world music has helped fill a kind of spiritual void in mainstream
Western pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of the pop music in America has been either just
innocuous on one level or nihilistic,'' Prather says, ``and you
listen to your basic salsa or South African music and it's so
vibrant, so positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Bowl is suddenly turning its back on its
traditional pops and classical constituency in favor of ``world
music,'' a dubious moniker that's been applied to everything from
Congolese rumba to Celtic pop.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Bowl's 70 performance events between June and September,
29 are pops concerts, 25 are classical, nine are jazz-oriented and
seven are world music. The Bowl's prime Friday and Saturday night
slots are reserved for the Los Angeles Philharmonic and its pops
counterpart, the Hollywood Bowl Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   But after drawing 50,000 total listeners last summer, when it
was lumped in with Sunday-night pops concerts, world music has been
granted its own separate subscription series this season. Patricia
Mitchell, chief operating officer of the Los Angeles Philharmonic
Association, says her organization is still testing the depth of
local interest in the catch-all world genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year does not a trend make,'' Mitchell says.
</P>
<P>
   However, anecdotal evidence and solid box-office numbers
convinced the Philharmonic to continue the series begun last year
under departed Philharmonic executive vice president and managing
director Willem Wijnbergen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have only to go through Tower Records and see the
expanding world music section to see there's a tremendous interest
in world music and in world music marketing,'' says Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Wijnbergen's mysterious and abrupt departure from the
Philharmonic last June, after only 15 months on the job, raised
questions about the long-term outlook for jazz and world music at
the Bowl, two of the Dutch-born administrator's pet projects.
(Wijnbergen has declined to speak with reporters since leaving the
organization.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet Schnabel believes that ``the Bowl still has its heart'' in
world music.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, evidence abounds that Los Angeles has reached a
critical mass of world music culture and appreciation. Relatively
new clubs like the Conga Room in the Mid-Wilshire District
regularly pack the floor with salsa and samba devotees. Schnabel
credits outgoing UCLA Performing Arts director Michael Blachly with
helping to popularize world music here through his support of
artists like Cesaria Evora, Zap Mama and Baaba Maal.
</P>
<P>
   Schnabel also points to the 1984 Olympic Arts Festival as a
local world beat watershed, when innovative avant-gardists like
Peter Sellars gave Angelenos ``a big taste of maybe something we
weren't even ready for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was sort of a turning point in terms of exposure to some
really new stuff,'' Schnabel says, ``and I think that the lesson
was not lost on presenters.''
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, world music's rising commercial profile is
evidenced by the mass-market appeal of pop stars like Ricky Martin
as well as the astonishing crossover success of Buena Vista Social
Club.
</P>
<P>
   As global culture grows into a vital two-way exchange _ not
simply a cliched cross-pollination of ``Third World primitivism''
with Western technological know-how _ Schnabel believes that
Americans' cultural attitudes are becoming much more cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   Until relatively recently, he said, ``People didn't travel as
much, people didn't have the curiosity about Sufism or the Dalai
Lama, America was so kind of insular and in love with itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Schnabel says, ``People are getting acupuncture and reading
Rumi (the 13th-century mystic poet Jalaluddin Rumi) and Deepak
Chopra. They're so much more receptive to different ways of seeing
things. I think that's part of the reason for the acceptance of
world music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
