<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8584 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-PRAYER-HNS &LR;      06-19 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PRAYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT BANS STUDENT-LED PRAYERS BEFORE FOOTBALL GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Strictly upholding the wall between church and
state, the Supreme Court ruled Monday that a Texas school district
violated the Constitution when it allowed a student to lead prayers
before high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   In a sweeping, 6-3 decision, the court said that by granting the
student the right to use the school's public address system to
speak to a large gathering at a school-sponsored event, the local
board of education gave preferential treatment to a particular
religious viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``School sponsorship of a religious message is impermissible''
because it tells ``nonadherents'' in the audience ``that they are
outsiders, not full members of the political community, and (it
sends) an accompanying message to adherents that they are insiders,
favored members of the political community,'' Justice John Paul
Stevens wrote for the majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delivery of such a message _ over the school's public
address system by a speaker representing the student body, under
the supervision of school faculty and pursuant to a school policy
that explicitly and implicitly encourages public prayer _ is not
properly characterized as private speech,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the Constitution ... prohibits any public school
student from voluntarily praying at any time before, during or
after the school day. But the religious liberty protected by the
Constitution is abridged when the state affirmatively sponsors the
particular religious practice of prayer,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Stevens were Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M.
Kennedy, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G.
Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Bagenstos, a Harvard law professor, noted that the ruling
strongly reaffirmed the court's 1962 landmark decision banning
organized school prayer. ``This decision is consistent with the
court's traditional stance of keeping a pretty high wall between
church and state,'' Bagenstos added.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' last major ruling on school prayer came in 1992.
In that decision, the court, by a slim 5-to-4 vote, barred
clergy-led prayers, invocations and benedictions at public school
graduation ceremonies.Monday's ruling _ which comes as many school
districts around the country are considering ways to allow prayer
in public schools _ should give officials more precise instructions
on how to avoid the constitutional minefield in church-state
relations, Bagenstos said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of school prayer denounced the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who had filed a brief urging the
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court to uphold such student-led prayer, said, ``I
support the constitutionally guaranteed right of all students to
express their faith freely and participate in voluntary student-led
prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Vice President Al Gore, also running for president,
</P>
<P>
   had no immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jan LaRue, a spokeswoman for the Family Research Council, a
Washington-based conservative group, said, ``Allowing students to
speak about their faith in public in their own words does not
create a government endorsement of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of school prayer hailed the majority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's decision signals a reaffirmation of the
appropriate role of religion in public schools _ one in which
private religious expression is constitutionally protected, but
officially sanctioned religious observances are not,'' said David
Harris, executive director of the American Jewish Committee, a New
York City-based civil rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas case began in 1995 when the Santa Fe Independent
School District, located near Galveston, was sued by two families,
one Catholic and one Mormon, who objected to the policy of letting
students elect a classmate as ``chaplain'' to lead prayers at
graduation ceremonies and home football games.
</P>
<P>
   After their lawsuit was filed, the policy was changed. Under the
new rules, the student body each year elected a student to deliver
a ``message or invocation'' before the home games and at graduation
ceremonies. It was up to the elected invocation leader to decide
whether to deliver a prayer or other more general, inspirational
comments.
</P>
<P>
   The school district maintained that the election and the
invocation leader's choice in selecting the content insulated the
district from impermissible entanglement in promoting religious
conduct. Instead, they argued, any prayer led by the invocation
leader is protected free speech that the courts are powerless to
block.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in the
case that students had to keep their graduation-ceremony comments
and prayers ``nonsectarian and non-proselytizing.'' The court also
decided that the student-led prayers at high school football game
were unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   School officials appealed both parts of that ruling, but the
Supreme Court focused Monday only on the football game issue,
passing up the graduation-ceremony dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, in upholding the ban on any student-led prayer before
the games, said the court recognizes ``the important role that
public worship plays in many communities, as well as the sincere
desire to include public prayer as a part of various occasions so
as to mark those occasions' significance.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``Such religious activity in public schools, as
elsewhere, must comport with the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, who wrote the dissenting
opinion supported by Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas,
said the majority ruling ``bristles with hostility to all things
religious in public life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist said the school's policy of allowing students the
right to vote for a representative to speak before the games and
then allowing that representative the freedom to choose the subject
of the speech meant that the district never ``endorsed or
encouraged'' prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sekulow, who represented the Santa Fe school district in
arguments last March before the high court, said the ruling ``will
interject additional confusion into the area of protected religious
expression in the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steven R. Shapiro, legal director of the New York-based
American Civil Liberties Union, said the Court's decision affirmed
the principle that the Constitution does not allow school officials
to hold elections to decide whether and when students should pray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's ruling should effectively put an end to so-called
student-initiated prayer at all school sponsored events, including
graduation,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
