<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WORDS OF WISDOM FOR WORLD TRAVELERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN FLINN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably the most useful piece of travel advice I was ever given
was: ``Never pack anything you have to plug in, iron or worry about
losing.'' Probably the second-best was: ``Every glass of `free'
mint tea you drink in a Moroccan carpet shop will end up costing
you $600.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of us has a few nuggets of hard-won road wisdom, perhaps
half-forgotten and languishing in some dusty corners of our minds.
As we pull out our suitcases in preparation for summer adventures,
I asked some fellow travelers to share their best advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just landed in a strange city and want to find a great
restaurant? Tell your taxi driver, `Take me to where you would go
if you wanted to propose marriage.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Sterling, author of ``The Fearless Diner``
</P>
<P>
   ``Pause should be taken before drinking alcohol served in
bottles without labels.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Amanda Jones, writer
</P>
<P>
   ``What most people regard as travel is actually a vacation.
Travel at its most enlightening is an ordeal. Afterwards, you need
a vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul Theroux, who would like to remind us all that his new
book, ``Fresh Air Fiend,'' is now in stores
</P>
<P>
   ``Cahill's Expedition Rule 1: Absolutely no one is interested in
the nature, quality or content of your last bowel movement.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Cahill, writer
</P>
<P>
   ``Silence may be golden, but in France you're better off with a
platinum tongue and steely nerves: Stand up and shout; you'll be
respected.''
</P>
<P>
   _ David Downie, writer
</P>
<P>
   ``In India, the first sign of a problem is when your guide (or a
bureaucrat) says, `No problem!'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lynn Ferrin, writer
</P>
<P>
   ``Never pack more than you can run with.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Christine Delsol, assistant travel editor, San Francisco
Examiner
</P>
<P>
   ```Five more minutes' uttered by a Sherpa can mean anything up
to four hours; it's said to keep their trekkers going.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Norbu Tenzing Norgay, American Himalayan Foundation
</P>
<P>
   ``No place ever looks as fresh as when you see it feeling
stale.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Thomas Swick, travel editor, South Florida Sun-Sentinel
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprises in store for the innocent traveler: A French letter
in Ireland, a dog dish in the Philippines, a Dutch cap in
England.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Theroux
</P>
<P>
   ``On puddle-jumper airlines, the larger the flight number, the
smaller the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Me
</P>
<P>
   ``While a guest in an Arab home, don't admire anything too much.
Your host will feel obliged to give it to you.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sterling
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't think it's possible for a flight from Los Angeles
to Rio de Janeiro to be 19 hours late because of a snowstorm in
Japan, you haven't traveled much.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Murphy, San Francisco Examiner
</P>
<P>
   ``When three guidebooks recommend the same restaurant, consider
asking a local for another suggestion.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bruce P. Gerstman, writer
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the flight, the greater the chance of an obnoxious
seat mate.''
</P>
<P>
   _ John Macdonald, travel editor, Seattle Times
</P>
<P>
   ``In Russia, vodka bottles are generally not restoppable. If one
is opened, it is meant to emptied.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sterling
</P>
<P>
   ``Nepal stands for Never Ending Peace and Love, India for I'll
Never Do It Again.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike McIntyre, Wander Year columnist for the Los Angeles Times
</P>
<P>
   ``The higher you climb, the better you think the view is.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Christopher Hall, writer
</P>
<P>
   ``The more heinous the experience now, the better the story
later.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jones
</P>
<P>
   ``If tourists don't go there, maybe there's a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Me
</P>
<P>
   ``In Italy if a restaurant's name includes words such as vecchio
(old), antico (ancient) or piccolo (small), rest assured that it
will be neither ancient, nor old, nor small _ and certainly not
cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Downie
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a mistake to travel to India with the Kama Sutra in
mind. On the other hand, Joyce's `Ulysses' is a great guide to
Dublin.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Theroux
</P>
<P>
   ``If, as Nelson Algren once said, you should never eat at a
place called `Mom's' or play poker with a man named `Doc,' nor
should you ever enter an establishment that advertises
`folklore.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Swick
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how hot the plane seems at the start of the flight,
get a blanket.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Murphy
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine is not a drink it Italy; it's a liquid food.
Overindulgence is offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sterling
</P>
<P>
   ``Pooh-pooh McDonald's in foreign countries all you want _ until
you're desperate for a clean restroom.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Me
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the sad truths of travel that no place is exotic
once you are in it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Swick
</P>
<P>
   ``If you drink hard liquor before a meal in France, your hosts
will shake their heads with that special bemused disdain they
reserve for foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sterling
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to eat street food, don't take the stuff
that's been sitting there, attracting flies; make the vendor cook
one just for you.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Me
</P>
<P>
   ``When they say, `Don't pet the animals,' take the advice very,
very seriously.'' _ Jones
</P>
<P>
   ``Wanting to go someplace is as important as going there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Seamus O'Banion, writer
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Swiss had designed the Alps they would have been much
flatter.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Theroux
</P>
<P>
   ``In France, if you cut the cheese, avoid disturbing the `nose'
_ the French get very upset if you cut the tip off their precious
curds.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Downie
</P>
<P>
   ``Travel is like having a child: it never seems to be the right
time, but if you let it happen, the rewards are inestimable, and
last a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Larry Habegger, editor, Travelers' Tales Books
</P>
<P>
   ``Every trip we take is a sobering reminder of how much we don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Swick
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
