<P>
   DAYTON HEARTLAND POLITICAL PROJECT
</P>
<P>
   Part 3 OF 5 PARTS
</P>
<P>
   HEARTLAND-ILLINOIS _ Summer in Illinois means heat. Sun baked
farmers worry about drought. Sweaty Chicagoans crank their air
conditioners during the first steam bath, then wait for the city's
electrical distribution system to overload and crash. Cubs fans
grouse about beer sales being cut off in the sixth inning at
Wrigley Field. This year's heat will create a torpid calm before a
political storm. Illinois is among a handful of states predicted to
hold the key to the White House in this year's presidential
election. Its huge, ancestral Democratic clubs of Chicago are
evenly offset by its suburban and downstate voters whose inborn
conservativism dates to the days of the prairie schooner and helped
spawn the Republican party. And then there is the Peoria factor.
The phrase ``does it play in Peoria,'' is shorthand for whether an
idea will get support from the nation's vast political middle. That
middle ground _ found in Peoria as well as places like Dayton,
Ohio, Midland, Mich. and Allentown, Pa., _ is where many expect the
White House to be won or lost. (Bebbington, Dayton Daily News). 60.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS-BAR _ The political battleground in Illinois has always
been the line between Democrat-steeped Chicago and the Land of
Lincoln-Republicans everywhere else. In 2000, those two groups face
off in Will County. (Bebbington, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
