<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8616 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-19 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RICHARDSON TAKES THE FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Scrub Energy Secretary Bill Richardson as a
potential running mate for Vice President Al Gore this fall.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame, really. Richardson is a smart politician with a
big heart. He is an energetic campaigner and a jolly soul spilling
over with the warm comradery that Gore can't seem to muster.
</P>
<P>
   But public figures with the whiff of scandal about them do not
get named to national presidential tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The security problems that have surfaced at the Los Alamos
National Laboratory are not Richardson's fault. But the controversy
happened on his watch, and Republicans are determined to hold him
accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Whoopee! Another Clinton administration scandal to hype just
when earlier ones were petering out.
</P>
<P>
   Several GOP senators promptly called for Richardson's head after
it was discovered that two computer hard drives containing secret
data on nuclear weapons were missing at Los Alamos for weeks. They
were recently found tucked behind a copying machine under murky and
alarming circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   (Maybe there's a poltergeist around. Remember how Hillary
Clinton's long-lost law firm billing records mysteriously appeared
one day on a White House table? No one has yet acknowledged having
a hand in either the disappearance or the amazing recovery.)
</P>
<P>
   The call for Richardson's resignation is a predictable political
response. But even the Republicans seem more interested in throwing
mud on the administration than in actually forcing Richardson out.
</P>
<P>
   Sen Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Select
Committee on Intelligence, launched a campaign to make Richardson
the poster boy for every security breach that has popped up lately.
This includes missing documents at the State Department and CIA,
with which Richardson has absolutely no connection.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott agreed: ``There's a pattern in
this administration of laxity on security,'' he said ominously.
</P>
<P>
   Security issues are complicated by the fact that they are of
necessity surrounded by secrecy. The details that surface publicly
are seldom the whole story. But in politics facts often matter less
than the appearance of things. And it appears that officials are
entirely too careless with information that may harm our interests
if it falls into what is euphemistically called ``the wrong
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's basic problem is that he overpromised and his
department didn't deliver. Last year scary allegations were made
that scientist Wen Ho Lee had stolen nuclear secrets from the lab
to give to China. The affair created quite a stink although Lee has
not been charged with espionage and the allegations against him
remain unproven.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Richardson stoutly shouldered all responsibility
for lab security and promised that he had made policy changes to
henceforth protect national secrets. Now he looks like a braggart
who is all hat and no cattle.
</P>
<P>
   In this, Richardson is not alone. Most administrations have
sheltered Cabinets containing lots of proven braggarts. There are
worse things.
</P>
<P>
   But as the campaign season's hot new Republican target,
Richardson would poison the Democratic ticket. Gore will look
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, weighed in on the issue
to blame the administration for ``confusion and chaos'' at Los
Alamos. But security laxity may be an awkward issue for him.
</P>
<P>
   His father's administration established the current relaxed
attitude toward handling ``secret'' data with new rules that
reduced safeguards previously in place. The looser accounting
procedures were not supposed to affect material classified ``top
secret,'' but such distinctions are known to become blurred.
</P>
<P>
   The information on the formerly missing Los Alamos hard drives
was classified ``secret'' rather than ``top secret'' even though
they contained data on the wiring and design of U.S., Russian and
other nuclear warheads that could be used by terrorists. In the
aftermath of the Lee case, an internal debate has raged among
security experts about whether to reclassify certain sensitive
information. The debate remains unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is conducting a criminal probe into the missing hard
drives and is focusing on a few scientists who gave contradictory
answers on polygraph tests. This story will go on for some time,
and Richardson will be forever tarnished even if it turns out the
discs were simply misplaced by accident with no intention of
spying.
</P>
<P>
   We non-scientists aren't experts on what exactly it is that goes
on at Los Alamos and other nuclear research centers and how much
secrecy is really necessary. But it's the look of the thing that is
troubling. And it looks bad.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
