<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8621 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-MYANMAR-HNS &LR;      06-19 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-MYANMAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT RULES THAT MASSACHUSETTS CAN'T HAVE A FOREIGN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Declaring that only the president can make U.S.
foreign policy, the Supreme Court on Monday ruled that
Massachusetts overstepped its authority when it used economic
sanctions to punish the repressive government of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   The court voted unanimously to strike down a Massachusetts law
that prevented the commonwealth's government from making purchases
from companies that do business with Myanmar, also known as Burma.
The court ruled that the Massachusetts statute was pre-empted by
the federal government's own sanctions against the Asian country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state act is at odds with the president's intended
authority to speak for the United States among the world's nations
in developing a comprehensive, multilateral strategy to bring
democracy to and improve human rights practices and the quality of
life in Burma,'' Justice David H. Souter wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   According to Douglas Kmiec, a law professor at Pepperdine
University in Malibu, Calif., the court's decision puts into
question dozens of state and local government laws that restrict
business with firms operating in such countries as China, Cuba,
Nigeria and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the courts have the opportunity to take a look at each
state or city law sanctioning foreign governments and to decide if
they infringe on foreign policy,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of such state and local statutes hailed the court's
decision, saying cities and states are making foreign policy
decisions that should be left to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 30 state and local sanction laws are on the books in
states and cities across America (and) it is time for those
jurisdictions to begin the process of rescinding those measures,''
Frank Kittredge, president of the National Foreign Trade Council
(NFTC), a Washington-based business lobby group that was the
successful plaintiff in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights groups said the court's decision will hurt
efforts to stop governments from abusing their citizens and
environments.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was criticized by Nick Penniman, spokesman for the
Alliance for Democracy, a Boston-based human rights group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people of Massachusetts want to use their economy to
punish a dictatorship, they should be allowed to do that,''
Penniman said. Massachusetts Attorney General Tom Reilly called the
ruling ``disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this law addressed basic human rights and allowed the
state to decide with whom it did business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The NFTC, along with a coalition of 34 firms represented by the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce, challenged the Massachusetts law in 1998.
Each of the companies had business ties to Myanmar, which prevented
them from bidding for contracts with the government of
Massachusetts. The NFTC was concerned that ``the mounting patchwork
of state and local sanctions was threatening to seriously hurt U.S.
interest _ while at the same time threatening a coherent U.S.
foreign policy,'' Kittredge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The founding fathers did not intend for Massachusetts to make
foreign policy,'' he added. Massachusetts enacted the so-called
Myanmar law in 1996 to protest the jailing of Nobel Peace Prize
winner Aung San Suu Kyi, who overwhelmingly won the 1990
presidential election but was never allowed to take the post. The
European Union and Japan also joined the NFTC lawsuit, saying firms
in Britain, Germany or Japan should not be forced to choose between
doing business with Myanmar or Massachusetts. Last June, the First
Circuit Court of Appeals in Boston agreed and struck down the law.
Writing for the appeals court, Judge Sandra L. Lynch said that
while there was no dispute over the ``deplorable'' conditions
imposed by the military government in Myanmar, a state had no
constitutional authority to regulate conduct beyond its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Myanmar_ one of the world's poorest countries, according to the
United Nations _ has been ruled for 38 years by a military
dictatorship that has brutally put down several democratic
movements.
</P>
<P>
   In its appeal to the Supreme Court, Massachusetts argued that
nothing in the Constitution ``requires the states to trade with
dictators.''
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth attorneys also noted that 23 states and 80 cities
once had laws restricting purchases from firms with interests in
South Africa to protest that country's policy of racial apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in our federal Constitution denies to the states the
right to apply a moral standard to their spending decisions,'' the
commonwealth brief said.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday the high court rejected that argument, saying that
the state law made the ``ultimate goal of restoration of democracy
in Burma'' more difficult because it stood as an obstacle to
devising comprehensive, multilateral strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Massachusetts law) compromises the very capacity of the
president to speak for the nation with one voice in dealing with
other governments,'' Souter wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
