<HEADER>
A8622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MACBETH-GRAMMER-NYT &LR;      06-19 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACBETH-GRAMMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MACBETH' WILL CLOSE AFTER ONLY 10 DAYS ON BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tomorrow, and tomorrow, and tomorrow. And that's
pretty much it for the Broadway production of Shakespeare's
``Macbeth,'' starring Kelsey Grammer in the title role.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of the ill-received revival said Monday that they
would close the production on Sunday, five weeks before its planned
closing, after being battered by most of the city's theater
critics.
</P>
<P>
   The production, which opened last Thursday at the Music Box
Theater on West 45th Street, will have played only eight previews
and 13 regular performances, making it one of the shortest runs in
recent years. Having opened just after the Tonys _ officially the
end of the old Broadway season and the start of the new one _
``Macbeth'' also takes its place as both the first show to open in
the 2000-2001 season and the first show of that season to close. It
will have lost some $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The production, staged by the British director Terry Hands,
nearly closed in Boston last month after mixed-to-poor reviews but
continued on to New York after Grammer assured producers that he
would help bear any financial losses they incurred.
</P>
<P>
   But the reviews in New York were no better. Writing in The New
York Times, Ben Brantley called it a ``blunt-witted new
production'' with ``a plodding quality that matches the lumbering
and circular steps with which the actors have been encouraged to
move.'' Other critics were less kind.
</P>
<P>
   In published interviews, Grammer said he knew it was a
professional risk to take on ``Macbeth,'' which is widely
considered one of Shakespeare's most difficult plays and is the
subject of much theatrical mythology. (Superstitious theater
professionals call it ``the Scottish play,'' rather than evoking
the legendary bad luck that seems to follow productions of it.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Grammer said he had long wanted to play the role, for
which he was an understudy in a 1981 production at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, at least, his classical credentials did not seem
completely lacking. He attended though he did not graduate from the
Juilliard acting program, and he received good notices for his
performance as Cassio in a 1982 production of ``Othello'' with
James Earl Jones.
</P>
<P>
   With the early closing, however, Grammer's stage credits are
likely to compare unfavorably with his career in television, during
which he created the character of Dr. Frasier W. Crane, the fussy
and fitfully unhappy psychiatrist on the long-running NBC sitcom
``Cheers.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a regular on that show for 10 years before spinning off
the character into its own successful series, ``Frasier,'' in which
he is still starring on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Monday neither the show's producers nor Grammer would comment on
the early closing, which will probably spare the show further
losses. But perhaps an explanation can be drawn from the play
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were done when 'tis done,'' says Macbeth in Act I,
``then 'twere well it were done quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
