<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SLAVERY-0620-COX     06-19 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVERY-0620-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW PROPOSAL CALLS ON CONGRESS TO APOLOGIZE FOR SLAVERY
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Civil rights advocates led by Rep. John Lewis on
Monday helped exhume a proposal to have Congress formally apologize
for America's prominent role in slavery, nearly three years after
the first attempt was buried beneath a torrent of hate mail.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, D-Ga., signed on as an original co-sponsor of a
resolution that would have Congress apologize ``to
African-Americans on behalf of the people of the United States, for
the wrongs committed against their ancestors who suffered as
slaves...''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also would have Congress ``recognize the
nation's need to redress these events.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the right thing to do,'' Lewis said. ``It is the fair
thing to do. It is the just thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was written by Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio, who first
proposed the idea of having Congress apologize for slavery in 1997.
Hall's first attempt didn't raise the issue of ``redress'' or
reparations, which is why Lewis and other black leaders were cool
to the idea three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The new resolution, introduced on the ``Juneteenth'' anniversary
that is recognized as the day 135 years ago the last of America's
slaves learned they'd been freed by the Civil War, would create a
commission to study the historical economic impact of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   The commission would explore the possibility of creating
scholarships and a national monument to slavery, in addition to
creating a foundation of information that could be used to develop
a plan for reparations. Hall's legislation stops short of seeking
reparations specifically, but does ask Congress to express a
``commitment to rectify misdeeds of slavery done in the past...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I believe there ought to be some kind of
reparation, some kind of restitution,'' Hall said. ``I believe the
apology is only the first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must do more than ask to be forgiven,'' he said of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And it is that element that drew a contingent of black civil
rights and religious leaders to support the new legislation at a
news conference on the Capitol grounds. While Hall's original
resolution was never formally addressed by the Congressional Black
Caucus, Lewis said Monday a ``great majority'' could be expected to
endorse the new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black folk are tired of words without substance,'' said the
Rev. Mark Pollard, president of the National Common Ground
Coalition in Atlanta, an umbrella organization of religious and
civil rights groups, who spoke at Monday's event.
</P>
<P>
   He said his group consulted with Hall during the drafting stage,
when Hall decided to add a section raising the issue of
reparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (resolution) is simply a continuation of our goal of
healing the nation,'' Pollard said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Hall agreed, too, that the climate for a resolution on
slavery is better today than it was three years ago. Religious and
civil rights groups have made declarations in support of slavery
apologies, as have a growing number of state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, President Clinton visited Africa on an 11-day state
visit in 1998 that including a dramatic stop at Goree Island off
the coast of Senegal, an infamous way station for slave traders
hundreds of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Clinton declined to apologize for America's
involvement in the slave trade, but he did express a regret that
was applauded by many in the black community as a significant
gesture for race relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going back to the time before we were even a nation,'' Clinton
said on that trip, ``European-Americans received the fruits of the
slave trade, and we were wrong in that.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Monday that President Clinton will leave
the matter to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's made perfectly clear how wrong he thinks
slavery was,'' said
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for adoption the new slavery resolution may be no
brighter than the last, despite the new support of black leaders.
The legislation would have to be routed through the House Judiciary
Committee, which has so far refused to take up a separate bill on
reparations offered each year by its highest-ranking Democratic
member, Rep. John Conyers of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, who is the
fourth-ranking member in the House and is the GOP's only black
member, said he couldn't comment on the apology legislation because
he hadn't yet seen it. But he seemed open to its potential to help
improve racial tensions in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real reconciliation, real healing is ... about repentance.
Forgiveness,'' Watts said. ``There was a spiritual basis for what
Congressman Hall tried to accomplish here a couple of years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery can be e-mailed at: scottm(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
