<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8625 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      06-19 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIDE EFFECTS: Cola Is No Boon for Bones, Study Says
</P>
<P>
   Young women dashing about, say, the lacrosse field and then
swilling soda to celebrate victory seems like the kind of image
commonly seen in television commercials. But a new study adds a
jarring note to this scene.
</P>
<P>
   Those girls have a much higher chance of suffering a fractured
bone, especially if their soda of choice is cola, Harvard
researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Grace Wyshak, a professor at the School of Public Health,
reported that active girls who drink cola were five times as likely
to have had fractures as were girls who did not drink any soda. The
study appears in this month's Archives of Pediatric and Adolescent
Medicine, and was based on interviews of 460 9th and 10th graders.
</P>
<P>
   According to Wyshak, the study confirms earlier research that
found a link between bone fractures in physically active people and
cola.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors believe that the phosphoric acid in cola drinks is
to blame, because it may affect calcium metabolism and bone mass.
Others cite dietary preferences, with cola replacing the milk that
young people need to develop strong bones.
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR: Medical Students' Biases Can Begin Early
</P>
<P>
   Several studies have found that medical diagnoses and treatments
are often different depending on whether a patient is black or
white.
</P>
<P>
   Now, researchers at Duke University believe that they have found
evidence that the attitudes that affect the behavior of doctors can
be seen in the earliest stages of a student's medical school
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting in a recent issue of The American Journal of Medicine,
researchers said racial and sexual bias surfaced when first- and
second-year students were asked to assess the conditions a black
woman and a white man who they believed were real patients. In
fact, the two were actors using identical scripts.
</P>
<P>
   With the information provided, the medical students should have
been able to diagnose a condition of angina in both ``patients.''
Instead, the white students, who made up 86 percent of the 164
participants in the study, were more likely to diagnosis angina in
the white patient than in the black one. And they were more likely
to rate the white patient's overall health as ``good.'' By
contrast, the minority students in the study made similar
evaluations of the two patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is,'' Dr. Kevin Schulman, the lead author of the
study, said, ``is that behavior that people bring with them to
medical school? Or is this something we're teaching medical
students?''
</P>
<P>
   If students arrive with biases, he said, then medical schools
need to teach them about the pitfalls of making racial assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   AT RISK: Alcohol Heightens Risks of Tobacco Use
</P>
<P>
   Smoking and heavy drinking are two risky behaviors that often go
together. But when combined, it now seems, they play an increased
role in causing a genetic mutation linked to lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco is known to produce changes in the tumor-suppressor gene
p53, and to be the major cause of lung cancer. The tobacco-cancer
link is so great that Dr. Steven Ahrendt of the Medical College of
Wisconsin, whose research team sought lung-cancer patients for a
new study, said, ``We had to get 140 just to get 10 nonsmokers.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavy alcohol use, on the other hand, while implicated in some
cancers, has not been tied to p53 mutations.
</P>
<P>
   But the study, published in last week's issue of Cancer
Research, found that regular drinkers who smoked were nearly twice
as likely to have p53 changes as nondrinkers who smoked, and five
times as likely as those who did not smoke or drink.
</P>
<P>
   TIMING: Slower Angioplasties Can Threaten Lives
</P>
<P>
   Emergency angioplasty is a proven way to save the lives of
patients having heart attacks, but two new studies suggest that for
it to be most effective, time is of the essence.
</P>
<P>
   One report, by researchers at Brigham and Women's Hospital,
found that for the best survival rate, the procedure should be done
within two hours after a patient arrives at the hospital. The study
looked at more than 27,000 heart attack patients treated at 661
hospitals from 1994 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the time period, only about 50 percent met this goal of
less than two hours,'' said Dr. Christopher Cannon, the lead
author. ``So we've got some work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In angioplasty, a balloon is threaded through a patient's
arteries to the heart and then expanded, clearing the blocked
artery so that that blood can resume pumping normally. Angioplasty
can also be done as an elective procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Cannon, who reported his findings in last week's Journal of the
American Medical Association, said that when delays of more than
two hours occurred, the mortality rate rose by 40 to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The other study appeared last month in The New England Journal
of Medicine and confirmed the longstanding belief that patients
given emergency angioplasties at hospitals that perform large
numbers of the procedures have lower mortality rates. Patients who
went to high-volume hospitals had a 28 percent lower mortality rate
in the hospital, amounting to two fewer deaths for every 100
patients treated.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing theory holds that surgeons get better with
practice.
</P>
<P>
   But the lead author of the study, Dr. John Canto of the
University of Alabama at Birmingham, said researchers had also
found that the failure of smaller hospitals to administer the
angioplasty quickly enough appeared to play a role.
</P>
<P>
   Both studies said that how quickly hospitals can get an
angioplasty in place should considered when doctors weigh whether
to use the balloon therapy or instead administer so-called
clot-buster drugs.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE LAB: A Shampoo That Highlights Head Lice
</P>
<P>
   A pediatrician at Yale says he has developed an improved
technique for detecting lice eggs, known as nits, raising hope for
the day when parents will not have to spend long hours delousing
their children _ only to find that a few missed eggs forces them to
begin all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sydney Spiesel, an assistant professor at the Yale School of
Medicine, has invented a shampoo that, after a single application,
stains the lice and their nits so that when exposed to commonly
available ultraviolet or black light sources, they glow brightly.
The nits, the size and color of a grain of sand, can then be easily
spotted and removed.
</P>
<P>
   Lice, which cause an estimated 12 million infestations a year in
this country, do not pose a health risk by themselves. But they do
cause itching, social stigma and much grief for parents.
</P>
<P>
   New strains, moreover, have become resistant to traditional
chemical treatments, leaving nit-by-nit removal as the only
effective remedy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new shampoo is not yet available, Spiesel has
obtained a patent for it and is meeting with potential
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   He even has a name in mind, courtesy of a girl who attended a
day care center in New Haven where he worked as medical adviser and
was required to certify that children were lice-free before they
could return. The girl, now 13, suggested ``Headlights.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a solution, Spiesel said he recalled his days as a
biology student and the nature of the hard exterior of lice and
their eggs, which are made of a substance called chitin. The chitin
is often stained by researchers as part of their lab work, and
Spiesel found that several stains, already widely used in products
like laundry detergents, worked well on the nits, without affecting
the hair or scalp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
