<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHIS-SUPERBIKES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLADIN ROARS TO SUPERBIKE RECORD AT LOUDON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Mat Madlin is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Mat Mladin originally planned to spend Monday
behind the wheel of his motorcoach on a leisurely trip to Columbus,
Ohio, where he would deliver his rig for an AMA Chevy Trucks US
Superbike event at Mid-Ohio July 14-16 before jetting off to his
residence in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   But those plans were put on hold when rain forced the
postponement of Sunday's Superbike event at the 77th AMA Loudon
Classic at New Hampshire International Speedway. So Mladin, who won
the pole position in record fashion with a lap of 1 minute 9.947
seconds (82.345 miles per hour), rode his American Suzuki hard and
fast Monday to win the 38-lap race in a record pace of 81.047
m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he had a motorcoach to Columbus to catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping this race would be good to us,'' said Mladin,
who expanded his lead over Nicky Hayden in the Superbike standings
from a scant 1-point (171-170) to a robust 14 (209-195) at the
halfway point of the season. ``Nicky had done a great job last week
(sweeping a doubleheader at Road America in Elkhart Lake, Wis.) but
we honestly believed we were beaten by horsepower. This week,
unfortunately, you can't use all that horsepower because it comes
down to getting around the corners quick and making sure your tires
last the race and we obviously did the best job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Australian-born Mladin, 27, won for the second time at NHIS
(he also won in 1997) to give his Suzuki team its fourth victory in
six events this season. He negotiated the winding, 12-turn,
1.6-mile road circuit without incident to beat runner-up Eric
Bostrom and third-place finisher Jamie Hacking, who recorded his
first podium effort of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden dropped back in the standings after finishing sixth. He
injured his right knee on Lap 26 when he struck a pylon in Turn 3
and was hampered for the remainder of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Mladin, who led start to finish, pressed the pace early to build
a commanding lead. The toughest part of his day, arguably, came
when he had to pass the lapped Ducati belonging to John Kocinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to thank John for his decency for not coming up inside
on me and overtaking me again, because he could've easily come back
underneath me, but that was nice of him,'' Mladin said. ``It would
have been a little nicer if he had taken a glimpse over his
shoulder and noticed that I was there for a couple of laps. The
Ducati accelerates hard and I really had to make sure that I could
get off Turn 2 hard so I could outbrake him (in Turn 3).''
</P>
<P>
   Mladin knew such a maneuver would not have been possible had he
been forced to race Sunday in extremely wet conditions. But after
track officials huddled with AMA officials and riders _ in a
somewhat contentious meeting on pit road _ it was decided that the
race would be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard call for everybody,'' Mladin said. ``It's hard
on the fans to try and come back here. I was totally against
running (Sunday). I believe this racetrack isn't suitable for us to
race in the rain and I think probably 8 out of 10 riders believed
the same Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Harley-Davidson rider Pascal Picotte, who turned a fast lap of
1:24.8 during Sunday's session, expressed a desire to race that day
in hopes of delivering his manufacturer its first Superbike
victory. However, he was in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose it would've been nice to win a race,'' said Mladin,
``but to win a race when the other 14 guys really don't care to be
out there really couldn't be satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only speak for myself. I think (the AMA) made the right
decision. I was out there and I had only done one lap and didn't
feel good at all. I tested a couple of spots and they were slick. I
think they made the right call and I have to thank the AMA for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it meant delaying his trip to Columbus by a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
