<SLUG> BC-COVENT-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN RESCUER OF LONDON'S ROYAL OPERA RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Kaiser, the American theater manager who helped rescue
London's Royal Opera House from the financial crisis and internal
feuding that plagued its recent $360 million redevelopment,
announced Monday that he would step down at the end of the
2000-2001 season after just 18 months as chief executive of the
Covent Garden complex.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, a former executive director of American Ballet Theater,
said in a statement that the decision had been ``the most
profoundly difficult'' of his career. ``But, for personal reasons,
it is time for me to return to my home'' in New York, he said.
Kaiser, who is 47, said he was announcing his intention now to
allow time for an orderly transition.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had no fixed-term contract, he predicted in an
interview early last year that he would need three to five years to
have the Royal Opera House operating without financial restraints.
He also expressed excitement over the challenge of bringing order
to a legendary theater that had known three board chairmen and
three directors in as many years, even pointing to a newspaper
headline that greeted him his first day at work: ``Chaos Reigns as
Kaiser Enters Opera House.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Covent Garden reopened last December after a
30-month makeover, Kaiser had virtually eliminated the budget
deficit and created a permanent endowment fund. He also had done
much to revive morale in both the Royal Ballet and the orchestra
and chorus of the opera house after the tabloid-pleasing scandals
that preceded him.
</P>
<P>
   After a year-long honeymoon with the British press, however,
Kaiser was criticized for pricing seats beyond the reach of many
opera lovers and for allowing an independent producer to operate
the house during the off-season months of July and August. He also
faced embarrassing teething problems with a new computerized stage
that forced cancellation of one entire opera production and
resulted in several breakdowns during early performances.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the consensus was that, having previously restored
financial health to the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater and to
American Ballet Theater, he had once again lived up to the nickname
of ``Mr. Turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, with Anthony Pappano to succeed Bernard Haitink as
music director in 2002 and Ross Stretton to succeed Sir Athony
Dowell as director of the Royal Ballet next year, an entirely new
team seemed to be in place. The first press reports this weekend
that Kaiser was planning to leave Covent Garden, therefore, came as
a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser could not be reached for comment beyond his formal
statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate statement, Sir Colin Southgate, the Royal Opera
House's board chairman, praised Kaiser's ``countless'' achievements
at Covent Garden. ``He has approached this enormously challenging
job with unrelenting energy, commitment and determination,'' the
chairman said. ``The Royal Opera House is now on a very sure
footing both financially and artistically and we owe him a huge
debt of gratitude.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
