<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-POLITICS-06201stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUPREME COURT PICKS HANG HEAVY OVER ELECTION
 &HT;    EDS: Corrects date of Roe v. Wade in 2nd graf
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in Washington and politics category
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's not much discussed in campaign appearances,
but the question of who will win the power to appoint the next
Supreme Court justices _ maybe up to four in the next four years _
hangs heavy over this year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two major presidential candidates, Vice President Al Gore
has raised the court issue most often. And when he does, it is
usually to evoke the specter of a Republican president undoing Roe
v. Wade, the 1973 Supreme Court ruling that guaranteed a woman's
right to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a Supreme Court majority that is in keeping with
the philosophy of Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson, that is what is
at stake in this election,'' Gore said during the Iowa caucus.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's likely Republican opponent, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, while less talkative on the subject of judicial appointments,
is nonetheless mindful that the next president's appointments could
have enormous influence on a nine-member court that is closely
divided on contentious issues.
</P>
<P>
   And, ironically, he has linked himself to Ronald Reagan rather
than to his father, George H.W. Bush, in putting forth a ``strict
constructionist'' view of judicial appointees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same position that Governor Reagan, soon to be
President Reagan, took in the '80 debate,'' Bush said during the
Iowa caucus.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of Supreme Court appointments bubbled to the
surface of the presidential contest Monday with the court's 6-3
ruling that student-led prayers before high school football games
violates the constitutionally required separation of government and
religion.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came in a case from Texas that included a brief
from Bush urging the high court to uphold such student-led prayer.
</P>
<P>
   But abortion is the central issue in the political debate over
the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the presidential primaries began this year, the
National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League (NARAL) ran
television ads in New Hampshire last December warning that Bush
would appoint justices who would overturn Roe v. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   And since the primaries, President Clinton has joined the fray,
noting earlier this year that there is ``absolutely no question in
my mind that whether Roe vs. Wade is preserved or scrapped depends
on what happens in the presidential election, and to pretend
otherwise is naive.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other divisive issues before the justices, however.
And one new justice could change the court's thinking on such
issues as racial preferences, separation of church and state,
voting rights, sex discrimination, criminal law and the power
relationship between Congress and the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is the hinge _ nearly every important vote is
5-4,'' said Herman Shwartz, a constitutional law professor at
American University's Washington College of Law.
</P>
<P>
   The three oldest justices are Chief Justice William Rehnquist,
75, Justice John Paul Stevens, 79, and Justice Sandra Day O'Connor,
70. Two of them _ Rehnquist and Stevens _ have already exceeded the
average length of services of justices, 23 years. And O'Connor will
mark her 23rd year on the court in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Of those appointed since 1986, the oldest is Ruth Bader
Ginsburg, 66, who has undergone surgery for colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to predict when a court opening will occur,
however. Three of the last four justices to retire did so when they
were well into their eighties: William Brennan at 84, Thurgood
Marshall at 83 and Harry Blackmun at 85.
</P>
<P>
   But both the Gore and Bush camps clearly anticipate that the
next president could appoint enough justices to affect domestic
politics well into the 21st century, beginning with abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said he would look for justices ``who understand that
our Constitution is a living and breathing document, that it was
intended by our Founders to be interpreted in the light of the
constantly evolving experience of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he has indicated he would ``not use a litmus test''
regarding abortion rights in selecting justices, he has vowed that
``you could rest assured that a Supreme Court majority appointed in
a Gore administration would support a woman's right to chose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he would name judges ``who will strictly interpret
the Constitution and not use the benches from which to legislate.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bush has cited Justice Antonin Scalia, perhaps the court's
most conservative member and most outspoken opponent of abortion,
as the justice he respects most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is indeed very encouraging that Scalia is the type of judge
that Bush would look to (for the court),'' said David O'Steen, the
executive director of the National Right to Life Committee, the
most active anti-abortion organization in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Ralph Neas, president of the liberal People for the American
Way Foundation (PFAWF), countered: ``If the far right succeeds in
remaking the court in the image of Scalia ..., the result would be
a disaster for millions of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as it is impossible to predict when a Supreme Court
vacancy will occur, so it is to predict how a new justice will
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives are still seething over the appointment of David
H. Souter to the court. Souter, who was appointed by President
Bush, is counted among the court's liberals in most instances and
has voted solidly in favor of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, when asked about his father's appointment of
Souter, ducked the question. ``Nice try,'' Bush responded. ``I'm
not going into all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   www.supremecourtus.gov
</P>
<P>
   www.eppc.org
</P>
<P>
   www.pfaw.org
</P>
<P>
   www. naral.org
</P>
<P>
   www.nrlc.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
