<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-OPEN-WOODS-BOS &LR;      06-19 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGING WOODS A PURE TERROR FOR OTHER PROS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ Always with Tiger Woods, there is
anticipation. What will he do next? It is a source of joy for golf
fans, but for those who must compete against him, it translates
into fear.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo, for example, was upbeat and almost charming when
talking to the media Sunday after his US Open scores of 69-74-76-71
produced his first top 10 finish in a major in four years _ until
he was asked about Woods's demolition of the field at Pebble Beach
Golf Links. Fear, though he would not admit it, overcame Faldo, who
had just sweated out four days of high-intensity, gut-wrenching
golf, played to perhaps his greatest ability, and still finished 18
shots behind Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen shots. Think about that. Woods could have given Faldo
two a side for all four days and still beaten him.
</P>
<P>
   And Faldo finished seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But there was the six-time major winner being asked about the
prospects of Woods at St. Andrews, site of the British Open, the
next major. ``I think St. Andrews will help the rest of us,'' said
Faldo, whose second of three British Open titles came at the Old
Course in 1990. He sounded as if he were trying to convince himself
more than the assembled media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a true links course, with big greens, and you can play it
with no real scare. The fact that there's no water will help us.''
</P>
<P>
   On Faldo went, temporarily overcome with fear, we assume,
rationalizing that the wide-open terrain of St. Andrews will allow
players to take gambles where Pebble Beach, with its treacherous
cliffs and deep rough, did not.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing is, golfers were saying a month ago that the
USGA set-up at Pebble Beach would bring Woods back to the field,
that the narrow fairways, deep rough, and rock-hard greens would
bring more players into the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that picture was totally out of focus, because only one
player was in it.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, of course. By 15 shots over his nearest challenger, which
is so absurd a victory margin that you would have to talk to Willie
Smith to get a sense of what it feels like, since he was the only
other player to post a double-digit win in any of the previous 99
US Opens. Of course, ol' Willie did his deed in 1899, so good luck
getting a quote.
</P>
<P>
   How dramatic a victory was it? Consider:
</P>
<P>
   --In the previous 20 US Opens, the average victory margin was
1.1 shots.
</P>
<P>
   --You have to go back 30 years, to Tony Jacklin's seven-shot
cushion at Hazeltine, to find a US Open that was decided by more
than three in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   --Jack Nicklaus, whose 18 major conquests is the record Woods
dreams about, won his four US Opens by a combined 12 strokes (which
includes his three-shot playoff win over Arnold Palmer).
</P>
<P>
   Incredible stuff? Yes. Unbelievable? Not to Tom Watson, who
knows greatness when he sees it. Twenty-five years ago, Watson
wanted to be the best, and to that end he had to travel a route
directly through Nicklaus, a challenge he accepted without
hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   The encounters are classics _ 1977 at Augusta, 1977 at
Turnberry, 1981 at Augusta, 1982 at Pebble Beach, major
championships all won by Watson, with Nicklaus second _ but unless
something changes quickly, we won't see a repeat of such a rivalry,
said Watson, because Woods is frightening away the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said a number of times that Tiger Woods has the best
swing on Tour,'' said Watson. ``Couple that with the fact he's the
longest hitter on Tour, has the best short game on Tour, and is one
of the best putters on Tour, and you know why he's got a 10-shot
lead in the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all playing for second,'' Watson added Sunday, and
that may be the case again next month at St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bomber's and a putter's course,'' said Nick Price.
``Perfect for him. That's his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all felt for the longest time that someone was going to
come along who could drive the ball 300 yards and putt like (Ben)
Crenshaw. Well, this guy drives the ball better than anyone I've
seen and putts better than Crenshaw. A phenomenon, no doubt about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Darren Clarke agrees. He was one of those players allegedly set
to enter the picture because the Pebble Beach set-up was going to
hinder Woods. Clarke pointed to a USGA staple _ thick rough _ as
proof that people did not have a true vision of what was going to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Woods's third-round drive at the par-5 sixth
hole, which went into rough right of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us would have punched it out, maybe 30 yards,'' said
Clarke. ``He knocks a 7-iron up the hill and on the green.''
</P>
<P>
   A 7-iron from 201 yards, no less. Uphill, directly on line with
the pin, even though it flirted with a cliff to the right that
invited double-bogey. Woods made the birdie, one of 21 he made in
four days. Consider that David Duval and Phil Mickelson made a
combined 22 birdies and you understand why Clarke, though friendly
with the 24-year-old living legend, is not going to send Woods any
invitations to play European events before the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is playing a different game than the rest of us,'' said
Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   It's an overpowering game, to be sure, but if the course is set
up to throttle his power, as Pebble Beach was, then he'll rely on
an umatched short game to finesse his way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was first in greens in regulation and sixth in putting,''
said Clarke. ``That's an amazing combination.''
</P>
<P>
   The next show is expected to get under way July 6 at the Advil
Western Open outside of Chicago, though Woods rarely confirms his
schedule that far in advance. But he is the defending champ there
and, besides, it offers a nice tune-up to the real task at hand _
the chance to complete the career grand slam at a time when he is
playing ferociously well and on a course with four par-4s that he
could drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get much better than this,'' said Woods, the
championship hardware from the US Open sitting right next to him.
``Pebble Beach and St. Andrews.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, most of his challengers are fearful that he's
right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
