<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8652 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX     06-19 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF SUPREME COURT CASE DOESN'T END TROUBLE IN TEXAS TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The same week last year that a girl's prayer propelled a Texas
school district to the U.S. Supreme Court, a 13-year-old boy was
lingering on lunch break in the Santa Fe junior high schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
   Four students, maybe more, surrounded eighth-grader Phil
Nevelow. In a singsong voice, they chanted:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler missed one! No more Jews!
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler missed one! He should have gotten you!''
</P>
<P>
   That Friday night, at the opening football game, high school
senior Marian Ward prayed for sportsmanship, safety and fans'
``good behavior'' in ``Jesus' name'' at the Santa Fe High School
Indians' game, beginning a season that ended Monday in a 6-3 defeat
at the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Fe, a town of 10,000 people in western Galveston County
only 20 miles from the Gulf of Mexico, the first court case is
over.
</P>
<P>
   A second may be only beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Nevelow was bullied all year, his family says. Now, three
teen-agers face juvenile charges in connection with a May 16 threat
on a school bus to ``hang'' Nevelow, the son of a ranking officer
in the Galveston County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   According to the family, he is the only Jewish student among
4,300 in the Santa Fe schools.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Nevelow said the family has yet to discuss suing the
school district, but that school officials have done ``nothing''
all year about slurs against her son, only phoning when he fought
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, this school district has to learn how to accept
outsiders, how to accept another culture, religion or race,'' she
said Monday by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to change. It's going to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're the ones who will have to insist on change.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Mormon and Roman Catholic ``John Doe'' families
winning the football game prayer lawsuit had remained publicly
anonymous _ by a judge's order after school officials began prying
and began interrogating students _ the Nevelows talk publicly about
life in a working-class town of 10,000 people, including two Jewish
families by Donna Nevelow's count. The 1990 census reported nine
African-American residents.
</P>
<P>
   Both Donna Nevelow and her husband, Sheriff's Maj. Eric Nevelow,
grew up in nearby Galveston. He is a 25-year veteran of the
sheriff's office. They've lived in Santa Fe 15 years and attend a
Galveston synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This community is not just divided'' over the prayer case, she
said. ``It's fractured.
</P>
<P>
   ``This town is hurting. Us, the Catholic families, the Mormon
families _ it's as if this is war and we're all on the other side.
Everybody else is against all of us. Nobody will even have a
logical discussion. You try to start a conversation, and people
just start shouting at you.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what Justice John Paul Stevens meant when he
wrote for the Court majority that public school students can never
be treated like religious ``outsiders'' by a bullying majority of
``insiders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the news this morning,'' Donna Nevelow said. ``I'm
happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, I'm concerned how it will affect us. I'm
concerned how much more separation and resentment this will
create.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nevelows' first meeting with school officials is fatefully
well-timed. They are scheduled to meet Tuesday morning, Donna
Nevelow said. The Nevelows will ask the district to send employees
to cultural awareness training and to add cultural diversity
lessons in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   In the May 16 incident, two 16-year-old boys and a 15-year-old
boy each face a misdemeanor charge alleging a terroristic threat.
Phil Nevelow told police that one boy said, ``We're going to hang
you, you dirty Jew,'' and that one of the boys said he should
``wander the desert for 40 years.'' They were arrested by Santa Fe
police.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for one of the boys has asked for a jury trial, said
a prosecutor in the Galveston County district attorney's office.
Lawyers for the other boys are considering plea bargain offers
before their next hearings, scheduled on July 12 and July 19.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Nevelow said she taped a local newscast when the school
superintendent called the case a ``teen-age prank.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it takes for the schools here to take
cultural diversity seriously,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think losing at the Supreme Court would be enough.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
