<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-SOSA20-COX     06-19 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chicago bracing for Sosa departure
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Tap your heart and blow a kiss. Tap your heart again
and say goodbye to Sammy Sosa's reign as Chicago's most beloved
athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, the Cubs' ultra-popular right fielder, is engulfed by
trade rumors as he arrives in Atlanta for a three-game series
against the Braves at Turner Field starting tonight.
</P>
<P>
   What was once the unimaginable in the Windy City has now become
the anticipated: The Cubs probably will part with Sosa before the
July 31 trading deadline. Shop owners around Wrigley Field are
bracing for it, and so are Sosa's fans and teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing for the Cubs for 13 years,'' first baseman
Mark Grace said. ``I've seen everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Say it ain't so, Sammy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem here,'' Sosa said. ``I'm employed, just
like everybody else. I see myself here, no doubt about it. I'm
still here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sosa, 31, probably won't be with the Cubs for long. Cubs
general manager Ed Lynch last week dispatched his top scouts, Ken
Kravec and Keith Champion, to watch minor-league teams of the Mets,
Red Sox and Yankees. Those three teams reportedly are expressing
the most interest in acquiring Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, the 1998 National League MVP, is being paid $10 million
this season and $11 million in 2001. Sosa's current contract
expires after next season and he reportedly wants a new deal that
will pay him between $15 million and $20 million per year. Sosa and
his agent, Adam Katz, want a new contract before July 31.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cubs seem unwilling to spend almost one-third of their
$60 million payroll on one player _ even Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three things that can happen: There could be a
(contract) extension, there could be a trade, or nothing could
happen,'' Cubs president and CEO Andy McPhail said. ``I really
don't have the probability on any of those three.''
</P>
<P>
   Souvenir shops around Wrigley Field are betting that Sosa is
traded. Since last week, several stores have been running Sosa
clearance sales, trying to unload everything that bears the
slugger's likeness or his No. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's love affair with the bleacher bums of Wrigley Field
doesn't seem to be what it was two summers ago, when Sosa and
McGwire led baseball's comeback with their remarkable home run
race. Most Cubs fans figure that, if the franchise can acquire a
core of young stars for the aging superstar, they're better off
without Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy is the subject of all the talk in the bar and dining
room,'' said Grant DePorter, managing partner of Harry Caray's
Restaurant. ``A lot of people are just hoping the Cubs do something
that will help them win. If that means trading Sammy, I think
people will believe it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, when the Cubs and White Sox met at Comiskey Park
in an interleague series, a fan held up a ``Sammy Meter'' sign that
included nine Ks, which represented Sosa's nine strikeouts in the
three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   A columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times said, ``Sosa is
shrinking,'' because the Cubs continue to badmouth and degrade him.
</P>
<P>
   ``With every unfair insult, every internal and external attack,
every reminder that the Cubs no longer want him, an icon is
becoming an eyesore,'' columnist Jay Mariotti wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Barely 40 percent into this season, the Cubs already trail the
St. Louis Cardinals by 10 games in the National League Central. And
the future isn't much brighter, with most of the team's top players
_ Grace (35 years), outfielder Henry Rodriguez (32) and pitchers
Rick Aguilera (38) and Kevin Tapani (36) _ nearing the end of their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs haven't ruled out trading Sosa because they realize his
value might never be higher. He has hit 149 home runs since Opening
Day 1998, a total second only to Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire's
160. Through 68 games this year, Sosa is hitting .311 with 20
homers and 62 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The trade speculation) is not going to stop me from going out
and playing or doing the best that I can,'' Sosa said. ``Whatever
happens off the field is not my problem. I've just got to take care
of business on the field. ... I believe everything is going to
settle down. If not, I don't have any control over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's critics claim he has gained weight the past two seasons,
which has caused him to steal fewer bases and has reduced his range
in the outfield. Sosa also strikes out at an alarming rate. In the
last three seasons, he has fanned at least 171 times. Sosa is the
only big-leaguer besides former Tiger Rob Deer to have three
seasons with at least 170 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sosa is what he is,'' Cubs manager Don Baylor said. ``He is a
home-run hitter, and one flaw home-run guys have is they strike
out. The (Mickey) Mantles. The (Reggie) Jacksons. The McGwires. The
(Mike) Schmidts. That is their M.O.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor and Sosa say they have repaired their relationship after
a public spat earlier this month. When Baylor insinuated that Sosa
needed to play harder in the field and steal more bases, Sosa said
Baylor had ``no class.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see (Sosa) being the problem,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cubs think that Sosa could be the solution to their
long-term problems. With Kerry Wood struggling to recover from
elbow surgery that caused him to miss all of last season, the
team's pitching staff is in disarray. Sosa could command as many as
three or four players, including at least a pair of highly regarded
pitching prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do everything I want to determine the value of a player,
but the other people are going to determine his value, what the
demand is on their end,'' Lynch said. ``The offers that come in for
any player determine what his value is.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sosa is traded, Lynch says, it will take time to complete the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people are ahead of themselves,'' Lynch said.
``Anytime you're talking about trading an impact player, it takes
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubs outfielder Glenallen Hill, one of Sosa's closest friends,
says the decision will come down to money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy doesn't want to leave,'' Hill said. ``He loves it here.
With Sammy, it's just about money.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sosa, however, his future could be about more than money.
Taped to his locker in the Wrigley Field clubhouse is an
advertisement torn from a magazine. It includes a picture of the
Yankees celebrating last year's World Series victory and the
headline, ``Winning Is Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa knows a trade could put him in the middle of a pennant
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible I could go a lot of places,'' Sosa said. ``I
don't know where I'm going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
