<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEDE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mayfield nudges Earnhardt to claim Pocono victory
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG POND, Pa. _ Jeremy Mayfield is NASCAR's newest overnight
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield won Monday's Pocono 500 with an outrageous and daring
manuever against Winston Cup's most feared competitor. Dale
Earnhardt, known as ``The Intimidator'' for his rough style of
driving, was less than 700 feet from victory when he was nudged in
the rear bumper by Mayfield. To the roaring approval of the crowd
at Pocono Raceway, the No. 3 Chevy slid up the groove and Mayfield
and two other drivers passed.
</P>
<P>
   As Mayfield cruised on his victory lap around the 2.5-mile
tri-oval, many other drivers signaled a thumbs up. Earnhardt drove
side by side with Mayfield momentarily, making a taunting gesture
with his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt said later he was telling Mayfield, ``You're No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second victory of the season for Mayfield and third
of his eight-year Winston Cup career. He was overwhelmed by fans as
he walked from the winner's circle to the garage area. Only hours
earlier, he went through the same route to pit road unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never intentionally tried to wreck (Earnhardt) or nothing,''
Mayfield, driver of the No. 12 Ford, said with a grin. ``We just
wanted to rattle his cage a little bit and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt had used the phrase ``just wanted to rattle his cage''
when he bumped leader Terry Labonte into the wall on the final lap
of August's Bristol race. Earnhardt passed Labonte for the
controversial victory and showed no remorse in post-race comments.
</P>
<P>
   The bump at Bristol was much more severe than Monday's last-lap
contact, which might have been Earnhardt's fault. Earnhardt, a
seven-time Winston Cup champion, mishandled his car in the second
turn, sliding to the top groove and losing valuable seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield took the second turn perfectly and built up enough
momentum to catch up with Earnhardt in the final corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like a hard hit; it didn't wreck him,'' said Dale
Jarrett who finished second. ``I'm glad to see that Dale didn't
wreck, but again (the bump) did its purpose and makes for exciting
racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett paused for quick smile and said, ``We all know
(Earnhardt) wouldn't have done that if he would've been the car
behind, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the key members of Earnhardt's team criticized Mayfield
or protested the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt: ``It felt like he hit me. I don't know if he did or
not. What did it look like on TV? He took the air off something.
... It was a good race, though. You don't ever have a win until the
checkered flag falls. I got beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Richard Childress said: ``Mayfield just knocked him out of
the way to win. It was just racing. There will be another day.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief Kevin Hamlin said: ``I don't know; it's just racing.
Some days, we're going to be running second and come out in the
lead at the end. Some days, we're going to be in front and finish
fourth.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield and Earnhardt have a history of mixing it up. Mayfield
said Monday was another chapter. ``I'm not intimidated by Dale
Earnhardt,'' he said, ``and never will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
