<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June. 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A band of showers and thunderstorms will produce heavy rain with
local flooding in the northern Mississippi Valley and western Great
Lakes as a vigorous cold front sweep across these regions. Some of
the storms will have damaging winds and hail. In the wake of the
front, strong winds from the northwest will deliver chilly air and
a few showers to the northern parts of the Rockies and Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Sultry air will persist from the southern Plains to the
Southeastern states. Converging winds near a warm front will
produce thundershowers in the Tennessee Valley and near the
southern Appalachians. A broken band of thunderstorms will erupt
during the heat of the afternoon from the western Ohio Valley to
central Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   After a cool dawn with patchy fog, the Northeast will be sunny
and seasonable. Clouds will increase late today in the interior as
the area of showers approaches from the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THE LONGEST SEASON
</P>
<P>
   The official start of summer is at 9:48 p.m. EDT Tuesday, and
astronomy, not meteorology, is the deciding factor. It is then that
the northward trek of the sun's direct rays across the planet will
cease. For the next six months, the direct rays of the sun will
move inexorably south, culminating in the winter solstice on Dec.
21. But the summer season is the slowest to fade. As a result of
the elliptical shape of the Earth's orbit around the sun, the
Northern Hemisphere's summer lasts 93 days while winter is 89 days
long. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
