<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CRIMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRONGER HATE-CRIMES LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been 20 months since the savage beating of Matthew
Shepard, the University of Wyoming student murdered because he was
gay. His memory should not be allowed to fade without national
action on hate crimes. An amendment to give the federal government
a stronger role in prosecuting crimes of bias deserves swift
approval when it is taken up in the US Senate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsored by US Senator Edward Kennedy, the amendment adds
violence motivated by gender, sexual orientation, and disability to
the roster of hate crimes. Currently, federal hate crimes are
limited to those committed on the basis of race, religion, or
national origin, and then only if they interfere with a narrow list
of six ``federally protected activities'' such as trying to vote or
registering for school. These restrictions allow thousands of hate
crimes a year to elude federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy amendment does not allow for enhanced penalties or
added sanctions, but it does offer the assistance of the FBI or
other federal resources to local law enforcement authorities in
investigating such crimes. Although 40 states have some sort of
hate crime statutes, many are limited to race or religion, and many
other states do not have the technical or forensic tools to pursue
a thorough investigation. The amendment respects local authority by
requiring that the US Justice Department consult with state law
enforcement officers and determine that the state either does not
have jurisdiction or requests the federal intervention.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative amendment by Senator Orrin Hatch, Republican of
Utah, would authorize a study of hate crimes. It is little more
than a red herring. But because of Senate rules, members will be
allowed to vote on both amendments Tuesday, and, if both pass, they
will be subject to complicated negotiations that could muddy the
waters. All 12 New England senators, with the exception of the two
in New Hampshire, are co-sponsors of the Kennedy amendment.
Supporting both would send a mixed message.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government should be enhancing justice for all
Americans victimized simply for being who they are. This amendment
is an important start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
