<SLUG> BC-TRUCK-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GROUPS PROTEST PLAN TO LET TRUCKERS DRIVE LONG HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the official start of summer, the nation's
highways could become more hazardous if a new federal proposal goes
into effect allowing truckers to drive up to 12 hours before taking
a break, a group of lawmakers and safety advocates warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under 60-year-old federal regulations, truckers can drive up to
10 hours straight, followed by at least eight hours off, leaving
open the possibility of driving as many as 16 hours in a 24-hour
period.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation (DOT) has proposed a rule that
would give truckers more rest but allow them to drive up to 12
hours straight per day.
</P>
<P>
   According to government figures, 755 people are killed and
19,000 injured each year in accidents caused by fatigued truck
drivers. Overall, more than 5,300 people are killed and 127,000 are
injured annually as a result of truck-related crashes. Sen. Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif., said in a statement that the new rule would ``only
lead to an increase in truck-related crashes and fatalities. And
that is just not acceptable. We know that overly tired truck
drivers put themselves and the public at risk. Why increase that
risk?'' Boxer asked.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Gillan, a vice president with Advocates for Highway and
Auto Safety here, said, ``Truck drivers are falling asleep after
eight or nine hours. To allow them to drive 12 hours (per day)
makes no sense at all. We are concerned that this rule is a step
back for highway safety. Those additional two hours can make a big
difference between a fatigued driver and a rested driver,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Claybrook, president of Public Citizen, a Washington-based
health and safety advocacy group, said, ``This is not someone just
sitting behind a desk. This is someone driving a huge rig that can
kill other people.'' If truckers ``take their eyes off the road for
a second, they can crash.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Longo, a DOT spokesman, argued that the proposal would
actually boost safety because it would increase the rest time
drivers are required to take, from 8 hours a day to 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Critics) say we are increasing driving time, but what we are
concerned about is providing drivers with more rest,'' Longo said.
</P>
<P>
   In April, when the proposal was first announced, Transportation
Secretary Rodney Slater said it would save 115 lives while
preventing 2,600 crashes and 3,000 serious injuries annually.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Daphne Izer, co-chair and founder of a Lisbon Falls,
Maine-based group called Parents Against Tried Truckers, charged
that the DOT proposal would encourage drivers to pull long shifts
and drive 12 hours straight. Izer, whose son was killed when his
car was struck by a driver who nodded off, said the long shifts
would result because many drivers are paid by the mile and not on
an hourly rate. So the more miles they can log, the more they get
paid.
</P>
<P>
   Several organizations have scheduled a news conference Tuesday
in front of the Capitol to protest the rule, which has received a
mixed response from the trucking industry.
</P>
<P>
   The American Trucking Associations, which represent truck
owners, said the proposal would force them to put additional trucks
on the roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposal could mean a 50 percent increase in the number
of refrigerated and dry van trucks on our already-crowded
highways,'' the associations said in a statement. ``That translates
into as many as 180,000 additional drivers and trucks on the road
just to keep the current economy moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Black, a spokesman for the Teamsters Union, which represents
about 175,000 truck drivers that the rule would affect, said the
labor organization is ``concerned'' over the increased time behind
the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   DOT is allowing the truck drivers and owners as well as
interested citizens to submit comments until October. Afterward,
the agency could take several more months to publish a final
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
