<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ABACHA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA FINDS MILLIONS LOOTED UNDER ABACHA IN LIECHTENSTEIN BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Representatives of Nigeria said Monday that they had
found bank accounts in Liechtenstein that probably held tens of
millions of dollars looted under Gen. Sani Abacha, the former
dictator of Nigeria. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sums in Liechtenstein are in addition to much larger
accounts already located in Switzerland, Luxembourg and Britain.
Officials estimate that $1.6 billion in accounts in those countries
is suspect.
</P>
<P>
   In Liechtenstein, documents show that more than $150 million had
been transferred to two banks and that a third bank had five
accounts where sizable deposits had been made by members of
Abacha's family, according to lawyers for the Nigerian government.
They are trying to have the money returned to the government.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations to report the exact amounts are under way with
Vaduz. In the past, the tiny principality between Switzerland and
Austria did not report any figures. But a stepped-up campaign to
rid links to money laundering has made cooperation much more
likely, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have irrefutable proof of the transfer of sums stripped from
the Central Bank of Nigeria, which were then sent to
Liechtenstein,'' the chief lawyer for the Nigerian government in
the case, Enrico Monfrini. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The paper trail shows that $100 million was transferred to the
Verwaltungs-und Privatsbank and $50 million to the Liechtenstein
Landsbank from banks or companies with ties to Abacha family
members, a lawyer said. Abacha is accused of stripping Nigeria's
oil wealth of billions of dollars in his five years in power. He
died in 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five family accounts have also been found in the Liechtenstein
Global Trust Bank, controlled by Prince Philipp, brother of the
country's monarch, Hans Adam II, according to investigators. The
police in Liechtenstein raided the bank last week as part of an
inquiry into money laundering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of large sums of money is quite likely to add to
pressure on Liechtenstein, a well-known tax shelter, to change its
secretive banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos has accused Abacha, his family and business associates of
embezzling billions, much of it through the central bank. The
largest suspect sum is $654 million in Switzerland, including in
Credit Suisse, one of the largest banks. Investigators said they
had found $630 million in MM Warburg &AMP; Co., a private bank in
Luxembourg, under false names used by the general's sons, Mohammed
and Abba. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Swiss authorities indicted Mohammed Abacha, who is
already in jail in Lagos while awaiting trial in the murder in 1996
of the wife of the late opposition leader. The Swiss charged him
with corruption and money laundering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the millions deposited in the Landsbank were part of an
estimated $250 million in bribes given for General Abacha's support
of $2.5 billion in steel-related projects, a lawyer for Nigeria
said. The Ajoakutu steel works has been at the center of much of
the investigation. Investigators said they had found $300 million
in the United Kingdom in recent months, transferred there to pay
Russian companies to build the factory. A financier Geneva is
seeking that money. He contends that the Russians signed over the
debt to him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
