A8685 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-SENATE-HATE-BOS &LR;      06-19 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-HATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE TO VOTE ON HATE CRIMES BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The crimes shocked the country as much for their
evidence of bigotry as for their gruesome quality: an
African-American man, dragged to his death in Texas; a gay college
student tied to a fence and beaten to death; Jewish schoolchildren
in California, terrorized by a gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, for the first time, the US Senate will hold a recorded
vote on whether these ``hate crimes'' should be punishable under
federal law, and whether the current law should be expanded to
prosecute violence motivated by gender, sexual orientation, and
disability.
</P>
<P>
   Senate aides in both parties said the measure, sponsored by
Senator Edward M. Kennedy, has a strong chance of passing.
</P>
<P>
   The vote is expected to be close, and some Senate aides were
predicting a 50-50 tally _ meaning Vice President Al Gore could
make the dramatic political gesture of breaking the tie. Gore has
criticized Texas Governor George W. Bush, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee, for his objection to a hate-crimes
law in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is seen as having dim prospects in the House, where
Republican leaders succeeded in killing a similar measure last
year. But in the Senate, sentiments, and some votes, have shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When James Byrd Jr. was dragged to death on a dusty Texas
road, something happened to me. I was horrified beyond my ability
to express it,'' Senator Gordon Smith, Republican of Oregon, told a
hushed Senate chamber Monday. ``When Matthew Shepard was beaten to
death on a Wyoming prarie, left on a fence to die, something
happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he had been reluctant to create a special crime
category for gays because he does not support their lifestyle,
which he described as a ``sin.'' But ``I have come to realize that
hate crimes are different. Hate crimes are visited upon one person,
but they're directed at an entire community,'' said Smith, who is a
cosponsor of Kennedy's bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying to fellow Christians everywhere is that it's
time to say to the gay community, I do not agree with you on
everything, but I can help you,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The current law allows federal prosecution of hate crimes under
limited circumstances. The crimes must be based on race, color,
religion, or national origin, and prosecutors must show that the
victim was prevented by the crime from participating in some
federally-protected activity, such as voting.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy proposal, offered as an amendment to a Defense
Department spending bill, would require the Justice Department to
prove only that the crimes interfered with interstate commerce _ a
very broad criterion. Further, it would expand protection to
victims of crimes motivated by sexual orientation, disability and
gender.
</P>
<P>
   Hate crimes ``wound not only the individual, but they also wound
and scar a community,'' Kennedy said during the floor debate. ``We
have had enough of Matthew Shepard cases. We have had enough of the
kinds of vicious murders based on race.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's bill would also allow the Justice Department to award
grants of up to $100,000 to state and local law enforcement
agencies that incur extraordinary expenses in prosecuting hate
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the legislation have long argued that ``all crimes
are hate crimes'' and say the prosecutions should be left to the
states. Forty-two states, including Massachusetts, have hate-crimes
laws, but not all are as sweeping as the Kennedy proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the bill, ranging from the families of Shepard and
Byrd to law enforcement officers and President Clinton, continued a
heavy lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crimes that are motivated by hate really are fundamentally
different, and I believe should be treated differently under the
law,'' Clinton told guests at a reception for the Southwest Voter
Registration Project in Houston. Earlier, the president met
privately with Byrd's sister and nephew.
</P>
<P>
   ``My views toward this issue went 180 degrees after I got
involved in the investigation of Matthew's death,'' said David
O'Malley, commander of the Laramie, Wyo., police department.
O'Malley will be in Washington Tuesday to lobby for the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's bill faces two major obstacles to becoming law: a much
weaker, competing measure by Senator Orrin Hatch, Republican of
Utah, and the adamant opposition to hate-crimes legislation in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has the option of approving one or both of the
hate-crimes proposals. To become law, the House would have to agree
to it in a House-Senate negotiations conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of now, the chances are really slim, because the Republican
leadership is dead-set against it,'' said Representative Barney
Frank, Democrat of Massachusetts, a backer of the Kennedy measure.
But ``political pressure has been known to turn them.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents hope that the weight of a recorded vote passing the
legislation would nudge the House to accept it. The horrific tales
of the victims of bias-based violence may also force the House's
hand, backers hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, they (the GOP leadership) have softened, as least
from my perception,'' said Representative Mark Foley, Republican of
Florida, who arranged a meeting between Shepard's parents and House
Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, Republican of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were taken by both the police officers' arguments
and by the Shephards' loss. I think there is a bit of a more
intellectual understanding of what we're trying to accomplish
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
