<HEADER>
A8692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SKAKEL-HEARING-BOS &LR;      06-19 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING TO WEIGH SKAKEL'S CULPABILITY IN MOXLEY MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 25 years after teenager Martha Moxley was discovered
murdered on her Greenwich, Conn., estate, Michael Skakel will enter
a juvenile courtroom Tuesday to discover whether he will stand
trial in the brutal slaying of his former next-door neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old nephew of Ethel Kennedy, whose entire adult life
has been shadowed by speculation linked to the killing, will hear
what evidence the prosecution has collected to convince Judge
Maureen Dennis that ``reasonable cause'' exists to try him for the
crime as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing, to be held in a small courtroom in Stamford, Conn.,
will be a mini-trial that is expected to last several days. Because
Skakel was 15 at the time of the murder, Dennis also must decide
whether any trial should be held in juvenile or Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel would face from 25 years to life if convicted as an
adult. The stabbing and bludgeoning death shocked exclusive
Greenwich and prompted a quarter-century of speculation and
innuendo, as well as true-crime books, fictional accounts, and
extensive print and broadcast coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Michael ``Mickey'' Sherman, Skakel's attorney, said he remains
confident the state does not have the evidence to reach the
``reasonable cause'' threshold required in juvenile cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm familiar with the quality of the state's case . . . and I
believe it will never pass scrutiny,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   When the state begins to press its argument for a trial,
prosecutor Jonathan C. Benedict is expected to question former
students from the Elan School, a Maine treatment center for
adolescents with substance-abuse problems, who reportedly heard
Skakel confess to the murder during his stay there from 1978 to
1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly with the Elan people, the (prosecution) will try to
connect Michael Skakel to that crime,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman will be allowed to cross-examine state witnesses, but
juvenile-court rules in Connecticut do not allow defense witnesses
in ``reasonable cause'' hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sherman and Benedict have indicated that, if Dennis does
not find ``reasonable cause,'' Skakel is likely to avoid any future
prosecution in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict, the state's attorney for Fairfield County, could not
be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said he expects Benedict will also call Greenwich police
officers to the stand as well as other crime-scene witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   That scene horrified residents of the gated Belle Haven
neighborhood in Greenwich. Moxley, 15, had been struck savagely
with a golf club belonging to Skakel's late mother. She also had
been stabbed with the club's shaft.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel originally told police that he and a group of teenagers
had left Moxley to drive his cousin home on the night of Oct. 30,
1975, and that he had gone to bed when he returned later.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a private investigation commissioned by his family
in 1992, Skakel reportedly said that, before going to bed, he
walked on the Moxley property and tried to attract Martha's
attention without success.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fuhrman, the former Los Angeles police detective who wrote
a book about the Moxley murder, has theorized that this altered
alibi is Skakel's attempt to account for his whereabouts if new
evidence places him at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman named Skakel as the likely suspect in his 1998 book
``Murder in Greenwich.'' That same year, Benedict requested that a
grand jury be named to reexamine the evidence, resulting in
Skakel's indictment this January.
</P>
<P>
   For Dorthy Moxley, Martha's mother, the hearing is vindication
of her years-long effort to retain public interest in the case.
Moxley will travel from her New Jersey home to attend the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be glad when it's over,'' Moxley said last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
