<P>
   NUKE-ENRICHMENT (Bethesda, Md.) _ Ever since Richard Nixon
proposed it in 1968, policy makers have talked about having the
federal government quit the business of enriching uranium for
nuclear power plants. It took decades but the Clinton
administration finally pulled it off two years ago, with Vice
President Al Gore claiming it as a victory for reinventing
government. But it may have came at the worst possible time. The
government never ran the enterprise particularly well. Since
privatization, however, the company has done much worse. The price
of shares in United States Enrichment Corp., as the new company is
known, closed Monday at $4.6875, down from $17.50 soon after the
initial public offering, in July, 1998. Orders are down, costs per
unit are up, and the price of its only product is declining. Now
the issue is coming to a head. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Also of interest:
</P>
<P>
   SEAGRAM-VIVENDI (Undated) _ Talks involving Vivendi, Canal Plus
and Seagram appeared to be heading toward a close, and observers
expected Vivendi to pay about $75 a share in stock. For Vivendi, a
utility, telephone and TV company, the main prizes in the deal
would be Seagram's Universal Studios and its music business, and
Vivendi was expected to sell some of its own water-company assets
along with Seagram's liquor business. But many investors remember
past alliances of these sort that floundered. By Geraldine
Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   SEAGRAM-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Brands like Chivas Regal,
Martell and Captain Morgan will be on the block if Vivendi, Canal
Plus and Seagram do in fact agree to merge. But which
distilled-spirits company is likely to emerge as their new owner?
Many industry experts say Allied Dome would be the probable winner.
By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
