<HEADER>
A8734 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-COURT-MYANMAR-BOS &LR;      06-19 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-MYANMAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT STRIKES DOWN LAW CURTAILING BUSINESS WITH BURMA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a blow to human rights activists who use state and local laws
to battle abuses abroad, the US Supreme Court Monday struck down a
Massachusetts statute that restricted state purchases from
companies doing business in Burma.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, in a unanimous decision, declared that the
Massachusetts law interferes with the federal government's ability
to conduct foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts had argued that it had a right to apply a ``moral
standard'' to its spending decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But the high court said the 1996 Massachusetts law is pre-empted
by the federal government's own sanctions against Burma, referring
to a 1997 executive order signed by President Clinton banning new
investment in the country because of its repression of human rights
and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state act is at odds with the president's intended
authority to speak for the United States among the world's nations
in developing a comprehensive, multilateral strategy to bring
democracy to and improve human rights practices and the quality of
life in Burma,'' Justice David H. Souter wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Burma human rights advocates said they consider the
ruling merely a ``setback,'' saying the decision still allows them
to use other strategies such as boycotts and shareholder
resolutions to generate economic pressure on firms doing business
with the military dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   But others, like Simon Billenness, a senior analyst with
Trillium Assett Management in Boston and co-author of the statute,
acknolwedge that the selective purchasing law was the most
effective tool in the fight for human rights there and in other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had the Supreme Court ruled this way in the 1980's it would
have severely blunted the anti-apartheid movement in the US,''
Billneness said. The Burma law had been modeled after the selective
purchasing laws that were adopted by 25 states and helped end the
racist regime in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have documented frequent abuses of rights in
the country, including harsh treatment of dissidents and
suppression of democracy in Burma, also known as Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts statute, which was the only state selective
purchasing law aimed at Burma in the nation, had created a serious
conflict between America and its major trading partners,
particularly the European Commission and Japan. European leaders
had appealed the case to the World Trade Organization, concerned
that European companies would be penalized.
</P>
<P>
   And they feared passage of similar laws now under debate,
including a Massachusetts lawmaker's proposal to punish firms that
trade with Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the White House dispatched trade officials to
Beacon Hill to ask lawmakers to repeal or amend the law, but they
were rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the decision was hailed by the US businesses that
operate overseas and those in the legal field, who have long
claimed that the law -- and similar other statutes passed by a
number of cities including Los Angeles -- had created serious
confusion and disrupted the country's international commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blow for rationality,'' said Andrew Grainger, president
of the New England Legal Foundation, which represented the
Associated Industries of Massachusetts and the Retailers
Association of Massachusetts in the case. He said the Burma law had
raised the cost of public contracts ``without achieving any
demonstrable impact on human rights halfway around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   David Schmahmann , a partner in the Boston firm Nutter McClennon
&AMP; Fish, said he is ``not the tiny bit suprised'' at the court's
decision because, he said, the US Constitution clearly assigns the
role of foreign policy to the federal government and that ``country
has to speak with once voice.''.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to foreign trade, you can't have one set of laws
passed by the federal government and another inconsistent set of
laws passed by cities and states,'' said Schmahmann, who has
represented business clients that were covered by the law. But
Robert Stumberg, a professor at Georgetown University Law Center
viewed the court's decision more narrowly. Stumberg, who
represented members of Congress who supported the state's law,
noted that the court was very specific in its ruling that the law
is only pre-empted because there is a federal statute addressing
the same policy issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a decision with sweeping constitutional impact,''
Stumberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The first blow to the law came in 1998 when US District Court
Judge Joseph Tauro in Boston struck down the statute, saying it
interfered with the federal governments right to conduct foreign
policy. Tauro's ruling was interpreted at the time on a more
general prohibition on states' meddling in foreign policy. That
ruling was upheld in a federal appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Stumberg said if the federal appeals court decision had stood
without further challenge, human rights advocates would have faced
more restrictions on the kinds of activities they could employ to
pressure other repressive regimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The constitutional claims were most sweeping in the opinion of
the (appeals court),'' Stumberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, using the decision as a guide, state Represenative Byron
Rushing, the Democrat who sponsored the Burma law, said he is now
ready to push the House and Senate to pass a bill that would ban
the investment of state pension funds in firms that do business in
Burma. That bill is currently before a House committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to find ways to put pressure on companies doing
business in Burma, ways that are constitutional,'' Rushing said.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts law was not an outright ban on state commerce
with firms conducting business with Burma. Instead, it penalized
them, making it hard for them to win government contracts by adding
10 percent to any bids the companies proposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
