<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 25)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York Seaway Trail Gets an Upstate Center
</P>
<P>
   The New York Seaway Trail is a 454-mile scenic alternative to
modern highways along Lake Erie, the Niagara River, Lake Ontario
and the St. Lawrence River. To introduce visitors to the abundant
cultural, historical and recreational resources along the trail,
the Seaway Trail Foundation will open the Seaway Trail Discovery
Center on July 15 in Sackets Harbor, just west of Watertown on Lake
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   The center, a three-story federal building built in 1817 as the
Union Hotel, has nine rooms with interactive exhibits on the
history, architecture and natural resources of 10 counties of New
York _ St. Lawrence, Jefferson, Oswego, Cayuga, Wayne, Monroe,
Orleans, Niagara, Erie and Chautauqua. Exhibits focus on the 27
historic lighthouses along the route; on local battles in the War
of 1812; woodlands, wetlands and beaches; famous residents, among
them Susan B. Anthony, Frederic Remington and George Eastman; and
agriculture. An exhibit features Federal and Victorian houses and
the work of Frank Lloyd Wright and Frederick Law Olmsted, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   The Seaway Trail Discovery Center, at Ray and West Main Streets
in Sackets Harbor, will be open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily through
Labor Day, then Monday through Saturday through October. Admission
is $4, $3 for students and ages 65 and up, $2 for ages 4 to 17.
Information: (800) 732-9298.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline Adds Choices For Renting Cars
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com, which lets people propose online the price they
will pay for air fares, hotel rooms, groceries and other services,
this month added two car rental companies, Hertz and Alamo, to its
vendors. In November, the Budget and National chains began renting
cars through Priceline.com. The four companies have about 70
percent of the domestic car rental business at airports.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour of filling out the online bidding form, customers
are notified by e-mail if their bid is accepted. Vehicles are
available only at airports, and bidders do not choose which company
supplies the car. They can select any type of passenger vehicle,
all of which come with unlimited mileage.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com said its vendors are renting cars at 100 locations
and adding more each week. It said that by the end of March, it was
processing 20,000 vehicle-days of car rentals each week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bidders will get the best deals on days, and in places, where
the rental companies have excess vehicles in their parking lots. If
a bid is accepted, there is a fee of $5 a rental. In addition,
customers pay normal rental taxes, which are disclosed in advance
at the bidding site. The Web site, www.priceline.com, accepts bids
from drivers 18 and older.
</P>
<P>
   A Very Big Picnic For Bastille Day
</P>
<P>
   On July 14, tanks will roll down the Champs-Elysees and fighter
planes will swoop overhead for the traditional military parade that
marks the birthday of the French Republic. Across the nation, there
will be fireworks and open-air dances.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Bastille Day 2000 calls for something special. Last
November, schoolchildren started planting thousands of saplings
along the Paris Meridian, the line running 2 degrees 20 minutes 14
seconds east of Greenwich, from Dunkirk to Prats-de-Molo on the
Spanish border. On Bastille Day, this 597-mile tree line sets the
stage for the largest dejeuner sur l'herbe in French history. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 405 miles of checkered tablecloth will be spread over
picnic tables _some of them up to six-tenths of a mile long _ along
the Meridian. Three million people are expected to bring picnic
baskets or stock up on regional delicacies at adjoining market
stalls. An air show and a multidisciplinary relay race _ on
everything from bicycles to roller skates to horses _ following the
picnic path will round out the festivities.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On or off the meridian, each town is adding its own flourish to
the nationwide party. Amiens puts an Aussie accent on the holiday
with a brass band from Canberra, boomerang lessons and a giant
Australian barbecue. Avignon will see off the Provencal lap of the
Tour de France bicycle race. And in Paris, over seven miles of
tables will be set up from the Porte de Montmartre to the Porte de
Gentilly _ a track that slices though the Avenue de l'Opera, the
Louvre courtyard and the Jardin du Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   News on the festivities is available at www.wmevent.net (in
French only) or www.2000enfrance.com.
</P>
<P>
   Tall Ships to Visit Boston Between Races
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Tall Ships 2000 Race Series, an international
fleet of more than 100 tall ships will visit Boston Harbor July 11
to 20 for Sail Boston 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The International Sail Training Association is sponsoring the
races, which started in April in England and Italy. After races
from Southampton and Genoa finished in Cadiz, the ships competed in
a trans-Atlantic race to Bermuda. From Bermuda, the fleet will
cruise north to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The tall ships are expected to start arriving in Boston on July
8. At 9 a.m. on July 11, the fleet will enter the harbor in a Grand
Parade of Sail, escorted by the USS Constitution, Old Ironsides,
the oldest commissioned warship in the world, whose berth is at the
Charlestown Navy Yard.
</P>
<P>
   The ships will be docked at the Black Falcon Cruise Terminal,
the World Trade Center, the North Jetty and the Navy Yard, and the
public will be allowed to board various ships, including the
aircraft carrier John F. Kennedy, free. Scheduled events range from
a Blessing of the Sails at Old North Church to a jazz and blues
festival to two displays of fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   On July 16, the ships will parade out of the harbor for the next
leg of the race, to Halifax, Nova Scotia. After Halifax, the ships
will race back across the Atlantic to Amsterdam. But some tall
ships will remain on view until July 21.
</P>
<P>
   A schedule of events is available at www.sailboston.com. More
information, including ticket prices for certain events, is also
available at (617) 439-4114.
</P>
<P>
   Till the Cows (and Moose and Pigs) Come Home
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Zurich staged an outdoor exhibition of hundreds of
fiberglass cows decorated by various artists, and Chicago did the
same last summer. Each was a hit, and similar exhibitions are
taking place in dozens of North American cities. Orlando, Fla.,
will be crawling with lizards; Grand Rapids, Mich., is a giant
rabbit hutch; New Orleans is awash in fish, and St. Louis is
sticking with two-leggers: people. Here are a few other examples.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI
</P>
<P>
   Big Pig Gig, until Oct. 31. About 400 life-size fiberglass pigs
in downtown Cincinnati, where live versions were herded through the
streets in the mid-19th century. Also displayed in Covington and
Newport, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (513) 333-0388, www.bigpiggig.com
</P>
<P>
   RHODE ISLAND
</P>
<P>
   The Birthplace of Fun, until Nov. 30. Over 50 six-foot-tall
statues of Mr. Potato Head (created in 1952 in Pawtucket, R.I., by
Hasbro), at attractions, restaurants and recreation areas
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (401) 222-2601, www.visitrhodeisland.com
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO
</P>
<P>
   Moose in the City, through mid October. More than 250 life-size
moose statues, mostly in downtown Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (416) 395-7350, www.city.toronto.on.ca
</P>
<P>
   ST. PAUL
</P>
<P>
   Peanuts on Parade, to early October. About 70 five-foot-tall
statues of Snoopy (a creation of a native son, Charles M. Schulz),
throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (651) 266-8542, www.ci.stpaul.mn.us
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK CITY
</P>
<P>
   CowParade New York 2000, until Sept. 3. Hundreds of life-size
cows painted by artists and schoolchildren are on display at parks
and other public spaces in the five boroughs. Stamford, Conn., and
Orange, N.J., will also have exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   Information: www.cowparadenewyork.com &QL;
</P>
