<HEADLINE>
LONDON FIRM TO BUY UNITED ASSET MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Old Mutual PLC, an insurer and mutual fund management
firm headquartered in London, agreed Monday to buy Boston-based
United Asset Management, the money management holding company that
started in 1980 with an innovative model but has stumbled of late.
</P>
<P>
   The deal underscored two trends, analysts said. First, even
institutions in Boston's venerable mutual fund industry are on the
auction block, following purchases by out-of-towners of banks,
media outlets, and department stores. Second, overseas interest in
US mutual-fund companies is at a peak.
</P>
<P>
   The UAM acquisition, for $1.4 billion or $25 a share _ a 22
percent premium over Friday's closing price _ is seen as a good buy
for Old Mutual, which is looking to diversify. The deal closely
follows announcements in the past month that CDC Asset Management
of France will buy Nvest Cos. for $2.2 billion and UniCredito
Italiano will acquire the Pioneer Group Inc. for $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're seeing is the final throes of mass globalization
of the industry,'' said Robert Powell, a former editor of Dalbar's
mutual fund newsletter and now launching moneycast.com, a financial
education Web site. ``There's going to be more consolidation and it
will probably accelerate. For a foreign player to come in and buy
this money management firm, that's an attractive proposition. They
can buy a semi-floundering business and distribute it overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   UAM, founded by Norman Reamer from Putnam Investments 20 years
ago, has $188 billion under management in a collection of 40
affiliated money-management companies. But UAM had to endure $7
billion in withdrawals in the first quarter of this year, part of a
trend of outflows attributed to retiring money managers, hot hands
that turned cold, and an emphasis on traditional pension-fund
investing.
</P>
<P>
   UAM's units include Pilgrim Baxter &AMP; Associates Inc. and Barrow,
Hanley, Mewhinney &AMP; Strauss Inc. James Orr III, president and chief
executive of UAM, said the affiliates will maintain their autonomy
after the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investment business in general is going through a period
of restructuring,'' Orr said. ``We were pleased to deliver a good
value to our shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Anstee, finance director for Old Mutual, said in an
interview from London the deal ``broadens our capability'' and was
a ``good strategic fit for our business.'' He said the affiliates
will be encouraged to do more cross-selling and work more closely
together.
</P>
<P>
   Old Mutual, South Africa's largest insurer, has been looking to
expand into asset management. It bought British broker and fund
manager Gerrard Group for $796 million in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
