<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN PRESIDENT DENOUNCES PREDICTIONS OF ELECTION FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ President Ernesto Zedillo on Monday assailed
opposition candidates who have warned of possible irregularities in
the July 2 election for president.
</P>
<P>
   Using sharp words for a normally mild-spoken chief executive,
Zedillo accused the opposition candidates of ``sowing mistrust'' in
the federal agency that is overseeing the vote.
</P>
<P>
   He said they were also trying to discredit the election with
``intransigent positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Zedillo did not mention anyone by name, his comments
seemed directed at Vicente Fox, a right-of-center candidate who is
challenging the governing party, and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a
left-leaning contender. The two candidates have been battling each
other furiously from the campaign trail, but last week they joined
in a pact to guard against voter coercion before the election and
against fraud during the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech last week, Cardenas proposed to all the candidates
that if the election is not clean, no one should declare victory.
Fox has predicted that if the governing party candidate, Francisco
Labastida Ochoa, does not win by at least 10 points, many Mexicans
will not believe that he won fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo said Monday, ``Those who proclaim election results
before the citizens have voted, and insinuate that they will not
recognize the outcome if they do not win, show no democratic
convictions or respect for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   His salvo echoed a speech Labastida made on Sunday in Mexico
City before tens of thousands of followers of the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI. The candidate
said this year's elections would be ``the cleanest and most
competitive in our history.''
</P>
<P>
   To shouts of joy, Labastida said, ``Only those who already feel
defeated would cry fraud ahead of time.''
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that this election is far more open and fair
than any other Mexico has had. The Federal Electoral Institute,
which for the first time is largely independent from the
government, has spent $918 million to level the playing field for
the candidates and build a foolproof system for tallying the
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   But the PRI, which has held presidential power for seven
decades, remains intertwined with the government and has a
tradition of using handouts or threats to sway the vote. Both
Mexican and international election observers have reported numerous
incidents that indicate that the PRI is making widespread use of
questionable tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of making this kind of comments, President Zedillo
should demonstrate his own democratic good will by taking his hands
off the electoral process and stopping the vote-buying by the
federal government,'' Marta Sahagun, Fox's spokeswoman, responded
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After months of being on the sidelines, Zedillo has become more
active in promoting Labastida and the PRI. According to the
newspaper Reforma, since April 1 Zedillo has been exceptionally
busy inaugurating public work projects around the country, worth a
total of $435 million.
</P>
<P>
   The president also ignored a call from the federal elections
agency to cancel advertising of government programs in the final
weeks before the election. Every day, the Mexico City newspapers
are filled with full-page ads touting the successes of federal
programs. Leading television and radio news shows are punctuated
with spots carrying the same message.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
