A8738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u c BC-LIVING-HISTORY20-COX     06-19 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVING-HISTORY20-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Living history: Putting a village together through artifacts
</P>
<P>
   By Dann Stupp
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Norm MacIntyre could easily crack open an Ohio
history book and learn all about the area's Fort Ancient
settlements. Of course, he prefers doing things the traditional
way.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's chiseling fish hooks from animal bones, digging out
a canoe or helping to revive a tall-grass prairie, the live-in
historian is helping to piece back together a Fort Ancient village.
</P>
<P>
   MacIntyre, a retired cop and now handyman extraordinaire for
SunWatch Indian Village, can stroll through his back yard on the
bank of the Great Miami River and learn firsthand about what daily
life was like 800 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first moved in, it was like letting a cat loose in a
seafood store,'' he says. ``There were all the raw materials I
needed here. People were always donating bones and hides and
feathers, and I had some spare time. I started just making stuff
for our museum's exhibits, but then I couldn't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   MacIntyre's creations will be featured at this weekend's annual
SummerFest at SunWatch, which celebrates American Indian culture
with demonstrations of crafts, sports, games and skills. There will
be dance performances, singing, storytelling, a children's activity
area and food.
</P>
<P>
   MacIntyre, 63, moved onto the site in 1990. But he was one of
the first volunteers to begin work on the salvation of the
prehistoric village in 1970. He would work a 4 p.m.-to-midnight
shift as a Xenia police officer and then work until 2 a.m.
excavating a site that, at the time, seemed to be nothing more than
a cornfield. He and the other original volunteers soon learned that
a whole village was buried just 12 inches under the ground's
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, SunWatch is home to a semi-restored village
with several reconstructed homes, including the Big House, which
served as the village's community center in the 1200s. In addition,
MacIntyre helped create exhibits of the villagers` tools, methods
of storing grain, houses and all aspects of their daily lives for
the SunWatch Indian Village Museum with the other volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   He also leads tours and educates students from all over the
area. However, he knows a traditional classroom approach won't cut
it with his younger visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``With third- and fourth- and fifth-graders, talking about
something just isn't like doing it,'' he says. ``So I got busy
making some instruments. A lot of drums, rattles and whistles _ all
things we had found when digging. Now the kids can go out there and
make a little music and get a big kick out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   His love of tinkering with clay, bone and stone eventually
became a passion. So a few years ago, he enrolled in sculpting
classes at Sinclair Community College in Dayton, and now his works
have become a favorite in SunWatch's gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like stealing,'' he says. ``I can't believe what
people pay for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people can believe it, including Tess Little, associate
professor of art at Sinclair and MacIntyre's teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great knack for putting things together,'' says
Little. ``He can find things, and he knows how to transform them.
He makes some really fun things that sell just as quick as he makes
him.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his latest pieces involved affixing tiny sculpted lizards
onto a log he found in the Great Miami. The piece, fittingly called
Lizard Log, is a prime example of his ability to see everyday
objects as potential creations.
</P>
<P>
   His style, which Little says is folklike, with an American
Indian touch, has become an important part of the village as well
as the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Little says it's more than an eye for creativity that makes
MacIntyre an asset to her classes. She says a big heart and a
passion for art makes him one of her most-cherished students.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very good man that goes out of his way to help
people,'' she says. ``He had the whole class over (to SunWatch) for
a picnic supper one time. The students were thrilled. He's such a
knowledgeable man about American Indian history and the region.
He's one of those students who really cares about giving back to
the community. SunWatch is very lucky to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than a Jack Russell terrier named Katy, MacIntyre lives
alone on the 10-plus acres of SunWatch. The peaceful setting was a
welcomed opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when when I retired, I said I never wanted to tell
anybody what to do or to have anybody tell me what to do,'' he
says. ``It's worked out pretty well for me and, I believe, for
SunWatch, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A heart problem forced MacIntyre to slow down nearly a decade
ago. He knew it was time to retire, but he wasn't about to quit
enjoying life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really worried about retirement my whole life because
there were so many things I like to do,'' he says. ``I like to fish
and garden and travel and work with my hands. This was the perfect
chance to do it all.''
</P>
<P>
   And others know how perfect it is, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word was out after my recent heart surgery,'' he says.
``SunWatch got a call from somebody that wanted to know if my
apartment was available because they heard I had died. Word travels
fast, but I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   And he doesn't plan to leave anytime soon. From his corner of
SunWatch, he can see the rebirth of an 800-year-old village that
he's spent most of his adult life recreating. According to
MacIntyre, there's nothing more satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   How to go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What: SummerFest 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When: 10 a.m. to 9 p.m. Saturday and noon to 8 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where: SunWatch Indian Village, 2301 West River Road.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Admission: $6 adults, $4 children 6-17; group rates available;
free parking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For more information: Call 268-1760 or go to www.sunwatch.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
