<SLUG> BC-3ap0620a </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marietta Square deal hits a snag
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The proposal for a 12-story high-rise on the Marietta Square may
have risen again, but both sides now say compromise may yield a
more lasting victory than an all-or-nothing fight.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether opponents in the battle can reach any
sort of agreement that appeases both the business and historic
preservationist communities in downtown Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman, square landlord and developer Philip Goldstein
is now negotiating with opponents of his proposed high-rise, which
is expected to have a fourth vote before the Marietta Historic
Board of Review within the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The building, which would set one block of the square on Mill
Street, has tentatively been approved once and denied twice by one
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Patti and Van Pearlberg, co-chairs of Cobb Landmarks and
Historical Society, and Goldstein all say they're trying to reach a
compromise on the height. Both sides have indicated eight stories
might be acceptable, although it would require concessions from the
city of Marietta, such as closing Denmead Street, a dead-end road
adjacent to the building site.
</P>
<P>
   But neither side has wholeheartedly supported going up or down
much with the size of the building, which the board has approved
for six stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to work together and come up with
something that is in between his first choice and our first
choice,'' said Patti Pearlberg, vice president of asset management
at Coro Realty Advisors. ``I think if the community embraced the
building the community could get the street closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much taller? That's what we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobb Landmarks is meeting with architects to drum up any
alternate plan that might provide Goldstein and developer Peter
Bright with enough square footage to shorten the building. The last
application was submitted not in Bright's name but in the name of
Mary Goldstein, Philip Goldstein's mother, who owns the property
jointly with her son.
</P>
<P>
   Initially when the controversy started to boil in March, neither
side showed much interest in compromising. Goldstein and developer
Peter Bright insisted on 12 stories. Cobb Landmarks and other
preservationists said six was the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Now compromise is being wrapped in the mantra of civic
responsibility. In reality, Goldstein has fought to bring a
high-rise to the Marietta Square, where his family owns about half
the real estate, for more than 12 years. He got one 10-story
project approved but failed to bring it to fruition.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
