<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Web effort helps monitor chronic diseases
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quick quiz: true or false?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  One-third of the U.S. population suffers from some form of
chronic disease: asthma, auto-immune problems, birth defects,
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Exposure to chemical changes in the environment _ industrial
solvents, tobacco smoke, pesticides, smog _ are believed to foster
development of some chronic diseases.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  There is no national system for tracking the occurrence of
most chronic diseases, and no statistical means of comparing
environmental problems with rates of chronic diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Answers: True, true and true _ and deeply problematic.
Infectious diseases, from HIV/
</P>
<P>
   AIDS to tuberculosis to E. coli O157:H7, are monitored by local
and state health departments and the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention. Though the CDC tracks a number of chronic
diseases such as asthma and cancer, there is no comparable local or
state structure feeding it more detailed data.
</P>
<P>
   A Web-based effort has set out to change that. Health Track
(health-track.org), a joint project of the Pew Charitable Trusts
and Georgetown University, is an elegantly designed,
easy-to-navigate site with a definite point of view: that chronic
disease problems should be monitored nationally and locally, and
that the Internet provides the means to do it. The effort, which
recently began national newspaper advertising, offers downloadable
research reports, links to national organizations and scorecards on
local environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
