<HEADER>
A8746 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOSPITALS-WIRED20-COX     06-19 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALS-WIRED20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online hospitals improve quality of care
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christina Grady just knew something wasn't right.
</P>
<P>
   Her newborn baby, Crystal, wasn't eating. Her family doctor had
chalked it up to Grady's not knowing how to breast-feed. But Grady,
of Austell, didn't believe that was the problem with her second
child.
</P>
<P>
   So she phoned Children's Healthcare of Atlanta's call center,
newly outfitted with a computer program armed with artificial
intelligence designed to help nurses make quick and detailed
diagnoses. In minutes, nurse Cathy Dandelikas determined that
Crystal wasn't having feeding problems but was probably struggling
for her life.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the baby underwent emergency surgery to correct a
blocked aorta, the heart's main artery. Today, Crystal is a happy,
healthy 2-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you ever express how grateful you are?'' asked Grady,
35. ``If she hadn't stressed to me how important it was to go (to
the emergency department) _ and to go immediately _ I would have
lost my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   For many people, medical technology means newfangled gadgets:
lasers, tiny cameras, heart monitors and whirring MRI machines. But
as hospitals become increasingly wired with sophisticated computer
systems and online capabilities, those behind-the-scenes
technologies are proving to be an important way to improve overall
health care. As a result, patients may see safer and better
treatment all the way from the emergency room to the surgical wing
to the billing department.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, two hospital systems _ Children's Healthcare of
Atlanta (www.choa.org) and Promina Health System (www.promina.org)
_ were named among the nation's Top 100 wired hospital systems by
the trade journal Hospitals and Health Networks. The list also
included the Medical College of Georgia Hospital in Augusta
(www.mcg.edu) and Memorial Health System in Savannah
(www.memorialhealth.com).
</P>
<P>
   They earned the distinction in part because of a wide array of
computer-based technology that is in place or will be within 18
months:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Children's Healthcare has a secure, encrypted Internet system
that allows doctors to view patients' medical records and
laboratory results from their personal computers at home. Within
six months, the hospital system hopes to give doctors PalmPilots to
expand their mobility and the amount of information at their
fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some doctors' offices that are part of the Promina network
have complete electronic patient records, which let them verify and
order prescription refills faster. They also can ship the data
electronically to patients' pharmacists and notify patients of drug
recalls within hours of an alert.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Children's Healthcare plans to install a new computer system
at Egleston and Scottish Rite hospitals and clinics to protect
patients from medication errors. Under the system, patients would
receive a bar code at admission. Before any medication is
administered, a nurse would swipe a patient's bar code and a drug's
bar code to make sure they match. When used elsewhere, the system
has been shown to reduce pharmaceutical errors, which account for
at least 7,000 deaths per year nationwide, by up to 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Piedmont Medical Center, an anchor hospital of the Promina
Health System, is building electronic records that can follow
patients from the cradle to the grave. This record system will
allow physicians to have a more comprehensive view of a patient's
overall health. It will include ``expert system technology,'' which
will flag lab results that seem abnormal when compared with the
patient's medical history.
</P>
<P>
   And Children's Healthcare has installed almost 30 computers in
nurses' homes so that they can help handle more than 40,000
emergency calls a month. ``The only difference between the nurse at
home and the nurse at work is the nurse at home may be in her
pajamas,'' said Cathy Addison, a manager of the call system.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Simon, vice president of Informatics at Children's
Healthcare of Atlanta, said such information technology is ``the
wave of the future for health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, new technology also brings new complications and
concerns. Hospital preparations last December for potential Y2K
glitches _ which never materialized _ underscored how
computer-dependent health care facilities have become more
vulnerable to an electronic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   There's also lingering concern about keeping patient records
confidential, as more files become computerized and accessible to
doctors and nurses. Although many hospitals say their Internet
communications are encrypted, they face the same security issues as
any other company doing business over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is always that quicker, faster and better will
translate into disaster, disaster, disaster,'' said Mike Donio of
the People's Medical Society, an Allentown, Penn., nonprofit
patient-advocacy group. ``We don't want to be Luddites, we need
progress, but we also need to use caution on who is going to get
access (to records) and how it's going to be sent.''
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, more hospitals are grappling with such issues. But
many hospitals across the state are still playing catch-up and
haven't had to deal with many of the ethical dilemmas that more
wired facilities face.
</P>
<P>
   Although all of the state's hospitals already do electronic
billing _ and about half have Web sites _ a majority are just
starting to branch out and explore the hundreds of different
applications that could strengthen and streamline their operations.
</P>
<P>
   Some hospitals are gathering data on their performance:
examining statistics on patient recovery, mortality, infection and
return visits. Of course, most aren't willing to share _ even in
the most basic way _ what they learn with their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Other hospitals are experimenting with ways to reach their
patients through their Web sites and e-mail. For example, most of
the top 100 wired hospitals offered online information about
asthma, depression, stroke and HIV, according to Hospitals and
Health Networks.
</P>
<P>
   And in the near future, Children's Hospital hopes to allow
parents, who would have normally called the 404-250-KIDS hotline,
to contact nurses through its Web site instead. More complicated
than e-mail, the new program will ask parents a list of questions
about their child's symptoms and how soon they need a call back,
Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing new opportunities emerging,'' said Glen Pearson,
executive vice president of the Georgia Hospital Association. ``Now
the question is how do we assess the best way to use these new
kinds of information technology.''
</P>
<P>
   There's so much interest that the Georgia Hospital Association
has created an ``Internet Technology Advisor Group,'' which hopes
to help hospitals evaluate what is valuable and what is merely
trendy. Its first meeting was in March.
</P>
<P>
   This new health care trend is still in its infancy. Among the
top 100 wired hospitals in the nation, only 58 percent of the
doctors could access their patients' records and 61 percent could
view lab results via the Internet. And only 10 percent of patient
appointments could be scheduled through the Internet, according to
Hospitals and Health Networks' survey.
</P>
<P>
   But already, experts say wired hospitals result in better care.
And no one believes that more than Grady, 35, and her husband,
John.
</P>
<P>
   After their daughter was stabilized at Cobb Hospital, she was
transferred to Egleston for emergency surgery. In the course of
that treatment, doctors also discovered two heart murmurs. But
everything was repaired, and now Crystal is an active 2-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's fine, she's healthy,'' Grady said. ``And we're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
