<SLUG> BC-LEA-THOMPSON20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nothing perky about this Lea Thompson
 &HT;    TV, movie star returns to stage for `Cabaret'
 &HT;    By Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lea Thompson as Sally Bowles, the down-on-her-luck saloon singer
in ``Cabaret''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Caroline in the City's'' Lea Thompson? ``Howard the Duck's''
Lea Thompson? ``Back to the Future's'' Lea Thompson?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and if notices in Pittsburgh, Detroit and Baltimore are any
indication, she's buried her perky image and fully embraced the
cheap chanteuse who's dancing in her undies and desperately seeking
love in 1929 Berlin. Hitler is waiting in the wings, but for Sally
and her friends at the seedy Kit Kat Klub, it's better to drink,
drug and debauch than worry about what might or might not happen in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Isherwood, who created Sally in his ``Berlin
Stories'' (1946), says, ``She sang badly, without any expression
... yet her performance was, in its own way, effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson describes Sally as ``just a really fun girl who is
trying to survive in the only way she knows how. She's a little
lost, and she's looking for love, so I find her very likable. . . .
It's just set in a really wild, terrible time. How awful to be
stuck in history and be that vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, the actress, is anything but vulnerable onstage, a
place where she feels at home, she explains, intermittently yawning
through a late-morning conversation from Baltimore, ``Cabaret's''
last stop before Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent from the time I was 9 until I was 21 onstage,'' she
says. Thompson grew up in Minneapolis, the youngest of five
children, and danced for most of her life. It was only after moving
to New York and realizing that she wasn't going to be as good as
she wanted to be (Mikhail Baryshnikov reportedly told her she was
``too stocky'') that she turned to acting.
</P>
<P>
   And although she's known for her TV and film work, Thompson has
never really left the stage, having done a half-dozen or so roles
on the West Coast, including Tony Kushner's ``The Illusion'' and
Cherie in William Inge's ``Bus Stop.''
</P>
<P>
   She comes from a family of performers. Her oldest brother,
Andrew Thompson, dances with the Colorado Ballet. Another brother,
Barry Thompson, is an actor in Los Angeles. And, Lea says, she's
living out her mother's dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom,'' Thompson says of Babah Hanson, ``is very talented.
She did just about everything. Big-band singer. Great piano player.
A wonderful actress. . . . She's also a director, songwriter,
sculptor. It goes back to my grandpas who were in the Chautauqua
circus and my uncles who were minstrel men. It was just always
around. Art and singing and dancing, that's how we played. We
didn't even have a TV. It was predetermined genetically that some
of us were going to become artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Artists. An interesting word to describe Sally Bowles, who in
this version of ``Cabaret'' inhabits a darker, more frightening
world than the one in the 1966 original with Joel Grey or the 1972
movie. Thompson is the latest in a line of Sallys in the current
production, beginning with 1998 Tony Award winner Natasha
Richardson and including Jennifer Jason Leigh, Teri Hatcher, Susan
Egan and Joely Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson auditioned for Sally in March 1999, while still doing
``Caroline.'' She sang ``Maybe This Time,'' Sally's last number in
Act 1, for choreographer and co-director Rob Marshall and ``a whole
huge amount of people.''
</P>
<P>
   She thought it went well, but heard nothing for a ... long ...
time. ``Caroline'' finished its fourth and final season on NBC.
Thompson took a year off and turned down a number of other jobs,
instead spending time with her husband, movie director Howard
Deutch, and daughters Madelyn, 9, and Zoe, 5. Finally, the call
came. ``This was really the one thing I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson will tour with ``Cabaret,'' a four-time Tony winner in
'98, until Aug. 1, then begin a three-month run on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   For now, she's anticipating the next challenge: Atlanta and the
4,600-seat Fox Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to it, even in that big hall,'' she says.
``These older places just fit the show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : Cabaret opens at the Fox:
www.cabarettour.com
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabaret''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight-Friday; 2 and 8 p.m. Saturday; 2 and 7:30 p.m. Sunday.
Contains adult themes and sexuality. $20-$42. Fox Theatre, 660
Peachtree St. N.E. 404-817-8700 or www.broadwayseries.com or
www.ticketmaster.com.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Janich writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
