<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jane admits to Oprah: `I changed'
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jane Fonda, who has remained relatively mum about her separation
from Ted Turner, opens up and tells all to Oprah Winfrey in the
second issue of O, the Oprah Magazine ($2.95).
</P>
<P>
   Fonda confesses that she has struggled with the ``disease to
please'' for most of her life and accepts much of the blame for the
separation. ``I changed,'' she tells Winfrey. ``I changed probably
more than he did, and we need to see what that means. ... Whatever
happens in terms of our living arrangements, we will always be
close.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonda also says she regrets posing with an antiaircraft gun for
a picture in North Vietnam in 1972. ``It was the most horrible
thing I could possibly have done.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, she talks about ``finding her voice'' for the
third act of her life, building a loft apartment with 20-foot
ceilings in a downtown Atlanta ``'hood,'' and finding spirituality.
She says she attends Providence Missionary Baptist Church as well
as other churches in Atlanta. And despite Turner's having once said
that ``Christianity is for losers,'' Fonda says he's hostile toward
organized religion, not God. ``Ted has read the Bible cover to
cover, twice. He can quote Scripture better than most preachers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More Jane: In a less revealing interview in The Season
($3.95), Fonda talks about her work with the Georgia Campaign for
Adolescent Pregnancy Prevention to new Associate Editor Kathleen
Neal, and this year's fund-raising premiere of the movie ``The
Perfect Storm'' June 27 at the Fox Theatre. The event is expected
to raise $500,000 for G-CAPP, and includes an appearance by Fonda's
brother, Peter, who will auction off a trip for four people to join
him on a motorcycle ride from his Montana ranch to Sturgis, S.D.,
where he'll be inducted into the Motorcycle Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Season Editor Gloria Lane says she's expanding the focus of the
Atlanta-based magazine to cover more lifestyle topics such as
dining, fashion, shopping and homes. The summer issue features
travel destinations from Switzerland and France to Dahlonega and
Florida's Emerald Coast.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Peeping passion: In its cover story, Time ($3.50) takes a
keyhole look at ``Survivor,'' ``The Real World,'' ``1900 House''
and other voyeuristic TV shows. Why are so many people watching
these shows, as well as clicking in on the Internet's 24-hour
Webcam sites? For one thing, says Paul Romer, creator of ``Big
Brother,'' there's always the possibility of a surprise. ``It's
like a baseball game. Even when the game isn't interesting, you
wait and stay because the next hit could be a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Behind the scenes: So just who is the brain behind
``Survivor''? Men's Journal ($3.95) visits with creator Mark
Burnett, who grew up in London, joined the British army during the
Falklands War and has supported himself as a nanny. Burnett says
he's simply holding up a mirror to modern culture and the American
dream with his show. And, he adds, he probably would be the first
to be voted off the island.
</P>
<P>
   Also in this issue is an entertaining profile of George Clooney,
whose idea of a fun evening is cutting his own hair and spending
the night alone with a plate of pasta and ``The Baby Goat
Murders,'' Mississippi writer Larry Brown's true story about life
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Heir apparent: The royals haven't been in the news lately,
what with the news moratorium placed on Princess Diana's sons after
her death. That apparently is over now that Prince William turns 18
on Wednesday. Newsweek ($3.50) features William as its cover story,
with the inside scoop on his life out of the spotlight. So what's
the scoop? Well, now we know that he drives a Volkswagen Golf and a
motorcyle, likes techno music, was rumored to be interested in
Camilla Parker Bowles' niece Emma, and plans to study art history
after taking a year off to see the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: AMI Auto World Weekly ($2.49) debuts today with
72 pages of buyer-friendly reviews, price comparisons and ``spy
photos'' of the newest, not-yet-released vehicles such as the
Lincoln pickup and the Audi A8. ... U.S. News &AMP; World Report
($3.50) takes a similar route with a look at the sleek new cars
marketed to appeal to baby boomers with empty nests and full
wallets. Models include the Chrysler PT Cruiser and the Chevrolet
SSR: a hybrid of a truck and a convertible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
