A8750 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CENDANT-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      06-19 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENDANT-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENDENT SUES ERNST &AMP; YOUNG, CHARGING COMPLICITY IN MERGER FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cendant Corp. contended in a court filing Monday that the
accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young knew of widespread fraud at CUC
International, a predecessor to Cendant, by 1997 and chose to help
the fraud along rather than expose it.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young immediately responded by attributing the fraud in
part to Cendant's current chief executive, Henry Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   Three former CUC officials pleaded guilty to fraud charges last
week, with one saying the fraudulent accounting practices began as
early as 1983. The Securities and Exchange Commission, in bringing
a civil action against Cendant, concluded that the fraud had begun
by the late 1980s and might have started much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   In an amended complaint filed Monday in U.S. District Court in
Newark, N.J., Cendant contended that ``by 1997 at the latest, E.&AMP;Y.
knew that the financial statements of CUC did not fairly reflect
its financial position and knew that CUC senior management was
fabricating the supposed support for its financial statements.''
</P>
<P>
   The amended complaint contends that the auditing firm concealed
the fraud ``first by negligence, then by conscious avoidance and
eventually by active facilitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The fraud was exposed in April 1998, a few months after CUC
merged with HFS Inc. to form Cendant. Cendant's current management,
largely the former management of HFS, says that it relied on Ernst
&AMP; Young for assurances in completing the merger after it was denied
access to information by CUC officials, ostensibly out of concerns
that HFS might become a competitor if the merger collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young has previously sued Cendant and its executives,
contending that by March 1998, when the accounting firm signed off
on the 1997 annual report, the former HFS officials had discovered
that CUC was manipulating merger reserves ``to manufacture phony
earnings,'' but did not tell the auditing firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are suing Henry Silverman and others responsible at Cendant
because they knew there was fraud and did not inform their auditors
or anyone else,'' said Larry Parnall, a spokesman for the
accounting firm. ``They made the conscious decision to keep that
from the public. We are ready, willing and able to litigate this
case in the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Those merger reserves also figure prominently in the new Cendant
complaint against the auditing firm, which contends that it was
Ernst &AMP; Young that had information that the merger reserves were
phony but nonetheless certified the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The Cendant complaint contends that Kenneth Wilchfort, a partner
in Ernst &AMP; Young, wrote the documents the company used to explain
an inflated merger reserve created for the deal that formed Cendant
and then inserted them in the file as company documents. Similarly,
in manipulating a reserve related to another merger, the complaint
says that Simon Wood, a manager for the auditing firm, wrote a
memorandum for CUC officials to sign that justified fraudulent
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the contention that Ernst &AMP; Young officials knew of the
fraud, the new Cendant complaint says that CUC officials ``were
careful not to place E.&AMP;Y. in the awkward position of knowing too
much or lacking documentation for its audits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They recognized,'' the complaint continues, ``that although
E.&AMP;Y. would facilitate the fraud, it would insist at all times on
`deniability.'''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint contends that the auditing firm ``tipped'' CUC
officials about what items would be audited so that much of the
fraud could be concentrated in areas that would not be audited.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant shares traded for more than $40 each in early April
1998, soon before the fraud was disclosed, but fell to a low of
$6.50 in the fall of that year. Monday, they fell 12.5 cents, to
$13.375.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
