<HEADER>
A8757 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-CLASSES-BOS &LR;      06-19 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CLASSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BRITISH, NOTHING LIKE A GOOD ARGUMENT OVER CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Last October, at his party's annual conference, Prime
Minister Tony Blair declared that Britain's class war was over.
</P>
<P>
   But Blair forgot to check with the British people, not to
mention his cabinet, most of whom seem to relish nothing more than
a good argument over class.
</P>
<P>
   For the last month, the debate has raged on the front pages and
newscasts as Britain's most privileged defend a system they
consider a meritocracy, while others plead for more equality of
opportunity in education, health care and employment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Blair's insistence, the class war in Britain, like the
soccer rivalry between Manchester United and Arsenal, is never
over.
</P>
<P>
   According to many Britons, even those who wish it weren't the
case, class is the biggest single issue facing them _ bigger than
race, bigger than their ambivalence toward the European Union and
integration with Europe, bigger even than soccer, the national
pasttime, bigger than anything.
</P>
<P>
   And while the conventional wisdom holds that Britain is a
country where a dwindling number of aristocrats cling to a
crumbling pedestal of privilege, class prejudice cuts both ways.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Blair proclaimed the class war over, members of
his Labor Party applauded a quartet of teenagers who played some
jazz for them. At the end of the performance, the students' teacher
informed the gathering that the quartet hailed from a exclusive
local private school. The cheers then turned to boos.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides of the class divide delight in labeling the
other. The upper classes are derided as toffs, judged by their
``posh'' accents. Rich people dismiss the poor as ``working
class,'' the words dripping with contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of Blair's allies guffaw at his claim that the class
war is over. One Labor member of parliament, Alan Simpson, _ who,
unlike the former US senator whose name he shares, is an avowed
liberal _ dismissed Blair's claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be daft to pretend that a problem goes away just
because you decide not to talk about it,'' said Simpson, who
represents Nottingham.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Wheen, an historian and author of a recent biography of
Karl Marx, said Blair is not the first British prime minister to
claim the class war was over. Harold Macmillan did it in 1959.
Without a trace of irony, Macmillan went on to name a cabinet that
included a duke, a marquess, and three earls, Wheen said.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``The English,'' Jeremy Paxman, who as the host and
chief interrogator on BBC's ``Newsnight'' is the Ted Koppel of
British television, says the English are ``class-obsessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxman says the widespread interest in the homes of rich people,
including the aristocracy, is part of the British obsession ``to
see how the other half lived and to imagine themselves in their
shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Britain is far less class-ridden than it was
when Macmillan declared the class war over. Yet the British
political system remains class riven, with the two major parties
identifying themselves with the extremes while battling for the
biggest group, the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservatives have long represented the interests of the
upper classes, including the aristocracy, while Labor was built on
the back of the working class. With the two extremes more or less
set in stone, the two major parties spend most of their time
striving to make themselves appear more in tune with what is known
as Middle England. Parliamentary observers claim that Conservative
leader William Hague has suddenly rediscovered the Yorkshire accent
he lost while studying at Oxford University.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, an 18-year-old honor student named Laura Spence
poured gasoline on the simmering class war when she accused Oxford,
Britain's most prestigious university, of rejecting her because she
had a working-class accent and attended a comprehensive, or public,
high school. Spence, who will instead attend Harvard on a full
scholarship, became the darling of the tabloids, and an object of
derision for the elite, who sought to brand her as an immature girl
hurling sour grapes.
</P>
<P>
   But showing just how volatile and seductive the issue of class
is, many of those championing Spence are members of the very elite
she says perpetuates institutional discrimination against
working-class and middle-class kids like herself. Several members
of Blair's cabinet publicly backed Spence.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Blair himself, and nearly every member of his
cabinet, like nearly every British minister over the last two
centuries, is a product of the exclusive private school system and
Oxbridge _ Oxford and Cambridge universities.
</P>
<P>
   Oxbridge graduates control much of Britain. Eight of the last
ten prime ministers attended Oxford. Three-quarters of the nation's
judges, two-thirds of its civil servants, and many leading
journalists are Oxbridge graduates.
</P>
<P>
   But while the influence Oxbridge's graduates wield is
undeniable, some see the attack on Oxford by Blair's top aides as
being disingenuous and opportunistic, a case of pandering the
majority who can't get in. Noting that Labor's latest offensive in
the class war came as the Conservatives have finally begun to chip
away at Blair's massive popularity, The Economist magazine
observed, ``To assault leading universities for being elitist is
nonsensical. You might as well attack the England football team on
the same grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   As The Economist and other opinion shapers contend, the real
problem is not the class of those getting into the universities,
but the wide gap between the academic performance of mostly poor
children at publicly-funded state schools and wealthy children at
expensive private schools, which confusingly are called ``public''
schools in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Only 7 percent of British children attend private schools, but
they get nearly half the places at Oxford and Cambridge. It is that
divergence in achievement, and a corresponding gap in spending at
public and private schools, that Blair's critics say perpetuates
the class divide, not the selective admissions at the elite
universities.
</P>
<P>
   Leanda de Lisle, who writes an occasional column for The
Guardian newspaper and who went to a private boarding school before
attending Oxford, says most of her classmates were not elitist. But
she rejects the claim by defenders of the Oxbridge system in
particular, and of the status quo in general, that Britain is a
meritocracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merit,'' she says, ``is never enough.''
</P>
<P>
   She and others maintain that it matters more here than anywhere
else in Europe where your family comes from, where you went to
school, what kind of accent you have _ and that all of those things
are linked.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the Guardian, de Lisle said the class stratification
in London is stifling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rarely hear an English regional accent in London,'' she
said. ``Everyone I meet talks with the same BBC-style received
pronunciation. That way, I suppose, they can be understood by the
aristocrats that attend any party thrown by the metropolitan elite.
It seems the rich and powerful need to have access to a class that
you have to be born into to feel really special.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair has used legislation to break down the hold of privilege.
Britain was the last country in Europe to end the practice of
giving the traditional nobility legislative powers _ in the House
of Lords, Britain's upper house of Parliament _ as a birthright.
Last year, Blair got rid of the so-called hereditary peers, who
have for centuries held a majority in the House of Lords and have
traditionally been very conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, however, has had less success in changing attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Would-be Oxford student Spence said that when she sat down for
her old-fashioned interview with a panel of Oxford dons, one made a
condescending remark about her accent. In the United States, and in
many other European countries, such a remark would be grounds for a
discrimination complaint. Not here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Britain, the laws dealing with discrimination are about 30
years behind the times,'' said Paul Kelley, the American-born head
teacher at Monkseaton Community High School near Newcastle, which
Spence attends.
</P>
<P>
   Because affirmative action is considered reverse discrimination
and is illegal here, Britain has been less successful than America
in integrating police and fire departments, and the military. While
blacks and other minorities make up more than five percent of the
59 million people in Britain, they hold about one percent of the
police, fire, and military jobs. In London, where about 20 percent
of the 7 million population is minority, the percentages are
roughly the same as the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley says the inability of Britain to integrate its public
sector is as much about class as it is about race and ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British in general don't think they are racist or
classist. They point to other places, like America, and see more
extreme forms of racism and delude themselves into thinking they
are not capable of such things. They are in complete denial,'' said
Kelley, a native of Berkeley, Calif., who was an activist in the
American civil rights movement of the 1960s. ``Class is the last
taboo here. My guess is they'll be talking about the class war long
after I'm gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
