<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8761 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV25-NYT     06-19 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By RAY CORMIER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Lines Redux
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently saw an advertisement for United States Lines. Is
this a rebirth of the old cruise line of the SS United States and
the America? _ Jan Heck, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The U.S. Lines is returning to the high seas, but it is not
the line you remember. The name was acquired by the American
Classic Voyages Co., a holding company with a collection of
passenger lines: American Hawaii Cruises, the Delta Queen Steamboat
Co., Delta Queen Coastal Voyages and now, United States Lines. It
operates from the Robin Street Wharf in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview, Roderick McLeod, the chief executive
officer, said American Classic had acquired the rights to the name
from an heir of a former director of the old line, which last
carried passengers in 1969. It became a cargo business, then went
bankrupt in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   For the new line, American Classic has contracted for the first
new oceangoing passenger ships to be built in the United States in
45 years. These 72,000-ton vessels, to carry 1,920 passengers each,
are being built at Ingalls Shipbuilding Yard in Pascagoula, Miss.,
and are expected to sail in 2003 and 2004, McLeod said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also acquired the 1,212-passenger Nieuw
Amsterdam from Holland America; after some refitting, it will be
used for weekly seven-day cruises among the Hawaiian Islands,
starting Dec. 9. The ship has been renamed the Patriot, and will
fly the American flag and have an American crew. When ready, the
two new ships will also be used in Hawaii, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriot will differ from other liners mainly in its American
ambience, McLeod said. ``Some of it will be in the food,'' he said.
``A lot of it will be related to the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes on the ship are the removal of the casino,
since Hawaii does not allow gambling; replacing it is a Hawaiian
cultural center. The old United States Lines will be evoked in the
names of lounges _ No. 1 Broadway, the old line's address, and
Digby's Bar, after the old telephone exchange of its headquarters.
The ship has two outdoor pools, and children's activity centers.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawaiian cruises on the Patriot will leave Honolulu on
Saturday and dock at Nawiliwili, Kahului, Hilo and Kona, then
return to Honolulu. Rates are $1,599 to $4,249 a person, double
occupancy. Reservations and information: (877) 330-6871, and
www.unitedstateslines.com.
</P>
<P>
   World War I Sites
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there travel agencies specializing in tours of World War
I battlefields in France? I am particularly interested in Verdun. _
Jack R. Siegelbaum, Ridgewood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Most American military tour specialists seem to deal with the
Civil War or World War II. But a Virginia company, Military
Historical Tours, has several tours that may interest you.
</P>
<P>
   According to Patrick Mooney, the company's executive vice
president, there will be four to six World War I tours next year,
including a two-week general overview in September 2001 that visits
Verdun.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the company has a Western Front Battlefields tour
from Aug. 16 to 25. It doesn't go to Verdun but does visit the
Marne, the Somme, Flanders and Ypres Salient. The cost is $2,495 a
person, including round-trip air fare from Newark, hotels, buses
and at least two meals a day.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Military Historical Tours, 4600 Duke Street, Suite 420,
Alexandria, Va. 22304; (800) 722-9501, fax (703) 212-8567;
www.miltours.com.
</P>
<P>
   An American specialist in World War II trips, Valor Tours of
Sausalito, Calif., also represents a big British battlefield tour
operator, Holts Tours, which has several World War I tours each
year. This year's Verdun tour, Sept. 14 to 17, is booked, but
another is planned for June 2001. Details will be available in late
October, Holts says.
</P>
<P>
   Other Holts tours this year include Four Days in Ypres, Aug. 17
to 20, from $595 a person, double occupancy; A Weekend on the
Somme, Sept. 9 and 10, from $250 a person; and Armistice, Nov. 10
to 12, including a memorial service and poppy parade in Ypres, from
$400 (prices include transportation from London and back, hotel and
half board).
</P>
<P>
   To find out more, contact Valor Tours, 10 Liberty Ship Way,
Sausalito, Calif. 94965; (800) 842-4504, fax (415) 332-6971, or go
to Holts' Web site, www.battletours.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Another British operator, Midas Tours, Post Office Box 376, West
Byfleet KT14 7FB, has a walking tour of Verdun Sept. 1 to 4. This
will explore the terrain of the pivotal battle partly on foot, with
walks of about eight and four miles on two of the days. It starts
and ends in London and costs $600, including lodging and two meals
a day. Call (44-1932) 407-000, fax (44-1932) 405-000 or see
www.midastours.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Church Music in Rome
</P>
<P>
   Q. In Rome, my wife and I will visit many churches, which we
know can seem like silent museums. Are there any where music can be
heard? _ Edward Kemp, Setauket, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. While it is true _ if surprising _ that Rome does not have a
big reputation for church music, many Masses are celebrated with
music. Here are a few churches with music at Sunday Masses (and
sometimes at weekday Masses, too):
</P>
<P>
   Chiesa Sant'Ignazio di Loyola, Piazza Sant'Ignazio 1; (39-06)
679-4506; at 10 and 11:30 a.m. and 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Chiesa Gesu e Maria, Via del Corso 45, (39-06) 361-3717; 10 a.m.
in Latin, and 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Chiesa San Paolo Entro le Mura, Via Nazionale, (39-06) 488-3339;
8:30 and 10:30 a.m., and in Spanish with guitars at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Chiesa di Santa Maria del Popolo, Piazza del Popolo 12, (39-06)
361-0836; at 8, 9 10 and 11 a.m. and noon.
</P>
<P>
   Basilica di Sant'Eustachio, Piazza Sant'Eustachio, (39-06)
329-1889; at noon and 7 p.m. At 7 p.m. Mass on Monday, Tuesday,
Wednesday and Friday, nuns play guitars, and on Thursday and
Saturday the organ is played.
</P>
<P>
   On the first and third Sundays of each month this year, except
August, the Benedictine monks of St. Anselmo are offering free
classical music concerts before Latin vespers at the Abbey of the
Aventine, Piazza Cavalieri di Malta 5; (39-06) 579-1319. The
concerts are at 6 p.m., with vespers at 7:15.
</P>
<P>
   To find out about church concerts that are part of the Vatican
Jubilee celebrations, call (39-06) 6988-7248, or see
www.jubil2000.org. Concerts are also listed in Wanted in Rome, an
English publication sold at newsstands (about $1.50), and its Web
site, www.wantedinrome.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
