<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8763 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-COURT-PRAYER-BOS &LR;      06-19 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PRAYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BARS SCHOOL-SPONSORED PRAYER ON PUBLIC PROPERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The US Supreme Court upheld the constitutional
separation of church and state Monday, reaffirming its longheld and
much-challenged position that there is no place for
school-sponsored prayer on public property, including high-school
football fields.
</P>
<P>
   In a case brought by two families _ one Mormon, one Catholic _ a
6-3 court majority ruled that a Texas public-school district cannot
allow a designated student to lead football fans in a pre-kickoff
``invocation,'' even if the solemn message is ``nonsectarian and
nonproselytizing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a stinging opinion written by Justice John Paul Stevens, the
court majority said the First Amendment's ``establishment clause''
forbids the state _ in this case, a school district _ from imposing
its religious views on its citizens. ``The district asks us to
pretend that we do not recognize what every Santa Fe High School
student understands clearly _ that this policy is about prayer,''
Stevens wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the Constitution ... prohibits any public-school
student from voluntarily praying at any time before, during, or
after the school day,'' Stevens added. ``But the religious liberty
protected by the Constitution is abridged when the state
affirmatively sponsors the particular religious practice of
prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, joined by Justices Clarence
Thomas and Antonin Scalia, vehemently objected to the majority's
``distortion'' of the Constitution, which, Rehnquist wrote,
President Washington got right when he heeded the request of
Congress and ``proclaimed a day of public Thanksgiving and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even more disturbing than its holding is the tone of the
court's opinion,'' Rehnquist wrote. ``It bristles with hostility to
all things religious in public life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has struggled with questions about public
observance of private faith for 40 years. In a landmark decision in
1962, the high court struck down school-sponsored prayer. A year
later, it outlawed Bible-reading and recitation of the Lord's
Prayer in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Civil libertarians predictably praised the ruling and hailed
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony Kennedy, David H. Souter,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg, and Stephen Breyer for joining Stevens to form
a solid majority on a court that so often splits 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great decision for religious freedom because it
guarantees that religious majorities cannot ride roughshod over
minorities at government-sponsored events,'' said Barry Lynn,
executive director of Americans United for the Separation of Church
and State.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sekulow, who argued the case for the Santa Fe Independent
School District before the high court, said the decision amounts to
censoring students and will cause more confusion about the bounds
of religious expression in public schools. ``The decision distorts
the First Amendment by exhibiting hostility toward student
speech,'' said Sekulow, chief counsel for the American Center for
Law and Justice, which was founded by evangelist Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Governor George W. Bush, who filed a brief urging the
justices to let the football-game invocations stand in his state,
said he was disappointed by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the constitutionally guaranteed right of all
students to express their faith freely and participate in voluntary
student-led prayer,'' Bush said in a statement released by his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore made no public statement on the decision.
Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for his presidential campaign, said
Gore supports private prayer in school but in the Texas case, ``the
prayer was found to be government-sponsored, and participation was
not truly voluntary.''
</P>
<P>
   Prayers at high-school football games are a time-honored
tradition in Texas, and the political winds blew so strong across
this case that the state Republican Party put a nonbinding
referendum on its primary ballot in March, asking whether
student-initiated prayer should be allowed at school sporting
events. The measure was endorsed by Bush and supported by 94
percent of the Texas GOP primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   The case began in 1995, when two families in Santa Fe, a town of
10,000 about 40 miles southeast of Houston, sued the local school
district, alleging it was engaged in promoting Christianity by
distributing Gideon Bibles on school grounds, encouraging
membership in religious clubs, and permitting prayers at graduation
and football games. The American Civil Liberties Union represented
the families, who said they feared intimidation and harassment in
their community and never allowed their names to be made public.
</P>
<P>
   To pass constitutional muster on the prayers, the school
district changed its policy of appointing student chaplains and
instead set up school elections to select student speakers and to
decide whether there should be invocations at games and graduation.
The modifications, aimed at drawing a distinction between what is
public speech and private expression, did not persuade the federal
district and appeals courts; both said the invocation policy still
violated the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court heard the case in March, and narrowed its
focus just to prayer at football games. In 1992, the court in Lee
v. Weisman ruled that graduation prayers organized and sanctioned
by public schools are unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling, Stevens wrote that the court ``refused to turn a
blind eye'' to the fact the school district was changing its policy
but not its purpose, which was to promote football game prayer. And
he dismissed the school district's argument that attendance at
football games was voluntary for students, noting that
cheerleaders, band members, and football players were required to
be there, and social pressure was strong on other high-school
students to attend as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``School sponsorship of a religious message is impermissible
because it sends the ancillary message to members of the audience
who are nonadherents that they are outsiders, not full members of
the political community, and an accompanying message to adherents
that they are insiders, favored members of the political
community,'' Stevens wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delivery of such a message _ over the school's
public-address system, by a speaker representing the student body,
under the supervision of school faculty and pursuant to a school
policy that explicitly and implicitly encourages public prayer _ is
not properly characterized as private speech,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Court experts said they doubted this would be the last judicial
word on school prayer. Both Gary Bauer, a social conservative who
ran against Bush in this year's GOP primaries, and Ralph Neas, head
of the liberal group, People for the American Way, said they hoped
this ruling would elevate the status of who serves on the Supreme
Court as a campaign issue this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Sekulow said the ruling was neither unexpected nor definitive on
the issue of school prayer. Several more cases on student-initiated
prayer at high-school graduations are pending in federal courts and
could work their way to the Supreme Court as early as next year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been litigating school prayer for 40 years, and I expect
it will be litigated for another 40,'' Sekulow said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
