</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-ILLINOIS-BAR20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chicago suburb reflects swing decision in Illinois
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLIET, Ill. _ The battle line in Illinois politics has always
run between Democrat-steeped Chicago and the Land of
Lincoln-Republicans elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign 2000, those forces will face off in Will County.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest of Chicago, Will County's northern fringe of farmland
is getting bought up, subdivided and paved at one of the fastest
rates in the nation. Many of the homes go for $200,000 to $1
million, with developers offering deals including no down payment
for buyers who agree to paint their new home's interior.
</P>
<P>
   Couples with young children and Chicagoans fleeing skyrocketing
rent and condo prices are flooding Naperville and Bolingbrook,
looking for good schools, a bit of yard and a two-car garage.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, this is uncharted water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody understands who is out there yet,'' U.S.
Sen. Dick Durbin, D-Ill., said recently in an interview with the
The Chicago Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's suburbs tend to lean Republican and, in the Naperville
area in Will County's developing northern tier, Republicans have
been able to recruit committee members in 18 of 21 precincts.
Democrats have none, according to a county political directory.
</P>
<P>
   But Will County also has its share of labor-Democrats and
moderate voters who have cast ballots for Bill Clinton. And,
interviews show, they are inclined to give Vice President Al Gore
the benefit of the doubt for nurturing today's good economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like the way the Democrats have handled the last two
terms, with the environment and economically,'' said Jeff Arthur,
43, an electronic engineering technician at the federal Fermi Labs
complex in the Naperville area. ``I don't have a lot of faith in
(Texas Gov. George W.) Bush. I don't think he's proved himself
nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the 3-year-old, $60 million Neuqua Valley
High School campus, Scott Storms, 32, took a break from moving into
his home in a new subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   Storms, a resident of the area all of two days and a manager for
IBM, is ready to vote for Gore as well, because of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel it should be somebody's right to choose,'' Storms
said.
</P>
<P>
   Will County, Illinois' fourth largest, extends from the
southwestern Chicago suburbs, past blue-collar Joliet into Illinois
farmland, and wraps around southern Cook County to the Indiana
line. The candidate who does well here is doing well among swing
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The county went for the winning Republican candidates in the
1980s, Ronald Reagan twice and Bush in 1988. But Clinton won here
twice, getting an assist from Reform Party Ross Perot's 33,000
votes in 1992, when Clinton's winning margin over President George
Bush was 1,300 votes.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Will County Republican Chairman Jack Partelow thinks
Bush has a good chance to return Will County to the Republican
column. The primary in March showed far more Republican voters
county-wide than Democratic, even though both primary races were
locked up by then.
</P>
<P>
   Partelow was encouraged because the busy suburbanites typically
do not bother with primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to primary elections you can't pry them out for
anything, we'll have 7 percent turnout,'' he said. ``Then in the
general election they'll come out like gangbusters.''
</P>
<P>
   Partelow believes Bush will have the numbers on his side if the
county party can organize new residents the old-fashioned way: door
knocking, phone calls, precinct captains and grass roots contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the thing's we're going to bring to bear is grinding it
out on the ground,'' Partelow said. ``We're going to do a Woody
Hayes thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The wide open spaces in the eastern Will County have seen a
decade-long battle over whether to site a third major Chicago
airport there, possibly in Will Twp., near the village of Peotone.
The long-suffering project has created strange political
bedfellows.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., a Democrat whose district includes
southern Chicago suburbs, is in favor of the project as a jobs
creator, as is Republican Gov. George Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Mayor Richard Daley, the protector of O'Hare Airport,
has fought against it, along with the conservative farmers who live
around Peotone.
</P>
<P>
   Will Twp. Supervisor Everett Schurman, a 70-year-old farmer, has
cast a virtually automatic Republican ballot for decades, but the
threat of losing his family farm to a runway has gotten him to
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this time around I'd have to think about it a bit
more,'' Schurman said. ``Gov. Ryan is supporting the airport and if
Bush came in, there could be the possibility of the airport coming
faster than otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schurman has lived amidst the Peotone airport debate for
10 years. He figures he has time to decide whether the airport
issue alone is worth picking Gore over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't look at that until (Election Day),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
