<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8766 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-HEARTLAND-ILLINOIS20-     06-19 2344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTLAND-ILLINOIS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ilinois seens as a key state in presidential battle
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Summer in Illinois means heat, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   Sun baked farmers worry about drought and sweaty Chicagoans
crank their air conditioners, then wait for the city's electrical
system to crash.
</P>
<P>
   But as it does every four years, this summer's looming inferno
will be a calm before a political storm. Like it or not, Illinois,
with 22 electoral votes, holds a key to the White House. The state
voted for the winning candidate in 23 of 25 presidential elections
in the 20th century, and is up for grabs this year. A poll taken in
early May showed Texas Gov. George Bush and Vice President Al Gore
running even, 41-41.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so close, somebody doing a really dumb stunt, or somebody
running a really brilliant campaign, it can make a difference,''
said John Jackson, political science professor at Southern Illinois
University at Carbondale.
</P>
<P>
   In Illinois, the huge, ancestral Democratic clubs of Chicago are
balanced by the city's suburban voters and by conservative voters
downstate, where the Republican Party has its roots.
</P>
<P>
   The state's top Democrat, Chicago Mayor Richard Daley, has less
power than his father, Chicago icon Richard J. Daley, but still
controls a huge party machine. The state's top Republican, Gov.
George Ryan, turns to the massive and growing Chicago suburbs for
support, but has been damaged politically _ even though not
directly implicated _ by a corruption scandal stemming from his
tenure as secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   And the state's voters are known for crossing party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illinoians have a great reputation for being ticket
splitters,'' said Charlie Wheeler, director of public affairs
reporting at the University of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Despite summer doldrums and distractions, the campaigns have
begun to do battle in this important state. In May, the Democratic
and Republican national committees started airing television ads in
selected markets here and in other key states. The Democrat ads
promote Gore's support for adding prescription drug coverage to
Medicare. The spots for Bush push his proposal to allow workers to
invest some of their Social Security contributions in the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Neither campaign will ignore other areas of the country, but in
Illinois, as in Michigan, Ohio and Pennsylvania, each with its a
history of swing voting, the candidates _ and voters _ are in for a
long, humid Midwestern summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who carries all four of those states you just mentioned
wins the election,'' said Jack Partelow, a retired vice president
for Dun and Bradstreet and Republican chairman of Illinois' fourth
largest county, Will County.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats rule in Chicago and some counties directly across the
state, near the Quad Cities along the Mississippi River, and again
southeast of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Illinois is mainly Republican. The first Republican
president was Illinois attorney Abraham Lincoln, and Republicans
haven't lost much ground downstate since.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of issues percolating near the top of political
discussions here, from $2 gas to Gov. Ryan's problems.
</P>
<P>
   But during recent interviews all across the state, people
repeatedly mentioned their children.
</P>
<P>
   Grumbling over gun safety often boiled down to keeping guns away
from kids, or protecting children and families from crime.
</P>
<P>
   And schools were the front-line of concern, whether the voter
lived in the massive Chicago Public School district or a
high-performance suburban district.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius Goodwin, president of a property management company
based in South Side Chicago's Bronzeville neighborhood, represents
one conundrum for the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the burgeoning black middle-class in Chicago, Goodwin
sends his son to a private high school. He has one chance to give
his son a good high school experience and figures his odds are
better there than in Chicago schools.
</P>
<P>
   But long-term, Goodwin sees public schools as the only thing
that will keep society from pulling itself apart.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his store-front office on a busy city street, Goodwin
said he vehemently opposes Bush's support for school vouchers, even
though parents like him would be a target audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to mean people like me could get a free education
at a private school but the people on the bottom will still be on
the bottom,'' he said. ``We'll have a permanent underclass.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 miles to the south in Decatur, blue-collar city of
about 82,500, schools also are at the heart of local conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur reluctantly made national headlines last fall when a
video-taped melee in the football bleachers led to the suspension
of four high school students. The Rev. Jesse Jackson and others
protested that the students involved were punished too harshly. The
region has launched a flurry of racial initiatives and programs
aimed at getting people of different color speaking with one
another.
</P>
<P>
   But voters black and white said what really matters are schools.
</P>
<P>
   Many were disgusted that city voters have repeatedly rejected
new school taxes _ leading the school district to close one of
three city high schools.
</P>
<P>
   Voters said they are inclined to give their vote to the
presidential candidate who can connect their policies to better
local schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to make sure about the future,'' said Sabrina
Hall, 27, of Decatur, who has a son finishing kindergarten. ``I
don't have any (presidential) preferences. (Education) is going to
be a factor for years.''
</P>
<P>
   In Illinois, as elsewhere, Gore can try to ride the coattails of
the nation's longest economic expansion. Many voters here said they
were inclined to keep him around in order to keep a good thing
going.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the good economic times, there are large pockets of
Illinois where the surging stock market is a distant murmur.
</P>
<P>
   Farm prices remain low, and the downstate economy is built on
the growing, trading and processing of corn and soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping the economy whole and moving along is certainly on the
minds of the people in southern Illinois because we're not as
prosperous as the rest of the state,'' said Jackson, the SIU
professor.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago _ where abandoned public housing projects are being
razed for $600,000 condominiums _ the differences between the haves
and have nots are becoming bizarrely obvious. One developer, in
fact, has proposed a condominium complex, with the cheapest unit
going for $200,000, for a neighborhood near the infamous
Cabrini-Green public housing project.
</P>
<P>
   In South Side Chicago, one of largest African American
communities, Gore will have to play the economy card carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a restaurant on East 35th Street, Clarence Walker,
63, looked out on the Bronzeville neighborhood and mused about the
odd pressures brought on by the strong economy. The neighborhood,
home to former Black Panther and current U.S. Rep. Bobby Rush, is
seeing its share of the economic good times. But housing prices are
rising quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The neighborhood) is getting what it needs now but it's
chasing most of the poor people out,'' Walker said. ``I can go
along with demolition, but you have to have replacement housing. If
I quit working it could be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Several blocks away, in the bright and bustling Spin Cycle
Laundromat, Vira Booker, 44, a hospital clerk on medical leave,
watched TV while waiting for for a load of clothes to finish.
</P>
<P>
   She has been worried more about her own finances than the
presidential race. In March, she said, the rent for the apartment
she had lived in for 21 years rose from $450 a month to $800. Her
neighborhood was gentrifying, and her landlord had rehabbed some of
the building and was trying to recoup the investment. Booker paid
the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paid for that building over time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the South Side offers a potential avalanche of votes for
a Democrat who can motivate.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1992 dogfight between Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton and
incumbent President George Bush, Clinton obliterated Bush on the
South Side. He earned about half of his statewide 700,000-vote
margin of victory in just the 1st and 2nd Congressional Districts,
which take in the South Side and some politically like-minded south
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Gore's biggest advantage is that Bush has an even
tougher hill to climb here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I prefer (Gore) so much as I don't like Bush and
the Republican agenda,'' said Goodwin, the real estate management
president.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Republicans' message hurts them on the South Side.
Bush's call for programs that help the middle class or even the
lower middle class does nothing for the poorest of the poor, said
Goodwin, whose neighborhood includes the Robert Taylor Homes
housing complex, one of the country's largest and poorest public
housing complexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to live with the underclass; (Republicans) don't have
to live with them,'' he said. ``We see them everyday, walking the
street, begging for money, unable to get jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Downstate, too, the economy has been frustratingly inconsistent.
Riverboat gambling has brought new money into Joliet. In Decatur,
the huge industrial plants of grain processor Archer Daniels
Midland and the manufacturing yards of Caterpillar are busy again,
but the city still shows the effects of crippling strikes of the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The city's unemployment rate was 6 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   L.L. Lehman, 68, a retired cable company worker, said the key to
the election will be his pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people have money, they're happy,'' Lehman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman retired once, then went back to work cutting grass and
helping friends on their farms.
</P>
<P>
   He backs Gore, as do many in the Decatur area, but said he would
have liked if Arizona Sen. John McCain had stayed in the race.
</P>
<P>
   McCain received 159,000 votes, 22 percent, in the Illinois'
Republican primary March 21, even though he had suspended his
campaign two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a registered Democrat but McCain, he cared about working
people,'' Lehman said.
</P>
<P>
   If the South Side can be the cornerstone of a Gore win, suburban
Chicago offers Bush a foundation. Due west of Chicago's downtown
loop, Brookfield and scores of other Chicago suburbs long ago
knitted together into a political force, mainly a conservative one.
The area is so consistently conservative Bill Clinton did not carry
Park Ridge _ Hillary Rodham Clinton's hometown _ in either 1992 or
'96.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Doig, 80, kneeling delicately to plant flowers alongside
her trim, Brookfield bungalow, said she is paying attention to the
presidential race and will likely vote for Bush. Folks in this area
make do for themselves, and the Republican message of self-reliance
has strong believers here.
</P>
<P>
   Doig is underwhelmed by the pandering to senior citizens in the
campaign so far and all the attention devoted to Social Security
and subsidized prescription drugs for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniors can't expect a free ride,'' she said, brushing dark
soil from her garden gloves. ``We believe you work and save to take
care of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Doig figures, Social Security is not in crisis yet. She
expects nothing to change until it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too political,'' she said. ``They're not going to touch
it. Ten years from now, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Downstate in the rural farmland, Bush's support for gun owners
is finding an ear among a strong hunting and pro-gun constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside highways in southern Illinois, gun supporters have
sequences of small signs that, like Burma Shave advertisements, are
meant to be read at 50 MPH.
</P>
<P>
   ``No gun has ever ... committed a crime ... time upon time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not campaigning in a vacuum, however. His honorary state
chairman, Republican Gov. Ryan, is being hurt by the ongoing
federal probe into bribes and the sales of truck driver's licenses.
Ryan has not been implicated directly in the scheme that stems from
his time as secretary of state, and has said he inherited a
secretary of state's office in which corruption was built into the
system.
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan's approval ratings have plunged statewide, and Bush
must juggle whether it helps or hurts him to tour Illinois with
Ryan at his side.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore also must decide how to get the most mileage out
of their money and time in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional approach _ visit Chicago, get on its television
stations, and reach half the state's voters _ has pitfalls. Those
campaign stunts don't really satisfy the Chicago voter, and then
make downstate folk feel ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Maher, the auditor for Will County, southwest of Chicago,
was county campaign chairman for three Kennedy presidential bids,
working for John, Robert and Ted. He believes Gore would make a
mistake just focusing on Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people running the campaigns in Chicago figure the collar
counties (which ring Chicago) are part of the same television
viewing market,'' Maher, 70, said. ``It ignores the fact that
people like to press the flesh. They like to talk to the candidate.
When they look at him on the tube instead of in person it has a
dampening effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush already has moved away from that practice, visiting the
downtstate capital of Springfield and other outlying cities during
a one-day swing through Illinois in March.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in the race for the heartland, however, Bush and
Gore are not just fighting each other, they're battling for
attention, especially over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of the two candidates excites people right now,''
Maher said. ``I think when McCain and Bradley . . . were both out
of the picture, the interest waned considerably. We are in a lull
period. We're in that trough right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Springfield,'' added the University of Illinois'
Wheeler, ``the presidential race isn't even on the radar screen
yet. We have a mini-drought underway already.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
