a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      06-19 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURF THE NET CAREFULLY, OR YOU COULD END UP SWIMMING WITH THE
FISHES
</HEADLINE>
  By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's all harmless fun, but I'm a little troubled by the
news that organized crime (the Mafia) and disorganized crime
(Congress) are both investing heavily in the Internet these days.
</P>
<P>
   This disturbs me nearly as much as Procter &AMP; Gamble's recent
announcement that it's developing special cartridges to bring
smells to computers. Oh, joy. Not only does technology furnish us
the opportunity to go into an America Online chat room and talk to
a 55-year-old loser named Ed who's pretending to be a leggy,
redheaded divorcee named ``HotMamma4U,'' now we'll be able to sniff
Ed's armpits too.
</P>
<P>
   You probably heard something about the Mafia's newfound interest
in the Internet. Last week, the FBI arrested 120 people, including
Robert ``Little Robert'' Lino, Frank ``Frankie'' Persico and other
members of New York's five most powerful crime families, on charges
of securities fraud. (Far be it from me to offer advice to the mob,
but what ever happened to the tradition of scary gangster names?
Frankie? Little Robert? For crying out loud, how about trying
something a little meaner for the Internet age, like Robert ``The
Spammer'' Lino or Frank ``The Delete Button'' Persico?)
</P>
<P>
   The FBI says these wise guys teamed up with shady stockbrokers
to talk thousands of investors into sinking $50 million into
companies of dubious merit. The sudden influx of cash drove the
company's otherwise worthless stocks up, enabling Little Robert,
Frankie and pals to dump their shares at a tidy profit.
</P>
<P>
   I thought that's how Wall Street ordinarily conducts business,
especially with Internet start-ups, but apparently it's quite
illegal. Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   The alleged scams, not surprisingly, include quite a few dot-com
stocks. In one case, the FBI says the mobsters were lining up
investors for a company that was supposedly planning to unveil a
new online trading system July 4. But oops the company never
bothered to seek regulatory approval for the system.
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet outfit, E-Pawn.com, is also under scrutiny. USA
Today reported, rather cryptically, that the company sells time
shares at race tracks. (``Pssst, I got a three days, two nights at
Preakness for $450. Great place to take your little filly. The
offer heh heh won't last furlong. Whaddya say?'')
</P>
<P>
   The company touts itself as ``the world's yardstick of great
value and fun.'' I'm guessing this was a tip-off to the feds. I
mean, who measures fun with a yardstick? Cement, maybe, but fun?
</P>
<P>
   In time, I'm sure the feds will be able to herd the Mafia into a
tiny, manageable corner of the Internet. Maybe the FBI can set up a
nice suite of chat rooms next to Ed, the leggy redhead, and keep an
eye on the mobsters from there.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure Congress will be so easily controlled, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's newly released financial disclosure statements show
that its members _ like many Americans _ are investing heavily in
hi-tech companies. At least 63 senators have substantial
investments in big-name firms like Microsoft, AOL, and Lucent
Technology, according to The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing illegal about this, of course. But the
investments become problematic, as always, when lawmakers take up
bills that could benefit sections of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., drew attention
this spring when he led an effort to try to help NextWave, a
bankrupt wireless company, hold onto a Federal Communications
Commission license. It turns out Torricelli has substantial
investments in Global Crossing, a telecommunications company that's
sinking money into NextWave to revive it.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli's office says he wasn't even aware that Global was
investing in NextWave. I have no reason to doubt him.
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, though, I'm hoping somebody is keeping an eye on
the flood of tech money flowing through the bank accounts and
campaign funds of our elected officials. Call me cynical, but I
don't need a special cartridge from Procter &AMP; Gamble to tell me
these arrangements could turn smelly rather quickly.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
