<HEADER>
A8771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIETNAM-STOCK-NYT &LR;      06-19 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNIST VIETNAM TESTS STOCK-TRADING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ This week, 25 years after unifying under communism,
Vietnam is testing the systems that will run the country's first
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The opening bell may ring next month, but like Vietnam's
tentative experiments in recent years with ``market socialism,''
the tests are getting mixed results and reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing will be believing,'' said J. Mark Mobius, a prominent
money manager who started a Vietnam fund in 1994 for Templeton
Asset Management Ltd., believing that the country would embrace
free-market reforms and make good on plans to open a stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese officials will not say exactly when the market will
open, though reports in government-controlled media have tipped a
July launch. In 1996, the government established a State Securities
Commission to create a stock market. But bureaucracy and corruption
have hindered efforts to lure foreign investment and privatize
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   There were some early indications on Monday that the Ho Chi Minh
City Securities Trading Center was getting off to a rocky start,
despite assistance from the Stock Exchange of Thailand. Mock
trading scheduled for Monday was reportedly thwarted by a power
outage that crippled the electronic trading board.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the board worked, it would report the stock prices of
just two companies _ the Refrigeration Electrical Engineering Corp.
and the Cables and Telecommunication Materials Joint Stock Co. They
are the only companies that have registered for a listing.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mobius' Vietnam fund, it withdrew from most Vietnam
investments in 1998 and broadened its focus to Southeast Asia.
Mobius said he remained unconvinced that Hanoi's communist leaders
could allow a free market to flourish in the former Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way,'' he said. ``I'm not getting on the first
plane to Vietnam. I've been there. Done that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
