<SLUG> BC-GLF-VECSEY-WOODS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TIGER WOODS APPROACHES HIGH TIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Watched some golf on Sunday. Really. Right after the
Spain-Slovenia soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   There on the tube was a most stunning impression, visual and
olfactory _ the lush swell of the Pacific Ocean, throbbing against
the cultivated lawns of a golf course called Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Smell-o-vision. This was a new one on me. You could inhale the
aroma of thick kelp and foamy saltwater surging alongside the
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aha, maybe you ought to play golf,'' said my wife, who wonders
what I will do with my spare time in the very distant future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' I said. ``I just want to walk along the ocean like we
did last summer on Big Sur.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, who would dare dream about committing to golf after
watching Tiger Woods?
</P>
<P>
   How could it possibly be good for the golf industry to let this
man perform in public?
</P>
<P>
   It was not hard to imagine, late Sunday night, the wracking
sound of men and women taking baseball swings with their golf clubs
against the nearest sugar maple or loblolly pine.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, some of the also-rans in the United States
Open would not have been blamed if they had hurled their entire
kits into the Pacific Ocean. What's the point? Why go on?
</P>
<P>
   If it was not clear before Sunday evening, it is obvious now.
Tiger Woods dominates sport _ not merely his sport, but sport in
general _ as completely as anybody we have seen in a long, long
time.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods has stolen this spring from everybody else _ Shaq,
Kobe and Reggie out in LA last night, Martin Brodeur performing
kick saves 'round midnight, Edgar and Pedro and Conchita and all
the other Martinezes, whoever it was who won the French tennis, the
three Triple Crown horses.
</P>
<P>
   He stole it with his composure and his compact power. If you
could tear yourself away from gazing at the sea, it was all Tiger,
all day, all weekend.
</P>
<P>
   You could imagine producers screaming: ``Stay with him! Stay
with him!'' at their camera operators, trying to capture every
precious shot, since there were not that many.
</P>
<P>
   The camera just adores him _ trim and young, as athletic as an
Olympic swimmer, as feral as a Tomba or a Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   The great golfers before him were not mistaken for athletes, not
the wiry Ben Hogan or the avuncular Arnold Palmer or the ursine
Jack Nicklaus, but this young man just bristles with quiet energy.
One could envision him as a whippet of a second baseman, with a bit
of pop in his bat, his throws not skulling anybody in the box
seats.
</P>
<P>
   When he twists his slender body, not much ripples inside the
mulberry shirt, but the ball bounces far ahead of drives by
fleshier men.
</P>
<P>
   As he walks down the fairway, he barely acknowledges the
gallery, his attention focused inward in what seems to be a
permanent state of grace.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is no defense in golf, virtually no teamwork, he
is out there alone, on some new frontier of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to Tiger Woods in recent decades has been
Secretariat barreling through the 1973 Triple Crown, winning the
Belmont by 31 lengths, so far ahead that the other horses could
only surmise by his hoof prints that they were indeed in a race.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan? He swaggered and stuck out his tongue and took
over a game, but there were roustabouts who could knock him off his
spot occasionally, and sometimes he would just plain miss.
Frustrated golfer and baseball player that he is, Michael knows
nobody commands a sport the way Tiger Woods does.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, pitchers throw the odd perfect game, but they are one-day
wonders. Lawrence Taylor was the most dominant football player of
his time, but LT did not play offense _ a failure of imagination of
his coaches and not his own doing, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Diego Armando Maradona could dish out one spectacular pass that
beat Brazil in a World Cup game, but only after this addled genius
had lain in the weeds for the other 89 minutes. Reggie Jackson hit
three homers in a World Series game, but he struck out a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky? There was a lot of Tiger Woods in him. Cool.
Excellent. Smart. Decent. But he had his Messiers and his Fuhrs and
his Coffeys and his Semenkos on his side.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger has no opposition, only a field. Ali had Frazier.
Navratilova had Evert. DiMaggio had Williams and Musial. McGwire
has Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger has only himself and his caddie and his touch and his
inner light, but that is quite enough. Even the pungent Pacific
swirls in for a closer look. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
