<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      06-19 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S CONSERVATIVE PARTY LEADER STEPPING MORE SMARTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ There is a new smartness in the step of Britain's
Conservative leader, William Hague, putting him in closer reach of
front-running Prime Minister Tony Blair and in distant sight of the
previously unimaginable destination of 10 Downing Street.
</P>
<P>
   With the likely date of the next national election less than a
year off, Hague is succeeding in dominating the political headlines
for the first time in the three years since he took over the
depleted and dispirited Tory party, once Europe's mightiest
election machine.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has not shaken the common conviction that Labor will
win the vote that is expected for next May, he has managed to throw
the long-unassailable government on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   A series of mistakes and miscalculations by the Blair
administration has given Hague an opportunity he has aggressively
seized to score points in areas where Tories have not shown well in
the past _ like city government, health care, law and order,
immigration and old-age pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's attempts to defend his record by calling Hague an
opportunist and pointing out past Conservative failures are proving
unconvincing. With Labor entering its fourth year of power, the
public now assigns it responsibility for social service shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Although Labor politicians still believe the party's re-election
chances are secure, they are unsettled at seeing the Conservatives
setting the current political agenda. Within the Conservative
Party, Hague's performance has stilled earlier talk of his being
removed after the next election and replaced by Michael Portillo,
the former defense secretary who had been the favorite of many
Tories longing for a bruiser at the head of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Hague has shored up his standing in the party by combining his
hardline stance against Britain's adopting the euro as its currency
with a new focus on combating an enemy he identifies as a ``liberal
elite.'' This element, he says, coddles ``bogus'' asylum seekers,
allows a ``flood'' of illegal immigrants into the country and is
soft on crime, school discipline and sex education for youth, and
not supportive enough of families.
</P>
<P>
   Deftly turning the tables on Labor, he criticized government
efforts to hold the line on pension increases as ``miserly'' and
said pensioners were the ``unwanted, unwelcome and uncool guests at
New Labor's banquet.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hague rises in people's estimations, however, even his
friends and supporters express concern that the steps he has taken
to turn himself into a more forceful leader of Her Majesty's
Opposition _ pushing hot-button populist issues in a way that can
leave him looking more like a rabble-rouser than a statesman _
might make him a less credible candidate for prime minister.
Building a protest movement is one thing, the reasoning goes;
leading a government is another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that people say those things, although obviously
they're wrong,'' Hague said in an on-the-run interview while
campaigning last Thursday in a by-election contest in Tottenham in
North London. ``Actually it's been an advantage over the past three
years to be consistently underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I said to the party after the last election that we
would go through several stages in the recovery of our party. First
of all, people would say, `There's no way you Tories can recover.
You lost so heavily, you're finished forever. There's no way you
can ever get back.' Then they would say, `OK, you're recovering but
you know you won't be able to recover quickly enough.' Then they'll
say, `OK so you're recovering more quickly than you expected, but
you know you won't be able to keep it up.' And then I said, we'll
go onto the next stage, which is when they will say, `We always
knew the Tories were going to recover and be back in.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' he concluded, ``we're not far off now from that fourth
point, and we're still very happy to continue to be
underestimated.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hague in the ascendancy, the weekly Prime Minister's
Question Time exchange of barked insults between Blair and him has
become blood sport. Hague opened last week's verbal punch-up by
quoting embarrassing criticisms of Blair in a leaked memo by the
prime minister's own public attitude-sounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again T.B. is pandering, lacking conviction, unable to
hold to a position for more than a few weeks and lacking the guts
to be able to tough it out,'' was one quote that Hague gleefully
read out to the Commons as Tory backbenchers lustily cheered him
on.
</P>
<P>
   Blair wagged his finger at Hague and warned that he could
retaliate with some focus-group comments about him, and when the
Conservative leader kept on, the prime minister made good on his
pledge to whoops of delight from the Labor side of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what they say,'' Blair bellowed. ``Boring, false, he
irritates me greatly, pathetic drip, nonentity, no substance, no
personality, complete waste of time, no policies, a very
unimpressive team, particularly William Hague.''
</P>
<P>
   Hague's arrival as a credible Conservative leader follows a
sequence of failed ``relaunches,'' fresh starts and new
initiatives. Though at 39, he is eight years Blair's junior, he is
prematurely bald, crisp in his Oxford Union debating style and
comes on as something of a young fogey to many Britons, who know of
his reputation for having read parliamentary reports, memorized
speeches by Winston Churchill and learned the names and districts
of all Tory members of Parliament, all when he was just 15.
</P>
<P>
   Hague famously burst upon the scene a year later when, as a
mop-haired student, he took the podium at the annual Conservative
Party conference and fired up the faithful with a call to arms in
defense of Tory principles. Photographs from the time show Margaret
Thatcher looking on enraptured.
</P>
<P>
   In pursuit of an updated image once he was the leader, Hague put
on jeans and a baseball cap, slid down amusement park water
sluices, went to ethnic culture festivals, took outdoor adventure
vacations with his new wife, Ffion, traveled the country in a
studiously informal ``Listening to Britain'' campaign, and began to
call his philosophy ``kitchen sink Conservatism'' before abandoning
it this year for the slogan ``The Common Sense Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Hague even cleared his office walls of pictures of his one-time
heroine Thatcher to stop colleagues from mooning over the party's
triumphal past and make them focus on the possibilities of a future
under him. Only now does it seem certain there will be one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
