<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CHICKEN-RUN-REVIEW-LA     06-19 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-RUN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUCKY INMATES MOUNT COOP D'ETAT IN `CHICKEN RUN'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on or after Wed., June 21, 2000 by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By GLEN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Wallace &AMP; Gromit'' gang has plenty to crow about with its
first feature-length animated film, ``Chicken Run,'' a clever,
inventive movie that puts poultry on the cinematic map. The Aardman
stop-motion animators have fashioned a film that works on several
levels _ adventure, comedy and a nifty homage to World War II POW
movies like ``The Great Escape'' and ``Stalag 17.'' Here we finally
have a summer family movie that isn't bird-brained, but instead
smart fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken Run'' bears more than a passing resemblance to the
``Babe'' movies both in its story _ animals living under the shadow
of the farmer's ax _ and its dark, foreboding visual design. Of
course, Aardman's Oscar-winning work has always worn its sardonic
sensibilities and subtle, off-center British humor as a badge of
honor. ``Chicken Run'' simply takes those tastes and runs with
them, rather like a chicken with its head cut off.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's action is set at the dreary Tweedy's Egg Farm, a
``fowl'' place of shabby, cramped barracks surrounded by fences
with barbed wire. Here, the English inmates _ the veddy proper
chickens _ must lay eggs regularly or face the chopping block. The
proprietor, Mrs. Tweedy (voiced with pinched perfection by Miranda
Richardson), is constantly looking for ways to boost her profits,
while her husband, the henpecked Mr. Tweedy (Tony Haygarth),
monitors the chickens' activities.
</P>
<P>
   The birds, understandably, aren't very happy, but being
chickens, they're mostly resigned to their lot. Not so Ginger
(Julia Sawalha), an enterprising hen that longs for a better life
not only for herself, but the entire flock. Ginger devises new ways
to bust out of camp; but all her scheming usually goes no farther
than landing her in solitary confinement (a trash dumpster, where
she bounces a rubber ball, a nod to ``The Great Escape'').
</P>
<P>
   Enter Rocky (Mel Gibson), a brash American rooster who somehow
flies into camp one day. This ``lone free ranger'' has escaped from
his employer, a traveling circus. He and Ginger make a deal: She'll
hide him if he'll teach the chickens how to fly. Time is of the
essence, too, since Mrs. Tweedy has just purchased a contraption
that will turn the birds into chicken pies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken Run,'' in its own way, is every bit as marvelous to
look at as Disney's computer-animated ``Dinosaur,'' and it boasts a
much sharper and imaginative story. Directors Nick Park (the man
behind ``Wallace &AMP; Gromit's'' delightful man-and-dog duo) and
Aardman co-founder Peter Lord take stop-motion animation to new
heights, while never forgetting (and having fun with the fact) that
its creations are lumps of clay. This leads to some great visuals
during those scenes when the chickens try to fly.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is also ably helped by his vocal cast. Gibson's manic
personality makes him a perfect fit for the cocky rooster, and
Sawalha, best-known for her work on the BBC sensation ``Absolutely
Fabulous,'' gives Ginger a tough-hearted tenderness that is quite
touching. Another ``Ab Fab'' alum, Jane Horrocks, provides
memorable voicing to Babs, a rotund chicken that's continuously
knitting, and Lynn Ferguson comically brings to life the Scottish
chicken Mac, the coop's counterpart to ``Star Trek's'' Scotty.
</P>
<P>
   That these are but a few of the film's noteworthy characters
illustrates just how well Park and Lord have brought their birds to
life and made them distinctive creatures. The movie, like the
chickens themselves, seems at times to be a prisoner of its static
setting. But when the filmmakers break free, like during an
inspired scene that has Rocky and Ginger going on a roller coaster
ride through Mrs. Tweedy's pie-making machine, their efforts more
than match the sophisticated whimsy of the ``Wallace &AMP; Gromit''
shorts. This is a wonderful film. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Chicken Run'' (G). &QL; 
The stars: Voices of Mel Gibson, Julia Sawalha and Miranda
Richardson. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Peter Lord and Nick Park. Screenplay
by Karey Kirkpatrick, based on a story by Lord and Park. Released
by DreamWorks Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 25 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
