<HEADER>
A8782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WEBMD20-COX     06-19 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Healtheon/WebMD restructures major deal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Healtheon/WebMD has reshaped its agreement to buy
Medical Manager and its CareInsite subsidiary, boosting the price
and relinquishing some control.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the acquired companies will become co-chief
executive of the merged company.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the deal is endorsed by shareholders and regulators,
the Atlanta-based, post-merger company will be called WebMD _ the
name under which it was launched just two years ago before
beginning a spectacular series of deals including a merger with
California-based Healtheon.
</P>
<P>
   Shortening the name underscores the millions spent on touting
the WebMD brand, said Jeffrey T. Arnold, now chief executive of
Healtheon/WebMD. ``It also shows that we will be one company.''
</P>
<P>
   Boosting its bid in the fear that the deal would be scotched by
shareholders, Healtheon/WebMD, which aims to put health care
transactions on the Internet, will exchange 2.5 shares for each
share of Medical Manager. When the acquisition was announced in
February, Healtheon/WebMD was set to swap 1.65 shares, in an
agreement then valued at more than $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Healtheon/WebMD stock has collapsed since then, falling from
$68 to less than $17 a share at the close of trading Friday. News
of the revised deal nudged Healtheon/WebMD down still more.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Monday's closing price of $14.56 a share, shareholders
of Medical Manager will be receiving stock worth less than $2
billion _ even with the sweetened rate of exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were also concerned about the merged company's
operations, anxiety that should be soothed by creating a shared CEO
slot in which Arnold would have equal billing with Martin Wygod,
who is now chairman of Medical Manager and CareInsite. ``That was
my idea,'' said Arnold. ``There has been uncertainty about whether
the deal was going to happen. Investors wanted to make sure that
Marty had an active role in the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, 30, is slightly less than half Wygod's age.
</P>
<P>
   This arrangement should break with most power-sharing
precedents, he said. ``Co-CEOs typically don't work. But we think,
with the age difference and our complementary skills _ we know it's
going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Chairman W. Michael Long, who will remain chairman of the merged
company, said the executives have divvied up their roles based on
their skills.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold is accomplished at marketing and deal-making, while Wygod
has a career's worth of experience and contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm a generalist, so I got to be chairman,'' Long
said. ``But the right team, the strongest management, will
determine winners and losers as much as capital and technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the deal from federal regulators could come by
mid-September, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, top executives are searching for places in
which the companies overlap, expecting to find tens of millions of
dollars that can be cut post-merger. Corporate and marketing
headquarters will remain in Atlanta, with technology work centered
in Santa Clara, Calif., Long said.
</P>
<P>
   However, smaller satellite offices may be closed and other jobs
cut.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,500 people work for Healtheon/WebMD, and about 3,000
work for Medical Manager and CareInSite, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon/WebMD has yet to be profitable, but that will change
by the end of next year, Long said. ``We believe we will beat the
most aggresssive estimates that are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon/WebMD has sought to provide ``end-to-end'' solutions
that will use the Net to connect patients, providers and those that
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Purchase of Medical Manager and its subsidiary would eliminate a
key rival for market share.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
