<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now good time to scrutinize investments
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Midyear is always a good time to take stock _ no pun
intended _ of the economy and the markets, which is what the
business press is doing right now.
</P>
<P>
   In its midyear investment outlook, Business Week (June 26)
offers articles that are cautious but positive, declaring that a
``soft landing'' _ slower economic growth but no recession _ is
likely, and there are still plenty of investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now's a good time to return to basics,'' says the magazine.
``If you've been socking money solely into large-capitalization
tech stocks, start with a short course on the benefits of asset
allocation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortune (July 3) says the Internet mania that gripped the market
late last year and early this year has ``finally, decisively,
burned itself out.'' But the industry is headed for ``a brutal
shakeout.'' A Merrill Lynch analyst says 75 percent of the publicly
traded Internet companies will not be around in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But far from being a requiem for the new economy... the market
has begun to separate the companies with staying power from those
that do little but burn through their backers' cash,'' Fortune
says.
</P>
<P>
   Business 2.0 (July 11), a ``new economy'' magazine, says the
spring stock market slide ``has already claimed the weakest victims
among Internet businesses.'' Reality, and austerity, have finally
set in on the stock market. But the magazine's advice to investors
is: ``Don't panic,'' and survival strategies are available.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans know of Richard Branson, if at all, because of
his Virgin Atlantic airline. But that's just one of the many
enterprises that bear the Virgin logo, Forbes (July 3) says in a
cover profile of this 49-year-old British businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Virgin empire started with a record company and now
encompasses over 150 separate enterprises,'' says Forbes. ``The
Virgin name may be found on cola, rail cars, storefronts selling
mobile phones and, of course, the Internet.'' His next target? What
about Britain's national lottery?
</P>
<P>
   Barron's (June 19) says Wall Street is looking for
second-quarter corporate profits to expand by 20 percent, and
companies that fall short of expectations will suffer the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Success (July/August) offers still another look at Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan in a cover story that doesn't offer
anything new but is a good summary of the Fed's current interest
rate strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
