<HEADER>
A8788 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     06-19 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV25-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPING WITH CANCELED FLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 25) 
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Midafternoon on Friday, May 26, was brilliant and sunny at La
Guardia Airport. Passengers were moving briskly in anticipation of
a holiday weekend. But a cloud was visible on the electronic
horizon: the schedule boards showed that United had canceled Flight
1719, due to depart at 7:30 p.m. for Dulles Airport near
Washington.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By 4 p.m., the airline had posted ``delayed'' next to the
listing for the preceding trip to Dulles, the 6:30 p.m. United
Express Flight 7685. ``Flow control into La Guardia due to wind,''
Yvette Lazu, a United ticket agent, told this reporter.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As hours passed, tangles compounded. The equipment for the 6:30
flight was changed, with a drop in passenger capacity from 50 to
29. Standby Dulles passengers were told there would be nothing for
them until Saturday morning. A queue of angry, quarrelsome,
occasionally weeping passengers began to struggle for ways to get
out before the holiday evaporated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``How can it be weather?'' a woman in line said. ``Look at that
beautiful day!'' She waved at the lowering sun, so blinding that
passengers shunned seats facing the windows. Others nodded,
distrusting the agent, even though weather was in fact to blame for
the cancellation.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Down in the windowless Port Authority offices at La Guardia,
where the tower's instructions crackle on the radio, Anthony Layne
and Larry McAleer, the managers on duty, made telephone calls and
reported that Federal Aviation Administration controllers in
Westbury, N.Y., faced with strong winds to the west, were spacing
arrivals and departures more widely, bringing delays of 30 to 45
minutes across the board, a situation that continued until almost 9
p.m. Bad weather elsewhere brought other cancellations among La
Guardia's 1,100 regular daily arrivals or departures on seven
scheduled airlines on May 26, a day the airport was handling 19
percent more passengers than on a regular Friday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The classic flight-cancellation mis en scene at La Guardia, and
some incidents observed by reporters the same afternoon at Atlanta
Hartsfield and O'Hare in Chicago, were clear examples of
passengers' suspicions of airline motives and airline employees'
reluctance to speak of unwelcome realities. The observations also
indicate some ways passengers can reduce the difficulties caused by
cancellations. They're worth knowing about, because the trend of
cancellations is upward.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airlines do not guarantee their schedules. They try to adhere to
published schedules because it is less trouble than rebooking
frustrated passengers. But weather, air traffic, mechanical
difficulties, rules governing crew hours and hundreds of other
causes, including human error, can upset schedules. The government
exercises only a few regulations over passenger service _ penalties
for overbooking notable among them _ and there are no federal
requirements on how passengers on canceled flights are to be
treated.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of flights canceled is not high: from May 1,
1999, to April 30, 2000, cancellations by the 10 major airlines at
29 big U.S. airports ranged from 1.8 percent (November) to 5.7
percent (January, a percentage spike in a bad weather period). But
as flight totals increase, the percentages represent bigger
numbers. Last month 8,590 flights were canceled out of 307,116
scheduled. A year ago it was 6,487 out of 299,132.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   When they cancel, the airlines say, they prefer to inconvenience
as few passengers as possible. A big plane intended for a lightly
booked flight may be transferred to replace a sidelined plane that
was to have carried a heavy load, and the lightly booked flight is
then canceled. This is not the easiest thing to do, airline
officials say, because the scheduled crew cannot always handle the
new equipment. But elimination of an undersold flight may be one
reason travelers believe cancellations are profit-driven, and
airlines can contribute to this perception. In Chicago on May 26,
when Trans World Airlines canceled Flight 207, due to leave O'Hare
at 5:44 p.m. for St. Louis, the attendant at the gate told a
reporter that it had been canceled because it was underbooked. A
spokeswoman for TWA in St. Louis, Julia Bishop-Cross, said later
that the flight had actually been full, that weather had caused the
cancellation, and that all the passengers were rebooked later that
evening. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With traffic growing heavier, the airlines have adopted another
strategy: cancel rather than let delays backlog. If possible, they
cancel early, notify passengers at home and rebook them for the
next day rather than deal with ``rolling delays'' that may create
long waits at the airport.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   May 18, during the week before the Memorial Day holiday, was an
evening of major thunderstorms in New York, and incoming flights
were diverted and delayed, and outbound flights canceled wholesale.
A number of Port Authority officials said that cancellations
enabled the lines to rebook their passengers to Friday flights and
get the situation back to normal quickly.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Spampanato, deputy general manager of Kennedy Airport, was
on duty, and he said the airlines' national headquarters, looking
at a Thursday night of foul weather, elected damage control. ``As
bad as it was on Thursday, the fastest way was to cancel flights
and recoup on Friday,'' he said. ``You have to position your
aircraft. It's a corporate decision the lines make looking at
everything from their headquarters. With a tie-up in New York, it
affects the globe.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To wit: on June 15 bad weather produced three- to six-hour
delays and 200 cancellations at La Guardia.
</P>
<P>
   On the holiday weekend, United's difficulties with its short
flights to Dulles on Friday considerably upset Tony Horan, a New
York lawyer, and his wife, Susan Trotter. The couple bought a
country place in Virginia in January, and after a try with US
Airways, which Trotter said did not seem reliable enough, she
booked United tickets to Dulles for every other weekend through the
summer, paying $129 a person for each round trip. They keep a car
parked at Dulles, in Chantilly, Va. The previous weekend they got
in about 1 a.m., because of a United cancellation. This time they
had everything necessary to board the 6:30 flight, but when it was
shifted to a 29-passenger Jetstream, because Trotter refuses to fly
on smaller planes, they looked for alternatives. ``You stand in
line for a long time,'' she said, ``and you find that someone with
more mileage gets the seats.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The couple left the line of passengers trying to get rebooking,
and sat with a cell phone in the gate area. The 7:30 p.m. had long
been a dead issue, and they were looking for something out of
Newark. Because their car was at Dulles, a flight to Reagan Airport
would not serve. Finally they arranged a one-way car rental from La
Guardia to Dulles.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are rethinking July 4,'' Horan said. On the drive to Dulles
they called United and asked for a refund of the tickets they did
not use. Eventually, the line gave it to them.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Linda Price of Charleston, W.Va., who works for AT&AMP;T, was on her
way home after running a training session for her employer in New
York. She finished early and arrived at the airport at 3 p.m. for
the 6:30 p.m. flight to Dulles, where she was to connect to a
flight to Charleston. As the delays mounted, she asked the gate
agent if she was going to make the second flight, and he told her
not to worry. When the flight finally took off at 8:34 p.m., she
was on board. But, said Gary Lonieski, United's manager of special
services at La Guardia, the flight did not arrive until 9:59, and
Price's connecting flight, 7603, had taken off at 9:50.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Layne of the Port Authority said that the sort of cascading
delays created by the winds in the west reported by the FAA's New
York Terminal Radar Control Facility in Westbury put airline
employees in a wringer. ``They are exceedingly slow to acknowledge
there are delays,'' Layne said. ``They push back from the gate on
time, but they know they will be held up getting out.'' That night,
takeoff delays reached an hour to an hour and a half before the
winds died at 8:50 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At about that time, the two United agents dealing with the
problems of those with tickets for the delayed, downsized flight
finally cleared the line-up. One passenger had taken 20 minutes,
during which she shouted at the agents: ``Who is going to pay for
the $500 hotel room I will not be occupying?'' After the flight
left, when the agent was asked what arrangements had been made for
that passenger, he said he did not remember. ``Not a great day,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, passengers on the canceled 7:30 flight were directed
to Gate 12C, where a United agent, Wally Cruz, was stationed to
rebook them. No one showed up. Cruz was asked if the flight was
empty, and he said no, 96 of the 112 seats had been booked, but
probably the passengers had learned earlier and taken other steps.
Some were probably rebooked on the 11:30 a.m. Saturday flight, he
said, because the 9:30 a.m. had also been canceled. This was a
result of a crew shortage, said Lazu, the ticket agent.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the airlines do not phrase it that way, a good
expedient for travelers is to resume the old habit of reconfirming.
Nine out of 10 of the major domestic airlines have telephone
numbers for automated systems on which flight numbers can be
punched in and status information obtained; the same information is
available on the lines' Web sites. The 10th airline, Southwest, has
a phone that is answered by employees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With cancellations increasing, travelers with immutable
deadlines _ weddings, graduations, speeches _ should probably
consider building an extra day into their schedules. People who use
travel agents can obtain telephone numbers that are staffed 24
hours, so rebookings can be made more easily than by standing in
line.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A day of watching the arrival and departure boards makes one
thing apparent: if there are incoming delays, there will be
outbound delays. When American Airlines Flight 354 inbound from
Chicago and Las Vegas was canceled on Friday evening, it was not
hard to see why Flight 303 scheduled to go to Chicago and San
Francisco at 6:30 a.m. Saturday was already canceled. It is doubly
worth checking the counter if such a possibility exists.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And looming cancellations are yet another reason to travel
light: those who carry everything with them are in a better
position to take a flight to an alternative airport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
