<SLUG> BC-U.S.-NKOREA-SANCTIONS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO EASE SOME ECONOMIC SANCTIONS ON NORTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration on Monday dropped many economic
sanctions against North Korea that were put in place a half century
ago after the country's communist forces invaded the South.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced in September that the United States
would ease the sanctions as a part of a strategy to coax the
Stalinist regime out of its largely self-imposed isolation. Last
week, after the summit meeting between the South Korean president,
Kim Dae-jung, and the North Korean leader, Kim Jong Il, the Clinton
administration said it would hurry to implement the change.
</P>
<P>
   The near complete collapse of North Korea's economy in recent
years has led to food shortages, starvation and widespread
stagnation. The end of sanctions by the United States could help
ease some of that economic desperation. North Korea will now be
allowed to export raw materials and goods to the United states and
open shipping routes between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Boucher, the State Department spokesman, also said
Monday that the administration had ceased referring to North Korea
and other countries as ``rogue states.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not changing behavior or policy,'' Boucher said. ``It's
finding a better description, a different description.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said in an interview
Monday on National Public Radio that the State Department would now
calling nations like Korea, Somalia and Afghanistan ``states of
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said the State Department had stopped calling North
Korea a rogue state several months ago. The announcement that the
State Department had formally dropped that designation may be a
step toward closer relations with the isolated nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the change in terminology will have no immediate practical
effect. North Korea is still classified as a terrorist nation, and
U.S. companies will still be prohibited from exporting
technologically advanced products that could be used for military
purposes. The United States, under law, must continue to oppose
World Bank and International Monetary Fund aid to the country,
Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   After the summit meeting last week, administration officials
said that if the North further cut its nuclear arms program and
made other concessions, it could possibly be removed from the list
of terrorist nations, opening up the possibility of further ties.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement was another sign that the Clinton
administration wants warmer relations with North Korea. But prior
agreements between North and South Korea have never been
implemented. And if last week's agreements to allow divided
families to reunite and to work toward peace on the peninsula fall
apart, the United States could quickly pull back from its strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The United States still has 37,000 troops based in South Korea,
along the border with the North. And North Korea's missile program
has been used as the administration's primary justification for
implementing a strategic missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of North Korea's missile program lead the Clinton
administration to announce last year that it would drop some
sanctions. In exchange for that promise, North Korea agreed to
cease testing its long range missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Monday will allow U.S. companies to invest in
agricultural and mining operations. And, according to the
announcement, U.S. companies will be allowed to export many goods
to the country without a license. U.S. residents and companies had
needed a Treasury Department license to do any business with North
Korea, including making humanitarian donations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Albright is scheduled to leave on Tuesday for a trip to China
and to South Korea, as she seeks to build on the momentum of
Monday's announcement and last week's agreement.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more concrete agreements from the summit meeting last
week would allow families split by the North-South division to
visit each other and even relocate. But it is unclear how far and
how fast the two countries will move toward national reunification.
</P>
<P>
   The summit seemed to indicate that Kim Jong Il is seeking to
hold on to power by opening his country up enough to win more aid
from South Korea, Japan and even the United States. But
reunification may not be in the personal interest of Kim Jong Il or
in the interest of South Korea, which would have to give billions
to create a market economy in North Korea or risk mass immigration
from the North to the South.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
