u a BC-BANTAM-MOTORCARS20-CO     06-19 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANTAM-MOTORCARS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cute little cars flock to maker's Ga. hometown
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARTOW, Ga _ The little old cars are uncomfortable,
underpowered, and a bit uncertain when it comes time to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, they're the stars of just about any car show where
they can be found.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: the Bantams are simply irresistibly cute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car is so silly that you have to love it,'' said Larry
Spindler, founder of the American Austin/Bantam Club. ``They're
just great little cars.''
</P>
<P>
   An expected 150 members of the club are gathering this week in
Bartow, the Middle Georgia town that is the birthplace of Roy S.
Evans, the supersaleman who bought the Bantam factory in Butler,
Pa., in 1937. Three years later, the company won the competition to
build the Army vehicle that became known as the Jeep.
</P>
<P>
   This year is the 100th anniversary of Evans' birth.
</P>
<P>
   The club presented the town _ whose population of about 300 is
roughly the same as when Evans was a boy _ with three large road
signs celebrating Evans' role in pioneering the Jeep.
</P>
<P>
   Today and Wednesday, there will be public events, including a
swap meet at the Bartow Community Center today and a tour to nearby
Louisville Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Jeeps and their commercial predecessors, the Bantams, were
not among the great success stories of American automotive history.
The factory did not have the capacity to build the number of Jeeps
the Army wanted, and the Bantams were too small for the public's
taste.
</P>
<P>
   But Evans' company did build vehicles that made history, and
before that, it turned out some pretty snappy little numbers.
</P>
<P>
   For those who collect the cars and come to the annual club
meets, the value is in the fun factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the Bantam was the neatest little car I ever saw,''
said Verlie Shroyer, of West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He bought a Bantam two years ago, spiffed it up, and now enjoys
all the attention it draws at the car shows. ``It draws more people
than the $100,000 Packards I park it next to, and it makes the
other owners jealous,'' Shroyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler Woodroof, of Franklin, Tenn., owns nine antique
automobiles, but his yellow 1938 bantam Roadster is his ``fun
car.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes it to local car shows or out for spins on most
weekends, he said, and in the two years he has owned it, he has put
a total of seven gallons of gas in.
</P>
<P>
   The Bantam was ``the world's first economy'' car, said Lee
Bortmas, of Butler, Pa. But light weight, small interiors and high
mileage were not what attracted buyers in those days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   They were durable, he said, but because not that many were made,
they're rare now.
</P>
<P>
   Bortmas drives one of the rarest of the Evans-made vehicles, a
converted Bantam Jeep that was never driven outside the company
factory. It was turned into a utility vehicle and used to shuttle
parts around the factory, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Miller of Fort Pierce, Fla., has restored four Bantams,
though he has been blind for about 40 years. He owned a Bantam in
his youth, when he still had his sight, he said, and he thought
``it was such a cute little car.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he knows the cars inside and out, he said, he lets his
hands take over the examination and repair work. ``There's just
something about saving a car that would have been destroyed that
just appeals to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the club members, nostalgia overrides their
appreciation for automotive engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lloyd, of Barrie, Ontario, said his father used a Bantam
delivery vehicle for his grocery business during World War II, when
gas rationing made a regular panel truck impractical to operate.
Also, that little truck was the first vehicle Lloyd ever drove.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
