A8798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLA-SKULVOUCHERS20-CO     06-19 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SKULVOUCHERS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida schools celebrate passing marks
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ The 350 children at Spencer Bibbs Elementary
School had never heard Principal Linda Scott shout so loud or jump
so high. They had never seen her dance down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the happiest I've ever seen Ms. Scott,'' said
11-year-old Kevin Mitchell, a Bibbs fifth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   Scott got the spring in her step Monday. That's when the only
two public schools in Florida classified as ``failing''
institutions received passing marks from the state Education
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel smart,'' Kevin said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his ``A Plus'' education reform program, a
cornerstone of his 1998 campaign, Gov. Jeb Bush declared that any
public school whose students failed a state standardized test two
years in a row would receive an ``F'' grade.
</P>
<P>
   The program produced two failing schools in a statewide public
system of 2,500 institutions. Both were elementary schools _ Bibbs
and A.A. Dixon _ in Pensacola, a Navy town near the sugar-white
beaches of the Florida Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Students at failing schools are eligible for tax-subsidized
vouchers that can be used for private school tuition. Florida
started the nation's first statewide voucher program. Legislators
in Georgia, Alabama and North Carolina, among other places, have
discussed vouchers as a tool to improve public schools.
</P>
<P>
   During the past school year, 52 Escambia County students
accepted vouchers as part of the only such statewide program in the
country. Prompted by the potential market for voucher students, new
private schools opened in Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   A state court judge in March ruled tax-supported vouchers
violate the Florida Constitution by draining money from public
schools. The state has appealed, putting the legal future of the
voucher program in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, students at Bibbs and Dixon _ which serve
the poorest sections of the city _ have labored under the failing
label. Scott said visitors expect to see children swinging from the
rafters and graffiti scrawled on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Walking home, Bibbs fifth-grader Brittany Brandon said people
she'd pass on the street would tease her for going to an ``F''
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it would make me feel bad. But they didn't really
know what was going on,'' a happier Brittany said Monday, after a
celebration in the school cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teacher told us we're not dumb,'' said second-grader Donna
Johnson, an 8-year-old at Bibbs. ``And anyway, `F' stands for
flying high.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott has spent as much time propping up self-esteem as she has
improving reading, writing and arithmetic. From memory,
second-graders repeat for classroom visitors the poem ``The Man Who
Thinks He Can,'' which concludes: ``Life's battles don't always
go/To the strongest or fastest man;/But sooner or later the man who
wins/Is the man who thinks he can!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of them,'' Scott said in her school's joyous
cafeteria Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Across town at Dixon, there was similar reaction. Students
cheered when officials announced that the school no longer was
branded with an ``F.'' As at Bibbs, kids snapped up chocolate chip
and sugar cookies brought by state Education Commissioner Tom
Gallagher. More than nine of every 10 kids at both schools qualify
for free or reduced-price lunches because of low family income. All
of them are entitled to free breakfast at Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon Principal Judith Ladner said she wanted to temper her
happiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be too excited, and I'll tell you why,'' she
said Monday in her office. ``I don't want to give any credence to
the A Plus plan. We don't feel the A Plus plan was appropriate.
What we did takes time. There is not a quick fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at both formerly failing schools said they began
addressing academic weaknesses years before Bush took office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a political play, and our kids have been right in
the middle of it,'' Ladner said.
</P>
<P>
   There are 20 schools that still could receive ``F'' grades for
the first time because of low writing scores. Their final grades
depend on math and reading scores, which haven't been released. If
those schools _ which the state education commissioner declined to
identify _ don't improve next year, their students could become
eligible for vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to prove that every child can learn,'' Bush
said. ``The minute we create standards and an accountability system
where there's a different consequence between mediocrity and
improvement, good things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's taking credit for the success, makes Dixon first-grade
teacher Fonda Robertson bristle. During the winter, Robertson
removed her 5-year-old son Daniel from a so-called A school in the
next county because he wasn't learning his letters. The
kindergartner now reads fluently and enjoys books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get the respect we should have gotten before,''
Robertson said. ``This didn't just happen this year. Politics is
dirty and it's just a power game. And we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
