<HEADLINE>
BIG 737 ORDER EXPECTED FROM SOUTHWEST AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. is in final negotiations with Southwest
Airlines for what would be one of the biggest orders ever for its
next generation 737.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources confirmed that the nation's largest low-fare
carrier is close to ordering 64 or more of the next generation
737-700s.
</P>
<P>
   The order, expected to be announced soon, would be worth more
than $3 billion at list prices. The 737-700 has a list price from
$43.5 million to $51.5 million, depending on the configuration and
options requested by the customer.
</P>
<P>
   Because Southwest is one of Boeing's biggest and best customers,
it is likely getting a significant discount on the jets, industry
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest has an all-737 fleet and was the launch customer for
the 737-700, the first of the next generation models. It entered
service with Southwest in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Boeing nor Southwest would comment on the pending order.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be the biggest that Southwest has ever placed with
Boeing, industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
   As launch customer for the 737-700, Southwest ordered 63 of the
jets in November 1993. The airline's next biggest order was for 59
of the same model jets in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing largest order ever for the next generation jets came from
American Airlines for 75 737-800s in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Delta ordered 70 of the 737-800s in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing builds four models of the next generation 737 at its
factory in Renton, Wash. They can fly higher, further and have much
greater fuel efficiency than the older ``classic'' 737s. The new
models are the 737-600, 737-700, 737-800 and 737-900. The first
737-900, the longest 737 ever, will roll out of the Renton factory
this summer for delivery to launch customer Alaska Airlines next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has recently landed several other big orders for its next
generation 737s. Last year, International Lease Finance Corp.
ordered 50 of the jets, and followed that with an order for 50 more
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus A320 family is the only competitor to the 737.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in this size category that Boeing has the most
competition,'' said analyst Peter Jacobs of Ragen MacKenzie.
``Essentially, Boeing splits the market with Airbus.''
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Southwest has stuck with Boeing, as have Delta and
American.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines can save on operating expenses by staying with one
manufacturer, rather than mixing their fleets with Boeing and
Airbus jets.
</P>
<P>
   And no customer has been as loyal to Boeing as Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 737s in the Southwest fleet are the older series
jets.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest has ordered 142 of the next generation 737-700s, and
taken delivery of 65.
</P>
<P>
   A Southwest spokeswoman said Monday the carrier will be
operating 342 Boeing 737s by the end of the year. It has taken
delivery of 11 of 21 737-700s scheduled to be delivered this year.
</P>
<P>
   The 737-700 can carry from 126 to 149 passengers, depending on
the configuration. The Southwest 737-700s have 137 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest is the nation's seventh largest carrier and is
steadily expanding the number of flights on existing routes while
adding additional cities. It currently flies to 56 U.S. cities in
29 states. It began flying to Albany, N.Y., its newest city, in
May.
</P>
<P>
   The airline announced Monday that it will begin flying to
Buffalo, New York, the third New York city added to Southwest's
system in 15 months as it expends in the northeastern United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Morning News first reported that Southwest would
place its largest order ever with Boeing for the 737-700. Southwest
is based in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper, quoting two unnamed people familiar with the
deal, said Southwest would order ```significantly'' more than 50 of
the jets within a couple of weeks. Industry sources independently
confirmed the forthcoming order to the Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Airbus has tried unsuccessfully to break Boeing's
737 monopoly with Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airbus has no chance with Southwest,'' said Richard Aboulafia,
senior aviation analyst at the Teal Group.
</P>
<P>
   He added that continued strong sales for the next generation 737
shows that it is more than holding its own against the popular A320
family of jets, which include the A319 and A321.
</P>
<P>
   In the past couple of years, the A320 family has enjoyed strong
sales, and several once loyal Boeing customers have bought the
Airbus jets rather than the next generation 737.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the competing planes are selling about the same.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, Boeing has 127 firm orders for all models of
its next generation 737.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus had 127 firm orders for its A319, A320 and A321 as of the
end of may.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Seddik Belyamani, Boeing's vice
president of sales and marketing, told the Post-intelligencer that
the next generation 737 has not lost an order competition this year
where it has gone up against the A320 family.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said the Airbus narrowbody jets, which use
fly-by-wire technology, are more advanced than the next generation
737.
</P>
<P>
   Aboulafia doesn't agree, though he acknowledged the A320 is a
``very good airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some thinking that Boeing is eventually going to have
to develop something all new, or should have,'' he said. ``I don't
buy into that at all. Part of me thinks it's an Airbus creation to
help sell the A320.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
