<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8800 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ARTS-LITERATURE-NYT &LR;      06-19 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-LITERATURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND IRELAND TO A WIDER YET OFTEN BLEAK WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRIAN LAVERY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ A stone's throw from Davy Byrne's pub, where
fans of James Joyce celebrated ``Ulysses'' on Friday night, St.
Anne's Church was packed to the organ pipes with more than 700
people waiting to hear Irish authors read from their work at the
Dublin Writers' Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Before stepping to the microphone, the writer Colum McCann asked
one of the festival organizers if he could read a letter by Joyce.
It was a fair question: on June 16, or Bloomsday, this city
delights in celebrating Joyce, its most famous prodigal son. But
Pat Boran, who helped found the festival four years ago, made it
quite clear that Leopold Bloom was not welcome at this particular
party, warning with some choice Irish obscenities, ``Don't you
dare.''
</P>
<P>
   Boran is not alone among Irish writers who want to keep their
distance from what has become the Disney World atmosphere of
Bloomsday, with literary tourists re-enacting scenes in Victorian
era bowler hats and frilly blouses. So the festival managed to give
Joyce a quick nod, then nimbly step out from under his shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gilligan, the festival director, said: ``There are other
great contemporary writers out there. We don't have to wait for
them to die to celebrate them.'' To that end, the festival featured
about 40 contemporary novelists and poets from Ireland as well as a
handful from Denmark, England, Germany and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day event opened with Doris Lessing, who engaged in a
lively conversation with the audience of 300 that upstaged her
reading of her new novel. Less mainstream material proved popular
as well, including a reading by children's authors. A session of
material written in Gaelic drew a full house.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, the spotlight shifted somewhat from the
Writers' Festival, which began on Thursday and ended on Sunday, to
the International Impac Dublin Literary Award. In its fifth year,
the award is gaining recognition for its $120,000 prize money, the
world's largest prize for a single work of fiction. By comparison,
Britain's prestigious Booker Prize offers around $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of these awards should be more substantial,'' said
James B. Irwin Sr., founder of the American management consultancy
IMPAC, which set up the award with an endowment of $1.5 million.
Thanks to his grandfather, who emigrated from Ireland to the Bronx,
Irwin holds dual citizenship and chose to locate Impac's European
headquarters in Dublin more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company ceded administration of the award to the Dublin
public libraries. Libraries around the world nominate works of
fiction, which are then narrowed to a short list and deliberated by
a panel of judges.
</P>
<P>
   During the buzz of Bloomsday activity, Impac mostly kept to
itself. Its glittery award ceremony was run with no reference to
the Dublin Writers' Festival. Guests at the black tie award
ceremony were greeted by a corps of bagpipe players, followed by
actors on stilts coated in gold and silver body paint.
</P>
<P>
   Nicola Barker, the British writer, won for her 1998 novel ``Wide
Open.'' John Hume, the Nobel Peace Prize winner for his efforts to
broker a solution in Northern Ireland, presented the literary award
at the Irish Museum of Modern Art here. Toni Morrison and Philip
Roth had been on the short list for the prize. Barker read from
``Wide Open'' at the festival's closing event. McCann had flown in
from New York because his 1998 novel, ``The Other Side of
Brightness,'' was on the short list for the Impac prize. Last
year's winner, Andrew Miller, read from an unpublished manuscript
entitled ``Oxygen'' and answered audience questions with Colm
Toibin, one of Ireland's most accomplished contemporary novelists.
</P>
<P>
   Hume's presence at the ceremony and Toibin's seat on the judging
panel reaffirmed that the award is more than just an international
literary event that happens to take place in Dublin; it is a
festival that celebrates Irish writing, allowing the nation's
authors to stand up to the legacy of Joyce as well as another
figure dominating Ireland's cultural landscape, Frank McCourt.
McCourt's work has in some ways made it harder for younger Irish
writers to work with the country's best-known literary themes, from
rural poverty to alcoholism to family strife.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland is experiencing both peace and economic prosperity for
the first time in modern history, which means a transition for its
literature after centuries of suffering and struggle. Still, a
handful of Irish playwrights _ including Sebastian Barry and Martin
McDonagh, both Broadway favorites _ continue to explore the harsh
conditions of decades gone by.
</P>
<P>
   The up-and-coming generation of Irish writers were born during
the 1960s, left the country during the '80s and have since
returned. To some, the Irish novel has become an international
novel, McCann said. His book ``The Other Side of Brightness,'' for
instance, explores the history of the New York City subway from the
point of view of what he calls international mongrels: manual
laborers digging the tunnels and homeless people living beneath the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   His forthcoming work opens in a devastating Russian winter
during World War II, as the Red Army retreats towards Moscow. Anne
Enright, who also read on Friday night, recently signed an American
publishing deal for her novel ``What Are You Like?,'' the tale of a
young Irish woman's life as an immigrant in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland is like Cuba, said Toibin, 45. The first thing you want
to do on a small island is escape it. To see the world is indeed a
type of intellectual exile. McCann says he now lives in New York
City because of curiosity, not because he cannot find a job in
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   It is also becoming apparent that Irish writers today are
generally not drinkers. The writers' pub, the deadly pint and
chaser of their forebears, have been supplanted by homelife and
parenthood. The embrace of such a lifestyle may pose a threat to
what the Dublin poet Paul Durcan, calls ``that will to die,'' which
in the popular imagination still remains essential to the Irish
creative mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
