u w BC-SCOTUS-RDP-NYT &LR;      06-19 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT UPHOLDS LAW ON PRISON INJUNCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Wis., Pa., Ind. ) (See also SCOTUS-TRADE, SCOTUS-PRAYER) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Monday that a recent law
that suspends certain federal court orders governing conditions in
state and local prisons does not amount to an unconstitutional
interference by Congress into the business of the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 decision upheld a provision of the Prison Litigation
Reform Act under which judges must either rule on the continuing
validity of an ongoing prison injunction within 90 days _ when its
validity is challenged by the state or anyone else _ or find the
injunction automatically suspended until they do rule.
</P>
<P>
   The challenged provision was one part of a far-reaching law,
passed in 1995, by which Congress sought to curb lawsuits by
prisoners and to cut back on the power of federal courts to keep
state and local prisons under long-term federal supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The law set tough new standards for issuing injunctions
governing ``conditions of confinement'' and authorized any
interested party to go to court and challenge an existing
injunction as not meeting those standards. In order to make sure
that judges would pay prompt attention to such challenges, Congress
included an ``automatic stay'' provision by which the injunction
would be lifted until the judge ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The federal appeals court in Chicago, ruling on a challenge
brought by inmates in an Indiana prison who opposed the state's
effort to invoke the new law, declared the automatic stay provision
unconstitutional. A legislative determination that a specific court
order had to be set aside violated the separation of powers, the
appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   In overturning that ruling Monday, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor's
majority opinion rejected the appeals court's characterization of
what the provision accomplished. The automatic stay did not
interfere with a court's final judgment, O'Connor said, because an
ongoing injunction, unlike a decision in an ordinary case,
``remains subject to alteration due to changes in the underlying
law.''
</P>
<P>
   The new standards contained in the Prison Litigation Reform Act
were such a change, she said, requiring an order governing prison
conditions to be ``narrowly drawn,'' to go ``no further than
necessary,'' and to be ``the least intrusive means necessary'' to
correct the violation. Congress specified that the law should apply
retroactively to make any ongoing prison injunction subject to
``immediate termination'' if it cannot meet those standards.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Miller vs. French, No. 99-224, put the Clinton
administration in an uncomfortable position. Although President
Clinton had signed the law, administration lawyers could not avoid
the fact that it raised troubling constitutional questions. In
defending the automatic stay provision before the Supreme Court,
the administration proposed a new reading of the provision. The
automatic stay was not quite what it appeared to be, the solicitor
general's office argued; rather, it did not strip federal judges of
their traditional authority to maintain the status quo in pending
litigation. Judges themselves could grant a stay of the stay, the
government said, and therefore avoid the separation of powers
problem.
</P>
<P>
   While the state of Indiana, which also appealed the ruling by
the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, was nominally on the same
side as the administration, the two briefs diverged dramatically.
The state, asking the court to uphold the law as written, said the
administration's statutory interpretation flew in the face of
Congress' clear intent to make the stay automatic.
</P>
<P>
   In her majority opinion Monday, O'Connor agreed with the state
and rejected the administration's view that the law could be read
to leave federal judges with any flexibility. ``Any attempt to
enjoin the stay is irreconcilable with the plain language of the
statute,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the nine justices agreed with the statutory
interpretation. In addition to the five in the majority _ Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony
M. Kennedy, and Clarence Thomas, along with O'Connor _ Justices
David H. Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg agreed that the law could
not be read to permit any flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   But there the two groups of justices parted company. In a
dissenting opinion, Souter and Ginsburg said that while the law did
not raise a separation of powers problem, the deadline it imposed
for judicial action was so short as to raise a question of whether
the law violated the constitutional right to due process. They said
the case should be sent back to the lower courts with instructions
to consider the due process implications.
</P>
<P>
   The majority opinion also noted that the law ``may implicate due
process concerns'' but said that this issue was not part of the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The only two members of the court to accept the administration's
interpretation of the statute were Justices Stephen G. Breyer and
John Paul Stevens, who said there was support in the statute for a
more flexible interpretation that would avoid serious
constitutional problems.
</P>
<P>
   With eight cases now remaining until the justices conclude their
term, there were also these other developments Monday.
 &UR;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; HMO Case
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the court summarily vacated and sent back to
the Supreme Court of Pennsylvania a case in which the state court
allowed a medical negligence case to proceed against a health
maintenance organization for refusing to authorize a member's
admission to the nearest hospital, which was not a participant in
the medical plan.
</P>
<P>
   The question in the case, United States Healthcare Systems vs.
Pennsylvania Hospital Insurance Co., No. 98-1836, is whether a suit
of this type can be heard in state court or whether, as the HMO is
arguing, it is pre-empted by a federal law, the Employee Retirement
Income Security Act of 1974.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision last week, the Supreme Court ruled that the
federal law, known as Erisa, does not provide a basis for suing an
HMO for giving doctors a financial incentive to ration health care.
But last week's decision left open a number of questions about the
pre-emptive effect of Erisa in cases involving not medical
treatment as such but benefits eligibility and the general
administration of a health plan. By its action Monday, the court
indicated that it wants these issues to be further developed in the
lower courts.
</P>
<P>
   Speedy Judgment
</P>
<P>
   The justices agreed to decide whether, when free speech
interests are at stake, the Constitution requires a prompt judicial
determination of a challenge to a state or local licensing law. The
case is an appeal by the owner of an adult bookstore in Waukesha,
Wis., which refused to renew the store's operating license in a
proceeding that lasted for many months.
</P>
<P>
   While the Supreme Court has required ``prompt judicial review''
in similar cases, it is unclear whether that means simply prompt
access to court, or a prompt decision, or at least a provision to
preserve the status quo during a lengthy process. The case, City
News and Novelty vs. City of Waukesha, No. 99-1680, is an appeal
from the Wisconsin Court of Appeals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
