<HEADLINE>
BUSH BENEFITS HANDSOMELY FROM VISIT TO SILICON VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Gov. George W. Bush used part of a western
campaign swing on Monday to discuss what modern technology could do
for public education. But there was also a lesson in what that
technology _ or at least its wealthy purveyors _ could do for Bush
and fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner on Monday night held at the home of John T.
Chambers, the chief executive of Cisco Systems, Bush collected what
campaign officials estimated to be more than $3.5 million from
Silicon Valley's entrepreneurs. Much of it was ``soft money'' _
largely unregulated donations _ and all of it was to be divided
between the Republican party in California and the Republican
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't relish these big fund-raising events,'' Bush said
beforehand, as his campaign plane flew west from Austin, Texas. But
he was set to grin and bear several of them during a campaign week
expected to be among his most lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's schedule included a dinner in Los Angeles on Tuesday,
expected to raise another $2 million for the state and national
parties, and a gathering in Houston on Wednesday night expected to
raise at least $4 million for the Republican National Committee,
according to Bush's aides. Factoring in a few smaller events, the
week's haul would likely exceed $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's other purposes as he traveled Monday to Vancouver,
Wash., and then on to Palo Alto was to promote a few new education
proposals that he said were intended to help make sure that
technology brought into public school classrooms was truly helping
students learn. He was also spending time in two states he would
like to make more competitive in the general election than
political analysts had predicted he could.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at an elementary school in Vancouver at midday, Bush
said the Clinton administration's efforts to wire classrooms to the
Internet _ it is spending about $3 billion annually on the project
_ had given local school districts too little flexibility in their
use of these federal funds, creating a system ``hidebound by
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for loosening those regulations and for spending
another $80 million a year in federal funds so that the Department
of Education could study the best ways of using technology in
classrooms and set up a clearinghouse to make the information
available to states and local school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal ought not to be how many classrooms are wired,'' Bush
said. ``The goal is how are we effectively teaching children. My
whole presidency will challenge process and focus on results.''
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for Vice President Al Gore,
said that in addition to the $3 billion, there was roughly another
$500 million now in the federal budget over which states and local
districts had ample discretion and could be used to provide teacher
training, software purchases and other activities to take advantage
of schools' connection to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very successful,'' Hattaway said. He added that
Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee, has set a
goal for his administration to assure that every student in America
was computer-literate by the eighth grade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
