<HEADER>
A8809 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HARCOURT-ADVISER-BOS &LR;      06-19 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARCOURT-ADVISER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARCOURT GENERAL EXPLORES WAYS TO BOOST STOCK PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Harcourt General Inc., the company that got its start
showing silent movies in Boston and now sells knowledge over the
Internet, Monday began what could be its closing chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring the New York investment bank of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., the
publishing company said it considers itself undervalued on Wall
Street and wants ``to explore a range of strategic alternatives to
enhance shareholder value, including the possible sale of the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors responded by bidding Harcourt General shares up
$12.7812 to a 52-week closing high of $54.8125, a 30 percent gain
that pushed the family-run company's total market to more than $4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that illustrates the point,'' Harcourt spokesman Peter
Farwell said. ``The press release did quite a job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point the sale of the entire company is a likely
outcome,'' Farwell said, adding that the company had examined a
variety of other options.
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt General's holdings include textbook publishers, medical
journals, online advisory services for doctors, and a list of
fabled works of literature _ a package analysts said might be
attractive to Bertelsmann AG, Pearson PLC, or Reed Elsevier, the
European publishing giants that in recent years have taken over
many of the best-known US names in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Managed by the Smith family since its founding as a movie
theater chain in 1922, the company posted $184 million in earnings
last year on $2.14 billion in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But, like hundreds of other companies Wall Street views as
low-tech tortoises, Harcourt General has attracted little investor
interest recently. Not even a decade of acquisitions, the sale of
its theaters, and the 1999 spinoff of a controlling interest in
Neiman Marcus Group could change that.
</P>
<P>
   As the Newton company's 75-year-old chairman, Richard A. Smith,
put it in the announcement: ``Harcourt General's value in the
public market does not presently reflect the quality of its
businesses, record results, and bright prospects of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt General was silent about how proceeds distributed if a
sale occurs, but the Smith family holds 28 percent of the shares
and would be big winners.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Smith, who took over the company from his father,
Philip, in 1961, handed control over last year to his son, Robert,
and son-in-law, Brian Knez _ who share the titles of president and
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts saw the move to sell Harcourt General as a sign of
the new chief officers' frustration with investor fickleness toward
established, low-technology, ``value'' companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The management may have been getting frustrated that the
market wasn't giving the company the measure of appreciation they
felt it deserved, so they decided to speed things up,'' Peter P.
Appert, a Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown analyst, said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, saw the move as an acceptance of a trend that
in recent years put US book publishers, such as Random House and
Simon &AMP; Schuster, in the hands of European conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media companies have all really moved away,'' said Darice
Grippo, a vice president with John Hancock Advisors, ``and the
education-related companies in the United States are all more and
more Internet-driven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the education world these days vs. the corporate strategy
of building global communications businesses,'' Robert E. Baensch,
director of the Center for Publishing at New York University, said.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths, while aggressive in building Harcourt General's
holdings _ the company paid $854 million in 1997 for National
Educational Corp. and has invested heavily in Internet technology _
didn't get into publishing until 1991.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the company, then still known as General Cinema
Corp., invested proceeds from the 1989 sale of its Pepsi-Cola
bottling interests in Harcourt Brace Jovanovich, the New York-based
publisher whose author list includes Antoine Saint-Exupery, T.S.
Eliot, Sinclair Lewis, and Gunter Grass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
