u f BC-BRONFMAN-PROFILE-ART-     06-19 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRONFMAN-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE BRONFMANS, THE BITTERSWEET END OF A FAMILY-CONTROLLED ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (With SEAGRAM-VIVENDI, SEAGRAM-MARKETPLACE)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seagram empire rose over three generations, rising on liquor
and blood and toil from the harsh plains of western Canada to the
skyscrapers of New York and the lush boulevards of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Now with Seagram expected to announce an agreement to sell
itself to Vivendi, an upstart French media company hardly known
outside Europe, the story of one of the world's largest
family-controlled companies is about to come to an end. For the
Bronfmans, the Canadian clan that rode from the Prohibition era
into dazzling wealth and power, this is a bittersweet day.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, Edgar Bronfman Jr., third-generation heir to the
Seagram throne, has tried to transform Seagram from a stodgy liquor
company into a media powerhouse. Along the way, he sold Seagram's
stake in Du Pont, bought the Universal movie studio, and made
Seagram the world's biggest music company.
</P>
<P>
   But Bronfman could never outrun his detractors, who jeered him
as an intellectual lightweight whose judgment was clouded by the
star-studded atmosphere of Hollywood and the record business. And
it was never clear whether Bronfman had the full support of his
uncle Charles, the co-chairman of Seagram along with Edgar Sr.,
Bronfman's father.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, soon after Seagram's stock rallied to what was then
an all-time high, Charles Bronfman sold more than $400 million of
Seagram shares. Charles attributed the sale to estate planning, but
it was hardly a sign of confidence in Seagram's long-term future.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors are equally skeptical of Bronfman's abilities.
Since he took over Seagram in June 1994, the company's shares have
roughly doubled. Over the same period, Time Warner shares have
quadrupled, and the S&AMP;P Entertainment industry index, which
measures the performance of several big media stocks, has more than
tripled. Seagram was lagging even further behind until this month,
when its shares ran up on rumors of the Vivendi deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my mind, he's done a pretty lousy job as CEO,'' said one
institutional investor whose company owns several hundred thousand
Seagram shares. Over the period that Bronfman has run Seagram,
``News Corp., Viacom, Disney, they've all done better,'' said the
investor, who said he could not be quoted by name because his
company is currently trading Seagram shares.
</P>
<P>
   But even though Seagram has been outpaced by other media
companies, its shares have actually outperformed Du Pont since
Seagram sold its 328 million share stake in the chemical company in
spring 1995. Since then, Du Pont shares have risen barely 50
percent, less than half Seagram's gain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all his efforts to preserve the family fortune,
Bronfman seemed to be slipping behind as the rest of the media
industry consolidated. September's combination of CBS and Viacom,
followed by January's titanic takeover of Time Warner by America
Online, created a new scale for media companies that Seagram could
not match. Seagram has no major United States broadcast television
network, no first-rank cable network, no cable systems. Its movie
studio has struggled for years, despite occasional hits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the music business is in the midst of a fundamental
change driven by the Internet, which has caused music piracy to
explode. In the long run, it is not clear whether the Internet will
help Seagram and other established music companies by cutting their
distribution costs or hurt them by increasing piracy. And until
that question is answered, music, which is Seagram's strongest
asset, will remain hobbled.
</P>
<P>
   So with Seagram's stock price stagnating and nagging questions
about Bronfman's abilities, the company turned to Vivendi and the
welcoming arms of Jean-Marie Messier. Like Bronfman, Messier hopes
to recast his company for a new century, turning it from a utility
and water company into a communications and media giant. Messier
sees a perfect fit between Seagram's music business and Vivendi's
cell phones, a marriage of content and distribution that some
analysts agree could give the new company the heft to compete with
Viacom and the combined AOL Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman may have simply been too far ahead of his time. With
spending on media and entertainment increasing worldwide, his
effort to remake Seagram could well be vindicated in years to come,
said Mario Gabelli, whose funds own three million Seagram shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vertical integration is a necessity,'' said Gabelli. ``It's a
terrific deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors have agreed, so far. Over the last week, as word of
the deal seeped out, Seagram stock has risen from $50.625 to $64, a
28 percent gain. For the Bronfmans, who own more than 106 million
shares of Seagram stock, the run-up has increased their wealth by
$1.4 billion and taken some of the sting out of Seagram's
underperformance over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   The total value of the Bronfman family stake in Seagram tops
$6.7 billion. The Bronfman stock is held in a complex web of
trusts; so unraveling how many shares are held by each individual
family member is nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the merits of the merger _ and it will take years
before investors find out how strong the proposed new company
really is _ it is certain that Bronfman will no longer be in the
driver's seat. Messier will run the new company, with Bronfman as
vice chairman with his actual duties still to be defined.
</P>
<P>
   That is a condition Bronfman's grandfather, the legendary Samuel
Bronfman, would never have accepted, said David Paperny, director
of a documentary on the Bronfman family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam went to great lengths to make sure the company would
remain in family hands,'' Paperny said. ``This included kicking
several of his brothers out of the family business so it would be
cleanly passed down to his own two sons, Edgar and Charles. Sam
would definitely regret seeing the family lose control.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Marrus, dean of the University of Toronto graduate
school and author of a biography of Samuel Bronfman, said ``Sam,''
as he was known before his death in 1971, ``was someone for whom
family mattered hugely.'' Samuel Bronfman would have been
especially torn by the news that Vivendi plans to sell Seagram's
liquor division after the merger, Marrus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that for Sam, whiskey is not something he made in
order to make money,'' Marrus said. ``He really cared about
whiskey, by which I mean he was to blended whiskey what Isaac Stern
is to the violin. He really cared.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he hoped to keep his company independent, Samuel Bronfman
made at least one miscalculation. At a family gathering in the
1960s, ``Sam jabbed his finger at Edgar Jr.,'' Paperny recalled,
``and said: `You're the one. You're the one to lead my company into
the future.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
