<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAM-MARKET-PLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: VIVENDI-SEAGRAM MERGER MEANS CHANGES IN GLOBAL
SPIRITS INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SEAGRAM-VIVENDI) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brands like Chivas Regal, Martell cognac and Captain Morgan rum
will be on the block if Vivendi, Canal Plus and Seagram do in fact
agree to merge. But which distilled-spirits company is likely to
wind up as their new owner?
</P>
<P>
   Many industry experts say Allied Domecq would be the probable
winner. Allied is the second-largest company in the highly
fragmented world of spirits, behind Diageo of Britain, which, after
it was formed by the merger of Guinness and Grand Metropolitan in
1998, became the industry leader with about 9 percent of the global
market. The next handful of companies have shares less than half
that size, with even smaller stakes held by others.
</P>
<P>
   The Seagram brands are expected to bring more than $7 billion,
roughly equal to Allied Domecq's sales last year. The sale of the
brands has been proposed by Vivendi management to rid the new deal
of $6.6 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   For Allied, which now owns brands like Beefeater gin and
Ballantine's Scotch, taking on the new brands would not be
impossible, particularly if the deal mixes stock and debt. That, at
least is what a group of Salomon Smith Barney analysts wrote in a
note to investors last week. Doing so might strengthen the
management pool for the two companies, they added. ``Seagram's U.S.
management is very strong,'' they wrote, ``and Allied's management
in Europe is by far superior.''
</P>
<P>
   The analysts estimated that the Seagram brands were worth about
10.5 times their earnings before taxes, which are expected to total
$723 million when the fiscal year ends this month. That works out
to $7.6 billion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire Hathaway, the investment company led by Warren
Buffett, bought more than 33 million Allied shares this spring, or
3 percent of the company _ an investment that caused a flurry at
Allied, sending its share price up briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Diageo could also buy the brands, and would not run into
significant antitrust hurdles except in the United States and
Canada. Such issues, experts say, could be sidestepped by disposing
of whiskey, gin and Scotch brands now sold in those markets.
</P>
<P>
   A third possibility is for the Bronfman family to hold on to the
division. With about 23 percent of Seagram shares in the family's
hands, the sale of the company would leave them with $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the current Seagram CEO, Edgar Bronfman, has been driven
by the media business in recent years, this strategy has arguably
failed, and the older family members of Seagram's management might
well wish to retrench to the original spirits activity,'' the
Salomon Smith Barney analysts wrote in their note to investors.
``Certainly these older family members see more value in drink than
Edgar appears to see.''
</P>
<P>
   A person close to the family said such a move was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Also for sale is about 30 percent of Vivendi's water business,
run by its Generale des Eaux division. ``The opportunity for water,
globally, is pretty strong,'' noted Michael Bellas, chief executive
of Beverage Marketing, a database and consulting company in New
York. Last March, Vivendi paid a hefty $6.2 billion for U.S.
Filter, a California supplier of industrial water-purification
equipment that also has a small consumer bottled-water unit. At the
time of that deal, Vivendi was the biggest player in the
fast-growing $300 billion water treatment industry.
</P>
<P>
   The spirits business has helped support other Seagram divisions
for years, several industry experts said Monday. In the recent
past, brands that did not perform well were scrapped so the company
could focus almost exclusively on high-priced, ``superpremium''
products, and the appeal of these brands to young adults has
improved in the last year or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a little bit of a resurgence'' in drinks sold in
bars and restaurants, Bellas said. ``They were up about 1 percent,
after being down all through the 1980s and 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   If the brands are sold to one of Seagram's competitors, that
could shake up the long-slumbering spirits industry, one of the
more fragmented industries worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the soft-drink industry _ in which Coca-Cola holds a
commanding 51 percent worldwide share and Pepsi has 21 percent,
according to Beverage Digest, a trade newsletter _ the spirits
business has not had any kind of transforming consolidation of
brands or distributors. Many predicted a wave of consolidation
after the formation of Diageo, but for various reasons no such
trend emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, companies like Seagram and Allied Domecq control much
of their distribution. In the United States, regulations forbid
companies that own liquor brands to own their distributors as well.
Along with the brands it owns outright, Seagram controls worldwide
distribution rights for Absolut vodka.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies that are expected to take a look at the Seagram
brands include Bacardi-Martini, the privately held owner of Bacardi
rum, Dewar's Scotch and Martini &AMP; Rossi vermouth. While Bacardi has
made acquisitions in the recent past, buying Bombay gin from Diageo
after the merger with Grand Met, the company took a sphinx-like
stand Monday when asked if it was interested in the Seagram
properties. ``We are always looking for opportunities to enhance
our portfolio,'' a company spokesman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Additional contenders could include Brown-Forman, the American
maker of Jack Daniel's and Southern Comfort, as well as Pernod
Ricard SA, the French owner of the Ricard pastis brand. Pernod
Ricard tried to sell its Orangina soft-drink brand to Coca-Cola in
1997 to concentrate on spirits. But the deal was rejected last year
by French regulators, who said it would give Coca-Cola too much of
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Pernod, which is only a $3.5 billion company, nor
Brown-Forman, with sales of about $2 billion, could swing the
Seagram acquisition on its own. But like so many other industries,
from computers to grocery stores, the spirits business has started
to see strength in scale _ the bigger the better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
