<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WRITER-NYT &LR;      06-19 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WRITER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERSEY GIRL MAKES IT BIG AT LEAST ON TV 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It's 8 a.m., and Diane Ruggiero is seated in a
super-trendy patio restaurant in a hotel on Sunset Boulevard.
Despite the early hour, most of the handful of diners are wearing
dark glasses, dressed in black and keeping their cell phones handy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are these people?'' whispered Ruggiero, a 29-year-old
writer who just flew in from New Jersey. ``When I checked in I
said: `Give me a break! These people wouldn't last 15 minutes in
New Jersey. I mean, I don't know these people.''
</P>
<P>
   She will quite soon.
</P>
<P>
   After years of struggling as a writer and working as a waitress
and bartender in and around the working- and middle-class North
Jersey towns North Arlington and East Rutherford, Ruggiero
(ROUGE-ear-oh) has been plucked from obscurity to write and help
produce a new autobiographical television comedy series, ``That's
Life,'' on CBS. The show, about a 30-something New Jersey waitress
who turns her life and her family's life upside down when she
decides to return to college, will make its debut in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Ruggiero, who is candid, funny and
self-deprecating, is temporarily moving from her big $600-a-month
apartment in North Arlington (``If I had the same apartment in
Manhattan I'd have to, like, hire call girls to work for me so I
could afford it'') to Los Angeles. Visibly reluctant to move here,
Ruggiero acknowledged that her career and life were changing
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   A film script she wrote, ``Pretty the Beast,'' is to be produced
by Nora Ephron. Her new television series, in which she is also a
supervising producer, is starting production. Ruggiero has ideas
for several other projects that are based, more or less, on growing
up in a large, tightly knit Italian family.
</P>
<P>
   In the series, for example, the family keeps photos of the pope
and Frank Sinatra in their home. ``I grew up thinking that Frank
Sinatra was actually a younger version of the pope,'' she said.
``When I made my communion we were talking about the pope and I
said, `My father has all his records,' and the nun was, like,
`What?' I actually grew up thinking that the pope sang `Summer
Wind.''' In a quasi-serious moment, Ruggerio said that moving to
Los Angeles, at least at the moment, filled her with dread. ``I'm
an Italian girl from northern New Jersey,'' she said. ``The sun is
kind of overbearing here. And the people! I was at the hotel bar
last night and I saw like five girls who wore little dresses and
had 10-foot-long legs. I don't like being the fattest person in
this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruggiero, who is not fat, has tried to write movies, plays and
stories since she was a child. She grew up in Old Bridge, N.J.,
where her father, Joseph, was a maintenance worker on the New
Jersey Turnpike for 30 years. (In the series, Paul Sorvino plays
the father of the young woman and works as a toll collector.) Her
mother, Carol, is British. ``When her relatives come over we have
peppers and eggs and tea and biscuits,'' Ruggiero said. ``My
mother's kind of a white-bread Italian.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school, Ruggiero kept writing and
worked as a waitress and bartender. She took courses for about 10
years at several colleges, mostly at Montclair State University.
(In the series, the college is called Montville.) Ruggiero said she
would drop courses to earn money to pay for unexpected car
insurance bills or a root canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point I was waitressing 80 hours a week and taking only
photography and astronomy,'' Ruggiero said. She also worked as an
Easter Bunny in a mall, made fruit baskets and was an assistant to
a publicity agent in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She still hangs out in East Rutherford with friends at a
restaurant where she once worked called Park and Orchard. While she
was a waitress there, a patron, Mark St. Germain, who lived nearby,
would come by with his young daughter. He asked Ruggerio what she
really wanted to do. ``I told him I was a writer, and he said that
he was a writer,'' she said. St. Germain, who has written some Off
Broadway plays (``Moby Dick,'' ``Jack's Holiday'') as well as
scripts for ``The Cosby Show,'' asked Ruggerio if he could read
some of her work.
</P>
<P>
   Ruggiero gave him 10 pages of her comedy screenplay ``Pretty the
Beast,'' about a suicidal writer who can't kill herself because she
has writer's block and can't write the note. St. Germain told her
she had talent and put her on a weekly writing regimen to complete
the screenplay. After she finished it, he gave the screenplay to
his agents at International Creative Management. Soon enough
Ruggiero had an agent there as well as a mentor in St. Germain.
(St. Germain is now writing some scripts for ``That's Life.'')
</P>
<P>
   Ephron, who optioned the screenplay, said, ``From the first page
it was absolutely clear that Diane was an extremely funny writer
with an absolutely clear voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruggiero was selected to write ``That's Life'' in an unusual
way. A CBS executive, Ghen Maynard, had proposed a series that
would be a twist on the premise of the hit show ``Felicity'':
instead of a young woman attending college an older woman would
decide to return to school.
</P>
<P>
   Talent agents sent more than 100 scripts to CBS, which was
seeking a writer for the show. Ruggiero's film script stirred the
attention of CBS; she said she would write the pilot if she could
turn the heroine into an Italian-American waitress from New Jersey
who decided to go to college _ just like herself. The script for
the pilot was welcomed by CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Addison, a producer of the show and a former CBS executive
who helped select Ruggiero from among more than 100 writers, said:
``This was dialogue we hadn't quite heard before. We didn't feel
like it was retreaded from other television shows. It was written
out of life's experiences, wonderfully irreverent.''
</P>
<P>
   The show stars Heather Paige Kent, a stand-up comedian and
actress born in the Bronx, as Lydia, a surrogate for Ruggiero.
Ellen Burstyn and Sorvino play her parents; Debi Mazar plays a
smart-mouth hairstylist friend, and Peter Firth is an arrogant and
sad professor. The characters are more or less based on real people
or composites.
</P>
<P>
   The series is to be broadcast on Saturdays from 8 to 9 p.m., the
time slot held for five years by ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman,''
which drew a strong, predominantly female audience.
</P>
<P>
   Like the clan in the show, Ruggiero's family was not so much
against her attending college as puzzled by her not wanting to
settle down, marry and have children. But for all the similarities,
she said, she had her antennae out for stereotypes that would be
demeaning to Italian-Americans or her home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one big problem with a house we were using,'' she said.
``It was a bit unkempt out front. And I said, `You know, these
people take care of their houses.' My father is like Edward
Scissorhands with the shrubbery. He has great pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want this show to be a joke where people have names
like Luigi and Cheech and it's all stereotypical and cheesy. I
mean, I grew up in this area that's thick with Italian culture and
I love it. And the same with New Jersey. In this hotel I was
talking to this woman from Germany and she began making fun of New
Jersey. And I said: `You're from Germany! How do you make fun of
New Jersey?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Have you ever been to New Jersey? You don't know
anything. Thomas Edison's from New Jersey. How bad could it be?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
