<SLUG> BC-COURT-ROUNDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT WON'T HEAR CASE ON EVOLUTION DISCLAIMER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LETITIA STEIN 
c 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday refused to consider a
case from a school board in Louisiana that wanted students to hear
a disclaimer before studying evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Three justices dissented the court's decision to let stand a
ruling that declared unconstitutional a disclaimer informing
students that lessons on evolution are ``not intended to influence
or dissuade the Biblical version of Creation or any other
concept.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's refusal to hear the case sets no national precedent
on the practice of teaching evolution in schools. Still, the denial
means the ruling of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals is
legally binding in Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi, states within
the appellate court's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   In their rulings, the lower courts found that the disclaimer's
stated purpose _ to encourage students to think critically about
the origin of life _ was a sham, and it had the effect of
protecting a particular religious viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   But without the disclaimer, the Louisiana school board argued,
students are being subjected to an ``orthodoxy of opinion,'' a
claim the 5th Circuit considered legitimate, while other aspects of
the disclaimer failed constitutional tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who do not adhere to the view of evolution as the origin
of man are somehow second-class citizens in the school community,''
school board attorney Barry Ashe said after the court refused to
hear the case. ``Their view is not even acknowledged.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court was just one vote shy of taking up the case.
Four of nine Supreme Court justices must choose to hear an appeal
in order for the high court to review the case.
</P>
<P>
   The court offered no explanation for its decision to pass on the
case. But Justice Antonin Scalia filed a dissent, joined by Chief
Justice William Rehnquist and Justice Clarence Thomas, criticizing
the court for not considering the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand by in silence while a deeply divided Fifth Circuit
bars a school district from even suggesting to students that other
theories besides evolution _ including, but not limited to, the
Biblical theory of creation _ are worthy of their consideration,''
Scalia wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Tangipahoa Parish Board of Education passed a
resolution requiring a disclaimer to be read at the beginning of
any lesson on evolution in elementary and high school classes. The
disclaimer stated that ``it is the basic right and privilege of
each student to form his/her opinion or maintain beliefs taught by
parents on this very important matter of the origin of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Students were urged to ``exercise critical thinking'' and
``closely examine each alternative'' in forming an opinion on the
origin of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   In response, three parents of students in the school system
challenged the school board resolution in court. The parents argued
the resolution, which offers Biblical creationism as the only named
alternative to evolution, violated a constitutional separation
between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The parents won their case in a federal district court and in
the 5th Circuit, as both courts struck down the disclaimer on the
grounds that it abridged a First Amendment clause prohibiting
government involvement in religion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dissent of the three justices, the majority of the
court has rejected attempts to allow religion in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ In another case, the Supreme Court also declined to hear
Houston, Texas, vs. Kolb, John E. et al.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Houston petitioned the Supreme Court to review a
dispute between the city and a group of developers in Harris
County. John E. Kolb and others filed suit in 1994 to challenge a
city ordinance that would have required them to dedicate a
right-of-way for the Grand Parkway before they could plat their
subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, a jury awarded the developers more than $2 million in
damages. That amount that now exceeds $3 million with interest,
according to attorney W. Allyn Hoaglund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STORY ENDS HERE &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
