<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seagram Set to Announce An Acquisition by Vivendi
</P>
<P>
   Seagram plans to announce Tuesday that it has agreed to be
acquired for $32 billion in stock by Vivendi, the French water
utility that is transforming itself into a telecommunications and
entertainment giant. The sale amounts to one of the largest media
deals ever and ends the Bronfman family's control over Seagram,
which Samuel Bronfman founded in 1924. Vivendi hopes to tap into
Seagram's library of films and music and distribute them over its
mobile telephone network in France and through its Internet portal
and pay-television company.
</P>
<P>
   IBM Builds Tiny Spacious Drive
</P>
<P>
   Plunging deeply into the world of pocket-sized personal
computing, IBM will introduce a version of its tiny microdrive hard
drive with a storage capacity of a billion bytes of information.
The new drive, which is the size of a book of matches, is a
milestone in the evolution of magnetic storage, executives said,
because it surpasses the same one-gigabyte barrier the company's
original refrigerator-sized 3380 hard drive surmounted in 1980s.
Shares of IBM rose $6.375, to $120.125.
</P>
<P>
   FTC Clears Pfizer-Warner Deal
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission cleared Pfizer's $90.2 billion
acquisition of Warner-Lambert after the companies agreed to divest
drugs for depression and Alzheimer's disease. They will also sell
one of two, competing over-the-counter lice medications.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Leads Dow and Nasdaq Higher
</P>
<P>
   Intel drove the Dow Jones industrial average and the Nasdaq
composite index higher. The Dow rose 108.54 points, or 1 percent,
to 10,557.84, while the Nasdaq advanced 129.27 points, or 3.4
percent, to 3,989.83. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index also
climbed, up 21.54 points, or 1.5 percent, to 1,486.00.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant Says Ernst Knew of Fraud
</P>
<P>
   Cendant contended in a court filing that the accounting firm
Ernst &AMP; Young knew of widespread fraud at CUC International, a
predecessor to Cendant, by 1997 and chose to help the fraud along
rather than expose it. Ernst &AMP; Young immediately responded by
attributing the fraud in part to Cendant's current chief executive,
Henry R. Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T in $3.3 Billion Wireless Deal
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T agreed to pay $3.3 billion in cash for wireless telephone
systems in Houston, San Diego and San Francisco to expand its
wireless telecommunications business.
</P>
<P>
   A Nasdaq Sibling Opens in Japan
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese offshoot of Nasdaq began trading eight stocks in a
technically smooth but low-volume start in the first attempt by a
stock exchange to go global. ``It's going to take a bit of time to
really unfold in its full form, but it's going to succeed,'' said
Frank Zarb, chairman of the National Association of Securities
Dealers, which runs the Nasdaq market in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   State Law on Myanmar Struck Down
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court unanimously struck down a Massachusetts law
aimed at boycotting companies that do business in Myanmar, formerly
Burma. The ruling was a victory for the oil company Unocal, which
has been courting controversy by doing business in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule Set in Microsoft Appeal
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court dismissed a government argument that it
lacked jurisdiction in the Microsoft antitrust case and set a
fast-paced schedule for reviewing Microsoft's request that the
judges block a lower-court order restricting its conduct. But if
the trial judge asks the Supreme Court to take the case directly,
the schedule would be suspended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
