<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-VALENTINO-FASHION-NYT     06-19 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALENTINO-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHEIK OF CHIC AND SO PERFECT, PERFECT, PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To give an idea just how perfect Valentino, the Roman
designer, is, two people, both Americans who don't wish their names
to be used, tell a similar story involving a hair dryer. Evidently,
when Valentino and his business partner, Giancarlo Giammetti, were
moored off Capri last summer in Valentino's 152-foot yacht, T.M.
Blue One, there was a lot of coifing going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them would jump in the water for a swim, come back out,
and suddenly you'd hear a blow-dryer going, `Bzzzzzzz,''' said one
of the observers, who was on a boat nearby. ``In Capri, you're
either wet from the water or from the heat. It's impossible to look
your best all the time. But all day long, you'd hear the sound of a
blow-dryer coming from their boat. `Bzzzzzzz.' Ten times a day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect'' was also the word Barry Diller, the media mogul and
a guest at the party Giammetti gave last Wednesday night at the
Four Seasons, used to describe what it's like to be in one of
Valentino's homes (Capri, Gstaad, London, Rome, New York, Paris) or
on his yacht, where everything _ from the Turkish towels to the
delicious food to the mix of guests and even the uniforms of the
staff _ is perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects a remarkable level of discipline,'' Diller said.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect was certainly the impression Valentino hoped to give
when he received me one morning last week in his Fifth Avenue
apartment, whose decorator style, by Peter Marino _ French
commodes, oil paintings, object upon object, all surrounded by
yards of brown silk gingham on the walls _ might be summed up as
Continental fancy-casual. Not a hair was out of place as Valentino
entered the room, settled into a chair and turned on the warmth
like a rotisserie lamp.
</P>
<P>
   As Giammetti said to me afterward: ``We can be having a fight _
and our fights are not fights, they are dramas, with broken things.
But suddenly you arrive, and he's'' _ Giammetti lowered a hand in
front of his face _ ``a mask.''
</P>
<P>
   Giammetti, who was 21 when he met Valentino Garavani, then 28,
in 1960, conceded that such immaculate composure was a useful
quality in the fashion business, where image is everything. ``But
sometimes,'' he said, ``I imagine people would also like to scream
and say what they think.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Valentino's 40th year in fashion, and his achievement in
a pantheon of glamorous self-made designers who came along in the
go-go years of fashion, when the truly swell did set the pace, was
acknowledged here last week in the usual ways.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Katherine Betts, editor in chief of Harper's Bazaar,
gave him a dinner. Carolina Herrera, who wore his clothes in the
1970s before she wore her own designs, followed on Wednesday with a
cocktail party at her Manhattan town house. Everybody was there:
Dominick Dunne; Judy Peabody; Pat Buckley; Henry and Louise
Grunwald; Annette de la Renta; Graydon Carter, the editor of Vanity
Fair; Patrick McCarthy, the editor of Women's Wear Daily; and C.Z.
Guest, who vividly recalled giving Valentino a pair of her riding
chaps after he had raved about how chic they were.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Council of Fashion Designers of America gave
him its Lifetime Achievement Award and, of course, there was the
dinner at the Four Seasons, where Valentino, his right arm in a red
sling from a fall at his house in France, moved from cheek to
powdered cheek. He seemed tanner than he had that morning, when
amid the oil paintings and decorator checks, he described his ideal
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all,'' he said with a smile, ``you have to wake up
and look at yourself in the mirror and say, `I'm not really so
bad.' I realize more and more that when you start your day in a
good mood, things go a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, reflecting on what seemed even to him to be a very
blossomy Barbara Cartland sentiment, and went on: ``You know, I
don't like to go out so much anymore. I love to see friends. I love
to have little dinners.''
</P>
<P>
   This seemed surprising coming from a man with homes in five
countries who lives lavishly and despite a reputation in the
industry for working hard and maintaining one of the best couture
ateliers in Europe, appears to be constantly playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``No! No! Totally the opposite,'' Valentino exclaimed. ``In
Rome, nobody invites me anymore because I always regret. Regret,
regret, regret!'' (Valentino tends to speak in triplicate.)
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``No, I love to stay with my dogs. I live a very,
very cozy life. I have this home in France, and I love to go to see
the garden, to walk and to think. I'm a very sensitive person, you
know.''
</P>
<P>
   It was while rescuing a dog at this house in May that Valentino
dislocated his shoulder. He was walking down a muddy slope when one
of his pugs came under attack by a swan, and he fell as he went to
the dog's aid. Nerve damage in the arm still gives him trouble, and
he has been seeing a specialist here.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Valentino is one of the last embodiments of jet-set
glamour. His designs _ the precisely tailored suits and coats, the
pin-tucked blouses and entrance-making columns _ have always struck
women as pretty and men as sexy, and rarely more than in the
high-spending 1980s, when Women's Wear Daily labeled Valentino
``the Sheik of Chic'' (though the paper's editor at the time, John
Fairchild, could needle him, too).
</P>
<P>
   One can't help wondering who among Val's gals left the deepest
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want some names?'' he asked. He clasped his hands together
and said, ``I have to say, not because she made me famous in the
United States, but for me Jackie Kennedy was one of the icons.'' He
looked thoughtful. ``You look like her.''
</P>
<P>
   I wondered if Valentino had had too much sun.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly added the qualifier, ``around the eyes,'' and then
returned to his recollections in a purring voice: ``Jackie did a
wonderful thing for my career. So did Babe Paley and Jayne
Wrightsman. So many, many, many ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   At the awards party given by the Council of Fashion Designers of
America, Carolina Herrera was asked if after all these years of
knowing Valentino, she could really say she knew him at all. ``Ah,
that's a tricky question,'' she said with a smile. ``He's very
clever. I think he only lets people know what he wants them to
know. He's always the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say he is predictable. In fact, he told a story
that says a great deal about what lies beneath the smooth corona of
hair and the Caraceni suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, arriving at the airport in Rome, I saw outside the
most terrible dog,'' he said. ``All dirty, not able to walk. I said
to my people, `Let's take the dog home in the car.'''
</P>
<P>
   The designer, who also has three pugs and two French poodles,
named the dog Stella. ``She's now the queen of the house,'' he
said, beaming.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you have to like a man who loves animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
