<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8825 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-EGAN-INSTALL-ART-1     06-19 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EGAN-INSTALL-ART-1020&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIESTS AND POLITICIANS FILL ST. PATRICK'S FOR EGAN'S
INSTALLATION 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Five weeks after bidding farewell to Cardinal John
O'Connor, New York's rich and powerful returned to St. Patrick's
Cathedral on Monday to see his successor, Edward Michael Egan,
installed as New York's ninth archbishop, in a ceremony reflecting
many of the elements that will inevitably shaped his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Egan's consecration, which began with a vespers service attended
by 2,700 Roman Catholics on Sunday evening, culminated in Monday's
far more elaborate Mass for 4,000, with eight American cardinals,
18 archbishops, nearly 100 bishops and 900 priests in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand were Hillary Rodham Clinton, the first lady, and
her rival for the Senate, Rep. Rick Lazio, Gov. George Pataki,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, former Mayors David Dinkins and Ed Koch,
and Justice Anthony Scalia of the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, coming five weeks to the hour after O'Connor's
funeral, seemed to complete a transition that began with the
cardinal's protracted struggle with brain cancer. The new
archbishop began to put his personal stamp on his service in New
York on Monday, with his personal selection of Mozart's and
Beethoven's most majestic works to guide the Mass of his
consecration, with readings offered in Spanish and English in
acknowledgment of the archdiocese's ever-more multicultural face,
and with a his homily stressing his role as a teacher of faith and
values.
</P>
<P>
   The pageant was, inevitably, stirring. More than 1,000 priests
and bishops wore white for the occasion, making the lengthy
procession from the Catholic Center on First Avenue to St.
Patrick's seemed almost like a white banner unfurled between the
administrative and spiritual hearts of the New York archdiocese,
shepherd to some 2.4 million Catholics in Manhattan, the Bronx and
Staten Island, and in seven counties north of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly, the priests in attendance had hair the color of
the white robes, a sign of how swiftly the clergy in New York is
aging. The average age of priests in the archdiocese is over 60,
and of 851 diocesan priests in New York, nearly 250 are retired or
otherwise inactive. Egan's success in recruiting young men for the
priesthood while he was bishop of Bridgeport, Conn., is believed to
have played a role in the pope's decision to name him to head the
church in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop himself wore a gold, green and red stole over his
off-white surplice, covered with a pectoral cross from a young man
who became a priest under Egan's guidance and then died soon after
of leukemia. The archbishop's appearance at the back doors of St.
Patrick's shortly after 2 p.m. brought not so much a round, as wave
upon wave, of applause as he strode smiling down the center aisle,
with the applause cresting when he reached the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps mindful of the enormous task ahead, not just in
recruiting but in reorganizing an archdiocese that has undergone
vast demographic changes in recent decades, the new archbishop
seemed more daunted than delighted through much of his consecration
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   His homily, which likened the Basilica of Saints John and Paul
in Rome to the church in New York, did not wander off into comic
asides, and the new archbishop smiled little. One noteworthy
exception came as Renee Fleming sang Mozart's Exsultate Jubilate,
when the archbishop closed his eyes and swayed for a moment, as if
transported by the soprano's strong, clear voice.
</P>
<P>
   Egan noted that the basilica dates from the fourth century, and
was built on top of the house in which the saints lived. The saints
had refused to offer sacrifices to pagan gods, and were executed by
the emperor Julian in 361. The archbishop said he loved the
basilica because ``it sums up for me what parishes and dioceses are
all about. We are communities that are built on uncompromising
acceptance of all that the Lord has revealed. This is our
foundation. Our strength is grounded in our faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishop also made a plea for social justice, and against
discrimination, abortion and euthanasia, drawing spontaneous and
sustained applause. ``May we allow the sick and disabled to be
neglected?'' he asked. ``May we stand idly by while the being
within the mother is killed, even though no one has ever been able
to prove that it is other than a human being with an inalienable
right to life? May we look the other way when the elderly are put
to death because someone questions the quality of their life?''
</P>
<P>
   The new archbishop, a canon lawyer and classical pianist, made
his mark in Bridgeport by rescuing the diocese from desperate
financial straits, in part by successful fund-raising among the
wealthy and corporate donors. Egan eagerly pumped the hands of VIPs
in the front rows, but also dashed straight out the back doors of
the Cathedral, as the chorus of Beethoven's Ninth, played from the
Cathedral over loudspeakers, filled Fifth Avenue. There, he went
straight up to the police barricades, holding high his crozier, and
began shaking the hands of well-wishers with his free hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across the street,'' an aide prompted the archbishop. There,
hundreds had stood throughout the service, straining through the
honking horns and passing buses to hear the service through
loudspeakers on the cathedral's facade. Many were tourists or
passers-by who stopped when they recognized what was happening.
Others said they made it a point to be as near as possible to their
new church leader, even if it meant standing behind a police
barricade.
</P>
<P>
   Egan swung around, looked up and waved to the onlookers across
the street. That brought a round of cheering and applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's beautiful, even though I'm not inside,'' said
Felicita Santiago, 63, of Queens. ``I'm not inside, but I feel like
I'm a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Whittier, of the Upper East Side of Manhattan, was
telling herself as she left the cathedral, ``This is so exciting.
This is so exciting.'' Asked why, she said, ``It's so exciting
because we have a new archbishop to replace Cardinal O'Connor, who
we loved so much.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   She said she was impressed by the diversity of the service,
which alternated English and Spanish readings and offered texts in
both languages. The Mass also featured a prayer in Portuguese,
Creole, Vietnamese, Russian and other languages.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx borough president, Fernando Ferrer, said that Egan's
message and his Spanish came across well. ``I told him his Spanish
was pretty good,'' Ferrer said, adding that he enjoyed the homily
even though it focused more on Rome than on the Bronx. ``He made, I
thought, a very interesting connection between Rome and New York,
and his message was about the foundation of our faith. I thought it
was very appropriate and very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer sat in the third row of pews, beside three of his likely
opponents in next year's Democratic primary for mayor _ the public
advocate, Mark Green; the city comptroller, Alan Hevesi, and
Speaker Peter Vallone of City Council. Vallone said that he
attended Mass every day and that he explained the Mass to his
political rivals, Hevesi and Green. ``They were very, very
respectful,'' he said. ``When I go to a synagogue, they do the same
for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
