<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SAATCHI-AD-COLUMN-NYT     06-19 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAATCHI-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: PUBLICIS PLANS ACQUISITION OF SAATCHI &AMP; SAATCHI 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Publicis SA, which last month lost out to the WPP Group in an
effort to buy Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc., plans to buy Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi,
the British agency company descended from the empire of the
acquisitive Saatchi brothers, for at least $1.5 billion in stock,
advertising executives close to the deal said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi unexpectedly disclosed Monday that its
executives had been approached to begin discussions that could
result in an offer for the agency, the world's 11th largest in
terms of billings and revenue. Though the terms of the proposed
deal were not disclosed and the potential acquirer was not
identified, shares of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi climbed 27 percent in
London, giving the agency company a market value of more than $1.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising executives close to the deal said that Publicis
would acquire Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi for $1.5 billion to $1.6 billion in
stock. The deal would significantly increase the Publicis presence
in the United States, the world's largest advertising market.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Levy, the chairman and chief executive of Publicis _
which has a worldwide ranking of eighth in billings and ninth in
revenue _ scheduled a news conference in Paris for Tuesday morning
on a topic he declined to discuss. Levy is expected to lead the
merged company.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition would be further evidence of the growing appeal
of independent agency companies as the consolidation of the
advertising industry that began six years ago continues at a
break-neck pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increasing globalization of brand marketing is
accelerating due to the Web,'' said Leland Westerfield, an analyst
with PaineWebber in New York. ``Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi could probably
operate favorably on its own, but agencies need to grow on a global
basis to serve key clients.''
</P>
<P>
   The pending acquisition of Y &AMP; R, based in New York, by WPP,
based in London, would create the world's biggest agency company in
both categories. A hook-up with Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi as a kind of
consolation prize for Publicis would create the fifth-largest
agency company in billings and revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``WPP and Y &AMP; R took the gloves off in terms of the size of the
deals,'' said Michael Russell Jr., an analyst at Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter in New York. ``Now we're talking about bigger names.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months ago, this would have been hard to accept,'' he
added, referring to a combination of Publicis with Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi. ``Now it's `Of course.'''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen at both agency companies declined to discuss the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can say is that we received an approach that may or may
not result in a merger offer,'' said Richard Walters at Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi in London, adding: ``I can't say any more. Watch this
space.''
</P>
<P>
   His counterpart at Publicis, Seth Goldschlager, said he would
not comment on ``market speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, there is no similar inhibition among industry
analysts and deal makers, who relished discussing what might become
of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the ones that had to go,'' said Abbott Jones,
managing director at AdMedia Partners in New York, which
specializes in transactions involving agencies and media companies.
``There aren't that many left.''
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi and Publicis are among six independent agency
companies that have been consistently identified by analysts as
ready to buy or be bought: the others are the Cordiant
Communications Group, Grey Advertising, Havas Advertising and True
North Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mega-agencies are in a wonderful position to handle the
business of megaclients,'' said Alan Gottesman, who follows
advertising for West End Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Though Publicis has already acquired several American agencies,
including Fallon, Hal Riney &AMP; Partners, the Evans Group and
Frankel, owning Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi will offer additional
opportunities to work with blue-chip marketers like General Mills,
Hewlett-Packard and Johnson &AMP; Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would require the blessings of giant clients of Saatchi
&AMP; Saatchi like Procter &AMP; Gamble and Toyota, which make up more than
a third of the agency company's billings, by Jones' estimate. There
could be some difficulties on that front because agencies now owned
by Publicis work for competitors of those companies like L'Oreal,
General Motors and Renault.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major clients dictate the marriage partner,'' Jones said.
``Look to the clients and you have the possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal will move forward, he added, if the merged agency
company ``can handle P &AMP; G and Toyota without getting in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi was founded by Maurice Saatchi and his
brother, Charles, and won widespread recognition for its ads that
helped bring Margaret Thatcher and the Conservative Party to power
in Britain. The agency grew rapidly during the 1980s with a spate
of deals.
</P>
<P>
   The debt from those deals, poorly received plans to expand
beyond advertising and the global recession all combined to deeply
wound Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi during the early and mid 1990s. That
enabled two American agency companies, the Interpublic Group of
Companies and the Omnicom Group, to race ahead by making
acquisitions of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interpublic and Omnicom have had 10 years of practice in
getting it right,'' Gottesman at West End Communications said.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi's recovery from its missteps was hampered by a
bitter dispute that emerged between the Saatchi brothers and the
agency company's board, which led to their departure at the end of
1994. As they formed their own agency, M&AMP;C Saatchi, Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi was renamed Cordiant PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Cordiant was ``de-merged'' to form two
separate agency companies, Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi and Bates Worldwide,
later renamed the Cordiant Communications Group. Cordiant
Communications shares also climbed Monday in London, rising 12.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi disclosure ``identifies the value of
Cordiant'' to investors, said Andy Boland, investor relations
director at Cordiant Communications in London, as the number of
independent agency companies of their size keeps dwindling. Saatchi
&AMP; Saatchi and Cordiant Communications each own 50 percent of Zenith
Media, a worldwide media services and research agency.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi has recently been selling interests in units
outside its core agency like Siegel &AMP; Gale, a corporate identity
consulting company now known as Siegelgale.com; and Cliff Freeman &AMP;
Partners, a creatively focused shop in New York. The trade
publication PR Week reported last month that the Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
public relations agency, Rowland Worldwide, would be sold to
Edelman Public Relations Worldwide in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The 27 percent increase Monday in the price of shares of Saatchi
&AMP; Saatchi marked the largest single gain since it began trading
separately from Cordiant in December 1997. In trading Monday on the
New York Stock Exchange, the American depository shares for Saatchi
&AMP; Saatchi climbed $7.6875, or 30.3 percent, to $33.0625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
