<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8828 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER20-COX     06-19 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PRAYER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High court rules on student-led prayers
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The U.S. Supreme Court ruled Monday that
student-initiated prayers before crowds at public school football
games is unconstitutional and went so far as to write the majority
decision in a way that could bar such prayers from graduations,
school assemblies or any other public school-sponsored event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a far-reaching decision,'' said Will Harrell,
executive director of the American Civil Liberties Union in Texas.
``It effectively puts an end to student-initiated prayer at any
school-sponsored event.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's 6-3 decision that the pregame prayers
violate the separation of church and state is a result of a dispute
between two Santa Fe, Texas, families that wanted the prayers
banned and the Santa Fe Independent School District, which claimed
it was a free speech issue. The Santa Fe families _ one Mormon, the
other Roman Catholic _ were represented by the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dangerous opinion,'' said Kelly Shackelford of the
Christian-sponsored Liberty Legal Institute and co-counsel for the
Santa Fe school district.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is now beginning to censor the religious speech of
private citizens _ for the first time in U.S. history,'' he said.
``This is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In the majority opinion, Justice John Paul Stevens wrote:
``School sponsorship of a religious message is impermissible
because it sends the ancillary message to members of the audience
who are nonadherents that they are outsiders, not full members of
the political community, and an accompanying message to adherents
that they are insiders, favored members of the political community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delivery of such a message over the school's public
address system by a speaker representing the student body, under
the supervision of school faculty and pursuant to a school policy
that explicitly and implicitly encourages public prayer is not
properly characterized as private speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens was joined by Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy,
David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Beyer in the
court's most definitive ruling on school prayers since public
school prayers were declared unconstitutional in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the first Supreme Court ruling involving school
prayer since 1992 when justices declared faculty-organized and
clergy-led prayers were unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court took up the Santa Fe case after the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans ruled against public
prayers at football games. That court also said graduation prayers
could continue if they did not mention a specific diety.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court declined to take up the graduation-ceremony
dispute. However, the majority's opinion was so tightly written
that its tentacles put school district's on notice that public
student prayers at school events that favor one religion seem to
imply school-supported favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe decision was blasted by Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist who wrote the minority opinion. He was joined by Clarence
Thomas and Antonin Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even more disturbing than its holding is the tone of the
court's opinion,'' Rehnquist said. ``It bristles with hostility to
all things religious in public life.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General John Cornyn, who argued in favor of the
school prayers during the Supreme Court hearing in March, said he
agreed with Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed in the court's decision,'' Cornyn said. ``I
agree with the dissenting justices that the court's opinion
`distorts existing precedent.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the probable Republican presidential
nominee, joined the attorney generals of nine other states who
wrote the Supreme Court, urging justices to allow the prayers and
not prohibit a student's right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the constitutionally guaranteed right of all
students to express their faith freely and participate in
voluntary, student-led prayer,'' Bush said Monday after the court
decision.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20 Texas school districts, including Leander, adopted
resolutions last year expressing disapproval of a ban against
student-initiated, student-led prayers over the public address
systems at football games.
</P>
<P>
   Marian Ward, the Santa Fe student who challenged the appeals
court ruling on free speech grounds, and her attorney, Kelly
Coghlan, could not be reached for comment. Ward's father is pastor
of a local Baptist church.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe school district was supported by religious right
leaders who condemned the Supreme Court's decision. Also coming out
against the court was the Council on American-Islamic relations,
which said the increase in juvenile violence, sexual promiscuity
and drug use at schools shows ``there is clearly a need for more
student-sponsored spiritual guidance, not less.''
</P>
<P>
   But Debbie Mason, a mother and spokeswoman for the two families,
whose names were sealed by the court, said she ``was so happy my
whole body was shaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who calls herself ``an American Baptist,'' and a handful
of other Santa Fe families that supported the lawsuit were
unpopular among their neighbors. The two families asked to remain
anonymous because they feared ostracization from their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In May, three Santa Fe high school students were arrested for
threatening to hang a 13-year-old Jewish boy, who was an
eighth-grader in the Santa Fe middle school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we were worried about,'' Mason said of showing
preferential treatment of one faith over another. ``The way the
(Santa Fe) school board was going, they were pitting student
against student.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country was founded on the right to pray or not to pray.
If you want to a Baptist or an atheist, no one has the right to
stand up ... and tell the kids to bow their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of Santa Fe's seven-member school board said Monday the
predominantly Baptist district does not foster a climate of
religious intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, Santa Fe school board member Robin
Clayton warned that the mostly Baptist district cannot control what
students or others say on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spontaneous things happen, don't they?'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin B. Cominsky, regional director of the Anti-Defamation
League which supported the court decision, said schools should use
the ruling to foster religious understanding. ``This is a teaching
opportunity to say `This is the law of the land and while some of
us don't agree it is something that protects everyone's religion,'
'' he added. ``The wall against church and state is a sturdy wall
and must be sturdy to protect everyone's freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect prayers to stop at the Legislature, city
council meetings, or even school board meetings. The new ruling has
no effect on government entities and in the Bible belt it is
unlikely they will re-evaluate their procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Lt. Gov. Rick Perry is presiding over the Senate
you can expect there to be prayer at the start of each day when the
Legislature is in session,'' said Eric Bearse, the spokesman for
Perry.
</P>
<P>
   In November, a Texas Poll showed that eight out of 10 surveyed
residents support public school student prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Mason said she doesn't even expect the Supreme Court ruling to
close the chapter on Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one part of it has ended, but I don't think the school
board is going to bow to the Supreme Court,'' Mason said. ``I
expect them to come out and say, ``We only listen to God.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
