<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8829 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-SEAGRAM-VIVENDI-ART-N     06-19 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAM-VIVENDI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH COMPANY REPORTED LIKELY TO BUY SEAGRAM; DEAL PUT AT $34
BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SEAGRAM-MARKETPLACE, VIVENDI-UNIVERSAL,
BRONFMAN-PROFILE) 
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make one-time purchases by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seagram Co., the spirits and entertainment company that includes
legendary names like Absolut Vodka, Chivas Regal, Universal Studios
and Polgram Records, will announce on Tuesday that it has agreed to
be acquired for about $34 billion in stock by Vivendi SA, a French
water utility that is transforming itself into a telecommunications
and entertainment giant.
</P>
<P>
   The sale amounts to one of the largest media deals ever and ends
the Bronfman family's control over Seagram, which Samuel Bronfman
took over in 1928. It has remained one of the nation's most
powerful liquor companies even as Edgar Bronfman Jr., a grandson of
Samuel Bronfman, began remaking the company into a media player in
1995, by first acquiring MCA, parent of Universal Pictures, which
produced American icons like ``E.T.'' and ``The Sting.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the nation's six major film studios, Universal also owns
a television production company, theme parks and a music business.
Just last year, Bronfman expanded Seagram's holdings by buying
Polygram, making Seagram the nation's largest record company in
terms of sales. That purchase reflected Bronfman's conviction that
music was a growth business.
</P>
<P>
   In the new company, which will be called Vivendi-Universal and
be based in Paris, Bronfman will become vice-chairman, with the
music and Internet businesses reporting to him. Vivendi executives
do not see the liquor business as part of the company's future and
plans to sell all of it, or at least a stake in it.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi hopes to leverage Seagram's library of films and music
by distributing it over its mobile telephone network in France, as
well as through its ambitious pan-European Internet portal, called
Vizzavi, and pay-television company, Canal Plus, of which it owns
49 percent and which it now plans to buy outright.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is a bet by both Vivendi and Seagram that by combining
popular content with a powerful distribution system, especially the
next generation of wireless Internet services in Europe, it can
create a company worth more combined than by working separately.
</P>
<P>
   However, there were some skeptics on Monday who felt that
Vivendi was unlikely to cull great benefits in merging. One analyst
who requested anonymity said that while Canal Plus was getting use
of the Universal Pictures film library to fill its programming
needs and Vivendi believed it could download music digitally via
cell phones, ``Maybe you are accelerating that synergy, but I think
it is a small niche,'' this person said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, a major payoff is at least several years away.
</P>
<P>
   The deal needs approval from the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi's purchase would mean that two major film studios are
now under foreign ownership. Sony bought Columbia Pictures
Industries in 1989. Matsushita Electrical Industrial acquired MCA
in 1990, owning it for five years, but sold it to Seagram.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest in a series of aggressive media mergers
that have seen the entertainment world consolidate into a handful
of major entities. The first wave, which began in the 1980s,
included mergers of movie and television production with companies
that could distribute their programs on hardware or cable or TV _
Sony and Columbia, Time and Warner, Viacom and Paramount, and then
CBS, and Walt Disney Co. and Capital Cities/ABC. Seagram's purchase
of MCA was unusual because Seagram was not a media company, though
it believed it brought international marketing expertise to MCA.
</P>
<P>
   The second wave of deals has included AOL's pending purchase of
Time-Warner, in which technology companies have begun seeking to
own ``content'' providers such as major film companies.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi's deal fits more directly in that category. Somewhat
like Seagram under the control of Edgar Bronfman, Vivendi has
developed under the leadership of Jean-Marie Messier, the French
company's chairman, into a holding company of sorts with a
hodgepodge of old-and new-economy businesses.
</P>
<P>
   While Vivendi very much remains a water distribution, waste
management and construction company _ more than half of its $40
billion in revenue come from those divisions _ Messier has been
steadily building an impressive stable of telecommunication and
entertainment properties.
</P>
<P>
   Vivendi now owns a 24.5 percent stake in the satellite
television business, British Sky Broadcasting PLC, which is
controlled by Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. It owns 59 percent of
Cegetel, which operates SFR, the second largest wireless telephone
network in France. Messier, also acquired Havas, the publishing and
advertising company, and last year increased Vivendi's stake in
Canal Plus by 15 percent, to 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Messier's most important deal to date was a move in
February to create an Internet portal with Vodafone Airtouch PLC,
the world's largest wireless telephone operator. That deal sealed
the fate of Vodafone's record $183 billion hostile bid for
Mannesmann and gave Messier an important ally in expanding his
wireless operations, which so far remain mostly in France.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the merger of Seagram and Vivendi would create a
company with a combined revenue of $65 billion, though the sale of
the liquor business and Vivendi's water business, which includes
U.S. Filter, would reduce that holding and trim the company into a
purer media business.
</P>
</TEXT>
