<SLUG> BC-TUITION-BACKLASH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HCC POLICY TO HELP UNDOCUMENTED IMMIGRANTS DRAWS COMPLAINTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EDWARD HEGSTROM 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Houston Community College trustees thought they were
doing a good deed last month when they agreed to lower tuition for
undocumented immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Now the policy has created a backlash from international
students with educational visas attending HCC.
</P>
<P>
   International students, who must continue to pay higher
out-of-district tuition, say they are being punished for obeying
the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crazy thing,'' said Harry Sudarma, a Baptist
minister from Indonesia who counsels Indonesian students at HCC.
</P>
<P>
   ``These students come to me and say they are better off being
illegal,'' said Sudarma. ``As a pastor, I have to tell them not to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehbi Rezai, 20, a student from Europe, added, ``I'm all for
everybody having an opportunity to get an education, but it should
cost the same for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   HCC administrators say there is a difference between
undocumented immigrants who have lived in Houston for years and
international students who come here temporarily to study.
</P>
<P>
   ``These (undocumented immigrants) are students whose parents
brought them here, sometimes with no choice,'' said Chancellor Ruth
Burgos-Sasscer of the HCC System. ``They are kids who are going to
be here in Houston, so if we don't educate them, we're going to end
up supporting them one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that children in the United
States must be allowed access to education through 12th grade,
regardless of their legal status. But there is no guarantee that
undocumented immigrants can receive a college education.
</P>
<P>
   HCC previously charged undocumented immigrants the same tuition
as out-of-district residents and international students _ about
$1,500 per term instead of $500. Under the new policy, undocumented
immigrants will be allowed to pay the lower fee.
</P>
<P>
   The board will also consider a clarification to the policy at
its Thursday meeting. The HCC administration recommends in-district
tuition be limited to students who have attended a Houston high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Some international students were angry when learning of the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike undocumented immigrants, international students typically
come to Houston to attend a college. Most arrive as adults carrying
legal student visas.
</P>
<P>
   HCC has more than 2,000 international students enrolled, third
highest total of any two-year college system in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Because of immigration rules, students must follow terms of
their visas or face being forced to return home.
</P>
<P>
   For example, students must take and receive credit for at least
12 credit hours per term. If they fail to meet that provision,
visas become invalid and students must return to their home country
to apply for a new student visa.
</P>
<P>
   HCC administrators tell dozens of students that they have no
choice but to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to go back to my country, and the trip cost me
$2,000,'' said Francisco Rojas, a Colombian student at HCC. ``I
would rather just lose my legal status.''
</P>
<P>
   Becoming illegal would not help students like Rojas if the HCC
board votes to limit reduced tuition to students who have gone to
local high schools.
</P>
<P>
   But it likely will not stop them from complaining about what
they see as an injustice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm paying three times as much tuition,'' Rojas said. ``It's
not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STORY ENDS HERE &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
