<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SECURITY-REPORT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials seek armed guards for treatment facility
 &HT;    By Pat Moore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUART, Fla _ Armed guards, light poles with criss-crossing
cables, observation towers and more razor wire were recommended
Monday as ways to prevent another escape from Florida's first
center for sexually violent predators in western Martin County.
</P>
<P>
   Top prison officials and the director of the Martin Treatment
Center, which is run by a private Pennsylvania company, criticized
the lack of security at the center, where a sex offender escaped
June 5 when a helicopter lowered inside the razor-wire fence.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush requested the reports after sex offender Steven
Whitsett jumped aboard a helicopter flown by his longtime friend,
Clifford Burkhart. The copter crashed about 100 yards from the
center and the two were captured after a 25-hour manhunt about 4
1/2 miles from the center.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after his escape, Whitsett told officials at the
Martin County Jail that he had planned the escape for two months.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan was to land the helicopter on the treatment
center's basketball court near the building, according to the
report by Robert Briody, executive director of the center operated
by Liberty Healthcare Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Briody criticized the design of the building _ a former minimum
security jail _ for contributing to the problems of housing the
sexual predators indefinitely under the Jimmy Ryce law.
</P>
<P>
   He also chastised the state for failing to complete security
improvements requested more than a year ago, such as installing
metal detectors, cameras, perimeter fence detection devices, fire
doors, lighting and paving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The limitations imposed by the Martin Treatment Center
physical plant promotes considerable idleness in a milieu where few
privileges can be suspended and a small outdoor recreation area
must be liberally used,'' riody wrote in his report detailing
Whitsett's escape.
</P>
<P>
   One treatment center employee was in the recreation yard with
about 40 sex offenders when Whitsett scaled a fence and jumped
aboard the hovering helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsett, he reported, was viewed by the staff as ``manipulative
and willing to challenge policy,'' but never engaged staff in angry
exchanges or opposed their authority.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment staff reported Whitsett was ``resistant, closed
and controlling'' and ``never took full responsibility for his
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   He regularly attended group therapy sessions, but his
participation was seldom genuine as he was resistant to treatment,
Briody reported.
</P>
<P>
   Briody also recommended hiring more staff to man the center,
which lacks adequate space for treatment rooms, offices and housing
units. The 105 sex offenders are housed about 14 to a room.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Thomas Crews, a top Department of Corrections
security administrator, also criticized security at the center in
the wake of Whitsett's escape.
</P>
<P>
   He also recommended guards outside the building be armed, cable
systems above the outdoor recreation field, barbed wire on the
building roof and improved lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Both men agreed the Liberty staff needs enhanced training and
that improved communication is vital among officials at Liberty,
the state prison system and the Department of Children and
Families, which oversees Liberty's $9 million contract to operate
the sex offender center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
