<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL LAW ON HATE CRIMES IS SCHEDULED FOR VOTE IN THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators of both parties condemned crimes based on
race, gender or sexual orientation as a dishonor to the nation
Monday in an emotional prelude to a vote scheduled for Tuesday on
creating a federal hate crimes statute.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., confident of passing the
legislation, called offenses like the killings of James Byrd Jr.
and Matthew Shepard ``modern-day lynchings that can easily
terrorize whole communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, the bill's chief sponsor, called it the necessary next
step in civil rights legislation, representing ``a continuum of
this nation attempting to define what this nation ought to be, that
is a nation that is going to be free from discrimination, hatred
and bigotry.'' The bill would allow the federal government to
prosecute crimes motivated by race, gender and sexual orientation
that are now outside its reach.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Gordon H. Smith of Oregon, the bill's leading Republican
backer, pointedly addressed conservative Christians. He said they
had told him they feared that any legislation favorable to gays
threatened the American family. To answer that, he quoted from
Scripture the story of the woman who had committed adultery, when
Jesus said, ``He that is without sin among you, let him cast the
first stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said, ``Adultery is a far greater threat to the American
family than homosexuality,'' and if an adulterer could be forgiven
by Jesus, ``it is time to say to the gay community, `We don't agree
with you on everything, but I can help you on many things.'''
</P>
<P>
   The only opposition to the Kennedy-Smith bill came from Sen.
Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, who heads the Judiciary Committee. He said
no one had shown that federal intervention was necessary and that
the Supreme Court's recent decisions on federalism foreshadowed a
ruling that Congress had no business making federal crimes of what
were basically state offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he believed that ``hate-related violence is to be
abhorred.'' He added, ``Nobody can deny that hate crimes are
occurring. I want to get rid of them as much as anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said he might eventually be persuaded that a new federal
crime law was needed. But he said all the Senate should do was to
demand a report on the effectiveness of existing law enforcement
efforts on hate crimes and to provide grants to states to help them
with such cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy-Smith bill would also provide grants to states to
help pay for prosecutions. But its major provision would be to
create a federal offense of crimes involving bodily injury based on
race, color, religion, national origin, gender, sexual orientation
or disability. Kennedy stressed that the federal government would
act only if states approved, or if they failed to pursue a case.
</P>
<P>
   Existing federal law deals only with crimes based on race,
religion and national origin, and only in cases where the victims
had been seeking to exercise a federally protected right. Those
include school enrollment, jury service, traveling in interstate
commerce and using a place of public accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Senate adopts the measure, a direct vote on it in
the House is no more than a remote possibility, because of
Republican opposition. But strong White House support could force
House leaders to accept it in the wrap-up legislation needed to end
the session and let lawmakers go home to campaign for election.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard was a gay 21-year-old student who was beaten to death in
Laramie, Wyo., in October 1998. Earlier that year, Byrd, a
49-year-old black man, was dragged to his death in Japser, Texas.
The killers in both cases were convicted, but proponents of the
Kennedy-Smith proposal said the bill would have made it easier to
prosecute them and avoided financial burdens on local law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence that a new law was needed, Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich.,
cited not only the Shepard and Byrd killings, but also a series of
attacks on gay men in Michigan. In those cases, he said, the
prosecutions would have been stronger if the federal government had
been involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one united voice,'' Levin said, ``we must not only condemn
these acts of violence that terrorize Americans every day, we must
act against them. America's agenda will remain unfinished so long
as incidents like these occur regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., said the present law was ``way too
narrow'' and hate crimes were the equivalent of terrorism against a
group or community.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James M. Jeffords, R-Vt., said that for that reason,
``crimes motivated by hate are especially harmful.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard J. Durbin, D-Ill., said the Hatch argument was all
too familiar. ``It's not a federal issue,'' he said, was the attack
made on legislation to protect the rights of blacks, women and the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch complained that supporters of the legislation were just
``making political points here on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill was also supported by three more Democrats, Sens. Jack
Reed of Rhode Island, John B. Breaux of Louisiana and Harry Reid of
Nevada, the Democratic whip, who said, ``People should not be
killed because they are different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
