r s BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN     06-19 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG ARMS AIDING ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It was under the direction of former Anaheim
Angels scouting director Bob Fontaine that the club drafted
pitchers Jarrod Washburn, Brian Cooper and Seth Etherton. But it is
the current regime that is having its season saved by the three
young starters.
</P>
<P>
   With injuries to Ken Hill, Tim Belcher, Kent Bottenfield, Jason
Dickson and Kent Mercker, the Angels have had no choice but to dip
into their farm system for help, and they found it.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn was called up first, on May 10, and is 2-1 with a 3.92
ERA in seven starts. Cooper came next, on May 23, and is 2-2 with a
3.18 ERA in five starts. And finally Etherton, called up on May 26,
is 2-1 with a 5.20 ERA in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, they are 6-4 with a 4.02 ERA in 17 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have been sensational,'' manager Mike Scioscia
said. ``You look at the contribution they've made, in the tough
situation we're in, and it's one of the big reasons we're as close
to the top as we are. The kids have been very, very solid the last
two, three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher has returned to the rotation, and Bottenfield's expected
return Saturday will fill out the rotation to five. Hill and
Dickson are both working toward returning in the next couple of
weeks, and that's when Scioscia and his staff will have some
decisions to make.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia recently joked about going to a seven-man rotation, but
obviously that's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard for a long time about having too many starters for
one position being a good problem to have,'' Scioscia said. ``But
it's not easy to tell a guy who's doing his job, `I can only pick
five and this is who we're going with.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One possibility would be for Dickson to go to the bullpen when
he is ready. But Scioscia will not do that with Hill, meaning at
least one of the three will go. Of course, that is barring more
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton, Cooper and Washburn all realize their situation but
say it doesn't affect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about anything like that,'' Etherton said. ``I
have no control over that. All I can do is get outs and help our
team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Short hops: Bottenfield will throw a simulated game today, and
if all goes well he'll start Saturday against the Twins. He threw
80 pitches during a bullpen workout last Saturday. ... Tim Salmon
is hitting .339 in June to raise his season average to .290.
However, he's hitting just .200 (11 for 55) with runners in scoring
position for the season. ... Mo Vaughn and Troy Glaus are the only
Angels to play in all 68 games. They also are the only 20-homer duo
on the same team in the American League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
