   The following photos have moved with the latest installment of
the New York Times series and race relations slugged:
RACE-POLITICS:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT706) BAINBRIDGE ISLAND, Wash. -- June 19, 2000 --
RACE-POLITICS-6 --Many voters say that by putting a Chinese
immigrant's son and two descendants of slaves atop the governing
pyramid of the state, Washington has transcended race. But if the
old racial order, of whites always on top, has eroded, a more
complex one has replaced it. Ron Sims speaks to students at
Bainbridge Island High School. Earlier, he spoke to a mostly white
audience at Woodward Middle School on the island. (Andrea Mohin/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT705) BAINBRIDGE ISLAND, Wash. -- June 19, 2000 --
RACE-POLITICS-5 --Many voters say that by putting a Chinese
immigrant's son and two descendants of slaves atop the governing
pyramid of the state, Washington has transcended race. But if the
old racial order, of whites always on top, has eroded, a more
complex one has replaced it. Hundreds of white faces greeted Ron
Sims at Woodward Middle School on Bainbridge Island where he gave a
speech about race. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT704) SEATTLE -- June 19, 2000 -- RACE-POLITICS-4 -- Many
voters say that by putting a Chinese immigrant's son and two
descendants of slaves atop the governing pyramid of the state,
Washington has transcended race. But if the old racial order, of
whites always on top, has eroded, a more complex one has replaced
it. Gary Locke and Norm Rice debated in Seattle in the 1996
Democratic primary. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT703) SEATTLE -- June 19, 2000 -- RACE-POLITICS-3 -- Gov.
Gary Locke divides his time between his constituents and his
family. with his son, Dylan, in his arms, his wife, Mona Lee,
looking over his shoulder, and his father, Jimmie, rear, in the
kitchen of his brother's house. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT702) SEATTLE -- June 19, 2000 -- RACE-POLITICS-2 -- Many
