<P>
   Our report today also includes:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) PADUCAH, Ky. -- June 19, 2000 -- NUKE-ENRICHMENT -- Ever
since Richard Nixon proposed it in 1968, policy makers have talked
about having the federal government quit the business of enriching
uranium for nuclear power plants. It took decades but the Clinton
administraiton finally pulled it off two years ago, with Vice
President Al Gore claiming it as a victory for reinventing
government. But it may have come at the worst possible time.
Hundreds of storage tanks filled with depleted uranium near the
Lockheed Martin Energy Systems' Paducah Gaseus Diffusion Plant in
February, 1998. (Christopher Berkey/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- June 19, 2000 -- OBIT-MARCHAND -- Nancy
Marchand, the distinguished character actress who excelled at
playing wise and imperious authority figures _ newspaper
publishers, queens and mesdames _ and who achieved perhaps her
greatest fame as the domineering mother of a mob boss in the
television series ``The Sopranos,'' died on Sunday at her home in
Stratford, Conn., one day short of her 72nd birthday. She also had
a home in New York City. Marchand, left, and Schuyler Grant in the
play ``The Importance of Being Earnest'' at the Irish Repertory
Theater in 1996. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) GALAPAGOS ISLANDS -- June 19, 2000 -- SCI-GALAPAGOS-5 --
Evolution's paths endlessly fascinate students of the Galapagos.
Scientists will use gene studies to determine how closely this lava
heron is related to the striated or green herons of the islands.
(Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) GALAPAGOS ISLANDS -- June 19, 2000 -- SCI-GALAPAGOS-3 --
Plants and animals in the Galapagos evolve to fill niches.
Cannibalistic red lava crabs feed on each other when other foods
are scarce. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) GALAPAGOS ISLANDS -- June 19, 2000 -- SCI-GALAPAGOS-3 --
Plants and animals evolve to fill niches in the Galapagos. The
jawbone of a marine iguana bears trident-shaped teeth for
scratching algae from rocks. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK, top, ST. PETERSBURG, Russia -- June 19, 2000
-- GUGGENHEIM-HERMITAGE -- Two art institutions with visions of
expansion but strikingly different economic positions, the Solomon
R. Guggenheim Foundation, which includes the Guggenheim Museum,
top, and the State Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg, Russia, have
reached an agreement to share their collections, organize joint
exhibitions and help each other develop a worldwide network of
museums. (Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) ZAMBEZI RIVER VALLEY, Zimbabwe -- June 19, 2000 --
SCI-ELEPHANTS-REPEL -- Dr. Ferrel Loki Osborn loves elephants. But
he also loves the villagers of the Zambezi River Valley in northern
Zimbabwe, whose fields of corn, cotton, and banana crops have long
tempted elephants looking for a convenient midnight snack. Isborn
has devised a multi-pronged array of repellants, some of which
rural farmers can concoct themselves, all using capsaicin, the
chemical that puts the heat in hot peppers. Elephants in Zimbabwe
climb over an electric fence to get at crops. (Courtesy of Ferrel
Loki Osborn and Guy Parker/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEWPORT, R.I. -- June 19, 2000 -- COSTUME-INSTITUTE-2 --
The Metropolitan Museum of Art, which abruptly cancelled a Coco
Chanel retrospective last month, named its replacement Monday: the
White House fashions of Jacqueline Kennedy. The show, the largest
of the year for the Met's Costume Institute, whose opening night is
one of the social season's most glittery affairs, has been pushed
back from December to April. Jacqueline Kennedy prepares to toss
her wedding bouquet from the main staircase of Hammersmith Farm in
Newport, R.I., in 1953. The dress is planned to be used in the
exhibit. (The Kennedy Museum/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- June 19, 2000 -- COSTUME-INSTITUTE-1 --
The Metropolitan Museum of Art, which abruptly cancelled a Coco
Chanel retrospective last month, named its replacement Monday: the
White House fashions of Jacqueline Kennedy. The show, the largest
of the year for the Met's Costume Institute, whose opening night is
one of the social season's most glittery affairs, has been pushed
back from December to April. One of the gowns planned for display
is this gown worn by Jacqueline Kennedy which she wore at a White
House dinner on April 30, 1963. (Kennedy Library/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- June 19, 2000 -- NY-EGAN-INSTALL --
Archbishop Edward Egan is greeted by various members of the clergy
at the Mass of Installation at St. Patrick's Cathedral, Monday.
Egan celebrated his first Mass as archbishop of New York Monday
during an elaborate installation ceremony beneath the massive stone
arches and tall stained-glass windows of St. Patrick's Cathedral
and exhorted followers to fight racism, poverty and abortion.
(Richard Perry/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- June 19, 2000 -- SCI-BRODY-HEALTH -- Earlier
this month at a conference sponsored by the American Medical
Association, Dr. Stuart Levy, director of the Center for Adaptation
Genetics and Drug Resistance at Tufts University in Boston, voiced
serious concerns about the more than 700 antibacterial products now
crowding the marketplace. Levy said that the soaps are not killing
all bacteria but leaving behind those that are strong enough to
survive and multiply. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- June 19, 2000 -- RADCLIFFE-FAUST-BOS
-- Drew Gilpin Faust, the incoming dean of the Radcliffe Institute
For Advanced Study is in the vanguard of a small band of women who
are Civil War scholars of standing. ``What can be more interesting
than trying to figure out what made people kill each other?'' she
says. (Jay Premack/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- June 19, 2000 -- CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS
-- The 1997 wedding of Steven and Emily Shalansky is now a fond
photo-album memory, but as of last week the Massachusetts couple
was still waiting for much of the china their wedding guests
purchased for them three years ago. The Shalanskys hold the few
dishes they have received from Bloomingdales. (Tom Landers/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 19, 2000 -- NY-SCHOOLS-MULTILANGUAGE --
Edda Barros, left, translates for her parents Eduardo and Aura
Barros, during a meeting about her brother with Terri McCleary, a
speech therapist. Like millions of young children in immigrant
families, Edda is much more than a translator for first-generation
parents who speak little English. She not only translates the
language but also interprets American culture, customs and mores
for her parents. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) GALAPAGOS ISLANDS -- June 19, 2000 -- SCI-GALAPAGOS-2 --
Fauna and flora like marine iguanas on Fernandina left Charles
Darwin unimpressed. He wrote in his diary that Galapagos plants
``smell unpleasantly,'' and called the island lizards ``clumsy.''
Eventually, though, he realized they could show him how nature's
creatures evolve. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) GALAPAGOS ISLANDS -- June 19, 2000 -- SCI-GALAPAGOS-1 --
Fauna and flora like a masked booby on Floreana Island left Charles
Darwin unimpressed. He wrote in his diary that Galapagos plants
``smell unpleasantly,'' and called the island lizards ``clumsy.''
Eventually, though, he realized the animals could show him how
nature's creatures evolve. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PRINCETON, N.J. -- June 19, 2000 --
SCI-PHYSICS-RENAISSANCE -- After years of impasse, the study of
subatomic particles has been undergoing something of a renaissance.
A new generation of physicists is stretching its collective mind
and coming up with radical ideas about how the universe may be
constructed. Dr. Lisa Randall and Dr. Raman Sundrum have devised a
theory in which the universe is surrounded by a higher dimension,
this one infinite in size. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- June 19, 2000 -- SCI-MARS-ROCKET -- A new type
of rocket engine under development could halve the travel time
between Earth and Mars should NASA ever decide to send astronauts
to the Red Planet. NASA hopes Vasimr, as seen in this artist's
rendering, a rocket that utilizes radio waves and magnetic fields,
might someday be a way to Mars. (Rendering by NASA/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) OBOLENSK, Russia -- June 19, 2000 -- SCI-CLINTON-RUSSIA-2
-- At this rundown research complex where Soviet scientists once
secretly worked to turn disease into weapons, the Clinton
administration is taking what many consider a perilous gamble. The
administration has been financing cutting-edge research here and at
other institutes throughout the former Soviet Union by scientists
who only a decade ago manipulated genes to make deadly viruses and
bacteria even hardier and resistant to vaccines and antibiotics. A
view of the infamous building No. 1, where deadly pathogens were
studied and perfected as weapons. (Judith Miller/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) OBOLENSK, Russia -- June 19, 2000 -- SCI-CLINTON-RUSSIA
-- At this rundown research complex where Soviet scientists once
secretly worked to turn disease into weapons, the Clinton
administration is taking what many consider a perilous gamble. The
administration has been financing cutting-edge research here and at
other institutes throughout the former Soviet Union by scientists
who only a decade ago manipulated genes to make deadly viruses and
bacteria even hardier and resistant to vaccines and antibiotics. A
containment suit on display in a control room in Building No. 1.
(Judith Miller/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 19, 2000 -- SCI-ELEPHANTS-REPEL -- Dr.
Ferrel Loki Osborn loves elephants. But he also loves the villagers
of the Zambezi River Valley in northern Zimbabwe, whose fields of
corn, cotton, and banana crops have long tempted elephants looking
for a convenient midnight snack. Isborn has devised a multi-pronged
array of repellants, some of which rural farmers can concoct
themselves, all using capsaicin, the chemical that puts the heat in
hot peppers. Osborn at the New York Zoological Society. (Librado
Romero/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
