<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-COSTUME-INSTITUTE-ART     06-19 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTUME-INSTITUTE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTUME INSTITUTE WILL SHOW JACQUELINE KENNEDY'S WHITE HOUSE
CLOTHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Metropolitan Museum of Art, which abruptly
canceled a Coco Chanel retrospective last month, has decided on a
replacement for its grand, annual exhibition: the White House
fashions of Jacqueline Kennedy. The show, along with its opening
night gala to benefit the Met's Costume Institute, has been pushed
back from December to spring 2001, and so for the first time in 51
years the splashy fund-raiser sometimes known as ``the party of the
year'' will take place not during the winter social season, but
amid the spring one, on April 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Met backed out of a Chanel show last month after Karl
Lagerfeld, the label's designer, and Met officials disagreed over
how expansive Lagerfeld's role as curator would be. It had been
Lagerfeld's ambition to show the work of artists like Jenny Holzer
alongside the legendary suits and cocktail dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacqueline Kennedy: The White House Years'' is unlikely to
spark any similarly unconventional bursts of inspiration among
those who assemble it. Fashion insiders said they thought the
choice was a crowd-pleasing, humdrum one.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition will focus on what Kennedy referred to as her
state clothes, including the fawn coat and pillbox hat she wore for
President John F. Kennedy's inauguration on Jan. 20, 1961; the
Givenchy coat and dress she wore on an official visit to
Versailles, France; and outfits for a visit to India and Pakistan.
The 80 pieces will come from the John F. Kennedy Library and Museum
in Boston. The curator, Hamish Bowles, who is Vogue's European
editor at large, has been spending his recent days there.
</P>
<P>
   The Library has 65 to 70 outfits. Nearly all will be in the
exhibition, said Bowles, a collector and connoisseur of vintage
couture. He will cull the additional items from the archive's
stable of Kennedy's accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Holzer, director of communications at the Met, said it
was not the sudden change of program that caused the show to be
rescheduled. Nor is it the need to replace Chanel's promised $1.5
million in underwriting for the show and gala. ``Money is not the
issue,'' Holzer said. ``It's when we could do it in terms of
getting out a catalog concurrent with the show.'' The show will be
held not in the underground Costume Institute but upstairs in the
museum's Cantor Galleries.
</P>
<P>
   When rumors of a Kennedy show began a few weeks ago, a
representative from Courreges, a favorite label of Kennedy, called
the Met to discuss possible sponsorship. So far, the call has not
been answered, the representative said. Holzer said, ``The Met's
first priority was cementing an agreement for the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Met named the fashion historian Harold Koda as
the head of its Costume Institute, replacing Richard Martin, who
died last year. Koda is unable to work on the Kennedy show right
away, however, because he is assembling an exhibition of Giorgio
Armani's work for the Guggenheim Museum in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   A show devoted to Kennedy's White House style had been discussed
at the Met for some time. ``This is something the museum had been
hoping to do for a good number of years,'' Holzer said. ``It is not
a light bulb that went off two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar show had been planned by the Corcoran Gallery in
Washington but was scotched, a representative of the Corcoran said,
when the Kennedy family said that it would prefer such an
exhibition to take place at the Met, an institution with which
Kennedy enjoyed strong ties. Her daughter, Caroline Kennedy
Schlossberg, will be honorary chairwoman of the gala.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the fashion world were disappointed at the Met's
decision to honor a style on which few who have ever picked up a
copy of Vogue need further schooling. ``Clearly it sounds like a
big commercial thing,'' said Lisa Eisner, the stylist and vintage
collector. ``Don't Elvis and Marilyn sell as much as Jackie?'' she
asked. ``Why don't they just do all three?''
</P>
<P>
   Marin Hopper, the fashion director of Elle magazine, said, ``It
will be interesting to see what will be brought to a theme and
style that's been very played out over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valerie Steele, curator of the Museum at the Fashion
Institute of Technology said she had few issues with a show
highlighting Kennedy's look. ``I don't have a problem with the
concept,'' she explained. ``Maybe it's not the most scholarly show
in the world, but her fashion was covered in headlines. In fashion,
we tend to focus on the influence of designers. But trendsetters
have just as much impact on history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
