<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PLATFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN PLATFORM SESSION FOCUSES ON THE MODERATE VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Aiming directly at the voters in the center,
Republicans turned their first official platform meeting Monday
into a showcase for the party's ideas on education, Medicare and
Social Security. Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin, the platform
committee chairman, said panel would produce a ``very fresh, very
visionary'' platform that would seal its reputation as the
reform-oriented party of the future.
</P>
<P>
   But away from the harmony on stage, the party's ideological
fault lines on abortion were apparent. Anti-abortion advocates had
a news conference outside the meeting hall in which they called on
party leaders to live up to their promises and retain the party's
strong anti-abortion plank; several of the activists said they were
confident the party would do so. The anti-abortion activists also
urged Gov. George W. Bush, the expected nominee, to name a
running-mate who opposes abortion. ``If Governor Bush selects a
pro-choice running mate, it will be a very serious strategic
mistake,'' said Peggy Lehner, president of Dayton Right to Life.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and the chairman of the Republican National Committee,
Jim Nicholson, reiterated to reporters that they did not expect the
platform's language on abortion to change, in accord with Bush's
wishes. The platform calls for an end to legalized abortion and the
appointment of judges who respect ``the sanctity of innocent human
life.'' Republicans who support abortion rights are struggling,
once again, to change it.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson, citing Bush's deep popularity in the party and his
ability to unify Republicans, said that he did not expect a fight
over abortion on the floor of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, one of the major themes of the day was the need
for change and fresh ideas. Thompson said he expected extensive
revisions to the platform to deal with rapidly changing issues from
e-commerce to bio-tech to women's health and to reflect the focus
of the Bush campaign on issues like education.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Thompson said he did not expect the party to call
for the abolition of the Department of Education, one of several
federal agencies that the 1996 Republican platform, a deeply
conservative document, wanted to dismantle. He also said he
expected the platform to ``change somewhat'' on immigration,
another area where the party staked out conserverative terrain four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting, in a state that generally plays a pivotal role
in presidential elections, was a careful selection of panel
discussions that highlighted parents and principals, health care
experts and pension analysts, and a collection of citizens from
Dayton itself. Republican officials heard from a Milwaukee mother,
Pilar Gomez, who talked of her ``empowering'' experiences with that
city's ``Parental Choice Program,'' that enabled her to use
publicly-funded vouchers to send her children to private school.
``Quality education,'' she said, ``that should be a right, not a
privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also heard from officials in Arizona, Florida, Ohio
and Pennsylvania, and their efforts to inject more flexibility and
accountability into public schools. ``Our party rejects the notion
that the Creator placed talent in children based on their skin
color or their wealth,'' said Lisa Graham Keegan, Arizona's
superintendent of public instruction. The Republican leaders also
highlighted complaints about the burden of cumbersome federal
regulations on local educators trying to find what works.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also focused on the need to ``reform'' Social
Security and Medicare. Sen. Bill Frist of Tennessee, a co-chairman
of the platform committee, argued that Medicare was in profound
need of modernization, in part because of the inadequacy of its
benefit package, which lacks prescription drug coverage. But he
argued that adding that benefit must be part of ``overall reform of
the system,'' and the creation of a new health care marketplace to
allow private plans to compete with traditional Medicare for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people attended Monday's event, in Sinclair Community
College in downtown Dayton, and several of the most attentive were
from various ideological and interest groups. Donald Devine, of the
American Conservative Union, said he was monitoring the proceedings
as part of the group's ``committee for a conservative platform.''
From his conversations with the Bush campaign and others, he said
he believed the Republican platform would be conservative and
``pretty close'' to his group's desires.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Republicans for Choice and the Republican
Pro-Choice Coalition were also on hand, although Republican leaders
had declared that abortion would not be the subject of any public
hearings leading up to the convention. In a conciliatory gesture,
an aide to Thompson said Monday night that at the next platform
forum, Friday in Billings, Mont., one local representative from
each side of the abortion issue would be scheduled to speak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
