r s BC-GLF-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     06-19 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS AVOIDANCE OF COLONIAL A MATTER OF COURSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tiger doesn't hate us. I'm convinced of that.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't avoid Fort Worth because he thinks we're all a bunch
of rednecks who eat too much red meat, burn crosses on folks' front
lawns and attend weekly Klan meetings.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that a few of those folks are a bit perturbed at all
the attention we've been paying to Tiger's incredible weekend at
the U.S. Open and have phoned to voice their opinions, mostly in
one-syllable, four-letter words.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the John Rockers of the world.
</P>
<P>
   They can lump it.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger stays out of Fort Worth for one reason and one reason
only, though you're not likely to ever hear him admit it.
</P>
<P>
   It's the golf course, dummy.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there was a time a few years ago when Woods became at
least mildly irritated with the folks out at Colonial. First, they
announced that he'd accepted an invitation to participate before he
was ready to make it official.
</P>
<P>
   You could hardly blame anyone for getting a little excited and
prematurely pulling the trigger on that little piece of news,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the infamous pre-Colonial practice round in 1997
with Fuzzy Zoeller after Fuzzy, always trying to be funny, made
those insensitive remarks about ham hocks and collard greens ``or
whatever you people eat'' weeks earlier at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger didn't like someone out at Colonial turning their little
makeup dance into a media circus either and the round never
actually came off.
</P>
<P>
   But those are mere minor irritants, probably long forgotten,
compared with Tiger's real problem with Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   It's just not the kind of course that brings out the best in his
game.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds a little strange right now, considering how he just
brought the vaunted U.S. Open to its knees, begging for mercy in
the fog and mist of Pebble Beach in what might well have been the
greatest individual performance in sports history, but that's it in
a nutshell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is intelligent about the golf courses he chooses to play
and the golf course doesn't suit him,'' says Fort Worth's Clark
Dennis, who knows the Colonial layout as well as any professional
golfer today. ``He can play and dominate anywhere, but it's not the
kind of course he can overpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can come to Colonial and win, but it's harder for him to
play that course as opposed to, say, the Nelson, where he can just
bomb it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, currently playing on the Buy.com Tour (formerly the Nike
Tour), where he finished 12th Sunday in the Buy.com Cleveland Open,
isn't knocking Colonial and certainly means no insult to Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was as amazed by Woods' magnificent performance at the
Open as any of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is God-given, but he's also worked hard,'' Dennis
pointed out. ``He's been in the weight room \Rwhere he bench
presses 300 pounds\S. He was already good, but he knew he wanted to
win a U.S. Open and he changed his game. I imagine he makes a lot
of sacrifices in his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was as focused on that par putt on 16 as he was on any shot
in the tournament and he was standing there with a 15-shot lead. It
didn't matter what he was winning by. He is just totally focused on
what he is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is, by far, the most dominant athlete in his sport in the
world. Sure, he could walk into Colonial on any given weekend and
lead wire-to-wire. But he's not as likely to lap the field there as
he is at any number of other courses in the country and he has
other reasons to forget Fort Worth as well.
</P>
<P>
   First, he plays a limited schedule anyway. He's only going to
play 15-18 tournaments a year. Four of those are the majors and
another couple are world championships. For the other dozen or so,
naturally he's going to be picky.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's that little matter of a guaranteed million dollars
to show up and play in a tournament in Germany the same week as
Colonial. You think maybe he'd ignore a million bucks laying on the
ground like you and I might walk past a penny?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the so-called sponsorship conflict. He
represents American Express. The Colonial is sponsored by
MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the two together isn't likely to cause some sort of
nuclear reaction, bringing about the end of life as we know it, but
it serves as a semi-rational excuse. Who knows, maybe American
Express simply asked him not to play at Colonial while MasterCard
is the sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's an inconsistently applied alibi. After all, the fact
that Woods also represents Buick hasn't kept him from playing in
tournaments sponsored by other automobile manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   What we keep coming back to then is that staid old lady we call
Colonial, with her narrow tree-lined fairways and premier
shot-maker's layout. She can be a fickle, difficult date, sweet as
a fresh fried pie one day, capricious as the howling south wind on
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why else he wouldn't play here,'' Dennis says. ``
Maybe now that he's retooled his game and he's got that 2-iron shot
he can `punch' out there 250, and he's hitting his wedges great,
he'll come back.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first time the dominant player of his era
returned to romance Colonial after a long absence. Jack Nicklaus
went six years between appearances here between 1975 and 1982, when
he returned and won the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Nicklaus was the Tiger of his day,'' Dennis said. ``He
stayed away for the same reason: For a while there, the course just
didn't suit his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Time is on our side. Tiger is only 24. One day he'll wake up
after sweet dreams of a lovely old course, lined with huge stately
oaks and with a wonderful tradition of great champions built around
it.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's course.
</P>
<P>
   One day, when he has conquered all there is to conquer, and
Colonial is still out there, beckoning like a Siren on the shore,
the allure will become too much, and he'll return, if only to meet
the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He ``will'' come back. They always do.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
