<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS RELIEVERS CARRY TAG OF UNRELIABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates will walk
deliberately to the mound tonight and remove left-handed starter
Kenny Rogers from the game against the Minnesota Twins. Assuming,
of course, Rogers does not provide the Rangers with their second
complete game this season.
</P>
<P>
   Oates will motion toward his bullpen and summon a left- or
right-hander, depending on the score, the inning, the hitter and
the available alternatives on the bench for Twins manager Tom
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   What transpires next at The Ballpark in Arlington is anyone's
guess, which is one of the Rangers' problems in their swoon to the
bottom of the American League West, with 10 losses in 11 games to
fall 71/2 games behind first-place Oakland. Oates has no idea what
will happen when he calls for relief.
</P>
<P>
   The days of the bullpen being a reliable source of strength
remain a distant memory from 1999. The bullpen might preserve a
victory, but it's just as likely they'll get hit hard, as they did
in an 11-10 loss to Baltimore last week. Right-handers Jeff
Zimmerman and Tim Crabtree, left-hander Mike Venafro and closer
John Wetteland surrendered five runs on seven hits and blew a
four-run, eighth-inning lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' Crabtree said. ``We're either all pitching well
or we're all in a funk. I've never seen anything like it. Usually,
there's at least somebody Johnny can go to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have already lost seven games when they've entered
the seventh inning with a lead, compared with nine such losses all
last season. The Rangers have also not fared well in games tied
after the sixth (1-4), seventh (2-5) and eighth (2-5) innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just say this: Your championship teams tend to have very
solid 'pens,'' Wetteland said. ``As a whole this year, I don't
think we've done the job.''
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen's earned-run average during the Rangers' 31
victories is 4.00. That figure swells to 7.45 in their 36 losses.
The bullpen's ERA during the team's 13 one-run victories _ not
including the 17-16 victory May 5 against Oakland _ is 4.03. It
skyrockets to 8.38 in their 15 one-run losses. The ERA is also a
tidy 3.18 during six two-run victories and 7.71 in their two
two-run losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were winning all those games \Rin May\S, our bullpen
was lights out,'' Oates said. ``That's how you win low-scoring,
one-run ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how the Rangers won the West a year ago. They were 24-16
in one-run games last year with a bullpen that went 30-16 with a
4.33 ERA and converted 47 of 66 save opportunities. The Rangers are
13-15 this season in one-run games with a bullpen that is 8-11 with
a 5.62 ERA and 16-for-28 in save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bullpen's struggles, general manager Doug Melvin is
not planning immediate changes. ``They're a talented enough group
of people,'' Melvin said. ``They just need to get it going and
pitch better.''
</P>
<P>
   He dismisses the idea of calling up right-hander Ryan Glynn or
left-hander Doug Davis from Triple-A Oklahoma to pitch out of the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to bring up Ryan Glynn and have him sit around in
the bullpen for six weeks like Matt Perisho did,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation bears some responsibility for the bullpen's
struggles, too, Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the starters don't take you deep enough into the game and
you have to use more than two pitchers out of the bullpen, somebody
is going to be off,'' Melvin said. ``You can't bring in four
relievers out of the bullpen and expect every one to pitch well.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate responsibility, though, lies with the bullpen to
turn its performance around.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't give up the lead and expect our guys to come
back and score more runs,'' Crabtree said. ``When our bullpen is
going well, W's are put on the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is hurt. Nobody is not feeling well. We've all got the
same stuff we had in May.''
</P>
<P>
   June continues to test their resilience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have many options,'' Oates said. ``We just need to
get one or two of them hot, and we'll be fine.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
