<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL APPEALS COURT AGREES TO REVIEW MICROSOFT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court stepped forcefully into the
Microsoft antitrust case Monday, dismissing a government argument
that it lacked jurisdiction and setting a fast-paced schedule for
reviewing Microsoft's request that the judges block a lower-court
order restricting its conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft applauded the decision by the U.S. Court of Appeals
for the District of Columbia Circuit, saying, ``Obviously, we are
pleased that the appeals court unanimously sided with Microsoft and
rejected the government's position.''
</P>
<P>
   But it will probably prove to be a Pyrrhic victory. The last
paragraph of the two-page order says that if the trial judge asks
the Supreme Court to take the case directly, ``this briefing
schedule will be automatically suspended.''
</P>
<P>
   That request could come as soon as Tuesday, and as a result the
government also proclaimed victory. ``We are very pleased with the
court's ruling that it would stay further proceedings if the
district court certifies the case for direct appeal to the Supreme
Court,'' said Gina Talamona, a Justice Department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 19 state attorneys general are trying
to send the case directly to the Supreme Court under a little-used
law known as the Expediting Act. It allows the direct appeal of
significant federal antitrust cases. Microsoft Corp. wants its
appeal heard in the Court of Appeals, which has sided with the
company in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Moving quickly last week, before the judge could send the case
to the Supreme Court, Microsoft tried to outmaneuver the government
by asking the Court of Appeals to consider its request to stay the
judge's order. And the Court of Appeals showed that it was eager to
take the case by declaring that the entire court, not a three-judge
panel, would hear the stay request and larger appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In reaction, the government argued in a brief that the Court of
Appeals does not have jurisdiction, on several grounds _ arguments
that the court dismissed Monday. The court set a schedule under
which Microsoft and the government will have only until July 6 to
file briefs on Microsoft's request to stay the court-ordered
remedy, unless the schedule is suspended.
</P>
<P>
   But the court order Monday also indicated another victory for
the government in the legal skirmishes that the two sides have
fought since U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson issued his
order on June 7 breaking Microsoft in two and forcing the company
to abide by a long list of restrictions while the breakup is
carried out.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had argued, in a Court of Appeals brief last week,
that the Expediting Act does not apply to the states' lawsuit since
it applies only to federal cases.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department countered that since the suits were
tried together, and since only single rulings and remedies were
entered for the two suits, the appeals of both should be carried
together to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the appeals court indicated it agreed with the
government. The court's order says it will suspend consideration of
the appeal of the states' case, too, as soon as Jackson issues the
certification to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Microsoft filed with Jackson a brief setting out the
company's arguments against a direct appeal. High on the list of
objections was the argument about the states' case, even though
hours earlier the appeals court had indicated it did not accept
that argument.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft also hit on the one argument that is most likely
to concern the Supreme Court justices, the need to read several
thousand pages of trial record in a direct appeal. Usually, the
Court of Appeals winnows that trial record for Supreme Court review
so the justices may only have to read summaries.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft promised that ``the sheer number of factual and
legal issues raised by Microsoft's appeals, as well as a range of
important procedural issues,'' make it ``completely unsuitable for
summary disposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft noted that addressing all of the issues to be raised
in the appeal ``would require review of the 13,466-page trial
transcript and the 2,695 trial exhibits that compose the record in
these cases, a time-consuming exercise the Supreme Court would not
likely be anxious to undertake.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also tried to argue that the case was not important
enough to warrant direct review, even though in a previous brief
Microsoft said the remedy imposed on the company ``could have a
significant adverse impact on the nation's economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Microsoft quoted the text of the Expediting Act, which
said cases of ``general public importance'' to the ``administration
of justice'' are eligible for direct review. The company took that
language about the administration of justice literally and said
Microsoft's appeal would not impair the government's ``ongoing
enforcement responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   And to the Court of Appeals statement last week that the case
was ``of exceptional importance,'' Microsoft said that view ``makes
it more important, not less, that the case proceed through
intermediate appellate review.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department may choose to file a reply to Microsoft's
brief on Tuesday. But it is also possible that Jackson will simply
issue the certification order on Tuesday. He has made it clear for
more than two months that he is eager to do that.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court does not have to take the appeal, in which
case it would be sent back to the Court of Appeals. No one knows
whether the Supreme Court will decide quickly, since it is near the
end of the court's term _ or wait until its next term, which begins
in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
