<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HINTS GOP FOILS JUDICIAL DIVERSITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
and GREG MCDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ President Clinton criticized Texas' two Republican
U.S. senators for delaying consideration of his El Paso nominee to
the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Enrique Moreno, a Harvard-educated El Paso lawyer with no
experience on the bench, was nominated by Clinton in September to
the New Orleans court.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, however, Sens. Kay Bailey Hutchison and Phil Gramm
questioned Moreno's qualifications in a letter to Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah, who chairs the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Moreno's confirmation process has stalled, and
Clinton, citing other examples involving his minority judicial
nominees, said Moreno's situation represents ``a distinctive
pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for him to be denied, not because he is political but
because he is not political enough in the right way, is wrong,''
Clinton told about 40 attendees at a reception benefiting the
Southwest Voter Registration Education Project in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was in Houston for a pair of fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who also visited Austin on Monday, was the featured
guest for two events at the downtown Four Seasons Hotel, including
the Southwest Voter reception and a lunch benefiting the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At the reception, attended by state Rep. Rick Noriega,
D-Houston; city Controller Sylvia Garcia; and City Council members
Carroll Robinson, Chris Bell and John Castillo, among others,
Clinton discussed Moreno and also his support of new hate crimes
legislation introduced Monday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He asked the predominantly Hispanic crowd at the Southwest Voter
reception, each of whom paid a minimum of $500 to attend, to make
themselves heard on the Moreno nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those in the other party who see the courts as an
instrument of partisan politics,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Moreno, Clinton cited Ricardo Morado, nominated
for the U.S. District Court in the Southern District of Texas, and
Kathleen McCree-Lewis of Detroit, who would be the first black
woman to serve on the 6th U.S. Court of Appeals if confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Morado's nomination has been put on hold and
McCree-Lewis can't get a confirmation hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want them on the court, but they don't want the
people you're trying to register to vote to know they don't want
them on the court,'' Clinton said. ``The answer is to blur
everything ... and hope nobody will know what really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moreno's case, the letter from Gramm and Hutchison noted that
the Texas Judicial Advisory Group, a nonpartisan group of Texas
attorneys that met in March, had voted 10-5 against the nomination.
Five other members of the advisory group said they could offer no
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fair to summarize the views of those recommending
against confirmation that Mr. Moreno simply had not achieved the
level of experience necessary to be fully engaged and effective on
a court one notch below the United States Supreme Court,'' the
letter stated.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno, 43, was nominated to replace Judge Will Garwood of
Austin, who left active status in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At a lunch with about 100 contributors to the DSCC, Clinton
rubbed shoulders with former Houston Mayor Bob Lanier and his wife,
Elyse; former U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen; lawyer David
Berg; and Bill White, one-time Texas Democratic Party chairman and
former deputy secretary of energy in the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees paid a minimum of $1,000 each. The money raised at the
event is used to help elect Democrats to the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   At the lunch, Clinton noted the ethnic diversity represented in
the room, notably a strong contingent of South Asians, and called
it an example of Houston's growth and strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing of all, which is why I like looking
around at this crowd, is that we find a way to live together with
all of our differences, that we find a way not just to tolerate
them but to celebrate them,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a handful of Muslims in traditional, loose-fitting
garments, Clinton said, ``We think they look very nice in their
garb, and they are probably more comfortable than we are in the
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Clinton attended a fund-raiser at the home of his old
friend Roy Spence, an advertising executive and Democratic
activist.
</P>
<P>
   The president commented on the posh setting in the hills near
Austin, and suggested it was symbolic of the economic prosperity
during his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Exhibit A for if you want to live like a Republican, you
should vote Democratic.'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Spence praised Clinton's tenure, saying, ``It's gone by too
fast. We are grateful for the contributions to this country. ... We
love you and we love what you have done for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The western swing band Asleep at the Wheel provided
entertainment at the gathering, and the 70 or so guests included
former Gov. Ann Richards, former Land Commissioner Garry Mauro,
former U.S. Rep. J.J. ``Jake'' Pickle, and U.S. Sen. Chuck Robb,
D-Va., son-in-law of the late President Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Robb, who is in a tight re-election campaign, will be one of the
beneficiaries of the fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Monday evening, Clinton attended a $10,000-per-couple event
hosted by Dell Computer executive Tom Meridith, whose home
overlooks the Colorado River in Austin. Among the guests were
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.; and Sen. Patrick Leahy,
D-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   A major theme of the event was creation of a committee within
the Democratic Party to focus on issues involving the emerging
high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Lyle Lovett entertained at that event.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STORY ENDS HERE &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
