<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8904 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CLINTON-LAZIO-GINGRIC     06-19 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LAZIO-GINGRICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGRETFULLY, CLINTON CONCEDES LAZIO IS NO GINGRICH 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the space of a few days last week, in speeches and
television advertisements, Hillary Rodham Clinton assailed Rep.
Rick Lazio as a friend to the gun lobby, a foe of abortion rights,
and hostile to women, children and families, by virtue of some of
the votes he has cast in Congress. But there was one thing notably
missing from the first lady's broad and calculated barrage on her
new opponent in the race for the U.S. Senate: any mention of Newt
Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, the former speaker of the House, was pushed to front
and center by the Clinton camp when Lazio entered the race a month
ago, as Clinton's senior advisers rushed to describe Lazio, a
Suffolk County Republican, as a ``foot soldier in the Gingrich
revolution.'' But Gingrich has now faded almost as quickly as he
appeared.
</P>
<P>
   That references to Gingrich have so suddenly vanished from the
Clinton campaign lexicon suggests an initial miscalculation by
Clinton and her advisers. Gingrich, it seems, is not the notorious
figure he was two years ago, even in New York, a realization
Clinton's aides said they reached quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But, perhaps more significantly, it suggests the complications
Clinton faces in running against an opponent who, while not as
moderate as Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, is not quite the conservative
Clinton would like to face in this Democratic state. Even Clinton's
advisers now acknowledge that Lazio is no Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   When those advisers first sought to discredit Lazio by noting
his support for Gingrich's policies during his reign, the strategy
struck some Democrats and Republicans as curious. Gingrich had been
the Democrats' favorite Republican in the years after he was
identified with the shutdown of the federal government in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 2000 round of congressional campaigns, with Gingrich
now back in private life, Democrats have largely concluded that
that line of attack does not have the potency it once had, which is
evident by the fact that his name has barely come up in any House
or Senate campaigns this year. Gingrich's successor _ that would be
J. Dennis Hastert, of course _ is neither as infamous nor as
polarizing as Gingrich once was, several Democrats acknowledged
wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fading,'' Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, chairman
of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, said of Gingrich's
role in the national campaign. ``It serves as an important
reference, but it's certainly fading.''
</P>
<P>
   In the scramble to adjust after Giuliani quit the New York race,
the initial belief in Clinton's camp was that the old Gingrich
script would work again, and that Gingrich remained an effective
target in a state that he often invoked as an example of Democratic
policies gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's senior advisers, Harold P. Ickes, attacked
Lazio in The New York Post for ``doing the work of Newt Gingrich''
_ a full day before Lazio had even announced his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in many ways, the mirror image of the Republican
strategy in the 1998 Senate race in New York, when, reprising an
old chestnut of a campaign tactic, they attacked Charles E.
Schumer, the Brooklyn Democrat, as being ``too liberal'' for New
York. Schumer, of course, went on to defeat Alfonse D'Amato, the
three-term Republican senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``When in doubt, go back to the old playbook,'' Hank Sheinkopf,
a Democratic consultant, said of Clinton's invocation of Gingrich.
``The problem is that the old playbook is not working. Gingrich is
old news. He's gone. He's off the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Gingrich is an unpopular figure in New York.
One out of two New Yorkers have an unfavorable opinion of him,
according to a New York Times/CBS News poll taken June 4 to June
10.
</P>
<P>
   But 36 percent were undecided or had no opinion at all,
suggesting that even Gingrich might be riding off into the
political sunset. Charles Cook, the editor of a Washington-based
political newsletter that tracks Congressional races, said that
while Gingrich was a ``metaphor for the excesses of '95 and '96,
that was four or five years ago. Republicans have been behaving on
most issues fairly carefully since then.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers said they noted that their attempts to link
Lazio to Gingrich had led to eye rolling in the media as they tried
to make the case to reporters the weekend Lazio entered the race.
That anecdotal observation was subsequently confirmed in a poll by
Clinton's pollster, Mark Penn.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's senior campaign strategist, Mike Murphy, said he noted
the change in strategy, though he was not surprised by it. ``It
backfired,'' Murphy said. ``And like so much of the Hillary Clinton
campaign, it could not pass the laugh test.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the political convenience of a Gingrich, Clinton has
been forced to pick and choose votes Lazio has cast over the last
seven years to emphasize the conservative edge of his ideological
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Clinton noted that Lazio had opposed a Democratic
bill to protect consumers in dealing with health maintenance
organizations, had opposed a so-called hate crimes bill, and had
voted against a bill to provide federal financing for 100,000 new
teachers. ``By the time this race is over, there isn't going to be
anyone who doesn't know that Rick Lazio voted against the 100,000
teachers,'' Torricelli said.
</P>
<P>
   But it has not been easy. When Clinton attacked Lazio for
opposing the registration of new guns and the licensing of gun
owners, Lazio countered by noting that he supports a ban on assault
weapons and voted for the Brady Bill, which imposes a waiting
period on handgun purchases.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton sought to present Lazio as an opponent of abortion
rights by noting his opposition to public financing for abortions
and support for a ban on the procedure that abortion foes describe
as partial-birth abortion, Lazio responded by noting his record of
opposing efforts to criminalize abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Given all that, is it any wonder that Democrats in New York
these days are speaking nostalgically about Gingrich as they
contemplate the race Clinton now faces? ``Gingrich was beautiful,''
said Sheinkopf, the Democratic consultant. ``He was larger than
life. He was extraordinarily vocal. He was a perfect foil for
Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big loss for Democrats,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
