<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-POCONO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYFIELD USES AN EARNHARDT TACTIC FOR BUMP-AND-RUN POCONO VICTORY  

</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG POND, Pa. _ It was a classic Dale Earnhardt maneuver, the
kind that earned him the nickname Iron Head and, after 75 career
victories in the last two decades, the title of King of the Car
Fights. Stalk and harass. Drop to pass. Then bump and run.
</P>
<P>
   The difference Monday in the Pocono 500 was that the tactics
were turned on Iron Head by a young driver Earnhardt had long
treated as softhearted: Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a half-mile from the checkered flag, coming out of the
final turn, Mayfield dropped to the bottom of the track below
Earnhardt and kissed the bumper of Earnhardt's No. 3 car, which had
led for the previous 14 laps.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Earnhardt's potential 76th victory was whiplashed as
Mayfield sneaked his No. 12 car inside for the third triumph of his
career, his second at the Pocono Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never tried to wreck him; I just wanted to rattle his
cage,'' said the 31-year-old Mayfield, who won the 500 here in
1998. ``I'm not sure I hit him. If there was contact, it wasn't
enough to turn him.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt made it clear that there was indeed contact and that
he did not enjoy being on the receiving end of it. Beyond the
finish line, after his car wobbled enough to let Dale Jarrett and
Ricky Rudd pass for second and third place, Earnhardt pulled
alongside Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   In the most terse terms, the man also known as the Intimidator
said facetiously that Mayfield was No. 1. ``I got in a corner, got
rubbed a little and got beat,'' said Earnhardt, who was fourth.
``It was good racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield's racing colleagues, however, were amused that the
young driver, whom Earnhardt bumped on the track during six years
together on the Nascar circuit and razzed often in the garage area,
had turned the tables. They gave Mayfield the thumbs-up as he made
his way to victory lane and chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Dale wouldn't have done that if he was behind him,''
Jarrett said with a sly smile.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, who had positioned his No. 88 car in third place, had
the best view of the impending tussle. He was also ready to take
advantage of it. Jarrett noticed Mayfield gathering steam on the
second of the track's three turns at the same time Earnhardt was
losing power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this might get interesting,'' said Jarrett, who is
third in the Winston Cup point standing behind Bobby Labonte and
Earnhardt. ``A lot of times when you get together and get the air
taken off the front of your car, like Jeremy did, a lot of times
that car will slide up, too. For that split second, I thought I
might have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett added: ``It means a lot to Jeremy. It shows he's a hard
racer. The best driver in this business, and he's been that for a
long time, is Dale Earnhardt. You go up against him and come out on
top. You've got to take advantage of those chances because more
times than not you're not going to come out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield had to wait a day for his opportunity after persistent
rain and dense fog on Sunday postponed the race until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield had seven top-10 finishes in 15 races this season,
including a victory in the California 500. But he started in the
No. 22 position at 10 a.m. Monday under overcast skies with the
temperature at 65 degrees before a depleted crowd, as many people
had to get back to work.
</P>
<P>
   He led for three laps _ 23 to 26 _ but was not confident of a
top-10 finish after running 41st last week in Michigan. But
Mayfield was running a strong second in the last 20 laps and was
intent on stalking Earnhardt when the field came out of the fifth
yellow flag on Lap 187.
</P>
<P>
   He opted for only two new tires on the final pit stop and
decided to nurse them until the final lap. Mayfield said he noticed
Earnhardt sliding on the final two turns, and he also acknowledged
that the Intimidator had intimidated him in races past.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also was smart enough to know not to try to get him
loose on Turn 1 or he'd come back and get me loose,'' Mayfield
said. ``A lot of people talk about Dale Earnhardt; he came the hard
way and drives that way. So did I.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the bump-and-run victory, Mayfield shrugged and said, ``You
got to do what you got to do to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the likelihood Earnhardt will remember that in a future race,
Mayfield showed a little hardheadedness. ``If he comes back to get
me,'' he said. ``then I'll go back and get him again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
