<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-HEARING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING BEGINS TUESDAY ON WHETHER SKAKEL WILL BE TRIED AS AN ADULT
OR JUVENILE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Fla.)   By PAUL ZIELBAUER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Michael Skakel, charged with killing
15-year-old Martha Moxley in Greenwich in 1975, is to return to
state court Tuesday, where a judge will open an unusual hearing to
decide whether the 39-year-old defendant should be tried as a
juvenile or an adult.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing could last a few hours or several weeks, depending
on how much evidence Judge Maureen Dennis of Superior Court decides
to allow state prosecutors and Skakel's lawyer to present. But
several lawyers following the case said they expected the
proceeding to take about four or five days, spread out over this
week and next.
</P>
<P>
   Many legal experts familiar with the case said they believed the
judge would order Skakel's trial moved from Juvenile Court to
Superior Court, where he would be tried as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that he will be transferred to an adult court,''
said William Dunlap, a professor of criminal law at Quinnipiac
College in Hamden, Conn. Noting Skakel's age, he added, ``Having
him tried as a juvenile seems like a farce.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, prosecutors will present several witnesses to
bolster their case against Skakel and will urge that the case be
moved to adult court. Defense lawyers will move to have the charges
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted in Superior Court, Skakel would face 25 years to
life in prison. In Juvenile Court, the sentence would be far
shorter.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel, a nephew of Ethel Kennedy, was charged by state
prosecutors as a juvenile because he was 15 when Moxley was found
bludgeoned to death under a tree in her family's yard a quarter
century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors believe Moxley was killed with a 6-iron golf club,
pieces of which were found around her body. The club had come from
a set owned by the Skakel family, the authorities have said.
</P>
<P>
   To determine whether to move Skakel's case to an adult court,
Dennis must operate under the laws in place in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   A juvenile charged with murder now is automatically tried as an
adult, but in 1975, when attempting rehabilitation was the
preferred method for dealing with violent youths, such a move was
rare. To try a child as an adult, a judge had to find ``reasonable
cause'' to take the youth out of the juvenile court system.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's looking at the law then,'' said one Connecticut juvenile
court lawyer, who spoke only on the condition of anonymity. ``It's
a 1975 courtroom tomorrow, except that it's open to the press. It's
unheard of. We've never had a case where we've had to go back 25
years.``
</P>
<P>
   Despite the greater burden the 1975 laws place on the
prosecution, Dunlap said, Skakel is unlikely to retain his legal
status as a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since it was possible to try him as an adult in 1975,'' he
said, ``and since it is almost automatic that he would be tried as
an adult if the crime were committed today, I think he'll be moved
to Superior Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Benedict, the state's attorney prosecuting Skakel, is
likely to present an array of witnesses, including a former
Greenwich police chief and former students at a school for troubled
youths that Skakel attended in the early 1980s. Benedict did not
return calls seeking comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Sherman, Skakel's lawyer, said he believed Benedict had
no physical evidence linking Skakel to Moxley's murder. But based
on the few clues they have in the case, prosecutors believe the
girl knew her killer. Skakel lived next door to Moxley.
</P>
<P>
   One piece of evidence they seem likely to bring out in the days
ahead is an eight-page autopsy report. The report, obtained from
Greenwich police records, found that the killer had battered
Moxley's head and neck with 13 powerful blows from a blunt object.
It details how several blows carved deep crescent-shaped wounds on
the upper part of her head; other wounds struck bone.
</P>
<P>
   The wounds detailed in the report _ by Dr. Elliot M. Gross, the
medical examiner who performed the autopsy _ suggest that Moxley
probably died from three blows that fractured the back of her skull
and penetrated her brain, said Dr. John H. Sinard, a Yale
pathologist who studied the report at the request of The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   While she lay prone but still alive, Moxley was also stabbed
completely through her neck, most likely with the golf club's
shaft, the autopsy found. The autopsy did not give investigators
any clues to the killer's identity.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman, Skakel's lawyer, said he would attack prosecution
witnesses in the hope of casting the the charges against his client
as too weak to warrant a Superior Court trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the first opportunity that we have to, No.
1, confront and, No. 2, cross-examine these witnesses,'' Sherman
said Monday. ``That is immeasurably important. Other than their
spoken words, there's no evidence to connect Michael Skakel with
that crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the hearing concludes, the judge will probably issue her
decision within a few weeks, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis is still considering a request by five newspapers,
including The Times, to grant public access to the case's court
documents, under seal since Skakel's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   On March 10, she decided to grant a motion filed by the same
newspapers to open the trial to the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
