<HEADER>
A8916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-DRUGS-1STL     06-19 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-DRUGS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND CHINA WILL COOPERATE IN FIGHT AGAINST DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Subs 2nd graf to change `legal agreement' to `formal
agreement'; changes quote in last graf slightly; other minor
changes throughout.)  By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The United States and China agreed Monday to step up
their cooperation against the production and smuggling of illegal
drugs, especially heroin and methamphetamine. The two drugs have
emerged as scourges in both countries and throughout much of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, American and Chinese law-enforcement
agencies have sometimes cooperated to stop contraband drug
shipments. But on Monday the two governments signed their first
formal agreement to share information and evidence related to drug
smuggling. Officials from both sides predicted more wide-ranging
collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was announced here by Barry R. McCaffrey, the
retired Army general who director of the White House drug-control
office. McCaffrey is visiting China with other anti-drug officials
as part of an eight-day tour and will also stop at Hong Kong, Hanoi
and Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important moment,'' McCaffrey said after two days
of talks with Chinese officials. McCaffrey, the first top American
drug official to visit China, said such collaboration was vital to
combatting global heroin trafficking and the fast-rising abuse of
methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   Since China began opening its borders in the late 1970s, it has
become a major transit route for heroin produced in southeast Asia,
especially Myanmar, the former Burma. Chinese gangs ship some of
that heroin to the United States, although most heroin sold there
is from Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, heroin addiction has risen in China,
especially in the southern province of Yunnan and in the western
region of Xinjiang, which receives heroin smuggled from
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   According to charts provided by McCaffrey's office, factories in
southeastern China are important producers of methamphetamine,
which is sold throughout East Asia, and of ephedrine, the
ingredient in legal medicines that is also used to produce
methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey listed several areas in which the United States hopes
to gain China's cooperation, including the sharing of intelligence
about drug operations, curbing money laundering, controlling
precursor chemicals, analyzing seized drugs to identify their
sources and fighting the smuggling of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States, which has since last year stationed a
Drug Enforcement Administration agent in Beijing, had also proposed
opening an FBI office here, but had not received an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Yang Fengrui, director of drug enforcement at China's Public
Security Ministry, appeared with McCaffrey Monday and said he
believed Sino-American cooperation ``is going to enter a new
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 100 ago in the Opium Wars, China was victimized, and
we can never forget that pain,'' Yang said, recalling an era when
Britain and other colonial European powers forced a defeated China
to accept opium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
