<DOCNO> NYT20000619.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AT&AMP;T-WIRELESS-NYT &LR;      06-19 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-WIRELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T BUYS WIRELESS OPERATIONS IN HOUSTON, SAN DIEGO AND SAN
FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Corp. agreed Monday to pay $3.3 billion in cash for
wireless telephone systems in Houston, San Diego and San Francisco
to expand its fast-growing wireless telecommunications business.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the transactions, the AT&AMP;T Wireless Group, the
company's mobile-phone arm, will add 1.3 million customers and
1,400 employees. AT&AMP;T will acquire operations in San Francisco from
Vodafone AirTouch PLC, in San Diego from the GTE Corp. and in
Houston from PrimeCo PCS, once a venture of Bell Atlantic and
Vodafone.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the impetus behind the deal came from regulatory
requirements that Vodafone AirTouch, GTE and the Bell Atlantic
Corp. shed overlapping wireless properties as they create Verizon
Wireless. Bell Atlantic and GTE agreed to merge in 1998; last year
Bell Atlantic and Vodafone agreed to combine their wireless
operations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Believing, at least for the short term, that AT&AMP;T negotiated a
good deal on these properties, investors pushed up shares in both
AT&AMP;T and its wireless unit.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in AT&AMP;T have been battered during the last three months,
sliding 36 percent as concern persists over declining revenue from
long-distance services. And shares of AT&AMP;T Wireless have not done
much better, remaining below their initial offering price of $29.50
in April.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T rose 5.62 cents, to $34, and AT&AMP;T Wireless added 3.75
cents, to $34.25.
</P>
<P>
   While AT&AMP;T is also expected to trim the roaming fees it must pay
to other phone carriers with this expansion into the three
remaining large American cities in which it could not offer
AT&AMP;T-branded wireless services, it is not clear how much the move
will affect long-term investor sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strategically, it's important for AT&AMP;T to have nationwide
coverage but it's nothing groundbreaking,'' said Kenneth Schapiro,
president of Condor Capital in Martinsville, N.J., a $480 million
money management company which owns some AT&AMP;T shares. ``It's funny
how a $3.3 billion deal doesn't mean much these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the fast-consolidating U.S. wireless industry, AT&AMP;T is
trying to grow to compete with Verizon, which would be the
country's largest wireless company with 23 million customers, and
with SBC Communications and BellSouth, which are forming the
second-largest wireless carrier with about 16.2 million customers.
When AT&AMP;T completes the acquisitions in San Francisco, San Diego
and Houston, it is expected to have nearly 15 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're using our IPO capital as a currency to extend our
footprint,'' John Zeglis, chairman of AT&AMP;T Wireless, said in a
telephone interview. AT&AMP;T Wireless raised a record $10.6 billion in
its April public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the deal is expected to cut into profits at AT&AMP;T
itself, which owns more than 80 percent of its wireless unit, by an
estimated 2 cents to 3 cents a share this year, according to AT&AMP;T.
As an additional part of the deal, AT&AMP;T expects to spend about $275
million over two years to adapt systems in Houston and San Diego to
its national standards.
</P>
<P>
   With the deals, AT&AMP;T will enlarge its capacity to sell its
wireless services in the nation's two largest states, to about 90
percent of Californians and 70 percent of Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``the company has a lot more work to do to stop leakage
of roaming costs,'' said Bruce Roberts, a telecommunications
analyst at Dresdner Kleinwort Benson. ``Wireless is a jewel for
AT&AMP;T but I still see dust gathering on that jewel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
