<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8918 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-OPENFOLO-HNS &LR;      06-19 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN </SLUG>
 FOLO-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Players admit beating Woods beyond them
<TEXT>
<P>
   Open
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ The gap, it seems, is getting wider as
opposed to narrower.
</P>
<P>
   Even the players, all of whom have egos and think they can beat
any other golfer in the world, are admitting this task is beyond
them.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, who despite not winning a tournament in over a year
still is the most consistently great golfer after Tiger Woods, is
realistic enough to know that, at the moment, there's no chance of
anybody threatening Woods as the top player.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' incredible runaway in the U.S. Open proved that.
</P>
<P>
   But it also proved another aspect of the game that Duval
supports: The USGA is not out to embarrass players in its national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like best about this golf tournament is the fact
that if you're playing excellent golf, you can do what Tiger did,''
Duval said. ``And if you're not quite on, you do what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a 19-shot difference between first-place Woods and
tied-for-eighth Duval during the Open at Pebble Beach. Duval, who
has struggled with his putting all year, didn't make many putts on
the small Pebble greens. Woods, meanwhile, made a bushel-full of
putts. That wasn't the full difference in Woods' huge victory. But
it was the main catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part for Duval and everybody else. How do
they put some fear into Woods?
</P>
<P>
   One sure thing is that it won't come in the form of pressure.
Trying to put pressure on Tiger Woods is like trying to out-wager
Bill Gates in a card game. It's hard to do when they know you don't
have the power to do so. And when you have $100 million or
thereabouts in the bank, financial concerns aren't a concern at
all.
</P>
<P>
   What it boils down to is hunger and pride and talent _ all of
which Woods possesses in great abundance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can anyone take over No. 1 in the world? No way,'' Fred
Couples said. ``He's just better than you are. And I'm all right
with that. I think Tiger is fundamentally perfect and that's not
going to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing awfully well. Nothing's stopping him. Whoever
beats him is going to have to play their best.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict that Woods is simply better than everybody else
right now is not open to appeal. He is. To hear Tour players talk
about him as they do is proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about somebody who is hitting it 350 yards dead
straight,'' said Brandel Chamblee. ``There are a lot of guys who
can hit it that far. But they can't tell you what zip code it'll be
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened is Tiger came along, and he's an extraordinary
athlete with a gifted mind. He's been molded since birth to be a
machine. He's been taught to win since birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now, you've got all these people lengthening golf courses
to Tiger-proof them and they're really playing right into his
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, shorter, tighter courses are the ones Woods probably
would have more trouble with, if he ever had to play them.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, it's time to marvel at a new master, who at 24
already has won more golf tournaments (20) than Ben Crenshaw,
Couples, Tom Kite, Tom Weiskopf, Nick Price, Curtis Strange or Greg
Norman, all of whom are twice as old as Woods, or close to it.
</P>
<P>
   The fact of the matter is that Woods already is a superstar. And
the only things standing between him and legendary status are time
and good health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger Woods is the man _ plain and simple,'' said Rocco
Mediate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can win 10-15 tournaments a year. He's that good.''
</P>
<P>
   The only story line at Pebble Beach other than Woods was the
strong showing by Europeans in the Open. A European player hasn't
won the U.S. championship since 1970, when Tony Jacklin was a
wire-to-wire victor. If not for Woods, this might have finally been
the year when Europeans broke through in the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more like what they're used to, links golf,'' said
John Huston, who besides Woods was the only other American in the
top seven. ``Other than that, I'd just say there's a lot of really
good players over there.''
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't agree more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a world game now,'' said Nick Faldo, who finished in
seventh at 6-over 290. ``Plus, the course and the setup have helped
the international players. We're used to bumping it around in the
wind and scrambling. It wasn't target golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very linksy. I think that's the major factor. If you
hit the middle of the greens, you had a great shot. And that's the
key this week. You were just trying to finish in a sensible area.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lee Westwood added: ``It's certainly nice to see the leader
board crammed with Europeans. It shows we can play a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   True. They were good enough to see Woods' bumper at times.
</P>
<P>
   As Faldo said, there were really only two goals to keep track of
for Europeans _ or anybody else who was chasing Woods for that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I made the top 15 and got exempt for next year's U.S.
Open,'' Faldo said. ``That was my only goal, along with finishing
less than 20 strokes behind Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   He just made it _ by two shots.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
