u a BC-MECHANICS-COMPETE-NYT     06-19 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MECHANICS-COMPETE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWAIIAN TEAM WINS NATIONAL SHOP BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This was not your ordinary bee. There were no
tricky spelling or geography questions. For this competition,
talented students had to endure grease, grime and muggy weather.
</P>
<P>
   But the pot for this national shop bee was a quarter of a
million dollars, to be divided among the top 10 teams.
</P>
<P>
   With the Washington Monument towering behind them, an
international cast of high school seniors, clad in white jumpsuits
with red and black racing stripes, competed Monday in a contest to
be the fastest at fixing balky automobile engines.
</P>
<P>
   Two-member teams from every state, Puerto Rico, Argentina,
Australia and Canada battled the clock and ``bugged'' Mercury Grand
Marquis engines for the prizes and scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The team from Maui High School, in Kahului, Hawaii, which
restored its car to working condition in the shortest time, topped
the team from Oregon by one minute and seven seconds. The Hawaii
team of Steven Garrard, 17, and David Sharp, 17, both seniors at
Maui High, completed the repairs in just under 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to thank the guys because they were the ones in the
field doing the work,'' said Dennis Ishii, 51, the students'
instructor. ``We've been close a couple of times before, but this
is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ishii and the two students finished in second place at last
year's competition. A team from Maui High won in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really nervous this morning, but it went away once we
got started,'' said Garrard, whose team met for a couple of hours
each school day this year in preparation for the event.
</P>
<P>
   The contest, which has been held annually since 1949, was
sponsored by the Ford Motor Co. and the American Automobile
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Before packed bleacher seats on the Mall here, the teams
repaired cars that had identical electrical and engine problems. A
judge supervised each team's efforts, and supplied replacement
parts as needed.
</P>
<P>
   When a team determined that the car was back in working order,
it slammed the hood shut, signaled a timer to stop the clock and
jumped into the driver's seat for a short road test.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, each team member took a 100-question written
examination. The multiple-choice examination tested the students'
ability to respond to ``typical repair shop situations,'' said
David Van Sickel of the American Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Van Sickel said, a contestant might be asked to
diagnose a car that is pulling toward the right when the brakes are
applied.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's competition, students from Minnesota finished
third, followed by teams from California and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy DeBoer, 18, a member of the second-place team from Vale
High School in Vale, Ore., was disappointed that his team came up
short. On the other hand, DeBoer said, ``it was definitely easier
than taking the SATs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
