A9017 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-HATE-CRIME-HNS &LR;      06-19 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE TO VOTE ON MEASURE TO STRENGTHEN HATE-CRIMES LAWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After almost three years of inaction, the Senate
began debate Monday on whether to expand federal laws against hate
crimes, an issue President Clinton uses to tweak congressional
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our opportunity to say whether we are going to be
serious about (fighting) bigotry and hatred,'' said Sen. Ted
Kennedy, a Massachusetts Democrat who won agreement from the
Senate's Republican leadership to allow a vote on the hate-crimes
measure.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the Senate's first recorded vote on whether hate
crimes should be punished under federal law. The vote, scheduled
for Tuesday,is expected to be close. Vice President Al Gore, who
presides over the Senate, has been alerted that he might be needed
to cast a tie-breaking vote.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, offered as an amendment to a defense spending
bill, would expand existing federal laws against hate crimes to
include violent crimes motivated by sexual orientation, gender or
disability. The proposal, sponsored by Kennedy, also would provide
financial help and federal expertise to state and local officials
investigating hate-crimes cases.
</P>
<P>
   Current law allows federal prosecution of hate crimes under
limited circumstances. The crimes must be based on race, color,
religion or national origin, and prosecutors must show that the
victim was prevented by the crime from participating in some
federally protected activity, such as voting.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said Congress should do more. Crimes motivated by race,
sexual orientation, gender or disability ``wound not only the
individual, but they also wound and scar a community,'' Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking against Kennedy's proposal, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
called for studies to determine whether state and local laws
adequately protect various minority groups. ``It could very well be
that we need to federalize all this, but we need the facts,'' Hatch
said. ``We need to determine whether there is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's debate began a week after the second anniversary of the
dragging death of James Byrd Jr., an East Texan whose racially
motivated slaying has been repeatedly cited by advocates of tougher
hate-crimes laws. Two of Byrd's killers have been sentenced to
death, and a third was sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's sister Louvon Harris and nephew Darrell Verrett were in
Houston to greet President Clinton when he arrived Monday for a
speech and fund-raiser at a downtown hotel. It was Clinton's third
trip to Texas this year in which he called for help passing the
hate-crimes measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership of the Senate has finally agreed to allow a
vote up or down on hate-crimes legislation,'' Clinton said in a
speech to the non-partisan Southwest Voter Registration Education
Project. ``We've got a chance now. We have to pass this
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The president cited FBI statistics indicating that nearly 8,000
hate crimes were reported in 1998, the latest year for which
information was available. Clinton said that translated into a rate
of nearly one hateful criminal act for each hour of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crimes motivated by hate are really fundamentally different
and, I think, should be treated differently under the law,'' said
Clinton, who has been pushing for tougher hate-crimes laws since
November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is running as a Democrat for the White House, has
criticized Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the likely Republican
presidential nominee, for his refusal to support a hate-crimes bill
under consideration by the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Kennedy hate-crimes measure clears the Senate, its
chances of passing the House are dim. Republican House leaders
succeeded in killing a similar measure in committee last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STORY ENDS HERE &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
