<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO PACERS AT ARENA EARLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Indiana Pacers obviously didn't return to Los
Angeles so they could watch the Oscar De La Hoya/Shane Mosley fight
Saturday night, but since they were in the neighborhood. ...
</P>
<P>
   And since Game 6 of the NBA Finals wasn't until Monday, and
since Mark Jackson and Jalen Rose are big fight fans, well, why not
see Staples Center in a different light?
</P>
<P>
   And maybe draw a few parallels to their own situation?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being the enemy, Jackson and Rose were just faces in
the crowd who were treated to quite a show as Mosley won a split
decision over De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get the opportunity to go and see two guys go
toe-to-toe for 12 rounds,'' Rose said before Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson called Staples Center ``a little bit more lively'' than
an NBA game but not as lively as when he saw Roy Jones Jr. fight at
Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the two Pacers, admitted Muhammad Ali fans, enjoyed
watching Mosley take the WBC title away from the hometown De La
Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since he was a boy, Rose has admired what fighters do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The will it takes,'' he said, ``You've got to have discipline
to train leading up to the fight. You've got to have focus. It
takes you away from your family; and then in the ring, you've got
nowhere to run, nowhere to hide, no teammate to pass to. Just you
against the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose said the reason Mosley won was he was the hungrier fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going to come in with something to prove,'' Rose said.
``He had the emotion to fight just as hard in round 12 as he did in
round 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time loser: As Sam Perkins sat in a quiet Indiana locker
room before the game, he didn't feel better knowing he was the one
who knew what it felt like to be on the losing team in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 with Seattle and in 1991 with the Lakers, Perkins felt
the sting of defeat as Chicago won the titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second place, no one remembers,'' Perkins said. ``You get
money (for finishing second), but you get money all year. I told
them the only thing I can tell them: (If you lose) you want to get
there again. Keep going and going. If you believe in the team from
the start, you got all the bases covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins said the four years between Finals appearances have
flown by, and he told his teammates not to take the moment for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the youth: Pacers coach Larry Bird might be gone after the
season, but he has opinions of Indiana's future.
</P>
<P>
   Several players, including Reggie Miller and Mark Jackson, are
free agents at season's end. Bird said Miller promised he would
play hard and Bird is satisfied he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see them all come back,'' Bird said. ``We've got a
good nucleus of younger players. Austin (Croshere) and the other
young guys have stepped up. I think it'll make the team stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Croshere has averaged 9.1 points and 4.7 rebounds in the Finals.
His rebound average ranks second among not just his team but among
all Lakers, too. Only Dale Davis at 11.3 is averaging more.
</P>
<P>
   He's the Best: Guard Travis Best, limited to 10 minutes in Game
5 after suffering a sprained left shoulder in Game 4, finally got
into Monday's game with 9:19 left in the first half. Bird said how
much Best played would be a game-time decision.
</P>
<P>
   In Best's six first-half minutes, he missed his two shots from
the field (one was blocked) and had two assists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
