<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON'S SPOT IN HISTORY? NOT NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even as he closed within one victory of the
championship, Los Angeles Lakers coach Phil Jackson said he was too
focused on the present to think about his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   A victory Monday night meant Jackson's seventh title in nine
seasons. It also would make him the second coach ever to win
championships with two teams (Alex Hannum was the first).
</P>
<P>
   But when asked if he would put himself in a class with legends
such as Red Auerbach, Jackson declined the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that's not important,'' he said prior to Game 6. ``To look
at it when you're in the midst of something, you do what you have
to do. When you retire 10, 15 years down the road - God willing,
you're still alive - you think about those things at a later
date.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the reality is we haven't - maybe on the cusp - we haven't
crossed that threshold of winning another championship as a staff.
As a coach, I'll say the hard work is still ahead of us. We still
have something very difficult to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Still growing: At every stop along the way of a 67-win regular
season and these playoffs, Jackson has contended the Lakers
remained a work in progress. And no matter how these Finals turned
out, he said that would still be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot of growing yet to do as a basketball club,
and that's going to take, in effect, more than just this year and
this championship run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Missing: The Lakers were dismissive of a news report Monday that
executive vice president Jerry West would retire at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the annual `Jerry West is going to retire' rumor,'' said
Lakers spokesman John Black. ``And that's all it is.''
</P>
<P>
   West was unavailable for comment and did not attend Monday
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he did not attend a single game, home or away, in the
last two playoff series. West has described watching the games as
too stressful and said he prefers to avoid the media swarm.
</P>
<P>
   Dubious honor: As it turns out, the Lakers set an NBA record
with Friday's Game 5 loss at Indiana. The defeat was their sixth in
an elimination game - the most ever for a single postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great,'' Jackson said sarcastically, offering two
thumbs up and a grin. ``It doesn't say a thing. It says something
about this team a little bit, but that's not the story.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers entered Monday night's game with a 3-6 record in
potential series clinchers, including an 0-5 mark on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing for free: When Kobe Bryant shot two free throws with
2:06 left in the first half Monday, it marked his first trip to the
foul line since Game 1 of this series - an amazing span of 112
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson offered more sarcasm when it was noted that Bryant -
never shy about driving to the hoop - took just two free throws in
the first five games of the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't get fouled,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Pacers) are a team that probably sends teams to the
free-throw line fewer than any other team,'' he said. ``That's the
strength of their game, is that they want to go to the foul line,
and they'll get you in foul trouble and then try to draw the fouls,
and they try to keep you off the foul line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
