<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-LAZIO-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      06-19 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZIO-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO COUNTERS CLINTON WITH HIS OWN ATTACK AD 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three days after Hillary Rodham Clinton began running
television advertisements critical of him, Rep. Rick A. Lazio shot
back Monday with his own pointed advertisement, even as he promised
to take the high road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton, you can run the negative campaign about tearing
people down,'' Lazio says in a 30-second ad that will begin running
this week. ``I'm going to run a campaign about building New York
up.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point in the commercial, Lazio, the Republican
nominee for the Senate, delivers his own jab at the Democratic
nominee while smiling steadily into the camera. ``Why is she doing
this? Because it's a lot easier for Mrs. Clinton to attack me than
to name a single thing she has ever done for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from the last word, Lazio's advertisement set off another
round of brawling between the candidates, who even disputed the
extent to which Lazio's commercial would be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Dan McLagan, a spokesman for Lazio, said the campaign had spent
a substantial amount to broadcast the advertisement across the
state, but he refused to provide a dollar figure, calling it
confidential information. Howard Wolfson, Clinton's spokesman, said
a check of television station logs showed the commercial would be
run only once in some markets, including New York City. Wolfson
said this suggested that the commercial's release was more a ploy
for publicity than a significant advertising push.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the only example of rancor between the camps.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Lazio's campaign manager was beginning a news conference
in Manhattan to announce the commercial, Lazio's second new
advertisement in a week, Clinton's press office was e-mailing
reporters to attack it, accusing Lazio of initiating the negative
tone last month in his nomination acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of two news releases that Clinton put out Monday
criticizing Lazio. The other challenged Lazio's reputation for
independence in the House by noting a report in Roll Call, a
Capitol Hill newspaper, that quoted unidentified Republicans as
saying Lazio has asked the Republican leadership for ``a pass'' to
vote against Republican-sponsored legislation that might discredit
his moderate credentials. McLagan called the report untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's ad came in response to ads that Clinton began running
Friday assailing Lazio for his previous opposition to recently
approved state legislation that will stiffen penalties for hate
crimes and his opposition to a Democratic-sponsored measure in the
House known as the patients' bill of rights that would give people
broader powers to sue health maintenance organizations. Lazio
supported a Republican version that instead called for tax
deductions to help people pay their medical premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has called Clinton's commercials a distortion of his
record, and in his new one, he says that she was trying to fool
voters and that ``I voted for a patients' bill of rights and I
oppose hate crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dal Col, Lazio's campaign manager, addressed the attacks,
vowing to rebut every advertisement Lazio perceives as negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will meet her at the battlefield at every point,'' he said,
though he maintained that Lazio's ads would not turn negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a way to do an ad where you educate voters without
attacking,'' Dal Col said. ``We will take the most efficient,
effective use of communication to get that message across so that
the voters can clearly see who Hillary Clinton is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
