<HEADER>
A9049 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-19 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE:
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN: REVEALING SECRET
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican said it would issue the full text of the so-called
Secret of Fatima, with a commentary, next Monday. The Vatican
disclosed in Fatima on May 13 that the secret predicted the 1981
assassination attempt on John Paul II. Many aficionados of the
Fatima secret expressed skepticism about the interpretation, so the
release of the text will be closely followed by conspiracy
theorists. The Vatican is expected to release a photocopy of the
original handwritten secret put to paper by Sister Lucia decades
after she said she witnessed the Virgin deliver the prophecy in
1917.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: BERLUSCONI CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   The center-right opposition leader Silvio Berlusconi, 63, was
cleared of charges he bribed judges in Rome in 1990 on the way to
buying Mondadori, a major publishing house. Berlusconi, a media
tycoon, was also cleared last month of tax corruption charges by an
appeals court in Milan. He still faces other trials, including
charges of illegal political contributions and false accounting in
the acquisition of a player for his soccer team, AC Milan.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: JOINING EURO
</P>
<P>
   Greece was approved by the European Union for membership in the
euro-zone, or single currency union, starting Jan. 1. The approval,
at a meeting of European leaders in Portugal, came two years after
rejection of the country's application because of its ``poor
economic performance.''
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   NEW PEACEKEEPING CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   A French expert on European defense has been appointed head of
U.N. peacekeeping operations. Jean-Marie Guehenno, board chairman
in Paris of the Institute of Advanced Studies in National Defense,
was picked to succeed Bernard Miyet, another French defense expert,
whose term ends on Oct. 1. Guehenno, 50, has been France's
ambassador to the Western European Union and is the author of a
1995 book, ``The End of the Nation State,'' in which he argues that
the strength of individual countries is dwindling in a global age.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA:
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES: REBELS ASK RANSOM
</P>
<P>
   Muslim rebels who have held 21 mostly foreign hostages in a
jungle camp for two months are demanding at least $1 million in
ransom for each of them, an aide to President Joseph Estrada said.
The rebels have previously said they want a separate state in the
southern Philippines and protection of their fishing rights.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: SUHARTO PROTESTS
</P>
<P>
   Former President Suharto has protested to the United Nations
that the house arrest imposed on him three weeks ago violates his
human rights, his lawyers said. The former president is under
investigation for corruption. President Abdurrahman Wahid said a
deal is being discussed under which Suharto would repay the
government in return for his freedom.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA: PULLOUT
</P>
<P>
   The day after signing a cease-fire with Eritrea, Ethiopia said
it was complying with the plan's terms by withdrawing from the
western Eritrean town of Teseney. The town is much farther inside
Eritrea than the 15.5-miles permitted by the accord. Eritrea,
meantime, began repatriating Ethiopians displaced into Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SEEKING SUMMIT
</P>
<P>
   Israel wants President Clinton to convene a ``working summit''
with Prime Minister Ehud Barak and the Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat within a few weeks, Danny Yatom, Barak's chief security
adviser, told reporters. Israel believes White House-sponsored
talks could produce a detailed outline for final compromises on a
range of crucial issues, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: 3 PALESTINIANS FREED
</P>
<P>
   More than a month after a Palestinian street uprising that
demanded the release of prisoners, Israel released three in what it
called a good-will gesture. Palestinian officials called it far too
few, too late.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SETTLERS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Settlers rallied near Parliament to protest what they expect
will be significant concessions of West Bank land to the
Palestinians. Schoolchildren joined their parents for the protest,
which eventually marched to Prime Minister Ehud Barak's residence.
</P>
</TEXT>
