<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BRIEFS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   A CONVENTION ROLE FOR BRADLEY
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party officials say Vice President Al Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley, his onetime rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination, have worked out matters to the point that
Bradley can expect a prominent speaking role at the Democratic
National Convention in Los Angeles. Asked over the weekend if
Bradley would get a ``prime-time'' role, the convention manager,
Terry McAuliffe, a close Gore ally, told CNN, ``I think he will.''
McAuliffe also said President Clinton would have a prominent
speaking role at the convention, most likely on opening night. But
ultimately, McAuliffe said, ``this whole convention is about Al
Gore, his vision for the future, what he is going to do as
president.'' Convention planners also expect Hillary Rodham Clinton
to address the convention.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON RAISES MONEY IN TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton ventured onto Gov. George W. Bush's Texas turf
Monday for the third time this year to raise money for Democratic
candidates. Stopping in Houston and Austin, Clinton raised $1
million to help elect Democrats to the Senate and encourage
Hispanic voters to turn out on Election Day. Clinton argued that
there are sharp differences between the governor and Vice President
Al Gore, who he said had the better plan to keep the national
economy growing. The president also took Senate Republicans to task
for stalling confirmation of some of his judicial nominees. He
cited the Senate's failure to vote on Enrique Moreno, who was
nominated for the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. ``From humble
beginnings in El Paso, he established, first of all, an utterly
brilliant academic career,'' Clinton said. ``I might add, more
brilliant than that of virtually everyone who'd be voting on his
confirmation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   GORE SUGGESTS GAS PRICES ARE FIXED
</P>
<P>
   As gasoline prices in the Midwest escalate, so does the concern
of Vice President Al Gore, who, as part of the Clinton
administration, could be held politically accountable. He suggested
Monday that the big oil companies might be fixing prices. ``The big
oil companies' profits have gone up 500 percent in the first part
of this year, just the time when these prices are going sky high in
the Midwest,'' Gore said in an interview with ABC News. ``I think
that justifies a much broader investigation into possible
collusion, price gouging and antitrust violations.'' Later in the
day, he focused on the economy. At a fund-raising dinner in
Washington for the Democratic National Committee, Gore said the
nation's economic turnaround had been brought about by Clinton
policies. Fifty-five people paid $10,000 each to join him and Sen.
Bob Kerrey, Democrat of Nebraska, who had endorsed Gore's rival,
former Sen.Bill Bradley, in the primaries. Kerrey called Gore ``the
most qualified person in my lifetime'' to be running for
president. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Los Angeles and Cupertino, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Lexington, Ky., and Des Moines
</P>
</TEXT>
