<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros nearing the point of no return
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The overwhelming historical evidence suggests we really don't have
to wait until the All-Star break to accept what the Astros likely
will concede over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a turnaround of unprecedented proportions throughout the
franchise's 38-year existence, the Astros' chances to contend for
their fourth consecutive postseason berth are about as good as
Ernie Els' chances of overtaking Tiger Woods during the final round
of the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, those Astros who spend a lot of time playing
golf during the offseason almost certainly will get an earlier
start this year. At 25-43, the Astros have the worst record among
the 30 major-league teams, and they are 14 games behind first-place
St. Louis in the National League Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there are 94 games remaining in the Astros' season and
strange things have been known to happen in baseball, referred to
by some as the most unpredictable game of them all. But at this
point, it appears nothing short of a miracle can pull the Astros
out of the dumps.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who 2{ months into the season still haven't won more
than two games in a row, might soon have to write off the 2000
season with regard to contending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting tougher and tougher as every week goes by,''
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``I've always, in my
mind, had the All-Star break as a deadline to make that decision,
and we're only a few weeks away from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1964 Cardinals were 15 games out at the All-Star break and
not only came back to win their division but went to the World
Series. But we've got some challenges to overcome that don't show
any signs of getting any better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Billy) Wagner situation is very much up in the air.
Without a reliable closer, no team is going to go very far. The
pitching has gotten better, but it's still been inconsistent.
(Scott) Elarton is coming off surgery with no real clues as to what
the rest of the season is going to hold for him; certainly nothing
to be encouraged about at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shortstop situation has been a revolving door, and we're
incorporating more youth into the lineup every day. With all of the
challenges in front of us, it would take a monumental effort to get
back into the race.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' best record over their final 94 games of a 162-game
season is 60-34, established in 1986 and 1998. Even if they matched
that this season _ an unlikely possibility considering their
overall inconsistency _ they would still finish with only 85
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 162-game schedule was adopted in 1961, only four teams
have reached the playoffs (excluding strike-shortened seasons) with
85 or fewer victories. And even if the Astros did match their
finishes of 1986 and 1998, the Cardinals _ who are currently 10
games over .500 _ would have to play three games under .500 for the
rest of the season in order for the Astros to catch them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be real tough,'' said Astros righthander Chris
Holt, who will start tonight's opener of a three-game series
against the Dodgers at Enron Field. ``We're embarrassed by our
record and by the way things have gone. We just can't catch a
break, and you kind of wonder if it's just one of those years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to give in. I know we're quite a few games
back. I don't know what's going to happen after the All-Star break,
where we're going to be, what the front office will do; we just
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty regarding the direction of the club probably
won't exist much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for the organization, and I think
that's something we'll address over the next couple of weeks,''
Hunsicker said. ``We have to make some difficult decisions here,
but they're decisions that have to be made so that we know what
direction we're heading.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean the club might be broken up if things don't
improve in a hurry?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what that means yet,'' Hunsicker said. ``I think
we have to evaluate the personnel we have and what we feel the
capabilities are, not only for the rest of this year but the next
couple of years, and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it appears the decision already has been made. The
Astros' roster includes far more young players than in recent
years, and trying to win a championship with an abundance of
inexperienced players is a risky proposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's game against the Giants, the Astros started Lance
Berkman, Julio Lugo, Mitch Meluskey and Chris Truby in the same
lineup. None of them has played a full year at the big-league
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization hasn't come out and said that we're going
with a youth movement, but every prospect we have is here,'' Astros
first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``We're mixing them in here and
there. I'd like to see us go in one direction. I'd like to know
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a few weeks, it should be crystal clear.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
