<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TIMES-BUILDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES SIGNALS INTENT FOR 40-STORY TOWER 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times is expected to sign an agreement
this week with state and city officials to build a 40-story
headquarters on Eighth Avenue, between 40th and 41st Streets,
according to executives involved in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, The Times would pay nearly $100 million for
the development rights to the site, the executives said. The city,
in turn, is expected to provide a series of tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed tower would sit within the borders of the Times
Square redevelopment project and across Eighth Avenue from the Port
Authority Bus Terminal. It would be the third home for the
newspaper in the Times Square area in 100 years, and would allow
The Times to consolidate operations now scattered among six
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in discussions with the city and state,'' said Catherine
Mathis, a spokeswoman for The Times. ``But there are many things
that have not been finalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis would not comment on ``any monetary terms of any
potential arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, or memorandum of understanding, serves as an
outline for the project and sets the stage for what will probably
be months of lease negotiations over the final terms of a deal with
the state and the city. Talks on the project began last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, The Times selected Forest City Ratner Cos. as
a developer and partner for the project. Under their agreement, The
Times would take up to 900,000 square feet in the tower, out of a
total of 1.37 million square feet, while the developer would take
the rest of the space. There would be retail stores on the ground
level.
</P>
<P>
   The state would have to condemn the property and demolish about
eight low-rise buildings now on the site before construction could
begin.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the newspaper's 87-year-old headquarters, on 43rd
Street between Broadway and Eighth Avenue, would be sold and
presumably razed for a new building, according to real estate
executives and government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Times is in the process of winnowing a list of potential
architects to four from eight. Candidates included Sir Norman
Foster, the British architect, and Cesar Pelli, who designed the
tallest buildings in the world, Petronas Twin Towers in Kuala
Lumpur, Malaysia. To encourage diversity of architecture in the
area, state and city officials had asked the newspaper to exclude
Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill; Fox &AMP; Fowle and other architects who
had designed Times Square buildings in recent years. The Times
considered a number of European architects, including several who
have never worked on office projects. The four finalists are to
submit designs in competition for the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The state's guidelines for the building require a symmetrical
mid-block tower set back from Eighth Avenue atop a large base of
six to eight floors, for the newspaper's newsroom, according to an
architect who has seen preliminary plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Times is resisting the state's demand that there be large
illuminated signs on the side of the building facing Eighth Avenue,
much as there are on buildings in Times Square, executives involved
in the discussions said. The state is also requiring that the
project embrace some kind of public amenity, like a subway
entrance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
