<HEADER>
A9070 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SUPREME-COURT-PRAYER-     06-19 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREME-COURT-PRAYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING ENDS GAME INVOCATIONS IN TEXAS CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday struck down the Santa
Fe school board's policy of having a student deliver an
``invocation'' before high school football games, saying the
gridiron speech violates the constitutional separation of church
and state.
</P>
<P>
   In its 6-3 decision in the Texas case, the court said the Santa
Fe Independent School District's call for a student to
``solemnize'' the game is an unconstitutional effort by a state
agency to inject religious prayers into a government-sponsored
event.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution's First Amendment protects each citizen's free
exercise of religion by prohibiting the government from endorsing
particular faiths, the court said. By providing the forum for
students to speak on religious themes, the school board has
impermissibly endorsed religion, the justices added.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' decision was the latest in a string of high court
rulings during the last 38 years that have struck down public
school efforts to conduct moments of prayer for students and to
have clergy members speak at graduation ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush called the decision ``disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the constitutionally guaranteed right of all
students to express their faith freely and participate in
voluntary, student-led prayers,'' said the governor and likely
Republican presidential nominee this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the presumed Democratic presidential
nominee, agreed with the court's decision, said Gore spokesman Jano
Cabrera. ``He does support private (student) prayer in school as
long as participation is truly voluntary,'' Cabrera added.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Cominsky, regional director of the Jewish Anti-defamation
League, which filed a brief in the case, said the court's ruling
upholds minority rights. ``It's really a victory for people of all
religions,'' Cominsky said. ``This decision reiterates that freedom
of religion is a constitutional right for both the majority and the
minority ...''
</P>
<P>
   Under Santa Fe's policy, which had been under court challenge
for five years, the student body elected a student to deliver a
``statement or invocation'' before football games.
</P>
<P>
   The selected student could draft their own message to
``solemnize the event, to promote good sportsmanship and student
safety and to establish the appropriate environment for the
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   In striking down the policy as an unconstitutional state call
for prayer, the justices seized on the word invocation, calling it
``a term that primarily describes an appeal for divine
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also took particular exception to the provision, under
which student speakers were elected by their peers. Leaving the
selection of speaker to a majority vote increases the likelihood
that students who believe in minority religions will not be chosen
and that their religious views will be ignored during the
government-endorsed pregame speech, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Santa Fe's majoritarian election might ensure that most
of the students are represented, it does nothing to protect the
minority; indeed it likely serves to intensify their offense,''
Justice John Paul Stevens wrote in the court's majority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Washington attorney Walter Weber, who represented Santa Fe, said
the court's ``very bad decision,'' will foment more litigation
involving public schools.
</P>
<P>
   School districts, in their court-ordered attempt to prevent
students from reciting prayers at campus events, may now find the
American Civil Liberties Union suing them for restricting the
pupils' constitutional right to speak freely, Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts school districts in a very untenable situation,'' said
Weber, an attorney with the American Center for Law &AMP; Justice,
which supports prayer in public schools. ``No matter what they do
they're going to get sued, either by us or the ACLU.''
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Anthony Griffin, who challenged Santa Fe's policy
before the Supreme Court, hailed the decision as a victory for
religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the court recognized today, religious belief and expression
is flourishing in our country precisely because America has avoided
the mistakes of other countries and resisted the temptation for the
government to endorse religion,'' said Griffin of Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Santa Fe Independent School District vs. Doe, marked
the Supreme Court's first major foray since 1992 into the thorny
First Amendment issue of governmental endorsement of religion at
public schools. In several decisions since 1962, the justices ruled
that the Constitution generally prohibits school district
involvement in sectarian activities, saying that such participation
alienates students of minority religions.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing that trend Monday, the justices soundly rejected the
school district's argument that it was not involved in the pre-game
speeches, which students wrote themselves, and, therefore, did not
violate the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the board was in fact a major participant, the court
noted that the school, about 35 miles southeast of Houston, set the
rules for electing the speaker, provided megaphones for the
student's address, scheduled and hosted the game at which the
speech was given and had the school's name emblazoned all over the
field and on shirts of players, band members and cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   The court, alluding to the continuing national debate over
whether prayer belongs in schools, went to great lengths to say
that students may still worship voluntarily on school grounds. The
Constitution merely prohibits governmental agencies, including
school boards, from compelling students to worship or to listen
while others express their faith, the justices added.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Stevens' opinion were Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
Anthony M. Kennedy, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and
Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   In a vehement dissent, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
assailed not only the court's decision striking down the policy but
the tone of the ruling, which he said ``bristles with hostility to
all things religious in public life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist said public expressions of religion are rich in U.S.
history, such as President Washington's proclamation of a day of
``public thanksgiving and prayer, to be observed by acknowledging
with grateful hearts the many and signal favors of almighty God.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the court's narrow reading of the Constitution could
impinge on the rights of student leaders to speak freely.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Rehnquist's dissent were Justices Antonin Scalia and
Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Mormon and Catholic students and their parents sued the Santa Fe
board in 1995 to stop the pregame practice as unconstitutional. All
federal courts that have considered the case have refused to
divulge the names of the families, referring to them as Doe and
citing what the judges called the parties' well-founded fear of
harassment from community members who objected to their challenge
to the policy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STORY ENDS HERE &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
