<SLUG> BC-SOTHEBY'S-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTHEBY'S BOARD MEETING SET FOR AUGUST, LEADERSHIP PLAN STILL
RANKLES INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Baron Capital Group, a New York mutual fund that
is Sotheby's largest outside shareholder, filed a notice with the
Securities and Exchange Commission on Monday saying that it still
believes that electing the son of the former chairman and some of
his friends to the board presents a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   A. Alfred Taubman, the real estate developer who is Sotheby's
largest shareholder, resigned in February amid allegations of
price-fixing at the company. Taubman, who retains voting control of
the company and its board through stock ownership, wanted his son
Robert to take his place on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Baron, chairman and chief executive of Baron Capital,
first voiced his objections in April just before the company's
annual meeting. It was postponed as Baron pushed Sotheby's board to
distance itself from its former chairman. Monday, however,
Sotheby's announced that the meeting had been rescheduled to Aug. 3
at its York Avenue headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's plans to expand its board to 14 members from 10 at the
annual meeting. Taubman's ownership of 63 percent of the Class B
shares gives him the power to elect 10 directors, while Baron's
ownership of 55 percent of the Class A stock carries enough votes
to elect the other four.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's said Monday that, on behalf of the Class A
shareholders, it had nominated four people: George Blumenthal,
chairman and founder of NTL Inc., a provider of business and
residential telecommunications services in Europe; Steven Dodge,
chairman, president and chief executive of the American Tower
Corp., an owner and operator of broadcast and communications towers
throughout the United States; Henry Jarecki, chairman of the
Falconwood Corp., an investment banking company; and Brian Posner,
co-founder and managing partner of Hygrove Partners, an investment
management company.
</P>
<P>
   Baron filed a notice Monday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission in which he said that he ``remains dissatisfied with the
independence of certain Class B directors.'' Besides Robert
Taubman, the board of Class B directors also includes Jeffrey Miro,
one of Taubman's lawyers, and Max Fisher, a business associate who
is one of Taubman's closest friends.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-19-00 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
