<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SMALL TALK, HUGE STEP IN PYONGYANG &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KIMARADERIE-KOREA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They met, they chatted, they may meet again soon. This week's
summit dispelled some of the personal chilliness between South
Korea's Kim Dae Jung and North Korea's Kim Jong Il. It made less of
an impression on the deep-frozen hostility that still divides the
two Koreas. But for South Koreans _ North Koreans are not at
liberty to say _ the summit has rekindled hope that divided
families will be reunited and that someday, somehow, Korea will be
too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,050 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD RIDDANCE, HAFEZ. GOOD LUCK, BASHAR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFTER-ASSAD-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The end of an era, it is said. And good riddance to it, if true.
Hafez Assad's 30-year dictatorship is honored for giving Syria
stability after years of political chaos. But it was stability of a
kind that most countries would gladly be without. Syrians, once in
the vanguard of Arab intellectual life, deserve better. Does Bashar
Assad, the heir-apparent-son-of-dictator, belong to the twilight of
the old era, or does he usher in a more enlightened one? Can he
perhaps be helped to move from one to the other? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUBBLY BLAIR BLATHER BEGINS TO BORE BRITS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TONY-BLAH-BLAH-BLAIR-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So Tony Blair is mortal after all. In the past few months
Britain's prime minister has suffered the slings and arrows of
outrageous fortune: His party was defeated in local elections and
humiliated in the London mayoral election. Even now he still feels
driven to dress his policies up in grand-sounding, ``deeply
personal'' and embarrassingly half-baked political philosophy: the
``third way'' (yawn) and all that. For the first time since Blair
entered 10 Downing Street, it is imaginable that Labour could
actually lose the next election. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN PRAISE OF 24-HOUR GLOBAL STOCK EXCHANGES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GLOBAL-BOURSES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Few things, you might think, are as enduring as a national stock
exchange. And yet most of the world's bourses are now in turmoil,
as they scramble to be seen making alliances or mergers, to fend
off electronic competitors, or simply to survive. Two outside
forces have come together to create all this turmoil. The first is
electronic. The growing power of the computer and the spread of the
Internet have made share-dealing easier and cheaper. The second
force is a growing desire on the part of investors, companies and
investment banks to move beyond national borders for trading shares
and raising capital _ a 24-hour global marketplace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPECIAL SECTION: SYRIA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRASS BANDS AND ICE CREAM IN DAMASCUS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GRIEF-LITE-SYRIA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAMASCUS _ When an Arab ruler dies, shutters are supposed to go
down and alcohol to disappear. Not in Damascus. The day after
President Hafez Assad's death, locals took advantage of their day
off to pour into the city's most famous ice-cream parlor, Bekdash,
for a scoop and a natter. In the big hotels, waiters kept offering
their patrons extra mugs of beer. There was mourning, of course,
but there was little of the sort of personal, genuinely heartfelt
grief that overwhelmed many Jordanians at the death of King Hussein
last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (475 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CURIOUSLY UNDERPOWERED GORE CAMPAIGN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GORE'S-HOLE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ At the center of Al Gore's presidential campaign is
a hole _ and it isn't the candidate's personality. The vice
president, the policy wonk's policy wonk, is weak just where he
should be strong: in defining what policies a future Gore
administration would follow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,050 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOS ALAMOS: NUCLEAR SECURITY'S CUCKOO NEST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOS-ALAMOS-OOPS!-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ More than trees and houses have gone up in smoke at
Los Alamos, N.M., in the seven weeks since a forestry-service fire
ran out of control and immolated a large tract of the surrounding
area. The most recent casualty is, at a minimum, the reputation of
America's most famous nuclear weapons laboratory for guarding its
secrets, and at worst, a chink in the country's defense against
nuclear attack. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICANIZATION OF WESTERN CANADIAN POLITICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USALBERTA-CANADA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CALGARY _ Canadians have long lived in fear of their country
being torn apart by the secession of French-speaking Quebec. But
today a bigger challenge to their tranquility _ or complacency _
may come from Alberta, in the western prairies. Alberta's
politicians are promoting a robust, American-style agenda of
government. And they are being successful enough to make opponents
fear that caring, consensual Canada might become a clone of its
southern neighbor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: JUNE 24 _ Conservative Party Convention, Calgary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GAS PAINS: WHY OIL PRICES ARE SO HIGH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GAS-PRICE-PUZZLE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Why is the oil price shooting past $30 a barrel yet
again? There are several reasons, but the real problem is an
accident of timing that has caused shortages in the American
gasoline sector, the world's single biggest guzzler of oil. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Midwest Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DVD VS. VHS VIDEO WARS _ THE SEQUEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DVD-VS-VHS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO _ It looks for all the world like a rerun of the video
wars of the 1980s, when Sony's clever little Betamax cassette
recorder was eventually trounced by the Matsushita camp's clunkier
but more versatile VHS machine. Certainly, Japan's two
consumer-electronics giants have been girding up over the past few
months to do battle again. This time, they are butting heads over
which of their digital video disc (DVD) recorder designs will
replace the aging video-cassette recorder (VCR) that they fought
over a decade and a half ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OIL SANDS: `BLACK GOLD' LIES BENEATH CANADIAN FORESTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OIL-SANDS-CANADA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, ALBERTA _ Since the great Klondike gold rush of a
century ago, this rugged corner of Canada has seen plenty of booms
and busts. The next big boom looks likely to come from the ``black
gold'' that lies under the region's forests: oil sands. Optimists
now think the region's huge reserves of this mucky material could
meet half of Canada's oil needs by 2010, up from just a quarter
five years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (475 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NET WEALTH: SELLING GLAMOUR ON THE INTERNET &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LUXURY-ONLINE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ A visit to Christian Dior's glittering boutique on the
Avenue Montaigne is a powerful lesson in how to sell luxury.
Exquisite handbags hang like modern art in classic, silvered rooms.
The floors have been imported from a castle in Scotland. In such a
surreal atmosphere, paying $1,000 for a Dior handbag seems, well,
rather a snip. But would it on the Internet? The question that many
luxury-goods companies now face is whether they can peddle their
illusions online, where shoppers go for low prices and convenience,
not mystique. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCE &AMP; ECONOMICS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVE OVER, BILL GATES: ANTI-TRUSTBUSTERS NOW HIT
`PLASTIC-GATE' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CREDITCARD-COPS-ECONOMIST-675&AMP;ADD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fifty years after the credit card was invented in
Manhattan, its popularity knows no bounds. But the structure of the
industry supplying credit and other charge cards faces
unprecedented scrutiny. This week, the trial began of an antitrust
lawsuit launched by America's Department of Justice against Visa
and Mastercard, which together account for around 75 percent of the
country's $1.3 trillion credit-card market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 optional trims, totaling 100; 1,100 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICAN BANCOS: SPANISH ACQUISTADORES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPAIN-BANKS-ON-MEXICO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mere weeks ago, Mexico's banking system looked
sickly and unpromising. Now it has a rather different air.
Following the second of two big mergers, the industry is stronger,
more solid _ and distinctly more Spanish. On June 12 the board of
Mexico's biggest bank, Bancomer, decided to reject a purchase offer
from the country's second-largest, Banamex, and accept one from
Spain's Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria (BBVA), ending weeks of
uncertainty in a battle of bids unprecedented in Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
