<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-19 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT &LR;      06-19 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES GAIN SECOND-BIGGEST MARGIN OF VICTORY EVER, 22-1, AT
FENWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Paul O'Neill peeked around a corner in the visitor's
clubhouse to make eye contact with Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees'
pitching coach, and with an impish smile, O'Neill drew back his
left arm and pretended to throw _ an instant audition, just in case
the team's need for pitching had become so desperate that
Stottlemyre would consider using a 37-year-old outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre laughed, easily. He has learned the worst of streaks
can turn quickly, ``and all it takes is a couple of well-pitched
games,'' he said. ``That's all it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is a performance like the ones Ramiro Mendoza and
the Yankee batters gave at Fenway Park Monday night in beating the
Red Sox, 22-1, the largest margin of victory by New York over
Boston in their century-old rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza pitched seven innings, improving his record to 6-3, and
all it took were a few well-timed hits, a few runs to relax the
hitters as they feasted for 19 hits, mostly off Boston's middle
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada and Derek Jeter slugged home runs in the fourth and
fifth innings, respectively, before the Yankees had their largest
single-inning outburst of the season: nine runs in the eighth
inning, eight of them unearned because of Red Sox errors.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer, Felix Jose and Scott Brosius also hit home runs
for the Yankees (35-29), who belted five and regained first place
in the American League East, a half-game ahead of the Red Sox
(35-30), who have been struggling almost as much as the Yankees in
the last month.
</P>
<P>
   One day after being deflated by a nine-run first inning and
crushed at home by the Chicago White Sox, 17-4, the Yankees
rebounded with a nine-run eighth and a seven-run ninth. In Yankee
history, Monday night's 21-run victory margin is topped only by a
25-3 pasting of the Philadelphia Athletics on May 24, 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the Yankees' principal owner, George Steinbrenner, who
is pushing his executives to make a significant player move, did
not attend Monday night's game. But he is expected to see at least
a couple of games in this four-game series, which resumes Tuesday
night with baseball's best pitcher, Pedro Martinez, facing the
Yankees for the third time in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Before they started steadily filing out of the stadium as Yankee
runners kept filing across the plate, many of the Fenway Park
patrons were steadily razzing the Yankees' second baseman Chuck
Knoblauch whenever he attempted throws Monday night. Knoblauch did
not make any errors, but he tossed the ball tentatively, and with
the Yankees leading by 6-0 after six innings, he was replaced by
Clay Bellinger, who promptly belted a bases-loaded single in his
first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Yankee veterans marveled after the 1999 season how
the team controlled its intensity; the Yankees could look horrible
against the Detroit Tigers, and when challenged by good teams, they
always played better.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees' margin of talent is not as significant as it
was last year: the starting pitching has been erratic, the defense
poor, some regulars have been slumping and all this has been
supported only sporadically by a thin bench.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox visited Yankee Stadium over the weekend, a
first-place challenger, and the Yankees did not respond. They were
obliterated. What the Yankees may have learned is that they are not
good enough to float through the regular season and expect good
things to happen. A playoff spot is not a sure thing; the Yankees
could be watching other teams compete to succeed them in October.
</P>
<P>
   They looked moribund in the early innings Monday night, against
Boston's Brian Rose. After the Yankees failed to get a runner on
base in the first inning or the second, Spencer smashed the first
pitch of the third inning to the center field wall, and when it
ricocheted away from the Boston outfielders, Spencer stood at third
with a triple.
</P>
<P>
   But Ricky Ledee popped feebly to third, Brosius fouled out to
the catcher and Knoblauch reached to hit a soft lineout to
shortstop. Three chances to score a runner from third, and nothing
to show for it, as Red Sox fans roared. The morale of the Yankees
appeared to be at a low ebb.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza gave the offense time, however. Nomar Garciaparra
slammed a double to lead off the second inning, and Mendoza retired
the next three hitters, and all three hitters in the third inning,
keeping the game scoreless. But the Yankees needed some runs,
needed to get a lead, needed reason to feel better about
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter opened the fourth by bouncing a line drive over the
right-field wall _ Jeter would have had a triple if it had stayed
in play _ and then O'Neill flied out to left and Bernie Williams
struck out. They were about to blow another scoring chance. But
Tino Martinez rolled a single through the middle, Jeter scored and
the Yankee dugout was alive, its inhabitants standing and clapping.
They were even louder when Posada destroyed Rose's next pitch,
sending it far over center-field wall. Posada crossed home plate,
and when he returned to the dugout, Jeter was there, smiling, a
fist raised.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, the Yankees found something to exploit in what Rose
does, for the hitting coach Chris Chambliss stepped to the front of
the dugout several times to say something to hitters, and the
Yankees kept hammering away at the Red Sox right-hander. Brosius
singled to right in the fifth, and two batters later, Jeter rippled
the net above the Green Monster with a home run, his sixth homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led, 6-0, in the sixth. The Red Sox threatened in
the bottom half of that inning, but Wilton Veras made a
base-running mistake for the first out; he was caught off second
base on a ground ball back to Mendoza. When Garciaparra hit a liner
at Jeter, the Yankees' shortstop caught the ball moving toward the
bag and swiped a tag on the runner Jeff Frye for a double play to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza allowed six hits and no walks in seven innings,
frustrating the Red Sox again. He made two crucial appearances
against Boston in the playoffs last year, and last week, he threw
five and two-thirds innings solid innings in relief of Roger
Clemens, and the Yankees survived Pedro Martinez and went on to
beat the Red Sox, 2-1. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
