<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T--CELLONE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T BUYING CELL ONE; MA BELL ENTERING BAY AREA MARKET 
 &HT;     BY CARRIE KIRBY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Nearly 1 million Bay Area users of Cellular One mobile phone
service will become AT&AMP;T Wireless customers, possibly later this
year, when AT&AMP;T completes its acquisition of that system.
<P>
   In announcing the deal Monday, AT&AMP;T Wireless promised to make
the transition seamles, but did not promise to leave the service
completely unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cellular One clearly has their own regional and statewide
plans _ we'll be taking a look at them to see if we will continue
them or modify them at all,'' said AT&AMP;T Wireless President and
Chief Executive Officer Mohan Gyani.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular One customers will have access to all AT&AMP;T Wireless
products, including the company's Digital One Rate plan, which
allows users to make calls from anywhere in the United States for a
flat monthly fee. Cellular One doesn't offer such a plan in the Bay
Area, although competitors such as GTE Wireless do.
</P>
<P>
   Besides having access to new services, Cellular One users will
notice AT&AMP;T's name on their bills within six months of the
acquisition, AT&AMP;T officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular One's current network uses TDMA, the same technology
that AT&AMP;T employs in its nationwide network, so there won't be any
technical changes. Therefore, there is little chance of technical
glitches during the change, Gyani said.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications analyst Steven Marasci agreed that major
glitches are unlikely, but added that such large-scale switchovers
are a relatively new phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to tell if there are going to be problems with
the transition,'' Marasci said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Wireless already owns 53 percent of the Cellular One system
in the Bay Area through a joint venture with Vodafone AirTouch. In
December, Vodafone joined with Bell Atlantic and GTE to offer
nationwide mobile phone services as Verizon Wireless. As a
condition of that deal's approval, the Justice Department wants
Verizon's owners to sell off systems that would overlap with their
new service.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the Bay Area system _ part of a $3.3 billion deal
that includes networks in San Diego and Houston _ became available
to AT&AMP;T Wireless as a result of the Verizon deal.
</P>
<P>
   The purchases include the physical networks and subscriber
lists. As a result of the deals, about 1,400 employees will
transfer to AT&AMP;T Wireless, including nearly 800 workers in South
San Francisco at the Vodafone/AT&AMP;T joint venture's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Large wireless companies are racing to add cities to their
nationwide networks in order to affordably offer flat-rate roaming
plans such as AT&AMP;T's One Rate. The acquisitions will save AT&AMP;T a
lot of money by eliminating the need to pay another carrier to pick
up its customers' calls when they ``roam'' into the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   These charges vary, but analysts estimate that AT&AMP;T could have
been paying anywhere from 20 cents to 35 cents a minute to the
Vodafone/AT&AMP;T joint venture every time one of its customers made a
call from the Bay Area. When the sale goes through, those charges
will be eliminated because AT&AMP;T will own the network it was once
renting. The company said it hopes the three purchases will cut its
roaming costs by 8 to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications analyst Drake Johnstone of Davenport and Co.
in Richmond, Va., said that with those savings, AT&AMP;T got a good
deal on the three systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If AT&AMP;T has a customer paying $100 a month for 1,000 minutes,
and they're using primarily AT&AMP;T networks, that's a profitable
customer,'' Johnstone said. ``But if the customer is making most
calls from San Francisco, and AT&AMP;T is paying another carrier 20 to
30 cents a minute, AT&AMP;T is losing money in that customer.''
</P>
<P>
   After the acquisition, AT&AMP;T Wireless will serve all of
California's major cities, covering 90 percent of the state, and
the 15 largest wireless markets in the country.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Wireless, which became a tracking stock separate from
AT&AMP;T's main stock several weeks ago, closed at $28.75 Monday, up
$1.13, while AT&AMP;T closed at $33.88, up 44 cents.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby &LR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
