<SLUG> BC-GRANNY--GOOSE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANNY GOOSE CASHES IN CHIPS  &HT;     BY DAVID LAZARUS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Granny Goose Foods, the Oakland maker of potato chips that
struggled in recent years to remain solvent, has finally thrown in
the towel.
<P>
   ``They are out of business,'' Geoff Berman, vice president of
Development Specialists Inc., the firm hired to sell off Granny
Goose's assets, said Monday. ``They ran up against a wall with
their creditors.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, he estimated that the company owes as much as $37
million.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Oakland, which extended $2.2 million in loans to
Granny Goose five years ago, will likely be reimbursed in full,
Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the loan was secured by the company's sprawling
headquarters, located near the Coliseum, which is now being offered
for $6.5 million and already has received nibbles from potential
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the market wasn't there,'' said Greg
Garrett, manager of the One-Stop Capital Shop, which handles
Oakland's lending to businesses. ``The competition killed them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a last-ditch effort to stay alive, Granny Goose said in April
that it was moving production to Utah _ a switch that took Oakland
officials by surprise. The company had been part of Oakland's
economic landscape for more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not enough to placate creditors. In essence, they
told the company's owner, Oakland entrepreneur Keith Kim, that the
well had run dry.
</P>
<P>
   He in turn was forced to choose between bankruptcy and a sale of
Granny Goose's assets. Kim had purchased Granny Goose from G.F.
Industries in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The privately held company owes about $16 million to Coast
Business Credit and an additional $4.5 million to Burlingame's
Doyle &AMP; Boissere Fund I.
</P>
<P>
   Once such so-called secured creditors and agricultural suppliers
are paid, Berman estimated that about $10 million will still be
owed to unsecured creditors, including equity holders.
</P>
<P>
   They will be lucky to see any money,'' Berman said. ``If you're
Mr. Kim, you've probably lost whatever you put into the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The Granny Goose brand will not disappear from store shelves,
however. It was purchased in May by Oregon's Snack Alliance. The
company's Padrino's tortilla line was sold to Grande Foods of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Kim has since moved to South Korea, where he reportedly has
refashioned himself as an Internet mogul.
</P>
<P>
   No one was answering the phones yesterday at the Oakland factory
that once employed as many as 400 people.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
