<HEADER>
A9143 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-E-LOAN--SECURED-SFCHR     06-19 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-LOAN--SECURED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE THE DARLING OF INVESTORS, BUSINESS-TO-CONSUMER WEB  COMPANIES
NOW STRUGGLE TO SURVIVE  
 BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; Here are three stock prices that illustrate how drastically the
fortunes of consumer-oriented e-commerce companies have shifted
lately: $14, $74.38, $3.75.
<P>
   The first was the price that the shares of E-Loan, the Dublin
mortgage lender and a leading Internet consumer finance site, sold
for when the company went public a year ago. The second was the
stock's high price, reached just a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   And that last sorry figure was the price at which E-Loan sold
for in a private placement two months ago after a sickening slide.
</P>
<P>
   The riches-to-rags saga of E-Loan _ an innovative, well-regarded
company with no profits and an uncertain outlook _ offers a vivid
lesson, or, if you will, a morality tale about the way investors
have flip-flopped in their view of the e-commerce world. It also
illustrates the tough choices managers must make when the market
turns against them.
</P>
<P>
   From indiscriminately throwing money at any entrepreneur with a
half-baked idea and a Web server, investors have become obsessed
lately with the pace at which Internet companies use up cash _
their ``burn rate.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Wall Street analysts and venture capitalists
on Palo Alto's Sand Hill Road want to know just when Internet
companies are going to start making money and punish any outfit
that doesn't have a convincing ``path to profitability.``
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of business-to-consumer Internet companies went
from extremely red-hot to extremely has-been in a matter of
minutes,'' said Jonathan Fayman, an analyst with the San Francisco
online investment bank WR Hambrecht.
</P>
<P>
   That shift in sentiment put e-commerce companies against the
wall. Suddenly, it is nearly impossible to raise money through a
public stock sale. For companies that need financing, choices are
grim: Cut spending, go crawling back to venture capitalists or sell
securities privately on unfavorable terms.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the choice faced earlier this year by E-Loan, founded
in 1996 by local mortgage brokers Chris Larsen and Janina
Pawlowski. Burning up cash and facing a hostile market, the company
agreed to sell roughly a 25 percent stake to five investors,
including online brokerage kingpin Charles Schwab Corp., for $3.75
a share, raising $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; That was 8 percent below where E-Loan's shares traded on the
open market before the deal was announced and less than a third of
the company's initial public offering price in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say what a horrible thing it was for E-Loan, but they
really didn't have a choice,'' said Fayman. ``It was the price of
survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Larsen, E-Loan's boyish-looking and upbeat chief executive, has
been selling his company nonstop to investors and customers since
1996. In a recent interview, even the bitter pill of a stock
offering at a distressed price became just another opportunity to
pitch his company.
</P>
<P>
   In connection with the financing deal, Larsen pointed out,
Schwab agreed to set up a co-branded mortgage lending page on its
Web site, giving E-Loan access to millions of brokerage customers.
A partnership with one of the investing world's top companies ``was
a dream scenario,'' he crowed.
</P>
<P>
   E-Loan's chief financial officer, Frank Siskowski, was more
candid. The company had always said it would need another round of
financing after the IPO. But ``selling a good size piece of our
ownership at that price was painful,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, Larsen put aside his salesman's smile. ``Building
a company is a very hard thing,'' he said. ``You become a realist.
That's the deal. We'll take the steps that need to be taken.``
</P>
<P>
   The newfound hostility of the stock market means that a shakeout
among online consumer lenders has begun in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one of E-Loan's competitors, San Francisco Internet
mortgage lender iOwn, has been forced to put off an initial public
offering indefinitely. Its auditors said the delay raises
substantial doubt about the company's ability to continue. IOwn
officials said they are looking at alternatives to a public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that billions of dollars of credit will be
extended over the Internet. But traditional banks, credit card
companies and home lenders that use a variety of channels to reach
customers may have deeper pockets and more staying power on the
Internet. Analysts say it's not clear that an Internet-only
strategy will work in the lending business.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true in the mortgage business. Profit margins
in the home-loan business are razor thin and lenders must handle
large volumes to cover their fixed costs. What's more, home lending
is very sensitive to interest rates. When rates go up, as they have
been for the last year, demand for credit falls off.
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet mortgage companies, such as North Carolina's
Lending Tree, don't make loans themselves but connect consumers to
third-party lenders. E-Loan is following the riskier path of
building a full-fledged mortgage-lending operation.
</P>
<P>
   Even E-Loan skeptics say the company has created an attractive
product for consumers. E-Loan's origination fees generally beat
traditional competitors and it offers a streamlined approval
process to borrowers with good credit records.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts question whether that's enough. ``This is a
very tough business economically,'' said Vincent Daniel of CIBC
World Markets. ``The question remains whether E-Loan can originate
these loans under their current model at a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, E-Loan took in $22.1 million in revenue, more than
three times what it collected in 1998. At the same time, the
company posted a net loss of $39.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter ended March 31, E-Loan's revenue fell 7.7 percent
from the December quarter, producing a net loss of $11.4 million.
The falloff in revenue was due to a sharp drop in the market for
mortgage refinancings as interest rates rose.
</P>
<P>
   To diversify its business, E-Loan bought an online car-loan
company from Bank of America last year. But analysts say the
company is still highly vulnerable to rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Larsen said he expects E-Loan to begin making
money in a couple of years. And the $40 million of new money in the
vault means the company won't have to beat the bushes for financing
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the biggest thing E-Loan has going for it is its link
with Schwab and the brokerage's nearly 4 million online clients.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab spent more than a year searching for an Internet mortgage
partner and the brokerage plans on making a big push to promote
E-Loan mortgages on its Web site. It liked E-Loan so much that it
agreed to take warrants to buy up to 13.1 million additional shares
in the company as part of the partnership deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there is tremendous upside in E-Loan's value from
having us as a partner,'' said Schwab chief strategy officer Dan
Leeman. A full purse and Schwab's blessing probably means that
E-Loan won't go under. But whether it will thrive or muddle along
until it is bought by a larger and stronger company remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Larsen expresses any doubts. He still has the
evangelical fervor that marked the early days of the Internet, when
paradigm shift was the buzz and no one talked about anything as
crass as profits. He says it's ludicrous to think that consumers
will be taking out mortgages in brick-and-mortar locations in a few
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this is going to be a societal-changing event,'' he
said. ``You've got to stick to your religion and not get caught up
with what's happening in the short term in the capital markets.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; id  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
