</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BANK ON DIVIDENDS 
 &HT;     BY ARTHUR LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;         c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Q:  &LR;  am interested in common stocks that have long dividend &LR; 
 &LR; histories. Can you recommend an information source? I would &LR;   &LR; also
be interested in the names of mutual funds that focus on &LR;   &LR; stocks
that pay high dividends. &LR;
<P>
   &LR; a  &LR;  A: Standard &AMP; Poor's keeps close track of dividend
histories. By consulting their monthly Stock Guide _ a handy
booklet with lots of financial statistics about thousands of
publicly traded stocks _ you can find out (among other things) how
long a company has paid cash dividends. General Electric, for
example, has paid them every year since 1899.
</P>
<P>
   It costs more than $100 per year to subscribe to the Stock
Guide, which seems like overkill in your case. See if you can find
a recent copy at the public library. Or ask whether your broker has
a copy lying around. Even one that is a month or so out of date
will serve the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   As for mutual funds that emphasize dividends, you ought to
rummage through the printed or Web-based materials provided by
Morningstar Inc. (Its Web site is  &LR; www.morningstar.com &LR; .) The funds
that will interest you most probably will have the word
``balanced'' in their names _ meaning that the fund manager tries
to draw a balance between income and capital appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to suggest that you might be wrongheaded in placing
heavy emphasis on dividends _ but I'll suggest it anyway. A lot of
truly spectacular stocks don't pay dividends at all.
</P>
<P>
   Take Cisco Systems, for example _ and boy, do I wish I had. It
doesn't pay dividends and never has, but its stock price has more
than doubled in the past 12 months and has shot up more than
twentyfold 20-fold  &LR; in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   If you owned Cisco, you could simulate dividend payments by
selling a few shares now and then. And if you held the shares for
more than a year, you would even get a tax break, because any
profits from the stock sales would be taxed at the reduced,
long-term capital-gains rate. Dividends, by contrast, are taxed at
full rates.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Trying to Track Portfolios
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Q: Can you recommend a good, free portfolio tracker? I've
tried a few but am invariably led to a screen that says that,
should I continue, all the confidential information I've just given
may go to an unsecured site.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; a  &LR;  A: You won't run into that problem with the Stockpoint
portfolio tracker, sponsored by Iowa's Stockpoint Inc. and
available at  &LR; www.stockpoint.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Stockpoint doesn't pry too deeply when you sign up.
To use its portfolio-tracking tools, you must disclose only your
e-mail address, your age bracket, your gender and your ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   It's all very informal. I strongly suspect that if you fudge any
or all of the answers, you will still be able to use the tracker.
Stockpoint, which earns revenues from online advertisers, is quite
eager to expose you to the advertisements, no matter who or what
you are.
</P>
<P>
   Partial Tax Relief
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: I need some tax relief. Where and how does one buy U.S.
Treasuries?
</P>
<P>
   &LR; a  &LR;  A: Buying U.S. Treasuries will indeed provide you with tax
relief, but it will be limited. The income they generate is exempt
from state income taxes but subject to the federal income tax.
</P>
<P>
   You can open an investment account with the government and buy
Treasuries online through the U.S. Treasury Department Web site. Go
to  &LR; www.treasurydirect.gov  &LR; for details.
</P>
<P>
   You also can sign up off-line by ordering materials from the
Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco. The telephone number is
(415) 974-2330.
</P>
<P>
   Send questions about how to manage your money ot
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103
</P>
