<SLUG> BC-IBM--DRIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW IBM TINY DRIVE GROWS IN CAPACITY 
 &HT;     BY HENRY NORR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
IBM is tripling the capacity of the Microdrive, its
silver-dollar-size removable hard drive for digital cameras, MP3
players and other portable electronic devices.
<P>
   The company Tuesday will announce 1-gigabyte and 512-megabyte
versions of the tiny drive, priced at about $499 and $399,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The 340-megabyte version the company has been shipping for the
past year will remain available, but at the reduced price of $299.
The other version introduced last year, with a capacity of 170
megabytes, will be discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   The new drives will begin shipping in limited volume in July,
</P>
<P>
   according to IBM, but won't reach retailers' shelves until
September.
</P>
<P>
   The Microdrive fits into an industry-standard slot known as CF+,
which is now built into most professional digital still cameras and
some handheld PCs. Via an adapter IBM includes with the drives,
users can also plug them into the PC Card slots found in most
notebook computers.
</P>
<P>
   John Monroe, chief analyst for rigid disk drives at Dataquest,
said the market-research company estimates that IBM shipped about
89,000 Microdrives last year, but he noted that volume shipments
didn't begin until June or July. IBM spokeswoman Michelle McIntyre
said her company expects a two- to fourfold increase in shipments
this calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   In part, IBM is betting that the drives will take off in
portable digital music players. A 1-gigabyte drive can hold nearly
18 hours of high-quality digital audio, compared with just over 30
minutes for stock MP3 players today.
</P>
<P>
   A company called i2Go already offers an MP3 player with a
Microdrive-compatible slot, and Diamond Multimedia, manufacturer of
the market-leading Rio series of MP3 players, plans to offer a
340-megabyte Microdrive as an accessory for its recently announced
Rio 600 model.
</P>
<P>
   In a camera, the 1-gigabyte drive can hold up to 1,000
high-resolution digital photos; in a notebook or handheld PC, it
could store 1,000 200-page novels, according to IBM.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to increased capacity, the new Microdrives offer
30-percent better performance, 50 percent more resistance to
non-operating shock and power savings of more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On a per-megabyte basis, the Microdrive costs 40 to 60 times as
much as a conventional PC hard drive, but only a half to a third as
much as flash memory, the current standard in handheld devices. In
addition, few current devices can handle more than 128 megabytes of
flash memory at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The new drives weigh less than 1 ounce. By contrast, IBM noted,
its first 1-gigabyte drive, introduced in 1980, was the size of a
refrigerator, weighed 550 pounds and cost $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
