<HEADER>
A9146 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCH     06-19 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESTREET.COM'S NEW SURVEY TURNS INVESTMENT RATINGS TOPSY-TURVY 
 &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TheStreet.com yesterday joined a growing cadre of print and
online publications and services that rate stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
   This cottage industry is growing so fast that pretty soon we'll
need a service to rate services that rate analysts. (That's my free
idea of the week for venture capitalists.)
</P>
<P>
   While they can be confusing and sometimes contradictory, these
services are a good tool for investors who wonder if they should
take the advice of the analyst they just saw on CNBC or pay for
Wall Street research being offered by many online brokers and
financial Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com's survey is the first to combine quantitative with
qualitative data. This methodology resulted in several upsets.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it names Morgan Stanley as the top research firm.
Merrill Lynch, rated No. 1 by Institutional Investor magazine and
the Wall Street Journal, ranks only third in TheStreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Morgan Stanley's prominent Internet analyst Mary
Meeker, the perennial favorite in the II survey, comes in third on
TheStreet.com. She was outranked by Henry Blodget, Merrill Lynch's
coming-on-strong Net guru.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, II had the analyst-rating game to itself. Its
annual All America Research Team became the Wall Street equivalent
of the Academy Awards, and analysts who made the list often found
greater fame, fortune and calls from headhunters.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Academy Awards, the II survey is criticized for
being little more than a popularity contest. The results are based
on a survey of institutional investors _ such as pension fund and
mutual fund managers _ who are the main clients for brokerage house
research.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from Hollywood, some analysts carried on
behind-the-scenes lobbying campaigns to garner votes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, II says on its Web site: ``To mitigate the likelihood
of extraordinary vote-generating activities on the part of firms or
analysts during the fieldwork, it is the policy of Institutional
Investor not to reveal the details relating to certain aspects of
the survey execution process.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, the Wall Street Journal jumped into the game.
Its quantitative survey _ which usually comes out in late June _ is
based solely on analysts' stock-picking and earnings-forecasting
ability. It uses data provided by Zacks Investment Research but is
switching to First Call this year.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com's analysis combines objective and subjective
analysis. It was spearheaded by Laurie Meisler, who spent the past
18 years running II's All Star project.
</P>
<P>
   Like II, TheStreet.com surveyed institutional investors, but it
focused on a smaller number of the bigger firms. Instead of a
write-in ballot, investors chose from a list of analysts nominated
by their brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   Institutions were asked to rate analysts on six factors, such as
``well-connected, makes money for me, saved me from disaster and
tells us the truth,'' Meisler says.
</P>
<P>
   Any analyst that received at least one vote from any of the 138
instiutions that responded was then rated based on his or her
stock-picking prowess, using data from IBES International.
</P>
<P>
   ``We calculated what would happen (over a one-year period ending
in February) if you bought what analysts said to buy and held as
long as they told us to hold and sold when they told us to sell,''
says Scott Rosen, director of research with IBES
</P>
<P>
   To come up with a final score for each analyst, TheStreet.com
gave 70 percent weighting to the popularity poll and 30 percent to
the cold hard numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that stock picking is one of the criteria voters
would use, so we didn't want to make it 50/50,'' Meisler says.
</P>
<P>
   By including quantitative data, Meisler thinks her new survey
turns up some unsung heroes such as Daren Marhula, who covers
health care distributors for the lesser-known firm U.S. Bancorp
Piper Jaffray. ``He ranked near the bottom in voting but got 100
(the highest score possible) in stock picking,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com survey suffers from the same drawback as the II
and Journal studies: All three come out only once a year and use
numbers that are quickly outdated. Even the day-old Street.com
report lists analysts with firms they have already left. Some of
the departures are noted, but some _ such as Rick Shutte, formerly
of Goldman Sachs _ are not.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a problem for  &LR; www.bulldogresearch.com &LR; . Launched May
1, this Web site is the most dynamic, comprehensive and interactive
analyst rating tool to date. While other surveys cover hundreds of
analysts, this one ranks 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   You can search the site for top analysts by company or sector.
Analysts are ranked separately on their earnings forecasts and
stock recommendations. Results are shown for time periods ranging
from one quarter to several years, and are updated daily.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like there's almost too much information, or maybe it's
just poorly organized or labeled. The folks in New York who run
this site say they're making it more user friendly.
</P>
<P>
   In a few months, a San Francisco startup called StarMine will
introduce a Web site similar to Bulldog Research.com, but it will
use stars instead of paw prints to rate analysts.
</P>
<P>
   StarMine, like Bulldog, will use IBES data, but will develop
different formulas for interpreting the data. StarMine is already
selling its services to institutional investors. One product it
sells is enhanced earnings estimates, which give more weight to
estimates from analysts with good track records than bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   One limitation to all these services is that they are
retrospective. There's no easy way the average investor _ without
direct access to Wall Street research or other expensive services _
can find out what a specific analyst thinks a specific company will
earn in the future, or what stocks he or she is recommending.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's proprietary. You have to pay big bucks to IBES or be a
customer of the brokerage firm'' to get that information, says Joe
Gatto, chief executive officer of StarMine.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some institutional investors don't think Wall Street
research is worth the paper it's written on. (Yes, these firms
still produce hard-copy reports, some as big as small laptops.)
</P>
<P>
   The Catch-22 with analysts is that the more popular they become,
the more time they spend doing things that promote their firms'
investment banking business (namely stock underwriting, where the
real money is), and the less time they spend doing pure research.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it makes sense to look for up-and-coming analysts,
and to use any report or recommendation as one tool in your
investment tool kit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
