<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL--CHIP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL BRINGS OUT REINFORCEMENTS FOR PROCESSOR WAR  &HT;     BY HENRY NORR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Rolling out some heavy artillery for an emerging battle with
startup Transmeta, Intel Monday unveiled five processors for
notebook PCs, including one that could rival its challenger's
much-ballyhooed Crusoe chip in low power consumption.
<P>
   Among the new Intel chips is a low-power mobile Pentium III
designed for 3-pound ``ultraportable'' laptops. Running at 600
megahertz on AC power and, via Intel's SpeedStep technology, 500
megahertz on batteries, the chip breaks no new ground in clock
speed, but it will burn far less power than any previous Pentium.
In battery mode, it requires only 1.1 volts and consumes less than
1 watt in typical use, according to Intel, compared with about 2
watts for previous mobile Pentium IIIs.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of ultraportables barely exceed 1 million units worldwide,
but market research company International Data Corp. recently
projected that they will double next year. By 2003, Intel said, it
expects that such units will account for 10 to 15 percent of all
notebook PC sales, which by then should be approaching 35 million
units.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement also included the fastest mobile PC
processor yet, a Pentium III that runs at 750 megahertz on AC power
and 600 megahertz on batteries. In its entry-level Celeron line,
the Santa Clara chip giant added 600- and 650-megahertz mobile
chips plus an extra-low-power version running at 500 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   All five chips are available immediately, according to Intel.
Major notebook vendors such as Compaq, Dell, Fujitsu, IBM, NEC,
Sony and Toshiba are using them in notebooks being introduced this
week and at next week's PC Expo trade show, as well as in
back-to-school models to be announced later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how much battery life users can expect from notebooks
with the new chips depends on other hardware variables, such as
screen size and the applications in use. Most notebook
manufacturers today claim around three hours of typical use per
charge for their larger models and two hours or less for
ultraportables, which usually have smaller batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The new chips aren't likely to change those numbers much, but
they will allow notebookmakers to offer higher performance while
maintaining battery life at current levels, according to Frank
Spindler, vice president and general manager of Intel's Mobile
Platforms Group.
</P>
<P>
   Transmeta's Crusoe has attracted intense media and industry
attention since its unveiling in January, largely because of the
company's claims that the Windows version of the chip will use less
than a watt of power and that notebooks incorporating it could run
all day on a single battery charge. IBM, Compaq and Gateway, among
others, are expected to demonstrate prototype Crusoe-based laptops
at next week's show.
</P>
<P>
   Those systems won't ship to customers until around October,
according to Transmeta spokesman Ed McKernan. But when they do, he
insisted, they will offer significantly better battery life, lower
weight and less heat than notebooks using the chips Intel announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's low-wattage claims are based on benchmarks that emulate
standard office applications, but in real life, McKernan argued,
users increasingly run graphics-intensive applications that demand
more of the processor.
</P>
<P>
   A Crusoe chip, for example, will consume only about 1 watt when
playing a DVD movie, he said. In a demonstration during yesterday's
Intel announcement, the 600-megahertz, ultralow-power Pentium III
used 3 to 3.5 watts most of the time while playing an ``Austin
Powers'' DVD, though at times it dropped to less than 1 watt.
</P>
<P>
   The Transmeta chips will also have a lower maximum power
consumption _ a variable that has little effect on overall battery
life but is important to notebook manufacturers, who have to make
sure their systems can handle the peak load and resulting heat.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said the maximum _ known in the industry as ``thermal
design power'' _ for its ultralow-power 600-megahertz Pentium III
will be 9.6 watts; for its 750-megahertz mobile processor the
figure will be 15.8 watts. The maximum figure for Transmeta's
Crusoe chips, according to McKernan, will be less than 5 watts.
</P>
<P>
   McKernan also noted that Crusoe has a memory controller built in
and is designed to work with low-power graphics chips; Intel's
mobile Pentiums require a separate memory controller and AGP
graphics, both of which use additional power, he said. The
Transmeta spokesman also said Crusoe will cost notebookmakers less
than $200. Intel's 750-megahertz mobile chip costs $562 in
quantity, while the low-power 600-megahertz Pentium III is $316.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
